(98, 4, 3, 62, 'chadwick-boseman-black-panther-director-ryan-coogler-pays-emotional-tribute-1598819006', 'Chadwick Boseman: Black Panther director Ryan Coogler pays emotional tribute', 0, '<p>Black Panther director Ryan Coogler has written a lengthy and loving tribute towards the film&#39;s star Chadwick Boseman, that has died aged 43.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Chad was an anomaly. He was calm. Assured. Constantly studying,&quot; authored the director on Sunday morning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The ancestors spoke through him,&quot; he added. &quot;How much of an incredible mark he&#39;s left for all of us.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boseman died on Thursday in your own home in La together with his wife, Taylor Simone Ledward, and family by his side.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He&#39;d been identified as having bowel cancer 4 years ago, receiving care while filming hit movies like Avengers: Endgame, 21 Bridges and Spike Lee&#39;s Da 5 Bloods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, he never discussed his diagnosis in public places, and Coogler stated &quot;he shielded his collaborators from his suffering.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Black Panther star Chadwick Boseman dies of cancer</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#39;Wakanda forever&#39;: Tributes pour in</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &#39;What Black Panther way to black people like me&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Black Panther star Chadwick Boseman on being &#39;young, gifted and black&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is actually the director&#39;s statement entirely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before discussing my ideas around the passing from the great Chadwick Boseman, When i first offer my condolences to his family who meant so much to him. To his wife, Simone, especially.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I inherited Marvel and also the Russo Brothers&#39; casting selection of T&#39;Challa. It&#39;s something which I&#39;ll forever appreciate. The very first time I saw Chad&#39;s performance as T&#39;Challa, it had been within an incomplete cut of Captain America: Civil War. I had been deciding whether directing Black Panther was the best choice for me personally. I&#39;ll always remember, relaxing in an editorial suite around the Disney Lot and watching his scenes. His first with Scarlett Johansson as Black Widow, then, using the South African cinema titan, John Kani as T&#39;Challa&#39;s father, King T&#39;Chaka. It had been at that time I understood I needed to create this movie. After Scarlett&#39;s character leaves them, Chad and John started conversing inside a language I&#39;d never heard before. It sounded familiar, full of the identical clicks and smacks that youthful black children will make in the usa. Exactly the same clicks that people would frequently be chided to be disrespectful or improper. But, it&#39;d a musicality into it that felt ancient, effective, and African.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Within my meeting after watching the show, I requested Nate Moore, among the producers from the film, concerning the language. &quot;Did everyone recover it?&quot; Nate responded, &quot;That&#39;s Xhosa, John Kani&#39;s native language. He and Chad made the decision to complete the scene like this on set, so we folded by using it.&quot; I figured to myself, &quot;He just learned lines in another language, on that day?&quot; I could not conceive how difficult that has to happen to be, although I had not met Chad, I had been already in awe of his capacity as actor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I learned later there was much conversation over how T&#39;Challa would seem within the film. The choice to have Xhosa function as the official language of Wakanda was solidified by Chad, a local of Sc, while he could learn his lines in Xhosa, there around the place. Also, he recommended for his character to talk with an African accent, to ensure that he could present T&#39;Challa to audiences being an African king, whose dialect was not overcome through the West.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I finally met Chad personally at the begining of 2016, after i signed to the film. He snuck past journalists which were congregated for any press junket I had been doing for &quot;Creed,&quot; and met beside me within the eco-friendly room. We spoken about our way of life, time playing football attending college, and the time at Howard studying to become a director, about our collective vision for T&#39;Challa and Wakanda. We spoke concerning the irony of methods his former Howard classmate Ta-Nehisi Coates was writing T&#39;Challa&#39;s current arc with Marvel Comics. And just how Chad understood Howard student Prince Johnson, who&#39;s murder with a officer inspired Coates&#39; memoir Between Your World and Me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I observed then that Chad was an anomaly. He was calm. Assured. Constantly studying. But additionally kind, comforting, had the warmest laugh on the planet, and eyes that seen much beyond his years, but tend to still sparkle just like a child seeing something the very first time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Which was the very first of numerous conversations. He would be a particular someone. We&#39;d frequently talk about heritage and just what this means to become African. While preparing for that film, he&#39;d ponder every decision, every choice, not only for the way it might think about themself, but exactly how individuals choices could reverberate. &quot;They not prepared for this, what we should are doing&hellip;&quot; &quot;This really is The Exorcist, this really is Lord from the Rings, however for us&hellip; and larger!&quot; He&#39;d say this in my experience basically we were battling to complete an impressive scene, stretching into double overtime. Or as they was covered in body paint, doing their own stunts. Or crashing into frigid water, and foam landing pads. I&#39;d nod and smile, however i did not believe him. I had no clue when the film works. I wasn&#39;t i understood things i was doing. However I think back and understand that Chad understood something all of us did not. He was playing the lengthy game. All while investing in the job. And work he did.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He&#39;d arrived at auditions for supporting roles, which isn&#39;t common for lead actors in big budget movies. He was there for many M&#39;Baku auditions. In Winston Duke&#39;s, he switched a chemistry read right into a wrestling match. Winston broke his bracelet. In Letitia Wright&#39;s audition for Shuri, she pierced his royal poise together with her signature humour, and will bring in regards to a smile to T&#39;Challa&#39;s face which was 100% Chad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While filming the film, we&#39;d meet in the office or inside my rental home in Atlanta, to go over lines and new ways to add depth to every scene. We spoken costumes, military practices. He stated in my experience &quot;Wakandans need to dance throughout the coronations. When they just stand there with spears, what separates them from Romans?&quot; At the begining of drafts from the script. Eric Killmonger&#39;s character would ask T&#39;Challa to become hidden in Wakanda. Chad challenged might requested, &quot;Let&#39;s say Killmonger requested to become hidden elsewhere?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chad deeply valued his privacy, and that i wasn&#39;t aware of the facts of his illness. After his family released their statement, I realized he was coping with his illness the whole time I understood him. While he would be a caretaker, an innovator, along with a man of belief, dignity and pride, he shielded his collaborators from his suffering. He resided an attractive existence. And that he made great art. Every single day, every year. Which was who he was. He was a legendary firework display. Let me tell tales about being there for a few of the brilliant sparks &#39;till the finish of my days. How much of an incredible mark he&#39;s left for all of us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;ve not grieved a loss of revenue this acute before. I spent the this past year preparing, imagining and writing words for him to state, that people were not determined to see. It leaves me damaged understanding that I will not have the ability to watch another close-from him within the monitor again or walk as much as him and request another take.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It hurts more to understand that people can&#39;t have another conversation, or Facetime, or text exchange. He&#39;d send vegetarian recipes and eating regimens in my family and me to follow along with throughout the pandemic. He&#39;d sign in on me and my children, even while he worked using the scourge of cancer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In African cultures, we frequently make reference to family members which have handed down as ancestors. Sometimes you&#39;re genetically related. Sometimes you aren&#39;t. I&#39;d the privilege of directing scenes of Chad&#39;s character, T&#39;Challa, contacting the ancestors of Wakanda. I was in Atlanta, within an abandoned warehouse, with bluescreens, and large movie lights, but Chad&#39;s performance managed to get feel real. It was because from the moment which i met him, the ancestors spoke through him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s really no secret in my experience just how he could skilfully portray a lot of our noticably ones. I&#39;d without doubt he would survive and then bless us with increased. But it&#39;s having a heavy heart and a feeling of deep gratitude to possess have you been in the presence, that I must reckon with the truth that Chad is definitely an ancestor now. And That I know that he&#39;ll keep an eye on us, until we meet again.</p>', 'Chadwick Boseman, Black Panther', '_114181817_gettyimages-915964024_1598819006.jpg', '2020-08-31 00:23:26', '2021-08-17 11:32:59'),
(99, 4, 1, 73, 'oral-sex-linked-to-vaginal-condition-bacterial-vaginosis-1598819193', 'Oral sex linked to vaginal condition bacterial vaginosis', 0, '<p>Dental sex may create an atmosphere for any common vaginal condition known as microbial vaginosis or BV, based on research within the journal PLoS Biology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BV isn&#39;t a sexually transmitted infection. It&#39;s an imbalance from the usual bacteria based in the vagina.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ladies who get it might have no signs and symptoms, however, many obtain a strong-smelling discharge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Researchers explored what effect mouth bacteria dress in microbes living and also be within the vagina.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>About BV</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BV isn&#39;t usually serious, but ought to be treated because getting BV makes women more susceptible to catching sexually transmitted illnesses and becoming urinary infections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the lady is pregnant, zinc heightens the chance of premature birth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Can you be sure for those who have it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is extremely common and ladies who&#39;ve it might notice they&#39;ve a unique discharge which has a strong fishy smell.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you notice a big change towards the colour and consistency of the discharge, for example becoming greyish-white-colored and thin and watery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your GP or reproductive health clinic could request a swab test to find out if you&#39;ve BV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If it makes sense positive, it may be given antibiotic tablets, gels or creams.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Sex activities and risks described</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; How safe is dental sex?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What did the brand new research find?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Women without BV generally have lots of &quot;good&quot; bacteria known as lactobacilli that keep your vagina more acidic, having a lower pH.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes this nutritious balance can tip and let other vaginal micro-microorganisms thrive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What can cause this to occur isn&#39;t fully known, but you are more prone to get BV if:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; you are if perhaps you are (but ladies who haven&#39;t had sex may also get BV)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; you&#39;ve had a big change of partner</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; you possess an IUD (contraception device)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; you utilize perfumed products around or in your vagina</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The research in PLoS Biology demonstrated the way a everyday sort of bacteria based in the mouth that&#39;s associated with gums and teeth and dental plaque may support BV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They did experiments in human vaginal examples as well as in rodents to check out microbial conduct.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The mouth area bacteria, Fusobacterium nucleatum, made an appearance to assist the development of other bacteria implicated in BV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They, Dr Amanda Lewis in the College of California and colleagues, repeat the findings show how dental sex might lead with a installments of BV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Experts know that BV could be triggered by sex, including between women.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof Claudia Estcourt, spokesperson for that British Association for Reproductive Health and Aids, stated research similar to this was important to increase the knowledge of BV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We all know BV is a very complex entity with a lot of adding factors.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She stated dental sex could spread sexually transmitted infections along with other bacteria that might or might not make a difference in other health problems.</p>', 'Oral sex, bacterial vaginosis', '_108732943_gettyimages-874067096_1598819193.jpg', '2020-08-31 00:26:33', '2021-08-14 22:40:17'),
(101, 4, 1, 63, 'altnagelvin-hospital-neonatal-intensive-care-unit-reaches-capacity-1598819379', 'Altnagelvin Hospital: Neonatal intensive care unit reaches capacity', 0, '<p>The Neonatal Intensive Care Unit at Altnagelvin Hospital in Londonderry no longer has sufficient beds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A spokesperson for that Western Trust told BBC News NI the problem was within the number on Sunday mid-day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s not associated with the Covid-19 pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An infant requiring intensive care born within the hospital over the following 48 hrs would probably be used in another hospital, the spokesperson stated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This really is using the Northern Ireland Neonatal Network, that Health insurance and Social Care Trusts are members of.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BBC understands an pregnant woman was accustomed to the possible lack of beds when she attended a cheque-up in the hospital on Sunday morning. She&#39;s since been used in another hospital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If your baby comes into the world in Altnagelvin Hospital over the following 48 hrs also it requires intensive care treatment, chances are the baby (and mother) is going to be used in a medical facility by having an available neonatal intensive care bed,&quot; stated the spokesperson.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The choice to move a mom and baby pre- or publish-birth to a new hospital isn&#39;t taken gently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s taken by senior obstetricians combined with the neonatal team and they&#39;ll always prioritise the security of the people or babies when you are performing so.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Inside a further statement to BBC News NI on Sunday evening a spokesperson for that Trust stated the neonatal unit continues to be &quot;temporarily relocated&quot; to allow maintenance try to occur.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We anticipate the unit is going to be reopened on 7 September 2020 when the maintenance works could be completed as planned,&quot; stated the spokesperson.</p>', 'Altnagelvin Hospital, Neonatal intensive care unit', '_109338033_neonatal_1598819379.jpg', '2020-08-31 00:29:39', '2021-08-14 22:37:02'),
(102, 4, 9, 143, 'robin-swann-increases-contaminated-blood-payments-1598819637', 'Robin Swann increases contaminated blood payments', 0, '<p>Northern Ireland victims from the contaminated bloodstream scandal are going to see financial support for them elevated to complement payments produced in England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Victims in Northern Ireland have formerly received under individuals in England, Scotland and Wales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Health Minister Robin Swann confirmed annual payments would now vary from &pound;18,745 to simply under &pound;45,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This could drive them consistent with payments produced in England, that have been considerably elevated in April 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The payment amount relies upon diagnosis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The funding dedication to increase payments can come to &pound;1.1m yearly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Why the NHS gave thousands Aids-contaminated bloodstream</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In The month of january and March of the year, Mr Swann announced payments to Northern Ireland victims from the plan would match individuals in England for that 2019/2020 period - which now being made permanent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The scandal led to individuals who had haemophilia receiving treatment with bloodstream have contracted hepatitis C or Aids within the 1970s and 1980s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This past year, the contaminated bloodstream inquiry heard harrowing tales from people over the United kingdom about how exactly lives have been destroyed by infected bloodstream.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>About 5,000 people, including 99 from Northern Ireland, were infected in what continues to be known as &quot;the worst scandal within the good reputation for the NHS&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Victims met using the health minister captured to induce him to deal with the disparity in payments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;The support they need&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The minister stated he requested officials in the finish of recently to create payments consistent with England, which following a necessary approvals on Friday, this could certainly be on-going.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He acknowledged individuals affected had faced additional distress because of the coronavirus pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve clearly stated formerly that my support can there be for individuals impacted by infected bloodstream.&quot; stated Mr Swann.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I continuously make an effort to ensure they obtain the support they require and deserve.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m delighted so that you can announce this significant uplift in rates and Hopefully this financial support goes a way to mitigate the harms and afford the good way to reside normally a existence as you possibly can.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Swann stated that beneficiaries would receive notification of the uplift within their rates by letter within the coming days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He stated that individuals impacted by the plan could be surveyed, to evaluate their feelings on the amount of financial and mental support.</p>', 'Robin Swann, blood payments', '_114179742_tv063061999_1598819637.jpg', '2020-08-31 00:33:57', '2021-09-23 08:15:58'),
(103, 4, 1, 39, 'coronavirus-in-scotland-where-are-the-latest-cases-1599583016', 'Coronavirus in Scotland: Where are the latest cases?', 0, '<p>There has been 20,318 confirmed installments of Covid-19 in Scotland and a pair of,494 individuals have died carrying out a positive test for that virus, based on Scottish government figures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This site is updated regularly and analyses the important thing figures for that coronavirus outbreak in Scotland.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Figures updated at 14:00 on 30 August 2020.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Confirmed installments of Covid-19</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the last 7 days there has been 507 cases detected carrying out a test, with 123 confirmed on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following chart shows the amount of daily confirmed cases after an NHS Scotland or United kingdom government test during the period of the outbreak, plus a seven-day moving average.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The particular number of individuals infected is going to be far greater compared to confirmed cases figure, since many those who have or had Covid-19 aren&#39;t tested.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://news-zilla.com/uploads/ckeditor/canvas_1598819827.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>', 'Coronavirus in Scotland, Where are the latest cases?', 'index_1598820021.jpg', '2020-08-31 00:38:11', '2021-08-14 22:37:52'),
(104, 4, 1, 114, 'coronavirus-cases-on-tui-flight-from-zante-to-cardiff-1598820261', 'Coronavirus: Cases on Tui flight from Zante to Cardiff', 0, '<p>All passengers who have been on the flight to Wales from the Greek island happen to be told to self-isolate after a little aboard tested positive for coronavirus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Medical officials say seven individuals from three different parties on Tui flight 6215 from Zante to Cardiff on Tuesday have tested positive for Covid-19.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Public Health Wales (PHW) is contacting the 193 passengers and crew aboard.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It comes down as someone from Plymouth tested positive for that virus after coming back from Zante on Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Cardiff and Vale test, trace, safeguard and Public Health Wales have identified a minimum of seven confirmed installments of Covid-19 from three different parties who have been infectious on Tui flight 6215 from Zante to Cardiff on 25 August,&quot; stated Giri Shankar of PHW.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Forget about deaths with coronavirus but 56 new cases</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; How you can fly throughout a global pandemic</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Do you know the latest social distancing rules?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Consequently, we&#39;re counseling that passengers about this flight are thought close contacts and should self-isolate.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These passengers is going to be contacted shortly, but meanwhile, they have to self-isolate in your own home because they can become infectious, even without developing signs and symptoms.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dr Shankar, PHW&#39;s Covid-19 incident director, stated the 187 passengers and 6 crew aboard the 3-and-a-30 minutes flight from Zakynthos to Cardiff Airport terminal on Tuesday which has signs and symptoms &quot;should book an evaluation immediately&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There have been 1,715 new coronavirus cases - and something dying - reported within the United kingdom on Sunday - the greatest number since 4 June.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While no new deaths with coronavirus were reported in Wales on Sunday, 56 cases happen to be confirmed by PHW.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The seven cases aboard the Tui flight are incorporated within the 12 new cases reported within the Cardiff and Vale College Health Board area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Can One still continue holiday to Poultry or A holiday in greece?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; You ultimately got abroad, but could it have been worthwhile?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tui stated all passengers adhere to Covid protocols &quot;throughout their flight&quot; including putting on goggles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The travel operator added their aircraft have &quot;condition-of-the-art, hospital standard air renal system&quot;, are deep cleaned after every flight and &quot;fully disinfected at least one time every 24 hrs&quot; in compliance with Eu Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) guidelines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The security and well-being of passengers and crew is our greatest priority so we operate consistent with EASA guidelines,&quot; stated a Tui spokesperson.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cardiff Airport terminal, which is a member of the Welsh Government, stated it&#39;s working carefully with airlines to &quot;facilitate passenger travel throughout this challenging here we are at the&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Tui takes every necessary measure following today&#39;s report, stated Spencer Birns, Cardiff Airport&#39;s interim leader.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Cardiff Airport terminal is carefully following guidelines put down by Public Health Wales, FCO and United kingdom Government and it has already taken numerous measures to guarantee the security and safety in our team and customers, that is our most important.&quot;</p>', 'Tui flight, Zante to Cardiff', '_114180176_zakynthos-nc_1598820261.png', '2020-08-31 00:44:21', '2021-08-15 17:35:24'),
(105, 4, 7, 28, 'coronavirus-norway-bunker-partygoers-poisoned-with-carbon-monoxide-1598879272', 'Coronavirus: Norway bunker partygoers poisoned with carbon monoxide', 0, '<p>After participating in an illegal rave in a bunker in Oslo, the Norwegian capital, 25 people were hospitalized with carbon monoxide poisoning. Five were in critical condition, and two police officers, vulnerable to party members, were poisoned. Authorities believe portable generators were the cause of the poisoning. The Rave Cave event, which was attended by about 200 people, was accidentally discovered when patrols greeted confused youths, police said. Country profile. Most of them left the bunker and called an ambulance. It did not immediately become known who organized the underground event planned three weeks ago and was known to be kept secret by the authorities. Oslo police are currently investigating why there were no enthusiastic warnings. What do you know about addiction? During the rescue operation, seven people were found unconscious in a bunker in the Saint-Hanshaugen area. Do you believe in the lives of all victims.&nbsp;</p>', 'Coronavirus, Norway bunker', '_114182918_mediaitem114182917_1598879271.jpg', '2020-08-31 17:07:52', '2021-07-28 05:21:18'),
(106, 4, 9, 118, 'how-wildfire-pollution-may-be-harming-your-health-1598879978', 'How wildfire pollution may be harming your health', 0, '<p>Smoke from burning forests and peat can remain in the atmosphere for weeks, travel thousands of kilometers and endanger the health of people far away. A golden yellow pot in the dark forest landscape below. However, fire damage suffered in the Krasnoyarsk Territory of Siberia at close range during the day. A wall of burning foam engulfed the vegetation. Behind him stood a tree, singed like a black toothpick, and a plume of smoke blocked the air and soared high into the atmosphere. According to the analysis of satellite images by Greenpeace International, as of early 2020, about 19 million hectares (73,359 sq mi) were observed in Russia due to forest fires. You warned us!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Siberian arctic wildfires set a record this summer. According to the European Center for Medium-Range Weather Forecasts, an 18-month magazine will cause more air pollution than any other in a month. In part, it has evolved into hot, resinous boreal forests, swampy peat and melting tundra ice sheets that emit high concentrations of carbon dioxide into the atmosphere along with toxic pollutants such as methane and mercury. But that&#39;s also because fires are more widespread and a by-product of the record heatwave that hit the Arctic in early summer. This melts the tundra and is much easier to burn. However, small light soot particles also enter with the gases emitted by forest fires. These &quot;particulate matter&quot; (PM) are a common component of urban air pollution, from which exhaust gases and heavy industry can be emitted. After all, the smoke from a forest fire can cause serious damage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, during the bushfire season in Canada, cities in British Columbia saw 20 times more dust particles than the daily average. Sarah Henderson, Senior Fellow at the Center for Disease Control in British Columbia, said: &ldquo;The small size and large number of dust particles have a lot to do with this. Wood fires tend to produce more fine dust particles than PM2. This is because even the finer nanoparticles, which are known to be extremely harmful to health, are generally small enough to see tiny particles 30 times the width of a human hair, and when inhaled, they can penetrate the lining of the lungs. and damage the airways. ...</p>', 'wildfire pollution, health', 'p08p8gjv_1598879978.jpg', '2020-08-31 17:19:38', '2021-08-10 20:21:26'),
(107, 4, 7, 29, 'why-clothes-are-so-hard-to-recycle-1598892255', 'Why clothes are so hard to recycle', 0, '<p>Fast fashion leads to the dumping of mountain clothes every year and has a huge impact on the environment. Can we turn unwanted clothes into something useful?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Open your closet and be honest. How long has it been since you last wore one of these dresses? Do you think it might be time to clean up?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tongue at the back of the wardrobe and the bottom of the drawer is an item of clothing that no longer fits, an item that is out of date, or even an item of clothing that has never been worn. According to a study by Manchester University sociologist Sophie Woodward, an average of 12% of the clothes in a woman&#39;s wardrobe she studied could be considered &quot;inactive.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&#39;ve been brutal, you may be able to fill a container or two with clothes you no longer want or need. But then what?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The weird truth about navel hair</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Could it really make you happy to mess up your house?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do you have to wear a coat inside?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>About 85% of all textiles discarded in the US - about 13 million tonnes in 2017 - were dumped in landfills or incinerated. The average American counts about 40 pounds of clothing each year. Worldwide, about 92 million tonnes of textile waste are generated each year, and every second the equivalent of a garbage truck full of clothes ends up in landfills. By 2030, more than 134 million tonnes of textiles are expected to be dumped annually.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The current fashion system uses a large number of non-renewable resources, including oil that is made to make clothes and is often used only for a short time. After that, most of the material is lost to landfills or incinerators,&quot; said Chetna Prajapati, who studies ways to Make sustainable textiles at Loughborough University in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This system depresses valuable resources such as water, pollutes the environment and damages ecosystems, and creates global social impacts.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are good reasons to look for alternatives to dumping clothes in the trash - the fashion industry is responsible for 10% of all greenhouse gas emissions worldwide. Textile production alone causes 1.2 billion tonnes of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere every year. Large amounts of water are also used to make our clothing, and the fashion industry is responsible for 20% of the world&#39;s wastewater. (Read more about the impact our fashion addiction has on the planet.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the same time, we are buying more clothes than ever before - the average consumer is buying 60% more clothes now than we were 15 years ago. The UK buys more than two tonnes of clothing every minute, more than any other country in Europe. Approximately 56 million tonnes of clothing are purchased worldwide each year, which will increase to 93 million tonnes by 2030 and 160 million tonnes by 2050.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finally, only 12% of the materials used in clothing are recycled worldwide<br />\r\nWhile most carefree clothing will last for years, a change in fashion means that changing consumer tastes will artificially shorten their lifespan. Industry data shows that modern clothing will last 2 to 10 years, with underwear and t-shirts last only one to two years while suits and coats last about four to six years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Does recycling our clothes help lower the tax our fashion addictions impose on the environment?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Currently, only 13.6% of the clothing and shoes discarded in the United States are recycled - while the average American throws away 37 kg of clothing each year. Finally, only 12% of the materials used in clothing are recycled worldwide. Compare that to paper, glass, and plastic PET bottles, which have recycling rates of 66%, 27% and 29%, respectively, in the US, and it&#39;s clear that clothing is lagging behind.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In fact, most of the recycled polyester used by the top fashion brands today comes from bottles, not used clothing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Much of the problem depends on the material of our clothing. The fabric we cover on our bodies is an intricate combination of fibers, bodies and accessories. They are made from a problematic mixture of natural yarns, man-made fibers, plastics and metals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;For example, 100% cotton t-shirts contain many other components such as labels and sewing threads, which are usually made from a different material such as polyester,&quot; Prajapati said. &quot;Likewise, typical jeans made of cotton thread, which is usually blended with spandex, as well as other components such as zippers and buttons and polyester sewing thread that are dyed with various dyes.&quot;</p>', 'Clothes Recycling, How clothes are recycled?', 'p08kds9r_1598892255.jpg', '2020-08-31 20:44:15', '2021-08-18 02:12:18'),
(108, 4, 8, 54, 'planting-trees-doesnt-always-help-with-climate-change-1598908639', 'Planting trees doesnt always help with climate change', 0, '<p>Reforestation is seen as a way to cool the climate and suck excess warming carbon from the atmosphere. But it&#39;s not always that simple.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Suddenly we are all told to plant trees. The hope is that they will save us from the worst effects of climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The idea is everywhere. Swedish climate activist Greta Thunberg made a film arguing for the added protection of the world&#39;s forests and replanting felled trees. George Monbiot, a British Guardian columnist, has launched a campaign called Natural Climate Solutions to help restore forests and other ecosystems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This isn&#39;t just a conversation. The UK government has planted millions of trees over the past decade and has pledged millions more between 2020 and 2024. Others have attempted a much more dramatic achievement: in 2016, the state of India planted 50 million trees in one day. Last July, Ethiopia said it was planting 350 million a day. Even the UK&#39;s Daily Mail, a far-right newspaper unfamiliar with its climate activity, has just launched a campaign to encourage all its readers to plant trees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may also like ...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How can you bring the forest back to life?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What would happen if all the trees disappeared?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Is It Wrong to Expect Climate Change?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Protecting existing forests and planting new ones is certainly a good thing. But scientists say we shouldn&#39;t trust trees too much to save ourselves. Last year in particular, the research team said we could plant an additional trillion trees and remove a quarter of the carbon dioxide currently in the air. These figures have been widely criticized for being exaggerated and unreliable. Trees will definitely help us slow down climate change, but they will not reverse it on their own.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The main problem is that our society emits greenhouse gases, especially carbon dioxide (CO2), which heats the Earth&#39;s climate to levels we&#39;ve never seen before. As a result, large ice sheets are melting and causing sea levels to rise, and extreme weather events such as storms and droughts are becoming more severe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The solution is to stop the emission of all greenhouse gases, for example by replacing fossil fuels with renewable energy sources such as solar energy. Deforestation is actually one of the biggest sources of carbon dioxide because when trees are cut down, much of the carbon stored in them is released into the air - especially if the wood is burned. For example, land use change - especially deforestation - contributed four billion tonnes of CO2 emissions to a total of 41 billion tonnes of CO2 in 2017. In other words, if we stopped cutting down trees, we would reduce annual emissions by about 10%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, it is no longer enough to just stop all of our emissions. At this point we have emitted so much CO2 and left emission reductions so late that we are almost certain that we will miss our target of limiting warming to 1.5 &deg; C or 2 &deg; C. This means we also need to find ways to actively eliminate. CO2 from the air.</p>', 'How our environment needs help?, #planttress', 'p08dsqlj_1598908639.jpg', '2020-09-01 01:17:19', '2021-08-15 17:48:01'),
(109, 1, 7, 54, 'trump-justifies-wisconsin-shooting-suspect-he-will-probably-die-if-he-doesnt-shoot-1598936074', 'Trump justifies Wisconsin shooting suspect: he will probably die if he doesn\'t shoot', 1, '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>US President Trump supported a 17-year-old boy on August 31, who was accused of killing two people during a protest in Kenosha, Wisconsin. Trump said that the accused gunman tried to escape at the time and that if he did not shoot, he was likely to be killed by the demonstrators.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump will visit Kenosha on September 1, local time. On August 23, a 29-year-old African-American man Jacob Black was shot by Kenosha police seven times and was paralyzed. Afterwards, local people demonstrated for many days to protest police brutality and racism.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the third night of the demonstration, 17-year-old Kyle Rittenhouse shot and killed three protesters with an assault rifle, two of whom died. Trump said at the press conference: &quot;He was trying to flee from them. He fell and they attacked him very violently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I think he was in a lot of trouble... he was likely to be killed. .&quot; Rittenhouse is currently facing two first-degree murders and one attempted murder, and his lawyer said he plans to defend himself.</p>', 'Wisconsin shooting suspect, shooting suspect, Trump', 'img_1598936074.jpg', '2020-09-01 08:54:34', '2021-08-16 12:32:35'),
(110, 4, 3, 34, 'bts-k-pop-group-reacts-with-tears-after-making-billboard-history-1598951961', 'BTS: K-pop group reacts with \'tears\' after making Billboard history', 0, '<p>The BTS members said they shed tears after becoming the first Korean pop to top the Billboard 100 singles list with their new English single Dynamite.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chimin, one of the seven members, said &quot;tears keep flowing&quot; and added in a tweet that he &quot;didn&#39;t know what to say&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also thanked his fans, known as ARMY, by saying, &quot;I&#39;m crazy right now, but you are doing this [to make it happen].&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The other Suga members recently posted a series of crying emoticons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dynamite, their first song to be sung entirely in English, hit 33.9 million streams in its first week and debuted at number one on the Billboard Hot 100.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Within minutes, the hashtags # BTS1onHot100 and #BTS_Dynamite began to emerge, and fans flooded the hashtags with congratulatory messages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;No words, just tears,&quot; said one Twitter fan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I can&#39;t express my feelings. I&#39;m very proud of you and how far you have succeeded,&quot; said another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even South Korean President Moon Jae-in took part and said the children were doing &quot;an extraordinary feat.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;After topping the Billboard 200 main album charts four times, they have reached number 1 on both charts,&quot; said Moon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The song Dynamite was created to convey a message of comfort ... it will bring comfort to Koreans who are suffering from a national crisis due to Covid-19.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dynamite broke records shortly after being released on August 21. The pastel dance video hit 101 million views on YouTube just 24 hours after its release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The band said they wanted the song to convey &quot;positive vibes, energy, hope, love, purity, everything.&quot;</p>', 'BTS, BTS Record', '_114192941_gettyimages-1207786892_1598951960.jpg', '2020-09-01 13:19:21', '2021-08-16 09:49:26'),
(112, 7, 7, 40, 'trump-has-denied-mocking-american-soldiers-who-were-captured-and-killed-in-action-1599223327', 'Trump has denied mocking American soldiers who were captured and killed in action', 0, '<p><strong>President Trump has denied allegations that he made derogatory remarks about American soldiers being captured or killed in action.</strong><br />\r\nAccording to The Atlantic magazine, Trump canceled a visit to a US cemetery outside Paris in 2018 because he said he was &quot;full of losers&quot;.<br />\r\nSince then, the allegations have been confirmed in AP reports by two senior military officials.<br />\r\nBut in a tweet, the president denounced the allegations as &quot;fabricated fake news&quot;.<br />\r\nDuring a visit to France in 2018, Trump canceled a visit to the Aise-Marne American Cemetery, and at that point the White House blamed the bad weather.<br />\r\nHowever, four sources told The Atlantic that he rejected the idea of visiting him because the rain would ruffle his hair and he did not believe in the importance of honoring American military deaths.<br />\r\nDuring the same trip, the President also claimed that the 1,800 American soldiers who died at Belowwood were &quot;gunfire&quot;. The fighting helped prevent the German invasion of Paris during World War I and was honored by the US Marines.<br />\r\nThree sources told The Atlantic that Trump called former President George HW Bush a &quot;loser&quot; at least twice because he was ousted by Japan while serving as a naval pilot during World War II. .<br />\r\n&quot;He couldn&#39;t imagine doing anything for anyone but himself,&quot; an unnamed retired military general told The Atlantic. &quot;He just thinks that anyone who does something when there is no immediate personal gain is a bastard. There is no money to serve the nation.&quot;<br />\r\nIn interviews with reporters, Trump described the Atlantic report as &quot;unthinkable&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;To think that I would make a negative statement about our military and our fallen heroes if no one does what I do with the budget, with the military budget and with salary increases for our military,&quot; the president said. &quot;This is a wicked situation from a magazine which is a terrible magazine.&quot;<br />\r\nMedia playback is not supported on your device<br />\r\nTrump and US Army media captions: Friend or Foe?<br />\r\nTrump has been criticized in the past for his comments about military veterans. In 2015, he challenged the heroism of Republican Senator John McCain, who was captured during the Vietnam War.<br />\r\n&quot;I like people who have never been arrested,&quot; he said in an interview.<br />\r\nTrump received five moratoriums from military service during the Vietnam War - four for academic reasons and one for bone spurs, a build-up of calcium in his heels.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'Donald Trump, Us Soldiers Mocking', 'Trumps_1599223326.jpg', '2020-09-04 16:42:07', '2021-08-17 08:21:50'),
(113, 7, 7, 50, 'fire-broke-out-on-the-oil-tanker-1599326797', 'Fire broke out on the oil tanker', 1, '<p>The fire broke out under the flag of the Panamanian oil tanker New Diamond, 38 nautical miles from Sangamankanda Point in eastern Sri Lanka, the country&#39;s Navy said on Thursday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Navy said it was responding immediately to distress signals from a boiler explosion, followed by a fire in the main engine room. According to distress signals from the Coordinating Center for Marine Rescue in Colombo, the oil tanker is operated by a crew of 23, including five Greek nationals and 18 Filipinos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tanker is expected to transport 270,000 tonnes of crude oil from the Mina Al Ahmadi port in Kuwait to the Paradip port in India. It is also alleged that 1,700 tonnes of diesel, which is needed to use the tankers, are stored on board.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As of September 4, the Sri Lanka Navy, Air Force, Port Authority, Indian Navy and Indian Coast Guard were still working to limit the spread of flames aboard the oil tanker, the Navy said. So far, according to the Indonesian Navy, there is no risk of oil spilling from the ship into the sea, it was revealed that a Filipino crew was not found after the incident.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In accordance with the health sector&#39;s instructions in the current Covid-19 emergency, steps have been taken to bring the rescued crew ashore for treatment and isolation, in accordance with the relevant health instructions,&quot; said a statement posted on the website. You are.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The Navy is responsible for maritime search and rescue operations in the Sri Lanka search and rescue area. The Navy remains loyal to its mandate and frequently responds to calls for this type of ship and ship type disaster,&quot; Fleet added. an explanation.</p>', 'Fire Broke, Oil Tnaker', 'Oil tanker_1599224429.png', '2020-09-04 17:00:29', '2021-08-07 09:12:18');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(114, 7, 3, 97, 'britney-spears-supports-the-freebritney-movement-1599225168', 'Britney Spears supports the #FreeBritney movement', 0, '<p>A court-appointed guardian has been in charge of their case since the public collapse in 2008. Her father Jamie has played the role most of the time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now the star is trying to remove him from power, claiming that the public has a right to know what happened.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The world is watching,&quot; his lawyer said in the lawsuit on Thursday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spears&#39; comments came in response to a suggestion from her father who wanted to seal the latest testimony on the case.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The star &quot;strongly opposes his father&#39;s attempts to hide his legal battle as a family secret in a cupboard,&quot; his lawyer, Samuel Ingham III, said in court documents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Spears team also supports the #FreeBritney movement, which claims the star went against his will by people who benefited financially from his position.</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Britney Spears calls conservatism &quot;voluntary&quot;</li>\r\n	<li>What exactly is the #FreeBritney campaign?</li>\r\n	<li>Britney assured fans that &quot;everything is fine&quot;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>His followers often staged protests outside of court, and the campaign was supported by celebrities including Cher, Miley Cyrus, and actress Ariel Winter, who received emancipation from her mother as a teenager.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At this point in her life, as she tries to regain some degree of personal autonomy, Britney welcomes and appreciates the informed support of many of her fans,&quot; wrote Ingham.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prior to this, Jamie Spears called the # FreeBritney movement a &quot;joke&quot; and described his followers as &quot;conspiracy theorists&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I have to go to court for every nickel and penny I spend every year. How do I steal something?&quot; he told the New York Post last year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Ingham challenged the idea in his recent court ruling</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Britney&#39;s conservation has attracted an unprecedented level of scrutiny from the mass media and social media,&quot; the court said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Far from being a conspiracy theory or &quot;joke&quot; as James put it to the media, this control is largely a plausible and even predictable outcome of James&#39; years of aggressive use of the sealing process to minimize the amount of meaningful information open to the public. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Britney Spears wants the court to remove control of her father</li>\r\n	<li>&nbsp;Britney Spears sister trying to control finances</li>\r\n	<li>Britney Spears is on an indefinite break from her job</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Spears and her lawyers routinely seek to shut down trials and closed trials, arguing that the cases contain personal medical information, details about Spears&#39; children and trade secrets that must be protected. Los Angeles Supreme Court Judge Brenda Penny regularly approves her applications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ingham said on Thursday that the strategy may have had &quot;merits&quot; years ago when the pop musician tried to continue his career, but the situation has changed.</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<p>&quot;The sealing proposal is believed to have been put forward by his father to&quot; protect &quot;Britney&#39;s interests, but he is very much against it,&quot; he wrote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Financial control</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spears has been subject to a conservatorship since 2008, when she was twice admitted to a psychiatric ward.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The arrangement is usually reserved for people with a diminished capacity to make decisions for themselves, but they rarely last this long.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a filing earlier this week, the 38-year-old indicated that she was happy for the conservatorship to continue - calling it &quot;voluntary&quot; - but she no longer wants her father to be in charge of her affairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jamie Spears and lawyer Andrew M Wallet were Britney&#39;s co-conservators from 2008 until the latter stepped down in 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Spears temporarily stepped down last year, citing health concerns, but retained control of her finances.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jodi Montgomery then became conservator of Britney&#39;s personal affairs. In legal papers lodged last month, Britney said she wanted Montgomery to stay in the role and strongly objected to her father returning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a new filing on Wednesday, she added that she wants a wealth-management company called the Bessemer Trust, to oversee her $57.4 million (&pound;42.5 million) fortune - a move that would push her father out entirely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her father has requested that Mr Wallet be reinstated as conservator, and that documents relating to that request remain sealed. Spears has opposed both motions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her lawyer also argued that the moment her father obtained the power to handle Spears&#39; affairs, he &quot;surrendered a large measure of privacy as to the manner in which he exercises that power&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Transparency is an essential component in order for this court to earn and retain the public&#39;s confidence with respect to protective proceedings like this one,&quot; he wrote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In this case, it is not an exaggeration to say that the whole world is watching.&quot;A hearing on the conservatorship is scheduled for October. Last month, Judge Brenda Penny also extended the current version of the conservatorship until 1 February, 2021, in accordance with Spears&#39; wishes.</p>\r\n</div>', 'Britney Spears, FreeMovement', 'Britney_1599225168.jpg', '2020-09-04 17:12:48', '2021-08-17 06:10:23'),
(115, 7, 6, 45, 'oil-kits-for-strong-weekly-dollar-losses-1599225587', 'Oil kits for strong weekly dollar losses', 0, '<p>Oil in New York is poised for its biggest weekly decline since early June after the dollar&#39;s rise made the US currency&#39;s commodity less attractive, with concerns about excess supply growth.<br />\r\nThis week, futures fell 4.4%, their first weekly loss since late July, as stocks&#39; decline after falling in the US added to the bearish sentiment. Meanwhile, the one-month gap in West Texas intermediate oil is near its biggest constant since June, suggesting investors are concerned about supply amid the devastating demand virus.<br />\r\nOil started to weaken in September after a four-month rally that saw the very large economy still struggling to contain the coronavirus and raised concerns about a sustainable recovery in consumption. This week Iraq signaled that it could seek expansion under the OPEC + deal to implement further production cuts, while China&#39;s crude imports are on a slow and hazy outlook.<br />\r\nThe market will be watching August non-farm wages data due Friday for signs of improvement in the US economy. Economists predict that the unemployment rate will fall below 10% for the first time since March.<br />\r\n&quot;The atmosphere is bad and people are selling risky assets everywhere,&quot; said Howie Lee, an economist at Oversea-Chinese Banking Corp. in Singapore. &quot;The key engine in the near term is tonight&#39;s US payrolls. Strong numbers will send oil back.<br />\r\nPrice<br />\r\nWest Texas Intermediate for October delivery fell 0.8 percent to $ 41.06 a barrel on the New York Mercantile Exchange at 7:55 am London time after falling 0.3 percent on Thursday.<br />\r\n&bull; Brent was traded on ICE Futures Europe in November, rising 0.8% to $ 43.73 after dropping 0.8% in the previous session.<br />\r\no Contracts will be reduced by about 3% this week<br />\r\nThe diesel market is also weighing on the demand outlook. One of the key indicators traders use to gauge market strength to fall to its lowest level in at least nine years is stagnating consumption and a string of bad news for global oil refiners. The fuel is used to power heavy industries such as agriculture and mining, as well as cars and trucks.<br />\r\nMore news about the oil market<br />\r\n&bull; China&#39;s crude oil imports fell 5.4 percent month-on-month to 10.9 million barrels per day and fell from a record high, according to Bloomberg<br />\r\n&bull; A tanker loaded with two million barrels of Kuwaiti crude oil bound for the Paradip India refinery caught fire off the coast of Sri Lanka on Thursday morning over fears of an oil spill.</p>', 'Oil, Price', 'Dollars_1599225587.jpg', '2020-09-04 17:19:47', '2021-08-14 22:40:14'),
(116, 7, 7, 46, 'the-us-created-14-million-jobs-in-august-but-has-still-lost-115-million-jobs-since-covid-1599226817', 'The US created 1.4 million jobs in August but has still lost 11.5 million jobs since Covid', 0, '<p><strong>Employers added another 1.4 million jobs to the US economy in August as the job recovery continued to slow.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This was in line with expectations of an additional 1.7 million jobs in July and 4.8 million in June.<br />\r\nAnyone who can return to work is a triumphant recovery from the unprecedented unemployment crisis caused by the Covid-19 pandemic. However, America still had 11.5 million jobs as of February.<br />\r\nThat means millions of families still need benefits to make ends meet as Congress continues to debate the next stimulus package.<br />\r\nJob recovery slowed in August<br />\r\n1.4 million jobs were added to the US economy in August, four months after losing more than 20 million jobs. More jobs were lost during the pandemic than during the Great Recession or Dotcom Bankruptcy.<br />\r\nThe unemployment rate has fallen to 8.4%. It&#39;s less than 10% for the first time since March - that&#39;s the height of the Great Recession.<br />\r\nThis is a much larger reduction than economists expected and appears to be due to short-term or temporary workers returning to work.<br />\r\nHowever, this increase was offset by several factors. Permanent job losses increased by more than half a million to 3.4 million. More than 8 million Americans have been unemployed for 15 weeks or more.<br />\r\nMeanwhile, the unemployment rate between groups has not improved evenly. The unemployment rate among whites is only 7.3%, while it remains above 10% for black, Spanish and Asian workers. The unemployment rate for blacks is highest at 13%.<br />\r\nDuring last week&#39;s Republican National Convention, President Donald Trump promised to create 10 million new jobs in 10 months. Even if the forecast is fulfilled, the US economy will not win back all the jobs lost in February.<br />\r\nTrump&#39;s promises can be difficult to keep. Recovery is slowing as incentives weaken the influx of sugar, millions of people still work from home, and retail, dining and other services continue to be rocked by the pandemic.<br />\r\nEconomic activity declined in March and April when home orders came into effect and began to improve as the federal government distributed aid, including inspection incentives, expanded unemployment benefits, and loans under a payroll protection program. .<br />\r\nBut recovery has slowed since then. CNN Business&#39;s return to its normal index, which tracks recovery, suggests that it has been largely sideways since June.</p>', 'US, Jobs, Covid', '1.4 m employees_1599226817.jpg', '2020-09-04 17:40:17', '2021-07-25 06:31:48'),
(117, 7, 10, 117, 'mail-voting-begins-when-north-carolina-sends-ballots-demos-are-very-popular-when-there-is-no-application-1599230300', 'Mail voting begins when North Carolina sends ballots. Demos are very popular when there is no application', 0, '<p><strong>Voting by mail began Friday when North Carolina became the first state to send ballots for the 2020 presidential election.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The state is expected to send more than 600,000 ballots to voters in response to an unprecedented surge in demands as some voters try to avoid physical voting amid the coronavirus pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of the ballots requested during the first wave of elections in North Carolina came from Democratic and independent voters. The number of ballots sent by post was 16 times more than the number sent by the state in the same period for the 2016 elections.<br />\r\nIn 2016, only a quarter of voters voted by letter, but this time election officials expected a majority of voters. States like Wisconsin received 100,000 more inquiries than in 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And in Florida, where 3.3 million people requested ballots by mail in 2016, government election officials saw 4.2 million requests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In North Carolina, Republicans have historically dominated postal votes. During that cycle, however, more than 326,000 ballots were requested by Democratic voters and 192,000 by independent voters. Only 92,000 questions came from the Republican Party.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>North Carolina voters can still request ballots by mail through October 27, but officials warn the November 3 election may be too close for staff to receive ballots and return them to local polls in time. . .<br />\r\nFigures in North Carolina and elsewhere show that Republicans are listening to President Trump and his warnings about some types of postal voting and avoiding postal voting, while Democrats are quick to use it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the Democrats&#39; advantage in absentee elections does not necessarily translate to electoral gains. Voting on election day is expected to be largely Republican.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A recent USA Today / Suffolk poll found that 56 percent of Republicans said they would vote directly on election day, compared to just 26 percent of Democrats. Opinion polls show that Democrats are more than twice as likely to vote in absentia or by post than Republicans.<br />\r\nThe postal voting controversy arises as Republicans, including Trump, reject the practice and warn of widespread fraud in upcoming elections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump&#39;s election campaign is already preparing for the possibility of a lengthy legal battle in the event of a controversial election and forming a so-called &quot;Advocates for Trump&quot; coalition to &quot;defend the integrity&quot; of the November vote. Campaign adviser Matthew Morgan told Fox News this week that the campaign encourages active and retired lawyers and even law students to volunteer for their national endeavors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The campaign comes amid a heated war of words between Trump and Joe Biden and their allies&#39; campaigns over the integrity of the vote - from GOP warnings in the Post to Democrat predictions that Trump will refuse to accept defeat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week Trump was heavily criticized for suggesting that people vote twice, first by letter and then in person, just in case. Then he said on Twitter: &quot;On voting day or initial voting, go to your polling station to see if your email vote has been counted (counted). If so, you won&#39;t be able to vote and the mail system will function properly. . If not counted, SELECT (which is the right of citizens). &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>TRUMP CAMPAIGN EVALUATING THE DEMOCRATIC GOVERNOR OF MONTANAS TO END POSITION OPTIONS</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Democratic National Committee has accused Trump of telling people to &quot;commit election fraud&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Trump Advocates Coalition is part of a joint &quot;Vote Protection&quot; campaign by the Republican National Committee and Trump&#39;s Campaign that has warned for months that &quot;Democrats are trying to use the coronavirus and the courts to legalize voting to enforce national policy. Post - in the voting system. and removing almost all precautions in our election. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this time, the Biden campaign has not commented on whether he would assemble such a team of lawyers in the event of a controversial or prolonged campaign, but Mike Guin, director of the Rapid Response Campaign, told Fox News it was ready.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The Biden campaign has made an unprecedented investment in a national program that will give voters access to polling stations and provide all necessary protection against tampering with their voting rights,&quot; Gwyn told Fox News.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, North Carolina is an airtight race on the battlefield. RealClearPolitics&#39; average shows Biden is less than 1% ahead of Trump.</p>', 'DonaldTrump, Voting, Demos', 'Mail in voting_1599230048.jpg', '2020-09-04 18:34:08', '2021-08-17 20:15:05'),
(118, 7, 7, 60, 'the-number-of-coronavirus-cases-remains-unchanged-in-the-uk-1599230902', 'The number of coronavirus cases remains \"unchanged\" in the UK', 0, '<p><strong>Coronavirus levels in the UK community will remain &quot;unchanged&quot; for the week ending August 25, according to the Office for National Statistics.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The latest survey of residents of the house estimates that there are around 2,000 new cases of the corona virus every day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This suggests that despite outbreaks in some local areas, the number of cases has remained stable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The ONS number</strong> provides one of the most accurate infection rate images.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They are based on more than 151,000 tampon tests collected from people at home, whether they have symptoms or not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The number of errors is always limited, as very few people tested positive in the last six weeks of the survey - only 71 out of 68 households.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The numbers also do not include what happens in hospitals or nursing homes, where the likelihood of transmission differs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, they continue to provide a definite picture of infections in private households in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>How do I get tested for the coronavirus?<br />\r\nThe Covids test leader is &quot;deeply sorry&quot; for the shortcomings.<br />\r\nWhen summer ends, England will have to face Kovid again.<br />\r\nStomach pain in children can be the corona virus.</strong><br />\r\nThe ONS estimates this week from August 19-25, 27,100 people in the community will catch the virus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This was similar to the forecast for the previous week and the previous weeks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Wales, 1,400 people are estimated to have contracted Covid-19 in the week ending August 25 - also unchanged from previous weeks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another type of test - an antibody test using a blood sample - that looks for evidence of previously infected people was conducted in 7,000 people as part of the ONS study.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The results show that about 6% of the population - or one in 17 people - has had the coronavirus in the past.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That&#39;s the equivalent of 2.7 million people in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>R. Number<br />\r\nThe R-number for the UK is between 0.9 and 1.1, according to government advisers, meaning the number of people with the virus remains constant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reproductive number or R is the average number of people who will transmit the virus to an infected person.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>R number 1 means that on average every infected person has infected another person, which means the number of transmission is stable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This R estimate is more of an indication of a general trend than a description of what&#39;s happening today.</p>', 'coronavirus, unchange numbers', 'CoronaVirus_1599230902.jpg', '2020-09-04 18:48:22', '2021-08-17 10:21:18'),
(119, 7, 7, 30, 'mother-slaughters-five-of-her-kids-in-german-town-1599234527', 'Mother slaughters five of her kids in German town', 0, '<p><strong>Berlin:</strong> German police have discovered the assortments of five kids in a loft in the western town of Solingen. Detail was given by mass-selling newspaper in its online edition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reporter given detailed that the kids&#39; grandma had called police to reveal to them her girl, matured 27, had executed five of her kids and was out of her home with a further kid. The police at that point found the dead youngsters, matured 1, 2, 3, 6 and 8.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The mother hopped before a train in Duesseldorf, close to Solingen, in the early evening and made due with genuine wounds, Reporter furthur told, including that a 11-year-old child was discovered safe at the grandma&#39;s home</p>', 'slaughters, kids, Mother', 'Polzei_1599234527.jpg', '2020-09-04 19:48:47', '2021-05-22 18:35:04'),
(120, 7, 6, 53, 'netanyahu-secretly-consented-to-us-arms-deal-plan-with-uae-1599235179', 'Netanyahu secretly consented to US arms deal plan with UAE', 0, '<p>NEW YORK: Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu obliged an arrangement for the Trump organization to sell progressed US weapons to the United Arab Emirates (UAE), in spite of emerging as an opponent of the arrangement openly, The New York Times announced Friday, refering to authorities acquainted with the exchanges.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The authorities said that the Israeli leader permitted the deals with an end goal to &quot;standardize&quot; relations between his nation and the Emirates before the updates on the conciliatory advancement became open toward the end of last month, as per the paper.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Donald Trump declared in August that the UAE would stretch out acknowledgment to Israel in return for a guaranteed end to Israeli addition of the involved West Bank an area.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the discretionary understanding was reported, the Trump organization pushed an arms deal manage the UAE that would incorporate the acquisition of F-35 secrecy warriors and furnished automatons, as per the Times.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The US bargain additionally allegedly incorporates a formerly unreported shipment of EA-18G Growler streams, the Times detailed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Netanyahu has recently called reports of the business &quot;counterfeit news&quot; and demanded Israel would not uphold an arrangement under those conditions. Be that as it may, authorities who addressed the Times negated his open proclamations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>American authorities demanded that the arrangement was not an immediate prize for the UAE consenting to perceive Israel, however said the nation&#39;s understanding had mellowed US restriction to such deals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The arrangement despite everything faces a tough move in Congress, because of laws against weapons deals that debilitate Israel&#39;s bit of leeway, as indicated by the Times.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ron Dermer, Israel&#39;s represetative to the US, said in an explanation that it is &quot;false&quot; that Netanyahu has approved the deal. Dermer included he stays sure the Trump organization &quot;is completely dedicated to keeping up&quot; the Israeli military favorable position.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hussein Ibish, a researcher at the Arab Gulf States Institute in Washington, told that he had gotten with sources in each of the three countries that the Israeli PM had endorsed the deal however expected to conceal any hint of failure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve heard it from parties on each of the three sides that he gave a green light on this,&quot; he was cited as saying.</p>', 'US amrs, UAE Deal', 'Benjamin Netanyahu_1599235179.jpg', '2020-09-04 19:59:39', '2021-08-14 22:40:02'),
(121, 7, 7, 39, 'pompeo-declares-new-limitations-on-chinese-ambassadors-in-us-1599237182', 'Pompeo declares new limitations on Chinese ambassadors in U.S', 0, '<p>WASHINGTON (Reuters) - The United States said on Wednesday it would require senior Chinese ambassadors to get State Department endorsement before visiting U.S. college grounds or holding social occasions with in excess of 50 individuals outside mission grounds.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Washington cast the move as a reaction to Beijing&#39;s limitations on American ambassadors in China. It comes as a component of a Trump organization crusade against supposed Chinese impact tasks and surveillance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The State Department said it would likewise make a move to help guarantee all Chinese government office and consular web-based media accounts were &quot;appropriately recognized.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;re just requesting correspondence,&quot; U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told a news instructions. &quot;Access for our representatives in China ought to be intelligent of the entrance that Chinese ambassadors in the United States have, and the present advances will move us considerably toward that path.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was the most recent U.S. venture to control Chinese movement in the United States in the approach the November presidential political decision, in which President Donald Trump has made an extreme way to deal with China a key international strategy stage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>China&#39;s Washington government office called the move &quot;one more outlandish limitation and boundary on Chinese strategic and consular staff&quot; that &quot;contradicts oneself announced estimations of receptiveness and opportunity of the U.S. side.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pompeo additionally said the State Department had composed as of late to the overseeing sheets of U.S. colleges making them aware of dangers presented by the Chinese Communist Party.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These dangers can come as illegal financing for research, licensed innovation burglary, terrorizing of unfamiliar understudies and obscure ability enrollment endeavors,&quot; Pompeo said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said colleges could help guarantee they had clean speculations and blessing assets by uncovering Chinese firms in such assets and dropping those associated with denials of basic freedoms.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Tuesday, Pompeo said he was cheerful the many Chinese-government subsidized Confucius Institute social focuses on U.S. grounds, which he blamed for attempting to enroll &quot;spies and teammates,&quot; would all be closed continuously end.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Wednesday, the Washington-based Confucius Institute U.S. Focus, which was required a month ago to enlist as an unfamiliar crucial Pompeo blamed it for propelling Beijing&#39;s &quot;insult impact,&quot; said it had been misrepresented by the State Department as a central command for Confucius Institutes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In opposition to what individuals have gotten with the State Department, CI programs in the U.S. are free of one another, set up and run by the schools that decide to set up Chinese language instruction, and staffed by individuals recruited and regulated by those schools,&quot; it said in an announcement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pompeo said he wanted to examine China and other provincial issues with the 10-country Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and other Indo-Pacific nations in virtual gatherings one week from now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The State Department said Pompeo would partake in an East Asia Summit Foreign Ministers&#39; gathering and another with his ASEAN partners on Sept. 9.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It said that on Sept. 11, he would dispatch a participation organization with Mekong River accomplice nations, Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand, and Vietnam, planned for reinforcing their self-sufficiency, financial autonomy, and manageable turn of events.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Likewise that day, he will partake in a gathering of the ASEAN Regional Forum, a 27-country gathering carrying ASEAN with discourse accomplices from around the globe.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wednesday&#39;s U.S. move goes farther than one final October requiring Chinese ambassadors to pull out of gatherings with state and neighborhood authorities and at instructive and research establishments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The State Department has likewise required Chinese news sources to enlist as unfamiliar missions and declared in March it was cutting the quantity of columnists permitted to work at U.S. workplaces of significant Chinese news sources to 100 from 160.</p>', 'New Limitations, U.S, Chines Ambassadors', 'Flag_1599237182.jpg', '2020-09-04 20:33:02', '2021-08-18 06:04:58'),
(122, 7, 6, 66, 'the-us-israeli-delegation-ends-with-a-historic-flight-in-the-united-arab-emirates-palestine-and-iran-are-not-satisfied-1599240478', 'The US-Israeli delegation ends with a historic flight in the United Arab Emirates. Palestine and Iran are not satisfied', 0, '<p>A US-Israeli Delegation, driven by Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and White House counsel and Son in-law of U.S president Donald Trump Jared Kushner, showed up in Abu Dhabi on Monday on the notable first business departure from Tel Aviv to check the standardization of ties between the Jewish state and the United Araab Emirates.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Flight LY971 of Israeli public transporter El Al is the principal ever business trip between the two Middle Eastern countries. What makes this flight significantly more noteworthy is that Saudi Arabia permitted the trip to cross its airspace, denoting the first run through an Israeli business plane uses A saudi area for an overflight.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The plane conveying the designation has &quot;tranquility&quot; composed on it in three distinct dialects: English, Hebrew, and Arabic. The flight was additionally named after &quot;Kiryat Gat&quot;, a city worked in 1950 on the remaining parts of two ethnically purified.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The deligation will put last contacts to the disputable harmony bargain reported on August 13, among Israel and UAE.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Response of Palestine:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Palestinian Prime Minister Mohammed Shtayyeh communicated his disappointment and hammered the trip as &quot;an unmistakable and unmitigated infringement of the Arab position towards the Arab-Israeli clash&quot;. &quot;We had would have liked to see an Emirati plane arriving in freed Jerusalem, yet we live in a troublesome Arab period,&quot; he included.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Response of Iran:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Iran&#39;s Khamenei called the move &#39;a double-crossing&#39;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Obviously, the UAE&#39;s double-crossing won&#39;t keep going long, however this disgrace will consistently be recalled. They permitted the Zionist system to enter the locale and overlooked Palestine,&quot; Khamenei said and included, &quot;The Emiratis will be disrespected perpetually [...] I trust they wake up and make up for what they did.&quot;</p>', 'Delegation, US-Israerl', '5f4e2dcc7abc0_1599240477.jpg', '2020-09-04 21:27:58', '2021-08-17 17:56:23'),
(123, 7, 7, 63, 'the-un-chief-called-for-steps-to-be-taken-to-end-enforced-disappearances-1599240705', 'The UN chief called for steps to be taken to end enforced disappearances', 0, '<p>UNITED NATIONS: The UN on Sunday called for increased efforts to end enforced disappearances, saying &quot;brutal crimes&quot; are often used as a strategy to spread terror in society.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The crime of enforced disappearance is widespread all over the world,&quot; Secretary General Antonio Guterres said in a message on the International Day of Victims of Disappearances. &quot;We see new cases almost every day, including the disappearance of environmentalists, often local.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Meanwhile,&quot; he added, &quot;the excruciating pain of the old cases is still acute as the fate of thousands of missing people remains unknown, making crime invariably in the lives of loved ones.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Disappearances have become a global problem - not limited to certain regions of the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previously, as a result of military dictatorship, according to the United Nations, enforced disappearances can now be carried out in situations of complex internal conflicts, especially as a means of political repression against opponents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of particular concern relates to the continued harassment of human rights defenders, relatives of victims, witnesses and legal counsel working on enforced disappearances.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The UN Committee and the Working Group on Enforced Disappearances have identified other worrying trends, said Guterres, &quot;including the repression of victims&#39; families and members of civil society, often in the name of security and the fight against terrorism.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also of concern is the use of enforced disappearances by the state to combat terrorist activity as an excuse for breaches of their obligations, as well as widespread criminal activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Impunity combines suffering and fear,&quot; he said, adding, &quot;It is imperative to carry out a credible and impartial investigation.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Under international human rights law, families and communities have the right to know the truth about what happened.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I urge Member States to take on this responsibility,&quot; he stressed. Hundreds of thousands of people have disappeared in conflict or periods of repression in at least 85 countries around the world, according to the United Nations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;With the support of international human rights mechanisms, states have a duty to increase efforts to prevent enforced disappearances, search for victims and increase support for victims and their families,&quot; said the senior UN official.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Special attention should be paid to vulnerable groups such as children and persons with disabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;On this international day, let us renew our commitment to ending all enforced disappearances,&quot; he said, calling on all countries to &quot;ratify the Convention on the Protection of All Persons from Enforced Disappearance and accept the competence of the committee to handle individual complaints.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He called it &quot;the first but decisive step in eliminating this heinous crime&quot;.</p>', 'UN Chief, Enforced disappearance', 'UN Chief_1599240705.jpg', '2020-09-04 21:31:45', '2021-08-18 04:08:13'),
(124, 7, 10, 72, 'trump-accepted-the-nomination-and-attacked-biden-when-the-republican-convention-ended-1599241256', 'Trump accepted the nomination and attacked Biden when the Republican Convention ended', 0, '<p>WASHINGTON: US President Donald Trump formally accepted the Republican nomination Thursday night before White House lawmakers launched a fiery assault on Joe Biden, his Democratic candidate in the November 3 election, calling him &quot;the Trojan horse for&quot;. called socialism &quot;.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is the most important election in the history of our country. No voter has ever faced a clearer choice between two parties, two visions, two philosophies or two daily plans,&quot; Trump said, after he &quot;heavily&quot; accepted his party&#39;s candidacy. will be.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As America is hit by the deadly coronavirus pandemic, deep recession, and racial unrest, Trump has proposed a blurry agenda for a second term and has instead focused on Biden&#39;s beading 41 times. Biden accepted the Democratic Presidential nomination last week and never mentioned Trump by name.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At the National Democratic Congress, Joe Biden and his party repeatedly attacked America as a land of racial, economic and social injustice,&quot; Trump said. &quot;So I am asking a very simple question tonight: how do the Democrats want to lead our country when they spend so much time destroying our country?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump hoisted flags on the red carpet at the White House, a decision that raised ethical concerns and questions whether it violated the Hatches Act, which prohibits federal officials from engaging in political activity while on duty. The President is exempt from this law. In the past four days, Trump and his officials have made numerous unorthodox White House appearances during Republican National Convention (RNC) events.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ethics expert Norm Eisen described Trump&#39;s conventional speech at the White House as &quot;the greatest mass breach in US history&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In particular, the RNC lacked several important party figures and the presence of the last Republican President George W. Bush. The Democratic Convention, meanwhile, contained speeches by former Republican elected officials who turned out to be outspoken critics of the president.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Thursday, advisers to two of the previous Republican candidates, the late John McCain and Utah Senator Mitt Romney, issued statements in support of Biden. The Biden campaign hopes that support will motivate moderates and Republicans to support centric Democrats.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to a new study by CNBC-Change Research released Wednesday, Biden, the former vice president, leads President Trump on the battlefields in six major states and is staying less than three months before election day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a lengthy speech, Trump accused his opponents of &quot;catastrophic treason and failure&quot; and warned of &quot;left anarchy and chaos&quot; if Democrats were to reclaim the White House, despite fears of widespread protests against systemic racism and police harassment this summer. triggered.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Joe Biden is not a savior of American souls,&quot; Trump said. &quot;He&#39;s an American job destroyer. And if he gets the chance, he&#39;s going to be a destroyer of American greatness.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speakers before Trump largely highlighted the gruesome stories of angry mobs who ignored the pandemic that left more than 180,000 Americans dead and up to 30 million Americans unemployed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Several high-level speakers, mostly Republicans, shared the evening, including Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell, Senate Chief, Tom Cotton, House Minority Speaker, Kevin McCarthy, daughter and adviser to President Ivanka Trump, and former Rudolf W. Giuliani York and a private lawyer. President.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump took over the stage hours after Hurricane Laura hit parts of eastern Louisiana and Texas, leaving at least four people dead and extensive damage. This is the basis of a convention in which no speaker is aware of the threat of man-made global warming. a phenomenon that Trump rejects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His remarks also came as protests and widespread vandalism, which escalated this week after police in Kenosha, Wisconsin, shot black man Jacob Blake seven times in front of his children.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even though protests erupted on Trump&#39;s custody, spokesmen alone accused Democrats and warned that Biden would make the country less secure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You can have President Trump for four more years,&quot; said Patrick Lynch, president of the New York Police Union, &quot;or you may not have security, justice and peace.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When President Trump accepted the Republican nomination for re-election in South Meadow, hundreds of demonstrators gathered outside the White House barricades to protest against racism and police brutality.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, on Thursday, Biden and his deputy, Senator Kamala Devi Harris, harshly criticized Trump for tackling the pandemic and racial relations and effectively preparing for the president&#39;s speech that afternoon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Miss Harris systematically blames the President&#39;s &quot;catastrophic&quot; mismanagement of the virus. The former prosecutor provided courtroom-style evidence to accuse Trump of demonstrating a &quot;cruel disregard for the welfare of the American people&quot; by not taking the coronavirus in January and February seriously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Instead of facing the toughest moment in his presidency, Donald Trump froze,&quot; Harris said. He was timid, petty, and vengeful.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'DonaldTrump, Biden', 'Trump_1599241256.jpg', '2020-09-04 21:40:56', '2021-08-16 07:41:24'),
(125, 7, 7, 31, 'former-prime-minister-of-australia-tony-abbott-appointed-as-uk-trade-advisor-1599245340', 'Former Prime Minister of Australia Tony Abbott appointed as UK Trade Advisor', 0, '<p><strong>Former Australian Prime Minister Tony Abbott has been appointed as unpaid trade advisor to the British government, according to the BBC.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boris Johnson dismissed claims that Abbott was inappropriate for the role of his previous commentary on women, LGBT people and climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The British Prime Minister said he &quot;disagrees with this view&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But he said he &quot;couldn&#39;t be expected&quot; to agree with someone working with the government.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that Abbott was elected by &quot;the great liberal democracy in Australia&quot; and added, &quot;I think that speaks for itself.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The role is not paid for and it is understood that he will not play a direct role in future trade negotiations rather than advising ministers and officials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Union leader Sir Keir Starmer said he had &quot;real concerns&quot; and &quot;would not appoint Abbott&quot; if he became prime minister.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Who is Tony Abbott?<br />\r\nBritain is &quot;drowsy in disaster&quot; beyond border plans<br />\r\nNew Zealand was &quot;disappointed&quot; by British trade talks</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nMR.Abbott, who was Australia&#39;s Prime Minister from 2013 to 2015, said he has spoken to British ministers about the role but this has not been officially confirmed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The letter reads, &quot;This is a man who describes abortion as the &#39;easy way out&#39; and suggests that men may be physiologically or more eagerly adapted to exercise power or give orders.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abbott is said to be &quot;fighting hard&quot; against a successful gender equality referendum in Australia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;For all these reasons and more, this person cannot represent Britain as our trade ambassador,&quot; the letter added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Abbott&#39;s sister, Christine Forster, defended him against accusations of misogyny and homophobia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As a woman who was always a part of her life and came to her as gay in her early 40s, I know Tony is not one of those things,&quot; she wrote on Twitter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Indeed, he is a man of great faith and intelligence; an undisturbed conservative, but with great compassion, respect for others, and an indispensable sense of doing the right thing.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that because of his experience entering into trade deals with Japan, China and South Korea, he would be &quot;the exclusive trade ambassador for Britain&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Abbott&#39;s position is on the UK Board of Directors, a group of experts formed to advise International Trade Secretary Liz Truss.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Thursday, Health Secretary Matt Hancock was asked by Sky News about concerns about Abbott&#39;s treatment of women and homosexuality.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Hancock said he did not think Mr Abbott was homophobic or misogynistic and when encouraged he added, &quot;He is also a trade expert.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Nausea&quot;<br />\r\nLabor also urged the government not to appoint Abbott on the grounds that it was &quot;totally unacceptable&quot; and &quot;instead to seek experts with views on women and equality that better reflect our British values&quot;. &quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Labor MP Chris Bryant and Wes Street accused Hancock of hypocrisy after the Health Minister posted on Twitter about a new &quot;fantastic&quot; LGBT relationship and sex education program being launched at schools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Bryant said, &quot;Why do you think of Tony Abbott as a trade ambassador?&quot; while Mr Streeting wrote on Twitter, &quot;Matt, we know you are a social liberal with decent experience choosing LGBT equality. That&#39;s why your defense of Tony Abbott is even worse.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the Commons on Thursday, International Trade Minister Liz Truss was asked about possible dates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following criticism from Labor MP Ruth Cadbury, Ms. Trass said: &quot;I think it is hypocritical to hear this kind of argument from the Labor Party.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is a party that has never elected a female leader, although there are always opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The reality is that they prefer to show benevolence and indulge in symbolism rather than take concrete action to improve women&#39;s lives.</p>', 'Tony Abbott, Trade Advisor', 'Ex PM_1599245340.jpg', '2020-09-04 22:49:00', '2021-06-15 21:47:59'),
(126, 7, 6, 48, 'technical-stocks-slumped-as-wall-street-moved-in-the-opposite-direction-1599246052', 'Technical stocks slumped as Wall Street moved in the opposite direction', 0, '<p><strong>US and Asian stock markets reversed after shares in major US technology companies fell</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Companies that took the US market to record highs - Apple, Amazon, Alphabet, Microsoft and Facebook - fell between 4% and 8%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Analysts said concerns over the economic shock from the coronavirus and a possible second wave had sparked a sell-off.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Tech Nasdaq closed 5%, the Dow Jones fell nearly 3%, and the S&amp;P 500 lost 3.5%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Asian trade, the Nikkei index in Tokyo fell 1%, while the Hang Seng in Hong Kong fell 1.4%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Apple is worth more than the entire FTSE 100<br />\r\nProfits are multiplied by increasing sales<br />\r\nTrump or Biden? China does not expect any services</strong><br />\r\nAutomaker Tesla, whose shares have jumped this year, fell 9 percent on Thursday after falling sharply in the last two sessions. Another tech heavyweight, Nvidia, lost 9.3%. Apple&#39;s 8% drop means $ 150 billion (&pound; 113 billion) has been cut from the value of the iPhone maker.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The sell-off came after mixed US economic data on Thursday, including reports of slower service sector growth in August, an unexpected sharp drop in new jobless claims, this year&#39;s record layoffs and an unexpectedly high trade deficit. for July.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although the recent weekly initial jobless claims have fallen more than expected, they remain high amid growing concerns that job growth may stop without additional economic stimulus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Charles Evans, chairman of the Chicago Federal Reserve, said Thursday that Congress will need more tax relief. He said US monetary policy would be further relaxed and interest rates would be kept very low for years to help the economy regain pre-pandemic strength.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Growing concerns over the health of the US economy are highlighted by the Vix Index, also known as the &quot;Anxiety Measure&quot;. It reached the highest level since mid-July.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The mood was not helped by warnings from US infectious disease expert Dr. Anthony Fauci, who is already improving, doubts a Covid-19 vaccine will be developed by the end of October.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>US elections<br />\r\nThe decline in the US hit European markets. The London FTSE 100 ended 1.5% on 5,850 points and the German Dax fell 1.4%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week Wall Street has hit new highs for what Connor Campbell, financial analyst at Spreadex, described as &quot;a combination of relatively unsubstantiated speculation with vaccines and incentives&quot;. The market is now seeing a &quot;sharp turn&quot;, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The S&amp;P 500 and Nasdaq closed at record levels on Wednesday, and the Dow hit 1.5% from its February highs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Emily Roland, co-chair of investment strategist at John Hancock Investment Management, says markets need to be tested in real life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Think about the increasing amount of risk that the market has diminished over the last few months. We have 60 days left before the election. This could be an area where investors get a little intimidation,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Stocks, Slumped', '_112871958_mediaitem112871957_1599246052.jpg', '2020-09-04 23:00:52', '2021-08-12 21:07:06');
