(127, 7, 5, 46, 'rival-jockey-forces-for-leadership-roles-in-hypersonic-aircraft-1599248102', 'Rival jockey forces for leadership roles in hypersonic aircraft', 0, '<p><strong>&quot;I&#39;ve spent my career on things flying fast,&quot; says Adam Dissel, who heads up the US operations of Reaction Engines.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>This British company is building engines that can operate at dizzying speeds,</strong> under conditions that would melt existing jet engines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The firm wants to reach hypersonic velocity, beyond five times the speed of sound, around 4,000mph (6,400km/h) or Mach 5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The idea is to build a high-speed passenger transport by the 2030s. &quot;It doesn&#39;t have to go at Mach 5. It can be Mach 4.5 which is easier physics,&quot; says Mr Dissel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At those kinds of speeds you could fly from London to Sydney in four hours or Los Angeles to Tokyo in two hours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, most research into hypersonic flight is not for civil aviation. It originates from the military, where there&#39;s been a burst of activity in recent years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&#39;Zoo of systems&#39;</strong><br />\r\nJames Acton is a UK physicist who works for the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace in Washington. Surveying the efforts of the US, China and Russia in hypersonic weapons he concludes that &quot;there&#39;s a whole zoo of hypersonic systems on the drawing board&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Special materials that can withstand the extreme heat created around Mach 5, and a host of other technologies, are making hypersonic flight in the Earth&#39;s atmosphere possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><big><strong>More Technology of Business</strong></big></p>\r\n\r\n<p><big><strong>Seaweed: The food and fuel of the future?<br />\r\nHow to fix erratic clothing sizes?<br />\r\nStress and burnout and redundancy in IT<br />\r\nTracking down billions of litres of lost water<br />\r\nRobots find their own way deep in the ocean</strong></big></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Experiments in piloted hypersonic flight date back to America&#39;s X-15 rocket-plane of the 1960s. And Intercontinental Ballistic Missiles (ICBMs) also re-enter the atmosphere at very high hypersonic speeds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now rival powers are striving to create weapons that can stay within the atmosphere, without needing to utilise the cooling properties of outer space, and that can be manoeuvred - unlike a static ICBM aimed at a city - towards a target that might be moving itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Carrier-killers</strong><br />\r\nMilitary spending is driving the hypersonic push by the three big national players.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a recent Pentagon media briefing Mike White, assistant director for hypersonics in the US military, talked about development being driven by &quot;our great power competitors and their attempts to challenge our domain dominance&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Accuracy is a major challenge for this hypersonic missile.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Possession of hypersonic missiles, called &quot;carrier killers,&quot; could force US carriers to move away from China&#39;s Pacific coast.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, hitting a nuclear-powered carrier traveling at speeds of 30 knots or more (35 miles per hour or 56 km / h) requires fine adjustments to the rocket heading which is difficult to achieve at Mach 5.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The heat generated around the rocket shell creates plasma or gaseous matter at supersonic speeds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This can block signals received from external sources such as communications satellites, and can blind internal guidance systems that are trying to locate moving objects outside.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plasma only accumulates where the highest temperatures are found.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The cone-shaped missile has a flat plasma layer, but the missile that looks like an elegant wing arrow can repel this plasma screen from the surface with the most refined antennae.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Shark cheeks</strong><br />\r\nAs if hypersonic flight wasn&#39;t difficult enough, chemical dissociation added to the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At extreme speeds and temperatures, this phenomenon causes oxygen molecules to break down into their atoms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This in turn complicates the chemical model on which every air breathing machine is based.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The advances in the hypersonic arms race have been dramatic. In 2010, the United States flew a shark-jaw drone over parts of the Pacific Ocean for five minutes at hypersonic speeds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The goal is more than pure speed. It is time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Five minutes may not sound like a long flight, but it is a victory when it comes to overcoming supersonic obstacles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This high-speed engine, the X-51A, was shot down by the high-flying B-52 bomber and hit Mach 4.5 with rocket boosters before starting the main engine.<br />\r\nKnown as a scramjet, this engine combines airflow with jet fuel in a serrated inlet to accelerate to supersonic speeds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This means dealing with the temperature of the air entering the inlet at 1000 &deg; C for several minutes. Finally, four X-51As departed on a one-way trip across the Pacific between 2010 and 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Shock wave</strong><br />\r\nAerojet Rocketdyne is a space engine and rocket engine specialist in California working on the X-51A. The level of confidentiality associated with this technology is that even seven years after the project ended, employees were simply speaking anonymously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A hypersonic expert for the company told the X-51A, &quot;The really hot engine part is up front, where the shock waves are forming, so that&#39;s where the material investment flows.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said that much was learned from the X-15 rocket aircraft and subsequent space shuttle programs in the 1960s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Reaction Engine is now demonstrating a process that will allow its air motor to absorb superheated hypersonic air without a hiccup.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His Saber had what he called &quot;pre-cooling&quot;. It is the first part of the engine to collide with hot, angry hypersonic air.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then the challenge is to mix with fuel to create traction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Hot like lava</strong><br />\r\nThe Saber engine underwent an intensive test mode at the Colorado facility in October 2019, where the reaction engine had to find a way to reproduce hypersonic flight speeds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The company took the supersonic engine, installed it, and directed the exhaled air from behind into the Saber engine entrance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pre-cooling the Saber does its job by injecting coolant into the system under high pressure and allowing the Saber to mix this air with the fuel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The materials needed here are not easy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The shuttle relies on high-temperature composite tiles to protect it from re-entering Earth&#39;s atmosphere. However, this requires extensive technical support, which is impractical for commercial traffic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An alternative approach is to use a nickel alloy called Inconel, which can handle a stream of air, which is heated to the same intensity as a lava flow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Dissel, Reaction Engines are now taking the Inconel alloy line. &quot;This is where we are now and there are also cooling channels for extracting heat,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The advanced thermal management system combined with Inconel shows the way to the future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Hypersonic guide</strong><br />\r\nIf this combination works, the vision of paying for passengers on hypersonic flights could become a reality in 15 years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The potential for hypersonic travel to allow VIPs to arrive with maximum impact was discovered by the US Air Force&#39;s Presidential Aircraft Division.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He hired Atlanta-based hypersonic launch company Hermeus to evaluate the Mach 5 transport design, which can carry up to 20 passengers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This means that one day the President of the United States could join the highly defensive group of Mach 5 travelers.</p>', 'AirCraft, Rival, Leadership', 'Hypersonic aircraft_1599248102.jpg', '2020-09-04 23:35:02', '2021-08-14 22:40:46'),
(128, 7, 5, 54, 'algae-food-and-future-fuel-1599250432', 'Algae: food and future fuel?', 0, '<p>The sun changes the wind and the rain as motorboats wind their way through the fiords of the Faroe Islands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s a little windy in here,&quot; said Olavur Gregarsen. &quot;We&#39;ll see how far we can get to the harvest ship.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We soon reached a shelter where steep mountains looked out over hundreds of buoys floating on the sea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;They maintain a horizontal line,&quot; explains Gregarsen, managing director of Ocean Rainforest, an algae producer. &quot;Every meter has a different line and algae grows there.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Breaking waves<br />\r\nThe aquaculture platform, which is installed on the ocean floor, consists of 50,000 m (164,000 ft) of underwater, grating-like cables designed for harsh marine conditions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The main structure is 10 meters deeper. That way we avoid the biggest break from the waves,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite Denmark&#39;s remote location in the North Atlantic, according to Gregarsen, the nutrient-rich deep waters are suitable for growing algae with stable temperatures between 6 &deg; C and 11 &deg; C.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His company is part of a wave of algal farming that is emerging in Europe and North America, driven by growing demand from the food and other industries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;They have biomass that can be used for food and feed, replacing fossil products as plastic packaging materials,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>mechanization<br />\r\nAlgae are fast growing algae. They use energy from sunlight and absorb nutrients and carbon dioxide from seawater. Scientists suggest that algae could help fight climate change and offset carbon emissions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ocean Rainforest was recently funded by the US Department of Energy to build a similar system in California, where there is interest in developing industrial algae production for future biofuels.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a classic car, the captain controls a mechanical arm that lifts the rope out of the water. Algae are cut freely by filling the container. It&#39;s a fast, messy job. The lines are then allowed to grow. This year, around 200 tonnes will be harvested.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the company is growing and plans to double its capacity this year. No money has yet been made, but it&#39;s expected soon, Mr said. Gregarsen to me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We can see how we can mechanize this, how we can make this a very effective activity on a large scale,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Not many companies are doing this as a profitable business if anything.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cosmetics and medicine<br />\r\nAlgae need to be processed quickly. In a small factory in Faroe village in Kaldbak, harvesting machines. Some are dried and sent to food factories. The remainder is fermented and sent to animal feed producers.<br />\r\nMost agricultural algae are consumed with food, but their extracts are used in a wide variety of products. Regardless of whether it is toothpaste, cosmetics, pharmaceuticals or pet food, they often contain hydrocolloids from algae with gelling or thickening properties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As more products arrive, other companies are working on textiles and plastic alternatives, including biodegradable packaging, water capsules and straws.<br />\r\nAlgae production is booming. According to the Food and Agriculture Organization, the volume doubled between 2005 and 2015 to more than 30 million tonnes per year. It is a company valued at more than $ 6 billion (&pound; 5 billion) worldwide.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, only a small proportion of the cultivation takes place outside Asia, where agriculture has long existed but is largely labor-intensive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Lots of effort&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Labor costs in Europe are very high, so that&#39;s a big part of it,&quot; said Annette Brun, senior scientist at Aarhus University in Denmark.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;A lot of effort has to be made to make it mechanic and scale.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To make agriculture economical, he said: &quot;The yields must be increased and costs must be lowered.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the agricultural system is not easy to reproduce. &quot;Different areas in different bodies of water all require modification. It is not expected that one solution will fit everyone,&quot; said Ms. Bruhn.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, he hopes and says there are &quot;many areas where you can make a breakthrough&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is what innovators like Sintef are trying to do. Norwegian research groups are working on new technologies to rationalize agriculture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Most of the algae is now used for food, but in the future we want to use it for fish feed, fertilizer and biogas. We need large quantities and we need to produce faster,&quot; said scientist Silje Forbord.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dry lab<br />\r\nA prototype machine such as a seaweed spinner automatically wraps a spool of yarn with seeds on a rope ready for use in the sea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another concept, SPoke (standard algae production), consists of a circular farming module in which algae grows from a line radiating outward. It is designed in such a way that the robot can move on spokes like a wheel - either to tie threads with young algae or to collect them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We make a hand with a robot that goes back and forth. It has been tested in a dry laboratory,&quot; explained Ms. Forbord, but more investment is needed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AlgaPlus grows inland algae in a number of lakes and reservoirs in northern Portugal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s a much more controlled environment,&quot; said managing director Helena Abreu, who believes it has more of an advantage over offshore farming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We maintain the temperature and everything in the tank,&quot; he said. &quot;You have year-round production.&quot;<br />\r\nMs. Abreu co-founded the company after working as a marine biologist in the Azores for five years. Small, high-quality seaweed is made for high-end food companies, cosmetic manufacturers and restaurants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>innovation<br />\r\nSeawater from the coastal lagoon flows into the lake. This is then pumped through the filter system into the algae tank. There is also a hatchery that plants seeds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have to innovate from the ground up,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These waters are rich in nitrogen, which the algae absorbs and mimics nature. &ldquo;We don&#39;t need additives, we don&#39;t need fertilizer. We use fish water to grow our algae, &rdquo;he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Abreu does not believe that land availability is a limiting factor. Former salt flats and fish farms could be reallocated, he said, noting that there were hectares in Portugal, France, Italy, Greece and Turkey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Algae cultivation is also practiced in Canada and South Africa. Microalgae are also grown in the tank system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But there are other challenges.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The biggest obstacle is the energy cost. When you work with the tank, you have to pump it and aerate it to keep the water moving,&quot; said Ms. Abreu.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Companies still can&#39;t stay on sales alone. However, Mrs. Abreu believes that the seaweed market will continue to grow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is a big trend,&quot; he said. &quot;Every year there are more companies. There are new entrants at every step of the value chain.&quot;</p>', 'Food or Fuel, Future', 'seaweed cultivation_1599250432.jpg', '2020-09-05 00:13:52', '2021-08-14 22:36:58'),
(129, 7, 5, 58, 'stress-exhaustion-and-strength-hard-times-at-it-1599251240', 'Stress, Exhaustion and Strength: Hard Times at IT', 0, '<p>You would think that an IT professional could easily turn to teleworking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, according to Jack Stevens, Senior Product Manager at Publicis Sapient, this is a misunderstanding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve only been worried all this time,&quot; he said of the start of the lockdown in Britain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her role involved a lot of teamwork and ad hoc conversation, and when the blockade started, the only conversation she had with her peers was using video conferencing tools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I get a lot of energy when I&#39;m with other people, and suddenly I don&#39;t have it anymore - everything has to go through the screen and it doesn&#39;t give me the social interactions I&#39;m interested in in the long run,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For hours<br />\r\nMr. Stevens struggled with sleep for several weeks, his productivity decreased and he was constantly feeling tired. He constantly worries that he will be fired because he only joined the company a year ago and this, combined with teleworking, kept him working longer hours because he struggled with presenterism.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve worked 10-14 hours on a project for four consecutive weekends and I don&#39;t think I got more work than if I had a normal 9-5 job, but that&#39;s a way to compensate for the fact that people don&#39;t.&quot; They saw you, &quot;he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her employer, Publicis Sapient, says she provides employees with a number of resources &quot;to help them manage their mental health and well-being during these uncertain times,&quot; including free subscriptions to Headspace Attention and Mediation- Apps and access to trained first aid specialists. . for mental health, support &quot;and ear secrecy when needed&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Stevens said that now that he has reduced his working hours, he is in a much better position and believes there is a better work-life balance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The case is ambiguous - more than a third of technology professionals (36%) have seen their mental health deteriorate due to the crisis, according to a May study by technology recruiter Harvey Nash.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than a third of those who were actively concerned about their mental health experienced this fear for the first time in their life. The two main reasons cited by respondents were lack of time for personal isolation (46%) and concerns about losing jobs or contracts during the pandemic (41%).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The crisis means a lot of extra work for IT professionals. And while the job inspection site says the sector is growing right now, it could be a double-edged sword for technical staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Offices are ordered to work 100% remotely immediately, and any technician who&#39;s already under pressure and stress from shaking their foundations suddenly has to make sure they can focus their full attention on their company&#39;s needs in no time,&quot; said Amber Coster.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He started his company, Balpro, with the goal of helping the company look after its employees after exhaustion at tech startups years ago.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There&#39;s a lot of adrenaline and a destination for many tech workers who focus on remote work, but that&#39;s short-lived because once the workforce has moved on, the question for IT staff is &quot;Now what?&quot; &quot; &quot; He says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>IT professionals, like everyone else in the country, then have to deal with managing their normal full-time jobs, as well as other tasks that have changed in the face of the pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Stress&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;I&#39;ve been working long hours, but working from home during a crisis is much more difficult,&quot; said Stu Hearst, cloud security engineer at Just Eat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There is a period of 10 to 12 weeks where my two young children, my wife and I are at home all day, and there are very stressful days,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Harvey Nash&#39;s study of 32% of children with children, parenting and home schooling were cited as the main causes of their stress.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This becomes more difficult because there is less storage to relieve stress or rest and because the system is still under constant pressure to work remotely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;Given the nature of the entire country working from home, these IT systems are much more up and running than ever before. We need to keep apps and tools working together, and this is where IT teams practice well. Shut down. &quot;said Mr. Hearst.<br />\r\nBut Ms. Koster said he was reluctant to blame telework for mental health problems. He believes it is up to managers to set limits on teleworking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The presentation comes when you&#39;re in an office where the working hours are long and it&#39;s really easy to hit those slippery slopes when you&#39;re working remotely,&quot; he says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Weight<br />\r\nLike thousands of other employees, many IT workers have been blown up or completely fired.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;A lot of technicians did a lot of work when everything collapsed, and then half of the team was told they were going to work, which means a smaller percentage of the group carried more of the load.&quot; said Mrs. Koster.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For those who are released, the prospects are dire as well, and have mental health implications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sam Reynolds took a job at Storm Technologies in January and worked with his former employer, Whistles until March. When she started on Storm, she was in a remote work environment, and two and a half weeks after her new role, she was told she would be fired.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It was a pill that was hard to swallow - at a time when my wife and I had a four month old baby and we wanted to move around so everyone could walk out the window,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At that time, Mr. Reynolds believes he will find a new job, but over time he believes the market has deteriorated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the past four months, he&#39;s been applying for six positions every day, getting paid to renew resumes, and completing a number of courses including the ScrumMaster, a project management certificate that many IT professionals crave. before any other candidate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But he didn&#39;t feel that any of this was helpful.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There are times when I want to cry, but I can&#39;t control it, I have no other job,&quot; she said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even workers may not have mental health support - half of employers do not provide formal mental health support and one in seven technicians identify their employer as inadequate for mental health problems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bev White, CEO of Harvey Nash, believes that employers should review their mental health support policies and provide virtual assistance via dedicated webinars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is also important to encourage employees themselves to share their views and experiences on this issue via blogs and deposits,&quot; said Ms. White.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Apart from getting support in the right places, the culture needs to change so that everyone feels that it is their responsibility to look after their co-workers and show a real interest in what they are doing.&quot;</p>', 'HardTime, IT Industry', 'Amber Coaster_1599251240.jpg', '2020-09-05 00:27:20', '2021-08-14 23:45:29'),
(130, 7, 5, 42, 'track-the-three-billion-liters-of-water-lost-1599251663', 'Track the three billion liters of water lost', 0, '<p><strong>You would think that of all the leaks in this country, the ones that occur in the street where a professor of living water systems would be cleaned up pretty quickly. But as Vanessa Speight tells you, sadly, it is not.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s just getting off the sidewalk and walking down the street,&quot; said Professor Speite, a drinking water quality expert at the University of Sheffield. He first reported the problem to his local water supply about a year ago. Despite attempts to find the source of the leak, the company kept drying up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Maybe it&#39;s been six times since they dug the road,&quot; added Prof. Speite.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Across England and Wales, nearly 3 billion liters of water are lost each day, the equivalent of 1,180 Olympic pools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How can engineers identify and repair leaky pipes to avoid the problems Professor Spete reports on his way?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The answer is technology, the water company claims.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Companies across the country are installing tens of thousands of sensors into their pipelines and connections to detect leaks. Some sensors have been in use over the years, but thanks in part to demands from industry authority Ofwat to reduce leaks by 16% over the next five years, the number of devices in use today has risen sharply.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>United Utilities, one of the UK&#39;s largest water companies, currently deploys 102,000 sensors on its network in northwest England. The company has installed 46,000. A large number, but Hannah Wardle, a network utility manager, explained that it only covers 10% of the company&#39;s pipeline.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The sensor uses an accelerometer, the same technology that detects the movement of your smartphone. In this case, however, the accelerometer will detect vibrations that may be associated with a leak anywhere along the pipe.<br />\r\nThere are other sensors, including an acoustic recorder, that can hear the characteristic hum of a working pipe. United Utilities teamed up with Fido Tech to improve an AI system that has been trained on these thousands of data sets. The system can now detect leaks with more than 90% accuracy and estimate them from low to high probability.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Most of the leaks were very likely to have been identified from behind,&quot; said Ms. Wardle.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ability to exploit the true source of these leaks is the holy grail of pipeline maintenance. Ms. Wardle said the United Utilities system wasn&#39;t perfect, but with more data and testing, his team hopes to keep improving it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another technology that helps make installations smart is NB-IoT communications, a means of transmitting signals from thousands of remote sensors using only a fraction of the bandwidth. This means the tubular sensor can send updates to a central server more frequently without draining the battery, which is designed to last.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Again, AI analyzes the increasing amount of data generated by these sensors to automatically detect any signs of leaks. The system should be released later this year, said Woodworth, who hopes SES can better identify leaks before customers report them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Water scarcity is a growing problem in the UK, said Prof. Speith. Efforts to increase UK leakage with big data and AI are the &quot;next generation&quot; of solutions to old problems, he added. However, he noted that the age of the state network was getting under control.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In a lot of cases, it&#39;s not in very good shape and it&#39;s time to really think about large scale replacement,&quot; said Prof. Speight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Nobody wants to deal with the cost, but in reality it has to be done at some point.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While Mr. Woodworth is excited about his company&#39;s new sensors, he agrees that there must be a long-term solution to improving pipeline infrastructure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We can no longer stick adhesive on our network,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Water Lost', '_113221211_leaks.worker.ses.water_1599251663.jpg', '2020-09-05 00:34:23', '2021-08-14 22:42:14'),
(131, 7, 5, 67, 'the-robot-penetrates-deep-into-the-sea-1599252083', 'The robot penetrates deep into the sea', 0, '<p><strong>&quot;It&#39;s very common,&quot; Jess Hanham said casually when asked how often she suspected bombs that had not exploded.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Hanham is a co-founder of Spectrum Offshore, a marine research company that does extensive work on the River Thames.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His company does all kinds of marine research, but working on site for a new offshore wind farm is becoming big business for him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Signals from unexploded ordnance will likely be detected during work on the Thames and other bombed areas during World War II.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You can also find a large number of contacts requiring more research on wind farms identified in the first pre-engineering studies,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nWith this information, project managers can decide whether turbines and other equipment should be located at a safe distance from bombs suspected or detonated by specialized companies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Currently, marine surveys are carried out by teams in boats who collect data and send it back for analysis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes it is a relatively small ship with a crew of two, a surveyor and his equipment. However, a larger inspection project at sea could involve a much larger ship with dozens of crew members and cost around &pound; 100,000 per day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sensor equipment varies depending on the company. Sometimes it could be a sonar grid pulled behind a boat, another job could be an unmanned underwater vehicle that could be controlled by a surface surveyor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bad weather can interfere with work and make life uncomfortable. &quot;I&#39;ve been at sea for nine years and done 10 holes and it&#39;s not a good place to work,&quot; said Brian Allen, CEO of Rovco.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His company is one of the few looking to disrupt this market through the use of artificial intelligence (AI). They see a future where underwater robots called Autonomous Underwater Vehicles (AUVs) can carry out survey work without much human supervision and send the data back to surveyors in offices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bristol-based Rovco is working on an important piece of technology. He trains AI systems to identify seabed objects based on data collected in the ocean. This process took four years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The addition of AI means that the data does not have to be analyzed by someone on board or sent back ashore for evaluation. This work is actually done there and then by AI, which can operate on ships or, soon enough, the underwater robots themselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Without AI, autonomous underwater robots are stupid enough - only to be able to trace pipelines and cables in pre-programmed paths,&quot; Allen said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If the AUV can analyze real-time data, you can actually tell the robot to do something else. If you run into a problem, the survey can stop and more data can be collected while the robot makes its own decisions,&quot; he said. he says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, if the AI signals something that looks like an unexploded bomb, the AI can stop, come back, and perform additional analysis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For some jobs, such as dismantling underwater oil and gas infrastructure, engineers need to know the exact dimensions and location of the equipment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To support this, Rovco has also developed an image processing system that produces accurate maps of underwater infrastructure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The system generates a 3D cloud from individual data points, a format used in modeling software such as CAD. These dots are combined with camera images to create a realistic 3D reconstruction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rovco currently combines vision systems, AI and underwater vehicles in one package.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other companies are also trying to introduce AI into the industry.<br />\r\nJake Tompkins is the UK-based CEO of Modus, which has a fleet of 12 unmanned underwater vehicles. A two-year program will be launched with the University of Durham to develop an artificial intelligence control system that will allow some of their underwater vehicles to detect their location, objects and anomalies during the study.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The combination with Durham is a very effective way to develop technology, because they have proven AI systems for the automotive and aerospace industries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using autonomous underwater robots to explore the ocean floor and inspect underwater structures will be &quot;a game for change,&quot; according to Tompkins, and should cut costs significantly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He believes underwater robots will soon be out in the ocean, perhaps in an offshore wind farm or at an oil or gas facility.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If necessary, they are awakened and sent for data collection, which is sent back to the ground control center for processing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think we may still be two years or more from the first commercial use of autonomous ATVs, but that&#39;s where we are going,&quot; said Tompkins.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His company is currently working on ways to maintain AUV recharging outside of the oceans and technology that can send data back.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are huge rewards for companies that can run and run smart underwater robots. According to Soren Lassen, director of offshore wind research at consultancy Wood Mackenzie, the offshore wind market is expected to grow &quot;enormously&quot; over the next decade.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only six countries currently have offshore wind energy on a commercial scale. In 10 years he predicts 20 countries will join the club.<br />\r\nLast year, 29 gigawatts of offshore wind power were connected to the worldwide grid. Wood Mackenzie estimates 180 gigawatts by 2029.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To do this, thousands of wind turbines had to be built and thousands of kilometers of cables had to be installed to connect these wind farms. All this requires underwater surveyor services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By 2029, most of the work at sea can be done in autonomous systems, with people returning to offices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jess Hanham will continue to update her business with the latest technology, but worries that her job will be of less use.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I love diversity. Because I stay in the office - I&#39;ll hate it. Going out and doing research, coming back and looking at it from start to finish - it gives you a sense of ownership of the job. I really enjoy it when we have a part of it.&quot; I thought that would be very embarrassing. &quot;</p>', 'Robot, New Tchonology, Seep Sea', 'Introduction A1_1599252083.jpg', '2020-09-05 00:41:23', '2021-08-16 15:51:29'),
(132, 7, 7, 49, 'the-blast-in-beirut-hope-for-survivors-is-fading-1599252529', 'The blast in Beirut hope for survivors is fading', 0, '<p><strong>Hopes dwindled in Beirut that after two days of searching, someone would be found under the rubble of buildings destroyed in last month&#39;s explosion.</strong><br />\r\nRescuers began examining the debris after sensing equipment detected possible signs of life.<br />\r\nBut the Chilean rescuers ended their second day of unsuccessful searches.<br />\r\nBeirut was in silence for one minute on Friday, a month after the explosion killed nearly 200 people.<br />\r\nThousands more were injured in the explosion, in which 2,750 tonnes of ammonium nitrate exploded.<br />\r\nHow long can the survivors survive under the rubble?<br />\r\nAngry that so many hazardous materials were stored in warehouses at the city&#39;s ports near many residential areas.<br />\r\nThe resignation of the Lebanese government shortly thereafter did not calm the demonstrators, who clashed with police in the city for several nights.<br />\r\nA month later, seven people are still missing, according to Lebanese authorities.<br />\r\nWhat happened to the request?<br />\r\nThe search began after a Chilean rescue team found possible signs of life under the destroyed building between the Jemayse and Mar Michael districts.<br />\r\nRescuers were walking around Wednesday evening when their sniper dog, trained to find bodies, signaled that someone was inside. When they returned on Thursday, the dog went to the same place and gave the same signal. The special sensor equipment then detects a pulsating signal in the environment.<br />\r\nChilean rescue team leader Francisco Lermanda told reporters on Friday that slow breathing was recorded at a depth of 3 meters under the rubble.<br />\r\nRescuers dug three tunnels to find a pulse was found, he said.<br />\r\nBut it is too early to know whether someone is &quot;dead or alive&quot; under the rubble.<br />\r\nOn the previous Friday, rescue coordinator Nicolas Saade told AFP that the pulse had slowed significantly since the previous day. Local journalists said the latest tests did not detect any signals.<br />\r\nThe crowd gathered to watch the search, expecting a miracle.<br />\r\nMohamed Houri told Reuters he hoped someone was still alive, but that even if only bodies were found, &quot;it is important for their families to find peace.&quot;<br />\r\nThe Chilean team stopped their search on Friday night without finding any victims or bodies. They said they&#39;d come back in the morning.<br />\r\nAccording to local journalists, the Lebanese team is continuing the search.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'Blast, Search of Survivors', 'Beroit people_1599252529.jpg', '2020-09-05 00:48:49', '2021-08-13 13:45:52'),
(133, 7, 4, 44, '2020-us-open-the-defeat-of-dan-evans-ends-britains-singular-hopes-1599252802', '2020 US Open: The defeat of Dan Evans ends Britain\'s singular hopes', 0, '<p>And Evans succumbed to French premature talent Corentin Mute in four sets when Britain&#39;s interest in the US Open singles ended on Friday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The second round of fixtures resumed after rain fell on Thursday as Evans appeared to be the favorite, gaining 2-1 in sets after 4-1.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, 21-year-old Mute struggled for the third set and led the fourth with a draw after a 4-1 deficit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mute sealed a 4-6 6-3 7-6 (7-5) 7-6 (6-1) win after Evans made a mistake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The release of the 23rd seed immediately followed compatriot Cameron Nori&#39;s third round defeat by Spaniard Alejandro Davidovich Fokina, also in fifth place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A beautiful mute overpowered Evans<br />\r\nEvans looks like a mirror image of himself in the world number 77, explosive and quick on the pitch, with lots of variety in his game. They are also excited when they verbally express their views about themselves and those in the crowd.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The pair were difficult to separate on Thursday before the game was stopped and on the resumption, it was no surprise that Evans held on to serve at 6-5 to clinch the third set with a draw.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The English number one won 4-1 before forehand and backhand errors allowed Moutet to equalize and then move on until Evans found the net. The great first serve was won and decided by the French tie-breaker at 5&#39;9 &#39;&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Evans regrouped and appeared to be strong favorites to win the game decisively. He led 4-1 after breaking his opponent&#39;s serve in the second game. But once again, the spicy Moutet leveled it up to return to game seven with delightful compliments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Evans looked annoyed while Moutet&#39;s serve game looked excellent. The draw was a one-sided affair as England fell and a hit in the net gave their opponent the win.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previously, Nori led with a breakthrough in the third set but then lost 11 of the last 12 games until she suffered a 7-6 (7-2) 4-6 6-2 6-1 loss in the third round in New York.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 25-year-old&#39;s usual mistakes were corrected in the last two sets, with Nori making a total of 57.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Live scores, results and order of play<br />\r\nNotifications: Receive tennis messages sent to your phone<br />\r\nNori, ranked 76, appeared to have taken control of the game as she tried to take a 2-1 lead in the third set, but world number 99 Davidovich Fokina immediately leveled and fled the game as England&#39;s performance faded. Afraid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She fought tooth and nail for serve in the late stages and lost more than 60% of the points in her own delivery in the third set. Then a double fault in the fourth set was set in the crucial stages, and Nori seemed to have an eye problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nori pulled back two sets and scored a match point against ninth seed Diego Schwartzman in the first half, but he was not satisfied with his form and certainly wouldn&#39;t be the same when he crashed out against the 21-year-old. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first two sets were very competitive, although they were still full of mistakes. After the break, the first continued with a draw, which was dominated by the Spaniard and who won the last five points.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nori saved three breakpoints in the fourth game of the second set and then immediately charged, chased and sent a downward forehand to climb to 3-2. After a new breakpoint was saved at 5-4, a similar shot sealed the set for England, but most had to drop from there.</p>', 'Defeat Dan Evans, Ended Hopes', 'Cameron Norries_1599252802.jpg', '2020-09-05 00:53:22', '2021-08-14 22:36:49'),
(134, 7, 5, 109, 'apple-is-slowing-down-new-steps-to-protect-personal-information-from-being-acted-upon-1599253038', 'Apple is slowing down new steps to protect personal information from being acted upon', 0, '<p><strong>Apple has postponed implementing new privacy measures designed to stop apps and websites tracking people online without their consent.</strong><br />\r\nThe changes also mean that the app must ask the user for permission to access the ad tracking ID on the iPhone or iPad.<br />\r\nThe steps will arrive in the fall of the last iOS 14 update.<br />\r\nHowever, according to Apple, the changes will be postponed until early 2021 to give app and website developers more time to customize their services.<br />\r\nFacebook has warned that Apple&#39;s privacy plan could &quot;make one of its advertising tools so ineffective for iOS 14 that it might not make sense to offer it on iOS 14&quot;.<br />\r\nThe social network said it was no longer collecting ad tracking IDs for iOS 14 users and that Apple&#39;s plans forced him to make that decision.<br />\r\n<strong>What has changed from Apple?</strong><br />\r\nApple devices, including the iPhone, iPad, and Apple TV Box, have a unique identifier called an Advertiser ID (IDAF).<br />\r\nThis feature allows the application to monitor the effectiveness of the advertising campaign. For example, you can find out if someone has downloaded the app after seeing an ad.<br />\r\nAndroid has a similar tool known as Android Advertising ID (AAID).<br />\r\nWith Apple, users can now disable access to their iOS IDAF.<br />\r\nHowever, once the changes take effect in 2021, they will be disabled by default and advertisers will have to request permission to access them.<br />\r\nApps should also be asked for permission to track what people are doing in the app and on other companies&#39; websites.<br />\r\nWhen iOS 14 comes out in the fall, apps will also need to determine what data they collect and how they track people on Apple&#39;s App Store.<br />\r\nAnother new security feature is highlighted when the application has access to information on the user&#39;s clipboard.<br />\r\nWhat else has changed?<br />\r\nOne of the biggest changes to the iPhone iOS 14 operating system is the blur of the home screen.<br />\r\nApple has updated the &quot;widgets&quot; - blocks that remove small application windows so they can be placed under icons for other programs.<br />\r\nIt also launched a new app called Translate which performs offline voice translations and is an alternative to Google Translate.<br />\r\n11 languages are supported, including English, Mandarin, French, German and Arabic.<br />\r\nFor the first time, users can set third-party email and web browser apps to default on iOS, not in Apple&#39;s own software.</p>', 'Protection, Measuring Tools', 'Apple_1599253038.jpg', '2020-09-05 00:57:18', '2021-08-16 16:33:48'),
(135, 7, 4, 52, 'lionel-messi-barcelona-team-didnt-afford-to-lose-good-player-1599253519', 'Lionel Messi:  Barcelona Team didnt afford to lose Good Player', 0, '<p>Barcelona&#39;s all-time leading scorer Lionel Messi said he was staying because it was &quot;impossible&quot; for the team to pay their release clause and did not want to go to trial against &quot;the club I love&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 33-year-old Argentine faxed Bar&ccedil;a last Tuesday saying he wanted to implement a clause in his contract that would allow him to leave for free.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the club said a &euro; 700 million release clause had to be complied with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think and I believe I can go,&quot; Messi told Goal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I tell the president and the president always says that at the end of the season I can decide whether to go or stay and in the end he doesn&#39;t keep his word.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Now I&#39;m going to continue at the club because the president told me the only way to go is to pay the $ 700 million clause and that&#39;s impossible.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Messi, whose contract expires next summer, said the fact he didn&#39;t tell Barca he wanted to leave before June 10 was very important and if he did, his release clause would not be honored.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Now they stick to the fact that I didn&#39;t say it until June 10 when it turned out that we were fighting for La Liga on June 10 in the midst of this terrible coronavirus and the disease has changed over the course of the season,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There are other ways and he has to sue. I will never go to court against Barca because the club I love has given me everything since I arrived.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s my club of life, I created my life here.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Messi&#39;s father, Jorge, held talks in Barcelona this week and insisted his son could leave for free so Liga could back up Barca&#39;s position on the release clause.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Manchester City were among Messi&#39;s clubs when he made it clear he wanted to end his 20-year stint at the Nou Camp nine days after losing 8-8 to Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-finals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The result saw Bar&ccedil;a end the season without cutlery, replacing manager Quique Setien with former Everton and Netherlands manager Ronald Koeman.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Messi has trained with his team-mates since Coman arrived and admits the club&#39;s recent lack of success influenced his decision to request his departure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I am constantly looking for and want to compete at the highest level, win titles and compete in the Champions League,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;When I announced my desire to leave my wife and children, it was a brutal drama.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;The whole family started crying, my children didn&#39;t want to leave Barcelona, nor did they want to change schools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I love Barcelona and I wouldn&#39;t find a better place anywhere than here. I still have the right to decide.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I will be looking for new goals and challenges. And I can come back tomorrow because I have everything here at Barcelona.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This could be worse,&quot; he said<br />\r\nSpanish football writer Andy West</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So Messi stays, but this saga is far from over.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The key conclusion of his interview was the brutal assessment of club president Josep Maria Bartomeu when he complained: &quot;There hasn&#39;t been a project or anything like that for a long time, they&#39;re juggling and covering holes as they walk.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bartomeu&#39;s term as president ends in March but he will now be under heavy pressure to step down immediately and it is difficult to see how he and Messi can coexist at the same club after the brutal assassination attempt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The big question, of course, remains: will Messi leave a free transfer next summer? If so, he will be allowed to negotiate a move in January and this is an issue that is sure to dominate the headlines over the next few weeks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A man in the center was recently appointed coach of Ronald Koeman, whose job it is to reintegrate the team captain and key players into a completely dysfunctional club that is still suffering from an embarrassing 8-2 Champions League defeat to Bayern. Munich is traumatized. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All the best Ronald. This unfortunate story still has a few chapters that could be worse.</p>', 'Barcelona Team, Good Player', 'Messi_1599253519.jpg', '2020-09-05 01:05:19', '2021-08-17 12:25:59');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(136, 7, 6, 53, 'mike-ashley-buys-old-rival-business-outside-of-administration-1599254211', 'Mike Ashley buys old rival business outside of administration', 0, '<p><strong>Billionaire entrepreneur Mike Ashley bought his fitness and fitness business from longtime rival and critic Dave Whelan after they joined the government.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ashley&#39;s Fraser Group said it would buy 46 leisure clubs and 31 retail stores from DW Sports Fitness for &pound; 37 million to join their own business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of the total 1,700 jobs across the company, about 922 jobs will be saved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DW collapsed earlier this month after its revenue ran out during the blockade.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The company has a total of 75 retail stores and 73 gyms which have had to temporarily close due to coronavirus restrictions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frasers, who also owns Lillywhites, Evans Cycles and House of Fraser, said DW&#39;s assets would &quot;complement&quot; its fitness and fitness club portfolio and would now be managed under the Everlast brand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Susanna Streetter, a senior market analyst at Hargreaves Lansdown, said it was surprising the group bought a fitness store because they are still grappling with the public&#39;s reluctance to exercise indoors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It will probably take some time before more people return to the gym, and it can be determined whether this latest acquisition is the right choice for the company.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DW also has a Fitness First fitness network, which is not affected by administration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>hostility<br />\r\nMr Ashley, who has bought famous street brands for the last five years, has a two-decade dispute with DW Sports owner Mr Whelan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2000, Mr Whelan is known to have told his younger rival from the south, &quot;There&#39;s a club in the north, kid, and you&#39;re not a part of it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ashley then notified the Fair Trade bureau at JJB Sports Store Mr. Whelan, claiming that he was involved in a soccer shirt pricing program.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OFTEN fines several million dollars for participants, including JJB.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whelan, 83, former owner of Wigan Athletic, founded DW Sports in 2009 when he bought 50 JJB Sports and adjacent off-management businesses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the year ended 31 March 2019, DW recorded a loss of more than &pound; 20 million.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frasers himself struggled during the pandemic, calling his final financial year the &quot;most challenging&quot; in its history.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sales increased slightly during the year ended April 26, but profits fell 20% to &pound; 143.5 million due to store closings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week he said more department stores in his department were expected to close for Fraser, which would likely result in further downsizing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It closed 10 of the 59 stores it bought outside management in 2018.</p>', 'Business Rival, Administration', '_114081799_gettyimages-952837588_1599254211.jpg', '2020-09-05 01:16:51', '2021-08-14 12:26:24'),
(137, 7, 4, 39, 'the-2021-rugby-league-world-cup-in-england-has-had-a-huge-impact-1599254427', 'The 2021 Rugby League World Cup in England has had a huge impact', 0, '<p><strong>Next year&#39;s sports calendar is full of the 2020 Olympics and European Football Championships, but a major event in England believes it can solve the mess.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Organizers of the 2021 Rugby League World Cup believe their tournament is unique - focused on community and heritage, as well as athletic and financial qualities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With ticket prices announced, I spoke with the tournament&#39;s executive director, John Dutton, about tournament planning in the shadow of the coronavirus and the potential impact on tickets, mental health and legacy initiatives, and attracting new teams and audiences to the sport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tickets and price adjustments due to the corona virus<br />\r\nThe World Cup&#39;s ambitious goals include getting 750,000 people to play, 50% more than in 2013, and doubling that number in Australia, New Zealand and Papua New Guinea in 2017.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ticket revenue is expected to represent 40% to 45% of the 2021 budget. &quot;We are very dependent on ticket money,&quot; said Dutton, 47.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>About 10% of ticket sales are expected to overseas fans, mostly from Australia and New Zealand, who lack World Cup or rugby experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rugby League World Cup organizers predict &quot;best event ever&quot;<br />\r\nWhy the 2021 Rugby League World Cup is different<br />\r\n&quot;Grow up to empower hated Britain,&quot; the report said<br />\r\nHowever, Dutton is aware of the impact of the coronavirus outbreak on disposable and ticket sensitive people&#39;s incomes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have had to review our budget ... over the last few months,&quot; he said. &quot;We&#39;re having a tough balancing act - ticket revenue is important to our commercial success, but we know how people&#39;s costs have changed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We understand our premier rugby league market well, but we also need to reach new markets both in the UK and abroad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That&#39;s why we made some adjustments to ticket prices last year. There are a lot of different price points.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ticket prices for RLWC2021 will be announced and fans can apply for tickets starting September 21.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prizes start at &pound; 2.21 for discounts and &pound; 10 for adults in all three tournaments. About 80% of tickets cost less than &pound; 50, and the highest-priced ticket, which has 4,000 seats in the final, costs &pound; 121.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tournament organizers awarded 20,021 tickets to key staff during the tournament to thank them for their contribution during the Covid-19 pandemic</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lingering spirit of Covid-19 overshadowed the event itself, and Dutton admitted, &quot;We looked at various scenarios including social distancing from game fans, indoor games, and what would happen if the event was postponed or not resumed at all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Every option is on the table, but we have tried to focus on what we can control. We try to be agile in our response because we are responsible for the public funds we have to protect.&quot; . &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fans will receive a full refund if any of the above situations occurs and the ticket cannot be used.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Social Impact and Mental Health Heritage<br />\r\nThe 2021 World Cup is the 16th edition of the tournament which was first held in 1954.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Said Dutton, &quot;Of course we want to fill the stadium and make it commercially successful. But we also want to implement our legacy program - social impact in terms of supporting the government&#39;s compensation program for the north of England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In 2015 we spoke with the government at the time about how we could focus more on cities and municipalities in what used to be Nordkraftwerk.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Nordic power plant was a proposal to stimulate economic growth in northern England and has since been replaced by promises from the Boris Johnson administration to calm down.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The outcome of discussions at Whitehall in 2015 was that the central government had allocated &pound; 25 million to fund the 16 nation tournament.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Approximately 80% of events take place in the north of England and are centered on the M62 corridor linking Liverpool and Hull via Manchester and Leeds. There will also be games in Newcastle, Middlesbrough, Coventry and London.<br />\r\n&quot;We wanted to make a difference,&quot; said Dutton, who was watching his Premier League games at the age of five. &quot;Our volunteer program will be very comprehensive and will represent the local communities where the games are held.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There will be culture, heritage, public health, education and participation initiatives. There will also be a mental health legacy as we work with Movember to develop resistance training for young adults.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s also important to leave a physical legacy in the form of a facility. We can help turn the facility into a smaller rugby club through cash grants.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New countries and audiences<br />\r\nIt was also the first time in World Cup history that competitions for men, women and wheelchairs were held at the same time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Under a contract with the BBC, all 61 matches will be broadcast live, compared to just seven of the 28 when the last event was held in England in 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are 21 seats of all shapes and sizes, including many high-level football stadiums.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Highlights include the opening match at Newcastle, a two-headed ball at Liverpool&#39;s home stadium, Anfield, Arsenal&#39;s first non-football event at the Emirates Stadium and the men&#39;s and women&#39;s doubles final at Old Trafford.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tournament&#39;s new names include Greece, Jamaica and Brazil.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We hope to reach a new global television audience so everyone can consume RLWC,&quot; said Dutton.<br />\r\nThe men&#39;s competition consists of 16 teams taking part in four groups of four teams each. Women&#39;s events have grown from six to eight teams, and wheelchair events have grown from seven to eight teams.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We make sure that every team is treated equally when it comes to money,&quot; said Dutton. &quot;For the first time ever, there are also cash prizes at women&#39;s and wheelchair competitions.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He continued: &quot;It is important that the World Cup plays a role in the development of the rugby league.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We want to make sure that this tournament can last a long time. We want to use the tournament to arouse and arouse people&#39;s interest in the sport.&quot;</p>', 'Rugby League, World Cup', '_113873727_gettyimages-884258116_1599254427.jpg', '2020-09-05 01:20:27', '2021-08-14 22:41:17'),
(138, 7, 4, 43, 'english-football-league-fans-view-cambridge-united-matches-as-a-trial-event-1599254490', 'English Football League: Fans view Cambridge United matches as a trial event', 0, '<p>Next week, fans will be able to participate in two English Football League matches as testing ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cambridge United&#39;s home game against Fulham U21 in the EFL Cup on September 8 and the League 2 match against Carlisle on Saturday September 12 are part of the government&#39;s pilot project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The club&#39;s Abby Stadium allows 1,000 fans for the EFL draw and 2,500 for league matches.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cambridge was chosen for both devices to enable fast &quot;learning&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The EFL statement said: &quot;Appropriate action has been taken at Abbey Stadium, with terraces and seating available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Because the two competitions take place at the same venue in such a short time, all training sessions can be carried out quickly and under the same conditions.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cambridge was previously part of a joint project between the EFL and the Sports Facility Safety Authority (SGSA) investigating the use of safe social distancing on soccer fields.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This work was supervised by the Crowd Dynamics expert from Movement Strategy who would also evaluate the pilot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Premier League season starts on September 12, but as of now, fans will not be allowed to play the earliest matches until the earliest October.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A limited number of fans are allowed to watch Brighton&#39;s friendly against Chelsea on Saturday, which also serves as a test event.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Wednesday, the Football Rugby Union announced plans to bring up to 20,000 fans to Twickenham to watch England play barbarian on 25 October.</p>', 'Football League', '_114229558_cambridge1_1599254490.jpg', '2020-09-05 01:21:30', '2021-08-14 22:38:33'),
(139, 7, 5, 92, 'facebook-will-freeze-political-ads-ahead-of-the-us-presidential-election-1599254795', 'Facebook will freeze political ads ahead of the US presidential election', 0, '<p><strong>Facebook has announced that it will not run any new political ads in the seven days leading up to the November 3 US election.</strong><br />\r\nThe company will continue to allow existing ads to continue to be promoted and targeted to different users.<br />\r\nCEO Mark Zuckerberg revealed the measure in a Facebook post.<br />\r\nHe said he was &quot;concerned&quot; about divisions in the country, which could lead to unrest.<br />\r\nHe added that Facebook will also flag posts from candidates trying to declare victory before the vote count.<br />\r\nThe social network has been criticized for allowing political advertising on its platform to be &quot;micro-targeted&quot; so that only a small community sees it instead of being discussed in more detail in the days after it appeared.<br />\r\nThe Mozilla Foundation says this makes it easier for politicians and their supporters to flaunt fiction as fact and avoid being asked to do so until it is too late, especially since Facebook has said it won&#39;t review ads advertised by candidates. Fact.<br />\r\nThese new steps could set a precedent for how the company will handle decisions elsewhere in the future.<br />\r\nFacebook also announced it would remove a video of President Trump asking North Carolina voters to vote twice, which is illegal.<br />\r\nAll videos of Mr Trump&#39;s comments without the contextualization of the information will be removed, the company said in a statement: &quot;This video violates our anti-fraud policy and we will remove it unless shared to correct footage.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Nation Divided&quot;<br />\r\nPresident Trump has repeatedly said that elections can be &quot;rigged&quot; by election fraud.<br />\r\nHowever, there was no evidence of widespread electoral fraud in previous opinion polls.<br />\r\n&quot;This election will be uncharacteristic,&quot; wrote Zuckerberg.<br />\r\n&quot;With the nation divided and the election results possibly taking days or even weeks to complete, there may be an increased risk of unrest across the country,&quot; he added.<br />\r\nIn order to curb the spread of rumors and intentional forgery on Facebook, the company announced a series of actions:<br />\r\nNo new political advertisements will be accepted in the week leading up to the election<br />\r\nPublications that claim people will catch Covid-19 if they choose will be removed<br />\r\nInformation labels are placed in places that aim to legitimize the election results<br />\r\nCandidates who wish to win will also be labeled their entries before the final result is entered<br />\r\nZuckerberg also said Facebook has also &quot;tightened&quot; its enforcement policies against movements known to promote conspiracy theories such as QAnon.<br />\r\nThousands of Facebook groups associated with the movement have been removed, he said.<br />\r\nHowever, the move has come under criticism.<br />\r\nThe head of Media Matters for America, the watchdog for liberal media, describes it as a pointless PR stunt.<br />\r\n&quot;They will continue to allow political advertising to be restarted and targeted at new groups in the [last] week as long as it is posted and has made an impression before October 27,&quot; tweeted Angelo Carusone.<br />\r\n&quot;So now you can run a bad ad, pause it, and use it again this week.&quot;<br />\r\nA scientist who specializes in technological and political interactions has written a related paper.<br />\r\n&quot;The campaign will produce and publish thousands of creative work in the days leading up to the break so they can spend the final week,&quot; said Daniel Kreis, professor at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.</p>', 'Freeze, Politics, US Election', '_114230167_zuck_1599254795.jpg', '2020-09-05 01:26:35', '2021-08-16 01:21:34'),
(140, 7, 5, 52, 'illegal-nsa-snowden-surveillance-1599254938', 'Illegal NSA Snowden surveillance', 0, '<p>The National Security Agency&#39;s (NSA) surveillance program was declared illegal seven years after being discovered by whistleblower Edward Snowden.<br />\r\nMonitoring the telephone records of millions of Americans first began in 2013.<br />\r\nThe US appeals court has now ruled that intelligence leaders who publicly defended the program had lied.<br />\r\nAnd Mr. Snowden said he felt justified in that decision.<br />\r\nThe FBI is concerned that the bell rings to spy on the police<br />\r\nMicrosoft banned the sale of police facial recognition<br />\r\nHe currently lives in exile in Moscow but last year expressed a desire to return to the United States, where he is accused of espionage over his decision to go public.<br />\r\n&quot;I never thought that I would see our court condemning NSA activities as illegal and confessing in the same rulings that I have disclosed,&quot; Snowden said.<br />\r\n&quot;But that day has come,&quot; he added.<br />\r\nSenior US intelligence officials publicly insist that the NSA never knowingly collected data from private phone records until Snowden provided evidence to the contrary in 2013.<br />\r\nFollowing the revelations, officials said the NSA&#39;s surveillance program had played an important role in the fight against domestic terrorism, including punishing Basaali Saeed Moalin, Ahmed Nasir Taalil Mohamud, Mohamed Mohamud and Isa Dore of San Diego for helping all armed groups. Shabab in Somalia.<br />\r\nHowever, on Wednesday, the appeals court said the allegations were &quot;inconsistent with the content of classified information&quot; and that the program violated the Foreign Intelligence Oversight Act.<br />\r\nThis decision does not affect the 2013 tariffs.<br />\r\n&quot;Today&#39;s decision is a victory for our right to privacy,&quot; the American Civil Liberties Union said in a statement.<br />\r\n&quot;It is clear that the NSA&#39;s mass arrest of American phone recordings is against the Constitution.&quot;</p>', 'Surveillance Program, Declared Illegal', '_114228241_whatsubject_1599254938.jpg', '2020-09-05 01:28:58', '2021-08-16 23:45:55'),
(141, 7, 7, 31, 'postponed-olympics-viral-problems-a-challenge-for-japans-next-prime-minister-1599306115', 'Postponed Olympics, viral problems: a challenge for Japan\'s next Prime Minister', 0, '<p><strong>TOKYO: Japan&#39;s next prime minister could face some tough challenges after Shinzo Abe announced last week that he was stepping down as the country&#39;s longest-serving leader for health reasons.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the ruling Liberal Democrats announce a vote on September 14 to replace Abe, who is stepping down for health reasons, here are some of the problems Japan&#39;s next prime minister will face:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Virus crisis</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite a relatively small coronavirus outbreak in Japan, Abe&#39;s government has been heavily criticized for fighting the pandemic, and its response has been slow and irregular.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Redistribution of cash distributions creates confusion, while the policy of issuing cloth masks to individual homes is derided as unnecessary and late.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And the government&#39;s recent campaign to encourage domestic travel has sparked fears of a new cluster of infections in the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The pandemic has exacerbated Japan&#39;s recession, forcing the 2020 Tokyo Olympics to be postponed next year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the run-up to flu season, experts warn that Japan - with the world&#39;s oldest population - must take steps to avoid a collapse of its medical system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tetsuro Kato, professor of politics at Waseda University in Tokyo, said the next prime minister must take &quot;bold action&quot; to deal with the outbreak, such as increasing testing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Nothing else - including the Olympics - can be handled without properly dealing with the virus,&quot; he told AFP.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The economy is shrinking</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The virus rocked Japan&#39;s already volatile economy, which shrank 7.8 percent from April to June to 27.8 percent year-on-year. This is the worst decline since the post-war period.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Japan has taken much more lenient measures to contain the spread of the coronavirus in many countries without forcing shop closures or stay-at-home orders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the economy was already in recession before the virus broke out, and the pandemic canceled many of the economic programs Abe signed up for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the long term, Japan still needs to undertake significant structural reforms to boost weak productivity, economists say.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Olympics were postponed</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Postponing the 2020 Tokyo Olympics came with many difficulties - from preventing mass infections to dealing with late expenses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Japan&#39;s borders are still largely closed to foreign visitors, and attendance is limited to domestic sporting events, leading to speculation about whether the Olympics are worth it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although officials have ruled out any further delays, a recent poll found that only one in four people in Japan want the Olympics to resume next year, with most favoring further postponements or cancellations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Foreign policy</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abe is focused on Japan&#39;s relations with its main ally, Washington, and has built a fragile relationship with President Donald Trump.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But now that the Donald Shinzo era is over, the next Japanese leader will have to hook up with either Trump or Democratic candidate Joe Biden.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This alliance is seen as more important given China&#39;s increasingly assertive and fragmented relations with South and North Korea which are increasingly unpredictable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Japan is also embroiled in tensions between the United States and China, its two biggest trading partners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is not enough for Japan to rely solely on its relationship with the United States to maneuver in the international community, and how to deal with China is a difficult one,&quot; said Kato.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abe&#39;s successor will also face a growing trend toward protectionism, which Japan supports with enthusiastic acceptance of international trade pacts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Problems with population</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abe&#39;s successor will inherit a population problem with a rapidly aging country plagued by low birth rates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employment issues, ranging from labor shortages to overtime, continue to hamper the economy, and efforts to loosen immigration restrictions and attract more women to work have had limited success.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite Abe&#39;s pledge to create a society where women can shine, Japan&#39;s top political and government positions remain stubborn of men, and the country ranks 121 out of 153 countries in the World Economic Forum&#39;s annual gender equality ranking.</p>', 'Olympics, Postponed, Japan Challenge', 'Olympics by Japanes_1599306114.jpg', '2020-09-05 15:41:55', '2021-08-03 15:09:43'),
(142, 7, 7, 50, 'putins-critic-navalny-is-poisoned-by-nerve-agent-novichok-the-merkelnomic-forums-annual-rankings-for-gender-equality-1599306297', 'Putin\'s critic Navalny is poisoned by nerve agent Novichok: The Merkelnomic Forum\'s annual rankings for gender equality', 0, '<p><strong>BERLIN / MOSCOW: Kremlin critic Alexei Navalny, who is in the intensive care unit of a Berlin hospital, was poisoned by Soviet nerve agent Novichok to kill him, Chancellor Angela Merkel said on Wednesday.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said Berlin now expects statements from Moscow and Germany to consult its NATO allies on how to react, which raises the prospect of new Western sanctions on Russia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Moscow has denied involvement in the incident. The Russian Foreign Ministry said Germany&#39;s claims were not supported by evidence and complained about how Germany decided to release information about Navalny.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is alarming information about attempted assassination by poisoning Russia&#39;s leading opposition,&quot; Merkel said. &quot;Alexei Navalny was attacked by a chemical neuroprotective agent from the Novichok group. This poison was clearly identified in the test.&quot; &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Novice is the same substance Britain says was used in an attack in Britain on a Russian defector and his daughter in 2018.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>44-year-old Navalny is an obvious opponent of Russian President Vladimir Putin and specializes in high-impact investigations into official corruption. He was flown to Germany last month after crashing on a Russian domestic flight after drinking a cup of tea his allies said had been poisoned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Kremlin said it wanted a full information exchange and that Germany and Russia needed to cooperate, but was not yet in a position to provide a true explanation of the German outcome.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previously, Russian authorities and doctors said they could find no evidence that Navalny was poisoned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Russia has been under Western sanctions since Ukraine annexed Crimea six years ago. Another confrontation with European countries or the United States could damage the economy even further. The Russian ruble increased its losses against the euro, according to a German government statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bulk under tough conditions</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Charite Hospital in Berlin, which is treating Navalny, said he remained in serious condition in an intensive care unit fitted to an artificial pulmonary ventilator, although some of his symptoms had subsided.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said he could not rule out the long-term effects of poisoning and hoped for a prolonged illness.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lithuanian Foreign Minister Linas Linkeviius tweeted that the federal government&#39;s identification of the poison novicok showed that Russian authorities were behind Navalny&#39;s poisoning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Kremlin denies accusations that they or the Russian state were involved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Navalny&#39;s allies agree with Linkeviius&#39; view. Leonid Volkov, a Navy aide, said on Twitter that using Novichok was like leaving Putin&#39;s signature at the scene.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ivan Zhdanov, another close ally of Navalny, said on Twitter that Novichok could only be managed by Russian intelligence agencies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Federal Foreign Minister Heiko Maas has asked Russia to investigate Navalny&#39;s poisoning after clinical trials showed he was attacked with a neurochemical.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is more urgent to identify those responsible in Russia and hold them accountable,&quot; Maas told reporters. &quot;We strongly condemn this attack.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Novichok is a group of lethal nerve agents developed by the Soviet military in the 1970s and 1980s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stephen Seibert, a spokesman for the federal government, earlier said in an email that tests carried out in a German military laboratory had provided &quot;clear evidence&quot; that Novichok had been used.</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<p>Britain says Russia used Novichok to poison former spy Sergei Skripal and his daughter in the British city of Salisbury in 2018. Russia has repeatedly denied involvement in the attacks that saved Skripal. One member of the community, Dawn Sturgess, 44, was killed.</p>\r\n</div>', 'Putin, Gender Equality', 'German Chancellor_1599306297.jpg', '2020-09-05 15:44:57', '2021-08-17 17:22:26'),
(143, 7, 7, 32, 'french-minister-macron-reaffirmed-iraqi-sovereignty-on-his-first-visit-to-baghdad-1599306769', 'French Minister Macron reaffirmed Iraqi \"sovereignty\" on his first visit to Baghdad', 0, '<p><strong>BAGDAD: French President Emmanuel Macron will make his first official visit to Iraq on Wednesday, where he plans to help Baghdad regain &quot;sovereignty&quot; amid rising tensions between the United States and Iran.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Macron will come directly from a two-day trip to Beirut, Lebanon&#39;s troubled capital, and will be the most significant leader visiting Iraq since Prime Minister Mustafa al-Qadhemi took office in May.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The trip was announced late Tuesday and officials in Paris and Baghdad are sticking to the arrangements for security reasons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On his final night in Beirut, Macron announced that he would travel to Baghdad &quot;to launch an initiative with the United Nations to support the process of sovereignty.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The struggle for Iraqi sovereignty is very important,&quot; Macron told reporters on Friday before heading to Lebanon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said Iraqis who have &quot;suffered terribly&quot; deserve options other than regional domination of power or extremism.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There are leaders and people who are aware of this and want to determine their own destiny. France&#39;s job is to help them do this,&quot; said Macron.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the 2003 US-led invasion that toppled dictator Saddam Hussein, Iraq was hit by a wave of sectarian conflict that ended with the Islamic State group invading parts of the country six years ago before the jihadists were beaten back by international support.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the same time, the country has been stuck between its two main allies, Iran and the United States, for years, a balancing act that has grown increasingly tormented since Washington withdrew from the multilateral nuclear deal with Tehran in 2018.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>France is one European country that remains a major supporter of the 2015 agreement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Big thing&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year alone, a US drone strike killed Iranian general Kasem Soleimani in Baghdad and prompted Iran to fire missiles at US forces in Iraq.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tehran-backed groups have been suspected of carrying out rocket fire at US diplomatic, military and commercial interests in Iraq in recent months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As the second-largest producer of the OPEC oil cartel, Iraq has also been hit hard by plunging global prices, and the coronavirus pandemic has forced its fragile economy further.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>France is signaling its support.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Top diplomat Jean-Yves Le Drian visited Iraq in July and insisted that Baghdad &quot;must secede from regional tensions&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On August 27, French Defense Minister Florence Parley stressed the need for continued support for the Iraqi armed forces in talks with high-level military and political leaders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Wednesday, Macron will meet Kadhemi and President Barham Saleh, whom he met in Paris in 2019, and a number of other political figures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The visit will be very important as it will be the third visit to the French authorities in one month, &quot;said Husham Dowwood, an adviser to the Iraqi Prime Minister.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unlike most foreign officials, the French president will not stop at Erbil, the capital of Iraq&#39;s Kurdish Autonomous Region. Instead, Kurdish President Nechirvan Barzani will travel to Baghdad for talks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shortly after winning the presidency in 2017, Macron sought to mediate between the northern Kurdish autonomy and the federal government, but financial disputes and between the two countries remain unresolved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There may be no new reports of financial or military assistance, Iraqi officials said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>France did not take part in the invasion that toppled Saddam, but instead joined the US-led coalition that was formed in 2014 to fight ISIS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Message to Ankara?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Earlier this year, following Daesh&#39;s territorial defeat and the Covid-19 outbreak, the last contingent of French troops stationed in Iraq as part of the coalition withdrew.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>France is struggling to develop its economic ties with Iraq, which Transparency International ranks among the 20 most corrupt countries in the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Macron&#39;s &quot;sovereignty initiative&quot; is also an indirect message to Turkey, said an Iraqi official.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ankara launched cross-border air and ground strikes against Kurdish rebels in northern Iraq in June, angering Baghdad in what it says is a violation of Iraqi territory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tensions between France and Turkey are already high over the conflict in Libya, where Paris and Ankara accuse each other of meddling and debate offshore gas rights in the East Mediterranean.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Macron&#39;s blitzkrieg comes after intense talks in Lebanon - the second since a colossal explosion at the port of Beirut on August 4, killing more than 180 people.</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<p>He chaired a donor conference for Lebanon last month and said he was ready to hold another conference along with a political meeting in October.</p>\r\n</div>', 'Sovereighnty, French Minister', 'France Macron_1599306769.jpg', '2020-09-05 15:52:49', '2021-06-16 11:26:35'),
(144, 7, 7, 46, 'trump-will-ask-the-us-appeals-court-to-block-prosecutors-access-to-tax-returns-1599307945', 'Trump will ask the US appeals court to block prosecutors\' access to tax returns', 0, '<p><strong>NEW YORK: Lawyers for Donald Trump on Tuesday will ask the federal appeals court to prevent Manhattan district attorneys from accessing the US president&#39;s tax returns in connection with a criminal investigation into his business practices.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump championed the summons of District Attorney Cyrus Vance to President Mazars USA&#39;s longtime accounting firm for one year to generate Trump&#39;s personal and business income for eight years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A second US appeals court in Manhattan is scheduled for 10:00 EDT (14:00 GMT) to hear an oral submission on Trump&#39;s motion to postpone the summons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the appeals court refuses to be late, Trump plans to ask the US Supreme Court to step in.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In July, the Supreme Court refused to block subpoenas and rejected Trump&#39;s request for immunity from criminal investigations while he was at the White House, but said he could raise other objections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since then, Republican Trump has argued that the subpoena to be &quot;grossly exaggerated&quot; largely reflects a subpoena from the Democratic Congress and maliciously issued to preside over it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Democratic Vance began his investigation after news that former Trump lawyer Michael Cohen had paid porn actress Stormy Daniels $ 130,000 to remain silent ahead of the 2016 election over alleged sexual relations with Trump, which the president has denied.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prosecutors say the trial effectively granted Trump, who wants to be re-elected by November 3, the immunity he has requested and which the court has rejected.</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<p>Vance also said filing a statement would do no irreparable harm to Trump, noting that the trial was secret at a major court hearing and that every other US president, starting with Jimmy Carter, had issued his tax returns.</p>\r\n</div>', 'Donald Trump, Appeals, Tax', 'Donald Trump.._1599307945.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:12:25', '2021-07-22 07:30:44'),
(145, 7, 7, 63, 'the-us-israeli-delegation-leaves-abu-dhabi-after-cooperation-talks-1599308071', 'The US-Israeli delegation leaves Abu Dhabi after cooperation talks', 0, '<p><strong>ABU DHABI: After a historic visit to the United Arab Emirates, the US-Israeli delegation left Abu Dhabi to discuss future relations between the UAE and the Jewish state following their extraordinary US-brokered deal.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The United Arab Emirates and Israel are expected to sign a deal at the White House in the coming weeks - Israel&#39;s first deal with a Gulf state and only a third with an Arab country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jared Kushner, President Donald Trump&#39;s son-in-law and White House adviser, led the delegation, which arrived in the emirate&#39;s capital on Monday on the first direct commercial flight from Ben Gurion Airport near Tel Aviv.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Israeli press celebrates the historic flight, which also reserves the right to cross Saudi Arabia&#39;s airspace.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The Flight of Peace&quot; appeared on the cover of bestselling daily Yediot Aharonot, commenting, &quot;No matter how we look at it ... this is an interesting historical event.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Elsewhere, the agreement between the United Arab Emirates and Israel has raised criticism after the Palestinians condemned it as a stab at the back of a major Arab player despite not having a state of its own.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Iran&#39;s Supreme Leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei said on Twitter that &quot;the UAE has betrayed the world to Islam, the Arab countries, the countries of the region and Palestine&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kushner also visited the United Arab Emirates Air Force Base on Tuesday, where the United States deployed the F-35 stealth fighter requested by Abu Dhabi. This is the most complex issue in Emirates&#39; newly built relationship with Israel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Israel has denied reports that the deal relies on selling US F-35s to the UAE, and Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said he opposed any move that could reduce its strategic advantage in the region.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kushner said Monday that the United States could maintain this advantage &quot;while enhancing our military ties with the United Arab Emirates&quot; and that the issue would continue to be discussed in the coming weeks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Extensive cooperation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Officials from the US, Israel and the United Arab Emirates said they had discussed cooperation in the fields of investment, finance, health, outer space, civil aviation, foreign policy, and tourism and culture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The result is broad collaboration between two of the region&#39;s most innovative and dynamic economies,&quot; all three said in a statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>National security adviser Meir Ben-Shabat from Israel and Sheikh Taunun bin Zayd from the United Arab Emirates held talks with Kushner on cooperation between two highly developed economies in the Middle East.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is unclear whether Kushner will return to Tel Aviv or fly to another country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The word &quot;peace&quot; is written in Arabic, English and Hebrew in the cockpit of the Israeli aircraft carrier El Al.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The plane was named after the Israeli city of Kiryat Gat, a point that was conquered by Palestinian Prime Minister Mohammed Steye.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It pains us to see an Israeli plane in the United Arab Emirates named Kiryat Gat, a settlement built on top of the (Palestinian) territory of Al Fallujah ... in clear and blatant violations of the Arab position in the Arab-Israeli conflict,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After Egypt and Jordan, the UAE is only the third Arab country to normalize relations with Israel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Its ally, Saudi Arabia, has announced that it will not normalize relations until Israel agrees to an independent Palestinian state in line with the ten-year stance of most Arab states.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Under the normalization deal with the UAE, Israel agreed to end the plan to annex the occupied West Bank - but Netanyahu insisted that the plan remain on the table.</p>', 'US-Israeli Deligation', 'US-Isreaki Dlegation_1599308071.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:14:31', '2021-08-17 23:31:16'),
(146, 7, 7, 74, 'israel-united-arab-emirates-will-cooperate-on-financial-services-under-the-normalization-agreement-1599308408', 'Israel, United Arab Emirates, will cooperate on financial services under the normalization agreement', 0, '<p>JERUSALEM: Israel and the United Arab Emirates agreed on Tuesday to form a financial services cooperation commission to encourage investment between the two countries, an Israeli statement said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Israeli delegation is on a historic trip to Abu Dhabi to work out a pact that will mark open relations between Israel and the Gulf state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Representatives of the two sides have signed the agreement, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said in a statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the priorities, said Netanyahu, is &quot;cooperation in the field of financial services and the elimination of barriers to financial investment between countries and promotion of joint investment in the capital market&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The parties will also cooperate on banking and payment arrangements, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Israeli officials are quick to exploit the economic benefits of the deal, which would once have included formal deals in tourism, technology, energy, health and safety, among others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A number of Israeli and Emirati companies have signed contracts since the normalization agreement was announced.</p>', 'Israel-UAE Agreement, Financial Coorperate', 'Isreli PM_1599308408.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:20:08', '2021-08-16 12:01:04'),
(147, 7, 7, 72, 'the-queens-parenting-style-had-a-deliberately-unpleasant-effect-on-prince-charles-1599308527', 'The Queen\'s parenting style had a \"deliberately unpleasant\" effect on Prince Charles', 0, '<p><strong>Queen Elizabeth&#39;s reign over the British monarchy is one of the best-documented governments in history. In view of the high hopes that were firmly entrusted to the queen of a young age, many biographers and royal scholars believed that she could not rule much of a domestic life.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Queen Elizabeth is a monarch who has always taken care of personal affairs and even in the era of digital media has managed to create a transparent veil for everything that goes on behind palace doors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although the Queen&#39;s personal life is not a known fact, many royal biographers who have studied the Queen over the years claim that she was never a mother who was &quot;practical&quot; and &quot;deliberately&quot; unfriendly to her children.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to director Tom Jennings, &quot;Being the Queen&quot; provides a deep understanding of the Queen&#39;s personal and domestic life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is filled with archival material and other tapes describing the chronology of the Queen&#39;s entire reign since her coronation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the most surprising parts of this documentary is about the style of the king&#39;s parents toward all of his children, Prince Charles, Prince Andrew, Prince Edward and Princess Anne.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The documentary depicts the reigning king as the &quot;main character&quot; in the maternal line. A royal biographer, Tim Hild, claims the queen&#39;s children are considered &quot;happy&quot; if they have to see their mother for a day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Heald was quoted as saying, &quot;It&#39;s not that someone is intentionally uncomfortable or cold ... it&#39;s just your way of doing things.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is not to say that biographers in any way blame the crown. The Queen has always put her citizens first, stepping back from public affairs to comfort Prince William and Prince Harry after their mother died.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Heald adds, &quot;Remember that running a monarchy is a full-time job multiplied by 20, so things like family time fail. Trusting your kids to boarding schools, tutors, and so on is good for education, but it&#39;s not the same as education and tutoring. you will receive from your parents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Helde admits, however, that &quot;the queen can be so steadfast in her own marriage, and yet the marriage of her children is messy left and right&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When the Queen does not take care of her relatives personally, boarding schools come into play because they can &quot;make people fat emotionally.&quot; All of the Queen&#39;s children attend these schools after the age of 13.</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<p>Another way the Queen balances her responsibilities is by &quot;depending on the babysitter of her children to control their daily lives.&quot;</p>\r\n</div>', 'Deliberately Unpleasant, Queen Elizabeths', 'Quees_1599308527.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:22:07', '2021-08-15 09:59:38'),
(148, 7, 7, 52, 'the-german-minister-did-not-recommend-a-second-blockade-because-the-economy-was-recovering-strongly-1599308718', 'The German minister did not recommend a second blockade because the economy was recovering strongly', 0, '<p><strong>FRANKFURT: Germany is in a V-shaped economic recovery and should avoid a new phase of the blockade, the Minister for Economic Affairs said on Tuesday, even though the coronavirus cases have already started.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Germany&#39;s GDP is expected to fall 5.8 percent in 2020, a recession tighter than the 6.3 percent decline previously estimated, said Peter Altmeier, signaling that the country is recovering from its worst crisis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Altmeier said Germany can and will avoid a blockade, as Germany experienced in March and April.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The rising infection rate will be countered by regionally limited and targeted measures so that the gradual economic recovery will develop further in the coming months,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More resilient to the pandemic than many of its neighbors, the country reported an average of nearly 1,250 new cases of COVID-19 per day over the past week, compared with an average of less than 500 in July and August, and is starting to tighten restrictions. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week the government announced a minimum fine of 50 euros for people caught without masks in places where wearing it is mandatory, a ban on major events until the end of the year and new quarantine rules for travelers returning from the area with high frequency cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chancellor Angela Merkel, a former scientist, won a lot and saw her approval rating for tackling the virus improve, but said last week that dealing with the outbreak will become more difficult in the coming months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since the first cases were discovered in January, more than 9,000 people have died from COVID-19 in Germany. This is a lower percentage than in other major European countries, where the blockade is more severe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is in line with the outlook for the German economy which is much better.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, France is expected to shrink its economy by 10.6% by the end of 2020, Spain by 10.9% and Italy by 11.2% according to EU statistics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The Road to Recovery&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Altmaier said Europe&#39;s largest economy was &quot;sadly in sharp decline, but then an unexpectedly rapid recovery&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prior to the press conference, the minister even showed a printed V-shaped diagram for photographers who had gathered to highlight the rebound.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The German economy collapsed by 9.7% in the second quarter of 2020, &quot;the sharpest drop since quarterly GDP calculations for Germany began in 1970,&quot; the Federal Statistical Office Destatis previously said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the Ministry of Economy, &quot;the lowest point of the recession&quot; passed in May.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recent surveys have shown an increase in business sentiment in the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, employment was stable for the third consecutive month and 6% in July, the German employment office announced on Tuesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week, the Ifo Institute announced that its monthly business confidence barometer showed that companies are growing more positively in the economic situation after the index fell to a record low in April.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The German economy is on the way to recovery,&quot; President Ifo Clemens Fuest told the data.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The German purchasing managers&#39; index also showed an expansionary trend from July.</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<p>The German economy is expected to grow by 4.4% in 2021, although pre-crisis GDP will be visible again until 2022, the Economy Ministry said.</p>\r\n</div>', 'German Minister, Second Blockade, Economy Recovery', 'German Economy Minister_1599308718.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:25:18', '2021-08-12 15:38:03');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(149, 7, 7, 51, 'the-united-states-is-helping-taiwan-fight-increasing-pressure-from-china-1599308934', 'The United States is helping Taiwan fight increasing pressure from China', 0, '<p><strong>WASHINGTON: To strengthen ties with Taipei and support each other in the face of increasing pressure from Beijing, the United States announced on Monday that it would start a new bilateral economic dialogue with Taiwan.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Washington also said it had released six Reagan-era security guarantees to Taiwan, which analysts said aimed to provide additional support to Taipei.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report comes from a time of increasing Chinese threats to Taiwan and when Washington-Beijing relations have sunk to their lowest level in decades. US President Donald Trump is fighting for re-election in November with a firm stance on China as one of the most important foreign policy platforms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>US State Department East Asia diplomat David Stillwell said in a virtual forum hosted by the conservative Heritage Foundation that the US move recently was not a political change, but part of a series of &quot;significant adjustments&quot; in &quot;China&quot; &#39;s long term. Washington Politics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Washington was forced to do so in the face of Beijing&#39;s &quot;growing threat to peace and stability&quot; in this vital region and Beijing&#39;s attempts to diplomatically isolate Taiwan by exposing it to military threats.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We will continue to help Taipei oppose the Chinese Communist Party&#39;s campaign to suppress, intimidate and marginalize Taiwan,&quot; Stillwell said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Thai Foreign Ministry thanked the support shown when it said China was using military intimidation to undermine peace and stability near Taiwan and said it would continue to strengthen its defense capabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The United States, like most countries, has official ties with Beijing, but not with Taiwan, which Beijing claims is Chinese territory. However, Washington has a legal obligation to assist Taiwan in its self-defense and is its main arms supplier.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Read more: The dispute between the US and China heated up when Beijing imposed sanctions on eleven US lawmakers</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Daniel Russell, Stillwell&#39;s predecessor to the start of the Trump administration, said the &quot;six promises&quot; made by former President Ronald Reagan&#39;s Taipei administration were &quot;top secret&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said the decision to publish it was a compromising response to pressure from administrative officials to abandon &quot;strategic ambiguity&quot; - a longstanding policy of maintaining clear US commitments to Taiwan&#39;s defense while showing sufficient support to help China. to prevent military adventures. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Guarantees made in 1982, but never officially released, include a statement that the United States has not set a cut-off date for arms sales to Taiwan, nor does it agree to consult Beijing beforehand or revise sales to Taiwan relations, which supports US policy on the island. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The guarantees, says Stillwell, &quot;hold on to the day.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Douglas Paal, the former US envoy to Taiwan, said the move would be especially demonstrated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think Style well and the government want to look solid now ... So they are approaching the Chinese red line, but they don&#39;t want to cross it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stillwell said the economic dialogue will &quot;examine our entire economic relationship - semiconductors, health care, energy and more, with technology at the center&quot;.</p>', 'US-Taiwan, China, Pressure', 'US Taiwan China pressure_1599308934.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:27:06', '2021-08-18 07:18:29'),
(150, 7, 7, 55, 'the-united-states-imposes-new-restrictions-on-chinese-diplomats-1599309007', 'The United States imposes new restrictions on Chinese diplomats', 0, '<p><strong>WASHINGTON: The United States imposed new restrictions on Chinese diplomats in Washington on Thursday by barring them from visiting campuses or meeting with local government officials without approval from the State Department</strong>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Washington accepted the move in response to Beijing&#39;s restrictions on US diplomats in China. It is part of the Trump administration&#39;s campaign against alleged Chinese influence and espionage operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The State Department said it would also take steps to ensure that all accounts on the Chinese embassy and consular social media were &quot;properly identified&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We just want reciprocity,&quot; US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told a news conference. &quot;Our diplomats &#39;access to China must reflect Chinese diplomats&#39; access to the United States, and today&#39;s steps will point us significantly in that direction.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was the United States&#39; latest move to curb Chinese activity in the United States on the eve of the November presidential election, during which President Donald Trump harshly views China as a major foreign policy platform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Chinese Embassy in Washington called the move &quot;another unjustifiable restriction and barrier to Chinese diplomatic and consular personnel&quot; that &quot;goes against the values of openness and freedom proclaimed by the United States.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pompeo also said the State Department recently wrote to the board of directors of American universities warning them of threats from the Chinese Communist Party.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These threats can be in the form of illegal research funding, intellectual property theft, intimidation of foreign students and vague talent recruitment efforts,&quot; said Pompeo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said universities can help ensure they have clean investments and donations by exposing Chinese companies to such funds and rejecting those linked to human rights abuses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Tuesday, Pompeo said he hoped that dozens of Chinese government-funded Confucius Institute cultural centers at US universities, which he accused of recruiting &quot;spies and collaborators&quot;, would close by the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Wednesday, the Washington-based American Center of the Confucius Institute, which was forced to enlist as a foreign mission last month after Pompeo accused it of promoting Beijing&#39;s &quot;evil influence,&quot; said it was falsely labeled a &quot;State Mission&quot; by the State Department. , the headquarters of the Confucius Institute.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Contrary to what Department of State people have heard, CI programs in the United States are independent. They are created and run by schools that choose to create Mandarin classes and are offered by people who employ and supervise these schools, &quot;he said in a statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pompeo said he plans to discuss China and other regional issues in a virtual meeting with 10 members of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) and other Indo-Pacific nations next week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The State Department said Pompeo will attend a meeting of East Asian foreign ministers and another meeting with ASEAN counterparts on September 9.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partnerships for cooperation with partner countries in the Mekong, Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam will be concluded on September 11 to strengthen autonomy, economic independence and sustainable development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition, on that day he will also attend the ASEAN Regional Forum meeting, a group of 27 countries brought together by ASEAN with speech partners from all over the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The US move on Wednesday was further away from last October. Chinese diplomats have requested that they notify meetings with local government and officials, as well as educational and research institutions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The State Department also urged Chinese media to register as a diplomatic mission abroad and announced in March that it would reduce the number of journalists allowed to work in US offices from major Chinese media outlets to 160 from 160.</p>', 'US, Impose Restrictions, China', 'Flag_1599309007.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:30:07', '2021-08-18 06:27:40'),
(151, 7, 7, 42, 'the-british-government-changed-its-mind-about-masks-in-british-schools-1599309093', 'The British government changed its mind about masks in British schools', 0, '<p><strong>London: British Prime Minister Boris Johnson on Wednesday tried to reassure students about the risks of returning to school after a reversal of the mask policy raises new questions about government management of the coronavirus epidemic.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The government resigned and insisted that students in Britain should not cover their noses and mouths when they return to classes next week because they are worried about an increase in new infections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The change is seen as another policy reversal just weeks after ministers were forced to end the use of an algorithm that gives students aged 17 and 18 worse than expected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During a visit to a school in Central England, Johnson thanked his students for months at home for the outbreak, which has helped the country control the disease.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Your health risk does not come from Covid because your chances of suffering from this disease are statistically very, very small,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The biggest risk you face now is that you still won&#39;t go to school.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new guidelines encourage students aged 11-18 and staff to wear face coverings in corridors and public areas in locations with local coronavirus restrictions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Teachers&#39; unions have asked the British government, which is responsible for education in Britain, to follow Scotland, which has a separate education system and is now asking students to hide between lessons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Critics, including the opposition Labor Party, welcomed the changes but said ministers had handed over responsibility and left law enforcement to schools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Labor education spokeswoman Kate Green called for &quot;half a turn,&quot; saying clearer guidelines should have been given earlier.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; ** - Under shot - **</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Underwater Education Secretary Gavin Williamson insisted schools do not need masks, and earlier this week Johnson&#39;s office said there were no plans to review the guidelines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Williamson, widely blamed for his excitement over the test results, said on Wednesday that the government would now follow the World Health Organization&#39;s advice for children 12 and over to wear masks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;No coverage of people in schools is required outside of restricted areas, although schools have the flexibility to introduce measures if they deem appropriate under the circumstances,&quot; he said on Wednesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I hope these steps provide added security for parents, students and teachers.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The coronavirus outbreak in Britain - Europe&#39;s biggest death toll - has killed some 41,500 people and the government&#39;s response to the pandemic has been criticized.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ministers were accused of not responding quickly enough, of not providing sufficient protective equipment for social workers and the testing regime.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>London scrapped its policy of wearing face masks in shops in Britain after initially saying they were not needed and was forced to cancel plans to reopen primary schools in July.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Education is the responsibility of local governments in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Older students in Northern Ireland are being asked to wear a disguise outside class next week. The Welsh Assembly in Cardiff will take a decision on Wednesday</p>', 'British Government, Dicisions on Masks', 'UK PM_1599309093.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:31:33', '2021-07-22 07:29:27'),
(152, 7, 10, 81, 'joe-biden-accused-trump-of-inciting-violence-ahead-of-the-us-elections-1599309209', 'Joe Biden accused Trump of \"inciting violence\" ahead of the US elections', 0, '<p><strong>PITTSBURG: Former Vice President and Democratic presidential candidate Joe Biden attacked President Donald Trump for inciting pre-election violence.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The stakes for Biden&#39;s speech in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania couldn&#39;t be higher the day before Trump&#39;s trip to Kenosha, Wisconsin, to unveil his dueling vision of chaos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After months of travel restrictions on COVID-19, Biden suddenly found himself on the defensive and ridiculed as weak by Trump in the face of events that combined left-wing anti-racism protests, civil unrest, deadly shootings and right-wing vigilance in Kenosha. and Portland, Oregon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As Trump steps in to shift the debate from his widespread handling of the coronavirus pandemic to his favorite crime scene, Biden risks losing the momentum that brought him forward in the November 3 election.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But 77-year-old Democrats have denounced the Trump presidency as a &quot;toxic presence in our country&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The fire was burning and we had a president who lit the fire instead of putting it out,&quot; said Biden.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The incumbent president cannot tell us the truth, he cannot face facts and he cannot heal.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since Trump spent much of the last week warning voters he would not be &quot;safe&quot; in Biden&#39;s America, Democrats attempted in his 22-minute speech delivered in a largely empty hall about the fear of the coronavirus. wanted to change his attitude towards the Republic. - with the question: &quot;Do you really feel safer with Donald Trump?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Read more: Joe Biden Says Trump Is The &quot;First&quot; Racist President of the United States</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump &quot;can&#39;t stop the violence because he&#39;s been fueling it for years,&quot; said Biden.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump &quot;may believe that saying the words&quot; law and order &quot;makes him strong, but his failure to encourage his own supporters to stop acting as an armed militia in this country shows you how weak he is.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Biden, accused by Republicans of not condemning violent leftist anti-racist protesters enough, has tried to calm this down.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Robbery is not a protest, arson is not a protest,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;None of these protests. It&#39;s a lawlessness, clear and simple, and those who do it must be persecuted.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At a press conference at the White House, Trump still complained that Biden &quot;mainly blamed the police and law enforcement agencies&quot; rather than the radical left.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kenosha flash point</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Tuesday, Trump will promote his own views on what went wrong in American cities by visiting Kenosha.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The city in one of the most swaying states on the voting map is in chaos after a white policeman arrested an African-American man in front of his children earlier this month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A microcosm of racial and ideological tensions since the Trump era, Kenosha has seen protests, riots and the arrival of armed white citizens culminating in an incident in which 17-year-old militia fan Kyle Rittenhouse shot two people to death. injure another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Democrats and supporters of police reform see Kenosha as a symbol of institutional racism leading to deadly encounters between police officers and black suspects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You see in Rittenhouse, a Trump supporter, a symbol of the right-wing militia who, in the political situation, are increasingly swinging arms and trying to act as amateur law enforcement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, Trump has made it clear that he has different priorities: he opposes what he repeatedly calls &quot;anarchy&quot; in democratic cities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He will &quot;meet with local law enforcement and several business owners and investigate the damage,&quot; spokesman Kaylee Makenani told reporters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Describing his desire to &quot;see people doing such a good job for me,&quot; Trump quoted law enforcement officials for suppressing the unrest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump also refused to condemn the alleged killing of Rittenhouse, who was on the street carrying a gun.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump called it an &quot;interesting situation&quot; and said the teenager who appeared in the murder video - allegedly Rittenhouse - reacted because he was attacked.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The White House has not announced Trump&#39;s plans to meet in Kenosha with the family of the black man who was shot dead by police officer Jacob Blake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although Biden is on the phone with the Blakes, Trump has also ruled that out, saying relatives want a family lawyer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That&#39;s inappropriate,&quot; he said without elaborating.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump said he had a &quot;great conversation&quot; with the &quot;pastor&quot; whom he described as a &quot;great man&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Blake&#39;s father, Jacob Blake Sr., said he was confused by Trump&#39;s comments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We don&#39;t have a family pastor,&quot; he told CNN. &quot;I don&#39;t know who he&#39;s talking to, I don&#39;t care.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wisconsin Governor Tony Evers asked Trump not to visit him for fear of further tensions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Trump replied that his trip &quot;can increase love and respect for our country&quot;.</p>', 'Joe Biden, Donald Trump, inciting Violence, Elections', 'bIDEN_1599309209.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:33:29', '2021-08-16 00:33:43'),
(153, 7, 10, 65, 'who-will-be-the-next-prime-minister-of-japan-shinzo-abe-1599309473', 'Who Will Be The Next Prime Minister of Japan Shinzo Abe?', 0, '<p><strong>TOKYO: Japan&#39;s ruling party, the LDP, said Wednesday it will vote on September 14 to replace Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, who resigned for health reasons.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The decision started a leadership race in the world&#39;s third largest economy. Three prominent candidates are expected to take the survey:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yoshihide Suga</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yoshihide Suga was Abe&#39;s top adviser for many years and had a major role in overseeing politics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His duties as cabinet secretary include coordination between ministries and authorities as well as government spokesman.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although the role was a step towards leadership in the past, prior to Abe&#39;s resignation, 71-year-old Suga repeatedly stated that he was not interested in the highest jobs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Suga, an amateur lawmaker for a political party of descent, grew up in northern Japan as the eldest son of a strawberry farmer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After high school, he moved to the capital and worked at odd jobs to graduate from college the night before being elected to the Yokohama City Assembly outside Tokyo in 1987.He won a seat in the lower cabinet in 1996.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pragmatic politicians are seen as neutral figures in the ruling Liberal Democratic Party. And while he does not lead any faction in the party, some of the most powerful have abandoned their support.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Suga&#39;s spokesman gave him a small chance to express his own views, but his somewhat anodic image resurfaced last year when he announced the name of a new imperial era: Reiva.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His photo, which contains hand-painted calligraphy for the name, earned him the affectionate nickname &quot;Uncle Reiva&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shigeru Ishiba</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Former Defense Minister Shigeru Ishiba is clearly a favorite of the public but is facing a tough battle for support from his own party.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A military expert with a quirky side - a self-proclaimed 70s pop fan who debates the existence of aliens - Ishiba doesn&#39;t hide his interest in higher education.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He asked Abe to lead the 2018 party race when he was easily defeated but has long been touted as a potential successor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 63-year-old former banker is descended from a political family and is considered a strong speaker with considerable experience - he entered parliament when he was only 29 years old.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like Abe, he is a defensive eagle seeking to empower the country&#39;s self-defense force within a pacifist constitution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He has served in various cabinet positions but struggled with his status as an outsider in the LDP.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He left the party in 1993, became independent, and then briefly joined other parties before returning to the executive committee, a political diversion that many in the LDP did not condone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fumio Kishida</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fumio Kishida is often described as the heir Abe&#39;s favor, but the calmly speaking 63-year-old seems to be struggling to take advantage of his heir status.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A political dove and former foreign minister, Kishida is currently the LDP political leader and has little to hide from his ambitions for the highest political office.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He is a descendant of a political family in Hiroshima, leads a large faction in the ruling party and is considered a safe partner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unlike some of his main rivals, Kishida has never challenged the Prime Minister for leadership and has chosen to remain a loyal minister and understands that he will eventually be approved by Abe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But that didn&#39;t appear to be working out as Abe said he would not endorse any candidate or influence competition for a successor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As foreign minister between 2012 and 2017, Kishida handled several difficult tasks, including negotiating agreements with Russia and South Korea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The focus of Kishida&#39;s tenure as top diplomat was accompanying Barack Obama in 2016 when he became the first incumbent president to visit Hiroshima.</p>', 'Japan, Elections', 'Japan PM_1599309473.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:37:53', '2021-08-18 04:03:50'),
(154, 7, 1, 107, 'coronavirus-schools-pose-no-greater-risk-than-at-home-to-students-and-employees-1599309604', 'Coronavirus: Schools pose \"no greater risk than at home\" to students and employees', 0, '<p><strong>According to a study of 131 schools, children and employees are at a higher risk of contracting the coronavirus than if they stay at home.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tests to see who has caught the virus have found similar levels of antibodies in students and teachers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the study of <strong>12,000</strong> adults and children in the UK was conducted in June and early July when there were very few cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Experts say more research is needed when all children are in school.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During the study, students and staff were tested during the last six weeks of the summer period when children were allowed to return to school from admissions, <strong>year 1 and year 6.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since then, millions of children across the UK have returned to school. In recent days teaching has continued in England and Wales. Schools opened in Scotland and Northern Ireland last month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Schools now look very different from before, and students must remain in their &quot;bubble&quot; group, following a one-way system and social distancing when necessary. Start times have also been introduced and hand washing stations and screens have been installed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Public Health England researchers who led the study found that only three people (one child and two employees) tested positive for the <strong>virus - 0.02%</strong> of tamponade.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no evidence that any of these three people passed the virus on to other people they lived or worked with. This reflects previous PHE studies which showed a low number of cases and outbreaks in schools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Antibody level</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A separate sample of 2,100 employees and children who were tested for antibodies found that 10.6% of students and 12.7% of employees had previously contracted the coronavirus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This could indicate that children are more likely to catch it than adults than are less susceptible to disease.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, because very few positive cases have been found in children, previous research has confirmed that they tend to have mild or no symptoms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The study found that children and staff who attended school more frequently were more likely to have positive antibody test results than those who did not attend school or attended school less frequently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This may mean that infection rates in schools only reflect virus levels in the communities where people live.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, some groups were more likely to have antibodies - they were not white, lived in the same house with a health care worker, and had symptoms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Secondary schools were not included in this study, so no conclusions can be drawn for older children.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&quot;Convincing&quot;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dr. Shamez Ladani, Consultant Epidemiologist at Public Health England, said: &ldquo;This is the largest study of its kind in the country and suggests that attending preschool and primary school does not pose additional risks to staff or students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&quot;Although these results are preliminary, they should be very reassuring to parents who are concerned about their children returning to school.&quot;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dr. Liz Whitaker, clinical lecturer and pediatric advisor at Imperial College London, said it was a &quot;benign study&quot; but &quot;time-limited&quot; because coronavirus transmission was very low during the study period.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&quot;It is imperative that such research continues over the next few months, especially in high schools and colleges,&quot;</strong> he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Williamson said A and GCSE grades are expected to be available next summer</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The workforce is calling for exams to be postponed next summer</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Exams for next year should be reduced, said the principal</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Professor Ravindra Gupta, professor of clinical microbiology at Cambridge University, warned that schools can now admit two to six times as many children, which could change the results.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&quot;The social distancing capacity is less than schools in June. We must not be complacent and misconvinced. We must implement adequate monitoring and testing strategies to detect infections in schools before they spread,&quot;</strong> he said. he.</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<p>Regarding the finding that children are often asymptomatic, Prof. Gupta said that meant &quot;children can continue their studies if we don&#39;t have regular virus tests in schools&quot;.</p>\r\n</div>', 'Coronavirus, Schools, Student Risk', 'student pic_1599309604.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:40:04', '2021-08-17 17:48:59'),
(155, 7, 1, 68, 'coronavirus-facebook-twitter-and-youtube-dont-treat-anti-vaccination-posts-1599309869', 'Coronavirus: Facebook, Twitter and YouTube \"Don\'t Treat Anti-Vaccination Posts\"', 0, '<p><strong>According to a group of campaigns, social networks do not discuss anti-vaccine-anti-vaccine publications that contain &quot;clearly harmful information&quot; even after their material is read.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>He recorded more than 900 examples on Facebook, Instagram, Twitter and YouTube by a team of volunteers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It said the company had not eliminated or handled 95% of the cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each of the four platforms has guidelines for limiting such content.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Center for Combating Digital Hate (CCDH) said lawmakers in Britain should speed up existing plans to bring the company to justice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>US companies receive a copy of the report prior to publication.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It contains selected examples. However, CCDH has not released a complete list of links to related posts, although it has committed to do so upon request after the report was released.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Misleading Instagram post about Coronavirus IMAGE COPYRIGHTCCDH</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CCDH said many publications that were marked were linked to the philanthropist Bill Gates</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This limits the ability of US companies to handle certain cases. However, the company says it has removed and tagged millions of other items since the virus was classified as a public health emergency.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vaccination rules</p>\r\n\r\n<p>None of the participating technology companies prohibited consumers from posting inaccurate information about vaccinations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following a series of measles outbreaks in 2019, Facebook - which owns Instagram - announced that users will be directed to trusted information from the World Health Organization (WHO) when searching for or visiting relevant content.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Twitter and YouTube also took steps in the same year to distract users from related conspiracy theories.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, after the Covid-19 explosion, the platforms tightened their rules.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook has announced that it will remove posts that could cause physical injury and post warnings on other relevant fact-checked posts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Twitter said it would remove posts related to the coronavirus that could cause widespread social panic and / or unrest and added a warning message about other controversial or misleading information about the pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And YouTube says it has banned content for Covid-19 that poses a &quot;serious risk of harm&quot; or violates medical information from WHO and local health officials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>conspiracy theory</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>CCDH said a total of 912 items had been given to the company by vaccine protesters between July and August that were found to violate Covid-19 rules.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From them:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook received 569 complaints. He deleted 14 posts, added 19 warnings, but didn&#39;t lock accounts - that&#39;s 5.8% of the action</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instagram received 144 complaints. He deleted three posts, suspended one account, and added two warning posts - which was an action 4.2% of the time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Twitter received 137 complaints. He deleted four posts, suspended two accounts, and didn&#39;t add any warnings - which is an act of 4.4% of the time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>YouTube received 41 complaints. It didn&#39;t affect any of them</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Examples of materials not considered under the CCDH are:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An Instagram post stated that &quot;the upcoming coronavirus vaccine is a killer&quot; which will cause &quot;DNA damage&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A post on Facebook claimed that the only way to catch the virus is to &quot;inject a vaccine&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A tweet said that vaccines have genetically modified humans and are no longer in line with God&#39;s intentions</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A YouTube video of one respondent who claims Covid is part of a &quot;depopulation program&quot; and the vaccine causes cancer</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CCDH adds that roughly every tenth example cites a conspiracy theory involving Microsoft co-founder Bill Gates, including the suggestion that people should be given microchips that would starve them to death if they refused vaccinations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&quot;Aggressive Step&quot;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook said it had &quot;taken aggressive steps to curb the spread of misinformation,&quot; including removing more than seven million articles and adding a warning to 98 million misinformation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Twitter says that while it doesn&#39;t take action on any tweets containing controversial information about the virus, it does prioritize those with a potentially dangerous call to action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Our automated systems have triggered millions of accounts that focus on discussions about Covid-19 with spam or manipulative behavior,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And Google says it has taken a number of steps to &quot;combat malicious misinformation,&quot; including banning some videos and displaying fact-checking panels with others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the CCDH chairman said politicians and regulators in the US and UK must now force companies to take tougher action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is an imminent crisis where a ticking time bomb will explode in our society,&quot; said Imran Ahmed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Social media companies ... are not listening to polite calls for change. Given the acute nature of the coronavirus crisis, their present inaction is bound to have real consequences.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>London-based CCDH is funded by the Pears Foundation, the Joseph Rowntree Charitable Trust and the Barrow Cadbury Trust, as well as others who have said the group would not wish to be named if targeted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Analysis box by Mariana Spring, disinformation and social media reporter</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Public health experts warn that conspiracy theories about a coronavirus vaccine are spreading rapidly online and posing a serious threat to all of us.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When large numbers of people choose not to have safe, approved vaccines, our ability to suppress disease is limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is reason to worry that the vaccine is safe and properly tested. You can also talk about this in private or online chats.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, he claims the coronavirus vaccine will be a means of mass surveillance or genocide will only do harm.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Theory is often promoted by popular pseudoscientific figures and large Facebook pages known to promote misinformation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They are then trickled into the diet of ordinary people and are sometimes amplified by celebrities who sow seeds of doubt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Social media companies say they are taking action, but critics say that if they stop doing it - voluntarily or under pressure, they could contribute to a public health catastrophe.</p>', 'CoronaVirus, Anti Vaccination Posts', 'Anti vacine_1599309869.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:44:29', '2021-08-14 22:37:49'),
(156, 7, 1, 50, 'coronavirus-cheap-steroids-save-lives-from-severe-covid-1599309903', 'Coronavirus: Cheap steroids save lives from severe Covid', 0, '<p><strong>Cheap steroids could save the lives of patients who are seriously ill with Covid-19, research shows.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>These results confirm the results of previous studies that have led to widespread steroid use in ICU patients with Covid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new results published in JAMA show that eight lives are saved for every 100 patients treated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The researchers said the results were impressive, but the steroids in focus were not a cure for the coronavirus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What progress are we making in medicine?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In June, a UK recovery study found the first drug - a steroid called dexamethasone - could save the lives of people with severe Covid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The latest study brings together all clinical trials of steroids in patients with coronavirus around the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This confirms that dexamethasone works and that another steroid, hydrocortisone, is equally effective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Media caption Catherine Milbank spent 15 days in hospital and was part of the recovery process</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At the start of the year, he felt almost hopeless because he knew we were not having special treatment,&quot; said Professor Anthony Gordon of Imperial College London.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It was a very worrying time, but less than six months later we found clear and reliable evidence in high-quality clinical trials of how to deal with this devastating disease.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The results of the study on 1,703 critically ill patients showed:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>40% die if they receive only standard treatment</p>\r\n\r\n<p>32% died while using steroids</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Study only for the sickest hospital patients. Most people recover with only mild symptoms. Steroids relieve inflammation and the immune system, which is why they have been used in conditions such as arthritis and asthma, as well as some serious infections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Medication is not considered useful in the early stages of a Coronavirus infection - if symptoms include coughing, fever, or a sudden loss of taste or smell.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, as the disease progresses, the immune system can become overwhelmed and damage the lungs and other organs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Covid stage is believed to help steroids.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;When you take a bottle of oxygen for a patient with Covid, you may need to take a prescription for a corticosteroid,&quot; said Professor Martin Landray of the University of Oxford.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These results are immediately usable. These results are widely available, inexpensive, and are a well-understood drug that reduces mortality.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Doctors are already using dexamethasone according to results earlier this year, but there is hope that different drug options will improve access to treatment worldwide.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Medicines can be swallowed in tablet form or given intravenously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far, research has focused on low-dose steroids. There is no evidence that a higher dose is more effective.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The World Health Organization is expected to publish new guidelines for doctors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the UK, NHS Executive Director Sir Simon Stevens said, &quot;Like dexamethasone, the NHS will now take urgent action to ensure that patients who may benefit from hydrocortisone treatment do so by adding one more.&quot; Weapons in the world&#39;s arsenal against Covid-19 &quot;.</p>', 'Cheap Steriods, Coronavirus', 'Cheap Steriod_1599309903.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:45:03', '2021-08-14 22:37:46'),
(157, 7, 1, 87, 'coronavirus-portuguese-quarantine-rules-come-into-effect-1599309971', 'Coronavirus: Portuguese quarantine rules come into effect', 0, '<p>Travelers coming to Scotland from Portugal will have to self-isolate for 14 days under new rules that took effect on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scotland and Wales have put the country on their &quot;quarantine lists&quot; - England and Northern Ireland have not.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UK Transport Secretary Grant Shaps said it was a confusing position but the Scottish Government insisted it was acting on scientific advice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The rules go into effect at 4:00 a.m.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>French Polynesia is now also on the list of countries to be quarantined, while Greece&#39;s self-isolation rules have been in place since Thursday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Significant Risk&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Justice Minister Humza Youssef said the decision to join Portugal was made after the number of coronavirus cases increased to more than 20 per 100,000 population.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Yousaf said: &quot;We are in the midst of a global pandemic and the situation in many countries can suddenly change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So people have to think well before making nonessential trips abroad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Due to Scotland&#39;s relatively low infection rate, importing new cases poses a significant public health risk.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Scottish government is also monitoring the situation in Gibraltar, he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the move has been questioned by UK Transport Secretary Grant Shaps, who told the BBC earlier this week that the Scottish government had decided to &quot;take up arms&quot; without including Greece on a quarantine list, according to data from the Joint Biosafety Center. (JBC).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Portugal, the decision does not take into account an increase in test levels. He said the positive numbers - the percentage of positive tests - were lower than when Portugal was added to the travel corridor list.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, a Scottish government spokesman said Chaps had decided to keep Portugal on its list of travel corridors before reviewing the latest JBC data.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The same approach</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Returning tourists to Scotland must self-isolate even though they have flown to an airport in England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prime Minister Boris Johnson later downplayed the differences between British states when he was interviewed during a visit to the West Midlands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While acknowledging that delegated administration sometimes took different approaches, he insisted that Britain &quot;act as a whole&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think you&#39;ll find Britain taking a similar approach if you dig beneath the surface of some surface differentiation,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Travelling Scotland to Portugal, Self Isolation, Corona', 'Portugaal_1599309971.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:46:11', '2021-08-14 22:37:59'),
(158, 7, 1, 63, 'coronavirus-test-can-intercept-dead-viruses-1599310181', 'Coronavirus: test \"can intercept dead viruses', 0, '<p><strong>According to Johns Hopkins University, there are currently more than six million cases of Covid-19 in the United States, nearly a quarter of the world.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said the country added one million new infections in less than a month. More than 183,000 people have now died.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Britain, France and Spain saw their infection rates fall from Sunday&#39;s figures, but the numbers can be adjusted later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Children across Europe are preparing to return to school this week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The total number of confirmed cases worldwide has exceeded 25 million, with more than 846,000 deaths linked to Covid-19. The true number of cases is likely to be significantly higher because many people who have the infection but do not show symptoms are not tested.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The World Health Organization (WHO) has now warned that urgent vaccination clearance requires &quot;a lot of seriousness and thought&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>United Nations chief scientist Sumia Suminanathan said every country has the right to approve drugs without a full study, but &quot;you don&#39;t do it easily.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to WHO, 33 potential vaccines are currently in clinical trials and 143 more in preclinical evaluation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s new in the US?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Monday, John Hopkins announced that there are currently more than six million coronavirus cases in the United States.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The university, which has been collecting data on the US and the global coronavirus since last year&#39;s outbreak in China, announced America&#39;s first infection on January 21.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The country reached its millions in 99 days, and on April 28 and 43 days later, the number of infections doubled.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Where are the global coronavirus hotspots?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump signed on to help tackle the virus after talks broke down</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Millions of Americans &quot;hang on the ropes&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Three million cases were confirmed over the next 28 days, increasing to four million on July 23 after the next 15 days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The five million mark passed for 17 more days, and it took the United States another 22 days for the six million infections to reach.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Media Signature Why the United States is struggling to reopen</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although the number of daily cases has fallen in recent weeks, the United States remains by far the worst-hit country in the world in terms of death and death tolls.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Donald Trump&#39;s administration has been repeatedly criticized for fighting the outbreak.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coronavirus: A week where things have changed for Trump</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But White House spokeswoman Kaylee Makenani said the United States was coping well with the pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We are encouraged to see a decrease in cases, deaths and hospitalizations,&quot; he told reporters at a news conference Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms McEnany said America had &quot;one of the lowest death rates in the world&quot; and added that &quot;our therapies are working and saving lives&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At other major events around the world:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the UK, the number of confirmed cases rose 1,406 - compared with 1,715 new cases Sunday. Two other deaths were reported</p>\r\n\r\n<p>France reported 3,082 new infections, each of which fell sharply by more than 5,000 cases in the past two days</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spain recorded more than 23,000 new coronavirus cases on Friday - suggesting that the national infection rate has fallen slightly from the previous week&#39;s high.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Indian economy contracted 23.9% in the quarter ending June 2020, official figures show</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Australia, Victoria, the epicenter of the country&#39;s latest outbreak, reported 222 new cases - the lowest increase in infections since July 18.</p>', 'CoronaVirus, Dead Virus', 'CoronaVirus_1599310181.jpg', '2020-09-05 16:49:41', '2021-08-14 22:38:11');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(159, 7, 4, 28, 'kai-haverz-who-signed-a-contract-with-bayer-leverkusen-chelsea-for-ps-71-million-1599311995', 'Kai Haverz: Who signed a contract with Bayer Leverkusen Chelsea for  71 million?', 0, '<p><strong>He was called &quot;the next Michael Ballack&quot; and was offered a future superstar.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>And after an endless transfer history, Kai Haverz signed for Chelsea and became the second most expensive new signing and seventh new signing this summer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Blues fans will hope it will help the team compete for the title, but why did the club agree to pay a fee of &pound; 71 million, including perks, for the 21-year-old?</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"1\" style=\"width:500px\">\r\n	<caption>Chelsea&#39;s summer signings</caption>\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Player</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Fee</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">From</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">\r\n			<table>\r\n				<tbody>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td colspan=\"1\">Position</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n				</tbody>\r\n			</table>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Age</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Kai Havertz</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">\r\n			<table>\r\n				<tbody>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td colspan=\"1\">&pound;71m</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n				</tbody>\r\n			</table>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Bayer Leverkusen</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">\r\n			<table>\r\n				<tbody>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td colspan=\"1\">Midfielder</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n				</tbody>\r\n			</table>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">21</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Timo Werner</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">&pound;47.5m</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">RB Leipzig</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Striker</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">24</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Ben Chilwell</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">&pound;45m</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Leicester</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Left-back</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">23</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Hakim Ziyech</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">&pound;33.3m</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">\r\n			<table>\r\n				<tbody>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td colspan=\"1\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;Ajax</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n				</tbody>\r\n			</table>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Winger</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">26</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Malang Sarr</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Free</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Nice</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Defender</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">21</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Thiago Silva</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Free</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">PSG</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Defender</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">\r\n			<table>\r\n				<tbody>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td colspan=\"1\">35</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n				</tbody>\r\n			</table>\r\n			</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Xavier Mbuyamba</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">\r\n			<table>\r\n				<tbody>\r\n					<tr>\r\n						<td colspan=\"1\">&nbsp; &nbsp;Free</td>\r\n					</tr>\r\n				</tbody>\r\n			</table>\r\n			</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Barcelona</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Defender</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">18</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">&nbsp;</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>The attacking midfielder made waves at the age of 17 and made his debut for Bayer Leverkusen in the 2016/17 season. It was clear from the start that one day he would become a superstar.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Haverz has the technical capabilities of the number 10, but cannot be classified as such. Its size (6 feet 2 inches) and dynamic style make it a choice for a variety of roles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He has often played in Leverkusen&#39;s midfield, but also in midfield, from the right flank and, more recently, as a striker. National coach Joachim Lowe also likes to test him in a deeper role.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some in Germany saw him as the new Michael Ballack. The former Bayern Munich and Chelsea midfielder shares similar traits: he not only pulls the strings with passes, but also makes powerful breakthroughs on the pitch.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While Haverz Balak&#39;s incredible physique is lacking, he is perhaps the shrewd runner who suddenly appears behind the back line to score.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Havertz is a modern playmaker who combines transition skills, foresight, calm under pressure and a high level of sportsmanship. He didn&#39;t try any terrible tricks or do anything ineffective. He is a useless player in the form of his new manager Frank Lampard.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Haverz lacks a colorful personality and, like many German players of his generation, lets his feet do the talking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What was Havertz&#39;s previous story?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He grew up as the son of a police officer and lawyer in the small village of Mariadorf and became a fan and youth player of local club Alemannia Aachen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When he was 10 years old, he caught the attention of talent scout Bayer Leverkusen, who persuaded him to switch to the Bundesliga power plant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since young Havertz still lived in Aachen, he had to drive from school to Leverkusen youth academy several times a week. After joining the U17s, he moved to the home of stadium announcer Klaus Schenkmann.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no history of wealth in tatters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Kai is lucky enough to come from a low-income family. Both his mother and father are humble,&quot; said J&uuml;rgen Gelsdorf, former director of the Leverkusen Academy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Havertz graduated from high school when he was a permanent member of the Leverkusen senior team. He once said, &quot;I can&#39;t go to school in the morning because we are practicing.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the afternoon he had to catch up on subject matter. &quot;At some point I couldn&#39;t do it anymore. My energy was gone. I wanted to give up.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Roger Schmid&#39;s manager persuaded him to stay on track, and it worked.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While his classmates traveled to Lake Garda in Italy, Haverz made his Champions League debut against Tottenham at Wembley in front of an audience of 85,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How did he fit in with Chelsea?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Havertz can be used in a variety of different positions and systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But his most likely role is as first choice number 10 in 4-2-3-1 or number eight continued in 4-3-3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Blues already have a wing group and with the signing of Timo Werner two very talented forwards. You don&#39;t need to experiment with Havertz.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He moves between the lines with ease and can offer a unique presence in Chelsea&#39;s midfield. Like Christian Pulisic and Hakim Zieh, they will benefit when the playmaker is right beside them, while the bottom-back midfielder has a boy as they fight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Former team-mates and coaches praised Haverz for his mental strength - seen as his greatest asset alongside his football talent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It may take a while to get used to the Premier League and its new clubs after 10 years at Leverkusen, but few can keep Havertz from becoming the backbone of Chelsea&#39;s attack.</p>', 'Contract Signed, Bayer Leverkusen Chelsea', 'Future Star Football_1599311184.jpg', '2020-09-05 17:06:24', '2021-08-14 22:39:33'),
(160, 7, 3, 72, 'nines-beat-metallica-and-katy-perry-in-first-place-1599316941', 'Nines beat Metallica and Katy Perry in first place', 0, '<p>The London Nines rapper beat out some of the biggest music stars - including Metallica and Katy Perry - to land his first number one album.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The musician&#39;s third album, Crabs In A Bucket, is the most played and downloaded album of the week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Its record is behind Metallica&#39;s S &amp; M2 throughout the week but overtook American metal bands in the last 24 hours to take first place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fewer than 2,000 sales separate the two, says Official Charts Company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>TOP 5 Albums</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<table cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"border-collapse:collapse; width:591px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:#f2f2f2; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:1px solid #ededed; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:1px solid #ededed; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p><strong>Artist</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:#f2f2f2; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:none; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:1px solid #ededed; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p><strong>Title</strong></p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:1px solid #ededed; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>1) Nines</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:none; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>Crabs In A Bucket</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:1px solid #ededed; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>2) Metallica</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:none; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>S &amp; M 2</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:1px solid #ededed; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>3) Gregory Porter</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:none; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>All Rise</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:1px solid #ededed; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>4) Disclosure</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:none; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>Energy</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:1px solid #ededed; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>5) Katy Perry</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n			<td style=\"background-color:white; border-bottom:1px solid #ededed; border-left:none; border-right:1px solid #ededed; border-top:none; height:32px; vertical-align:bottom\">\r\n			<p>Smile</p>\r\n			</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Crabs In A Bucket is Nines&#39; third studio album and his first on a major label, reflecting his journey from Church Road in London to national recognition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The title shows how difficult it is to leave one&#39;s past behind. Last June, the musician was stabbed to death in Maida Vale, a few kilometers from his parents&#39; home in northwest London.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The best selling songs of the summer are revealed<br />\r\n&quot;I can be anywhere in the world after that success,&quot; he told The Guardian last month. &quot;I could book a flight and cool off on the beach, but I hang around the mansion every day, top the charts, and see, I ended up getting stabbed.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that he felt like cancer in the bucket kept trying and not coming out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The rapper&#39;s latest album topped the download and streaming charts, but Metallica sells more on CD and vinyl<br />\r\nReal name 20-year-old Courtney Leon Freckleton celebrates her first place and poses with her tribute to the official rank outside the mansion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I thank everyone who put me in this position,&quot; he said. &quot;I ended up winning the golden boots - I was there with Alan Shearer, Andy Cole and the other winners in the gold boots!&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The results marked the Top 5 Nines&#39; third album, with 2017 debuting One Foot Out at number four and subsequent 2018 Crop Circle debuting at five.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her victories came a week later on major releases where each of the top five albums was a new record.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lewis Capaldi&#39;s foundation<br />\r\nJazz singer Gregory Porter&#39;s sixth album, All Rise, debuted at the age of three, followed by dance duo Disclosure, whose long-awaited third record, Energy, came in at fourth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pop star Katy Perry has released her fourth consecutive top 10 album with Smile - a slight improvement on her latest album Witness, which debuted on six albums in 2017.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week&#39;s number one, The Killers&#39; Imploding The Mirage, dropped to number seven.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Caption<br />\r\nLuis Capaldi is the first British artist to debut one million sales of Rag &#39;N&#39; Bone Man in 2017.<br />\r\nMeanwhile, Luis Capaldi&#39;s debut album &quot;Divine Uninspired To A Hellish Extent&quot; sold millions of copies this week, a major event for the Scottish star.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the hit singles Hold Me While You Wait and Someone You Loved, the album spent 68 consecutive weeks in the top 10, 10 of them at number one.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This marks the first UK debut to sell a million Rag &#39;N&#39; Bone Man in 2017.</p>\r\n\r\n<h2>Top 5 singles</h2>\r\n\r\n<table>\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Artist</th>\r\n			<th scope=\"col\">Title</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>1) Cardi B &amp; Megan Thee Stallion</td>\r\n			<td>WAP</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>2) Joel Corry ft MNEK</td>\r\n			<td>Head &amp; Heart</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>3) Nathan Dawe ft KSI</td>\r\n			<td>Lighter</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>4) 24kGoldn ft Ian Dior</td>\r\n			<td>Mood</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td>5) Headie One, AJ &amp; Stormzy</td>\r\n			<td>Ain&#39;t It Different</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nIn the single rap chart, Wild Cardi B and Megan Thee Stallion reached their first number one with their WAP duo ranked X.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The song&#39;s success ended Joel Corey&#39;s and MNEK&#39;s six-week reign at the top of the charts with the club hit Head &amp; Heart.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Calvin Harris and The Weeknd have their biggest new show at 33 with their new collaboration Over Now - Harris &#39;35. Get into the top 40.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Blackpink and Selena Gomez debuted at number 39 with the brilliant pop song Ice Cream, which received 176 million views on YouTube in a week.</p>', 'Metallica, Katy Perry, Nine Beats', 'Crabs IN A bucket_1599316941.jpg', '2020-09-05 18:42:21', '2021-08-16 19:28:12'),
(161, 7, 3, 58, 'strictly-come-dancing-jackie-smith-completes-the-lineup-for-2020-1599317138', 'Strictly Come Dancing: Jackie Smith completes the lineup for 2020', 0, '<p><strong>Former Home Secretary Jackie Smith was confirmed as the 12th and final celebrity candidate for Strictly Come Dancing this year.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Smith will be joined by stars like Bill Bailey, Clara Ampho and HRVY.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 2020 streak will start in October but will be shorter than usual and Judge Bruno Tonioli will play a lesser role due to the coronavirus restrictions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Participants stay at the hotel for two weeks before recording all group dances.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BBC has also confirmed that they can train, perform and return to their families every night - per government guidelines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rival</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jackie Smith was confirmed as the final celebrity dancer on Steve Wright&#39;s Radio 2 show on Friday afternoon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The former Labor politician became the UK&#39;s first female Home Secretary in 2007 under Prime Minister Gordon Brown and has worked as a political cameraman since then.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was speechless with excitement when I was asked to join in so strictly - and that&#39;s very rare for me,&quot; said Smith.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Fifty years ago I received a bronze medal for Scottish mountain dance and it&#39;s time to dance again.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I couldn&#39;t be in better hands with the Strictly team and I&#39;ll be challenging myself. Warning!&quot; He added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Smith now chairs the NHS Foundation Trust and Sandwell Children&#39;s Trust at Birmingham University Hospital. He also had a base called &quot;To Many&quot; which he dedicated to television cameraman Ian Dale.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Caption</p>\r\n\r\n<p>HRVY has more than 10 million social media outlets</p>\r\n\r\n<p>HRVY was turned down as a candidate on the Kiss Breakfast Show and said he was &quot;very grateful to be involved&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The pop singer, whose real name is Harvey Lee Cantwell, has more than a billion streams to his name.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She has more than 10 million on social media and attended BBC Radio 1&#39;s Big Weekend in Middlesbrough last year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 21-year-old player rose to fame after uploading his music video to Facebook. He has sold out on tour in the UK and Europe and his debut album will be released later that year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Strictly speaking, this will be an extraordinary experience and I am very grateful to be able to participate this year,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think my mom is more excited to see me every Saturday night!&quot; Macy Smith is an actress and singer best known for her role as Tiffany Butcher-Baker on EastEnders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Put me in this sequin,&quot; he said in response to his announcement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I can&#39;t wait to dive into some absolutely fantastic dresses this winter!&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Before attacking Albert Square as Bianca&#39;s daughter Tiffany, Smith made her acting debut in The Other Boleyn Girl in 2008, alongside Scarlett Johansson and Eddie Redman.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For her role in the old BBC soap, she won the 2009 Young Soap Awards Young Actress Award for best dramatic performance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jamie Laing returns to the show this year after retiring from last year&#39;s record before starting injury-related.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She became a household name on the Channel 4 reality show, Made in Chelsea, in 2011, and this year released her own podcast, 6 Degrees by Jamie and Spencer, along with Spencer Matthews.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2012 he also founded Candy Kittens cake shop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Here too we hope this time I can last long enough until my mother sees me dancing,&quot; said Laing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added, &quot;The reason I did it was to make my mum proud, but all I did last year was just upset her even more. Let&#39;s change this year, I can be hard to wait !!&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>JJ Chalmer&#39;s career as a Royal Naval Commando was cut short after sustaining life-changing injuries following an IED explosion in Afghanistan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The explosion crushed his eye sockets, damaged his eardrums, crushed his right elbow, detonated two fingers on his left hand, and left a hole in his leg.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After years of rehabilitation, including more than 30 surgeries, he continued to compete in the 2014 Invictus Games where he led the Trike Cycling Team and won three medals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He then began a career in broadcasting, covering the Paralympics in Rio and amplifying BBC One&#39;s coverage of the Invictus Games.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Comparing himself strictly to his military experience, he told ITV&#39;s Lorraine: &quot;I&#39;m always looking for a challenge, I&#39;m always trying to push myself out of my comfort zone.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite the injury, Chalmers said he wanted to be treated like &quot;any other athlete&quot; and did not want &quot;special treatment.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Anyone I work with has stopped working, he added. Bill Bailey is a comedian, actor and musician best known for appearing on television shows such as QI, Black Books, and Never Mind the Buzzcocks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In these strange times we are experiencing, it feels right to do something different and take on new challenges,&quot; he said in a statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t go to school and learn to dance. I don&#39;t live to dance ... I&#39;m not really a dancer. I&#39;m a dancer,&quot; he joked. &quot;It&#39;s going to be quite a challenge, but then it&#39;s about gaining new skills.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 55-year-old Bailey made a name for himself in the stand-up chain before being a regular on panel discussions, television and film actor, documentary filmmaker and BBC sketch host Bill Bailey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He is also a classically trained musician and has published a manual for English birds. On Wednesday, The Daily Telegraph said in looking back at its first live concert in six months that it &quot;remains one of the UK&#39;s funniest and most brilliant original comedians&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Clara Ampho, BBC Radio 1&#39;s morning slot host, helps ensure she can&#39;t wait to fully enjoy the Strictly experience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the last few years, Amfo has covered Glastonbury, the Brit Awards, Big Weekend Radio 1, Bafta TV Awards, and The Proms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As we know, this year is a real challenge and I know we are all excited to get away from dancing,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So, I can&#39;t wait to teach myself to be a professional and experience fantasies. I can see you on the dance floor!&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ranvir Singh is UK Political Editor and occasional moderator for Good Morning. She has also appeared on other ITV programs including &quot;Loose Women&quot;, &quot;Tonight and Eat&quot;, &quot;Shop, Save&quot;. Hosts the new Sunday morning event, All Around Britain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Singh said he was &quot;very surprised&quot; at the idea of attending and compared it to &quot;taking the train&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prior to that, he was a BBC producer and reporter for 12 years, representing BBC North West Tonight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Singh says, &quot;The initial feeling of validation is, strictly speaking, a feeling of horror - it&#39;s like getting on a train that you really want to do, but you are just as scared.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I hope that after the first dance I will feel more excited than sick!&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Media headline Nicolas Adams: same-sex couple &quot;big step&quot; for Strictly Come Dancing</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Olympic boxer Nicola Adams will tell the story of Strictly Come Dancing by becoming the first athlete to be part of a same-sex couple.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He told BBC Breakfast that it was he who offered to partner up when producers asked him to participate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Strictly speaking, presenting the first same-sex pair of its kind</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think it&#39;s very important,&quot; he said. &quot;It is time for change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Adams won a gold medal for Great Britain at the 2012 London Olympics and again in Rio in 2016. He retired from the sport last year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Award-winning actress and presenter, Caroline Quentin, is known for a number of acting roles, including Maddie in Jonathan Creek and DCI Janine Lewis in Blue Murder.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She has also appeared in &quot;Kiss Me Kate&quot;, &quot;Life Begins&quot; and &quot;Riley&#39;s Life&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Perhaps her most famous role, however, was playing Dorothy on the hit 90s sitcom Men Behaving Bad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He recently presented the documentary series &quot;Emergency Homes for BBC Two&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Quentin said he was &quot;excited and scared to participate in Strictly Come Dancing&quot; this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Television cameraman Jason Bell is a retired American professional footballer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He plays as a cornerback / security guard in the National Football League for the Dallas Cowboys.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bell then played for Houston, Texas, where he was named the winner of the Ed Block Courage Award, one of the league&#39;s top honors. He ended his professional career with the New York Giants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bell has hosted the Jason &amp; Osi Podcast with another former NFL star, Osi Umenyiora, and the pair have emerged as experts on the BBC&#39;s NFL show.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is a complete embodiment of British television and this year, more than ever, I am very proud and humbled to attend,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It was absolutely the first show I ever saw when I moved to England and I am a huge fan. My six year old daughter never got the chance to see me run off the pitch in an NFL game, but she is very happy to be out. on the dance floor. I wish I could make him proud. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Singer and actor Max George rose to prominence as a member of the boy band The Wanted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Former teammate Jay McGeany won Strictly Come Dancing back in 2015.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>George said he was &quot;very happy to be there this year&quot; and joked, &quot;I wasn&#39;t exactly off the dance floor, but I am very comforted by the fact that Jay McGeany has set the bar so low on The Wanted.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Wanted had two UK number one singles - All Time Low and Glad You Came - the latter of which topped the US Billboard charts.</p>\r\n\r\n<div>\r\n<p>After The Wanted took his hiatus, Max moved to Los Angeles to pursue an acting career, starring as Clint in the sixth season of Glee. He has recently returned to music as a solo artist.</p>\r\n</div>', 'jACKIE sMITH, Dancing', 'jACQUI_1599317137.jpg', '2020-09-05 18:45:38', '2021-08-16 22:18:37'),
