erday wear', 'Causual neck top_1599386710.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:05:10', '2021-08-12 23:43:34'),
(201, 7, 10, 121, 'coronavirus-melbournes-lockdown-has-been-extended-by-two-weeks-1599388964', 'Coronavirus: Melbourne\'s lockdown has been extended by two weeks', 0, '<p>The tight lockdown on the Australian city of Melbourne has been extended by two weeks, with officials claiming new cases of Covid-19 have not waned enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Victorian Prime Minister Daniel Andrews said the restrictions would remain in effect until Sept. 28, with some relaxation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The gradual easing measures will be implemented from October.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The state is the epicenter of the second wave of countries, accounting for 90% of Australia&#39;s 753 deaths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australia has registered a total of 26,000 cases out of a population of 25 million.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of Melbourne entered the second block on July 9 after an increase in cases. A 5km travel limit and a curfew apply when shops and businesses are closed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The current Level 4 ban was originally meant to end on September 13.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What are some of the new changes?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Melbourne opening hours will be extended from 9:00 p.m. until 5:00 a.m. Individuals are entitled to form and attend balloons, and travel limits currently do not apply to these gatherings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There is only one option, namely in a series of stairs that are stable and safe. You can&#39;t spend a block. Because you just entered the third wave and we will all be locked up again, &quot;said Pak. Andrews at a press conference.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We can&#39;t open now. If we have to, we will lose control very quickly ... I want Christmas to be as normal as possible and that&#39;s the only way, these steps are the only way to get to this point.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the number of daily cases averages between September 30 and September 50, the city will enter a third phase of restrictions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At that time, general gatherings will increase to five from two households, and there will be a gradual return to multi-school and technical schools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the average number of daily cases drops below five on October 26, the curfew will end.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why is Melbourne seeing more cases when it&#39;s banned?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australia&#39;s arrest of the blockade is controversial</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Outside of most of Melbourne, other parts of Victoria will ease restrictions more rapidly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From September 13, up to five people from two households can gather outside. An outdoor pool and playground will open, and services can be held outdoors for a maximum of five people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The announcement comes a day after hundreds of people across Australia took part in protests against the blockade.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Melbourne, about 300 people marched across the city in violation of the act.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s selfish to protest and it&#39;s illegal. Any behavior by someone who adds more virus than less and more restrictions isn&#39;t in anyone&#39;s interest,&quot; Andrews said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;People want this over, me too,&quot; he added.</p>', 'Melbournes, lockdown, extended', 'Melbourne_1599388964.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:42:44', '2021-08-17 13:02:44'),
(202, 7, 7, 33, 'fire-in-california-rescuers-are-working-to-evacuate-dozens-of-people-trapped-in-tanks-1599389105', 'Fire in California: Rescuers are working to evacuate dozens of people trapped in tanks', 0, '<p>A massive rescue operation is underway in California after wildfires trapped people in a popular reservoir.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The helicopters have so far taken dozens of people out of Mammoth Pool, about 60 miles northwest of Fresno.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rescuers returned for another, saying the number of prisoners was unknown. So far, two people have been seriously injured and 10 others slightly injured.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fast-moving fire started around 6.45pm on Friday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By Saturday afternoon, it had grown to about 5,000 acres in Sierra National Forest - an area of rugged, rugged terrain, the LA Times reported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A statement from the Fresno District Fire Department just before midnight local time (7:00 a.m. ET) said that 63 people had been rescued by military helicopter and taken to Fresno Yosemite International Airport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It read: &quot;The planes are returning to resume rescue operations. It is not known how many more.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The rescue came as parts of California were experiencing record heat waves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Friday, Governor Gavin Newsum declared a state of emergency, warning that blackouts could be used in rotation to meet excessive demand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Temperatures up to 49 &deg; C are expected to persist the weekend off for Labor Day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The National Weather Service (NWS) said parts of southern California could experience &quot;rare, dangerous and very possibly fatal&quot; temperatures.</p>', 'California, Fire, Rescue', 'california_1599389105.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:45:05', '2021-08-16 23:36:07'),
(203, 7, 7, 59, 'piercing-in-birmingham-police-declare-major-incident-because-several-people-were-injured-1599389176', 'Piercing in Birmingham: Police declare \"major incident\" because several people were injured', 0, '<p>Several people were stabbed to death in Birmingham city center and police announced a &quot;major incident&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>West Midlands police said they were called in about the stabbing at around 12:30 a.m. ET on Sunday and more knife stabs were reported not long after.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Police said there were &quot;a number of people injured&quot; but could not say how serious the injuries were.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>West Midlands Mayor Andy Street said the Hearst Street incident &quot;appears to be linked&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, according to him, his motivation is still unknown. A police briefing is expected soon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the scene of the incident, the BBC&#39;s Nick Clithero says the incident took place in the part of Birmingham where the gay village meets Chinatown, which is usually bustling with clubs and bars at night.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added, &quot;It appears that this started as a big battle between a large group of people, but it seems that at some point the knife was pulled out and stabbed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This will be very worrying for everyone who lives here. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Major incident&quot; describes any situation that causes damage or a serious risk to public safety.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It also means that all emergency services take special precautions to cooperate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Surprised&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Witness Kara Quran, the organizer of the club operating at the Arcade Center, said the night was busier than ever since the lockdown began.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said he finished his shift at around 12:30 CET and was drinking with a coworker when he heard &quot;loud thunder and a lot of commotion&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added, &quot;I found some people fighting with their fists ... people came out of pubs and clubs and started to see what was going on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There are women, men, old people, young people, a mixture of people like that, it doesn&#39;t seem real at that time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve been working on the club stage for over two years and I&#39;ve always seen a lot of fights, but nothing like tonight. Body language and behavior are very different.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The multitude of things I heard in three hours tonight, with stings, car accidents and many other things, was a huge shock to me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Being an eye-witness of something that happened was quite an emotional night that I&#39;m still a little shocked.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Series of incidents&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mayor Andy Street said he had been directed by the chief of police to confirm that there had been &quot;a number of incidents on Hearst Street.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added, &quot;The motivation is still unclear. The area is deserted and people have been instructed to run their business but remain vigilant.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>West Midlands Police said: &quot;We are aware of a number of victims, but at the moment we cannot say how many or how serious they were.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It said emergency services at the site were working together to ensure that injured victims had received medical care.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The statement further reads: &quot;Work to determine what has happened is still ongoing and it may take a while before we can confirm anything.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At this early stage, it would not be appropriate to speculate on the cause of the incident.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The emergency services have an established plan for dealing with major incidents. Our response is continuing in Birmingham city center and it will take time. Borders have been established and some roads are closed.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The armed forces later said there were no reports of gunfire, adding: &quot;We are known for some of the comments that shots were fired, we have not been notified at this time.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Beware&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lots of people sat outside at tables eating and drinking on a Saturday night.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Roads in the area have been closed to traffic due to coronavirus restrictions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BBC&#39;s Simon Jones says there was some police activity at a second place in the Snow Hill area, about a 10-minute walk from a fenced area believed to be linked to the Hearst Street incident.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Foreign Minister Dominique Raab said people had to be &quot;very vigilant&quot; in the area of a major incident in Birmingham.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaking to Sky News&#39; Sophy Ridge on Sunday, Raab said: &quot;My thoughts are on the victims and their families, a police investigation appears to be underway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I can&#39;t say too much at the moment, but one has to be very vigilant when in this area.&quot;</p>', 'Piercing birmingham, Major incident, Pople injured', 'Barmigham_1599389176.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:46:16', '2021-08-10 05:26:12'),
(204, 7, 7, 45, 'john-cages-musical-work-changed-chords-for-the-first-time-in-seven-years-1599389382', 'John Cage\'s musical work changed chords for the first time in seven years', 0, '<p>Fans flocked to a church in Germany to hear chords turned into musical compositions that lasted 639 years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the first slow change in employment in seven years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The work comes from the American avant-garde composer John Cage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It started 19 years ago with a gap that lasted nearly 18 months. Chord changes occur in specially constructed organs where the composition is played.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>St. Burchard&#39;s Church in Halberstadt began making music in 2001, and the last note exchange took place in 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The score consists of eight pages of music played very slowly on the piano or organ.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the wait for the next scheduled chord change will be shorter than the date set on February 5, 2022.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The song will end at 2640.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cage, who died in 1992 at age 79, wrote the song in the 1980s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The composer is perhaps most famous for his 4&#39;33 &quot;, which was only four minutes and 33 seconds of silence.</p>', 'Joh Cages, Musical world, Chords Change', 'Chord_1599389382.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:49:42', '2021-08-06 07:22:34'),
(205, 7, 9, 139, 'typhoon-haisheng-200000-had-to-be-evacuated-as-japan-prepared-for-the-storm-1599390314', 'Typhoon Haisheng: 200,000 had to be evacuated as Japan prepared for the storm', 0, '<p>More than 200,000 people have been ordered to evacuate areas of Japan at risk of an impending storm.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Typhoon Haishen is expected to intensify on Sunday, causing heavy rains, storms and winds of over 160 km / hr.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It will pass through Kyushu on Sunday and is expected to land in South Korea on Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It came days after Typhoon Maisak, one of the strongest hurricanes in the region in many years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A recent typhoon closed factories, schools and businesses in western Japan. Hundreds of flights and trains have also been canceled.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Japanese government will hold an emergency cabinet meeting on Sunday to respond to the storm.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The country&#39;s meteorological agency said it was unlikely to issue the heaviest typhoon alert, but added that residents should exercise &quot;greatest precautions&quot; of possible record high rains and waves along the coast.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yoshihisa Nakamoto, director of the agency&#39;s forecasting division, told reporters that tidal waves can cause flooding even in low-lying areas, especially near estuaries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What are hurricanes, cyclones and hurricanes?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a result of the storm, hundreds of thousands of people were urged to move to certain emergency shelters such as schools and community centers. This includes all 36,600 residents of the city of Goto, Nagasaki, where typhoons can hit head-on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Local media reported that some people have chosen to seek safe places in local hotels to reduce the risk of the coronavirus spreading in crowded public accommodations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Typhoon Haishen also forced the Japanese Coast Guard to stop searching for sailors who disappeared from cargo ships that sank during Typhoon Maisak.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gulf Livestock 1 was carrying 43 crew members and 6,000 cows when it went missing on Wednesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Three crew members are saved alive.</p>', 'Typhoon, Japan', 'Typhoon japan_1599389465.png', '2020-09-06 14:51:05', '2021-08-14 09:04:20'),
(206, 7, 13, 113, 'earths-lost-sight-is-only-the-tip-of-the-iceberg-1599897919', 'Earth\'s \"lost sight\" is only the tip of the iceberg', 0, '<p>Using fossil evidence of past extinctions, scientists have calculated how many mammals could be lost in this century.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Their predictions suggest that at least 550 species will follow in the footsteps of the mammoth and saber-toothed cat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With each &quot;lost species&quot; we are losing some of Earth&#39;s natural history, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite these &quot;dire&quot; predictions, we can save hundreds of species by increasing conservation efforts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A new study published in the journal Science Advances shows that humans have been responsible almost entirely for mammal extinctions over the past few decades.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And interest rates will increase in the future if we don&#39;t take action now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite these &quot;alarming&quot; scenarios, we could save hundreds, if not thousands, of species with more targeted and effective conservation strategies, said Tobias Anderman of the Global Center for Biodiversity in Gothenburg and the University of Gothenburg.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To do this, we need to raise our collective awareness of &quot;the coming escalation of the biodiversity crisis and take action to combat this global emergency&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Time is running out,&quot; he said. &quot;With each species loss, we are permanently losing a unique part of Earth&#39;s natural history.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scientists have collected a large number of fossils that show the timing and rate of recent extinctions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Their computer-assisted simulations predict a large increase in extinction rates by 2100 based on the species&#39; current threat status.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conservation: A glimmer of hope for the world&#39;s rarest primates</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Billions of years of evolutionary history&quot; are in jeopardy</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Natural crisis: humans &quot;threaten 1 million species with extinction&quot;</p>', 'Lost Sight, Iceberg', 'Species_1599389538.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:52:18', '2021-08-18 01:48:49'),
(207, 7, 13, 91, 'the-secret-of-the-male-elephant-community-in-the-wild-is-revealed-1599896761', 'The secret of the male elephant community in the wild is revealed', 0, '<p><strong>According to a study on African elephants, older male elephants play an important role in the species&#39; survival by passing on their skills and knowledge to younger males.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lead mothers lead the group of daughters and chicks as the males grow and leave the flock.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The researchers found that adult male elephants played an important role in leading these younger men.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And losing them through hunting or hunting could be &quot;catastrophic.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The study, published in the journal Scientific Reports, suggests that older bulls are likely to play a role in male societies similar to that of matriarchs in female breeding herds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It has long been known that older women become more effective herd leadership because of their increased experience. We strongly support the same role for older men in male societies,&quot; said Connie Allen of the University of Exeter and a charity. Elephants for Africa.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Researchers studied the behavior of more than 1,250 male African savanna elephants traveling to and from the Boteti River in Makgadikgadi Pans National Park in Botswana.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Male elephants alone accounted for a fifth of sightings in camera-trapped elephant trails, with juvenile male elephants using this route less than expected, suggesting that traveling alone is more risky for younger, less experienced males.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Adult bulls are more likely to travel ahead of the male group, indicating that they are primary guides with valuable environmental knowledge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Secret to Survival</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The idea that the lonely old man didn&#39;t do much to keep the species alive was used as an argument in favor of the legitimate old man&#39;s hunting trophy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, new research suggests that the killing of an older man could have &quot;catastrophic consequences&quot; for the dismissal of a key figure in male elephant society.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The oldest bulls, with the potential for decades of experience dealing with the environment and handling critical resources, tended to be at the top of all the bulls in our study,&quot; said Connie Allen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This suggests that younger, more recently independent, and younger men are targeting these individuals because of their increased social and environmental knowledge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The extermination of these rare key individuals could have catastrophic effects on the wider banteng population and seriously disrupt the flow of information between generations of this long-lived species.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Males have long been considered solitary animals after gaining independence and leaving their family groups. However, there is growing evidence that both men and women lead rich social lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is more difficult to study in male elephants who travel long distances and harder to track.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof.Darren Croft from the University of Exeter said the new research highlights that older male elephants can act as a repository of environmental knowledge, such as when and where to find food and water, which in turn is beneficial to the survival of young people. connected to them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These results raise concerns about the removal of elderly males from elephant populations through trophy hunting and poaching, as well as the need to protect older male elephants,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The sudden death of more than 275 elephants in northern Botswana made headlines earlier this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tests proved inconclusive, blaming a number of factors for the mass extinction, including natural toxins.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than 20 elephants have died in neighboring Zimbabwe from suspected bacterial infection or the stress of walking long distances to get food and water. In both cases, hunting is excluded.</p>', 'Secret Elephant, Wild, Science', 'Elephant_1599389661.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:54:21', '2021-08-10 20:26:45'),
(208, 7, 8, 37, 'scientists-have-the-answer-to-the-secret-of-the-tadpole-1599389826', 'Scientists have the answer to the secret of the Tadpole', 0, '<p>Scientists have found a way to identify frogs by their pop lies to save amphibians from extinction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Efforts to protect breeding grounds for the endangered frogs have been hampered by difficulty distinguishing pop heads.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now researchers have solved the puzzle of a frog that lives in Vietnam&#39;s remote forests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your work on the Asian horned frog will help stop amphibians extinction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some survive only in small forest areas that are rapidly changing or destroyed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Benjamin Tapley, curator of reptiles and amphibians at ZSL (Zoological Society of London) said: &quot;These frogs are found in some of the most exploited forests in the world and are suffering from rapid loss and degradation of their habitat.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These parts of the river are a common sight on the river for several months of the year, but once they turn into frogs, they disappear into bushes or trees where they may never be seen again.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since frogs and their priestly lies are not alike, it is important to know which head is which frog, he explained.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This helps us identify the presence of a species, especially since adult frogs can be seasonally active and difficult to spot, and allows us to identify which breeding sites may be important breeding grounds for susceptible frogs.&quot; said Dr. Tapley.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The researchers collected geographic data, took photos, measured poppy rays and compared their DNA with samples from known adult frog species.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They were able to identify the pop Tadpole of six species of Asian horned frogs found in Vietnam&#39;s mountainous forests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Poppy seed scoops are unusual with funnel-shaped lips, whereas adults, named for the protrusion of the horns above their eyes, are brown with leaf-like folds of skin that help cover the forest floor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vietnam has more than 250 species of frogs and toads, many of which are critically endangered but still very little is known.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amphibians are increasingly threatened by habitat loss, wildlife trafficking, climate change and deadly diseases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Killer frogs destroy 90 species</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How did the frogs disappear from the lake</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The world&#39;s &quot;loneliest&quot; frog has a date</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only one disease, one fungal species, causes the extinction of at least 501 amphibians, or 6.5% of known species.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The study, carried out with the Indo-Myanmar Conservation Charity, the Asian Turtle Program and the Australian Museum, is published in two articles in the journal Zootaxa.</p>', 'Scientists', 'Frog_1599389826.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:57:06', '2021-08-15 01:34:41'),
(209, 7, 8, 34, 'the-eu-budget-will-be-catastrophic-for-research-1599389879', 'The EU budget will be \"catastrophic\" for research', 0, '<p>According to the researchers, the European Union risks running a &quot;catastrophic&quot; budget for science.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sixteen thousand scientists wrote open letters asking the EU to use its current funding proposals, which they believe could lead to dangerous brain drain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most importantly, they want protection from the European Research Council (ERC).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ERC is the Union&#39;s leading funding agency supporting blue sky research.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There is no doubt that the ERC has set the standard for quality and innovation in science and invention in the European Union - and is recognized worldwide,&quot; said Prof. Ben Feringa, winner of the 2016 Nobel Prize in chemistry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In my opinion this is indeed one of the most successful achievements of the European Union,&quot; the Dutchman told a virtual press conference organized by the Euroscience Open Forum (Esof), adding: &quot;I am sure that the ERC budget compromise will adversely affect Europe&#39;s future. . &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The EU is currently negotiating the next seven-year multi-year financial framework (MFF), which will enter into force in January.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The European Commission&#39;s original (EU executive) proposal for 94 billion euros was rejected by the Council of Europe (head of government of member states), which wanted a figure of less than 86 billion euros.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the decline is confirmed, it basically means the company&#39;s research budget and the ERC&#39;s position within that framework are also limited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far, the block has always increased its research expenditure from one MFF to the next.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Written by ERC friends, the petition was signed by more than 16,000 scientists worldwide, including 14 Nobel Prize winners, many other prestigious scientific award winners, and more than 50 top European universities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The recipients of the letter included the ministers of science in each of the member countries, three EU presidents Ursula von der Leyen (Commission), Charles Michel (Council) and David Sasoli (Parliament).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If we don&#39;t strengthen the next European framework program, Europe&#39;s share of global knowledge production will decrease - there&#39;s no doubt about that,&quot; said Prof. Doug Rune Olsen, Chancellor of the University of Bergen in Norway. &quot;This will have serious long-term consequences for European innovation and industrial leadership.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The budget, which is now obscured by the Commission, Council and European Parliament, does not include contributions from Britain. Britain left the European Union earlier this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, as part of trade talks between London and Brussels, the UK is looking to link up with the MFF&#39;s next research program called Horizon Europe. That means the UK is subscribed to billions of euros.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UK researchers have historically been the main beneficiaries of EU grant schemes, particularly ERC-related funds. Nearly a fifth of all funding from the European Research Council in its 14 year history goes to UK-based colleagues.</p>', 'EU Budget, Catastrophic', 'Eu_1599389879.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:57:59', '2021-08-12 21:07:49'),
(210, 7, 8, 49, 'shark-researchers-are-scaling-a-real-megalodon-for-the-first-time-1599389932', 'Shark researchers are scaling a real \"megalodon\" for the first time', 0, '<p>The fierceness of the prehistoric mega-shark known in Hollywood films was finally discovered by researchers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far, only the length of Megalodon&#39;s Otodus, as depicted in the 2018 film &quot;Meg&quot;, has been assessed based on fossil teeth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, teams from the Universities of Swansea and Bristol combined mathematics with nature to find out how great it was.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The study is published in the journal Scientific Reports.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Researchers have used mathematical methods and comparisons with living relatives to determine the overall size of the megalodon, which lived about 23 to three million years ago.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The results showed that 16 megalodons - nearly three times longer than a great white shark - likely had a head length of about 4.65 meters, a dorsal fin the size of an adult, and a tail length of about 3.85 meters. 13 feet) high.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jack Cooper, who is currently pursuing a PhD in paleobiology from Swansea University, called the study a &quot;dream project.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Megalodon is the animal that inspired my paleontology, but studying the whole animal is difficult because we actually have very isolated teeth,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Strange discovery in Wales</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Dinosaur footprints&quot; on the beach rock were examined</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From mammoth skins to Jurassic fossils</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is important for us now to be able to calculate the proportions and sizes of body parts when no fossils are to be disposed of.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The dimensions in the film are actually quite accurate.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previously sharks were only compared to great white sharks, but recent analysis has been expanded to include five modern sharks, including the macos shark, salmon and shark.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Cooper adds, &quot;We can take the growth curves of the five modern shapes and design the overall shape as it gets bigger - up to sixteen meters long.&quot;</p>', 'Shark, megalodon', 'Shark_1599389932.jpg', '2020-09-06 14:58:52', '2021-08-17 08:59:13'),
(211, 7, 8, 33, 'the-zombie-fires-caused-record-co2-emissions-in-the-arctic-1599390001', 'The zombie fires caused record CO2 emissions in the Arctic', 0, '<p>Research shows that summer carbon emissions from wildfires in the Arctic are a third higher than the previous year&#39;s record level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Copernicus Atmospheric Monitoring Service is concerned that fires that occur during the summer heat wave are cause for concern.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They say some of the so-called zombie fires burn in the peat below the frozen surface in winter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These underground fires then reignited surface vegetation in the spring.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This raises two problems: not only CO2 emissions from burning vegetation, but also peat, which of course is a CO2 reserve.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Researchers estimate that Arctic CO2 emissions from fires were 244 megatons from early January to late August.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a very large number - similar to the sum for the entire economy of, say, Malaysia or Eygpt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is climate change? Very simple guide</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A warming world will &quot;destroy&quot; the frozen plains</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What Greta Thunberg did with her school year</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The forest fire index is only 17 years old, so it cannot provide a complete historical picture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, scientists are concerned that this year&#39;s increase in forest fires is following the previous record in 2019, which in turn dampens the previous trend.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scientists say fires can be caused by lightning strikes or human activity, as well as zombie fires.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A senior Copernican scientist, Mark Parrington, told BBC News: &quot;The number of fires last year surprised us, so it&#39;s all the more surprising to see this year&#39;s figure even higher.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Obviously the question is - we really didn&#39;t anticipate that there would be so many wildfires.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Massive fires also raged in Russia&#39;s Far East Federal District, and large parts of the United States experienced wildfires during the heat wave - with large streams of smoke visible over the Great Lakes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>California in particular has experienced widespread fires, including the second and third largest fires in state history.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rod Downey, chief polar advisory at WWF, said: &quot;The Arctic is collapsing. Large areas are burning before our eyes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The climate crisis behind this record breaking is a global problem. In the UK, we have the opportunity to lead the world at next year&#39;s Glasgow summit - but we can only do this if we drastically and immediately increase our ambition.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Copernicus scientists say man-made climate change does not directly cause fires, but that rising temperatures make the fires more likely to continue.</p>', 'Zombie Fires, C02 emissions', 'Zoobies fire_1599390001.jpg', '2020-09-06 15:00:01', '2021-08-14 00:52:24'),
(212, 7, 8, 60, 'europes-small-vega-rocket-is-back-in-action-1599390062', 'Europe\'s small Vega rocket is back in action', 0, '<p>European Vega missiles return to service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The forced lull after losing the vehicle in July 2019 ended Wednesday night with the successful deployment of 53 new satellites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The payload is lowered well above ground level using a new dosing system that will now become an integral part of future missions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The goal is that Vega can serve most of the busy market that is now emerging for small satellites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These spacecraft operators, often just launch vehicles, SMEs or university departments, are unable to carry out special launches and are trying to cut costs by sharing the journey into orbit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lunar rocket fired in a critical test</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Methane, which the British closely watched as the main base</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The space radar company has a persistent vision</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The development of the Small Spacecraft Service Dispenser (SSMS) used in Wednesday&#39;s mission was funded primarily by the European Space Agency.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This introduction demonstrates that Esa is able to use innovation to reduce costs, be more flexible and flexible and take steps towards commercialization,&quot; said Jan W&ouml;rner, the agency&#39;s Director General.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The enhanced ability to access space for this innovative small satellite will yield a number of positive results from new environmental research and demonstration of new technologies.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The dispenser can accommodate a wide range of volumes and masses - from 1 kg, 10 cm cube nano satellites (or cubes) to more volume 500 kg mini satellites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In fact, one company in the flight, San Francisco-based Swarm Technology, deployed 12 small spacecraft measuring just 4 x 10 x 2.5 cm on Wednesday. In other words, it&#39;s no bigger than a smartphone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They must be used in communication constellations that transmit short messages and data from connected devices - the so-called machine-to-machine service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The most widely used satellite for unknown subscribers weighs 138 kg.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The largest cargo shipments belong to companies that monitor planet Earth. He placed 26 of his &quot;Super Pigeons&quot;. The planet will use satellites to get a once a day picture of the whole world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Super Doves has upgraded the sensor compared to previous iterations which return better spectral information and allow for more detailed analysis of objects and earth properties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One of the medium (15 kg) satellites on board is a methane observer developed by GHGSat of Montreal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Methane is a strong greenhouse gas and, like carbon dioxide, increases its concentration in the atmosphere.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Canadian company wants to help reduce emissions by, among other things, tracking oil and gas leaks and alerting owners of the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GHGSat intends to establish its global analytics center in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vega is the second missile in two weeks to return to flight after the previous crash.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AS-NZ electrons operated by Rocket Lab were successfully launched on August 31 from their base on New Zealand&#39;s North Island.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The rocket uses only one satellite - a new radar platform for American startup Capella Space.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Called the Sequoia, the spacecraft, weighing less than 100 kg, is the first commercially available sensor of this size.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Radar has the great advantage of always being able to see the planet&#39;s surface regardless of weather or light conditions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The previous electron anomaly occurred during the flight on July 4. The Vegas flop happened on July 10 last year. In both cases, the engineers said they could identify causes and take corrective action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Arianespace, which operates Vega from French Guiana, tried to start the vehicle in late June but was forced to let the flight glide over the Cuoru space port due to unacceptable wind conditions for long periods of time.</p>', 'Rocket, Science', 'Vega Rocket_1599390062.jpg', '2020-09-06 15:01:02', '2021-08-17 22:31:03'),
(213, 7, 7, 52, 'protesters-against-extinction-rebellion-block-the-newspaper-printing-press-1599390211', 'Protesters against Extinction Rebellion block the newspaper printing press', 0, '<p>Extinction Rebellion (XR) activists suspended the distribution of several national newspapers after blocking access to three Rupert Murdoch publishers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Protesters against newspapers in Broxburn, Hertfordshire, Knowsley, Merseyside and near Motherwell, North Lanarkshire.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prime Minister Boris Johnson said the actions of protesters across the country were &quot;unacceptable&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>80 people were arrested.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The press made headlines about Rupert Murdoch&#39;s News Corp, including the Sun, Times, Sunday Sun, Sunday Times and Scottish Sun. They also print the Daily Telegraph and Sunday Telegraph, the Daily Mail and Mail on Sunday, and the London Evening Standard.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The protesters accuse the newspapers of failing to cover climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The XR blocked the road to the printer by vehicle, while demonstrators were chained to the building.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The van was covered with news banners, including &quot;Release the Truth&quot; and &quot;Refugees are Welcome Here&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boris Johnson said on Twitter: &quot;A free press is essential to compel governments and other powerful institutions to answer questions that are important to our country&#39;s future, including the fight against climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is completely unacceptable to restrict public access to news in this way.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joe Stevens, Secretary of State for Digital Culture, Media and Sport at Shadow said, &quot;People have the right to read the newspaper they want.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It would be wrong to prevent them from being distributed and the printer from doing its job.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And Interior Minister Priti Patel wrote on Twitter that the XR last night was an &quot;attack on democracy&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Journalists also condemned the protests as &quot;an attack on the free press as a whole,&quot; which they said targeted workers other than newspapers facing &quot;financial sanctions.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Thanks to other industrial partners, the pressure is diverted to other locations,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Earlier, Telegraph editor Chris Evans had emailed staff saying that although the newspaper was not XR&#39;s main target, it was &quot;severely affected&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He told them: &quot;I am also very concerned - and I hope you are - about attacks on freedom of expression.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Whatever your policy, you need to worry about it. There are also questions for the police who may have the right of a handful of these people to protest the right of others to read a free press.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hertfordshire Police said officers were called to the Great Eastern Road near the Broxburn factory at around 10pm CET, where they found about 100 protesters &quot;supporting the building and each other&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At 6 a.m., the delivery van was still unable to leave the construction site to distribute documents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to police, 50 people were arrested on suspicion of causing public trouble.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chief Charlie Hall said the group&#39;s actions were &quot;a deliberate and unacceptable protest that was premeditated and carefully coordinated to disrupt local businesses for an extended period of time.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hertfordshire officials arrived &quot;within five minutes of the initial report,&quot; he said, &quot;but the nature of the protests required very specialized resources and cutting equipment to safely remove protesters from their locations.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Each must be stripped of the bamboo structures they build, Hall added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although the business is rebuilding on site, he said staff will stay there to monitor the area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Merseyside Police tweeted Saturday morning that there were employees at the Knowsley plant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The site was released by protesters at around 10.30am and 30 people were arrested on suspicion of serious injuries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scottish police said in a statement that the protests at the Eurocentre headquarters near Motherwell were &quot;quiet and there were no problems&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>XR accused the newspaper and its owners of &quot;neglecting the climate and environmental emergency&quot; and of &quot;polluting the national debate&quot; on dozens of social issues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Federation of Independent Retailers condemned the demonstrations, saying members left without paper supplies had to &quot;deal with angry customers who couldn&#39;t get to their daily newspapers&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>National President Stuart Reddish said it also meant retailers would not be able to obtain paperwork for elderly and vulnerable customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Newspapers played an important role in getting newspapers into the hands of readers during Covid-19 and it did not help at a time of every important sale,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Extinction Rebellion plans 10 days of action and urges governments to do more to tackle climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the latest statement following the latest protests, a spokesman said: &quot;We have fallen on an unprecedented scale and the documents we are targeting do not reflect the scale and urgency of what is happening to our planet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;To every small business that was out of operation this morning, we said, &#39;We&#39;re sorry. We hope our actions match the severity of the crisis we are facing and the day of this disruption sets the alarm for a major disruption to come.&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than 300 people were arrested during protests in central London on Thursday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, climate change protesters have been warned that they risk large fines if they fail to comply with coronavirus rules, which prohibit the collection of more than 30 people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A march of activists that came from Brighton a week ago then protested the last section of Parliament.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Police said the Westminster travel risk rating &quot;did not meet the standards&quot; and barred the XR from driving the 20-meter model boat named after teen activist Greta Thunberg on the streets of Westminster.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At around 2:45 pm on Saturday, a group of people accompanying the ship posted a video on social media saying members were &quot;stopped by lots of police officers and 14 police cars on the A3 right after Kennington Park&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>XR protesters gathered at London&#39;s Trafalgar Square were widespread, police said, and police spokesman Met said officers were also in Euston, where protesters locked themselves on cranes.</p>', 'Protestors, Rebellion', 'Rebellion activist_1599390211.jpg', '2020-09-06 15:03:31', '2021-08-15 21:59:52'),
(214, 7, 9, 137, 'typhoon-maisak-north-korea-vows-to-punish-officials-for-casualties-1599390306', 'Typhoon Maisak: North Korea vows to punish officials for \"casualties\"', 0, '<p>North Korea has promised to punish local authorities for the typhoon that hit the east coast on Wednesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Labor Party newspaper accused authorities in the coastal town of Wonsan of failing to prepare for Typhoon Maisak and accused them of &quot;irresponsible treatment&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The newspaper did not say how many were missing, injured or killed, but said there were &quot;dozens of casualties&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The officials allegedly did not follow the ruling party&#39;s instructions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Local authorities in Wonsan have been instructed to &quot;immediately organize a project to thoroughly identify vulnerable objects and evacuate all residents,&quot; Rodong Sinmun reported on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It was decided to impose severe political, administrative and legal penalties on those responsible for the victims.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kim Jong Un warned of typhoons and the coronavirus</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kim Jong Un &quot;gave his sister more power&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>South Korea is battling deadly floods and landslides</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is impossible to verify that local officials have ignored these orders or have been wrongly attacked by the ruling party to quell public discontent, said Celia Hatton, the BBC&#39;s Asia Pacific editor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>State television broadcast KCTV earlier this week showed bridges and concrete walls in Kangwon province being destroyed by heavy flooding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Typhoon Maisak caused devastation in North Korea just a week after another typhoon, Typhoon Bavi, hit the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>North Korea is particularly vulnerable to flooding due to deforestation in the mountains and hills. Due to poor infrastructure, natural disasters are a challenge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Typhoon Maisak also hit South Korea, killing at least two people and causing the evacuation of more than 2,200 in the southern city of Busan.</p>', 'North korea, Typhoon, Casualitites', 'Typhone_1599390306.jpg', '2020-09-06 15:05:06', '2021-12-19 17:27:49');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(215, 7, 8, 46, 'incredible-stone-remains-from-a-2500-year-old-royal-palace-from-the-time-of-the-kings-of-judah-have-been-found-outside-the-walls-of-jerusalem-and-have-been-carefully-buried-1599581152', 'Incredible stone remains from a 2,500-year-old royal palace from the time of the kings of Judah have been found outside the walls of Jerusalem and have been carefully buried.', 1, '<p><strong>Archaeologists have unearthed magnificent stone remains from a 2,500-year-old royal palace outside the walls of Jerusalem, which - oddly enough - were buried with care.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The remains - including the &quot;capital&quot; ornate with stone pillars - date to the time of the kings of Judah, archaeologists say.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The palace will have views of King Solomon&#39;s temple in the heart of Jerusalem, but is said to be 586 BC. It was destroyed by the Babylonian invaders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/13/32776912-8698075-image-a-28_1599224365227.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAccording to scholars, the so-called &quot;Proto-Aeolian&quot; style observed in the capital was typical of a royal building - which increases the likelihood that the palace belonged to a king.<br />\r\n&quot;This is a very interesting find. The construction of the capital is the best observed, and the state of preservation of the objects is rare,&quot; said senior archaeologist Jacob Bilig of the Israel Antiquities Authority.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, archaeologists are confused as to why parts of this palace were so well buried, and thus preserved, when the rest were looted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At this point, it is still difficult to say who hid the capital the way they were found and why they did it,&quot; explained Professor Bilig.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Undoubtedly, this is one of the secrets of this unique site that we will try to provide a solution for,&quot; he added.<br />\r\nScholars believe the palace was built between the failed Assyrian siege of Jerusalem in 701 BC. And the destruction of the city by the Babylonian army of Nebuchadnezzar II Around 586 BC. Built.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At that time, Jerusalem was ruled by eight different kings, five of whom are listed in the Bible as ancestors of Christ.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The relationship between these ancient kings and their artifact style is so close that a resemblance to the actual stone masonry can be seen on the modern Israeli five shekel coin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fact that the palace was built outside the city walls reflects a certain level of confidence, according to experts.<br />\r\n&quot;This discovery indicates a new resurgence in the city and, to some extent, the &#39;off the walls&#39; of the First Temple period after the Assyrian siege,&quot; said Professor Bilig.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We found large houses, mansions and government buildings outside the city walls,&quot; he continued.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It shows the help the people felt in the city and the resumption of construction in Jerusalem after the Assyrian threat ended.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Artifacts from the palace, carved from soft limestone, will be on display in Jerusalem in the coming days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/13/32776902-8698075-image-a-32_1599224390942.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>', 'Incredible stones, Royal Palace', 'Antiquitites_1599394436.jpg', '2020-09-06 16:13:56', '2021-08-12 21:03:11'),
(216, 7, 8, 48, 'europes-largest-telescope-captures-stunning-images-of-the-sun-that-show-intricate-details-of-sunspots-and-plasma-like-never-before-seen-1599581111', 'Europe\'s largest telescope captures stunning images of the sun that show intricate details of sunspots and plasma like never before seen.', 1, '<p><strong>The sun shines more than 150 million kilometers from Earth, but the new images offer a close-up view of the complex structure only 30 kilometers long on its fiery surface.</strong><br />\r\nUsing the largest telescope in Europe, GREGOR, scientists have captured impressive details about the evolution of sunspots and the intricate design of solar plasma.<br />\r\nThis is the highest-resolution image observed by European telescopes, which the team says comes from the new optics, through which the magnetic fields of massive stars, convection, solar flashes and sunspots - like never before - can be examined in detail.<br />\r\nThe photos show the sun&#39;s magnetic field with a wavelength of 516 nanometers and a sunspot with 430 nanometers, which astronomers say, &quot;is like looking at a needle on a very sharp football field from a distance of one kilometer.&quot;<br />\r\nOur star is covered in many cell-like cells - each the size of the US state of Texas - that are the result of strong convective motion that carries heat from the depths to the sun.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><a href=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/22/32792212-8699321-image-a-47_1599254989055.jpg\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/22/32792212-8699321-image-a-47_1599254989055.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></a></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Using the largest telescope in Europe, known as GREGOR, scientists captured stunning details of sunspot evolution and complex design of solar plasma. Pictured is a&nbsp;A sunspot observed in high resolution by the GREGOR telescope at the wavelength 430 nm</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any hot plasma, it rises in the center of the cell&#39;s light before cooling and sinks back into the star to form a dark screen that GREGOR can see - some compare it to popcorn types.<br />\r\nDr. Lucia Kleint, who heads the German solar telescope and project in Tenerife, said: &quot;It was a very interesting project, but also very challenging. In just one year we completely redesigned the optics, mechanics and electronics to achieve the best image quality.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kleint and his team achieved a breakthrough under the coronavirus blockade in March that allowed them to observe the sun closely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/22/32792206-8699321-image-a-48_1599254994216.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The photographs show solar magnetic fields taken at a wavelength 516 nanometers (pictured) and sunspots at 430 nanometers, which astronomers say it is &#39;as if one saw a needle on a soccer field perfectly sharp from a distance of one kilometer&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe group is stuck at the observatory, which allows them to design a new optical laboratory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dr. Svetlana Berdyugina, professor at the University of Albert-Ludwig in Freiburg and director of the Leibniz Institute for Solar Physics (KIS), was very satisfied with the outstanding results: &quot;This project is quite risky because repairs to telescopes like this usually take years. But work. a good team and careful planning resulted in this success.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Now we have a powerful tool for solving the puzzle of the sun.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The stunning images follow the first slide taken in July by a team using Hawaii&#39;s Inouye solar telescope. With these images, astronomers can analyze the details of the sun&#39;s surface and learn more about the formation of space weather.<br />\r\nMatthew, president of the Astronomical Studies Association, said in July, &quot;On Earth we can predict whether it will rain exactly anywhere in the world, but space-time has not arrived.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/22/32791112-8699321-image-a-57_1599255319152.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our estimate is 50 years, if not more, behind Earth time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We need to understand the basic physics behind spacetime, and that starts with the sun, which the Inouye solar telescope will explore.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://videos.dailymail.co.uk/preview/mol/2020/01/29/2635190342146962208/636x382_MP4_2635190342146962208.mp4\" /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://videos.dailymail.co.uk/preview/mol/2020/01/29/2635190342146962208/636x382_MP4_2635190342146962208.mp4\" /></p>', 'Captured, Stunning Sun, Plasma', 'Sun layers_1599395010.jpg', '2020-09-06 16:23:30', '2021-08-13 03:52:38'),
(217, 7, 8, 52, 'hundreds-of-dead-fish-washed-up-on-the-banks-of-the-yellowstone-river-which-according-to-official-reports-were-killed-by-parasites-in-the-water-1599581240', 'Hundreds of dead fish washed up on the banks of the Yellowstone River, which according to official reports were killed by parasites in the water.', 1, '<p><strong>Hundreds of dead mountain white fish have swept the banks of the Yellowstone River in Montana and started investigating the cause of death.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although the death toll has not been confirmed, park officials believe the fish died from proliferative kidney disease (RDD), a parasite that lurks in the water.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In that case, biologists counted about 200 bodies in the river between Big Timber and Livingston.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Incident reporting began in late August, with the largest group found nine miles away and a total of 149 dead fish collected.<br />\r\nProliferative kidney disease can be seen in an enlarged kidney and spleen, as well as pale gills, all of which cause anemia in fish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The white mountain fly is a thin silver creature found in Yellowstone rivers and streams that prefers deep pools and clear, pure water.<br />\r\nPark officials noted that these fish are also very sensitive to pollution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Montana Fish, Wildlife, and Parks (FWP) found reports of dead fish appearing in late August.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/21/32789684-8699173-Proliferative_kidney_disease_can_be_spotted_by_a_swollen_kidney_-a-1_1599250202623.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Proliferative kidney disease can be spotted by a swollen kidney and spleen, along with pale gills &ndash; all of which results in the fish becoming anemic. (Pictured is images of dead fish that died from the same parasite in 2016)</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since then, biologists studying mortality have observed hundreds of people across several stretches of the river, which stretch 700 miles through Wyoming, Montana, and North Dakota.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The team saw seven in a day, roughly nine miles from the fishing spot to reach the Springdale Bridge to the predatory bear fishing ground of Big Timber.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The next day, 149 dead white fish were found between the hog farm and the Springdale Bridge fishing ground downstream of Livingston.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And then they counted 38 dead whitefish over 20 miles between the Pine Creek access point and Livingston Highway 89 fishing ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The FWP will continue to monitor conditions on the Yellowstone River,&quot; the statement said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;No closure or restriction is currently expected for the Yellowstone River or its tributaries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A similar incident occurred at the park in 2016, forcing staff to close a 183 mile long section of the Yellowstone River.<br />\r\nBut at that time there were still thousands of dead fish on the beach.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/21/32789728-8699173-A_similar_incident_occurred_in_2016_at_the_park_that_forced_offi-a-4_1599250202653.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This attack is unprecedented on its scale. We&#39;ve never seen anything like it in Montana,&quot; said Andrea Jones, a spokeswoman for Fish, Wildlife and Parks in 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wildlife officials have documented more than 2,000 dead mountain whitefish and estimate the total number of animals killed to be in the tens of thousands.</p>', 'Dead Fishes, YeloowStone River', 'Dead Fishes_1599397045.jpg', '2020-09-06 16:57:25', '2021-08-15 17:17:08'),
(218, 7, 8, 72, 'facebook-claims-that-ar-glass-will-feel-superpower-by-blocking-background-noise-and-tracking-users-eye-movements-to-see-what-they-are-focused-on-1599581225', 'Facebook claims that AR glass will \"feel superpower\" by blocking background noise and tracking user\'s eye movements to see what they are focused on.', 1, '<p>Facebook is entering augmented reality, but the company isn&#39;t just focused on what we see.<br />\r\nIn one post, the social media company raised the curtain on Facebook Reality Labs&#39; pioneering work in developing audio enhancement technology.<br />\r\nIts purpose is to enhance &quot;audio presence&quot; where sound from speakers, headphones, or other devices is indistinguishable from the actual source.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/20/32787126-8698941-image-a-14_1599246576004.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Facebook Reality Labs is perfecting technology that would enable a phone call from a crowded bar to sound crystal clear. It&#39;s also working to make sounds coming through speakers or headphones virtually identical to a real world source</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>Neither of them will be out anytime soon, but the technology could have life-changing applications, even for the deaf or hard of hearing.<br />\r\nThe study will likely find its way into Facebook&#39;s augmented reality glasses, which are expected to be released for some time between 2023 and 2025.<br />\r\nA team of world-class researchers, engineers and designers strives to enhance what we hear so that conversations in a busy coffee shop or calls from thousands of miles are clear.<br />\r\nBy analyzing your eye and head movements, Facebook AR glasses with built-in speakers can recognize what you want to hear and reduce external noise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/20/32787144-8698941-image-a-15_1599246609462.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>A prototype for Facebooks &#39;perceptual superpowers&#39; technology, which tracks head and eye movements to&nbsp;tune out background noise and focus on the person speaking</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><br />\r\nAre you trying to listen to your date in a noisy bar? Look them in the eye and the argument at the next table disappears in a whisper.<br />\r\nThis technology can also be activated using the Facebook LiveMaps feature, because AI will automatically reflect on traffic and other disturbances.<br />\r\n&quot;We are researching new technologies that can expand, protect and enhance your hearing. That way, you can focus and focus on interacting with other people and the information you care about,&quot; said Tony, director of hardware research. M&uuml;ller.<br />\r\nThis is not just theoretical, as the laboratory has developed a prototype that can track eye movements and adjust sounds accordingly.<br />\r\nThe continuous sound calibration system allows users to hear ultra-high precision sound through the headphones without distortion or color.<br />\r\nThe effect is that the footage is essentially identical to the original, according to Oculus blog writer Lisa Brown Yaloza.<br />\r\n&quot;It is so realistic that it is practically indistinguishable from reality,&quot; he wrote after listening to scientist Pablo Hoffman and then listening to reproductions.<br />\r\nMonitor audio from Facebook Monitor Labs. While a lot of work started in the context of AR and VR, researcher Philip Robinson said, &quot;We have come to realize that all the technology we build here can serve a higher purpose, which is to improve human hearing.&quot;<br />\r\nMonitor audio from Facebook Monitor Labs. While a lot of work started in the context of AR and VR, researcher Philip Robinson said, &quot;We have come to realize that all the technology we build here can serve a higher purpose, which is to improve human hearing.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;If I sit next to him at my table, I&#39;ll bet he is talking to me while I see him in my peripheral vision.&quot;<br />\r\nSpatial sounds can also be combined with ultra-realistic avatars and full body tracking to create virtual encounters that are indistinguishable from face-to-face encounters.<br />\r\n&quot;Imagine talking on the phone and forgetting that you are separated by a distance,&quot; said researcher Philip Robinson. &quot;That is the promise of the technology we develop.&quot;<br />\r\nRobinson says that most of his team&#39;s work started with AR and VR: &ldquo;We&#39;ve learned that any technology we develop here can serve a higher purpose, which is to improve human hearing. &quot;.<br />\r\nIn one experiment, researcher Vladimir Turbabin called Jalosa&#39;s phone from a room and played loud music. The turbabin pressed a button and the sound became as clear as daytime.<br />\r\n&quot;It looks like someone has turned down the background noise volume so I can easily focus on what they are trying to say,&quot; he wrote.<br />\r\nThe key is a set of microphones on the tourbabins glasses that isolate the sound from background noise.<br />\r\n&quot;Our moment is a very important moment in the history of AR / VR technology,&quot; said Ravis Mehra, head of research for the FRL audio team.<br />\r\n&quot;In five or ten years, someone joining the field will be chasing the taillights. At that point we can really determine what the future will be like.<br />\r\nAccording to CNBC, Facebook partnered with parent company Ray-Ban Luxottica for AR glasses last fall.<br />\r\nCodenamed Orion, smart awnings replace smartphones, allowing users to make calls, view information on small screens, and broadcast their visual perspectives live to followers on social media.</p>', 'Facebook, SuperPower', 'Facebook_1599397557.jpg', '2020-09-06 17:05:57', '2021-08-16 02:47:56'),
(219, 7, 8, 82, 'outdoor-green-time-is-better-for-childrens-mental-health-and-academic-performance-than-screen-time-1599580848', 'Outdoor \"green time\" is better for children\'s mental health and academic performance than \"screen time\"', 1, '<p>Children&#39;s mental health and performance could be improved by devoting more &quot;green time&quot; in the wild and less &quot;screen time&quot; to staring at devices, new research shows.<br />\r\nA review of 186 studies found that time spent in forests, parks and nature reserves has a positive effect on children&#39;s mental well-being and academic achievement.<br />\r\nMeanwhile, screen time - the time you spend watching television, computer, or video games - has been associated with poor mental performance, including increased mental illness, poorer cognitive function, and worse academic performance.<br />\r\nIn general, children with low socioeconomic backgrounds are underrepresented in research on the effects of lack of access to green space, which means the problem may be worse than expected.<br />\r\nChildren and adolescents with lower socioeconomic backgrounds have more screen time and less access to nature in their environment, &quot;said Tasia Oswald of the University of Adelaide, South Australia.<br />\r\n&quot;The psychological consequences of excessive viewing time appear to be worse for these children, while the psychological benefits of green time appear to be greater for these children.&quot;<br />\r\nThe prevalence of mental illness in children and adolescents is increasing worldwide, and depression and anxiety in particular are the main causes of decreased quality of life in children and adolescents.<br />\r\nExperiences with depression and anxiety symptoms in childhood and adolescence are associated with an increased risk of poor mental health in adulthood, suggesting &quot;lasting consequences,&quot; say the experts.<br />\r\nHowever, it is often said that immersing children in nature can enhance their scientific understanding, awaken the senses, and give the living room a psychological calm.<br />\r\nOther studies have shown that simply taking photos of trees and green space can affect psychological outcomes - even if the space itself doesn&#39;t change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/15/32780770-8698091-image-a-61_1599230326512.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nOswald and his colleagues based their findings on 186 previous studies of the mental health and academic performance of children and adolescents, as well as their time on screen, in nature, or both.<br />\r\nMost (114) are for screen time only, 58 are for green time only, and only 14 have their second element.<br />\r\nThe review gathered evidence to establish an association between screen time, green weather, and psychological outcomes for toddlers (under 5 years), college students (5 to 11 years), early teens (12 to 14 years), and older teens (15). up to 15 years) 18 years level).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In general, high screen time appears to be associated with adverse psychological outcomes - mental health, cognitive function, and academic performance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Green weather, on the other hand, is likely to be associated with favorable psychological outcomes.<br />\r\nIn general, green weather can &quot;withstand&quot; the high screen time effect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/15/29217432-8698091-In_lockdown_Italian_children_with_obesity_added_nearly_five_hour-a-58_1599230134659.jpg\" style=\"height:420px; width:634px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hence, nature can become an &ldquo;underutilized public health resource&rdquo; for the psychological well-being of young people in the high-tech era.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oswald said it was still difficult to know whether alone watching time, low green time, or a combination of the two led to worse mental health in children and adolescents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;More research in this direction will help us understand whether we should focus our efforts on reducing young people&#39;s screen time, or whether simply increasing their green time along with screen time will benefit their mental well-being.&quot; He says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many studies on screen time have looked at older technology - televisions, video games, and computers, says Oswald.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Therefore, future research should focus on the psychological effects of wearable technologies such as smartphones and tablets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They support a wide variety of uses that can actually contribute to mental health and, as was shown during castles, to academic study.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The experience of mental illness in childhood or adolescence has an impact on the development of a person&#39;s mental health throughout his life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Therefore, prevention is key, and identifying exposures that are harmful or improve mental health is very important for young people, &rdquo;said Oswald.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/15/32780546-8698091-image-a-59_1599230137705.jpg\" style=\"height:421px; width:634px\" /><br />\r\n&quot;When parents, teachers, researchers, policymakers, and teens themselves get a summary of the evidence, they can better understand the psychological consequences of uncovering screen-based technology.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Parents don&#39;t necessarily interpret these reviews as a sign of their children&#39;s decline in media use, according to Professor Dam Till Wicks, a psychologist at King&#39;s College London who did not participate in the study published in PLOS ONE.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It all depends on what kids are doing with their time, and the combination of activities is what kids need most,&quot; she said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This can be a lifeline for teens who need social support, even if it&#39;s a distraction from family time.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previous studies also used children&#39;s access to green spaces as measured by their proximity to parks and fields.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The problem is that families living near green spaces differ in many ways from those living in cities,&quot; says developmental psychologist Dr. Sam Vas from the University of East London, who was neither, participated in the study.<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s impossible to be sure that the difference is in the green itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Likewise, families where children are given more screen time differ in many ways from families where children are given less time - and it is impossible to be certain that it is not one of the other factors that actually influences the psychological outcome. . .<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'Out Door Greenary, Mental Health', 'Out Side Greenary_1599398862.jpg', '2020-09-06 17:27:42', '2021-08-18 10:02:28'),
(220, 7, 8, 35, 'the-disk-of-tattooed-planets-orbiting-three-suns-in-the-solar-system-glistening-in-the-distance-distorted-by-the-gravitational-dance-of-their-parent-star-1599580813', 'The disk of tattooed planets orbiting THREE Suns in the solar system glistening in the distance, distorted by the \"gravitational dance\" of their parent star.', 1, '<p>Tatooine, a planet called Luke Skywalker Star Wars, has two suns, and astronomers now have a better understanding of how this complex multi-star system actually formed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A strange young star system 1,200 light years from Earth has been studied with powerful telescopes. Unlike the Tatooine system, this convex system has three stars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Researchers at the University of Exeter tracked their &quot;gravitational dance&quot; and found that the force was so great that they tore apart and transformed the surrounding dust cloud, forming a planet that is usually a disk shape.<br />\r\nThis means that the planets that will later form in this disk cloud are not on a flat plane, as is the case in our solar system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead, they were at a different angle because the cloud that was creating them was currently very distorted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Astronomers say the view of one of these planets will be similar to that of the legendary Star Wars Tatooine scene, but with the addition of the sun.<br />\r\nResearchers have long known that some planets in the solar system have more than one star, and it is estimated that more than half of star systems have at least two stars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They also know how planets formed in disk-shaped dust clouds over 200 years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, 18th century theory focused on a single star and did not take into account the complex gravitational fields created by several stars rotating around each other.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a result, this is the first study looking at how planets can form around multi-star systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The GW Orionis study emerged from a large program focused on young star systems using a new method to track infrared radiation from six telescopes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The tool was developed specifically to provide new insights into the formation of stars and planets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stefan Kraus, professor of astrophysics at the University of Exeter who led the research, said it was the sharpest sight of an amazing system to date thanks to an excellent instrument called the MIRC-X.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Planets usually form around a flat disk filled with swirling dust and gas - but our images show extreme cases where the disc isn&#39;t flat at all,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Instead, it is distorted and has misaligned rings that are peeling off the disk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The irregular rings are in a disc near three stars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The effect is that the view of a potential planet in this ring is very similar to Tatooine, Star Wars glory.&quot;<br />\r\nThe only difference, apart from the fact that one is real and the other is fictional, is that Tatooine has two stars while GW Orionis is three.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Within the system, three stars behave in a unique way. Two of them orbit it, handcuffed by gravity, some ninety million miles away, roughly the size of the space between our earth and our sun.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a pair, they fly around the center of the system in an ellipse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The third star is much further away and orbits two related stars every 11 years from a distance of about 720 million miles, similar to the distance from the Sun to Jupiter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The orbits of these stars are what distort the surrounding disk and therefore affect where the planets are created.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The images show that the innermost ring of dust is deflected and contains 30 Earth masses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While Luke Sykwalker could survive on his desert planet, the planets that could form in GW Orionis would be much friendlier as the world is estimated to be 46 times farther from their star. because the earth comes from the sun which makes it frozen and barren.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/03/17/32744456-8694505-image-a-35_1599150941162.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/03/17/32744588-8694505-This_is_a_snapshot_from_the_computer_simulation_showing_how_the_-a-36_1599151023893.jpg\" style=\"height:583px; width:634px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>The research team was able to delineate the inner ring with the SPHERE instrument from VLT and the ALMA telescope observations and confirm its incompatibility.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The team looked at these ring shadows on the rest of the disk to understand the 3D shape of the rings and the disc&#39;s overall geometry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alexander Kreplin of the University of Exeter said that any planets that formed in the misplaced ring would orbit the star in a very tilted orbit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We assume that many wide-angled planets will be found in future planetary imaging studies,&quot; said the Kreplin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Since more than half of the stars in the sky are born with one or more satellites, the prospect is interesting: there could be an unknown population of exoplanets orbiting their stars in very tilted and distant orbits.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To arrive at this conclusion, the GW Orionis team observed for more than 11 years and mapped the orbits of the stars with unprecedented accuracy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alison Young, a member of the University of Exeter and Leicester team, said, &quot;What we found is that the three stars don&#39;t rotate in the same plane, but their orbits are not parallel to each other and with the disk.&quot;<br />\r\nAn international team of researchers from Great Britain, Belgium, Chile, France and the US then combined their extensive observations with computer simulations to find out what was happening to the system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the first time, they were able to clearly link the observed discrepancy with the &quot;disc-splitting effect&quot; theory, which suggests that the opposing gravitational pull of stars in different planes can distort and destroy surrounding disks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We ran simulations showing that a mismatch in the orbits of the three stars could cause the disks around them to break up into different rings. We saw them under observation,&quot; said Matthew Bate, professor of theoretical astrophysics. in Exeter which runs some computer simulations on the system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The observed inner ring shape is also consistent with predictions of how the disc will tear.&quot;</p>', 'Parent Stars, Gravity', 'Sphere_1599399345.jpg', '2020-09-06 17:35:45', '2021-08-12 21:07:37'),
(221, 7, 8, 56, '43-million-americans-have-been-subjected-to-excessive-heat-monitoring-and-asked-to-stay-indoors-due-to-record-temperatures-of-up-to-120-degrees-1599580779', '43 million Americans have been subjected to excessive heat monitoring and asked to stay indoors due to record temperatures of up to 120 degrees.', 1, '<p>About 43 million Americans are exposed to the extreme heat and are expected to stay indoors as record temperatures are expected on the west coast over Labor Day weekend.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Forecasters have warned that a dangerous heat wave will hit large parts of California, southern Nevada and western Arizona over the next three days, and temperatures will rise by up to 120 degrees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>California is preparing for one of the hottest days in history, at a time when the Golden State is engulfed by dozens of giant wildfires that have so far destroyed more than 1.5 million hectares.<br />\r\nFear is growing that the intense heat will be hard to shake as large utility companies warn that increasing energy consumption for much-needed air conditioning will marginalize the grid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>California Governor Gavin Newsum declared a state of emergency on Thursday to safeguard the state&#39;s energy capacity and prevent a repeat of last month&#39;s blackouts when the August surge disrupted thousands of households.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/18/32784754-8698643-image-m-3_1599239004916.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>About 43 million Americans are in extremely hot weather and are expected to stay indoors as record +7 temperatures are expected to occur on the west coast over Labor Day weekend.</p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe National Weather Service has issued excessive heat warnings for large parts of the Southwest, including Utah, Arizona, Nevada and California.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The temperature of shortness of breath is projected to be 20 to 25 degrees higher than normal, with the hottest days likely to be recorded in some areas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the NWS, hot hours will start in the valleys and mountains on Friday before reaching the coastal areas on Saturday.<br />\r\nLos Angeles is expected to be one of the hardest hit areas. Temperatures rise to 120 degrees on Sundays, while Phoenix and Las Vegas have highs around 117 degrees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The expectation that the temperature will cool down as night falls is limited. The lowest value at night was still expected in Los Angeles in the 1970s and 1980s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UCLA climate researcher Daniel Swain told CNBC: &quot;I&#39;m very concerned about this California heat wave.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;All-time highs make sense in the Central Valley [and] parts of the SoCal. More than one million hectares are actively burned in NorCal and we are still in the midst of a pandemic.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/20/32784742-8698643-California_is_bracing_for_what_could_be_one_of_its_hottest_days_-a-1_1599246402754.jpg\" style=\"height:583px; width:634px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<hr />\r\n<p>NWS LA warned residents that &quot;all outdoor activities should be restricted or canceled during the day&quot; as fears grew that lack of rest would cost lives in the heat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also warned of &quot;the extreme load on our energy infrastructure [which can] lead to blackouts&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The independent California-based system operator that manages power in California is urging residents to save electricity every day from 3 p.m. to 9 p.m. PST for a three-day weekend to avoid a possible blackout.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also wants the utility to delay maintenance of the power plant so that all available power supplies are ready.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The high temperatures cause concern about the risk of further wildfires as the country continues to be ravaged by some of the biggest wildfires in its history, and troops still struggle to control them.<br />\r\nWildfires broke out in California last month as the state experienced a violent heatwave - a heat wave that was less dangerous than experts said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than 875 wildfires ravaged the country and thousands of residents fled their homes before being destroyed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two of the wildfires rose to become the second and third largest in state history. The LNU Lightning Complex Fire has burned over 375,000 hectares and the SCU has burned 391,000 hectares to date.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The National Guard was called in to keep the fires under control and firefighters came from Australia and other states as Governor Newsom asked for more resources.</p>', 'Global warming, Human Impact', 'America_1599399811.jpg', '2020-09-06 17:43:31', '2021-08-15 08:09:10'),
(222, 7, 8, 196, 'aviation-accounts-for-35-of-the-human-impact-on-global-warming-13-billion-tonnes-of-co2-over-the-past-20-years-1599580563', 'Aviation accounts for 3.5% of the human impact on global warming 13 BILLION tonnes of CO2 over the past 20 years.', 1, '<p>According to a new study, aviation&#39;s impact on global warming has more than doubled in the past two decades.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Using computer models, the researchers found that aviation is responsible for about 3.5 percent of humanity&#39;s contribution to climate change, and two-thirds of that comes from power cuts and other non-CO2 emissions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The team estimates that the global aviation industry produced 26 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide between 1940 and 2018 - half of which was generated in the last 20 years.<br />\r\nAlthough the plan is based on the coronavirus pandemic, experts warn that an almost complete shutdown will have minimal impact in the long term.<br />\r\nIt takes into account non-CO2 emissions such as cycles, water vapor, and nitrous oxide and allows for the impact of aviation on climate change in comparison to other sectors such as shipping and land transportation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Aviation&#39;s massive impact on climate change has many different components,&quot; said co-author Laura Wilcox, an atmosphere researcher at the National Center for Atmospheric Sciences. &quot;On the plus side, we have many options for making changes to reduce it.&quot; .&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/17/32781108-8698387-image-m-22_1599237012097.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nUsing computer models, the researchers found that flying is responsible for 3.5 percent of the global warming effects of human activities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those statistics have remained constant since 2000, says lead author David Lee, director of the Center for Aviation, Transport and the Environment at Manchester Metropolitan University, but only because other sources have improved dramatically.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the same time period, the heating effect of flying has almost doubled.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lee estimates that the global aviation industry produced 26 billion tonnes of carbon dioxide between 1940 and 2018, half of which was produced in the last 20 years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far, most of the efforts to limit aviation&#39;s environmental impact have focused on reducing this percentage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In July, for example, JetBlue announced it would offset CO2 emissions from jet fuel on domestic flights through various global partnerships.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the opponents formed by the soot and exhaust gases from the jet engines had the bigger effect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://i.dailymail.co.uk/1s/2020/09/04/17/32781420-8698387-Contrails_and_other_non_CO2_emissions_are_responsible_for_two_th-m-24_1599237424686.jpg\" style=\"height:472px; width:634px\" /><br />\r\nThey and other carbon-free emissions are responsible for two-thirds of the industry&#39;s impact on climate change, according to the new report.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At high altitudes, contrast is created when water vapor condenses and freezes around the exhaust gas stream.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These artificial &quot;clouds&quot; can last seconds or hours, depending on temperature and humidity, and their effects are complex and sometimes conflicting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The controller heats the planet, reflects heat back towards the earth, but also has a lower cooling effect and reflects sunlight back into space.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You&#39;ll be responsible for everything from bad weather to respiratory ailments to homosexuality.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although this conspiracy theory has been largely debunked, scientists say the effects of fighting global warming are not being taken seriously.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 2016 Paris Agreement on Climate Change does not include non-carbon emissions as a contradiction. (Excludes international flights, which account for 64 percent of all air traffic.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And while flights have dropped significantly because of the coronavirus, &quot;with the change in the COVID-19 pandemic, air traffic is likely to recover to meet levels projected on multiple scales,&quot; Lee said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Changing flight routes can help prevent counter-cirrus build-up, but means longer flights and more fuel burn, which will result in more greenhouse gas emissions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Carbon-free heating is the elephant in the room,&quot; Bill Hemmings of Transport and the Environment told New Scientist in 2019. &quot;The mindset is there is uncertainty, so let&#39;s sit back and do nothing.&quot;</p>', 'Global Warming, Aviation', 'Aeroplane_1599403342.jpg', '2020-09-06 18:42:23', '2021-08-17 19:15:42'),
(223, 7, 7, 71, 'belarusian-lukashenko-protesters-reject-tight-security-1599424051', 'Belarusian Lukashenko: Protesters reject tight security', 0, '<p>Tens of thousands of people gathered in the Belarusian capital, Minsk, for a new, unauthorized protest against President Alexander Lukashenko.<br />\r\nPolice in riot gear stormed the demonstration on Friday, transporting hundreds of protesters and spraying pepper and batons.<br />\r\nThe protesters are demanding the resignation of the old president.<br />\r\nThey accused the authorities of faking his re-election a month ago, leading to fatal riots.<br />\r\nSince then, at least four people have been killed and hundreds injured as the government tries to clear up dissent.<br />\r\nA number of opposition activists left the country. Activist Olga Kovalkova was the last person to say on Saturday that she had sought refuge in neighboring Poland under threat from prison.<br />\r\nLukashenko, in power since 1994, accused western countries of meddling.<br />\r\nProtesters, human rights activists and observers said riot police brutally suppressed the peaceful march.<br />\r\nThe former Soviet republic borders Russia, where Russia is heavily dependent on energy and with which it has historically had close ties, as well as with Ukraine and the EU countries.</p>', 'Belarusian Lukashenko, Protestors', 'Belarus_1599424051.jpg', '2020-09-07 00:27:31', '2021-08-10 04:21:43'),
(224, 7, 7, 41, 'piercing-in-birmingham-search-as-one-killed-and-seven-injured-1599580487', 'Piercing in Birmingham: Search as one killed and seven injured', 0, '<p>Police are looking for a vagina that killed one person and wounded seven others in stab wounds for two hours in downtown Birmingham.<br />\r\nThe first knife stab took place at 12:30 p.m. CET on Constitutional Hill. After that, the assassins moved south and appeared to attack randomly, police said.<br />\r\nThe knife appeared to have nothing to do with terrorism, gangs or civil unrest, West Midlands police said.<br />\r\nHomicide detectives say they are chasing a suspect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/23BA/production/_114264190_hi063197658.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe armed forces use video surveillance or mobile footage to urge anyone to contact them.<br />\r\nOne man died, another man and woman were seriously injured, and five others were seriously injured.<br />\r\nCh Supt Steve Graham said the attacker stabbed people on Livery Street, Irving Street and finally Hurst Street, where the city&#39;s gay village met Chinatown at around 2:20 a.m. ET.<br />\r\nPolice said there was no evidence that the sting was a hate crime.<br />\r\nOne woman celebrating her 29th birthday described helping another woman who was &quot;bleeding a lot on the street.&quot;<br />\r\nNikita Denton from Edgbaston said, &quot;My best friend Jay is holding her head and negotiating with her all the time and doesn&#39;t want to leave her.<br />\r\n&quot;He looked so dizzy and confused, he couldn&#39;t speak. But he talked to my friend with a wink.&quot;<br />\r\nWhen the paramedics arrived, they asked for his help.<br />\r\n&quot;I took water and used the flashlight on my cell phone to help them see the wounds because they didn&#39;t have a flashlight at the time,&quot; he said.<br />\r\n&quot;There are about four wounds.&quot;<br />\r\nHe added, &quot;I don&#39;t want to think if we weren&#39;t there tonight because he was alone.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/12058/production/_114261837_reuters.jpg\" style=\"height:351px; width:624px\" /><br />\r\nCh Supt Graham said officers - some armed - were staying downtown to reassure people.<br />\r\nHe added that his party had received a number of statements from the suspect but had not released the details.<br />\r\nHe said: &quot;The early hours of the morning were tragic, shocking and terrifying.<br />\r\n&quot;It appears this attack was unintentional because we did not find a connection between the victims based on their nature or communication.<br />\r\n&quot;Make sure we do all we can to find out who is responsible and try to find out what really happened.&quot;<br />\r\nSavvas Sfrancis, who works nearby, said he saw a man stabbing a girl several times, but people initially thought he was trying to retrieve the necklace.<br />\r\n&quot;He was very cold and didn&#39;t panic, didn&#39;t react or anything. After stabbing him between five and seven times ... he left like nothing happened,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nOfficials used to find the knife in the gutter, but Graham said it was &quot;too early&quot; to say whether it was linked to the case.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/F7C2/production/_114262436_knifepicreuters.jpg\" style=\"height:351px; width:624px\" /><br />\r\n&quot;What I think is suggesting is the broad nature of our research - that people are already wasted - we have a level of traceability,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nDavid Nash, who runs the Village Inn on Hearst Street, said after a &quot;normal night&quot; between 2:00 a.m. and 2:15 a.m. he heard someone shout &quot;stop him - he just stabbed someone&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;The bars are starting to shrink and the next thing we know is that the area is surrounded by armed vehicles, ordinary police vehicles, police on foot and ambulances,&quot; he said.<br />\r\n&quot;They just came and the area was full of them, then the police helicopter went up.&quot;<br />\r\nHe said he later saw paramedics treating two people who appeared to have been stabbed.<br />\r\nNathan Hudson of the West Midlands Ambulance Service said 14 ambulances were present and he was among 11 paramedics who were also dispatched to help.<br />\r\nSt. Volunteer Team John at the Arcadia nightclub also takes care of the victims.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/98EA/production/_114264193_hi063201265.jpg\" style=\"height:351px; width:624px\" /><br />\r\nPrime Minister Boris Johnson thanked emergency services, &quot;who are working hard on the ground&quot;.<br />\r\nHe tweeted, &quot;All my thoughts are on those affected by the terrible incident in Birmingham last night.&quot;<br />\r\nWitness Kara Quran, the organizer of the club operating at the Arcade Center, said the night was busier than ever since the lockdown began.<br />\r\nHe said he finished his shift at around 12:30 CET and was drinking with a coworker when he heard &quot;loud thunder and a lot of commotion&quot;.<br />\r\nRoads in the area have been closed to traffic due to coronavirus restrictions.<br />\r\nWest Midlands Police and Crime Commissioner David Jamieson said police would work with the council to see if &quot;additional action needed to be taken downtown&quot; following the knife thrust.<br />\r\nThe increase in violence was &quot;almost inevitable&quot; because of the pandemic, when people were feeling &quot;reluctant&quot; and some were unsure of their future, Labor said.<br />\r\nOutside the stables, most city centers, such as the Bullring Shopping Center in Birmingham and the Sealife Center at Brindleyplace, are open as normal.</p>', 'Birmingham, Seven Injured, One Killed,', 'Barmigham_1599425127.jpg', '2020-09-07 00:45:27', '2021-08-14 04:13:24');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(225, 7, 10, 104, 'tunisia-a-police-officer-and-three-fighters-died-after-terrorist-attack-1599425313', 'Tunisia: A police officer and three fighters died after \"terrorist attack\"', 0, '<p>Tunisian security officials said a police officer was killed and another wounded in a knife attack in the coastal city of Sousse.<br />\r\nThree of the attackers were shot dead after what became known as a terrorist attack.<br />\r\nIn 2015, Sousse was the site of one of the worst attacks in Tunisia when 38 people, most of them British tourists, were killed by an assailant.<br />\r\nThe most recent incident occurred two days after the new government was installed.<br />\r\nThe alleged fighters rammed their car into a National Guard checkpoint at an intersection near the city port.<br />\r\n&quot;A patrol of two National Guard officers was attacked with knives in the center of Sousse,&quot; National Guard spokesman Hoseem Edin Jebably was quoted as saying by AFP.<br />\r\n&quot;One died as a martyr and the other was injured and hospitalized,&quot; he said.<br />\r\n&quot;It was a terrorist attack.&quot;<br />\r\nDuring the attack, knife makers stole weapons and police vehicles before they left, Jebably said. Security forces chase them through the tourist area of El Kantaoui.<br />\r\n&quot;Three terrorists died in the crossfire,&quot; he said, adding that two guns and a car had been found.<br />\r\nIt is unclear whether the attackers are linked to an extremist group, but a bigger threat in Tunisia in recent years has spread across the boarding houses of jihadists returning from Syria, Libya and Iraq, according to the BBC&#39;s Rana Javad. in the capital city of Tunisia.<br />\r\n38 people died when an assailant opened fire on tourists in El Kantaoui in June 2015. Thirty of those killed were British tourists staying at the Rui Imperial Marhaba Hotel.<br />\r\nIslamic State (IS) said it was behind the attack on Tunisian student Seyfedine Rezgui.<br />\r\nThe situation in Tunisia has improved considerably since then, despite the emergency.<br />\r\nSince 2015, successive governments have shifted their counter-terrorism strategies to focus more on prevention rather than response, our reporter said.<br />\r\nCountries such as Germany and Britain have helped train security forces.<br />\r\nThis week the Tunisian parliament approved a new government formed by the Prime Minister appointed by Hichem Mecici.<br />\r\nMr Mecici has appointed technocrats to his government, not members of political parties as in the past.</p>', 'Terrorist Attack, Casuality', 'El kantaoui_1599425313.jpg', '2020-09-07 00:48:33', '2021-08-16 18:13:56'),
(226, 7, 7, 72, 'horse-mutilation-in-france-police-chase-two-suspects-in-losne-1599580455', 'Horse mutilation in France: police chase two suspects in Losne', 0, '<p>Police in France have been searching for two suspects after a series of recent horse mutilations.<br />\r\nForty officers flew to the town of Losne near Dijon by helicopter after a horse was attacked early Sunday.<br />\r\nDozens of horses were killed or maimed across the country that year, causing public outcry.<br />\r\nThe police did not know why the animals were targeted, or whether it was someone&#39;s doing, or whether the first attack resulted in the killing of the spear.<br />\r\nIn the most recent incident, the horse owner called the police at around 02.00 local time (01.00 CET) on Sunday after seeing a light in his yard light.<br />\r\nProsecutor Dijon told local media that the horse had a hip injury, although it was not too serious.<br />\r\n&quot;Cruel Wilderness&quot;<br />\r\nIn France, more than 30 cases have been reported of horses with severed ears and retained genitals. Another one was found excavated.<br />\r\nDuring the investigation into the attack in Ion, northwest of Dijon, last month, police gave the impression that an artist was the suspect who was found at the scene.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/196A/production/_114260560_yonne.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAgriculture Minister Julien Denormandi then promised to bring those responsible for the attack to justice.<br />\r\n&quot;All branches of the country are being mobilized for justice,&quot; Denormandi said during a visit to Saint-Eusebe in central France, where a horse&#39;s ear was recently cut off.<br />\r\nThere is definitely professionalism, people act with a certain level of technology, he added.<br />\r\nSerge Lecomte, President of the French Equestrian Federation, accompanied Mr. Denormandi during the visit.<br />\r\n&quot;This is the kind of savage savage that we have rarely seen before,&quot; he told AFP. &quot;Is that a sect? Cruelty to animals is the forerunner of human cruelty.&quot;</p>', 'Horse, Police Chase', 'Horses_1599425563.jpg', '2020-09-07 00:52:43', '2021-08-17 08:40:46'),
(227, 7, 7, 65, 'a-man-in-the-ice-box-breaks-a-world-record-1599426276', 'A man in the ice box breaks a world record', 0, '<p>An Austrian broke a world record by standing in a box filled with ice for more than two and a half hours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With over 25 minutes in time, Josef Koeberl broke the previous full body record he set last year.</p>', 'Ice, Record Break', 'Record break_1599426276.jpg', '2020-09-07 01:04:36', '2021-08-18 03:29:34'),
(228, 7, 7, 27, 'the-father-is-dressed-as-a-transformer-on-his-sons-first-day-of-school-1599474028', 'The father is dressed as a transformer on his son\'s first day of school', 0, '<p>A father in Shanghai, China uses his creative skills to attend his son&#39;s school in a giant robot costume.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Based on the Transformers character Bumblebee, the son and his classmates&#39; surprise outfit on their first day of school in over six months due to blocking action to fight the coronavirus pandemic.</p>', 'Sons First Day, School, Father Dressed', 'Father transform_1599426651.jpg', '2020-09-07 01:10:51', '2021-08-10 09:46:31'),
(229, 7, 10, 92, 'four-year-old-toby-nye-from-leeds-receives-a-superhero-surprise-1599427024', 'Four year old Toby Nye from Leeds receives a superhero surprise', 0, '<p>A four year old cancer survivor receives a special superhero surprise when some of his favorite characters appear at his home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Toby Nye from Osmundtorp, Leeds, has neuroblastoma stage IV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the Sunday show hosted by CPM Entertainers, characters such as the Transformers robot Bumblebee, War Machine and Wonder Woman entertain Toby, his family and friends.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mama, Stacey, said she was shocked.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s amazing, just out of this world. We never expected anything from him, it&#39;s just amazing,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Cancer Survivor, Four Years, Super Hero', 'Four Year Survival_1599427024.jpg', '2020-09-07 01:17:04', '2021-08-12 21:02:23'),
(230, 7, 8, 63, 'super-bacteria-survive-outside-the-space-station-for-three-years-1599474045', 'Super bacteria survive outside the space station for three years', 0, '<p>Scientists who installed strains of bacteria outside the International Space Station were surprised to find that the bacteria survived for three years in space.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The experiment, led by a team of Japanese researchers, included the bacterium Deinococcus radiodurans, also known as Conan the Bacterium for its extraordinary resistance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Experts say the study could influence our understanding of whether life could exist on other planets.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'Super Bacteria, Survive, Space station', 'Super Bacteria_1599427354.jpg', '2020-09-07 01:22:34', '2021-08-13 11:16:29'),
(231, 4, 2, 86, 'new-creatives-showcases-next-generation-of-filmmaking-talent-1599591432', 'New Creatives showcases next generation of filmmaking talent', 0, '<p>Ability improvement conspire New Creatives supports craftsmen matured 16-30 to push imaginative limits and mirror their encounters of living in Britain today. From a sleeping disorder instigated dreams to a totally different highschool melodic, here are four movies exhibiting the venture&#39;s extension.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ability improvement conspire New Creatives will, more than two years, give 500 craftsmen matured 16-30 the opportunity to build up their specialized and innovative aptitudes and the chance to have their New Creatives bonuses communicated on BBC stages.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The pieces charged in this first tranche incorporate show, movement, verbally expressed work, soundscapes and move, with subjects running from migration to psychological well-being, investigations of sexual orientation, environmental change, computerized reasoning, melancholy and love. New Creatives means to offer chances to developing specialists from foundations that are as of now underrepresented in human expressions and broadcasting, offering an extraordinary stage for youthful, rising craftsmen to recount to the tales they need to tell, carrying them to BBC crowds across BBC TV, radio and on the web.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New Creatives is a key part of the BBC&#39;s more extensive activity BBC Introducing Arts, with remembers plans for Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. New Creatives is co-subsidized by BBC Arts and Arts Council England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Filmmaking, filmmaking news', 'p07nglfc_1599591430.jpg', '2020-09-08 22:57:12', '2021-08-14 11:09:07'),
(232, 4, 7, 61, 'new-yorks-last-great-jazz-parlour-1599594419', 'New Yorks last great jazz parlour', 0, '<p>The Beaux Arts Royal Building, a national historic landmark of the 1910s, was originally intended only for white tenants - a policy that ended when African Americans flocked to New York from South America in the early 20th century. of the great migration that took place. Making Harlem the center of black America&#39;s vibrant cultural and intellectual fervor. During the Harlem Renaissance and for decades afterward, it was home to a roster of legendary black musicians, including Duke Ellington, Earl Basie, and Andy Kirk, who developed the jazz, swing, and big band music that roamed the 14-story structure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now, however, the melodic tracks on the piano come from 3F Apartments. Outside, an impatient crowd of about 40 people had gathered around a handwritten sign outside the door that read &quot;Music: 3:30&quot;. There was an old couple from the upper west standing next to three students from France. A woman from Denmark brings two teenagers and their mother. Another couple approached from the elevator and said shyly, &quot;We&#39;re here about Marjorie.&quot; A man near us answers, &quot;Everyone here is about Marjorie.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Marjorie Elliott is a little woman in her 80s, and Apartment 3F is more than just her home - it&#39;s the view. Over the past 25 years, pianists, actresses and playwrights have shoved 50 folding chairs into their 700-square-meter apartment every Sunday, inviting some of the best musicians in town to their home and opening doors for anyone wanting to listen to intimate jazz. Theater performances, free. He never knew exactly who would appear or where they would come from. No tickets or reservations - you just have to be outside when the music starts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the years, the event known as Parlor Jazz has developed into an unchanging Harlem tradition and has drawn audiences from all over the world. When the door opened, a wave of strangers who were chatty and talkative as a family burst into Elliott&#39;s house. The first guests gathered on folding chairs by the sizzling radiators of their living room. When they are full, onlookers flock to their kitchen, crowding around the microwave and rice oven. When they appeared, they walked through Billy Holiday&#39;s entrance and into a narrow alcove that led to their bedroom. Between songs, the musicians step &quot;off the stage&quot; from the living room to the hall, where they often go from knee to knee with the audience. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In captivating silence, guests watch Elliott and his band play jazz standards and bebop tunes that have grown straight out of the neighborhood and transformed American pop music.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While Elliott&#39;s performances at home inspire audiences, they grew out of personal tragedy. In 1992, Elliott&#39;s son, Philip, died of kidney failure at the age of 32. Philip died on Sunday, and Elliott viewed the Sunday concert as a tribute to him and a way to relieve his grief. He was an actor and a lover of music, and at his funeral Elliott played the piano &quot;Somewhere Over the Rainbow,&quot; a song he taught him as a child.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He never forgot the chords I showed him,&quot; said Elliott.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The music entertained him, and on the one year anniversary of his death, Elliott planned a concert in his honor on the lawn of Maurice Jumel, the oldest Manhattan residence where George Washington had lived with his black slave. &quot;I killed myself by distributing flyers and going all over the house to pick people up,&quot; said Elliott.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People don&#39;t just come, they want to hear more. &quot;Everyone said, &#39;Go ahead.&#39; You have to do it every week. &quot;So that&#39;s it,&quot; Elliott recalled.</p>', 'newyork pizza, new york jazz', 'p087fz3q_1599594419.jpg', '2020-09-08 23:46:59', '2021-08-18 04:23:42'),
(233, 4, 1, 63, 'covid-19-how-to-travel-safely-on-the-bus-train-and-subway-share-using-email-share-on-twitter-share-on-facebook-1599594913', 'Covid-19: How to travel safely on the bus, train and subway Share using Email Share on Twitter Share on Facebook', 0, '<p>Apart from clear precautions, what can you do to reduce the risk of catching or spreading the coronavirus on public transportation?<br />\r\nOh<br />\r\nOn the London Underground, the smartest passengers know the hidden trick of getting from A to B. In a pedestrian tunnel between platforms, for example, an unmarked route can offer a shortcut. And if you choose a particular car, you will be taken to your destination right at the exit of the platform so you can get away from the crowd.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, public transportation during a pandemic is something even the most experienced traveler has never encountered. Moving fast now felt much more important than moving safely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use of public transportation fell sharply during the pandemic. In London in late August, buses operated with more than half of the passengers that year, and Tube carried only a third. But while locks are unlocked and offices open for many countries, many travelers are traveling back on trains, buses and subways.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may also like ...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Are face shields effective?<br />\r\nThe advantage of washing hands for 20 seconds<br />\r\n&quot;What I learned from the vaccine studies at Oxford&quot;<br />\r\nHow can wise travelers reduce their risk? Of course, there are basic things you need to do: wear a mask, avoid rush hour if you can, and follow physical discharge instructions at stations and on planes. Compliance with the local health council is paramount and will greatly reduce the risk. (Read more about how to use face masks to control Covid-19.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, there are less clear steps that need to be studied. Findings from traffic research and passenger psychology can provide clues - and point to a change in how we handle them in the coming months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ventilation and airflow are essential</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With a respiratory disease like Covid-19, the more people breathe, cough and talk in the same air as indoors, the more likely it is to be infected with the virus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you can ride a bicycle, take a walk, or ride a scooter to go to work outside, this is the best option because there is more room to get away from other people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of course, the car is also safer in person, provided you are traveling with people in your own home. However, if everyone drives, it creates a &quot;general tragedy&quot; with more traffic and higher environmental costs. Therefore, it is difficult to recommend it as a socially responsible choice. &quot;Cars use urban infrastructure very inefficiently. If we all drive in one car, nothing moves,&quot; said Carlo Rati, director of Senseable City Lab at MIT in Cambridge, Massachusetts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"http://news-zilla.com/uploads/ckeditor/aweawerawe_1599594825.\" style=\"height:50px; width:89px\" /></p>', 'how to use bus in corona], travel in corona', 'dfgh_1599594913.', '2020-09-08 23:55:13', '2021-08-15 20:20:47'),
(234, 4, 8, 64, 'the-wind-turbines-standing-up-to-the-worlds-worst-storms-1599595234', 'The wind turbines standing up to the worlds worst storms', 0, '<p>Japanese engineers hope to build wind turbines that can withstand the world&#39;s worst typhoons and generate power even amid natural disasters.<br />\r\nM.<br />\r\nMariel Robedizo Engranes was 15 years old when a typhoon hit Haiyan. He lives in his hometown of Dolores, Eastern Samar, in the eastern Philippines. The country regularly experiences typhoons, but Typhoon Haiyan, known in the Philippines as Yolanda, was extraordinary. It arrived on November 8, 2013 and is one of the strongest tropical cyclones ever recorded.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At six in the morning I heard my mother screaming and screaming,&quot; recalls Egranes the morning when Yolanda attacked. &quot;I&#39;ve been watching the water in our house. The waves are very high.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Typhoon Haiyan caused a storm - palm trees were uprooted by winds of up to 314 km / hr and the roof was torn off. More than 6,300 people died in the storm and thousands more were displaced. For survivors, a lack of power hinders the process of rebuilding their lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Engranes said his neighborhood had no electricity for two months after the typhoon. &quot;They took three months in some areas,&quot; he said. &quot;But electricity in our country is usually unstable, like it was before Hayan.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reliable electricity supply to many of the archipelago&#39;s islands is a challenge for the Philippines, and typhoons are exacerbating the situation. After a natural disaster, the hardest thing to do is provide energy when it&#39;s most needed. But new answers could come from engineers in another disaster-prone region: Japan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may also like ...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The specific beaches that grow in the world<br />\r\nThe most powerful renewable energy<br />\r\nSpy hunting pirate fish<br />\r\nA Tokyo-based startup called Challenergy has designed and built wind turbines specifically designed to operate in typhoon-prone areas. For Atsushi Shimizu, founder and CEO of Challenergy, the ideal setting for this powerful wind turbine is somewhere in East Samara where reliable power is scarce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But it wasn&#39;t Typhoon Haiyan that originally inspired Shimizu. This was another natural disaster which affected the Japanese people greatly. The 2011 earthquake in Tohoku (or Sendai) off the east coast of Japan was devastating and caused a tsunami. The tsunami struck the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant in Okuma, Fukushima Prefecture, and caused three nuclear accidents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Typhoon Hagibis left more than 270,000 households without electricity from October 9-13, causing more than $ 15 billion (&pound; 11 billion) in losses in Japan<br />\r\nThe Fukushima disaster caused the Japanese government to abandon nuclear power. While 54 nuclear reactors supplied nearly a third of Japan&#39;s electricity, today 24 of Japan&#39;s 33 reactors are shut down. One consequence is the loss of an enviable market leader status in low greenhouse gas emissions.</p>', 'wind turbines news, turbine news', 'turbine_1599595234.', '2020-09-09 00:00:34', '2021-08-18 07:04:06'),
(235, 4, 7, 34, 'why-people-object-to-laws-that-save-lives-1599595452', 'Why people object to laws that save lives', 0, '<p>Wearing a seat belt or face mask can save lives. Why do some people still refuse to wear them, even protesting against the law that obliges them?<br />\r\n&quot;I just hate them,&quot; said one woman when asked why she refused to wear them. &quot;I think I hate them because you have to wear them and I think it&#39;s more &#39;you have to wear them&#39; so I don&#39;t want them.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I thought whether you were a man or a woman, it was a matter of domination,&quot; replied the man next to him. &quot;I said, don&#39;t tell me what to do.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the kind of excuse you can expect from protesters who refuse to wear masks when they are in public during a pandemic. Their objections weren&#39;t just about consolation or even skepticism that they could save lives. He was also unhappy that the authorities were telling them what to do. In addition to the fact that the above respondents are not disappointed with laws that make face masks mandatory in public in many countries. Instead, they talked about seat belts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The respondent was a British driver who admitted to having untied his car in 2008, even though Britain has been required to wear the backseat on the front seats of vehicles since 1983 since 1991.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may also like ...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How to convince others to follow the rules<br />\r\nWhy is a face shield not enough<br />\r\nThe deadly digital bug behind Covid-19<br />\r\nThe comparison between face mask protests and seat belts is very popular. Celebrities have emphasized that abstinence is always there. The media quoted him to explain the origin of the protests against measures that could help control the spread of the pandemic. However, the application of the seat belt law is much clearer than the requirement for wearing a face mask. It is chaotic, crowded and slow. (Read more about how face masks can control the spread of Covid-19.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But there is much we can learn from the introduction of seat belt laws and other public health interventions. For example, why do there appear to be differences between the application of regulations in different countries? And why are some willing to question a measure of health that is sure to save lives?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Unsafe start</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While the evidence that seat belts save lives is not debatable, it seems uncertain when they were worn. Car manufacturers, insurance companies, law enforcement agencies, politicians, and drivers have a stake in seat belt laws.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For automakers, cost is a problem. At the time, they hoped seat belts would become mandatory because they cost a lot less than air bags, which other tech lobbyists championed. &quot;[If seat belts become mandatory], airbag enthusiasts, which swell on impact to protect the driver, fear the device will never be widely used,&quot; wrote the New York Times on February 28, 1985.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Up to 65% of Americans oppose seat belts for convenience reasons<br />\r\nOne air bag cost up to $ 800 in the mid-1980s compared to a few dollars for seat belts. If the law required all cars to wear air bags, the price of the new car would go up, which would shock the market a little.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Drivers are most interested in comfort. One study found that 86% of Americans admit seat belts save lives, while only 41% of those people actually use them (other research shows the numbers are even lower in other countries). Meanwhile, 65% of Americans oppose seat belts for convenience reasons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Insurance companies prefer airbags to seat belts. The advantage of air bags is that they are &quot;passive&quot; - ready to save your life. When airbags are installed, drivers have no choice but to use them or not, thereby reducing injury and death from accidents and, consequently, company payments. Police are against stopping drivers to enforce the law. Passive airbags mean employees can avoid stopping.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Seat belt unit faces the pro airbag unit. But debates usually don&#39;t focus on what saves more lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New York was the first US state to enact legislation on January 1, 1985, a few years after Britain, Canada, France and Germany made seat belts mandatory in the front seats.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, it took years for seat belt laws to be fully implemented. In some countries, differences between their first acquaintance with the driver in the front seat and the passenger in the rear seat have existed for decades. For example, Japan first made seat belts mandatory in the driver&#39;s seat in 1971, but became a legal requirement for rear seat passengers in 2008.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laws have also been introduced in some states and before others. This means you can travel US lines in the US, wear your seat belt when out, but take it off when you travel. And New Hampshire doesn&#39;t have a law that requires adults to wear seat belts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are three countries in the United States that do not require helmets for motorcyclists of all ages<br />\r\nThe same confusing approach applies to other public health measures, such as the adoption of the motorcycle helmet law. There are three states in the United States (Illinois, Iowa, and New Hampshire) that do not require helmets for motorcyclists of all ages, but border states where all riders are required to wear them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cultural context</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Illinois, another state that introduced new seat belt laws in 1985, wearing seat belts was seen as a minor offense from the initial introduction with a fine of up to $ 25 (nearly &pound; 50 when adjusted for inflation). A reasonable fine should convince motorists that the law should not be strictly enforced. Instead, police officers have announced publicly that they will only impose fines if there is another crime worthy of stopping the driver. The law goes even further, stating that violating the Seat Belt Act cannot constitute negligence, meaning insurance companies still have to pay if a driver is injured without wearing it. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nevertheless, four motorists accused under the new law have tried to challenge his constitutionality in court. There&#39;s a positive side: when Illinois passed a law requiring motorcyclists to wear helmets in 1969, the Illinois Supreme Court imposed unconstitutional restrictions on personal freedom, a decision that continues to this day. However, on that occasion, the court sentenced the suing motorist.</p>', 'Laws that save lives, airbags law', 'Why people object to laws that save lives_1599595452.', '2020-09-09 00:04:12', '2021-07-02 01:46:42'),
(236, 4, 1, 61, 'is-a-20-second-handwash-enough-to-kill-covid-19-1599595825', 'Is a 20-second handwash enough to kill Covid-19?', 0, '<p>Between castles, wearing a mask and keeping a distance from soap and water played an important role in the fight against Covid-19, which is easy to forget.<br />\r\nme<br />\r\nIt&#39;s something many of us instinctively do several times a day, almost like muscle memory. But that&#39;s rarely as important as it was in the last six months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Among the arsenal against the coronavirus - masks, self-isolation and social distancing - one thing is very easily overlooked: washing hands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since the coronavirus became a global health emergency in February, health officials have been trying to tell people how to protect themselves from the new virus. One piece of advice that is repeated daily in newsletters, advertisements, and expert interviews is to wash your hands with warm water with soap for at least 20 seconds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The World Health Organization publishes a widely remembered table showing the correct way to wash your hands: instructions familiar to anyone who has worked in a bar or restaurant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Six months later, a confusing global picture of hopping and local blockages - such as the recent night in Melbourne, Australia - suggests washing your hands at the border. Against the backdrop of the growing reaction in some neighborhoods to the use of masks and face coatings, this other silver bullet against coronavirus infection has been removed from the spotlight. An unverified Ethiopian observational study found that less than 1% of the more than 1,000 people who visited the hospital had washed their hands properly. But has the board changed? (Read Why Some People Don&#39;t Wash Their Hands.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may also like ...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason some people don&#39;t wash their hands<br />\r\nWhy do we all have to wear masks<br />\r\nWhy should personal contacts change<br />\r\nNot at all, say experts. If nothing else, they have doubled their effectiveness.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thomas Gilbert, professor of chemistry and chemical biology at Northeastern University in Boston, Massachusetts, said the coronavirus&#39;s chemical makeup could not be compromised by anything more specialized than cheap soap and warm water.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These viruses have a membrane that surrounds genetic particles called a lipid membrane because they have a fatty and fatty structure,&quot; he said. &quot;It&#39;s more of a structure than neutralized by soap and water.&quot; This outer &quot;shell&quot; disintegration destroys the viral cell and the genetic material RNA, which hijacks human cells to make copies of the virus, is stored and destroyed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve never heard of anything that reduces hand washing time,&quot; says Gilbert. &quot;What you want to do is wet your hands, get some soap and apply a suitable lather, then scrub your hands for 20 seconds and do it at every corner.&quot; That gives enough time, Gilbert said. carry out chemical reactions between membrane lipids and soap. &quot;There is another benefit - it also allows the soap to properly dispose of the ingredients.&quot; And with warm water, Gilbert added, the entire fight against the virus is &quot;happening a little faster.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Martin Michaelis, a professor of molecular science at the University of Kent in the UK, says water alone is not enough to kill the virus. &quot;If you have olive oil on your finger when you boil it, it is very difficult to remove it with just water,&quot; he said. &quot;You need soap.&quot; As for the corona virus, soap is needed in the same way &quot;to remove this lipid shell so that all viruses are deactivated&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The effectiveness of hand washing is somewhat skewed due to the widespread use of hand sanitizers or small bottles that people carry outside of homes or stations that people should use when entering supermarkets and bars.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you&#39;ve been at home all day and 20 strangers aren&#39;t running around your house, washing your hands isn&#39;t necessary for just that reason - Thomas Gilbert<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s not a bad idea to have something like this in your car or at your front door,&quot; says Gilbert. &quot;These things are great if you don&#39;t have access to a sink, soap, and water. I always prefer soap and water to hand sanitizer.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So how often should we wash our hands?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the start of the pandemic, the UK government&#39;s Scientific Council was supposed to wash their hands every few hours - despite the fact that the majority of the population was locked in their homes. Gilbert says this doesn&#39;t really matter to those who stay at home most of the day - although of course they should wash their hands normally after going to the toilet, before prep, and before eating.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those caring for someone with Covid-19 - and many other viruses for that matter - are likely to want to wash their hands more often, especially if they come in contact with objects or surfaces that an infected patient has touched. or cough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If you are at home all day and 20 strangers are not running around your house, that&#39;s why washing your hands is unnecessary,&quot; he said. Another article cited by doctoral student Thi Mui Pham from Utrecht University found that washing hands immediately after coming into contact with a potentially infected person or surface is much more effective than washing regularly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some people have turned to antiviral hand washing and believe that it is more effective than regular soap - and it isn&#39;t, says Michaelis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You really don&#39;t need things like that,&quot; he said. &quot;Most of the antimicrobials on the market are actually antibacterial.&quot; Overuse could cause problems in the future, he warned. &quot;If you have too many antibacterial agents (which don&#39;t work on viruses) in your wastewater, you have a greater chance of fighting bacteria,&quot; he said. &quot;Any other disinfectant you can use [except soap] ... can create more environmental problems and create more problems with resistant bacteria along the way.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both Gilbert and Michaelis agree that water doesn&#39;t have to be drinkable to be a weapon against the coronavirus.<br />\r\nOf course, washing your hands is much easier when you have a reliable supply of water. In less developed parts of the world, water is a less secure resource - and in many of these places public health standards and living conditions are often sub-optimal. In fact, until this month, the World Health Organization (WHO) announced that only two out of five schools in the world had adequate hand washing facilities before the corona virus pandemic broke out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both Gilbert and Michaelis agree that water doesn&#39;t have to be of drinking quality to be a weapon against the coronavirus. &quot;As long as you have soap or something, that&#39;s okay. You can swim in water that you can&#39;t drink because of the barrier in your skin,&quot; says Michaelis.</p>', 'How much time a handwash needs to kill covid 19, hand wash', 'sdrf_1599595825.', '2020-09-09 00:10:25', '2021-08-14 22:39:27'),
(237, 4, 1, 65, 'exponential-growth-bias-the-numerical-error-behind-covid-19-1599596151', 'Exponential growth bias: The numerical error behind Covid-19', 0, '<p>A simple math mistake could explain why many people underestimate the dangers of the coronavirus and avoid social distancing, masking and hand washing.<br />\r\nme<br />\r\nImagine getting a deal with your bank that doubles your money every three days. If you only invested $ 1 today, how long would it take you to become a millionaire?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Will it be a year Six months? 100 days?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The correct answer is 60 days after your first investment if your balance is exactly $ 1,048,576. In 30 days you will make over a billion. And at the end of the year, you&#39;ll have over $ 1,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000.00.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If your predictions are distant, you are not alone. Many people continually underestimate how fast that value is going up - a mistake known as the &quot;exponential growth bias&quot; - and while it may seem abstract, it could have huge consequences for people&#39;s behavior this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Numerous studies have shown that people who are prone to exponential growth bias are less concerned about the spread of Covid-19 and are less likely to support actions such as keeping their distance, washing their hands, or wearing a mask. In other words, these simple math errors can cost lives - meaning correcting deviations should be a priority as we try to smooth the curve and avoid a second wave of pandemics worldwide.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may also like ...</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Problems in math that could stop the world<br />\r\nThe 3.5% rule: How a small minority can change the world<br />\r\nPeople with hidden immunity to Covid-19<br />\r\nIn order to understand the origin of this particular tendency, we must first look at different types of growth. The best known is &quot;linear&quot;. If your garden is producing three apples a day, you have six in two days, nine in three days, and so on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conversely, exponential growth accelerates over time. Perhaps the simplest example is population growth. The more people you reproduce, the faster the population will grow. Or if you have weeds in your pond that triples every day, the number of plants may be small - only three per day two and nine per day three</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Our tendency to ignore exponential growth has been known for thousands of years. According to Indian legend, the brahman Sisa ibn Dahir was offered a reward for creating an early version of the Shah. He asked for a grain of wheat to be placed in the first room of the board, two for the second room, four for the third room, and to be duplicated each time in the 64th room. Apparently, the king laughed off the humility of Ibn Dahir&#39;s request - until his treasure hunters announced that they would surpass any food in the country (a total of 18,446,744,073,709,551,615 grain).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It wasn&#39;t until the late 2000s that scientists began to officially investigate this bias. Research shows that most people - like Remnant King ibn Dahir - intuitively assume that most growth is linear, which leads them to grossly underestimate exponential growth rates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This early study looked primarily at the impact on our bank balances. For example, most savings accounts offer compound interest, which gives you additional interest on the interest already earned. This is a classic example of exponential growth and means that even low interest rates will pay off over time. If you had 5% interest, &pound; 1,000 invested today would cost &pound; 1,050 next year and &pound; 1,220.50 next year ... which is more than &pound; 7,000 in 40 years. However, most people don&#39;t know how much money they will make by investing early, so they leave little time for retirement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Image copyright Getty Images Image caption If the number of pearls on the chessboard is doubled for each square, 64 &quot;holds&quot; 18 trillion<br />\r\nImage copyright Getty Images Image caption If the number of pearls on the chessboard is doubled for each square, 64 &quot;holds&quot; 18 trillion</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition to reducing their savings, this bias also makes people more vulnerable to negative credit, which is debt that increases over time. According to a 2008 study, bias increases the debt-to-income ratio from an average of 23% to an average of 54%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Surprisingly, higher levels of education do not prevent people from making this mistake. Even mathematics-trained natural science students can face risks, says Daniela Sele, who studies economic decision-making at the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology in Zurich. &quot;This helps a little, but doesn&#39;t get rid of bias,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This may be due to the fact that they rely on intuition rather than advisory thinking. Even if they learn about complex interests, they forget to apply them. Worse, most people will confidently report that they understand exponential growth, but then still succumb to the tendency when asked to rate something as compound interest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As I explore in my book The Intelligence Trap, intelligent, educated people often have blind spots and believe they are less prone to error than other people - and the exponential growth bias seems to be dead at the center of them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most people will report confidently on an understanding of exponential growth, but then stick to a bias<br />\r\nOnly this year - at the start of the Covid-19 pandemic - did researchers begin to consider whether bias could influence our understanding of infectious diseases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to various epidemiological studies, the number of new Covid-19 cases is doubling every three to four days without intervention, which is why so many scientists recommend a rapid blockade to prevent the pandemic from getting out of control.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In March, Joris Lamers of the University of Bremen in Germany started an online study together with Jan Cruzius and Ann Gast of the University of Cologne, where people were asked about the possible spread of the disease. Their results suggest that the trend toward exponential growth dominates understanding of the spread of the virus, with most people significantly underestimating growth rates. More importantly, the team found that these beliefs were directly linked to participants&#39; views on how best to limit spread. The worse their judgment, the less likely they are to understand the need for social distancing: the trend toward exponential growth has made them complacent about formal advice.</p>', 'number of covid cases, grown of corona', 'Exponential_1599596151.', '2020-09-09 00:15:51', '2021-08-14 22:38:40'),
(238, 4, 7, 59, 'is-there-such-a-thing-as-a-good-or-bad-recession-1599596617', 'Is there such a thing as a good or bad recession?', 0, '<p>How do the economic prospects look so bleak while economists remain optimistic? Not all recessions affect people the same.<br />\r\nW.<br />\r\nWhen British Chancellor Rishi Sunak announced his economic intervention at the start of the blockade, the slogan he continued to use was &quot;unprecedented&quot;. It was &quot;an unprecedented act for an unprecedented time,&quot; he reminded the British public. The choice of words, when repeated, is not insignificant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some of the numbers used to explain the current financial crisis are astonishing. In the second quarter of this year, the US economy contracted 32.9% - a huge loss that was bigger than the decline recorded. France, Italy, Germany, Spain; Nearly every major economy also saw a sharp drop in gross domestic product (GDP) earlier this year. In the UK alone, GDP fell 20.4% in April alone, and is on track for the biggest decline in 100 years. By comparison, during the Great Recession of 2008 UK GDP fell by no more than 1% in one month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, some economists remain optimistic and expect a quick &quot;V-shape&quot; recovery. How can they think that the worst economic performance is no big deal?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GDP doesn&#39;t tell the whole story. As the economy grows, this is another very disadvantage - small businesses have to give up taking savings from the life of their owners; Graduates are forced to give up their dreams and find work in offices instead; Families are left trapped in mortgages that have to be paid, with no option to sell their home. People who face the stress of not knowing how to pay their bills or imagine the future. And when it comes to those human prices, all recessions are simply not the same thing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What makes a recession &quot;good&quot; or &quot;bad&quot; is who it affects and how badly it affects them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While they are generally normal, they are additionally difficult to foresee. A similar working paper from the IMF found that private part and authority state business analysts were similarly awful at foreseeing downturn years. The writers put this down to a hesitance from business analysts to understand positive or negative news accurately. &quot;Right now everybody is kind of grinning at one another and imagining that we&#39;re not in a downturn. They&#39;re thinking, &#39;How about we trust we can get out snappy when it occurs&#39;. Be that as it may, it is difficult to tell right now since we are in the eye of the tempest,&quot; says Bentham.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fortunate or unfortunate?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bentham recently worked at the Bank of England and before that at EY, one of the &quot;Huge Four&quot; bookkeeping firms, where she took a shot at fixing guideline to make banks stronger in direct reaction to the 2008 money related accident. She says that banks are vastly improved set up to deal with a budgetary emergency than 10 years prior. &quot;National banks have discovered that when there is monetary area strife they step in with liquidity, modest financing, to support them,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coming into a work market [during a recession] has long shadows for weak laborers, yet not for gifted specialists &ndash; Carol Propper&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, not all downturns are the equivalent. &quot;The 2008 downturn was about the lodging business sector and offers, which hit excessively higher pay gatherings,&quot; says Carol Propper, a teacher of financial matters at Imperial College London. &quot;At present the emergency is by all accounts hitting especially the lower pay gatherings; the weak specialists, youthful and less gifted. This resembles the last part of the 70s, mid 80s downturn, which influenced youthful and incompetent specialists. What we think about those laborers is that coming into a work market has long shadows for those weak specialists, yet not for gifted specialists. It influences the entire long lasting direction for those incompetent specialists in the work market.&quot; So while the monetary area may be in an ideal situation in this downturn on account of the exercises took in 10 years prior, the least well off individuals may endure substantially more.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are different exercises from 2008, as well. Regardless of the feeling that downturns lead to huge quantities of employment misfortunes, this isn&#39;t generally the situation. Individuals who were laid off in the Great Recession were jobless for quite a while however cutbacks were concentrated among few individuals. The drop in recruiting was a lot more extreme than the quantity of cutbacks, making it hard for the jobless or ongoing school-leavers and college graduates to get a new line of work.</p>', 'recession', 'Is there such_1599596616.', '2020-09-09 00:23:37', '2021-08-17 00:15:35');
