(255, 4, 4, 26, 'football-denmark-vs-england-1599600952', 'Football: Denmark vs England', 0, '<p>Britain played out a terrible stop with Denmark in Copenhagen as the Nations League meeting transformed into a dull non-occasion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Harry Kane nearly won it for England in the perishing seconds when he went round Denmark manager Kasper Schmeichel, just to see his shot tidied up the line by Mathias Jorgensen - however such a low quality experience scarcely merited an emotional finale.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supervisor Gareth Southgate will have sought after some ideas on the test out after the off-field interruption that saw youthful team Phil Foden and Mason Greenwood sent home for breaking Covid-19 conventions in Iceland.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wolverhampton Wanderers commander Conor Coady made a deliberate England debut while Leeds United&#39;s Kalvin Phillips had a peaceful presentation - and Aston Villa midfield man Jack Grealish at last got his hotly anticipated bow with 14 minutes left.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Denmark had the better possibilities until Kane&#39;s late exertion, with England guardian Jordan Pickford sparing admirably from Kasper Dolberg in the primary half and Christian Eriksen shooting over when very much positioned late on.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Britain were sterile and traditionalist, making next to no separated from a Kane header askew and a low shot from Raheem Sterling that brought a savvy spare from Schmeichel before that late possibility.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Weapons store adolescent Ainsley Maitland-Niles turned into England&#39;s fourth debutant in the last minutes on an evening of next to no energy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Follow Denmark v England response here&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rate the players out of 10&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Southgate traditionalism neglects to motivate&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Britain&#39;s ploy of playing a three-man focal protection and viably two holding midfielders in Phillips and Declan Rice managed Denmark such a reg