(264, 4, 4, 50, 'nba-play-offs-boston-celtics-beat-toronto-raptors-la-clippers-edge-denver-nuggets-1599603023', 'NBA play-offs: Boston Celtics beat Toronto Raptors, LA Clippers edge Denver Nuggets', 0, '<p>The Boston Celtics beat the Toronto Raptors to take a 3-2 arrangement lead in their Eastern Conference semi-last and leave the protecting victors near the very edge of NBA play-off end.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A heavenly protective appearing in the initial quarter put the Celtics 25-11 up and they pushed on to a 111-89 win.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The activity isn&#39;t done,&quot; said the Celtics&#39; Jaylen Brown. &quot;We must come join the fun with a similar force.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Celtics can seal the best-of-seven arrangement in game six on Wednesday.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Raptors point-watch Kyle Lowry stated: &quot;They were truly agreeable from the bounce. We weren&#39;t as emphatic as we ought to have been.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the night&#39;s other game in Orlando, Florida, Paul George scored 32 focuses as the Los Angeles Clippers won a to and fro fight with the Denver Nuggets to take a 2-1 arrangement lead in their Western Conference semi-last.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Denver drove 78-67 halfway through the second from last quarter and the lead changed hands multiple times before the final quarter started.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The game boiled down to one of the two groups was going to play some safeguard,&quot; Clippers mentor Doc Rivers said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;For three and a half quarters the two groups were essentially scoring and the most recent six minutes it was our protection.&quot;</p>', 'NBA play-offs, Boston Celtics beat Toronto Raptors', '_114279805_bostonceltics_1599603023.jpg', '2020-09-09 02:10:23', '2021-08-12 21:05:18'),
(265, 7, 7, 30, 'trump-michael-cohens-book-former-attorneys-key-claims-1599623445', 'Trump Michael Cohen\'s book: Former Attorney\'s Key Claims', 0, '<p><strong>Donald Trump acts like a gangster and, according to former US President Michael Cohen&#39;s attorney, has &quot;the low opinion of all black people&quot;.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The allegations come from Cohen&#39;s new book Disloyal: A Memoir, written while in prison, partly for violating Trump campaign funding.Cohen claims that Trump also made racist comments against Nelson Mandela and the Spaniards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>The White House said Cohen was lying.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Cohen is a humiliated criminal and disenfranchised lawyer who lied to Congress,&quot; spokesman Kaylee McEnnany said in a statement last weekend. &quot;He&#39;s lost all faith and it&#39;s no surprise that he last tried to exploit a lie.&quot; In the book, Cohen claims that Trump is &quot;guilty of the same crimes&quot; that imprisoned him, calling his former boss &quot;conman, liar, scam, bully, racist, predator, scam&quot;. He said he had a &quot;mafia boss&quot; mentality.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>American news outlets published excerpts from the book, due for release Tuesday. Here are some of the most important statements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>In black people and Mandela</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As a rule, Trump expresses the contempt of all black people, from music to culture to politics,&quot; writes Cohen in his book. He claims Donald Trump said the late South African President and anti-apartheid activist Nelson Mandela was not a &quot;leader&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/12973/production/_114274167_mandela.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Tell me that a country run by black people is not a hole. They are all full of [offensive] toilets,&quot; Trump once said, according to Cohen. The words echo a similar claim made in 2018 that Trump branded African countries &quot;stupid&quot;. Then Trump said to reporters, &quot;I&#39;m not a racist. At least I&#39;m the racist you interviewed.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The racism accusations tarnished his first term and remained a problem when the Republican president took on Democratic rival Joe Biden in November.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>For Obama</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In his book, Cohen claims that Trump has &quot;hatred and contempt&quot; for his predecessor, Barack Obama.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/F3F9/production/_114275426_obama.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Trump hired Faux-Bama to take part in a video in which Trump&quot; ritually belittled the first black president and then fired him, &quot;wrote Cohen. Since then, the American media has shown old videos in which Trump reaffirms his role as host of television show The Apprentice and fires a man posing as President Obama.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is believed to have been created for the Republican Convention in 2012, when Mitt Romney was nominated for the Republican Party candidate but was never nominated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>For Hispanic voters</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Cohen, Trump once said, &quot;I will never get the Spanish vote. Like black people, they are too stupid to vote for Trump. They are not my people.&quot; His comments on Latin were scrutinized during his presidency, mainly because he repeatedly neglected Mexicans during his campaign. In 2019, President Trump said at a rally in New Mexico: &quot;Nobody loves the Spanish anymore.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Evangelist</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/DB53/production/_114274165_trump2.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cohen said after Mr. Trump met with evangelical leaders at the Trump Tower shortly after his election victory, he turned around and said, &quot;Can you believe that people believe that [explicitly]?&quot; Trump passionately seduced the voice of the gospel, saying that he himself is a very believer. Its Vice President, Mike Pence, is a devout evangelist. The editor refused because of Trump&#39;s evangelist support</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>For Putin</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Donald Trump admires Russian President Vladimir Putin because he &quot;managed to take over the entire nation and run it as if it were his private company - like the Trump organization,&quot; Cohen wrote. According to Cohen, Trump gave President Putin access to Russian money if he lost the 2016 election. However, Cohen added that Trump&#39;s campaign was &quot;too chaotic and incompetent to actually talk to the Russian government&quot; while in power.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>For Boer Daniels</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2016, Cohen arranged a cash payment for adult film star Stormy Daniels, who admitted to having an affair with Mr Trump. Payments that violated campaign finance rules were among the crimes that led to Cohen&#39;s prison. Cohen has long insisted he obey the president&#39;s orders, but Trump has always denied this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There was never any point in arranging these things, but many, many friends advised me to pay,&quot; Trump said, according to Cohen&#39;s book. &quot;When he comes out, I&#39;m not sure how he will play with my fans. But I&#39;m sure they will be happy if I sleep with a porn star.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Who is Michael Cohen?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cohen worked closely with Trump for years and is often referred to as a &quot;problem solver,&quot; but they fell and Cohen gave brutal testimony to Congress before Trump&#39;s impeachment last year. In 2018, Cohen was jailed for tax evasion, misrepresentation and campaign finance offenses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lawyer who was released is currently serving the remaining three years at his New York home after being released from prison for fear of the spread of the coronavirus. He immediately returned to prison until a federal judge stepped in and ruled that the government had taken action in response to the fact that he had written his book.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Mr. Trump called Cohen a &quot;rat&quot; and a liar.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cohen once said he would take a bullet for Donald Trump. He has since said he has received death threats from Trump supporters.</p>', 'Book, Key Claim, Trump Mocheal', 'Ex lawyer_1599603876.jpg', '2020-09-09 02:24:36', '2021-08-17 01:15:30'),
(266, 7, 7, 19, 'the-russian-navalny-out-of-coma-after-being-poisoned-1599645776', 'The Russian Navalny Out of coma after being poisoned', 0, '<p><strong>Doctors treating Russian opposition leader Alexei Navalny said he had recovered from a coma and was improving after being poisoned.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It responds to verbal stimuli, they say. 44-year-old Navalny was brought to Germany in August after flying to Siberia. His team claims he was poisoned by order of Russian President Vladimir Putin, who denies any involvement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>German doctors claim that Putin&#39;s critics were poisoned with the nerve agent Novichok. On Monday, Sharite Hospital in Berlin announced in a statement that Navalny had been weaned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He responded to verbal stimuli. It is too early to assess the possible long-term effects of severe poisoning,&quot; he said.&nbsp;The doctor is also said to be closely related to Mr Navalny&#39;s wife.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alexei Navalny: Russia&#39;s harsh critic of Putin</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two hours that saved Alexei Navalny&#39;s life</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is the Novichok nerve agent?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Navalny spokesman Kira Yarmish tweeted, &quot;Message from Alexei. He was taken out of induced coma today. He is gradually being cut off from the ventilator. He responds to language and what he is talking about.&quot; Navalny is an anti-corruption activist who has become Putin&#39;s most prominent opposition politician in Russia in recent years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What happened to Alexei Navalny?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Navalny fell ill on August 20 on a flight from Tomsk to Moscow. His followers suspect the poison was put in a cup of tea at Tomsk Airport. &quot;Alexei started moaning and screaming. He was clearly in pain. He was lying on the floor in the section of the plane reserved for cabin crew,&quot; a passenger sitting next to Mr Navalny on the plane told the BBC. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The plane was diverted to Omsk, where the opposition politician was admitted to a makeshift hospital. Russian officials initially refused to bring in Mr. Navalny went abroad for medical treatment, but three days later he was taken to Berlin by air.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/15A97/production/_114272788_tv063023705.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week, doctors in Germany said the results of toxicology tests carried out in a military laboratory provided &quot;clear evidence&quot; that Navalny had been poisoned by the nerve agent Novichok. Doctors in Omsk insisted that no poisonous substances had been found in Mr Navalny&#39;s body during his time in their care.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Monday, the Kremlin said it was &quot;absurd&quot; to hold Russia responsible for Navalny&#39;s poisoning. &quot;Attempts to link Russia to what is happening are unacceptable to us, it doesn&#39;t make sense,&quot; said Putin&#39;s spokesman Dmitry Peskov.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Russian Foreign Ministry spokeswoman Maria Zakharova said claims that Novichok were used were not supported by evidence. The nerve agent Novichok was used to poison former Russian spy Sergei Skripal and his daughter in Britain in 2018. Investigations in Great Britain accuse the Russian state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What&#39;s the international response like?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Monday, the British government asked the Russian ambassador to Britain to &quot;express deep concern about the poisoning&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is completely unacceptable that banned chemical weapons have been used and that Russia should carry out a comprehensive and transparent investigation,&quot; Foreign Minister Dominique Raab said on Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Germany, there is increasing pressure on Chancellor Angela Markel to take a firmer stance on the incident. Last week, he said Mr Navalny was murdered and the world would seek answers from Russia.</p>', 'Politician, anticorruption activist, Posioned', 'Alexei Navalny_1599645609.jpg', '2020-09-09 14:00:10', '2021-06-14 01:26:55'),
(267, 7, 7, 42, 'coronavirus-the-surge-in-the-uk-is-a-big-problem-says-van-tam-1599646326', 'Coronavirus: The surge in the UK is a big problem, says Van Tam', 0, '<p><strong>The recent &quot;major changes&quot; in coronavirus infections in the UK are &quot;very concerning,&quot; said Britain&#39;s Deputy Chief Medical Officer.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof. Jonathan Van Tam said that people were &quot;too relaxed&quot; in the summer and &quot;we have to take this very seriously again&quot;. Otherwise, Britain will &quot;have an uneven journey over the next few months,&quot; he warned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said the infection then spreads among younger people in EU countries to older age groups. His comments come as more regions of the UK will face tighter restrictions as the number of cases increases. On Sunday, British authorities announced 2,988 new cases - the highest number since May 22, while BST reported an additional 2,948 cases in the 24 hours to Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The stricter home visit rules will be extended to two additional areas in western Scotland from midnight. In Wales, the Caerphilly district will be located under a local block from 18.00 CET on Tuesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lonely wedding that destroyed Bradford castle</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How close are we to developing a vaccine?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;People are too relaxed. Now is the time to get involved again and realize that this is a continuing threat to us,&quot; said Prof. Van Tam. He added that hospital admissions and deaths were &quot;very low&quot; in the UK and the increase was most pronounced among people aged 17-21, but that the country was following the risk of several EU countries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;When the number of cases initially increases in the younger population, they in turn screen out and lead to increased morbidity and hospitalization in the older age group, and we know that&#39;s happening.&quot; a serious public health problem, &quot;he said. &quot;The fact that 17-21 year olds are not sick means they are lucky, but they also forget that they are strong spreaders because the disease is not severe for them.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof Van Tam added that the trend has shifted away from &quot;specific hot spots&quot; such as the one that emerged in Leicester last month. In contrast, &quot;there is a broader and more subtle geographic trend in the UK that disease rates are now starting to increase.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He urged public health officials and politicians to think about how to treat the virus not in the short term but &quot;in the spring&quot; over the next six months. Transport Minister Grant Shaps also announced that travelers coming to the UK from the seven Greek islands must isolate themselves for 14 days starting at 4:00 CET on Wednesday.</p>', 'UK, CoaronaVirus', 'UK cases Rises_1599646326.jpg', '2020-09-09 14:12:06', '2021-08-18 09:32:43'),
(268, 7, 7, 42, 'chinese-chip-giant-smic-was-taken-aback-after-an-impending-trade-ban-in-the-us-1599646686', 'Chinese chip giant SMIC was \"taken aback\" after an impending trade ban in the US', 0, '<p><strong>Shares of China&#39;s biggest chip maker fell after the US announced it could be the next target for a trade ban.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The International Semiconductor Corporation (SMIC) said it was &quot;deeply shocked and confused&quot; after the Pentagon announced that it had proposed the company be blacklisted by the government. This would prevent suppliers from providing American technology to it without special permission.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Beijing says it is &quot;very much against&quot;. A State Department spokesman accused Washington of &quot;grave abuse&quot; and accused national security issues of violating international trade rules.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The move could make SMIC the next focus of a commercial conflict that has threatened the survival of Chinese tech firm Huawei and has forced Bytedance to negotiate the sale of US operations to video-sharing app TikTok.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SMIC has a production line that is less advanced than some of its competitors - SMIC cannot make the smallest possible transistors, which limits the ability to manufacture some of the most advanced chips found in the latest smartphones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the company is a major semiconductor supplier to Chinese companies, including Huawei, and serves international customers including Qualcomm. According to analysts, the trade ban could jeopardize SMIC&#39;s existence and thereby hinder Beijing&#39;s efforts to boost the country&#39;s semiconductor industry as part of its China-Made 2025 strategy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/3851/production/_114271441_smic.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;SMIC will not be able to update the software on any computer in the US or employ vendor employees to make it work,&quot; Richard Windsor, founder of research firm Radio Free Mobile, told to News Channels. &quot;In addition, it is not possible to purchase more equipment or upgrades for new technology. If this is sustained over the long term, it will pose an existential threat that could cause the company to close its doors.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This, in turn, could jeopardize China&#39;s broader technological and artificial intelligence ambitions.</p>', 'SMIC, CHines Giant Chip', 'SMIC_1599646686.jpg', '2020-09-09 14:18:06', '2021-08-14 14:59:35');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(269, 7, 7, 30, 'protests-in-belarus-maria-kolesnikova-was-arrested-by-masked-men-1599647017', 'Protests in Belarus: Maria Kolesnikova \"was arrested by masked men', 0, '<p><strong>A prominent opposition figure in Belarus disappeared shortly after witnesses said they saw him in the van and drove him away.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maria Kolesnikova&#39;s whereabouts are unknown. Witnesses say he was taken by a masked man in downtown Minsk. Police refused to arrest them, Russian news agency Interfax reported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Kolesnikova is one of three women working together to challenge incumbent Alexander Lukashenko in August&#39;s presidential election. Mass riots following his re-election were accused of election fraud.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than 600 people were arrested on Sunday following the fourth weekend of anti-government protests in Minsk and other cities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What happened in Belarus?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Breathe freedom&quot; - Belarusians hope for change At least four people were killed and hundreds injured as the authorities tried to quell dissent in the country. The EU head of state and government did not recognize the election results and agreed to impose sanctions on Belarus. EU diplomats will sanction 31 top Belarusian officials, including the Minister of the Interior, according to Reuters. Lukashenko, in power since 1994, accused western countries of meddling in his country. On Monday, the Kremlin announced that it would visit Moscow for talks &quot;in the coming days&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Russia has long been a close ally of Lukashenko.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What happened to Maria Kolesnikova?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An eye witness told Belarusian news agency Tut.by that he saw the masked man take Kolesnikova&#39;s cellphone and shove her into a van on Monday morning. Ms. Kolesnikova is a member of a coordinating council set up by the opposition to ensure the transfer of power. Government officials have launched criminal proceedings against opposition leaders, stating that &quot;a Coordinating Council was created and operated to seize state power and undermine national security.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/163D8/production/_114269019_gettyimages-1228272888.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>She is the last of three women who united against Lukashenko, who lives in Belarus. Veronika Tsepkalo and presidential candidate Svetlana Tikhanovskaya left the country shortly after the vote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tikhanovskaya&#39;s mother said the recent detentions were an attempt to disrupt the work of the Coordination Council. &quot;The more they try to scare us, the more people take to the streets,&quot; he said in a statement from Lithuania. Meanwhile, the Coordinating Board mentioned Ms. Kolesnikova was &quot;unknown&quot; and accused Lukashenko of &quot;publicly using terror methods&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The council said its press spokesman Anton Rodnenkov and executive secretary Ivan Kravtsov had also disappeared. Police said no information on the detention was reported. In an interview with News Channel Russia last month, Kolesnikova described the recent anti-government demonstrations as &quot;not a power struggle&quot; but &quot;a struggle for human dignity and self-respect&quot;. He said he and his team decided not to use bodyguards because it didn&#39;t make sense.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I understand that if a bus full of police officers stops us, not a single security guard will help,&quot; he said. &quot;We all know what the police state is capable of.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another activist, Olga Kovalkova, announced on Saturday that she had escaped from prison to Poland under threat..</p>', 'Maria Kolesnikova, Arested', 'Maria_1599647016.jpg', '2020-09-09 14:23:37', '2021-08-17 01:54:56'),
(270, 7, 7, 27, 'police-followed-a-12-year-old-on-the-ground-in-hong-kong-1599648226', 'Police followed a 12 year old on the ground in Hong Kong', 0, '<p>Hong Kong police have come under fire after footage of police officers dealing with a 12-year-old girl on the ground near pro-democracy protests went viral. Police said the girl was involved in an illegal encounter and officers used &quot;minimal force&quot; after &quot;escaping in a suspicious manner&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The girl&#39;s family said they just wanted to buy school supplies and were terrified when they collided with the police. Nearly 300 people were arrested on Sunday during unauthorized demonstrations.</p>', 'Hong Kong, Arrested 12years girl', '12y boy_1599648226.jpg', '2020-09-09 14:43:46', '2021-06-11 05:36:02'),
(271, 7, 7, 35, 'prince-harry-the-frogmore-cottage-refund-has-been-returned-1599649401', 'Prince Harry: The Frogmore Cottage refund has been returned', 0, '<p><strong>The Duke of Sussex has reimbursed for the renovation of Frogmore Cottage near Windsor Castle.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Its costs, estimated at &pound; 2.4 million in 2018-19, are covered by sovereign subsidies from taxpayers, but the Duke and Duchess say they will pay them if they leave their royal duties. A spokesman for Prince Harry said he paid the bill in full by contributing to the grant. The estate remains the British residence for the Duke and his family.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Harry and Megan retire as prominent kings There&#39;s nothing left but to back off, said Harry&nbsp; It came days after the couple announced that they signed a deal with Netflix to make various programs, some of which may appear. Multi-year contracts include documentaries, documentaries, feature films, scripts and children&#39;s programs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frogmore Cottage must be a fabulous family home. Instead, it was one of the reasons Harry and Megan ended up leaving England and the official website of the royal family. The cost of the renovations - &pound; 2.4 million in 2018-19 which can be seen afterwards - sparked critical commentary and a wave of stories, mostly illusory about what the money was being spent on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just as the couple made a first place together and made a home for their child, they were the subject of some unfair and disturbing comments. For decades, taxpayer funding has been a sensitive issue for the royal family. It is a point of contact for critics pointing out state grants and security costs and asking whether the monarchy lives in luxury and is good value for money. Money - inevitably - became a serious issue in negotiations for the couple&#39;s resignation from royal duties earlier this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Harry and Megan are the ones to announce that they will pay to renovate Frogmore Cottage. This way, the line is drawn and the partner can feel relieved of any obligations they have handled. And Frogmore Cottage is an empty, somewhat lonely memorial to an unfortunate chapter in royal history.</p>', 'Prince Harry, Tax Return', 'Prince Harry_1599649401.jpg', '2020-09-09 15:03:21', '2021-08-01 05:05:08'),
(272, 7, 7, 14, 'explosions-in-beirut-i-love-you-dont-leave-me-1599649597', 'Explosions in Beirut: \"I love you, don\'t leave me\"', 0, '<p>Lebanon is still struggling to recover from a devastating explosion in the port of Beirut on August 4 which killed more than 190 people and destroyed parts of the city. This happened when more than 2,000 tonnes of ammonium nitrate, which had been in port for six years, exploded.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the Resource correspondents of News channels and reporters visits the ruins of a 100 year old house where a brother died and another was rescued by a cousin who didn&#39;t give up.</p>', 'Beirut, Explosion', 'Beirut blast_1599649597.jpg', '2020-09-09 15:06:37', '2021-06-13 15:36:11'),
(273, 7, 7, 26, 'german-house-on-the-lake-with-a-close-look-at-history-1599649755', 'German house on the lake with a close look at history', 0, '<p>Thomas Harding&rsquo;s family were forced to flee Germany and their Berlin home when the Nazis came to power.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sixty years later the author returned to the house by the lake with his grandmother. It became an obsession for Thomas, who has now written a children&rsquo;s book about the house and its inhabitants and how it has been a window on Europe&#39;s history.</p>', 'German House, History, Lake', 'German House_1599649755.jpg', '2020-09-09 15:09:15', '2021-08-17 01:00:32'),
(274, 7, 7, 47, 'the-boom-in-beirut-the-rowers-have-nothing-and-cling-to-the-olympic-dream-1599651732', 'The boom in Beirut: the rowers have nothing and cling to the Olympic dream', 0, '<p><strong>Rodrigue Ibrahim could easily lose his life on August 4th.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The soldier and rower planned to go to their favorite rowing club outside Beirut Harbor at 5:30 p.m., but there was a Zoom Bible study with a friend in London. &quot;Because of that meeting, I didn&#39;t go to the rowing club. I had to be there at that time,&quot; said Rodriguez, 28. About half an hour later, there was a huge explosion in the harbor, sending a mushroom cloud into the air and sending a wave of supersonic pressure across the city. Nearly 200 people were killed and thousands injured.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Lebanese Rowing Association&#39;s training center was completely destroyed just 200 meters from the port.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What do we know about the Beirut explosion?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The blast in Beirut: Hell and the mysterious ship</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/17306/production/_114228949_mediaitem114228948.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The club was usually full of rowers at the time, but due to coronavirus restrictions imposed just days earlier, the building was empty. Rodrigue is one of the few people who still manage to attend the center as a coach. Despite feeling relieved that no one was in the building, Rodrigue was devastated to see that it had been demolished.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I do everything for free. I train people for free. I fix things for free. Everything is free because I love it and this is my life,&quot; he said. &quot;That&#39;s why I cried when the explosion happened. It was so loud.&quot; The Lebanese Rowing Association was founded in 1968. Despite being underfunded and run almost entirely by volunteers, it is home to about 20 active rowers, from children to veterans from Beirut waters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like the city itself, this society was home to rowers of all origins. Rodrigue is a Christian and his dual partner Akram is a Shia Muslim. Many of the Sunni, Shia and Christian rowers at the club have close ties outside the club, such as attending weddings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We are like family,&quot; said Rodrigue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/CF0B/production/_114230035_mediaitem114230034.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>General Hassan Rustom, President of the Confederation since 1998, recalls when the explosion occurred. &quot;I was sitting at home with my family and suddenly my house was shaken by an earthquake. I can&#39;t even describe the sounds and feelings that are left for us,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Find the dog that was lost in Beirut explosion &quot;We rushed to read the news and learned of the explosion in Beirut port. I went straight to our training center.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I will never forget what I saw that day on the way to the training center. It was a nightmare. Thank God no one was training at that time because of the Covid-19 restrictions. The rowing center was completely destroyed.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/3E6E/production/_114228951_mediaitem114228950.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The rowing club has been an important part of Fara Jarudi&#39;s life since he was ten years old. She collected four gold medals at the Lebanese National Championships between 2003 and 2013, but now she only counts when she has free time from her job as an interior designer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many of Fara&#39;s most beautiful days have been spent rowing the 2 km up and down the harbor. It compares the movement back and forth with meditation. &quot;I feel like I&#39;m with water. It&#39;s very comforting,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/B8BC/production/_114229274_mediaitem114229273.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>During a break in training, he and his rowmate Hiba relax on the boat and catch up. Sometimes they play music and sing to the legendary Lebanese singer Fairuz as the sun sets over the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And because they are in open water, the rowers in Beirut encounter more wildlife than most. &quot;Sometimes the dolphins come in. If they lose track, they go to the port. We have turtles that are very old - sometimes they come to the surface and we are very happy, &rdquo;said Farah with a laugh.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As soon as we reach 2 km at the end, you are near open water. There are a lot of seagulls there - that&#39;s a good sight.&quot; Sometimes the water can be dangerous and the rowers have to keep an eye on the ships entering the harbor. On August 4, Farah was on vacation in Istanbul when she was bombarded with WhatsApp messages asking if she was okay. Then he saw the material from the explosion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We kept saying, &#39;Looks like Hiroshima, looks like Hiroshima.&#39; I continued watching the video. I was shaking, like I was in a movie, &quot;he said. &quot;Before Beirut was full of color, now it&#39;s black and white. It looks the same as it was during the civil war,&quot; he said. Even though the club was destroyed, there was hope for recovery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rowers from all over the world have expressed a desire to help with boats and other equipment while others have offered donations. There are also plans to create a crowdfunding page. Rodrigue, who won a silver medal at the Arab Indoor Rowing Championships in 2018, dreams of hosting the 2024 Olympics in Paris. He acknowledged that prior to the explosion was a difficult task due to a lack of funds and facilities in Lebanon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I imagined my coach, who I didn&#39;t have. I imagined him standing in front of me. When my sword fell, I imagined the coach yelling at me, &#39;Watch out!&#39; He said. Rodrigue is determined to get the club up and running as quickly as possible - even if there is a lack of hope in Beirut. Lebanon was besieged by an economic crisis and the coronavirus pandemic even before the outbreak broke out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;After all this happened, I can&#39;t hope anymore. When I hope something happens and it goes away, it&#39;s hard to overcome, it&#39;s very difficult,&quot; he said. &quot;I go through each day, but I care about my future and I don&#39;t want to give up my dreams.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But even though his club was destroyed along with most of his city, Rodrigue still counts the blessings. &quot;I can&#39;t wish for anything else,&quot; he said. &quot;Looking at myself in the mirror and knowing that I&#39;m still alive is the best thing I have right now.&quot;</p>', 'Beirut, Olypmics', 'Beirut blast olymp_1599651732.jpg', '2020-09-09 15:42:12', '2021-08-14 06:45:55'),
(275, 7, 7, 50, 'australian-journalist-launched-from-china-amidst-diplomatic-conflict-1599651969', 'Australian journalist launched from China \"amidst diplomatic conflict\"', 0, '<p><strong>Two Australian news agencies have expelled their journalists from China because of the diplomatic conflict.&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bill Beartles of the Australian Television Corporation and Mike Smith of the Australian Financial Review landed in Sydney on Tuesday. The Chinese authorities questioned the two men before leaving. The ABC reported that Birtles was &quot;not questioned about his reporting or behavior in China&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Relations between Australia and China have deteriorated in recent years. Australian Foreign Minister Maris Payne said consular officers were helping the couple, the only Australian media reporters currently in China. &quot;Our embassy in Beijing and the consulate general in Shanghai have made a commitment to the Chinese government to ensure their welfare and return to Australia,&quot; he said in a statement on Tuesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AFR reported that Chinese authorities questioned reporters about Cheng Lei, an Australian journalist for Chinese state media who has been detained since last month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cheng Lei: Who was the TV presenter caught by China?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ABC reported that Australian diplomats advised Birtles and ABC management to leave China last week. He was then booked for a flight due to leave Beijing last Thursday. But the situation escalated at midnight last Wednesday when seven Chinese police officers visited the reporter&#39;s home as he said goodbye to friends, the ABC reported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Officials told Birtles he could not leave the country and would then be questioned about &quot;cases of national security,&quot; the report said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She immediately contacted an Australian consular officer who picked her up and took her to the Australian embassy, where she spent the next four days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During this time he was interviewed by the Chinese police in the presence of the Australian Ambassador to China, Graham Fletcher.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Smith, who lives in Shanghai, was also visited by police, encouraging him to go to the Australian consulate. The two men were interviewed about AFR, AFR reported. You are allowed to leave the country to agree to be interviewed by the police.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s the reaction like?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s really frustrating to leave like this,&quot; said Birtles in Sydney. &quot;What a relief to be back in a country with real rule of law. But it was a whirlwind and not a very good experience.&quot; AFR editors Michael Stutbury and Paul Bailey are delighted that the two journalists have survived.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This incident, which targeted two journalists carrying out their normal reporting duties, is unfortunate and unsettling, and not in the interests of Australia-China cooperation,&quot; they said in a joint statement.</p>', 'Australian Journalist, China, Conflict', 'Australian Journalist Flown_1599651969.jpg', '2020-09-09 15:46:09', '2021-08-04 13:53:58'),
(276, 7, 7, 37, 'how-dependent-is-australia-on-china-1599652396', 'How dependent is Australia on China?', 0, '<p><strong>Currently, Australia&#39;s relationship with China is not very happy. Canberra&#39;s calls for answers about the origins of the pandemic infuriated Beijing. In the past month he has imposed several bruising sentences and travel warnings. Many have urged Australia to reduce its economic dependence on China, but is that really an option?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I love Chinese people,&quot; said Chris Kelly, an Australian who has been sowing barley on his family farm for decades. &quot;Love them. Every barley farmer in Australia likes the Chinese because they make us rich.&quot; Last year Australia produced more than 8 million tonnes of golden grain for beer and pork. China buys more than half - at a premium.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But last month China imposed an 80 percent tariff on Australian barley. It came after Canberra, which covers the United States, called for an investigation into the origins of Covid-19, a move that Beijing described as &quot;politically motivated&quot;. Since then, China has suspended some of Australia&#39;s top beef imports and has warned students and tourists not to travel to the &quot;racist&quot; country. This week a man from Australia was sentenced to death for drug trafficking in a secret trial.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This led to an insane debate in Australia: is China retaliating against accusations of manipulating the coronavirus? Could this be the beginning of a trade war like the one between the United States and China?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/56B4/production/_112869122_gettyimages-1206472146.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Australia&#39;s dependence on China</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like other liberal democracies, Australia is increasingly being challenged by the need to balance its economic dependence on China with its own values and interests. Canberra has recently raised concerns about human rights in Xinjiang and Hong Kong, barring Chinese company Huawei from establishing Australia&#39;s 5G network and discussing allegations that Beijing has infiltrated the interior.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This friction is not unique to Australia. Canada, Japan and South Korea - among others - have experienced economic rejection from China, ostensibly for political reasons. However, Australia&#39;s economic dependence on China is greater than many other countries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the past decade, China has been Australia&#39;s biggest trading partner and now accounts for 32.6% of its exports. Australian mines already supply iron ore, coal and gas to drive Chinese growth - favored by competitors in Brazil for their quality and geographic proximity. This is an agreement that benefits both countries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other sectors - education, tourism, agriculture, wine - are also booming in the Chinese market. But like barley, they are less exclusive to Australia and more prone to political tensions, economists say. All of this has sparked debate about whether Australia is too dependent on China and whether Australia should look for other trading partners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This needs to drastically strengthen relations with Asia&#39;s neighbors, said Dr. Lai-Ha Chan, political scientist at Sydney University of Technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He was trying, he said, noting that Prime Minister Scott Morrison was planning a trip to India this year and had repeatedly asked Prime Minister Narendra Modi for information. His visit to Vietnam last year - the first by an Australian leader in 25 years - should recognize its rising star as a market economy, he added. Australian ecotourism and the university sector is actively promoting the two countries. Dr. Chan suggested that Australia could count on a combination of these countries - plus Indonesia, Japan and South Korea - to reduce dependence on China.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/10E4C/production/_112869196_gettyimages-1179902084.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Currently not all of them are in Australia&#39;s top 10 trading partners. In most cases there is no free trade agreement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, economists refute the idea that the Chinese market can easily be replaced.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>India has often been cited for its potential. Australia has set a target of $ 45 billion Australian dollars (&pound; 25 billion; $ 31 billion) in annual exports to India by 2035. Last year, however, more than A $ 160 billion was sold in China alone.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There is no other option that comes close to finding numbers in China,&quot; said Professor Jane Golly, a specialist in Chinese economics at the Australian National University.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Attempts at government (a practice observed in Japan) are a waste of money, say economists. &quot;It&#39;s a little strange for the government to tell companies that you can&#39;t sell to China or have to sell more to other countries when other countries don&#39;t try to buy,&quot; said Dr. Shiro Armstrong, an East Asia specialist. BBC.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australian companies are already working hard to reduce their dependence on China, added Dirk van der Kley of the political research group China Matters, citing the university in particular. &quot;Of course they make a little difference. But the market is important here.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>More options with China?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof Goli believes that calls by some security analysts to turn away from China - which is being covered by the media - are &quot;sad&quot;. &quot;I wonder if the people on the street reading the headlines think we have to stand out from China. I always wonder if they are thinking about what this means and how it can lead to it. They or their children are no longer able to. have a job in the future. &quot;. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Australia and other countries, Australia is better served if you look at the bigger picture. It is much less dependent on exports (20% of GDP) than many countries. However, this income flows directly to jobs and wealth, making China the main engine of Australia&#39;s prosperity. Richard Maude, a former head of foreign affairs for the Australian government, said it was important that Australia could work with China on food security, energy and climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Van Der Clay predicts that markets other than China&#39;s middle class will emerge in Australia, particularly in sectors such as healthcare and nursing. Australia&#39;s significant Chinese diaspora should not be overlooked, said another. Australia is home to more than 1.2 million people of Chinese descent, many of whom have emigrated in the last decade alone - creating deep connections with the community. Chinese consumers continue to choose Australia for education and tourism, for this reason too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Politically, however, there is consensus that Canberra-Beijing relations have fallen to their lowest level in decades. Despite repeated requests from Australia, three years have passed since the bilateral meeting of heads of state and government.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/CBE4/production/_112869125_gettyimages-521114682.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" />Professor Goli said the government should work hard to help Australian companies connect with Chinese counterparts, but feared this would be impacted by &quot;deteriorating&quot; political relations. Others say Australia needs to be more strategic in diplomacy - for example, being able to criticize China from a group of like-minded people rather than go on strike alone. They also suggested that Prime Minister Scott Morrison should arrest Government Hawks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After all, in the end, brilliant diplomacy is just &quot;packaging,&quot; said Maud, a former diplomat: &quot;China still often objects to what&#39;s in it, no matter how well packaged.&quot; Morrison said, &quot;We are just Australians. We haven&#39;t done anything, nor have we tried to do anything that goes against our values, or we have tried in any way to antagonize our partnership with China.&quot; &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australia hasn&#39;t changed, but China has fundamentally changed, said Maude. He claims Beijing is becoming more self-confident and authoritarian. Canberra, like other democracies, can no longer ignore the political realities of economic gain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The risk of economic retaliation will become a permanent feature of the &#39;new norm&#39; in relations,&quot; he said. &quot;We also can&#39;t drink and eat the cake.&quot; But for Mr. Kelly on the barley farm, he felt like the proverbial canary in the gold mine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have been concerned for years - this has been going on for a long time,&quot; he said. &quot;The worst case scenario appears to have occurred.&quot;</p>', 'China Australia, Relationship', 'Australia China_1599652395.png', '2020-09-09 15:53:16', '2021-08-15 19:09:19'),
(277, 7, 7, 35, 'why-chinas-growth-exposes-australias-vulnerability-1599652666', 'Why China\'s growth exposes Australia\'s vulnerability', 0, '<p><strong>Australia and China continue to trade fees and charges in increasing order with far-reaching consequences. Amid criticism of Beijing, Australia has not studied well for a long time, wrote China and Australia expert Kerry Brown.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mao Zedong, founder of the People&#39;s Republic of China (PRC), reportedly called Australia a &quot;deserted continent&quot;. Today, Australians feel far from being lonely after the recent ups and downs in bilateral relations. China provides Australia with a large and growing number of foreign tourists and students and has been the country&#39;s biggest trading partner since 2010.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Investment is also growing exponentially, but is causing growing problems due to Canberra&#39;s security concerns and disruptions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>How did we get here?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australia has changed its national leader five times in the last decade. Despite their differences, prime ministers from Mandarin spokesman Kevin Rudd to Scott Morrison today have one thing in common: They all find that dealing with China is never easy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is not due to a lack of experience in finding a working model. Mr Rudd tries to &quot;tell the truth to real friends.&quot; This broke out into shallow accusations from Beijing that it was actually too close to the United States, allowing naval forces to move into Darwin&#39;s northern port.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Julia Gillard tries to spread the canvas to take an Asian approach. The simple fact that China is so big in Asia made it difficult to implement, and Tony Abbott quickly abandoned that approach when he was elected in 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/1765A/production/_109543859_gettyimages-166164303.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>He tried to get closer to Japan. Maybe it will work - if it lasts more than two years in Canberra&#39;s brutal atmosphere, or, for that matter, if Japan does offer such a lucrative financial offer as Beijing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For Malcolm Turnbull, the early promises of his years to become a senior lawyer and strategist in a more pragmatic and more balanced relationship were thwarted by claims that local and national politicians were influenced by Beijing. Intervention laws were followed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Morrison is now following the same zigzag path - harsh in China in its own language, but has to accept the harsh reality that China still offers the best potential bet for the country&#39;s future prosperity. And as demonstrated in his meeting with Chinese Premier Li Keqiang this week, courtesy almost always returns.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why is that a problem?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When Chinese President Xi Jinping visited the country in 2014, he finally stood before Parliament in Canberra and said they needed to be more ambitious and courageous in their vision for China. And China likes things like the rule of law and institutions that Australia can predict. Why try to violate this attribute?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Part of the problem is size. The emergence of China as a key player, perhaps a key player for Australia - a country of only 24 million people with a large area around the coast for police and a fleet of only 27,000 people - will always be puzzling.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Add to this the combination, the manner in which this whole phenomenon creates some deep, but often hidden, flaws in the Australian national soul. This is a country that until recently, despite its geographic location, should never have been considered Asian.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Europe has been a major source of migration for decades, and America has been a security and a large part of its economic growth. Australia is now accepting a large number of new nationals whose families are from the region, including many from China.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australian universities are a good case. Some have thousands of Chinese students, which means that these usually liberal institutions depend on funding from interest groups of very different values.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The recent documentary Four Corners published on ABC national television contained almost paranoid allegations that a large number of these groups were at security risk because of their political interference and the way they work as technology spies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Canberra to deal with foreign interference in universities</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m in Australia but I feel censored&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why the university angered Chinese students</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There have been cases when some scientists were under pressure when discussing topics such as Taiwan, Hong Kong or Xinjiang. The Chinese government and its agents have been violent at times. However, it is easy to see why some Chinese may be confused because their contribution to the coffers of the country where they are learning and acquiring new skills is interpreted so frighteningly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Challenges for Australia</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The simple fact is that no Australian leader has ever really seen another part of the Chinese equation. If it suits them, they want to talk about the threat this new and very different partner poses to values and worldviews. But they tend not to talk about their own country&#39;s fears and the problems it has.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Only Abbott provided a vivid picture of it when, in a moment of untainted honesty, on camera of Angela Merkel, she said Australia&#39;s attitude toward China was marked by &quot;fear and greed.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australia can avoid investment, students and opportunities from China, and sometimes - Huawei is one example. Trying to do this on a grand scale, however, and seeking partnerships in the Indo-Pacific, for example, would mean great sacrifice and a huge reorientation of its way of thinking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Morrison now appears to be following in the footsteps of his predecessors and taking a very controversial stance. This may be for the very simple harsh reality that despite all the optimistic talk of fighting the Chinese threat, his government and country have no other choice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kerry Brown is Professor of Chinese Studies and Director of the Lau China Institute at King&#39;s College, London. From 2012 to 2015 he was Professor of Chinese Politics and Director of the Chinese Research Center at the University of Sydney.</p>', 'China Growth, Australia Vulnerablity', 'china rise exposes aus_1599652666.jpg', '2020-09-09 15:57:46', '2021-08-14 22:42:47'),
(278, 7, 7, 58, 'protests-in-belarus-maria-kolesnikova-imprisoned-on-the-border-with-ukraine-1599653213', 'Protests in Belarus: Maria Kolesnikova \"imprisoned on the border with Ukraine\"', 0, '<p><strong>An opposition leader was reportedly arrested in Belarus on the border with Ukraine a day after he disappeared.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>State media reported that Maria Kolesnikova was arrested at the border Tuesday morning. This happened a day after witnesses reported that a masked man loaded them into the minibus. She is one of three women who worked together to challenge President Alexander Lukashenko in the August elections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mass protests following his re-election on charges of election fraud. Authorities said more than 600 people were arrested on Sunday during the fourth weekend of anti-government demonstrations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What happened in Belarus?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Breathe freedom&quot; - Belarusians hope for change Mr Lukashenko has ruled his country since 1994. He accuses western powers of meddling. But he has the support of Russian President Vladimir Putin and is expected to visit Moscow &quot;in the coming days&quot;. The European Union on Monday called for the release of all political prisoners and plans to impose sanctions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What happened to Mrs. Kolesnikova?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are conflicting reports about the existence of the opposition. A border official with Belarus said Ms. Kolesnikova was detained at the Ukrainian border Tuesday morning. Two other opposition members, Anton Rodnenkov and Ivan Kravtsov, crossed the border.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The three were at the BMW, the officer said. At the intersection, the car drove &quot;strong&quot; and Ms. Kolesnikova was &quot;outside the vehicle&quot;. The official said he was &quot;kicked out&quot; by him and he moved to Ukraine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ukrainian Border Service sources confirmed that only two men had arrived and both were arrested until their fate was decided.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Belarusian Election: &quot;He threatened to burn us alive&quot; &quot;If we retreat now, we will become slaves.&quot; Great-grandmother took over President Lukashenko</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Monday, eyewitnesses saw a masked man grabbing Kolesnikova on a street in central Belarus and pushing her into a van. The Coordinating Council, a body set up by the opposition to oversee the transfer of power after controversial elections, later said it was not aware of its existence. He added that Press Secretary Rodnenkov and Executive Secretary Kravtsov also disappeared. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Interior Office said it had no information about the detention of any of the council members. Ms. Kolesnikova is the last of three women who banded together against Mr. Lukashenko, who lives in Belarus. Veronika Tsepkalo and presidential candidate Svetlana Tikhanovskaya left the country shortly after the vote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tikhanovskaya&#39;s mother said the recent detentions were an attempt to disrupt the work of the Coordination Council. &quot;The more they try to scare us, the more people take to the streets,&quot; he said in a statement from Lithuania. &quot;I am the only three of us left here,&quot; said Kolesnikova in an interview with BBC Russia last month. &quot;You really have to be here to find out what really happened.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Kolesnikova described the recent demonstrations as &quot;not a power struggle&quot; but &quot;a struggle for human dignity and self-respect&quot;. He said he and his team had decided not to use bodyguards. &quot;No guard will benefit us when a bus full of police stops us,&quot; he said. &quot;We all know what the police state is capable of.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another activist, Olga Kovalkova, announced on Saturday that she had escaped from prison to Poland under threat.</p>', 'Maria olesnikoba, Imprisoned, Ukraine Boarder', 'Maria Kolsnikova missing_1599653169.jpg', '2020-09-09 16:06:09', '2021-08-15 20:35:12');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(279, 7, 7, 50, 'in-a-record-area-in-california-wildfires-continued-as-they-continued-to-spread-1599734288', 'In a record area in California, wildfires continued as they continued to spread', 0, '<p><strong>Wildfires burned a record acre in California this year as firefighters continued to fight some of the state&#39;s major wildfires.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The State Department of Forestry and Fire Protection said the Cal Fire burned more than two million hectares, more than the size of Delaware. The fire, El Dorado, which spanned more than 7,000 hectares, was set on fire by sex-exposing parties, officials said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>California is currently experiencing a record heat wave. On Sunday, Los Angeles County reported its highest temperature was 49.4 &deg; C. Although temperatures are expected to drop from Tuesday, it can cause gale-force winds that can start fires, the National Weather Service warned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Living in &quot;the hottest place in the world&quot; Summer can be &quot;too hot for people&quot; More than 14,000 firefighters continue to extinguish 24 fires across the state, said Cal Fire. The biggest fire known as the Creek Fire has burned more than 78,000 acres since it erupted in the Sierra Mountains on Friday, and authorities say nothing has been contained.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The fire burned at least two dozen homes in Big Creek City, reports the Los Angeles Times. More than 200 tourists had to be taken out of the popular giant pool after it caught fire on Saturday. San Diego County Valley of Fire burned more than 10,000 acres and evacuated remote Alpine towns. Meanwhile the Bobcat Fire destroyed nearly 5,000 acres in the National Forest of Angelis and evacuated the Mount Wilson Observatory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cal Fire alleged &quot;smoke-generating pyrotechnic devices were used during sex disclosure parties&quot; to start the El Dorado fires in San Bernadino County. Gender-specific parties are celebrations that announce whether prospective parents will have a daughter or a son. Several major parties have failed in recent years, even causing the death of one woman in 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/7C2A/production/_114268713_gettyimages-1228376355.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Cal Fire is a reminder to the public that in dry conditions and critical fire weather, it doesn&#39;t take much time to start wildfires,&quot; the tweet read. The people who caused the fires &quot;can be held accountable financially and criminally,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Has the gender party gone too far?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alligators, a &quot;gendered party&quot;, have been criticized California has seen nearly 1,000 fires, often caused by lightning, since August 15. Cal Fire said not only two million hectares burned that year, but eight deaths and more than 3,300 buildings were destroyed. In 2018, 1.96 million hectares were burned - the highest since Cal Fire began tracking numbers in 1987, the Associated Press reported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cal Fire spokesman Lynn Tolmachev told the AP that they were concerned about how early the fires started this year. &quot;It&#39;s kind of worrying because September and October are historically the worst months for fires. It&#39;s usually hot and the fuel dries up completely. And we&#39;re seeing a lot more wind.&quot; A state of emergency was issued in five California counties - Fresno, Madeira, Mariposa, San Bernardino and San Diego - and people were told not to hike after a tourist died.</p>', 'California, WildFires, Spread', 'Califonia in fire_1599657365.jpg', '2020-09-09 17:16:05', '2021-08-14 22:39:20'),
(280, 7, 10, 122, 'president-trump-and-bidens-rivals-have-been-arguing-over-the-covid-19-vaccine-1599657561', 'President Trump and Biden\'s rivals have been arguing over the Covid-19 vaccine', 0, '<p><strong>Donald Trump and Joe Biden insult each other about their position on the Covid-19 vaccine.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Trump has reiterated that there may be a vaccine ahead of the November presidential election, accusing his Democratic rivals of &quot;reckless rhetoric against vaccines.&quot; Mr Biden is skeptical that Trump will listen to scientists and implement a transparent process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are six million cases of coronavirus in the US, the highest in the world. The virus also claimed nearly 190,000 lives, leading to a major recession, double-digit unemployment and falling consumer confidence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week it became clear that the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) had asked states to review &quot;waiver requirements&quot; for getting a vaccine by November 1 - two days before the January 3 election. November - can distribute.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No vaccine has yet been completed clinical trials, which makes some scientists more afraid of politics than health and safety.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How close are we to developing a vaccine?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What drugs can help treat the corona virus?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both Biden and Vice President Kamala Harris have questioned the President&#39;s confidence in the matter. Harris said on Sunday he would not believe Mr Trump&#39;s word the vaccine was safe, and Mr Biden asked if the general public would believe it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He said so many things that weren&#39;t true. I fear people are not ready to get a really good vaccine,&quot; Biden said Monday at Labor Day in Pennsylvania.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/D65D/production/_114277845_mediaitem114277844.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>But he added, &quot;If I can get a vaccine tomorrow, I will. If I have to choose, I will. We need the vaccine and we need it now. We have to listen to scientists.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Poll leader Trump responded to a press conference at the White House, calling Biden &quot;dumb&quot; and Ms Harris &quot;the most liberal person in Congress ... not a competent person in my opinion&quot;. He said they were &quot;destroying this country and destroying this economy&quot; adding that &quot;they should immediately apologize for the cruel anti-vaccine rhetoric they are talking about now.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The president, who sometimes urges journalists to remove their masks when they have questions, again suggested that a vaccine is available next month. &quot;We will have a vaccine soon, maybe even before a very special date,&quot; he said.&nbsp;America&#39;s leading infectious disease expert, Dr. Anthony Fauci said it was unlikely but &quot;not impossible&quot; to get approval in October and Stephen Hahn of the Food and Drug Administration said it may be &quot;appropriate&quot; to approve a vaccine before the end of clinical trials, if the benefits outweigh the risks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both scientists and the White House and the heads of five leading pharmaceutical companies have made it clear that there will be no compromise on the safety and effectiveness of vaccines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Three vaccine trials in the US are in their final stages, involving 30,000 people each, being photographed three weeks apart and then monitored for coronavirus infection and side effects for a week to two years, reports the Associated Press. Press.</p>', 'President Trump, Covid-19, Vaccine', 'Trump_1599657561.jpg', '2020-09-09 17:19:21', '2021-08-14 07:01:04'),
(281, 7, 10, 62, 'rnc-2020-key-findings-from-trumps-speech-and-the-republican-party-convention-1599658002', 'RNC 2020: Key Findings from Trump\'s Speech and the Republican Party Convention', 0, '<p><strong>On Trump&#39;s Day, the White House courtyard looks like a fortress. Security officials installed several layers of barricaded fences around the site to prevent protesters from violating the speech of the president who accepted the convention from the southern courtyard of the Executive Building.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As law enforcement agencies build physical balloons around the White House, Republicans have built a psychological bubble around the president over the past four days, a more entertaining reality sheltered from the chaos of the past six months.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The party&#39;s goal this week is to welcome a winning coalition of voters into this bubble - not just Trump&#39;s loyal base, but disgruntled border guards who may not be comfortable with the president&#39;s policies, women being rejected by his confrontational tone. is, and the ethnic groups affected. Minority for the growing racist tensions in the nation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recent public opinion polls show that a large proportion of Americans believe the country is going in the wrong direction. This is poison for the incumbent president who wants to be re-elected. Trump warned that Biden would &quot;crush&quot; the American dream&nbsp; Republicans, from the president downwards, have tried to prove that things are really good and for the better - or at least that they&#39;re going to get significantly worse with Democrat Joe Biden.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a tall order, but here are six ways the president and his party are trying to meet them.&nbsp; I sell Covid-19 as a success story There have been nearly six million cases of Covid-19 and more than 180,000 deaths in the United States. It&#39;s a cold and hard fact that Trump and the Republican Party spent the week talking. For the first time ever, party leaders such as Mike Pence, Melania Trump and President Trump himself have shown sympathy for lost loved ones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As a nation we grieve, we grieve and we forever hold memories of all the lives in our hearts that were tragically taken away,&quot; Trump said. &quot;In his honor we will unite. In his memory we will win.&quot;&nbsp;Republicans have focused on steps the president is taking such as banning some travel from China to the US (even though commercial flights have been suspended), streamlining and coordinating therapeutic research, the $ 750 million just announced for the new fast. Coronavirus test results and speak of the upcoming miracle of American ingenuity - vaccines - before the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apart from a cursory mention by the President himself during a segment at the White House on Monday, they ignored previously promised breakthroughs such as hydroxychloroquine and missed the fact that the head of the Food and Drug Administration (FDA) is restoring the healing benefits of plasma, which the President highlighted on Sunday. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many speakers referred to past coronavirus pandemics and suggested - or perhaps hoped - that the worst was over. &quot;We provide life-saving therapy and will prepare a vaccine before the end of the year or maybe sooner,&quot; Trump said. &quot;We will beat the virus, end the pandemic and come out stronger than ever.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The re-election of the president is dependent on American voters believing him, even though the virus continues to wreak havoc in the United States - far worse than many other developed nations around the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Promises further economic benefits</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Earlier in the year, in its 127th month of enlargement, the 2020 Presidential campaign had to work hard with the US economy to give the president another four-year term. Everything changed with the pandemic. The United States is currently in the midst of a record recession with double-digit unemployment and falling consumer confidence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But there are signs of life, and Trump and Republicans were quick to say that this week. The stock market reaches new heights and the company&#39;s acquisitions are back. Opinion polls show the president still scores his best in terms of how he handles the economy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the main focus of the Republican Convention appears to be to remind Americans of pre-pandemic economic achievements - the 2017 tax cut bill, renegotiation of trade deals with Canada, Mexico, and South Korea, and what was once a record - low unemployment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Has Trump kept his election promises?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Republican Party&#39;s main argument is that all was well during the first three years of the Trump&nbsp; administration, so he&#39;s the one who can fix it. &quot;In a new term as president,&quot; Trump said in his acceptance speech, &quot;we will rebuild the largest economy in history - we will soon achieve full employment, increase incomes and prosper again.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Or, as Pence said more succinctly on Wednesday, Trump &quot;will make America great again. Again.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Racial make-up</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During his time at the White House, Trump had mixed results in racing. Although the government helped pass bipartisan laws to reform criminal justice through Congress, opponents of the president&#39;s words - and especially his tweets - accuse him of frequently undermining his actions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They cited the president&#39;s cold-blooded efforts to respond to the message behind the recent protests against police brutality and systemic racism as further evidence of his indifference to the concerns of the black community. This week Republicans made a determined effort to portray the president as a de facto supporter of this community.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Night after night, a congressional spokesman claimed personally and professionally that Trump was taking care of black Americans. Former soccer star Herschel Walker, Senator Tim Scott, Kentucky Attorney General, Daniel Cameron, Secretary of State for Housing, Ben Carson, White House official, Ja&#39;Ron Smith - these are probably the main focus of the modern Republican convention on black courts To reach voters .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Donald Trump cares deeply about the lives of black people,&quot; said Clarence Henderson, a 1960s civil rights activist who spoke at Congress late Wednesday. &quot;His politics shows his heart.&quot; In a somewhat controversial display of presidential power during political conventions, Trump pardoned John Ponder, a convicted criminal who is now running a program to help former prisoners return to society and perform citizenship ceremonies for various immigrant groups.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The message in question was clear - as was the strategic point. In 2016, black voters made up 10% of the electorate, with 90% voting for Democrat Hillary Clinton. If Trump can prevent Democratic support in this demographic, it will really pay off - especially in the Mediterranean state, which the president won four years ago. Praise from the black community may also help relieve moderate Republicans who are worried about Trump&#39;s racial segregation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In three years I have done more for the black community in 47 years than Joe Biden,&quot; Trump said. &quot;And if I am re-elected, the best will still come.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For more than three months, racial issues have been a growing fire in the United States, a fire the President occasionally ignites despite a four-day convention. The recent riots in Wisconsin could suggest that if the president is re-elected, there will be more protests and clashes like him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President of Law and Order Four years ago, in a speech to Congress, Trump promised that &quot;the crime and violence affecting our nation will end soon&quot;. In his opening speech, he said that &quot;this American massacre stops here and now&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, three and a half years later, violent crimes erupted in several cities across the United States, and protests against police brutality have sometimes turned ugly. Therefore, the president argues it&#39;s the fault of the state and local Democrats - and voters can send them a message by re-electing Trump.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Your choice will determine whether you protect law-abiding Americans or give free rein to anarchists, agitators and criminals who commit violence that threatens our citizens,&quot; Trump said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since mass protests began after George Floyd&#39;s death, presidents have focused on violence in places like Minneapolis, Portland, Chicago, and now Kenosha, Wisconsin, rather than the police action that triggered it. It happened again on Thursday night.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In his speech, the President mentioned &quot;police mistakes&quot; in passing and said the justice system would hold &quot;wrongdoers&quot; accountable. &quot;But what we will never experience is a situation where things are happening the way they are today. We must not let the crowd rule,&quot; Trump said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How the US attitude towards the police has changed</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the president did not name the 17-year-old man who was accused of killing two protesters late Tuesday. And when Vice President Pence spoke about David Patrick Underwood, a murdered Oakland officer, he was implying that the protesters - not the right - were accused of the crime.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was a growing divide in the country over who was to blame when protests swept American cities. The president said those siding with police over protesters will lead him to victory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Attack Biden repeatedly</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If none of the Republican Party&#39;s attempts to restore its image and restore confidence in America&#39;s current state of affairs are successful, the back-up plan is to move that election from a presidential referendum to one between Trump and his Democratic opponents. To replace.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2016, Trump won despite negative reviews for approval, as his opponent Hillary Clinton was seen as equally disadvantageous. When voters who have concerns about both candidates have to vote, they mostly turn to Trump.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Over the course of the week, Republicans such as party leaders Ron McDaniel and Pence took advantage of the lack of political detail in the Democratic Convention to label Biden a left-wing prisoner. America wouldn&#39;t be safe if Biden won - pence Trump urged Biden to take a drug test before the debate</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Others, such as Senators Scott and Cameron of Kentucky, have questioned his sensitivity to racial issues and threw some of Biden&#39;s more prominent racing mistakes in his face. Pence said Biden was too weak to protect the nation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The harsh truth is that you are not safe in America Joe Biden,&quot; said Pence. In a speech on Thursday evening, Trump repeated all of these attacks - and many more. &quot;The Biden Report is a shameful naming of the most terrible betrayal and error of our lives,&quot; Trump said. &quot;He has been on the wrong side of history throughout his career.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He paid particular attention to the Biden document in support of a free trade agreement - a hot topic for him against Clinton in 2016, especially in Midwest states. He warned that Biden would raise taxes and energy bills, encourage undocumented migration, free criminals on the streets and &quot;confiscate your weapons.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was a flawed attack of varying validity in the hope that some would draw blood. &quot;Biden is a Trojan horse for socialism,&quot; Trump said. &quot;If Joe Biden doesn&#39;t have the power to fight savage Marxists like Bernie Sanders and radicals, how will he defend you?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We fight them</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Political space is all well and good, but modern elections are won by increasing your loyal guerrillas and attracting a fraction of the voters who haven&#39;t really made a decision. Therefore, much of the Republican Convention&#39;s rhetoric is aimed at motivating grassroots presidents - warning them that the media, big technology companies, a liberal &quot;cancellation culture&quot; and a &quot;so-called expert elite class,&quot; according to Christie, governor of South Dakota Noah, you want to bring him. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mark and Patricia McCloskey, St. Louis, pointing their guns at Black Lives Matter protesters, has suggested that Democrats want the suburbs to be removed. &quot;If you defend yourself, the crowd pushed by allies in the media will try to crush you,&quot; said Patricia Makloski.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What really happened at St. Louis that day?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In his speech on Wednesday, Pence said Trump would protect America&#39;s heritage. &quot;If you want a president who keeps quiet when our legacy is insulted or insulted, he is not your man,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Complaints are always part of the fuel that drives Trump&#39;s rise - his followers feel like they are missing something valuable, and the most extraordinary politician, Donald Trump, is the one who will help them defend it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Always remember,&quot; Trump said, repeating the line he had said earlier, &quot;you follow me because I fight for you.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s a recipe for a collapsed campaign as Trump and his supporters seek a long-term and brutal struggle to defend the presidency. President Trump claims his Democratic rival for the presidency, Joe Biden, supports the idea of rejecting the police.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Biden said he would not take money from the police. He wants to invest in public projects and social programs to free the police. Since George Floyd&#39;s death by a Minneapolis police officer in May, calls have been made to divert money from police to spend on other services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What did Biden promise about police funds?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The June 8 statement from the Biden communications team supports the need for reform, with a focus on funding education programs, as well as mental health and drug treatment projects, to focus the work of police officers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These programs should be separated from police funds, he said. Biden&#39;s campaign website also pledged a $ 300 million investment in community police, which relies on recruiting police officers who &quot;reflect the racial diversity of the community.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It also provides additional funding for body-worn police cameras. Seven ideas for reforming the American police force. In a June interview with CBS News, Biden said he does not support police protection, adding, &quot;I support giving government assistance to the police depending on whether they meet some basic standards of decency or not ...&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Biden also wrote a statement to USA Today last month saying, &quot;While I don&#39;t believe that federal dollars should go to police departments that violate human rights or use violence as the first example, I do not support the police&#39;s defense.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why was Biden accused of supporting the rejection?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An interview Biden gave in July led to accusations that he helped take money from the police after Republican Congressman Steve Scalis posted a revised version on Twitter. In this version, Mr. Biden answers the question whether he agreed to the transfer of funds with a &quot;Yes&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Trump made reference to this when referring to the Republican Convention, adding that if Biden becomes president, &quot;the radical left will get rid of police departments across America. However, the video posted by Mr Scalis was deemed defaced by Twitter because the words &quot;for police&quot; were edited in connection with the funding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the unedited original, interviewer Ady Barkan said, &quot;We can reduce the responsibility given to the police and shift some of the police funds towards social services, psychological counseling and affordable housing.&quot;&nbsp;Joe Biden talks about the different kinds of police reform he wants to see when Mr Barkan stops asking, &quot;But do we agree we can divert some of the funds?&quot; He didn&#39;t mention the word &quot;police&quot; in the question, but Mr. Biden answered nonetheless, &quot;Yes, of course.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Republican Steve Scalis deleted his Twitter post with the video, but maintained his view that Biden was talking about police funding. The Biden campaign called the edited video a &quot;big fake.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Who supports police protection?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are several prominent Democrats who support cuts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New York Congressman Alexandria Ocasio-Cortes supports the denial of police service and reinvesting money in local communities. New York Mayor Bill de Blasio has taken steps to save $ 1 billion from the city&#39;s law enforcement agencies by diverting funds to youth programs - although Congressman Ocasio-Cortes said this was achieved through &quot;budget tricks&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Los Angeles Mayor Eric Garcetti has taken $ 150 million from the police department&#39;s budget to spend on other local programs. In other cities such as Washington, San Francisco and Baltimore, local politicians have expressed support for some form of opposition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Seven ideas for reforming the American police force</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Are cities in the United States experiencing an increase in violent crime?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And in Minneapolis, the city council has promised to dismantle the entire police department, although it is not yet clear what will replace it. The Black Lives Matter movement launched a petition to undermine the police, saying, &quot;We are calling for the protection of the national police. We want to invest in our community and resources to ensure that black people not only survive but thrive.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Defundation advocates believe that spending more on education, housing and health care than law enforcement will help reduce crime, meaning fewer police officers are needed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, critics say the kidnapping will not include the reforms needed to train and operate police officers, nor will it improve the functioning of police in society. They also said that simply withdrawing money from the police could make people living in areas with high crime rates more vulnerable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>How much money did the police authorities get?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of the fees to the police department come directly from local governments, the rest from federal government grants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The most recent data, compiled by the Washington-based research organization Urban Institute, shows that an estimated $ 115 billion was spent on police in the United States in 2017. This number has continued to increase over the last 50 years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Overall, crime rates have decreased across the country since the 1990s, although the number of homicides in several US cities this year has increased year over year. A recent poll found that 60% of Americans oppose cutting police budgets and reallocating money for other social programs.</p>', 'Donald Trump, Speech, Republic Party', 'RNc_1599658002.jpg', '2020-09-09 17:26:42', '2021-08-13 00:35:23'),
(282, 7, 7, 41, 'the-new-brexit-law-will-not-violate-the-eu-trade-plan-1599658247', 'The new Brexit law will not \"violate\" the EU trade plan', 0, '<p><strong>The government will introduce new laws that could change customs plans with the EU after Brexit - but 10 euros has denied that it would &quot;violate&quot; existing agreements.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The two sides agreed terms for a UK exit in 2019, including future trade in Northern Ireland. According to reports, the new law could &quot;invalidate&quot; the legality of withdrawal agreements. But Downing Street said it would &quot;make small clarifications in a very specific area&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p> 10 confirms that the new UK Internal Market Act will be published on Wednesday. The European Union said &quot;full implementation&quot; of the withdrawal agreement was &quot;a precondition for negotiations on a future partnership&quot; between the bloc and Britain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ministers are planning legislation to replace part of the Brexit agreement What&#39;s the problem with the Brexit trade negotiations?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Trade negotiations: what do the UK and the EU want?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The news comes at the start of another week of negotiations on this future trade deal. The transition period that has existed since Britain left the European Union in January ends on December 31, and the two sides are trying to reach an agreement to replace it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, Boris Johnson said if a deal is not reached by the October 15 Council of Europe, the two countries will have to move forward - meaning Britain will continue to trade with the bloc in international trade. Northern Ireland&#39;s Secretary of Labor Louise Hay said if the government&#39;s recent move was a bargaining chip, it was not &quot;very effective&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He told BBC News: &quot;This undermines all progress made in the last few months and completely jeopardizes future trade relations.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What did the UK and the European Union agree on?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The two sides signed a withdrawal agreement last year before Britain left the bloc on January 31. The document covers a number of areas, from how much Britain will have to pay for a &quot;divorce bill&quot; to intentions for future relationships.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, one of the main obstacles in the negotiations is how the Northern Ireland issue is handled. Both the UK and the EU have committed to protecting the peace process in the region and preventing the reintroduction of border controls on the Irish island.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, they also agreed that the land border between Ireland and Northern Ireland will be the border between Great Britain and the EU, therefore customs regulations must be followed and obeyed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The UK and EU have agreed on a protocol for Northern Ireland. This will result in Northern Ireland continuing to comply with certain EU customs rules after the transition period. This will require customs declarations for goods transported from Northern Ireland to the UK, as well as some new controls over goods being transported from the UK to Northern Ireland.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He was unpopular with some of the Tories and the Democratic Unionist Party of Northern Ireland which previously supported the government. However, the agreement was passed by the Parliament and the Northern Ireland Protocol became part of an international treaty.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is the British government offering now?</p>\r\n\r\n<p> 10 states that it is bound by the Withdrawal Agreement and the Northern Ireland Protocol. He said he was continuing to work with the EU on a joint commission to simplify how this would work in practice. However, he said he wanted something to protect trade in the UK&#39;s four countries if a deal is not reached by the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The text of the law has not yet been published, so we cannot be sure what will be in his words. However, Downing Street said it would allow ministers to unilaterally decide which specific goods are &quot;at risk&quot; of entering the EU when crossing Britain and Northern Ireland and are therefore subject to EU tariffs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The law would also give ministers the power to cancel export declarations for goods transported from Northern Ireland to the UK, and would make it clear that EU state aid requirements - when the government financially supports domestic companies in business - apply only in Northern Ireland.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The government, however, insisted that the bill only took &quot;limited and reasonable steps&quot; to &quot;clear up ambiguity&quot; - and not &quot;revoke&quot; the withdrawal agreement, as government sources suggested on Sunday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What&#39;s the reaction like?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brussels is concerned about reports from Downing Street. The president of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen, wrote on Twitter that he trusts the British government to implement &quot;a withdrawal agreement, an obligation under international law and a precondition for future partnerships&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that the Northern Irish Protocol is &quot;essential for maintaining the peace and stability of the island and the integrity of the internal market&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Northern Ireland Deputy Prime Minister Michelle O&#39;Neill wrote on Twitter that any threat to amend the Protocol would amount to &quot;treason which could cause irreparable damage to the entire Irish economy and the Good Friday Agreement&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He signed a joint letter from the anti-Brexit party in Northern Ireland to Prime Minister and EU negotiator Michel Barnier, saying it was &quot;completely unacceptable to abandon these protective and mitigating measures&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Labor has accused the government of &quot;misleading the public&quot; by signing so-called &quot;oven readiness&quot; for Brexit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shadow Health Minister John Ashworth told BBC Radio 4 Today Radio: &quot;Parliament supported the withdrawal agreement earlier this year. It made a pledge and signed a treaty on the treaty for Northern Ireland and now appears to be leaving it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And Scotland&#39;s first minister, Nicholas Sturgeon, said the move would &quot;greatly increase the likelihood of leaving a transitional period without a trade deal&quot; and &quot;the resulting economic damage will be entirely caused by the Tories. What a con&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But a government source told the BBC that the law was &quot;not meant to derail negotiations,&quot; and a spokesman said Britain would continue to approach negotiations with the EU in good faith.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As a responsible government, we are considering alternatives if this is not achieved to protect the people of Northern Ireland,&quot; he added.</p>', 'Brexit Law, EU Trade', 'EU trade plans_1599658247.jpg', '2020-09-09 17:30:47', '2021-08-15 18:01:06'),
(283, 7, 3, 41, 'instagram-photo-filters-for-the-filterdrop-model-campaign-1599658497', 'Instagram photo filters for the #filterdrop model campaign', 0, '<p><strong>Filters have become a popular way to manipulate photos, especially for those who want to keep up with the increasing beauty standards in the world of social media.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A recent study by Girlguiding found that one-third of young girls and women would not post a selfie online without using filters to change their appearance. 39 percent of the 1,473 respondents aged 11 to 21 were annoyed that they couldn&#39;t see what they were doing online in real life.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The survey results reflect the concerns of make-up artist and curve model Sasha Palari, who recently posted the hashtag #filterdrop in hopes of seeing &quot;more real skin&quot; on Instagram. I just thought: does anyone know how dangerous that is? She shared when she saw that global beauty brands had published content filtered from influencers promoting their products.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t want kids to grow up thinking they are not good enough because of what they see on social media.&quot; The 28-year-old from Bristol turns to his Instagram show to post &quot;online conversations.&quot; The response was so good that he organized a #filterdrop campaign.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Then it exploded. It&#39;s phenomenal to see a series of realistic and honest photos,&quot; said Miss Palari. He asked people to upload unfiltered photos to their Instagram account and &quot;rate who they are by their appearance&quot;. &quot;We just don&#39;t see enough normal skin,&quot; he says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s fine for me to take pictures without makeup and without filters, but for some women who do ... well, one of them said it&#39;s scarier than having a baby.&quot; Elementary school teacher Katie McGrath has been following Miss Palari on social media for about a year. She never thought her nightly Instagram scrolling would be her job, but she&#39;s doing it this summer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Towards the end of the blockade, I received emails from parents expressing my concern about changes in their child&#39;s behavior,&quot; said McGrath. &quot;The email continues that the child has a problem with his appearance. I am amazed. This child is four, only four years old. &quot;Then I felt even sadder because our children realized how they looked at such a young age.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A 29-year-old man from Cumbran, South Wales found that the student had seen makeup classes on social media. &quot;[She] talked to me about how she dislikes her face without makeup and wants to change her hair color.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;#Filterdrop came in here and saved me.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I feel like I can talk to students about the confidence of whatever I&#39;m personally trying to take away from the campaign.&quot; The four-year-old then asked Miss McGrath why she wears makeup every day, a question she couldn&#39;t answer. The following week he went to school with an &quot;innocent face&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I couldn&#39;t have done this without the confidence of the Sasha campaign,&quot; he said. Miss McGrath is just one of hundreds of women who responded to Miss Palari&#39;s campaign with stories of their own.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The model said she was given the strength to keep trying to tackle a problem she once considered &quot;too big.&quot; Miss Palari&#39;s video for the #filterdrop Instagram campaign has been viewed by nearly 50,000 people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was overwhelmed with messages from supporters, many of whom didn&#39;t realize how much they were connected to the filter until asked not to use it. One woman who replied, a 33-year-old mother from Glasgow, had stopped allowing others to photograph her about three years ago - around the same time she started observing and tracking the hugely influential fitness and beauty.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I really wanted to be one of those women who supports what Sasha is doing, but when I opened my camera I cried because I was physically disgusted by the man who was staring at me,&quot; she said. &quot;I can&#39;t stand the idea of having this image there so people can rate and compare it with a large modified image.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The NHS staff member said she had experienced physical, psychological and emotional abuse in the past and &quot;her pride was not where it should be&quot;. &quot;There are so many people who feel like me, rely heavily on filters, and stare at the path of dysmorphism,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Mental health needs to be a national focus. We have no reason not to know how this unhealthy perception has the potential to provoke and negatively impact our younger generations.&quot; Another Miss Palari follower, Zia Hutchings, said, &quot;Sasha started sharing something on her Instagram through a filtering campaign and I realized that I really hated my face, one without makeup and two without filters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I have seen so many beautiful girls or models on social media with perfect skin, perfect nose and perfect figure. I have freckles, sun-damaging pigmentation, and babies,&quot; said the 27-year-old woman. &quot;At first I didn&#39;t have the courage to take part, then one night I was very scared by my real face.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I have an 18 month old daughter. If I can&#39;t share a photo of my face without makeup and filters, how can I expect her to truly love each other?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The thought breaks my heart.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms. Palari hopes the campaign will have three results: The Advertising Standards Authority (ASA) needs influential social media to declare whether they use filters to advertise cosmetics; Remove face change and morphing filters from Instagram; and &quot;see what&#39;s more realistic on Instagram.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>[The use of filters] is often not announced, so people keep thinking, &ldquo;Why don&#39;t I look like this? &quot;And that&#39;s because they don&#39;t sell the truth,&quot; said Miss Palari. He didn&#39;t want to see the end of the filter, but said some face morphing filters &quot;shouldn&#39;t be around&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One recent one that I found weakens my nose, weakens my face, and is very realistic,&quot; he said. I never thought my nose was big and I looked at it and I thought &quot;maybe it&#39;s big&quot; ... so how would that spoil it for someone who lacks confidence?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;On social media, we have a responsibility to make that change. We choose what we put there. &quot;If this filter has to be declared, the cycle can be broken.&quot; Instead of &quot;naming and shaming&quot; companies that use filters, Miss Palari wants to send direct messages to brands using filters or republish photos that use filters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said there were mixed reactions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ASA confirmed that after contacting Ms. Palari, they investigated whether the use of filters in Instagram ads &quot;misleadingly transmits the effectiveness of cosmetic products&quot;. He adds, &quot;While it is perfectly legal for influencers to use a post-production style in advertising, it is important that filters do not mislead or exaggerate product achievements. We will publish our research results from time to time.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When asked to comment on the negative impact of the filter on Instagram, the social media platform said it had taken steps to reduce social pressure, including testing the removal of &quot;likes&quot; to fit comparison culture. zoom out. and review research and trends to tailor their policies &quot;as needed&quot;. A statement said: &quot;We want the effects of Augmented Reality (AR) to be a safe and positive experience for our community and for developers to be able to express themselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That&#39;s why we allow people to create and use face modification effects on Instagram, but we don&#39;t recommend them in our Effects Gallery. So many people find them.&quot; Responding to the comments, Miss Palari said, &quot;It is a pity that there is still not sufficient acknowledgment of the dangers of Face Alteration and Face Morphing filters, whether they appear in the Effects Gallery or not. They can still be found or not.&quot; It is very easy just by just by doing it. associate it with simple words like &quot;beautiful&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Filters are most often used by developers and influencers with the largest platforms to reach people who are much more impressive with their stories than by finding filters. &quot;I hope that we will immediately take responsibility for how much weakening the nose in less than five seconds can undermine our confidence.&quot;</p>', 'Instagram, Photo filters, campaign', 'Instagram_1599658497.jpg', '2020-09-09 17:34:57', '2021-08-14 22:39:24'),
(284, 7, 1, 69, 'coronavirus-seven-greek-islands-have-been-added-to-the-uk-quarantine-list-1599660231', 'Coronavirus: Seven Greek islands have been added to the UK quarantine list', 0, '<p><strong>Travelers coming to the UK from the seven Greek islands will have to self-isolate for 14 days from 4:00 CET on Wednesday, said Grant Shaps.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The islands affected are Crete, Lesbos, Mykonos, Santorini, Serifos, Tinos, and Zakynthos (also known as Zante). The government says islands could be treated differently from the mainland if infection rates varied.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the airlines criticized the timing - Easyjet&#39;s boss said the changes were &quot;too little, too late&quot;. You end up getting overseas, but is it worth it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Britain is divided over quarantine rules in Portugal</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Can I still vacation in Portugal or Greece?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaking to community lawmakers, Transport Secretary Shaps said the government would use better data to determine the risks to the popular islands.&nbsp; He said this would give &quot;more flexibility&quot; to add or remove them from the quarantine list for the UK - except for continental destinations - by changing infection rates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said this would &quot;help stimulate the UK tourism industry&quot; while ensuring the safety of the traveling public. Shaps said the percentage of coronavirus infections in Spain&#39;s Balearic Islands and Canary Islands was still too high to be removed from the list of destinations where travelers returning to the UK must be quarantined.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travelers coming to the UK from the seven Greek islands will have to self-isolate for 14 days from 4:00 CET on Wednesday, said Grant Shaps. The islands affected are Crete, Lesbos, Mykonos, Santorini, Serifos, Tinos, and Zakynthos (also known as Zante).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The government says islands could be treated differently from the mainland if infection rates varied. But the airlines criticized the timing - Easyjet&#39;s boss said the changes were &quot;too little, too late&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You end up getting overseas, but is it worth it?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Britain is divided over quarantine rules in Portugal Can I still vacation in Portugal or Greece?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaking to community lawmakers, Transport Secretary Shaps said the government would use better data to determine the risks to the popular islands. He said this would give &quot;more flexibility&quot; to add or remove them from the quarantine list for the UK - except for continental destinations - by changing infection rates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said this would &quot;help stimulate the UK tourism industry&quot; while ensuring the safety of the traveling public. Shaps said the percentage of coronavirus infections in Spain&#39;s Balearic Islands and Canary Islands was still too high to be removed from the list of destinations where travelers returning to the UK must be quarantined.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Provided that the government sets its own travel rules and there are differences between countries in the UK, including Greece. Tourists coming to Wales from the six Greek islands must now be quarantined - the islands are Crete, Lesbos, Mykonos, Paros and Antiparos, and Zakynthos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Scottish government has imposed quarantine restrictions across Greece. Northern Ireland is currently putting Greece on a quarantine list.</p>', 'Coronavirus, UK Quarantine, Greek Islanad', 'England_1599660231.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:03:51', '2021-08-12 22:05:24');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(285, 7, 1, 74, 'coronavirus-blocking-restrictions-have-been-extended-west-of-scotland-1599660361', 'Coronavirus: Blocking restrictions have been extended west of Scotland', 0, '<p><strong>According to experts on BBC Radio 4, File 4, stronger NHS support is needed for people who have been suffering from chronic Covid-19 symptoms for months.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Royal College of General Practitioners is calling on a national network of post-covid clinics to help such people. But less than 12% of the 86 NHS care groups Surved and&nbsp;&nbsp;said they used the service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>NHS England said it was &quot;rapidly building new and strengthened rehabilitation centers&quot;. Tim Spector, professor of genetic epidemiology at King&#39;s College London and head of the Covid Symptom Study app, said about 300,000 people in the UK have reported symptoms that last more than a month - the so-called &quot;old covid&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that data from the app showed that around 60,000 people had been sick for more than three months. However, many of these people may not have had a Covid test.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I just want to get my life back.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The government withdrew from community testing on March 12, instead testing only those who were hospitalized. This means that people who have recovered from the suspected Corona virus at home cannot access the test.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How long will my recovery take?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ellie MacDonald, 37, from Surbiton, was training for the London Marathon when she first developed symptoms of Covid on March 21.&nbsp;She has been suffering from shortness of breath and severe fatigue for more than five months, but has yet to receive a positive test result - because community testing was introduced late to detect her illness.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He changed his practice as a general practitioner after initially feeling helpless. Ellie said, &quot;Just knowing I actually have people who take me seriously - that&#39;s so important to my recovery. I just want my life back.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Paul Garner, professor at Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine, has been suffering from Covid since March 19 and believes some patients distrust health care professionals. &quot;I think the evidence lies in our symptoms and our stage in the epidemic,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We need sensible guidelines that really help society. The government is not doing enough with existing medical expertise. It needs to be ordered and put together to work together.&quot; In File 4, all 212 Clinical Commissioning (CCG) groups and health councils in the UK are asked whether they have set up a post-Covid clinic for patients who have not been hospitalized with the virus - but who have not necessarily tested positive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 out of 86 respondents stated that they had operated the facility. Another 16 said they were planning or redesigning the service. Many patients are seen by a general practitioner or existing service. Martin Marshall, General Practitioner and Chair of the Royal College of General Practitioners, said, &ldquo;We know, without a doubt, that there will be an increasing number of people who will have significant and disturbing Covid symptoms in the long term.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;A small portion, but generally a lot, need expert advice. &quot;So we really need to see more and more clinics after Covid.&quot; The NHS UK&#39;s new Your Covid Recovery website offers personalized support for all patients recovering from Covid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lynn Turner Stokes, professor of rehabilitation medicine at King&#39;s College London, said there were some &quot;good resources&quot; but &quot;we still have a lot to do&quot;. He said, &quot;For a person who has never been to a hospital, no one has really checked their lungs, heart, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It would be very useful if we had more services at one (face-to-face) counter.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Personal rehabilitation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The UK government and the UK NHS say there will be new and strengthened rehabilitation and non-profit centers in every part of the country. In Wales, community rehabilitation programs and specialists are most likely the forum for covid treatment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Northern Ireland&#39;s Ministry of Health is currently assessing the needs of Covid patients who have left hospital to highlight future work, while Scotland is planning &quot;high-quality, personality-centered rehabilitation in a variety of settings&quot;.</p>', 'Coronavirus, Scotland restrictions', 'Scotland_1599660361.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:06:01', '2021-08-15 12:23:52'),
(287, 7, 1, 80, 'more-than-200-migrants-have-returned-to-the-english-channel-1599662067', 'More than 200 migrants have returned to the English Channel', 0, '<p><strong>More than 200 migrants were arrested by a Border Force ship off the coast of Kent on Monday.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Interior Ministry confirmed that the 223 people were stationed in 18 small boats. The eight other boats with 106 people on board were prevented from crossing by French authorities, said an Interior Ministry spokesman.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Sunday, 21 migrants came to England in two boats and six were rescued by the French. Last week Prime Minister Boris Johnson said Britain had &quot;become a target and magnet for those who exploit vulnerable people&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than 1,468 migrants made the crossing by small boats in August, despite Interior Minister Priti Patel vowing to make the dangerous route &quot;unprofitable&quot;. The Interior Ministry did not provide any information on how many children were crossing in the small boats.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brief presentation of transparent lines</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dan O&#39;Mahony, Commander of the Secret Channel Threats, said: &quot;This crossing was facilitated by criminals who were willing to risk people&#39;s lives for money. &quot;France is a safe country with a fully functional asylum system - asylum seekers can and should seek asylum there. &quot;I admit that the numbers that still reach Britain are still too high,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week, O&#39;Mahony told the Internal Affairs Committee that French authorities were &quot;obliged&quot; like Britain to prevent migrants from crossing the English Channel in small boats. He told the commission that many migrants were forced to travel in small boats and that some who arrived in England &quot;didn&#39;t even want to come to England&quot;.</p>', 'Migrants, Return', 'English_1599662067.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:34:27', '2021-08-18 08:10:52'),
(288, 7, 4, 66, 'lionel-messi-reported-on-barcelonas-training-session-after-confirming-his-stay-1599662181', 'Lionel Messi reported on Barcelona\'s training session after confirming his stay', 0, '<p><strong>The 33-year-old Messi requested a transfer on August 25 but said last Friday he would stay as it was impossible for any team to pay their release clause.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is the first time since the arrival of new manager Ronald Koeman that the Argentine has trained at the club. Barcelona start in La Liga against Villarreal on 27 September. Messi trains by himself, as did Philippe Coutinho, while the rest of the team train together.</p>', 'Lionel Messi, Barcelonas', 'Massi_1599662181.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:36:21', '2021-08-15 10:15:54'),
(289, 7, 4, 52, 'serena-williams-beat-maria-sakari-and-reached-the-us-open-quarter-finals-1599662315', 'Serena Williams beat Maria Sakari and reached the US Open quarter-finals', 0, '<p><strong>Six-time champion Serena Williams will play Greek 15th Maria Sakari for the US Open quarter-finals.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Williams, 38, was calm as he made the first set after 37 minutes. The third winner lost tight in the second set and had to find his best tennis to break out of the third set and win 6-3 6-7 (6-8) 6-3 almost two hours later.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I keep fighting,&quot; said Williams.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He&#39;s doing very well. He&#39;s very aggressive and I know I have to do the same.&quot; Williams plays French number 56 Alize Cornet or Bulgaria Tsvetana Pironkova - their next first 2017 Wimbledon tournament.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The American is seeking her 24th Grand Slam singles title as she tries to hit Margaret Court&#39;s record. Live scores, results and order of play</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Give back Williams victory</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At first, Williams looked vulnerable on the set in the third round tie against Sloane Stevens, and it was again Sakari who started faster.&nbsp;The two met two weeks earlier in the last 16 of the Western and Southern Open when Williams had one set and one set to lose.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The seven-time Wimbledon champion was under threat when Sakari scored three points in the first set to break serve 2-2, but the Greek failed to capitalize on an early chance. Momentum changed hands as Williams dominated a quiet forehand rally to break the world number 22 on the third try.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And an ace in the middle ensured grip to give the American the first set. Sakari leveled up to reach Williams power Williams&#39; service saved him several times, hitting 124 mph at one point. Sakari had chances to break through in the second set 3-2 and 40-40, but Williams slammed the door with two aces.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And the seven-time Australian Open champion was just as strong from the start: An incredible forehand hit Sakari and changed the dynamics in the seventh game. The Greek increased his intensity in response to Williams&#39; level and the rope in his favor gave Sakari a set point and caused Williams to scream in pain.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A more difficult serve saved this and a second set point, which resulted in a draw.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An 89-mile forehand and a fresh boom in the back saved Williams two more points for a set, but in the end his forehand went deep to give Sakari the set. Williams Fitness passed the third hundred test</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Weak wins have been a problem for Williams of late. The most recent example is Sakari&#39;s loss in straight sets two weeks ago. And although Williams was getting sacked, it looks like history could repeat itself when Sakari broke up in the first game of the third set.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Williams was breathless as he shot back and forth along the baseline to keep his game of duty.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Rest a little longer for the fans here,&quot; he said after the match. &quot;I can use it a little in this game.&quot; Without hesitation, Williams handed Sakari a forehand to Cross Court to return him to serve, and a deluxe serve helped him take a vital lead for the first time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The younger players indicated that he would not give up as he handed out an ace to keep love, but Williams continued to show his level best. A forehand winner at the line paved the way for three stops, and he finished third until Sakari&#39;s forehand found the net.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Williams was adamant as he ran the game and ended the consolation race when the Greek failed to return a powerful backhand shot to Cross Court.</p>', 'Serena Williams, Maria Sakari, Open Quarter Final', 'serena williams_1599662315.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:38:35', '2021-08-15 15:10:38'),
(290, 7, 10, 90, 'james-rodriguez-everton-signed-real-madrid-to-attack-the-midfielder-1599662532', 'James Rodriguez: Everton signed Real Madrid to attack the midfielder', 0, '<p><strong>Everton have signed a deal for Colombia to attack Real Madrid midfielder James Rodriguez for &pound; 20 million.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 29-year-old comes to the Toffees on a two-year contract with an option for one more season. He joined Real Madrid from Monaco in 2014 after winning the Golden Boot at the World Cup in Brazil this summer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I am very happy to be at this great club, a club with so much history and here with a manager who knows me very well,&quot; said Rodriguez.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What did Everton get from James Rodriguez?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m looking forward to achieving great things here - and to win, that&#39;s what everyone is aiming for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I came here to try to improve, to improve. I also came here to help the team win, to play good football - fun football.&quot; Rodriguez, entering the final year of his contract with the Spanish champions, made 14 appearances for Zinedine Zidane&#39;s side last season.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was signed for the third time by Everton boss Carlo Ancelotti after joining Italy at Real Madrid and Bayern Munich. &quot;I believe we can do great things with Carlo and his technical staff and one of the main reasons [that I signed] is the presence of Carlo Ancelotti,&quot; added Rodriguez.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I had great moments with him at two different clubs. That&#39;s a good reason to come here.&quot; Ancelotti said: &quot;James is known as a fantastic player with a lot of great quality and ability to help strikers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He is very happy with the club project and the fact that we want to improve. He is very excited to sign a contract and I did not take the time to convince him - he is sure.&quot; Rodriguez is part of Ancelotti&#39;s ambitious Everton recovery program. The &quot;Sophisticated&quot; signed Brazilian national boxer Alan Napoli and negotiated a fee for French midfielder Watford Abdoulai Ducour.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Colombian has been marginalized at the Bernabeu under Zidane and allowed to skip pre-season training to determine his future. Ancelotti, who became Everton boss last December, was the driving force behind the deal and Rodriguez is drawn to the idea of working with the Italian again.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/onesport/cps/800/cpsprodpb/17B75/production/_114214179_2.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rodriguez won two La Liga titles and two Champions League titles with Real, but was then loaned to Bayern for two seasons and won the Bundesliga in both seasons. He returned to the Bernabeu last season but made only eight league appearances and scored one goal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thanks to his time at Porto and Monaco, Rodriguez had built a fine reputation across Europe before 2014. He won the Portuguese league three years in a row before he turned 21. During that time, he was the youngest to win the 2012 Division Player of the Year award at the age of 20 before Monaco bought him for &pound; 38.5 million.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He scored 10 goals and provided 14 assists in 38 games for Monaco before impressing on the world stage. He scored six goals to win the Golden Boot at the 2014 World Cup in Brazil and secure a move to Real Madrid.</p>', 'James Rodrigues, Real Madrid Attack', 'james Radrigues_1599662532.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:42:12', '2021-08-17 23:16:10'),
(291, 7, 4, 40, 'uk-phil-foden-and-mason-greenwood-leave-camp-after-breaking-quarantine-1599662756', 'UK: Phil Foden and Mason Greenwood leave camp after breaking quarantine', 0, '<p>Phil Foden and Mason Greenwood were forced to leave camp in Britain following violations of Iceland&#39;s &quot;unacceptable&quot; coronavirus quarantine guidelines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The football association is investigating fouls following Saturday&#39;s 1-0 Nations League win.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>20 year old Manchester City midfielder Foden and 18 year old Manchester United striker Greenwood made their international debuts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Manager Gareth Southgate said they were &quot;naive&quot; and apologized.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A spokesman for the Reykjavik Police Department told BBC Sport that the two players had been fined 250,000 Icelandic kroner (&pound; 1,360).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is a very serious situation and we have handled it and acted as quickly as possible,&quot; added Southgate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We got it right. I know your age, but the whole world is involved in this pandemic.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a post on social media late Monday, Foden said the absence of England&#39;s next match against Denmark on Tuesday was &quot;painful&quot; and &quot;will learn valuable lessons from that misjudgment&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I made bad decisions and my behavior was not up to the standards I expected,&quot; he wrote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I apologize to Gareth Southgate, my team-mates in England, the staff, the fans and also the club and my family.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What happened?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to reports in Iceland and other media, Foden and Greenwood claim that they met two women in separate parts of the hotel, away from where the British team was staying.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When asked about the report, Southgate said, &quot;Nothing has happened in the area we occupy at the team hotel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;re still going through all the information because I only realized it a few hours before training.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We had to decide very quickly that they couldn&#39;t interact with the rest of the team, they wouldn&#39;t be able to travel to train.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Given the procedures we now have to follow, they will have to return to England separately.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An FA spokesman said Monday: &quot;While in Iceland, both Phil Foden and Mason Greenwood spent time outside our private team room in violation of our Covid-19 rules.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Even though they didn&#39;t leave the team hotel, it was an unacceptable violation of our protocol. Both apologized for the lack of serious judgment.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The FA has launched a &quot;full investigation&quot; and apologized to the Icelandic Football Association for &quot;taking the right steps&quot;. He also assured the Danish Football Association &quot;that all other players and staff in our group were isolated during this time&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Southgate is yet to choose a replacement and will have a team of 21 players to choose from for Tuesday&#39;s League of Nations match against Denmark (19.45).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>England&#39;s Greenwood draft follows a breakthrough season at United scoring 17 goals, while Foden made regular appearances for Pep Guardiola&#39;s City side in 2019-20.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Manchester City spokesman said Foden&#39;s behavior was &quot;utterly inappropriate&quot; and &quot;far below the standards expected of a Manchester City and England international&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A statement from Manchester United said the club &quot;have been in contact with association football and are disappointed by Mason Greenwood&#39;s actions&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Analysis &quot;You disappointed Southgate, the team and the fans&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Former England winger Chris Waddle live on BBC Radio 5</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Being a footballer is a high discipline. This boy has made his debut and a bright future awaits them. They are very talented footballers and it is likely that they will continue to make many posts, and he [Gareth Southgate] did the right thing by sending them home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You are not responsible. You didn&#39;t just disappoint Gareth; You let the band and fans down. They are still young and unfortunately they have to learn.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m sure they will come back when they start again next year if they do well for their club. This is a terrible lesson to learn at a young age, having just joined the team. This will irritate Garrett.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You are young and naive. These are players who are just starting their career and will stay with them for a long time.</p>', 'Phil Foden, Mason Greenwood, Breaking', 'Mason_1599662756.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:45:56', '2021-08-12 21:09:03'),
(292, 7, 4, 53, 'kylian-mbappe-france-has-sent-a-positive-test-for-the-coronavirus-1599662837', 'Kylian Mbappe: France has sent a positive test for the coronavirus', 0, '<p><strong>Paris Saint-Germain forward Kaylian Mbape has tested positive for the coronavirus and will miss the League of Nations match against Croatia on Tuesday.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Six Paris Saint-Germain players tested positive for the coronavirus last week and Mbappe&#39;s results put the start of their Ligue 1 season into question. Mbape, 21, scored the only goal when France beat Sweden in the inauguration of the League of Nations on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He was kicked out by his teammates on Monday and has been discharged since then. France will face Croatia on Tuesday at 19.45 CET at the Stade de France.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The Covid-19 test conducted by UEFA on Monday morning was positive. After receiving the results at the end of training, he was separated from the team and returned home that evening,&quot; the French Football Association said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Mbappe was tested before joining the team. The results were negative, as happened on Wednesday at UEFA&#39;s request for the Sweden match,&quot; he added. Defending champions PSG will begin defending their Racing Lens title on Thursday after taking a long hiatus after appearing in the Champions League final last month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Ligue 1 season has started but the opening match between Marseille and Saint-Etienne had to be postponed last month after four of the hosts tested positive for Covid-19.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The league told clubs last week that its coronavirus treatment protocol resulted in more than three positive cases at a club likely causing delays.</p>', 'Kylian, France, Positive, Corona', 'Kylian_1599662837.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:47:17', '2021-08-12 21:33:59'),
(293, 7, 10, 75, 'louis-hamilton-formula-1-world-champion-starting-extreme-e-1599662904', 'Louis Hamilton: Formula 1 world champion starting Extreme E.', 0, '<p><strong>Six-time Formula 1 world champion Louis Hamilton will join the team from the new Extreme E racing series.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hamilton, 35, said the new climate-friendly sport, which is scheduled to start in January 2021, has been challenged &quot;because of its focus on the environment&quot;. Its X44 team will compete with electric jeeps in five remote locations to &quot;highlight a topic that matters to the world.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The series was broadcast live on the BBC iPlayer, Red Button and BBC Sport websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What is Extreme E and how can I watch it on the BBC?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Each of us has the power to make a difference and it means a lot to me so I can use my love of racing and my love for our planet to make a positive impact,&quot; said Hamilton, who will not be competing. alone, but will &quot;help lead a special team&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is the first time since his F1 debut for McLaren in 2007, Hamilton has resumed motor sports. Since then he has won 89 races and is considered one of the greatest racers of all time. Hamilton&#39;s X44 team - named after its Mercedes car number - will compete against nine other contestants, including team Veloce, whose main character is F1 design guru Adrian Newey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use of a new SUV with extreme climatic conditions. Extreme E started its first race in Dakar on 23 January in January 2019. Five races are held every two days in Senegal, Saudi Arabia, Nepal, Greenland and Brazil. Each track was designed in this remote area and the competition was held in two rounds of roughly 10 miles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Teams - including male and female pilots - compete against each other. Alejandro Agag, Founder and CEO of Extreme E, said: &ldquo;We are delighted to welcome Louis Hamilton and his X44 team to Extreme E.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Like us, Lewis is passionate about motor sports, but he shares the belief that we can use sport to emphasize climate change and equality. &quot;Lewis is one of the most successful riders of all time and we are all delighted that his X44 team performed on and off the track under his extraordinary leadership.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scientists who specialize in specific forms of pollution will travel on Extreme E-Teams to document what&#39;s in each location and implement an inherited plan. &quot;I look forward to building my team on important values like sustainability and equality,&quot; said Hamilton.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;None of us are perfect and we all need to make improvements, but I love using our platform to highlight the most serious problems facing our planet and the solutions we can all be a part of.&quot; In 2014 Agag also presented the fully electric Formula E racing series.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Louis Hamilton X44 design team paint</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Hamilton X44 team will have a purple livery</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During his 13 years in motorsport, Hamilton spoke on a number of topics outside of sport, most recently about the need to address racial injustice following the death of African-American George Floyd in May. Hamilton was at the forefront of an organized stance against racism during the F1 season, criticizing some pilots for a lack of support and sports organizers for inadequate process coordination.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hamilton, born in Stevenage, wants to use the Extreme E to promote diversity in motor sports. He recently formed a diversity committee to tackle similar issues in sport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s not clear who the drivers will be, but they may come from the Extreme E-Driver Program, which includes racers Jamie Chadwick, Billy Monger, and European Rally Champion Chris Ingram.924</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Formula 1, Louis Hamilton', 'Formula 1_1599662904.jpg', '2020-09-09 18:48:24', '2021-08-17 11:50:47'),
(294, 4, 3, 47, '14-facts-about-the-grammy-songs-of-the-year-award-1599677825', '14 facts about the Grammy Songs Of The Year award', 0, '<p>In 1959, Grammy judges introduced Song Of The Year &ndash; and it&#39;s gotten one of the most searched after prizes at the service&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 62nd Annual Grammy Awards will happen at the Staples Center in Los Angeles over this end of the week, and Song Of The Year is one of the most pined for prizes. Win this, and you join a blessed lobby including melodies from just the most regarded lyricists of the cutting edge time: The Beatles, Frank Sinatra, Elton John and, er, The Doobie Brothers (well, it was the finish of the Seventies).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Grammys acknowledgment of the best tune of it is somewhat more muddled than most honors. Tune Of The Year compensates the lyricists who composed and created the tune, however the honors additionally have Record Of The Year, a prize that goes to the artist and creation group.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A year ago, This Is America by Childish Gambino won the Song Of The Year grant, this year the designations are:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Continuously Remember Us This Way (Lady Gaga)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trouble maker (Billie Eilish)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bring My Flowers Now (Tanya Tucker)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hard Place (H.E.R.)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sweetheart (Taylor Swift)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Norman F***ing Rockwell (Lana Del Rey)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Somebody You Loved (Lewis Capaldi)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Truth Hurts (Lizzo)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For a long time the Song Of The Year class has remunerated melodies that have become part of our aural history. It&#39;s likewise hurled some perplexing choices as well. In front of the service this year, here&#39;s BBC Music&#39;s pruned history of the Song Of The Year grant in 14 realities. [Note: the years refered to are those in which the tunes were delivered and were granted for, not the year the function occurred, which is the accompanying year.]&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The principal Song Of The Year was in Italian&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The US music industry is enormous and expansive enough to have overwhelmingly expand the positions of Song Of The year champs. Be that as it may, when the class commenced in 1959, the Grammy Awards judges gave the prize to Domenico Modugno&#39;s Volare. The tune had just been Italy&#39;s entrance into the Eurovision Song Contest in 1958 and went through five weeks at the head of the Billboard diagrams, transforming Modugno into an easily recognized name. Modugno, unexpectedly, later turned into an individual from parliament in Italy and a frank pundit of Chilean despot August Pinochet &ndash; to such an extent that he was denied passage to Chile to play a show.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jimmy Webb&#39;s By the Time I Get To Phoenix is viewed as one of the great melodies of the 1960s, made much more essential by the sugary tones of the late Glen Campbell. The Grammy board appropriately gave it an assignment for best melody in 1967, however the tune was whipped by, Up And Away &ndash; additionally composed by Webb. Along these lines, The fifth Dimension&#39;s tribute to hot-air swelling made it into the Grammy history books, rather than probably the best articles of sentimental yearning at any point recorded.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Minimal Green Apples beats The Beatles&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bobby Russell&#39;s Little Green Apples is a show-stopper of expressive songwriting; the sort of blue grass melody that causes you to feel you&#39;re directly in the live with the characters. It was initially recorded by nation legend Roger Miller, however the tune&#39;s confession booth approach implied different vocalists before long clamored to cover it. Patti Page and OC Smith both shrouded it in 1968, and Smith&#39;s adaptation earned Russell the Song Of The Year Grammy. Some may have believed that another tune that made the class that year may have prevailed, anyway The Beatles&#39; Hey Jude passed up a major opportunity.</p>', 'Grammy Songs, Grammy Songs Of The Year award', 'p081374g_1599677825.webp', '2020-09-09 22:57:05', '2021-08-15 10:31:18'),
(295, 4, 3, 37, 'the-best-james-bond-themes-that-never-made-it-to-the-screen-1599678044', 'The best James Bond themes that never made it to the screen', 0, '<p>The James Bond film subject tunes have become a permanent piece of popular music culture.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nearly as it so happens, with Sean Connery&#39;s industry-making turn as the smooth spy in Dr No, the Bond movies&#39; makers hit upon an equation as durable as the spy himself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While every official Eon Productions Bond film has included the trademark subject tune by Monty Norman &ndash; you&#39;re murmuring it now &ndash; they have additionally highlighted an unmistakable advantage, one which makes each film as particular as the reprobate the vodka-martini-tasting spy needs to despatch: the signature tune.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s difficult to consider Live And Let Die (1973) without Wings&#39; whole-world destroying cut of rock show, or A View To A Kill (1985) without Duran&#39;s self important signature melody. Furthermore, that is before we even consider Shirley Bassey&#39;s masterclasses of artistic unsubtlety with Goldfinger.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this way, save an idea for those notable specialists who wrote a Bond topic seeking after interminability, just for it to be dismissed on the projecting sofa. As Billie Eilish plans to release her Bond subject No Time To Die at the Brit Awards, BBC Music glances back at a portion of the Bond topics that may have been&hellip;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Film:Thunderball (1965)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lost to: Tom Jones&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Superior to the picked subject? Tied&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most Bond-like verse: Somewhere, there is a man who could stop the thing in time/He is known by not many however he&#39;s dreaded by all in wrongdoing&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Thunderball, your blazing breath can consume the coldest man!&quot; articulates The Man dressed in Black, in a way both ridiculously camp and as stony looked as an Easter Island sculpture. Expressively, Cash&#39;s bombed Bond topic follows the film&#39;s plot steadfastly &ndash; seaside city menaced by a boat containing a monster bomb &ndash; in a realistic nation style loaded with challenging sponsorship vocals and blasting metal. Tom Jones, obviously, may have recorded the genuine subject, however Cash&#39;s exertion is a hero among disappointments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Film:The Man With The Golden Gun (1974)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lost to: Lulu&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Superior to the picked topic? No&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most Bond-like verse: The man with the brilliant/Gun in his pocket/The man with the brilliant/Gun in your face&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an imaginary world, Alice Cooper could have been an ideal Bond scalawag &ndash; or at any rate, a scene-taking associate (unmistakable advantage &ndash; a fire tossing guitar, maybe?). Furthermore, in another imaginary world, it would have been him singing the topic to the 1974 Roger Moore film. This limited glitz rock offcut surely isn&#39;t one of Cooper&#39;s solid metal works of art, and furthermore experiences essentially no connection to the real film separated from the title. Less a tasteful mixed drink relax, more a plunge bar at 2am with The Sweet on the jukebox.</p>', 'James Bond, James Bond themes', 'The best James Bond themes that never made it to the screen_1599678044.', '2020-09-09 23:00:44', '2021-08-17 23:46:21'),
(296, 4, 3, 27, 'the-oddest-grammy-album-of-the-year-awards-1599678188', 'The oddest Grammy Album Of The Year awards', 0, '<p>Hard work over The Beatles? Eric Clapton over Nirvana? Steely Dan over Eminem? Herbie Hancock over Amy Winehouse? Definitely some mix-up?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Grants function making a decision about boards are regularly blamed for being pale, male and stale, a maturing secrecy withdrawn from contemporary culture.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s a brickbat that has been heaved at the Grammy casting a ballot board for quite a while. In 2018, the just one of its best collection chosen people not to play one of their tunes live was the main lady up for the prize &ndash; Lorde. The exact year, U2 were highlighted no under multiple times during the transmission, notwithstanding not in any event, being up for an honor. The honors reliably ignored move music, just making a class for it in 1998, 10 years since the prime of move culture. Furthermore, the less said about the Grammy&#39;s a safe distance relationship with hip-jump the better.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The honors&#39; occasionally bewildering rundown of classifications &ndash; which presently remains at 78, having been cut from 109 out of 2012 &ndash; implies craftsmen in a wide range of less prominent kinds (jazz, parody, children&#39;s) get their gestures close by the typical honorary pathway top picks. For example, Elmo the Muppet has won a Grammy multiple times &ndash; for Best Musical Album for Children in 1998 (Elmopalooza!), 1999 (The Adventures Of Elmo In Grouchland), and 2001 (Elmo And The Orchestra).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, at the core of the Grammy problem is regularly an issue &ndash; regardless of whether to perceive the uncompromisingly aesthetic, or full for the more secure wager. No class bears that out superior to Album of the Year. This time round, the board appears to have made a nice showing, adjusting the pop likes of Arianna Grande and Billie Eilish with basic sweethearts, fo