any case, hello, in any event they were assigned this time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2004&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Won: Ray Charles and Friends, Genius Loves Company&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ought to have won: Kanye West &ndash; The College Dropout, or Franz Ferdinand, Franz Ferdinand&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steely Dan&#39;s success in 2000 underlines a disappointing imperfection that can influence sundown profession collections from set up specialists. Similarly that neglected veteran chiefs here and there get an Oscar for lesser, later work, the Grammys can compensate specialists for their proceeded with nearness. It&#39;s additionally conceivable that the torment of losing blue legend Ray Charles &ndash; who passed on in June 2004 &ndash; brought Genius Loves Company into sharp help when it was delivered after death a couple of months after the fact. It was a loose yet unspectacular two part harmonies record, blending Charles with any semblance of Willie Nelson, Norah Jones and Diana Krall.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could contend that two great collections of that year could have won the prize. Franz Ferdinand&#39;s eponymous presentation was a certified sensation, a hit record over the globe, and the ideal refining of frontman Alex Kapranos&#39; craving to compose tunes &quot;your sweetheart will move to&quot;, precise and intriguing but then loaded down with radio-accommodating snares. Kanye West&#39;s The College Dropout, then, remains apparently his imaginative apex. Recorded more than four years while West was repelled by record mark after record name, The College Dropout effervesced with determined vitality.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2007&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Won: Herbie Hancock, River: The Joni Letters&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ought to have won: Amy Winehouse, Back To Black&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On paper, Amy Winehouse&#39;s characterizing collection, Back To Black, was impeccable Grammy grain. Winehouse herself appeared radiated in from an</p>', 'Grammy Album, Grammy Album Of The Year awar