(307, 4, 3, 67, 'the-greatest-hip-hop-songs-from-around-the-world-1599680936', 'The greatest hip-hop songs from around the world', 0, '<p>We surveyed 106 pundits from 13 nations across six mainlands to discover the best hip-bounce tune &ndash; here are their picks of tunes from outside the US&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The worldwide development of hip-jump is best estimated in decades. After Rapper&#39;s Delight assumed control over the radio waves toward the finish of the 1970s, New York turned into the superheated focal point of this valiant new stable. All through the &#39;80s, hip-jump remained to a great extent a restricted scene. Turntablists like DJ Kool Herc were scratching and turning records in the Bronx, Run DMC were making rock-impacted tracks in Queens, and Kurtis Blow was throwing account rhymes up in Harlem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 1990s saw a blast of the sound over the US. Each area built up their own sonic mark, from the vividly astounding tracks that Virginia-local Missy Elliott dropped to the hacked and screwed rhythms of Port Arthur, TX&#39;s UGK and the spirit and-gospel arched rhymes of Chicago&#39;s Common. (The year 1990 was likewise the first run through a hip-jump tune took the main spot on the Billboard Hot 100. Tragically, it was Vanilla&#39;s Ice Baby.)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dizzee Rascal has carried grime to a worldwide crowd (Credit: Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dizzee Rascal has carried grime to a worldwide crowd (Credit: Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the point when the Millennium showed up, hip-jump began to crawl into the standard account around mainstream society. The sound was all over, as the green shoots of its global ascent were starting to show, with specialists like MIA. what&#39;s more, Dizzee Rascal turning out to be global stars.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The previous decade has dug in hip jump as a lasting piece of mainstream society, yet as mainstream society itself. Hip-jump is the means by which individuals talk about themselves from Kashmir to California. The class that was once so firmly characterized has begun unlimited parts of new types. Hip-jump doesn&#39;t simply have a place with the Bronx any longer. It&#39;s all over the place.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Accordingly, we felt it was the perfect chance to ask pundits around the globe what they believe are the best hip-jump melodies ever. No curve balls to see that practically the entirety of the 280 melodies designated altogether are from US specialists. Yet, we additionally got designations for tunes starting external the US. As the motivation behind these rundowns ought to be to empower revelation just as discussion, we figured we would assemble a rundown of the pundit&#39;s picks from around the globe to make a worldwide playlist. Here are the champions from the pundits&#39; picks that show hip-bounce&#39;s fifty years of development into a worldwide marvel.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shinjitsu No Dangan, King Giddra (1995)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because worldwide hip-jump didn&#39;t become famous until the noughties doesn&#39;t mean there weren&#39;t craftsmen attempting to carry the class to their own shores. Ruler Giddra &ndash; not to be mistaken for MF DOOM&#39;s moniker King Gheedorah &ndash; was a Japanese gathering which submitted political general direction to bunches like Public Enemy, featuring the unmistakable monetary reality for some Japanese individuals in the shadow of a profound downturn. Musically, Shinjitsu No Dangan (Bullet of Truth) is a blend of East coast blast bap and the stone touched sound of Cypress Hill. Creation shrewd it may not be horribly imaginative, yet the tune is loaded with fire.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Je Danse Le Mia, IAM (1994)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event that you ask any hip-jump head where the best non-English rap hails from, the appropriate response is perpetually France. IAM came to conspicuousness in the mid &#39;90s, submitting equivalent general direction to New Jack Swing and R&amp;B. Je Danse Le Mia arrived at number one in France, and remained there for quite a long time, motivating a totally different age of hip-jump craftsmen who saw that the class had star-production potential. The tune falls in line among silly and irresistible, with a funk-infused beat that wouldn&#39;t have been strange during the 1970s.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Italina rapper Frankie Hi-NRG MC was included at the very beginnings of Italian hip-bounce (Credit: Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Italina rapper Frankie Hi-NRG MC was included at the very beginnings of Italian hip-bounce (Credit: Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I Luv U, Dizzee Rascal (2003)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Regardless of whether grime is hip-jump or not is a discussion that despite everything seethes today, yet nobody can contend that Dizzee Rascal carried the particularly English kind to the world&#39;s stage. The beat and stream of Dizzee&#39;s hit is proto-grime, all forceful wilderness and carport beats over fast fire rhymes that despite everything sound smooth at 140bpm. I Luv U didn&#39;t begin grime, however it catapulted it into the open awareness.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Soweto, Pro Kid (2005)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are rappers that set whole urban areas up for life. Think Meek Mill and Philadelphia or Drake and Toronto. Soweto&#39;s Pro Kid was another of these, advocating a territorial hip-jump style brought up in the acclaimed Johannesburg suburb. Soweto has all the triumphant strut of Jay-Z or Rick Ross rhyming over a vintage Just Blaze beat, yet Pro Kid likewise brought a particular jargon of Sowetan slang and vernacular to the table, making something grand simultaneously.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The most effective method to Rap About Africa, Black Vulcanite (2016)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2005, Kenyan writer and columnist Binyavanga Wainaina composed a satiric paper marked How to Write About Africa. It turned into a milestone bit of analysis, parodying the individuals who might go to the landmass and follow a drained equation that featured clich&eacute; stories about neediness, destruction, and debasement. After 10 years, the Namibian gathering Black Vulcanite put Wainaina&#39;s paper to music, giving it a fuming beat that submits general direction to notable makers like DJ Premier and Madlib. The subsequent track, How to Rap About Africa, is less offhanded and all the more harshly basic, bringing the mutinous fire of Public Enemy and Dead Prez to an entirely different period and topography.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sub City, Stogie T (2016)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>South Africa&#39;s hip-jump scene is one of the world&#39;s generally experienced, and it has created probably the most masterfully talented MCs this side of Queens. Yet, even in that packed field, Stogie T stands separated. The 38-year old MC broadly flexed his abilities on public broadcast Sway in the Morning, spitting an impeccable free-form over the beat from Nas&#39; NY State of Mind. It was a star-production second, however Stogie T has been rhyming since the turn of the thousand years, including the champion track Sub City from his eponymous 2016 collection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cuban gathering Orishas were one of the spearheading Caribbean hip-jump acts (Credit: Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cuban gathering Orishas were one of the spearheading Caribbean hip-jump acts (Credit: Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ngqangqa, Kanyi (2017)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As hip jump turned into a prevailing melodic power, it additionally turned into an outlet for those looking to keep their own oral and story conventions alive in a time of social homogenisation. Kanyi Mavi, a MC hailing from Cape Town, raps in Xhosa &ndash; a language expressed by in excess of 8,000,000 South Africans that contains particular &quot;click&quot; consonants. Mavi&#39;s rapping is studded with those snaps, giving the grave, coarse beat on her 2017 track Ngqangqa another layer that would be difficult to include utilizing another dialect.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Battle da Faida, Frankie Hi-NRG MC (1993)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Italy may not be the main nation you consider with regards to hip-bounce, however Frankie Hi-NRG MC has been in the game as long as unbelievable acts like Common and UGK. His presentation single is as politically charged as any Public Enemy track, railing against the impact of the mafia in Sicily on a meager, springy beat revolved around a Sly and the Family Stone example. Frankie does his best Ice Cube impact on Fight da Faida, realizing that downplayed style can be the most destroying approach to convey a rhyme.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Atrevido, Orishas (2000)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The vast majority of the tunes on this rundown sound like American hip-jump. Atrevido, a track from Cuban rap bunch Orishas, doesn&#39;t. It&#39;s hip-bounce by craftsmen personally acquainted with Cuba&#39;s complex melodic conventions, from rumba to bolero to jazz, yielding a sound that could fit easily into quite a few classes. Orishas&#39; capacity to shape move and mix legacy with current tastes has enlivened specialists from Bad Bunny to Camilla Cabello, and made the Caribbean one of the cutting edge forces to be reckoned with of contemporary hip-bounce.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More on BBC Music&#39;s most prominent hip-jump tunes ever:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 25 biggest hip-bounce tunes ever&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What pundits needed to state about the best 10&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Full rundown of pundits who took an interest &ndash; and how they casted a ballot&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why Juicy is number one (not accessible in UK)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Patterns and astonishments in the survey (not accessible in UK)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For what reason are there not many ladies in hip-bounce surveys? (not accessible in UK)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Playlist of the main 25 melodies (Spotify)</p>', 'hip-hop songs, hip-hop songs from around the world', 'The greatest hip-hop songs from around the world_1599680936.', '2020-09-09 23:48:56', '2021-08-18 04:00:28'),
(308, 4, 3, 46, '2019-hyundai-mercury-music-prize-live-performances-1599681105', '2019 Hyundai Mercury Music Prize: Live performances', 0, '<p>This year&#39;s Hyundai Mercury Award, which celebrates the best British or Irish artist&#39;s album in the past 12 months, went to Dave for Psychodrama. The South London rapper&#39;s album is an extraordinary debut designed as an excerpt from a year-long therapy course that addresses issues of sadness, racial identity, domestic violence and depression.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The award recognizes the best British and Irish album in the past 12 months and was selected by a group of British music critics and industry professionals. Psychodrama hits from Black Midi, Foals, Nao, Little Simz, and others, and is joined by other similar rap winners, including Dizzee Rascals Boy in Da Corner and Skeptas Konnichiwa. Dave accepted the award, invited his mother on stage and paid tribute to his brother, who is currently in prison, for inspiring the album.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Psychodrama Dave is the winner of the 2019 Hyundai Mercury Prize<br />\r\nList of selected Hyundai Mercury Prize for 2019<br />\r\n12 x 1 Mercury Prize Podcasts<br />\r\nLive highlights from selected artists<br />\r\nThe prizes include live performances by the nominated artist. Enjoy all the shows listed below. (Warning: some shows have offensive language.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Foal, on the moon</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stallions - On the Moon (Hyundai Mercury Prize 2019)<br />\r\nFrontman Foal Yannis Filipakis didn&#39;t play guitar after being stabbed so he couldn&#39;t play anymore - Felix White of the Maccabees stepped in to save the day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Anna Calvi, don&#39;t hit my boy girl</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Anna Calvi - Don&#39;t Knock the Girl Out of My Boy (Hyundai Mercury Prize 2019)<br />\r\nDescribing the song, Anna Calvi said, &quot;This is a song about the challenge of happiness. It&#39;s about the freedom to identify yourself the way you want, without the boundaries of society.&quot; &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Little Sims, selfish</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Little Simz - Selfish (Hyundai Mercury Prize 2019)<br />\r\n&quot;I&#39;m in my mid-twenties - nobody warned me it would be this difficult,&quot; Little Sims told Annie Mack on BBC Radio 1. &quot;I feel like a gray area - that&#39;s why I named the album.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SEED Ensemble, Interplanetary Migration</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SEED Ensemble - Interplanetary Migration (Hyundai Mercury Prize 2019)<br />\r\nThe ten-man project, led by composer, arranger and saxophonist Cassie Kinoshi, combines South African jazz with soul and hip hop influences from the 1960s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fontaine, boy in a better country</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fontaines D.C. - Boys in a Better Country (Hyundai Mercury Prize 2019)<br />\r\nQuick and Furious: The band said the only lighting they had when recording some songs was flash.</p>', '2019 Hyundai Mercury Music Prize', '2019 Hyundai Mercury Music Prize Live performances_1599681105.', '2020-09-09 23:51:45', '2021-08-14 22:36:38'),
(309, 4, 3, 62, 'how-ric-ocasek-and-the-cars-shaped-the-sound-of-pop-1599681267', 'How Ric Ocasek and The Cars shaped the sound of pop', 0, '<p>Ric Ocasek of The Cars kicked the bucket on Sunday, matured 75. To stamp his passing, we glance back at how the band made a standout amongst other presentation collections, time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nIt could be the ideal collection opener, however it wasn&#39;t.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The introduction is the word reference meaning of effortlessness &ndash; an eighth-note guitar riff with a subsequent guitar abruptly blasting into life like a splendid fire on the seventh note. It&#39;s irresistibly relentless.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-BLAM-tchk!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-BLAM-tchk!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The bend, when it comes in the fifth harmony, is similarly as basic. This time, crescendo hits twice, on the seventh and eighth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-tchk-BLAM-BLAM!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With their melody Just What I Needed, The Cars had thought of one of the best stone introductions ever, utilizing the sort of fundamental, stripped down guitar aptitudes you could might get in your initial hardly any guitar exercises. It is a masterclass of pressure and delivery &ndash; the bass and drums sliding in as artist Ben Orr offers one of the most surrendered opening lines ever to elegance a hit tune: &quot;I don&#39;t worry about you coming round/and burning through the entirety of my time.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Exactly when you ponder to detonate, you&#39;re out of nowhere interfacing with a pre-tune, lit with melancholy console. At the point when the tune at last comes, its effect &ndash; an angry guitar lick, backing vocals stacked consistently on head of one another in sparkling agreement &ndash; is all the all the more overpowering.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cars, The Cars - the band&#39;s presentation collection&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cars, The Cars - the band&#39;s presentation collection&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That the melody doesn&#39;t start procedures on the band&#39;s self-named 1978 presentation isn&#39;t so much a prosecution of their capacity to arrangement a collection as evidence exactly how intimidatingly great the remainder of their collection is. Truth be told, The Cars&#39; presentation is so crammed with hits that a melody most pop-musical crews would murder for doesn&#39;t come into see until 33% of the route through. &quot;We used to joke that the main collection ought to be known as The Cars Greatest Hits,&quot; guitarist Elliot Easton later said in the band&#39;s assemblage Just What I Needed: The Cars Anthology.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Long street to progress&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The band&#39;s sound &ndash; which combined force pop, new wave and great stone &ndash; figured out how to sound both like popular music of the past and popular music of things to come, and promptly won them an enormous after. Yet, what appeared as though a short-term achievement was over 10 years and a few groups really taking shape.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cars were no bundle of bratty adolescents. Frontman Ric Ocasek was 33 when the band recorded their introduction. He&#39;d met bassist Benjamin Orr in Ohio during the 1960s when both were playing for neighborhood groups. The fellowship suffered however a vocation booking groups together in the mid-west before the couple moved to Boston in the mid 1970s.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The band&#39;s sound &ndash; which combined pop, new wave and exemplary stone &ndash; figured out how to sound both like popular music of the past and popular music of things to come.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cars were not the pair&#39;s first wound at progress. In 1973, they delivered a society rock collection under the name Milkwood (alongside guitarist Jas Goodkind). It neglected to outline. Their subsequent band Richard and the Rabbits was additionally a fleeting sensation, yet it introduced them to Greg Hawke, who might bring the brand name synthesizer sting to The Cars influence pop melodies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When Ocasek and Orr started playing together as an acoustic pair at a Cambridge caf&eacute;, a portion of the main Cars tunes began to come to fruition. Another fleeting band rose and fell &ndash; Cap&#39;n Swing. Berklee Music School-taught Elliott Easton, would get one of the establishments of The Cars. The last piece was David Robinson, the drummer with neighborhood legends The Modern Lovers, generally well known for their driving hymn Roadrunner.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By this stage, Orr and Ocasek had composed and composed and composed. They had street tried melodies enough to record demos that were played on Boston nearby radio. Two of the demo tracks &ndash; Just What I Needed and My Best Friend&#39;s Girl&ndash;are among the initial three tracks on the presentation collection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cars in 1978 (Credit: Getty Images)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cars in 1978 (Credit: Getty Images)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That Boston airplay prompted enthusiasm from record organizations, quick to sign groups peaking the New Wave. The Cars at last marked with Elektra, at the time the home of people craftsman Jackson Browne and The Eagles, whose melodies administered US radio. The band deserted to London to record their collection with maker Roy Thomas Baker, who had created Queen during their ascent to progress.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;With The Cars, you had this band with a scanty cadence area and an exceptional vocalist in Ric Ocasek, yet when the harmonies kicked in, it was a mass of sound,&quot; Baker revealed to Mix magazine in 1999. &quot;They came when rock radio truly required some sprucing up.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pastry specialist creator&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cars collection opens with Good Times Roll. The guitar is humming and grating, Ocasek&#39;s voice lost in the ether behind it. It sounds scanty and clean. However, at that point comes Baker&#39;s clear-cut advantage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At the point when the amicability vocals come in, there are the same number of vocals there as there were in a Queen record,&quot; Baker disclosed to Mix magazine. &quot;The main contrast is it was in and afterward it was no more. Great Times Roll is an exemplary one for that. At the point when they sing those words, it&#39;s immense and afterward it&#39;s gone, and everything has returned to meager once more. I had the option to put large vocals on a scanty, punkish foundation, kind of creating post-punk pop.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bill Janovitz, the frontman of Boston musical crew Buffalo Tom and a music author, was in a flash snared. &quot;This collection came out when I was 12 or 13. It was an ideal chance to hear it, and it was wherever on the radio.&quot; he reveals to BBC Music.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was still in New York, however when I moved to the Boston zone a couple of years after the fact, The Cars were god, buddy,&quot; he says. &quot;I am aware of nobody who dare affront this record. I sincerely think everybody cherishes it. Everybody I know, at any rate. On the off chance that they don&#39;t care for it, I don&#39;t care for them.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ric Ocasek from The Cars (Credit: Getty Images)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ric Ocasek from The Cars (Credit: Getty Images)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Janovitz trusts it&#39;s an unashamedly exemplary stone record, notwithstanding the New Wave synth sheen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is positively introduced the &#39;80s. Yet, it is a simple as-damnation record,&quot; says Janovitz. &quot;Cylinder (valve) amps, old guitars, huge drums, stacked vocals from Roy Thomas Baker, all conveying Suicide-and-Roxy-Music-and-Beats-verse educated bubblegum pop.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Driving heritage&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Cars would part in 1988, having recently become a MTV staple gratitude to any semblance of 1984&#39;s You Might Think and its PC designs weighty video. Ocasek immediately left on a performance vocation, yet additionally turned into a popular maker. He was behind the work area for Weezer&#39;s initial two collections in the mid 90s, just as Nada Surf&#39;s 1996 presentation and a portion of No Doubt&#39;s 2000 collection Rock Steady.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 1999, the Swedish force pop band The Wannadies recorded their collection Yeah with Ocasek. Frontman P&auml;r Wiksten had known about The Cars&#39; music already, however started to dive further into the band&#39;s inventory once Ocasek had consented to deliver the collection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I had the option to put enormous vocals on a meager, punkish foundation, kind of designing post-punk pop&quot; - Roy Thomas Baker&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We practiced with Ric in London before going to New York to record. He was clearly perceived in London, yet when we got to NYC &ndash; amazing!&quot; he discloses to BBC Music. &quot;Individuals blaring their horns, yelling from over the road, cheering! The Cars and Ric were/are totally gigantic in America!&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The meetings, Wiksten says, had some strangely unplanned likenesses with the collection that characterized The Cars&#39; vocation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At the point when me and [bandmate and wife] Christina were beginning to play with harmonies, particularly on the title track Yeah, Ric would leave the room. &#39;I never used to meddle when we recorded with Roy Thomas Baker either. You do what wanna do,&#39; he said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;What&#39;s more, when we had layered the sponsorship vocals a few times, Ric&#39;s associate Haig hurried to get Ric: &#39;It seems as though Queen, man!&#39; Ric stated, with a delicate grin: &#39;It does. All around done!&#39;&quot;</p>', 'Ric Ocasek', 'How Ric Ocasek and The Cars shaped the sound of pop_1599681267.', '2020-09-09 23:54:27', '2021-08-17 10:30:46'),
