(374, 4, 6, 52, 'can-artificial-intelligence-create-a-decent-dinner-1599772009', 'Can artificial intelligence create a decent dinner?', 0, '<p>It is the night prior to the week after week shop. I look in the ice chest and think about my three tomatoes, the yam and the asparagus.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ordinarily, I&#39;d accept this as my prompt to nip to the fish and chip shop.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nonetheless, I&#39;m evaluating Plant Jammer, an application that vows to stir up a formula dependent on whatever food you have lying around, utilizing man-made brainpower.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It look through 3,000,000 plans to discover regularly matched things. It at that point counsels a library of fixings that the organization has employed proficient gourmet experts to gather by flavor - salt, umami, harsh, oil, crunch, delicate, sweet, unpleasant, fiery, new and fragrance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At long last, the product gains from this information and devises new plans.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Future food?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Michael Haase, the organizer of Plant Jammer, says this last advance is the thing that makes his application exceptional.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conventional formula applications are fueled by information bases - you list what you have in the refrigerator and the application sends a previous formula it found on the web.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That is the old way,&quot; says Mr Haase. &quot;We are really building new plans without any preparation each time with an AI [artificial intelligence]. This will be what&#39;s to come.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plant Jammer is one of a small bunch of formula applications, food merchants and even occasions organizations that are going to man-made reasoning to increase an edge in the food business.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More Technology of Business&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For what reason are there not many dark tech business visionaries?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Adversary powers racer for lead in hypersonics&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How to fix whimsical apparel sizes?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stress and burnout and repetition in IT&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Finding billions of liters of lost water&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To utilize my yam, the application proposes a few dinners including a stew and a cook.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I decided to make them into vegetable burgers. I tell the application I have no dietary limitations, at that point tick off my fixings. Ultimately, it asks what flavors I may have.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In light of what I have ticked, my yam patties will likewise incorporate asparagus, aubergine, chickpeas, lemon squeeze and squashed up pecans. I include some flavoring and moved oats to tie them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They go into the stove for 15 minutes. The outcome is four overcooked, and emphatically oat-seasoned, plates.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Changes&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the point when I tell Mr Haase, he concedes that only one out of every odd formula is a triumph and furthermore concurs the formula presumably required more alternatives to tie the patties together.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After an hour, the stage has changed to alter for my input. I guarantee to attempt the formula once more.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightPLANT JAMMER&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture subtitle&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Haase (third from right) with the Plant Jammer group&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a prime participation accessible, which around 5% of clients pursue, paying for the running of the application.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plant Jammer likewise sells membership plans to stores, offering fixing options in contrast to their site plans.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So in the event that you need to make it veggie lover, gluten free or Thai we can modify any formula,&quot; says Mr Haase.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He trusts Plant Jammer will offer individuals the opportunity to ace less inefficient, veggie lover cooking.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;The most difficult way possible&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Indeed, even bundled food makers have gone to computerized reasoning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Expository Flavor Systems is a New York innovative work firm that utilizes AI to prompt food organizations on improving their items or making new ones, including drinks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Its AI stage Gastrograph can foresee the flavor, fragrance and surface a beverage would need to take into account any local food inclination.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;ve done this the most difficult way possible,&quot; says author Jason Cohen, who has gone through the previous 10 years running trials around the globe.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightBITSXBITES&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture inscription&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jason Cohen says recognition has an enormous impact in the flavor understanding&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Consistently, his board of 50 testers attempt diverse bundled food items a few times each day. Before Covid-19, they likewise had a voyaging group visiting an alternate nation every week to test provincial inclinations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What individuals taste is less significant than what they see when they taste, says Mr Cohen, a previous tea sommelier, who includes &quot;recognition is an exceptionally simple thing to play with&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;For instance, in the event that we include vanilla at around one section for every million to drain, you won&#39;t have the option to taste the vanilla, however you&#39;ll state that the milk is creamier and better,&quot; he clarifies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The man-made consciousness programming goes through several choices until it figures out how to foresee how great an item is going to taste - in light of what the item is intended to pose a flavor like, board testing and local tastes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Innovative choices&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Utilizing AI to discover new mixes of flavors for cupcakes and mixed drinks put Bristol-put together media office Tiny Giant with respect to the guide.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prime supporters Richard Norton and Kerry Harrison have utilized AI demonstrating to help make advertising occasions, promotion crusades and even gin names.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With Monker&#39;s Garkel gin, Tiny Giant&#39;s coders took care of a PC several distinctive gin names. The PC examined the examples so it could concoct its own.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightTINY GIANT&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture subtitle&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Okay let AI think of a name for your gin formula?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This sort of AI is known as a neural organization - when a PC makes one it will perceive an example, similar to &#39;what does a gin mark sound like or what goes into a cupcake?&#39; - and afterward settle on an innovative choice about it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After Tiny Giant&#39;s week by week AI mixed drink night got the consideration of bigger organizations, they were immersed with demands from enormous enterprises to have occasions with AI-produced mixed drinks and cupcakes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I didn&#39;t generally anticipate that this should turn into a thing where we would become food makers, however why not?&quot; says Mr Norton.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Astounded&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cookbook writer and gourmet expert Meera Sodha concurs the matching of AI and food can encourage exploration, innovativeness and manageability, yet says you can&#39;t &quot;cut off a formula from its story&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms Sodha was enlivened to master cooking after an excursion to Brick Lane with college companions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightDAVID LOFTUS&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture subtitle&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meera Sodha needed to record her family&#39;s plans for successors&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;My brilliant astute white companions asked me what they should arrange from the Indian curry house,&quot; she reviews. &quot;I was surprised that they believed that this Indian food was what I grew up eating.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the point when she figured out how to cook from her mom she had a further &quot;tremendous snapshot of frenzy&quot; when she found no family plans were recorded.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They would all kick the bucket with her in the event that she didn&#39;t make a record of them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;What I love about cooking the plans gathered from my mum, my grandmother or my auntie is that I feel associated with them when I cook that food in my kitchen,&quot; she says. &quot;I feel like they are there close by.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture inscription&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nell Mackenzie and Anne Mooney cook with a formula made up with man-made brainpower&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this soul, I endeavor the potato patties again yet this time with my mom Anne Mooney, a previous expert cook, over Skype.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, she inclines toward not to let the application reveal to her how to cook - utilizing it rather as a springboard for thoughts, especially the blend of chipotle, cilantro and pine nuts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We both dodge the oats and fry our patties.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They taste better, however I think this has more to do with our online party than our order of innovation.</p>', 'artificial intelligence', '_114081270_nellfood_1599772009.jpg', '2020-09-11 01:06:49', '2021-08-14 17:02:28'),
(375, 4, 7, 48, 'world-trade-organization-how-an-african-head-could-make-a-difference-1599772117', 'World Trade Organization: How an African head could make a difference', 0, '<p>With three of the eight possibility to turn into the following head of the World Trade Organization (WTO) originating from Africa, BBC Africa business supervisor Zawadi Mudibo takes a gander at what improvement having one of them in charge would make for the mainland.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a developing inclination among African ambassadors that somebody from the landmass ought to be in charge of one of the world&#39;s top monetary organizations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While an American has consistently driven the World Bank and an European has consistently been at the top of the International Monetary Fund, an African has never taken a proportional position.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, on the off chance that one from Nigeria&#39;s Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala, Kenya&#39;s Amina Mohamed or Egypt&#39;s Abdel-Hamid Mamdouh rises up out of the long choice cycle as the WTO&#39;s next chief general, the landmass can feel that it is playing comparable to the remainder of the world.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ladies in an article of clothing factoryIMAGE COPYRIGHTGETTY IMAGES&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionGarment processing plants, similar to this one in Kenya, could profit if exchange opened up&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The WTO sets the guidelines for worldwide exchange and mediates in exchange debates between countries. It is additionally, as per its site, expected to &quot;open exchange to support all&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Geneva-based association&#39;s capacity to get worldwide arrangements of essential rules that each nation joins to has been hamstrung as of late yet the WTO head has impact and a harasser platform. The chief general goes to G7 and G20 meeting and can expedite questions between world pioneers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, is there additional to be picked up for the mainland beside the strategic profile?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Exchange not help&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite the fact that the chief general&#39;s job is fundamentally one of a director, an African head could help guarantee that the interests of the mainland are considered in WTO exercises.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala quote box&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Exchange talks may appear to be exclusive and happen away from plain view, yet their result can influence everybody&#39;s lives.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From the little merchant who crosses a fringe a few times each month, to the customer purchasing an imported thing in a market, to somebody with a vocation in an assembling industry: they are totally influenced by the principles of exchange.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Africa, exchange is seen as a driver of development, a route towards supportable turn of events and as an apparatus for neediness annihilation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amina Mohamed quote box&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Unfamiliar guide won&#39;t do it for Africa. Like wherever else since the beginning it is exchange,&quot; says David Luke, top of the exchange strategy focus at the UN&#39;s Economic Commission for Africa.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So conventional Africans will comprehend that an African heading the WTO shows we are not kidding about exchange.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Africa-wide streamlined commerce zone&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms Okonjo-Iweala, a previous account serve, told the BBC that it was the normal African that she was generally worried about.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She said that she needed to &quot;make sense of how to get ladies and youth, who are behind these motors of development in Africa, to profit more from world exchange&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She was additionally quick to ensure that the mainland moves from trading crude materials and rather &quot;enhances the merchandise or items we produce for the worldwide market.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;For example, we import 94% of drugs on the mainland while we can create these locally in Africa.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ms Mohamed, who has filled in as both exchange and unfamiliar priest in Kenya, told the BBC that she can bring a &quot;new point of view&quot; that was &quot;expansive [and] comprehensive&quot; to the activity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, she would not like to be judged &quot;similarly as an African head or a lady chief, yet as an accomplished pioneer [and] an agreement developer&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abdel-Hamid Mamdouh quote&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On his part Mr Mamdouh, who has been haggling for Egypt at the WTO since 1985, said his huge involvement with the exchange body will empower him to perceive how it can enable the mainland to further.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;My plan for Africa is incorporate Africans more into the exchanging framework,&quot; he said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I will likewise call upon political pioneers in African nations to give specific consideration to their exchange approaches.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, verifiable in this answer is that however the WTO&#39;s chief general can campaign presidents, the person can&#39;t drive them to act with a specific goal in mind.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2px presentational dark line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Full rundown of possibility for WTO chief general:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mohammad Maziad Al-Tuwaijri - Saudi Arabia&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Liam Fox - UK&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jes&uacute;s Seade Kuri - Mexico&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abdel-Hamid Mamdouh - Egypt&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amina Mohamed - Kenya&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yoo Myung-hee - South Korea&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ngozi Okonjo-Iweala - Nigeria&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tudor Ulianovschi - Moldova&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2px presentational dark line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By and by, with regards to understanding Africa&#39;s huge exchange strategy - the African Continental Free Trade Agreement (AfCFTA) - the WTO head could assume a job.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The understanding, the usage of which has been deferred by Covid, wants to set up the world&#39;s biggest deregulation region.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This will guarantee all the more top notch items out of the landmass, along these lines, placing more cash in individuals&#39; pockets and assisting with destroying incessant destitution,&quot; exchange master Mr Luke said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>media captionCould streamlined commerce bargain be another first light for Africa?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The standards and points of the AfCTA are viable with those of the WTO, and an African chief of the exchange body could help steer it towards more help for the mainland. That could be in offering specialized assistance, exchange examination and strategy ability, transforming the fantasy of deregulation across Africa into the real world.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, similarly as Africa is currently moving towards a more liberated exchanging condition, the way of talking of protectionism in different pieces of the world gives off an impression of being on the ascent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Interceding US-China exchange column&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The exchange war between the US and China, and US President Donald Trump&#39;s America First strategies appear to reverse the situation against the confidence in deregulation. Limitations forced as a result of Covid have additionally influenced the free development of merchandise.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Road workmanship gives US President Donald Trump and Chinese President Xi Jinping wearing defensive cover and kissing at an area of the previous Berlin Wall.IMAGE COPYRIGHTGETTY IMAGES&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionTrade strains among China and the US have subverted moves towards less limited exchange&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Besides, the US&#39; refusal to endorse arrangements or re-arrangements to the WTO body that hears offers against the association&#39;s choices has tossed this key aspect of the exchange body into emergency. It additionally takes steps to subvert the WTO in general.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Its viability in setting up new guidelines that everything nations can concede to has likewise been tested. In 2001, the WTO dispatched the purported Doha round of talks, which should attract up new courses of action to help creating countries.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the dealings fizzled and were basically slaughtered off over 10 years after the fact.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the setting wherein the following chief of the association will get down to business in November.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Given that, the prompt assignment of the new chief general will be to support the WTO and reestablish confidence in the association.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It should be a decided figure paying little heed to where they are from. In the event that one of the three Africans prevails in the race to become WTO manager then endeavors to help the landmass may originator in the event that the person neglects to fortify the association.</p>', 'World Trade Organization', '_114273823_gettyimages-664721724_1599772117.jpg', '2020-09-11 01:08:37', '2021-08-14 22:42:56'),
(376, 4, 6, 93, 'the-women-behind-one-of-guccis-most-liked-insta-posts-1599772260', 'The women behind one of Gucci\'s most-liked Insta posts', 0, '<p>The BBC&#39;s week after week The Boss arrangement profiles diverse business pioneers from around the globe. This week we address Laura Johnson and Zoe Proctor, authors of Zebedee Management, an ability office that speaks to models and entertainers with physical and learning handicaps.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zoe Proctor and Laura Johnson were strolling along a sea shore when they concocted their business thought.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laura, who is the accomplice of Zoe&#39;s sibling, reviews how she was visiting her sister-in-law in 2017 during her maternity leave from her activity as a social laborer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightJAMES GREEN STUDIO&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture inscription&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zoe (left) and Laura concocted the thought while out strolling together&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We were having a visit and putting the world to rights, discussing the absence of portrayal of handicapped individuals in the media,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zoe, a model-turned-performing expressions instructor for impaired grown-ups, was stating that while her understudies &quot;were so capable and sharp&quot;, they confronted restricted chance. The ladies thought about how, without an ability organization, Zoe&#39;s understudies and other handicapped individuals, could ever get acting or demonstrating work. So they chose to set one up themselves.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It sounds messy, yet it resembled a light second,&quot; says Laura.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightDARREN BLACK&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture inscription&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zebedee now has in excess of 500 individuals on its books&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Work started the second they got back from the Lincolnshire shoreline. They named their organization after Zebedee, the character who skips on a spring in the much-adored kids&#39; TV program The Magic Roundabout.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As it were, he has his such a versatility needs, and is likewise such a truly upbeat, fun character,&quot; says Laura.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They messaged UK inability gatherings and set up web-based media records to interface with likely ability. Only three years after the fact, Zebedee now has in excess of 500 individuals on its books the world over.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightDARREN BLACK&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture subtitle&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zebedee speaks to customers with physical and learning inabilities&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After Laura and Zoe had made sure about their first customers in 2017, their next test was to procure a notoriety for being a confided in ability organization, as projecting chiefs are bound to work with specialists they realize they can depend on. Connections are everything.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We pounded on entryways and asked individuals to see our kin,&quot; says Zoe. &quot;Everybody thought, &#39;who are these ladies?&#39;&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With projecting chiefs posting position adverts on industry sites each day, portraying the look, age or sexual orientation required, Zoe and Laura likewise chose to put their customers forward for work whether inability was recorded in the promotion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;On the off chance that we sat tight for a call saying &#39;inability&#39;, we&#39;d have no positions,&quot; says Laura.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightJAMES GREEN STUDIO&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture inscription&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The sisters-in-law state they endeavored to improve known&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Their first advancement came when a customer was picked to show a lot of bright emergency clinic outfits. Somewhere in the range of 200 jobs were made sure about that first year, contrasted and 600 so far in 2020, regardless of the Covid pandemic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zebedee Management gathers a little level of the charge from each projecting, in accordance with industry principles of between 10-15%.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the point when they started the office, Laura and Zoe state they were frequently asked what might be their fantasy promoting effort for one of their customers to front. Laura, another mum at that point, yearned to see an infant with an incapacity on a nappy or child wipe advert. Zoe wanted to consider one to be their customers as the face speaking to a very good quality style brand.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This mid year, both they had always wanted worked out as expected.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In June, Ellie Goldstein, a 18-year-old from Essex, who has Down&#39;s disorder, included as the substance of a Gucci Beauty promoting association with Vogue Italia. The image Gucci put on Instagram, in which Ellie wore its Mascara L&#39;Obscur item, has been one of the brand&#39;s most mainstream presents on date, preferred by in excess of 863,000 individuals.</p>', 'Gucci\'s most-liked Insta posts', '_114208803_elliegoldsteinforguccibeautyandvogueitalia_davidpdhyde_1599772260.jpg', '2020-09-11 01:11:00', '2021-08-15 02:06:28'),
(377, 4, 6, 75, 'lloyds-bank-and-pizza-hut-cut-more-than-1000-jobs-1599772478', 'Lloyds Bank and Pizza Hut cut more than 1,000 jobs', 0, '<p>Lloyds Banking Group and Pizza Hut are the most recent firms to declare work cuts during the Covid pandemic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lloyds said it was eliminating 865 positions in zones, for example, protection and riches the executives as it resuscitated designs to rebuild the business.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Independently, Pizza Hut is wanting to close 29 eateries with the loss of 450 positions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The caf&eacute; network said it was essential for a salvage bargain &quot;to alleviate the budgetary effect of Covid-19&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A heap of organizations have declared positions cuts and terminations as shopper request has evaporated during the emergency.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>English bosses arranged in excess of 300,000 redundancies in June and July alone, as the nation slipped into its most honed downturn on record.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lloyds, which has around 65,000 workers, had cautioned of cuts in January yet put them hold until the harvest time because of the emergency.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Covid: 300,000 redundancies arranged in June and July&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While it is cutting posts, it additionally said it would make 226 jobs and would attempt to redeploy individuals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nonetheless, the Unite association said that it was stressed over representatives entering a positions market &quot;during exceptionally testing occasions&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The pandemic has exhibited the stunning versatility and adaptability of this workforce,&quot; said Unite public official Rob MacGregor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The business ought not zero in exclusively on reducing occupations and expenses however rather the bank ought to put resources into a workforce that has just demonstrated dependability, commitment and difficult work through the great occasions, and the awful.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Troublesome time&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pizza Hut said it had confronted &quot;noteworthy interruption&quot; from the pandemic and would need to close 29 of its 244 UK eateries. It didn&#39;t state which destinations would close.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It said the arranged cuts would leave it with 5,000 representatives.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Notwithstanding a speedy, Covid-safe returning, deals are not expected to completely bob back until well into 2021,&quot; it said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We comprehend this is a troublesome time for everybody included,&quot; it included.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Friendliness has been one of the parts hardest hit by the emergency, notwithstanding caf&eacute;s and bars getting a lift in August from the administration&#39;s Eat Out to Help Out plan.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A developing rundown of caf&eacute; networks have needed to declare terminations lately including Pizza Express, Byron Burger and Frankie and Benny&#39;s-proprietor the Restaurant Group.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Industry body UK Hospitality says around 33% of caf&eacute;s and bars have still not resumed in spite of the facilitating of lockdown, as individuals stay anxious about the spread of the infection.</p>', 'Pizza Hut', '_114298784_pizza-hut-lloyds_comp_getty-002_1599772478.jpg', '2020-09-11 01:14:38', '2021-08-17 14:50:19'),
(378, 4, 1, 84, 'coronavirus-transport-for-london-reveals-cost-of-pandemic-1599772740', 'Coronavirus: Transport for London reveals cost of pandemic', 0, '<p>Transport for London (TfL) said its promoting incomes plunged by 90% during the most testing monetary quarter in its 20-year history.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Covid-19 pandemic implied organizations dropped agreements to promote on the London Underground organization, TfL said in a money related report.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Managers said Covid had caused a &quot;calamitous effect&quot; on the business.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Huge changes to ventures, for example, Crossrail and the Northern Line expansion likewise impeded TfL&#39;s financial plans.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TfL distributed its first quarterly budgetary outcomes (Q1) on Thursday which has assessed its income from 1 April until 27 June.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Specialist at Oxford CircusIMAGE COPYRIGHTPA MEDIA&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionAt the stature of the pandemic TfL set up signs over the Underground notice individuals against unimportant travel&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Individual boarding busIMAGE COPYRIGHTAFP&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionCommuters utilizing London transports were told for a period in March and April to not pay admissions&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report by TfL boss fund official Simon Kilonback and gathering account chief Tony King, said the main quarter of the year had been &quot;the most trying for TfL in its history&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They included: &quot;The Covid pandemic has catastrophically affected our association, with the death toll of some of our partners, a serious decrease in traveler numbers and critical changes to our activities and task conveyance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The continuous vulnerability on the spread of the infection, which may affect future government direction on movement, and the effect of the pandemic on the UK economy makes estimating and planning significantly more troublesome.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Worker sanitiserIMAGE COPYRIGHTPA MEDIA&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionAround 800 sanitiser units have been set up over the London Underground organization to help lessen the spread of Coronavirus and different ailment causing germs&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Limits Green station closedIMAGE COPYRIGHTGETTY IMAGES&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionBounds Green was one of many Tube stations compelled to close as TfL cut back administrations in March&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lockdown limitations were refered to as the purpose behind brands dropping agreements as the &quot;publicizing crowd was eliminated&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It implied TfL just took in &pound;3m in promoting income in the initial three monetary months - in contrast with the past quarter, 1 January to 31 March, when publicizing income was &pound;47m.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report included: &quot;We have as of late began to see crowds return, and there has been some upward development in promoting salary.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We are working intimately with our publicizing accomplices to guarantee that, as the crowd returns securely to London in accordance with rising government guidance, we are in a situation to help the arrival of brands to our arrange and remake our income streams at the earliest opportunity.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Suburbanite on TubeIMAGE COPYRIGHTAFP&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionPassengers need to go with a cover when utilizing the Tube&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cylinder carriageIMAGE COPYRIGHTEPA&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionTfL said organizations and brands &quot;dropped&quot; advert contracts during the Covid pandemic&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report additionally demonstrated TfL took &pound;32m from the administration&#39;s leave of absence conspire for 6,542 representatives - around a fourth of its workforce.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In response to the pandemic in March, TfL needed to downsize administrations on the London Underground, close many Tube stations and change the manner in which key specialists boarded transports.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How London suburbanites are adjusting to new standards&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TfL leaves of absence 7,000 staff as budgetary hardships develop&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>London transport &#39;will run out of cash in weeks&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A crisis &pound;1.6bn bailout was concurred with the administration in May, however TfL said in its monetary report it needed to utilize &pound;600m of money holds in the initial two months of the episode.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The bailout &quot;was dependent upon various conditions&quot;, the report stated, &quot;counting expanding incomes, limiting costs, putting resources into strolling and burnning plans through the new Streetspace for London plan, and a quickened increase of administrations back to ordinary levels sooner than arranged&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The current government bailout will help uphold TfL&#39;s funds until 17 October.</p>', 'Coronavirus', '_114314792_061581208_1599772740.jpg', '2020-09-11 01:19:00', '2021-08-15 17:16:20');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(379, 4, 5, 49, 'huawei-to-shift-phones-to-its-own-harmony-operating-system-from-2021-1599772876', 'Huawei to shift phones to its own Harmony operating system from 2021', 0, '<p>Huawei has reported designs to pre-introduce its own Harmony working framework on its cell phones from one year from now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Chinese organization said it would likewise offer the product to different makers to use as an option in contrast to Android.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Huawei is presently the world&#39;s second top of the line handset-producer, after a short time in the best position.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, others have attempted and neglected to challenge Google and Apple&#39;s strength.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Google&#39;s Android represented 85.4% of cell phones dispatched a year ago, as indicated by research organization IDC, and Apple&#39;s iOS the staying 14.6%.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also, those figures mirror the reality Samsung&#39;s Tizen, Amazon&#39;s FireOS, Microsoft&#39;s Windows Phone, and Canonical&#39;s Ubuntu have all neglected to make progress on handsets.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Huawei&#39;s move has been incited by the reality it can not, at this point offer Google&#39;s applications and administrations on its most recent gadgets, in view of a US embargo - in spite of the fact that the limitation doesn&#39;t keep it from offering Android itself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Inside China - where purchasers don&#39;t utilize the Google Play store and a considerable lot of Google&#39;s administrations are hindered - this impediment has not caused Huawei issues.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, in different nations, interest for its latest telephones has been frail since Google&#39;s instruments are well known.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionSales of Huawei&#39;s P40 handsets have been moderately powerless outside of China due to their absence of Google applications&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One master said the destiny of the new working framework may rely upon what number of other innovation organizations Huawei persuaded to come ready.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This move will be upheld by the Chinese government since it fits into its more extensive Made In China 2025 technique,&quot; Marta Pinto, from IDC, said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Be that as it may, it will possibly take off somewhere else if other Chinese merchants, for example, Xiaomi and Oppo, embrace it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;And, after its all said and done, it will in any case be a test in geologies like Western Europe and Latin America, where endless individuals and organizations depend on Google&#39;s items.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two frameworks&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Huawei declared its arrangement toward the beginning of a three-day designer gathering close to the city of Shenzhen.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first form of Harmony OS was uncovered a year prior, when it was contributed for use smartwatches, TVs and other savvy home devices.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the organization presently expects to deliver a new form - Harmony OS 2.0 - that can be tried on handsets from December, in front of a proper dispatch in October 2021.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In equal, it will in a matter of seconds discharge EMUI 11 - an adaptation of its cell phone UI dependent on Android 11.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>EMUI 11IMAGE COPYRIGHTHUAWEI&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionHuawei says the new form of EMUI will make it simpler to utilize its telephones with two applications on screen without a moment&#39;s delay&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After October, a portion of its cell phone models will be offered with Harmony OS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, it will keep on offering EMUI as another option.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recode applications&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some portion of Huawei&#39;s test is it will require engineers to code their applications explicitly for Harmony if the product is to run locally and subsequently get the best presentation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The organization has shown it will be generally simple to recode applications previously composed for Android.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, this has demonstrated a staying point for other bombed working framework challengers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Designers either chose the additional work was not justified, despite any potential benefits or didn&#39;t focus on it, which means the applications commonly came up short on the most recent highlights accessible on Android and iOS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Included impetus&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Huawei has the building ability, the aspiration, and a home market advantage,&quot; Ben Wood, from the consultancy CCS Insight, said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;What&#39;s more, if the Chinese government got completely behind Harmony and made help for it a condition for different organizations to offer their items and administrations in the nation, that would give an additional impetus to Huawei to build up a third cell phone stage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In any case, regarding worldwide desires, history shows it&#39;s as yet a troublesome thing to accomplish.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Huawei faces other quick concerns.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From 15 September, the organization will be not able to get a greater amount of its Kirin processor chips fabricated, on account of further US exchange limitations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionWhile Huawei has developed loads of its own chips, it faces being not able to create further developed variants for future models&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Samsung and SK Hynix will not, at this point have the option to sell it memory chips.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Also, it has been accounted for Samsung and LG will be not able to keep selling it OLED shows for its cell phone screens.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Huawei has shown it has developed reserves of segments to overcome the short term.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, the destiny of its buyer division may lay on Washington changing its situation after the US presidential political decision.</p>', 'Huawei, operating system from 2021', '_114314532_harmony_1599772876.jpg', '2020-09-11 01:21:16', '2021-08-12 21:03:04'),
(380, 7, 6, 119, 'coronavirus-up-to-ps-35-billion-in-fraudulent-claims-or-incorrect-payments-hmrc-1599813244', 'Coronavirus: Up to  3.5 billion in fraudulent claims or incorrect payments  HMRC', 0, '<p><strong>Up to &pound; 3.5 billion in coronavirus storage systems could have been fraudulently billed or mistakenly paid, the government said.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>HM revenue and customs told lawmakers on the Public Finance Committee that 5-10% of the money paid had been misappropriated. The latest figures show the program has cost the government &pound; 35.4 billion to date. The system pays 80% of workers&#39; wages on leave from March up to a maximum of &pound; 2,500 per month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speaking to lawmakers, HMRC Permanent Secretary Jim Hara said on Monday, &quot;For our planning purposes, we have speculated that the error and fraud rate in this system could be between 5% and 10%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These range from deliberate scams to mistakes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Public Accounts Committee estimates a total of &pound; 30 billion in tax lost due to tax errors and fraud in 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both the Ministry of Finance and HMRC have been ordered to appear before lawmakers to explain how they intend to address the issue. &quot;In our risk assessment, we have said that we will not try to find employers who made legitimate mistakes in making their claims as this is clearly something new that everyone has to deal with at a very difficult time,&quot; said Mr Hara.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;While we expect employers to review their claims and pay excess amounts, our focus is on fighting abuse and fraud.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far, 8,000 calls have been made to the HMRC hotline. HMRC is currently handling 27,000 &quot;high-risk&quot; cases in which it believes serious errors had occurred in the numbers demanded by employers, he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Harra pointed out that any employees who feel that their employer has fraudulently requested money can report to HMRC by filling out a form on their website. &quot;While we are unable to establish a relationship between employees and employers, we can definitely claim back all grants that employers are not entitled to, including those they have not paid their employees as salaries.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the first time HMRC has spoken publicly about potential fraud affecting the coronavirus retention system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Swetha Ramachandran, investment manager for GAM Investments, told the BBC, &quot;The pace at which they want to accelerate this program is to ensure that it is available to employers to minimize potential damage.&quot; Caused means there is always a chance this will happen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So I don&#39;t think that&#39;s too surprising.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said other government programs, such as the loan abandonment program or the coronavirus business suspension system, could run into similar problems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Maybe it won&#39;t happen in a few months,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The think-tank says the government&#39;s bailout program is vulnerable to fraud because of the size of the package and the speed it takes to save people and businesses from economic collapse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The calculation is based on the level of fraud in government spending expected by the Cabinet and the Ministry of Manpower and Pensions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report said that actual fraud depreciation may be closer to the high end estimate &quot;due to higher than usual fraud rates associated with disaster management.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It states: &quot;This is a serious waste of public finances and requires sufficient resources to be allocated to post-event events to convince the public that every possible step has been taken to reduce the extent of this fraud.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A government spokesman at the time said he was asked to &quot;conduct a full review of incentives and support payments to detect fraud and win money back for taxpayers.&quot;</p>', 'Fraudulent claims, HMRC', 'HMRC_1599813244.jpg', '2020-09-11 12:34:04', '2021-08-17 15:52:57'),
(381, 7, 6, 81, 'british-negotiators-call-for-eu-realism-with-brexit-1599813389', 'British negotiators call for EU realism with Brexit', 0, '<p><strong>Britain&#39;s chief negotiator for Brexit is calling for &quot;realism&quot; from the EU ahead of the next round of trade talks, which begin in London.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lord Frost said there was &quot;still time&quot; for the two sides to agree on a post-Brexit trade deal next year. But he said the EU must recognize Britain&#39;s negotiating position from that of a &quot;sovereign state&quot;. His words followed Boris Johnson&#39;s promise to step down from talks if a deal was not reached by October 15.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The EU said it would &quot;do everything in its power to reach a deal with Britain&quot; but was &quot;ready&quot; for a no-deal scenario.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The swap also came after  10 announced it would introduce new customs laws in Northern Ireland if negotiations broke down. The announcement raised concerns from Brussels that Britain would fail to honor a withdrawal agreement reached before leaving the bloc in January.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the government said the law would only provide &quot;minor clarifications&quot; and committed to previous agreements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;A Thought Move in DUP&quot; by NI Protocol The new Brexit law will not &quot;violate&quot; the EU trade plan</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s the problem with the Brexit trade negotiations?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trade negotiations: what do the UK and the EU want?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The transitional period, during which Britain follows a number of EU regulations while the two countries try to negotiate a trade deal, ends on December 31.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the agreement is not signed and ratified by parliaments across Europe by then, Britain will begin trading with the bloc under World Trade Organization rules, which include tariffs. Critics fear this will hurt the economy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Johnson opposes extending the talks, and although the two sides have recently acknowledged little progress, he set a deadline for mid-October - when the Council of Europe is due to meet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an email to Conservative Party members on Monday, the Prime Minister said if an agreement is not reached by that date, &quot;then I don&#39;t see a free trade agreement between us and we have to accept it and move forward.&quot; .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Trested Land&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lord Frost, who has led Britain&#39;s negotiating team since March, will meet his European Union counterpart, Michel Barnier, Tuesday at the start of the eighth round of talks between the two countries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He was previously introduced as a fellow in the House of Lords after being honored by Johnson in July.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prior to meeting Mr. Barnier, Lord Frost promised &quot;to take home our clear message that we must move forward this week to reach an agreement on time&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lord Frost added: &quot;We have been talking for six months now and can no longer cross trodden land. We need to see more realism from the EU about our status as an independent nation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As we have done publicly and privately from the start, I will support our simple and sensible call for a free trade agreement based on an agreement previously signed by the European Union with like-minded people.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lord Frost said Britain had &quot;listened closely&quot; to the bloc team and &quot;hinted at flexibility&quot; regarding where to move, but added: &quot;We have repeatedly stated that a key element of our position stems from the foundation of time that the EU fully recognizes this reality. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said Britain had &quot;stepped up&quot; preparations for a no-deal result but also expressed hope that progress could be made this week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>European Commission spokesman Dan Ferry said the European Union had so far committed to talks &quot;constructively and in good faith&quot; and would be &quot;fully focused on getting the most out of this week&#39;s talks&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But while he said the bloc had &quot;Britain&#39;s desire to reach a deal quickly&quot;, it had to be &quot;in line with the EU&#39;s long-term economic and political interests&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Ferry added: &quot;The EU has made very constructive proposals to advance negotiations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;And Michel Barnier has often said that later this year the European Parliament and the Council should have enough time to discuss a deal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Whether or not a deal is reached by the end of the year, Britain&#39;s decision to leave the single market and customs unions is sure to create trade barriers to cross-border exchanges that no longer exist today.&quot;</p>', 'Realism, Brexit', 'Brecit Negotiation_1599813389.jpg', '2020-09-11 12:36:29', '2021-08-11 23:57:21'),
(382, 7, 6, 70, 'coronavirus-300000-redundancies-planned-in-june-and-july-1599813440', 'Coronavirus: 300,000 redundancies planned in June and July', 0, '<p><strong>British employers plan more than 300,000 layoffs in June and July when the coronavirus outbreak hits workplaces.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>1,784 companies plan to cut nearly 150,000 jobs in July, an increase of nearly seven times over July 2019. The number was obtained at the request of the BBC for Freedom of Information.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In June 1888, employers put forward plans to cut 156,000 jobs, a four-fold increase from the previous year. The coronavirus closures and the resulting record-breaking economic downturn have closed restaurants and shops and halted travel, forcing companies to downsize.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A government spokesman said he had protected 9.6 million jobs on a retention system and paid billions in loans and grants to thousands of companies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We continue to support livelihoods and income through our work plans to ensure nothing is left without hope or opportunity. This includes a &pound; 1,000 retention bonus for companies that can get employees back to work.&quot; , he says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;With our Kickstart program, we also created new roles for youth, created incentives for apprenticeship training and training, and supported and protected jobs in the tourism and hospitality sector through VAT cuts and last month&#39;s Eat Out to Help Out program.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boots, John Lewis, Marks &amp; Spencer, owner of Zizzi Azzurri, and furniture retailer DFS were among the household names announcing layoff plans for July. A survey found that every third company expects to lay off some employees between July and September.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What are my rights if I am released?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why is the unemployment rate nearing a 40 year low?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s new in the release schema?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Companies planning 20 or more layoffs within a &quot;company&quot; must by law notify the government via a form called HR1 which states how many jobs they wish to lose.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both the number of companies submitting reports and the number of risk positions indicate at an early stage that a large number of jobs are likely to be created in the coming months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The grant scheme, under which the government temporarily pays workers&#39; salaries, expired in October, raising fears that employers will have to cut more jobs by the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The reason this data is so useful is because there was a delay in presenting all other official data,&quot; said Nay Comineti, senior economist at the Resolution Foundation think tank.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This puts policymakers in a very challenging position. A huge government support program is coming to an end, but on official data we still don&#39;t know how big the jobs crisis is or where we are going when we enter the fall.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that the data, along with other company surveys and projections, show &quot;a rather bleak and consistent picture for the next few months&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employers planning fewer than 20 layoffs are not required to file notifications, so the number of planned layoffs will be higher than these figures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Official employment statistics, which are usually months behind what happens on the ground, still do not show a sharp increase in unemployment or layoffs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the government&#39;s Bureau of Budget Responsibility estimates that in the worst case scenario, unemployment could hit four million in the next year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Northern Irish businesses submitted form HR1 to the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency and are not included in these figures.</p>', 'Redundancies planned, coronavirus', 'redundancies_1599813440.jpg', '2020-09-11 12:37:20', '2021-08-11 23:58:35'),
(383, 7, 6, 95, 'patients-with-covid-19-need-a-treatment-program-said-the-doctor-1599813675', 'Patients with COVID-19 need a treatment program, said the doctor', 0, '<p><strong>According to experts on BBC Radio 4, File 4, stronger NHS support is needed for people who have been suffering from chronic Covid-19 symptoms for months.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Royal College of General Practitioners is calling on a national network of post-covid clinics to help such people.&nbsp; But less than 12% of the 86 NHS care groups surveyed and&nbsp;said they used the service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>NHS England said it was &quot;rapidly building new and strengthened rehabilitation centers&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tim Spector, professor of genetic epidemiology at King&#39;s College London and head of the Covid Symptom Study app, said about 300,000 people in the UK have reported symptoms that last more than a month - the so-called &quot;old covid&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that data from the app showed that around 60,000 people had been sick for more than three months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, many of these people may not have had a Covid test. &quot;I just want to get my life back.&quot; The government withdrew from community testing on March 12, instead testing only those who were hospitalized.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This means that people who have recovered from the suspected Corona virus at home cannot access the test.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How long will my recovery take?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ellie MacDonald, 37, from Surbiton, was training for the London Marathon when she first developed symptoms of Covid on March 21.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She has been suffering from shortness of breath and severe fatigue for more than five months, but has yet to receive a positive test result - because community testing was introduced late to detect her illness.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He changed his practice as a general practitioner after initially feeling helpless.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ellie said, &quot;Just knowing I actually have people who take me seriously - that&#39;s so important to my recovery. I just want my life back.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Paul Garner, professor at Liverpool School of Tropical Medicine, has been suffering from Covid since March 19 and believes some patients distrust health care professionals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think the evidence lies in our symptoms and our stage in the epidemic,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We need sensible guidelines that really help society. The government is not doing enough with existing medical expertise. It needs to be ordered and put together to work together.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In File 4, all 212 Clinical Commissioning (CCG) groups and health councils in the UK are asked whether they have set up a post-Covid clinic for patients who have not been hospitalized with the virus - but who have not necessarily tested positive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10 out of 86 respondents stated that they had operated the facility. Another 16 said they were planning or redesigning the service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many patients are seen by a general practitioner or existing service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/CE30/production/_114248725_emacdonald1.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Martin Marshall, General Practitioner and Chair of the Royal College of General Practitioners, said, &ldquo;We know, without a doubt, that there will be an increasing number of people who will have significant and disturbing Covid symptoms in the long term.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;A small portion, but generally a lot, need expert advice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So we really need to see more and more clinics after Covid.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The NHS UK&#39;s new Your Covid Recovery website offers personalized support for all patients recovering from Covid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lynn Turner Stokes, professor of rehabilitation medicine at King&#39;s College London, said there were some &quot;good resources&quot; but &quot;we still have a lot to do&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said, &quot;For a person who has never been to a hospital, no one has really checked their lungs, heart, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It would be very useful if we had more services at one (face-to-face) counter.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Personal rehabilitation</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The UK government and the UK NHS say there will be new and strengthened rehabilitation and non-profit centers in every part of the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Wales, community rehabilitation programs and specialists are most likely the forum for covid treatment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Northern Ireland&#39;s Ministry of Health is currently assessing the needs of Covid patients who have left hospital to highlight future work, while Scotland is planning &quot;high-quality, personality-centered rehabilitation in a variety of settings&quot;.</p>', 'Treatment Prog', 'Covid_1599813675.jpg', '2020-09-11 12:41:15', '2021-08-16 15:57:17'),
(384, 7, 15, 127, 'diana-rigg-the-star-of-the-avengers-and-game-of-thrones-died-at-the-age-of-82-1599898997', 'Diana Rigg, the star of The Avengers and Game of Thrones, died at the age of 82', 0, '<p><strong>Diana Rigg, a British actress who became a style icon as secret agent Emma Peel in the 1960s TV series The Avengers and later starred in Game of Thrones, has passed away. He is 82 years old.</strong><br />\r\nRig agent Simon Beresford said he died at his family home early Thursday. Rigg&#39;s daughter Rachel Stirling said she died of cancer, which she diagnosed in March.<br />\r\nRigg &quot;spent his final months happily thinking about his extraordinary life, filled with love, laughter and deep pride in his work. I will miss him,&quot; said Stirling.<br />\r\nIn &quot;The Avengers&quot; she plays Emma Peel, assistant to secret agent John Steed, played by Patrick McNee. The pair are a well-dressed duo who fights bad guys and swaps tricks on shows whose combination of adventure and humor makes a lasting impact.<br />\r\n&quot;Why do you think Mrs. Peel was hugged like her?&quot; Anthony Mason of CBS News asked Rigg in 2018.<br />\r\n&quot;Because he was ahead of time,&quot; said Rigg. &quot;Because he is very smart, capable, funny, sexy, and independent.&quot;<br />\r\nThe British series turned Riga into an international sensation.<br />\r\n&quot;Sexy, resourceful and confident - with deadly self-defense knowledge - Rigg&#39;s character has become an icon of the growing feminist movement,&quot; the BBC wrote on Thursday. &quot;His fascination with girls combined with his hoarse voice - the result of his 20-day smoking habit - also won him a lot of male fans.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/10/c2b46ccc-dbf6-4653-b225-3243d7179147/thumbnail/620x450/b14acd74b7e78ed6aafac813846a7435/rigg.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nRigg also starred in the 1967 James Bond thriller &quot;On Her Majesty&#39;s Secret Service&quot; as the only woman ever married to Agent 007.<br />\r\nShe then played Elena Tyrell on Game of Thrones.<br />\r\n&quot;I am very happy with young people who identify with the naughty old bag I played with,&quot; he told Mason about his Game of Thrones character.<br />\r\nRigg also played Duchess von Bucklich in Victoria and starred as her daughter in British sitcoms Detector.<br />\r\nRigg spent several years in the 1960s as a member of the Royal Shakespeare Company, combining screen work with famous stage careers in plays including Mrs. Bertolt Brecht&#39;s Courage and Tom Stoppards Jumpers at the National Theater in London.<br />\r\nStoppard said Rigg was &quot;the most beautiful woman in the room, but she used to be called a jumpsuit.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;He works for everyone with his sleeves rolled up and smiling. His talent is brilliant.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/10/a5d51311-ff24-405f-ba3e-7319ac6d464b/thumbnail/620x413/4dce809fbfb6990f014887557e0dbe00/gettyimages-830958172.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>', 'Diana Rigg, Died', 'Diana Rigg_1599816820.jpg', '2020-09-11 13:33:40', '2021-08-17 18:45:14'),
(385, 7, 10, 99, 'nfl-in-uncharted-territory-as-the-new-season-begins-against-the-backdrop-of-the-pandemic-1599817156', 'NFL in uncharted territory as the new season begins against the backdrop of the pandemic', 0, '<p><strong>The NFL hopes America is ready for football. The new season starts Thursday night in Kansas City. Fans are being asked to follow social distancing guidelines amid the coronavirus pandemic.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is America&#39;s biggest sporting test since the pandemic began: the Super Bowl champions welcome the Texans to a game that puts the NFL into uncharted territory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s a unique year and we all know it. We believe in protocol,&quot; said head coach Andy Reed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nearly 17,000 spectators will perform at the 76,000 capacity stadium. Masks are required for ticket holders. There will be no cheerleaders or talismans in the field.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We believe it&#39;s much safer than going to a bar or having several people in your house,&quot; said Dr. Rex Archer, Kansas City Health Director.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/10/e1fac713-42df-429b-9b1c-469bce5cdae3/thumbnail/620x413/89e959f64a107211d3abc9ed03c7c388/gettyimages-1271793048.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nPandemic bubbles - like those used by the NBA - have never been taken seriously by the NFL.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I believe the precautions they are taking are completely legal,&quot; said Marian Mackenzie of Kansas City. &quot;I&#39;m just for myself as a person who gets sick easily - I chose not to.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And there will be a seismic shift on the ground in the racial equality and social justice movement. Peaceful protests are expected ahead of the match and players can now send messages of support. At one end of the end zone of Arrowhead Stadium, the inscription &quot;End Racism&quot; can be seen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are many trips on Thursday. In a few weeks, the COVID-19 figures will show whether safety measures are effective here.</p>', 'NFL, UNcharted territory, pandemic', 'NFL_1599817156.jpg', '2020-09-11 13:39:16', '2021-08-18 01:56:35'),
(386, 7, 3, 77, 'ronald-halis-bell-co-founder-of-kool-the-gang-died-at-the-age-of-68-1599817465', 'Ronald \"Halis\" Bell, co-founder of Kool & the Gang, died at the age of 68', 0, '<p><strong>Ronald &quot;Halis&quot; Bell, co-founder, singer and producer of Kool &amp; the Gang, has passed away. He is 68 years old.</strong><br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nBell died Wednesday morning at his home in the US Virgin Islands with his wife next door, said journalist Sujta Murty. The cause of death was not reported.&nbsp;Kool &amp; the Gang emerged from jazz roots in the 60s and developed into one of the main bands of the 70s, mixing jazz, funk, R&amp;B, and pop. After a brief decline, the band made a comeback in the 1980s.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nBell formed a band with his brother Robert &quot;Cole&quot; Bell along with Dennis &quot;D.T.&quot; Thomas, Robert &quot;Spike&quot; Mykens, Charles Smith, George Brown, and Ricky West.&nbsp;Kool &amp; the Gang won a 1978 Grammy for the soundtrack work Saturday Night Fever. The band received the BET Soul Train Lifetime Achievement Award in 2014 and entered the Songwriting Hall of Fame four years later.&nbsp;<br />\r\nAs a self-taught musician, Bell created his own signature sound with a line of horns, basses and synthesizers.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nBell wrote and composed some of the band&#39;s best songs, including &quot;Holiday&quot;, &quot;Cherry&quot;, &quot;Jungle Buggies&quot; and &quot;Summer Madness,&quot; which have been used in several films including &quot;Rocky&quot; and &quot;Baby Boy&quot;. The song was also used in a 2006 Nike shoe advertisement starring LeBron James.<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nBell is working on a number of collaborations, including the Kool Baby Brotha Band solo initiative. He also has plans to create an animated short film series called &quot;Kool TV&quot; for their childhood and career.</p>', 'Ronald, Kool and Gang, died', 'Kool_1599817465.jpg', '2020-09-11 13:44:25', '2021-08-12 21:06:21'),
(387, 7, 3, 70, 'microsoft-will-release-the-xbox-series-x-on-november-10-just-before-the-holidays-1599818956', 'Microsoft will release the Xbox Series X on November 10, just before the holidays', 0, '<p><strong>The battle for video game consoles is heating up. According to Microsoft, the new Xbox Series X will cost $ 500 and will hit the market on November 10 before the holidays.</strong><br />\r\nThere has been no new generation of video game consoles for several years. The newest Xbox, Xbox One, was released in 2013, as was Sony&#39;s PlayStation 4. The shortened version, Xbox Series S, costs $ 300 and is available at the same time. Pre-orders for both consoles will begin on September 22. The console will launch without Halo Infinite, 343 Industries&#39; exclusive product, which was recently postponed to 2021, according to Media<br />\r\nRetailers like Amazon and Walmart and others have created landing pages for the X Series. In addition to the initial features, you can subscribe to many mailing lists that will ping you as soon as the official order window opens.<br />\r\nOf course, you can find the latest specs, announced game titles and other details on the recently redesigned controllers, which offer improvements to existing ergonomics and add-ons, on the Microsoft Xbox Series X homepage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New video games at launch included Assassin&#39;s Creed Valhalla, Gears Tactics, Dirt 5, and Watch Dogs Legion. Rival Sony is expected to announce pricing soon for its PlayStation 5.</p>', 'Microsoft, Xbox Series', 'X-box_1599818956.jpg', '2020-09-11 14:09:16', '2021-08-14 10:22:06'),
(388, 7, 15, 116, 'alec-and-hilaria-baldwin-welcomed-their-fifth-baby-1599898988', 'Alec and Hilaria Baldwin welcomed their fifth baby', 0, '<p><strong>The growing Baldwin family has just welcomed a new member. Alec and Hilaria Baldwin welcome their fifth child, a boy the podcast host announced on Instagram on Wednesday.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We had a baby last night. She is perfect and we couldn&#39;t be happier,&quot; wrote Hilaria Baldwin, 36. &quot;Look for a name.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Baldwins are now parents to 6 year old Carmen, 5 year old Rafael, 3 year old Leonardo, and 2 year old Romeo. Alec Baldwin is also an Irish father, 24, with his ex-wife Kim Basinger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nHilaria Baldwin announced on Instagram in April that she and her husband were expecting their fifth baby. Yoga instructors are also open to two abortions, according to Entertainment Tonight - one in April 2019 and one in November.<br />\r\nIn November, he shared a video of his daughter Carmen comforting him. &quot;We are very sad to hear today that our baby has died at 4 months of age,&quot; she wrote in an Instagram post. &quot;We also want you to know that we are fine, even though we are not in good shape at the moment. We are very lucky with our 4 healthy babies - and we will never forget it. I have it, Carmen said and I take it so I can. send it. &quot;from Alec. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The post came after Baldwin said on his Instagram Stories that he was nervous about meeting him that day. After Baldwin shared her fights, she continued to use social media to tell fans about her recent pregnancy. His post about the new boy drew comments from many celebrities on Wednesday.</p>', 'Alec and Hilaria, Fifth Baby', 'Alec Baldwin_1599819562.jpg', '2020-09-11 14:19:22', '2021-12-19 17:39:16'),
(389, 7, 3, 76, 'the-ellen-degeneres-show-set-a-release-date-and-yes-well-talk-about-it-he-said-1599824190', 'The Ellen DeGeneres show set a release date. \"And yes, we\'ll talk about it,\" he said', 0, '<p>The Ellen DeGeneres show returns on September 21 after accusations of misconduct and a toxic work environment and the dismissal of three top producers following an internal investigation. DeGeneres announced the return of his show in a statement received by CBS News on Wednesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I can&#39;t wait to get back to work and get back to our studio. And yes, we will talk about it,&quot; DeGeneres said in a statement. DeGeneres filmed their show from home while under quarantine. The new season, Season 18, begins with guests at Tiffany Hadish Studios. The premiere week will also include Kerry Washington, Alec Baldwin, Chrissy Teigen, Chris Rock, Amy Schumer, Adam Sandler and Orlando Bloom, the statement said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Resident DJ Stephen &quot;tWitch&quot; Boss will also host an upcoming episode of the show this fall. The boss has welcomed guests, the statement said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boss has been appointed as the show&#39;s executive producer, WarnerBros&#39; representative, following last month&#39;s alleged misconduct. confirmed by email to CBS News. This isn&#39;t the only change made after multiple employees made allegations of abuses and a toxic work environment, first reported by BuzzFeed News.<br />\r\nSpeaking in August, a Warner Bros. spokesman confirmed to CBS News that top producers Ed Glavin, Kevin Lehmann and Jonathan Norman had split from the show.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an article published July 16, BuzzFeed News spoke with one employee and ten former employees of the show who accused &quot;racism, fear and bullying&quot; at work. In the second article on July 30, multiple allegations of sexual harassment were made against Glavin, Lehmann and Norman.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an email to CBS News on July 31, Lehmann said the BuzzFeed News article was &quot;full of false claims&quot; and &quot;emphatically&quot; denies &quot;any form of sexual indecency.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a statement to CBS News following his dismissal in August, Leman&#39;s attorney said, &quot;The fact that the BuzzFeed article was so flawed resulted in an innocent man leaving is shocking.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Glavin and Norman did not respond to requests for comment from CBS News. Norman denied all charges against him in a statement to BuzzFeed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While DeGeneres has not publicly considered allegations of misconduct in his broadcast, he did respond to allegations of racism and toxicity in a July 30 letter to his CBS News staff. In the letter, DeGeneres said he hoped the show would be a &quot;place of happiness&quot; where everyone was &quot;treated with respect&quot; and &quot;disappointed to learn&quot; that it was &quot;not&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DeGeneres said in his July letter, &quot;My name is on the show and everything we do, and I am responsible for it ... As we grow exponentially, I can&#39;t control everything and depend on other people to do their job.&quot; because they know that I want to end it. Obviously some don&#39;t. &quot;&quot;</p>', 'Ellen Degeneres, Show Date Releases', 'Ellen DeGeneres_1599824190.jpg', '2020-09-11 15:36:30', '2021-08-16 04:13:37');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(390, 7, 11, 168, 'oscar-announced-a-new-look-and-containment-requirements-for-best-picture-1599897334', 'Oscar announced a new look and containment requirements for Best Picture', 0, '<p>In recent years, the Oscars have come under fire for a lack of nominations in their category. However, on Tuesday, the Academy of Arts and Sciences for Feature Film announced that films must now meet new performance and inclusion standards in order to be nominated for Best Picture - one of the Big Five categories at the annual event - #OscarsSoWhite is a trend making the past.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe new standards are part of the Academy Aperture 2025 initiative and are intended to &quot;promote equal on-screen and off-screen performance to better reflect the diversity of film audiences,&quot; said a statement from the academy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like previous years, the 2020 Oscars have been criticized for being underrepresented. Film critic Justin Chang noted that the nominees felt &quot;in many ways a return to a kind of white male nostalgia.&quot; While about a third of the nominees were women, there were no female nominees for best director, and only one black male was nominated for one of the acting categories.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Changes will begin gradually with the 94th Oscar in 2022. For the 94th and 95th ceremonies, secret standard forms for inclusion must be sent to the Academy in order for each film to qualify for the best picture. , but not necessarily up to a certain standard during these years. Starting in 2024, films must meet two of the four newly established standards to win best film.<br />\r\nThe Academy says this standard does not apply to other categories.&nbsp; News has also been notified that the terms and conditions will be reviewed annually and may change in the future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The standards for the academy are as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>STANDARD A: SCREEN REPRESENTATION, TOPICS AND NARRATIVE<br />\r\nTo achieve Standard A, the film must meet one of the following criteria:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A1. Main or important supporting actor</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At least one of the main or supporting actors comes from an underrepresented race or ethnic group.<br />\r\n&bull; Asia<br />\r\n&bull; Spanish / Latinx<br />\r\n&bull; Black / African American<br />\r\n&bull; Indigenous / Indian / Indigenous peoples from Alaska<br />\r\n&bull; Middle East / North Africa<br />\r\n&bull; Locals of Hawaiians or other Pacific islands<br />\r\n&bull; Other under-represented races or ethnicities</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A2. The main ensemble</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At least 30% of all supportive and supportive actors come from at least two of the following underrepresented groups:<br />\r\n&bull; women<br />\r\n&bull; Race or ethnic group<br />\r\n&bull; LGBTQ +<br />\r\n&bull; People with cognitive or physical disabilities, or are deaf or deaf</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A3. Main story / topic</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The main plot line, theme or narrative of the film focuses on one or more underrepresented groups.<br />\r\n&bull; women<br />\r\n&bull; Race or ethnic group<br />\r\n&bull; LGBTQ +<br />\r\n&bull; People with cognitive or physical disabilities, or are deaf or deaf</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nSTANDARD B: CREATIVE LEADERSHIP AND PROJECT TEAM<br />\r\nTo achieve Standard B, the film must meet ONE of the following criteria:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B1. Creative management and department heads</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At least two of the following creative management positions and department heads - casting director, cameraman, composer, costume designer, director, editor, hairstylist, makeup artist, producer, production designer, set designer, voice, VFX supervisor, writer - belong to the group. the following are underrepresented:<br />\r\n&bull; women<br />\r\n&bull; Race or ethnic group<br />\r\n&bull; LGBTQ +<br />\r\n&bull; People with cognitive or physical disabilities, or are deaf or deaf</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At least one of these positions must belong to the following underrepresented races or ethnic groups:<br />\r\n&bull; Asia<br />\r\n&bull; Spanish / Latinx<br />\r\n&bull; Black / African American<br />\r\n&bull; Indigenous / Indian / Indigenous peoples from Alaska<br />\r\n&bull; Middle East / North Africa<br />\r\n&bull; Locals of Hawaiians or other Pacific islands<br />\r\n&bull; Other under-represented races or ethnicities</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B2. Another key role</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At least six crew / crew and other technical positions (excluding production personnel) are from under-represented racial or ethnic groups. These positions include, but are not limited to, First AD, Gaffer, Script Supervisor, and others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>B3. Number of crew<br />\r\nAt least 30% of film crews came from the following underrepresented groups:<br />\r\n&bull; women<br />\r\n&bull; Race or ethnic group<br />\r\n&bull; LGBTQ +<br />\r\n&bull; People with cognitive or physical disabilities, or are deaf or deaf</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nSTANDARD B: ACCESS AND OPPORTUNITY IN INDUSTRY<br />\r\nTo achieve Standard C, the film must meet both of the following criteria:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C1. Paid internships and internship opportunities</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Film distribution or finance companies pay for internships or apprentices that are from the following underrepresented groups and who meet the following criteria:<br />\r\n&bull; women<br />\r\n&bull; Race or ethnic group<br />\r\n&bull; LGBTQ +<br />\r\n&bull; People with cognitive or physical disabilities, or are deaf or deaf</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Big studios / distributors must have extensive and ongoing paid internships / internships involving under-represented groups (including racial or ethnic groups) in most of the following departments: Production / Development, Physical Production, Post Production, Music, VFX, Acquisition, Business, sales, marketing and advertising affairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Independent or mini-sized studios / distributors must have at least two trainees from the above underrepresented group (at least one from an underrepresented racial or ethnic group) in at least one of the following departments: production / development, physical production, post-production, music , VFX, acquisitions, business affairs, sales, marketing and advertising.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>C2. Training and skills development opportunities (crew)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Film production, distribution and / or finance companies provide training and / or job skills development opportunities under the guidance of people from the following under-represented groups:<br />\r\n&bull; women<br />\r\n&bull; Race or ethnic group<br />\r\n&bull; LGBTQ +<br />\r\n&bull; People with cognitive or physical disabilities, or are deaf or deaf<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>STANDARD D: AUDIENCE DEVELOPMENT<br />\r\nTo achieve the D standard, the film must meet the following criteria:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>D1. Representation in marketing, advertising and sales</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nStudios and / or film companies have a number of in-house executives from the following underrepresented groups (must include people from underrepresented racial or ethnic groups) in their marketing, advertising, and / or sales teams.<br />\r\n&bull; women<br />\r\n&bull; Race or ethnic group</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Asia<br />\r\nSpanish / Latinx<br />\r\nBlack / African American<br />\r\nIndigenous / Indian / Native peoples from Alaska<br />\r\nMiddle East / North Africa<br />\r\nA local Hawaiian or other Pacific islander<br />\r\nOther underrepresented races or ethnicities<br />\r\n&bull; LGBTQ +<br />\r\n&bull; People with cognitive or physical disabilities, or are deaf or deaf</p>', 'Oscar, Best Pictures', 'Oscars_1599825654.jpg', '2020-09-11 16:00:54', '2021-08-18 04:31:35'),
(391, 7, 3, 67, 'the-final-season-of-keeping-up-with-the-kardashians-will-air-next-year-the-family-said-1599826829', 'The final season of \"Keeping up with the Kardashians\" will air next year, the family said', 0, '<p><strong>Fans will soon find another way to deal with one of America&#39;s most famous families. The 20th and final season of &quot;Keeping Up with the Kardashians&quot; will air early next year, the family said on social media on Tuesday.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;After 14 years, 20 seasons, hundreds of episodes and many individual shows, we are very grateful to everyone who has watched us over the years - good times, bad times, happiness, tears and lots of relationships and children&quot;, he says. the family publishes a joint statement on social media. &quot;We will forever keep fond memories and of the many people we met along the way.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The statement listed the names of the famous &quot;momager&quot; Chris Jenner and the sons Courtney, Kim, Chloe and Rob Kardashian. and Kendall and Kylie Jenner. Kourtney&#39;s former partner and father of three, Scott Disick, was also included in the announcement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The decision to &quot;say goodbye&quot; to Hit E! The show was created &quot;as a family,&quot; said the statement. The family also thanks everyone who attended the long performance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Without following the Kardashians, I wouldn&#39;t be where I am today,&quot; wrote Kim. &quot;This show made us who we are and I will forever be indebted to everyone who has shaped our careers and forever changed our lives.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reality show premiered on October 14, 2007, according to Entertainment Tonight, and helped kickstart the career and business empire of the Kardashians and Jenner families. The show&#39;s success resulted in 12 spin-off series and plenty of pop culture moments as it often recounts the extravagant daily lives of siblings and their growing family.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The show&#39;s 19th season returns on September 17th.</p>', 'Keeping up with Kardashians, Final season', 'Final season_1599826829.jpg', '2020-09-11 16:20:29', '2021-08-16 17:35:30'),
(392, 7, 3, 61, 'mulans-trend-to-boycott-on-twitter-after-the-loan-shows-the-areas-of-china-where-the-film-was-shot-1599827050', 'Mulan\'s trend to boycott on Twitter after the loan shows the areas of China where the film was shot', 0, '<p><strong>&quot;Mulan&#39;s Boycott&quot; trended on Twitter after the film was released live on streaming service Disney + on Friday. Many critics pointed to the end of the film thanks to the Chinese Communist Party&#39;s Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region Committee.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the United Nations, more than 1 million Chinese Uighur Muslims have been detained in state internment camps in the Xinjiang region. China calls its detention camps in Xinjiang Province a &quot;re-education institution&quot; for fighting extremism and separatism in the region. The US Congressional Executive Committee on China described it as &quot;the largest mass shutdown of the world&#39;s current minority population&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The US State Department for Human Rights has reported detailed cases of torture, sexual assault, repressive surveillance, the forced consumption of pork and alcohol (both of which are prohibited for devout Muslims), confiscation of chickens, and even death in cemeteries in Xinjiang camps since 2018.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The film&#39;s production designer, Grant Major, revealed in a recent interview with Architectural Digest that his team had spent months &quot;in and around northwestern Xinjiang Province.&quot; Many have now criticized the director for making films in areas linked to widespread human rights abuses.<br />\r\n&quot;Mulan especially thanks the advertising department of the CPC Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Community Commission for its credit. You know, the site of the cultural genocide,&quot; writer Janet Ng wrote in the tweet. &quot;You take a lot of pictures in Xinjiang, which the subtitles calls Northwest China.&quot;<br />\r\nNg said his message was not about the &quot;police&quot; seeing the films people watch, but rather about encouraging viewers to act: &quot;[W] your agent&#39;s ritual (if any), read this Trouble, let&#39;s say you sign a petition to your friends, write a sign for the next protest you follow, another boycott, &rdquo;he tweeted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another reviewer on Twitter said the film&#39;s credits were included thanks to the Xinjiang Turpan Public Security Bureau. &quot;This particular public security bureau is deeply involved in the Xinjiang concentration camps,&quot; wrote B. Alan Embryman in a report from Axios China.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The United States added the Turpan Municipal Public Security Bureau to its list of export regulators for &quot;involvement in human rights abuses and abuses in the conduct of China&#39;s campaign against oppression, arbitrary mass detention, forced labor, and high-tech surveillance of Uighurs.&quot; Kazakhs and other members of the Muslim minority in the Xinjiang Uighur Autonomous Region. &quot;<br />\r\nOther critics have posted comments from film star Liu Yifei, who posted on Chinese social media site Weibo last year that she supports Hong Kong police. Hong Kong police are accused of using harsh tactics against demonstrators who took to the streets violating new &quot;national security&quot; laws imposed by China&#39;s central government in the region.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hundreds of protesters have rallied since protests first erupted last year sparked by a bill that would weaken the region&#39;s independent judiciary.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hong Kong activist Joshua Wong has posted heavily on Twitter about Mulan, citing Liu&#39;s comments and Xinjiang region productions as reasons for boycotting the film.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s getting worse! Now you see #Mulan, you are not only blocking police brutality and racial injustice (based on what key players are advocating for), but you may be involved in the mass closure of Uyghur Muslims,&quot; he tweeted.</p>', 'Mulans Trend, Boycott', 'Boycott Mulan_1599827050.jpg', '2020-09-11 16:24:10', '2021-08-17 18:32:03'),
(393, 7, 15, 111, 'record-motorbike-racer-ralph-hudson-died-after-having-an-accident-at-a-speed-of-40-km-h-1599898979', 'Record motorbike racer Ralph Hudson died after having an accident at a speed of 40 km / h', 0, '<p><strong>Ralph Hudson, a 69-year-old motorcycle veteran, died Sunday of complications from an injury he sustained on August 14 when he crashed his motorcycle while traveling at a speed of 40 km / h. At the time, Hudson was trying to set a speed record at Salt Bonneville Salt Apartments.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I must destroy our racing community with heartbreak because Ralph Hudson died of his injuries last night in Bonneville on August 14,&quot; the Southern California Association said on Facebook.<br />\r\nThe association announced that Hudson was being treated by an on-site medical team and taken to Intermountain Medical Center in Salt Lake City.<br />\r\n&quot;We are extremely grateful to everyone for their kind words, prayers and support during this very difficult time,&quot; continued the Southern California statement. &quot;Ralph wants everyone to stay strong and move fast.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hudson holds several speed records and has even hit 300 miles per hour in a Bonneville salty apartment in the past, according to Desert News. Pat McDowell, vice president of the Southern California Association, told Deseret News that Hudson was a legend in the competition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Nice guy,&quot; McDowell told Hudson. &quot;Great athlete and innovator. One of our sports legends ... I&#39;ll miss him.&quot;</p>', 'Palph Hudson, Record Motorbiker', 'Ralph_1599827250.jpg', '2020-09-11 16:27:30', '2021-12-19 17:39:03'),
(394, 7, 3, 63, 'father-and-son-help-nonprofits-serve-food-with-human-kindness-1599827799', 'Father and son help nonprofits serve food with human kindness', 0, '<p>From 8 a.m. to 11 a.m., Keith shares brunch meals - food for the body and soul - while remembering his golden rules and beliefs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He wouldn&#39;t be mad at me if I didn&#39;t do what I had to,&quot; Brunch said to his son Keith, pointing to God and sorting the food.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This branch works with Kids Bring Life - a non-profit organization whose goal is to feed children who are food insecure. However, with the coronavirus pandemic and a stalled economy, millions of families are dependent on food, and Kids Bring Life is starting to feed all children, young and old.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;People are trying to figure out how to support their families and feed their children,&quot; Brunch said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lunch and his 15 year old son distributes 50 meals a day, five days a week. This non-profit organization has 40 locations in Dallas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/08/d435c357-8aa9-42aa-9a62-bfd402bac943/thumbnail/620x349/47e942dd2c214d11a9915db798b322bd/0908-en-villarreal2.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>CBS News spoke with Janelle Hicks, Operations Manager at Kids Bring Life, and asked how much food was prepared each day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We make about 2-3,000 a day,&quot; said Hicks. &quot;Obviously there is an increase. I see a lot more people just being grateful. Some people who use money for bills don&#39;t need to use it anymore for groceries.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I feel really good. It seems like there are people who really care about each other,&quot; said one grocery recipient.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coronavirus has taken a lot out of so many things, but it has given Brunch and her son the opportunity to practice what she preaches - by doing things to others that require a dose of human kindness and love.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You never know who you&#39;re going to touch,&quot; Brunch said. &quot;And if you just believe that God brought you here for a reason, you will inspire someone.&quot;</p>', 'NonProfit, Food, Father & Son', 'Non profit_1599827799.jpg', '2020-09-11 16:36:39', '2021-08-17 09:26:51'),
(395, 7, 3, 104, 'golden-girls-was-reworked-by-black-actors-such-as-tracy-ellis-ross-and-regina-king-1599828026', '\"Golden Girls\" was reworked by black actors such as Tracy Ellis Ross and Regina King', 0, '<p>The all-black cast special &quot;Golden Girls&quot; will be broadcast on Zoom on Tuesday night. The actress involved in the project took to Instagram this week to announce virtual episodes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tracy Ellis Ross will play Rose Nilund, originally played by Betty White. Sanaa Lathan will play Blanche Devereaux, Regina King will play Dorothy Zbornak and Alfre Woodard will play her mother Sophia Petrillo.<br />\r\nGina Prince-Bytewood, episode director, and Lena Waite, host, also posted about it on Instagram.<br />\r\nThe episode, which is part of the &quot;Zoom Where It&#39;s Happening&quot; series, will be broadcast on the video conference platform on Tuesday evening at 9pm. ET / PT, 20.00 CT.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Come and join us in the evening to see the comedy of the past - before you can stop your screens or watch too much,&quot; says the show&#39;s page. Fans can sign up for a virtual party and check out the Zoom Where It&#39;s Happening page.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This event is in collaboration with Zoom. The first episode focuses on Color of Change and supports Color of Change, the largest online organization for racial justice in the country,&quot; said the event&#39;s website. This appears to be the first in a series of reenactment episodes of the sitcom to be aired on Zoom.</p>', 'Golden Girls, Black Actors', 'Trace Ellis_1599828026.jpg', '2020-09-11 16:40:26', '2021-08-17 14:40:56'),
(396, 7, 3, 66, 'tenet-made-20-million-in-its-opening-weekend-1599828279', 'Tenet made $ 20 million in its opening weekend', 0, '<p>Christopher Nolan&#39;s &quot;Tenet&quot;, a litmus test for American films during the pandemic, grossed an estimated $ 20.2 million in American and Canadian theaters over the weekend getaway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The result can be hailed as a rejuvenation of American cinema - more Americans are going to theaters this weekend than in nearly six months - or as an expression of drastically lowered standards for the best Hollywood blockbuster in the situation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>About 70% of theaters in the US are currently open. Those in the country&#39;s best markets - Los Angeles and New York - will remain closed. The operating theater limits the audience capacity to a maximum of 50% for supervising moviegoers. Tenet played in 2,810 locations in North America, about three-quarters of most major versions.<br />\r\nWarner Bros. refused to separate receipts from the United States and Canada. &quot;Tenet&quot; was shown a week earlier in cinemas in Canada, where cases of COVID-19 are much lower than in the US. The film makes its US debut with previews every night from Monday, August 31 to Wednesday, before officially opening on September 3. Warner Bros. include all of the above in planned gross Sundays, along with estimated Labor Day returns on Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Internationally, Tenet has exceeded expectations. It opens even harder in China, where it debuts Friday through Monday with $ 30 million in ticket sales. In the two weeks since its founding, the total overseas amount was $ 126 million, totaling $ 146.2 million.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/03/26/785d442f-84f1-404b-b7c5-a38f001d892b/thumbnail/620x452/4e99ef32fc93300a274cbce010009fb2/tenet-bu9vs9.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nWarner Bros. stressed that the usual weekend counting was done through the window. Some viewers believe that a way to judge how Tenet will unfold is possible. Films, which cost $ 200 million and have at least $ 100 million, have to hit nearly $ 500 million to find a balance.<br />\r\nFor films: Currently she has almost completely mastered the screen for herself. Some multiplexes play the principle up to 100 times on weekends. With something more in sight, Warner Bros. rely on long-term plans for Tenet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not for the film: Audiences don&#39;t like Nolan these days. Cinema-goers rated the thriller, starring John David Washington, Robert Pattinson and Elizabeth Debicky &quot;B&quot; CinemaScore, the lowest rating for Nolan&#39;s 2006 edition of The Prestige. The reviews (75% positive for rotten tomatoes) are good, but far from exaggerated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Movie star Tom Cruise surprised theater audiences at a preview in London, after which he wrote on Twitter: &quot;Big film. Big screen. I love it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Warner Bros. declined to provide executives to discuss the opening, but said in a statement that Tenet should be rated differently. &quot;We are in an unprecedented region, so comparing it to the world before COVID would be unfair and baseless,&quot; said the studio.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Solid start considering the circumstances<br />\r\nAnalyzing the film&#39;s performance is nearly impossible, senior media analyst Paul Dergarabedyan told data company Comscore. He acknowledges that North America is still a more competitive market than Europe or Asia, but calls it a solid start to a long tenet for Tenet.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It took longer to assess this,&quot; said Dergarabedian. &quot;The only win is having an open film. That means a lot to me.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tenet discharge is also discussed in terms of the health risks associated with indoor gatherings. Several prominent film critics have stated that they will not review Tenet for ethical reasons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, the theater chain is struggling to stay fluid. Exhibitors say they need a new film to survive. Last weekend was the first significant opportunity for US cinemas to draw back audiences. Disney&#39;s &quot;New Mutants&quot;, a spin-off of the X-Men, brought in about 2,412 seats last weekend. The total value, which fell dramatically at the end of the second week, now stands at $ 11.6 million.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In keeping with the year turned upside down, the &quot;Tenet&quot; palindrome - a thriller where the times are reversed - basically starts the summer film season over the weekend, which usually ends. Labor Day weekend, which historically takes place in theaters this year, is usually one of the sleepiest weekends of the year in cinemas.</p>', 'Tenet, 20Million', 'Tenet_1599828279.jpg', '2020-09-11 16:44:39', '2021-08-12 21:07:18'),
(397, 7, 3, 95, 'a-woman-shares-a-quality-card-with-passengers-at-houston-airport-during-the-pandemic-1599829206', 'A woman shares a quality card with passengers at Houston Airport during the pandemic', 0, '<p><strong>The airport may be one of the last places people expect to pull off a casual friendly act, but one of those travelers who travel a lot is doing what they can to raise their spirits.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Catherine Knight hopes to change the world with one good word. &quot;I just want someone to be better,&quot; said Knight. I really just wanted to make the world a better place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While traveling for work, he passes out cards to strangers at Houston Airport. Each card contains a message designed to explain those dark days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/07/1cc415ea-5dd6-46e6-9f58-2ed4c57f779c/thumbnail/620x349/2b6d3a41afe7809b37d0a5a9b8437e63/1599519809980.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;You have to wear a mask so you don&#39;t see anyone smiling or sad,&quot; said Knight. &quot;So if you pay attention to someone&#39;s eyes, you can somehow tell that person might need some time.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;People need to know that there is still good in this world,&quot; he added. But in the era of COVID-19, Heidi Botkin was not to blame for being a little skeptical until the news broke.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was very stressed carrying my three children alone,&quot; said Botkin. &quot;So, yeah, that&#39;s a nice little take.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This random act of kindness started three years ago. Knight and his son Parker write uplifting messages for people they have never met and who they may never meet again. More than 25,000 have been written to date, including one for pilot Michael Jones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It helps, you know, I think everyone has their own personal struggles right now,&quot; said Jones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When we need to be apart, it&#39;s a little reminder that we&#39;re still together.</p>', 'Passengers, Pandemic', 'Card of Kidness_1599829206.jpg', '2020-09-11 17:00:06', '2021-08-14 20:38:45'),
(398, 7, 15, 98, 'bruce-williamson-former-temptations-lead-singer-has-died-at-age-49-1599898915', 'Bruce Williamson, former Temptations lead singer, has died at age 49', 0, '<p><strong>Bruce Williamson, a former Temptations singer for several years, has died aged 49, according to a post on Facebook by his son Bruce Alan Williamson Jr. Message has been read.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I love you Daddy thank you for being great, thank you for loving, thank you for being the real you ... I pray to God and we will meet again,&quot; wrote Williamson Jr.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TMZ reported that Williamson died of the coronavirus at his home in Las Vegas on Sunday night.<br />\r\nOn Monday morning, Williamson&#39;s son posted a live post on Facebook: &quot;Pain is not the right word.&quot; In the video, Williamson Jr. thank everyone for their condolences and for contacting him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://scontent.fisb5-1.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-0/p350x350/119042644_707539893439725_4302537020349950107_n.jpg?_nc_cat=110&amp;_nc_sid=110474&amp;_nc_eui2=AeFdZMQmWIV0WXKCntI9HYKdc45ZEhonnPdzjlkSGiec98MRSKXqU2psEPDeKVvBlz-n-SR52yJXmErngKbAUn3j&amp;_nc_ohc=Conb8zr4FiMAX99oBvh&amp;_nc_ht=scontent.fisb5-1.fna&amp;tp=6&amp;oh=bc93550f4f9a170980e1d05a7835a130&amp;oe=5F82DE15\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Many of us loved him ... my father was a great man,&quot; said Williamson Jr. &quot;We lost an icon in my eyes. But I will make sure the legacy continues.&quot;<br />\r\nWilliamson joined The Temptations in 2006, replacing tenor G.C. According to ET Online, Cameron left the band in 2015. He was replaced by former Tower of Power singer Larry Brags.<br />\r\nThe original members of the band are known for Motown hits such as &quot;My Girl&quot;, &quot;The Way You Do Things You Do&quot;, &quot;Don&#39;t Look Back&quot; and &quot;Not Too Proud to Ask&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Williamson, who was born and raised in Los Angeles, spoke about his desire to join The Temptations in a 2016 interview with Chapter &amp; Verse Network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve never lost my dream of being tried,&quot; he said. &quot;But I don&#39;t want to be a clone or someone pretending to be my predecessor. I want to be who I am.&quot;</p>', 'Bruce Williamson, Died', 'Temptaion Singer_1599829514.jpg', '2020-09-11 17:05:14', '2021-12-19 17:38:50'),
(399, 7, 3, 76, 'john-oliver-mayor-in-dispute-over-naming-olivers-sewage-treatment-plant-1599830683', 'John Oliver, Mayor in \"dispute\" over naming Oliver\'s sewage treatment plant', 0, '<p><strong>Danbury, Connecticut - Mark Button, Mayor of Dunbury, told WTNH-TV he would accept Oliver&#39;s challenge to name the city sewer after Oliver offered to donate $ 55,000 to a local charity.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Button said there was an agreement to change the name of the facility. &quot;We have very specific conditions. You have to come here in Danbury and be physically present when we cut the tape,&quot; he said in a Facebook video posted Sunday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;And I have to tell you,&quot; he continued. &quot;Fifty-five thousand dollars? That&#39;s a little light for someone at one percent. But the deal is a deal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Now look - don&#39;t tell Oliver. If you don&#39;t take this offer ... we must have something we named you think - your private pot gate - John Oliver&#39;s house ----. So, Mr. Oliver: Go to Danbury. and sit on your throne.<br />\r\nThe announcement is the final shot in a verbal battle between HBO presenters &quot;Last Week Tonight with John Oliver&quot; and Bouton after Oliver Danbury first met a jury selection segment on August 16 in a segment about racial differences that actually occurred in. The focus is on other areas of Connecticut. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If you want to forget Connecticut, why don&#39;t you forget Danbury?&quot; Oliver said. He ends his story with a grin: &quot;When you leave there, you are always invited to hit John Oliver - including the kids.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/07/4091031a-2993-4e1a-a2dc-58a17a1670e1/thumbnail/620x344/2c639edb77d4ae3d183e696bdf6fd3a6/ap-20244699349020.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nButton followed a Facebook post on Aug.22 featuring the mayor in front of the city&#39;s sewers. &quot;We will change the name to John Oliver Memorial Sewer,&quot; said the mayor of the Republic. &quot;Why? Because he&#39;s full of bullshit like you, John.&quot;<br />\r\nOliver raised the stakes for his event on Aug.30, offering to donate $ 55,000 to a charity in the Danbury area if officials named the facility after him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The comedian posted a video from Bouton saying the offer was a joke and saying, &quot;Wait, so you didn&#39;t do it?&quot; Oliver said he didn&#39;t know he wanted his name down the drain, &quot;but now that you&#39;ve sent it as an option, that&#39;s all I want.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A request for comment on Bouton Oliver&#39;s request to participate in the cutting of the tape has been sent to Oliver&#39;s manager.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s not clear why Oliver first chose Danbury, a town of about 80,000 in Fairfield County that was once the center of the hat.</p>', 'John Oliver, Dispute', 'John Oliver_1599830683.jpg', '2020-09-11 17:24:43', '2021-08-12 21:03:42'),
(400, 7, 3, 68, 'lou-brock-an-outside-player-in-the-hall-of-fame-died-at-the-age-of-81-1599831030', 'Lou Brock, an outside player in the Hall of Fame, died at the age of 81', 0, '<p>Hall of Fame Lou Brock, one of the baseball strikers and grassroots thief who helped Cardinal St. Louis won three flags and two World Series titles in the 1960s, having passed away. He is 81 years old.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dick Zitzman, Brock&#39;s agent and longtime friend, confirmed Brock&#39;s death on Sunday but said he could not provide any details. The Cardinals and Cubs also observed a moment of silence in the minds of the outsiders before their match at Wrigley Field.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brock has lost a leg to diabetes in recent years and was diagnosed with cancer in 2017. &quot;In my 25 years as his agent, he&#39;s probably the happiest Hall of Fame I&#39;ve ever met,&quot; said Zitzman. &quot;I think he&#39;s living a life that will never be imitated,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/media/EhRpk1KXsAI47kD?format=jpg&amp;name=small\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe man was later referred to as Running Red Bird, and Elementary Theft arrived at St. Louis in June 1964, replaced by dice thrower Ernie Brolio in one of the worst sides of baseball.<br />\r\nBrock stole 938 bases in his career, including 118 in 1974 - both major league records until broken by Ricky Henderson.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brock&#39;s death comes after the death of Hall of Fame thrower Tom Sever on Monday. Brock and Severus have faced each other 157 times, the most rewarding match for both of them in their careers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Together with starter Bob Gibson and central tennis player Kurt Flood, Brock became the anchor for St. Petersburg. Louis because of his combination of speed, defense and quality made him a leading team in the 1960s and a symbol of the National League&#39;s more aggressive style at the time. made of. with the American League.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The card was world champion in 1964 and 1967 and lost seven games against the Detroit Tigers in 1968. Opposing teams were warned to keep Brock off the base, especially in lows 1967-68 when one round was often possible to win a game. But the fast-paced left winger with slide pop-ups has been a consistent stealer and producer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/07/c67dafe3-c523-40f0-8757-65747571ddf5/thumbnail/620x395/7776fd8a484d5877a7c4811d50c5af03/gettyimages-452892582.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a lifelong .293 striker, he has led the league eight times in thefts, scoring 100 or more runs seven times and scoring 3,023 goals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brock was even better in the game after this season, scoring .391 with four homers, 16 RBIs and 14 points stolen in 21 World Series games. He had a record 13 hits in the 1968 World Series and hosted 4 matches, tripled and doubled as the Cardinals beat Detroit and 31-game winner Danny McLain 10-1.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brock hasn&#39;t played in another world championship since 1968 but remained a star during the last 11 years of his career.<br />\r\nHe is so synonymous with theft because in 1978 he became the first major league to receive an award named after him while he was active - the Lou Brock Award for National League Leader in Theft. For Brock, basic theft was an art form and a kind of war. He was one of the first performers to study films of the opposite tone, and once at the base he relied on skill and psychology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Lou Brock&#39;s 1976 treatise: Stealing is My Game, he describes his success. Take &quot;humble leadership&quot; and &quot;silence.&quot; The thrower must move, if only to &quot;deliver anvil&quot;. &quot;He also had two things on his mind: dough and me,&quot; wrote Brock. &quot;I mean just one thing - steal it. The business of being annoying itself is extraordinarily complex.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brock finished his career in 1979 with .304 goals, making him his sixth game in an All-Star Game, and winning the Return Player of the Year award. The team removed the number 20 uniform and was inducted into the Hall of Fame in its first year of participation in 1985.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Quiet Brock is determined regardless of the outcome, and sometimes annoys opponents and teammates and steals even when cards are far ahead. He also made two dangerous mistakes which helped St. Louis in the &#39;68 World Series.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Game 5, with a 3-2 card on the heel tip and leading the series 3-1, Brock doubled with one shot and looked sure to hit when Julian Javier put one down on the left. But Brock never tried to sneak up, and Willie Horton&#39;s powerful throw to the left arrived just in time to be caught by hunter Bill Frehan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tigers are among many who point to this moment as a turning point. They came together to win 5-3 in Game 5 and win the two finalists at St. Petersburg. Louis. In Game 7, which Detroit won 4-1, Brock made another critical omission: he was first selected by Mickey Lolich of the Tigers after the single finished in the sixth inning when nothing came out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After retiring, Brock worked as a florist and ABC commentator for Monday Night Baseball and became a regular member of the Spring Training Card. She worked as a part-time teacher and remains a fan favorite for signing autographs, some of which are wearing Brock-a-Brellas, a hat with an umbrella she designed.</p>', 'Lou Brock, Died 81', 'Lou brock_1599831030.jpg', '2020-09-11 17:30:30', '2021-08-13 11:53:30'),
(401, 7, 15, 196, 'the-real-paris-hilton-1599898892', 'The real Paris Hilton', 0, '<p><strong>By now, you might think you&#39;ve seen everything in and around Paris Hilton: worldly people working as dumb blonde, reality TV star known for her stardom, voice of a Barbie doll doing nothing. say.</strong><br />\r\nNow he says that person is acting. Correspondent Tracy Smith asked Hilton: &quot;What do you think the difference is between this character you create and the real Paris?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There are so many differences,&quot; he replied. &quot;In her character, mostly the blonde, cheerful, ignorant Barbie kind. And in real life I&#39;m quite the opposite. I&#39;m not a stupid blonde, I&#39;m just good at pretending.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even today he talks about the new film, &quot;This is Paris&quot;, which depicts a time in his life that he finds too painful to describe.<br />\r\nSmith asked, &quot;With everything that&#39;s happening in the world, are you afraid people will say,&quot; Oh come on, everything that happens, I really care about Paris Hilton? &quot;&quot; &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hilton replied, &quot;I think when people see the film, they will see a different side. And they will see that I am human and have feelings. And they will understand me more. I know that I did a lot of things.&quot; have more than they think. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Paris Hilton, the heir to the historic legacy of the Hilton Hotel, was born to rich but hardworking parents Richard and Cathy. She said they were strict - no makeup or gatherings allowed. But as a teenager, Paris had a wild streak, so wild that her mother and father sent her to a number of schools to &quot;change her behavior&quot; in the 1990s.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;How did your parents get to the point where they thought it was the answer? What did you do?&quot; Asked Smith.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I didn&#39;t really do anything, I just moved from Los Angeles to New York and then my life changed completely,&quot; Hilton said. &quot;Basically, I just got through, I went to the club, I didn&#39;t go to school and I didn&#39;t take classes. And then my parents thought it was time to go.&quot;<br />\r\nIn 1998, Paris, then 17, was liquidated at Provo Canyon School in Utah, where young people with mental and behavioral problems are cared for. But in &quot;This is Paris&quot; he describes the place as more of a prison camp with physical isolation and violence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said his employees set an example and choked and beat him. &quot;It&#39;s weird to think now because I&#39;ve buried it with my emotions for so long,&quot; Hilton said. &quot;So now that you think about what happened, it&#39;s very strange to me, what exactly is it?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sunday morning reach Provo Canyon. In a statement, they said in part that &quot;Provo Canyon School was sold from its previous holdings in August 2000,&quot; and therefore &quot;cannot comment on operations or patient experiences prior to that time&quot; and that it &quot;does not condone or promote&quot; anything. Harassment form. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hilton said she never told her family about her experiences there, but suffered from nightmares years later. In the film, Katie Hilton says, &quot;She would tell me things after - &#39;I&#39;m still having nightmares, it&#39;s still in the middle of the night,&#39; she&#39;d say - and I always take what people say with a grain of salt.&quot; thought, &quot;Yes, it bothers him, but that&#39;s how we saved you.&quot; &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Smith asked Paris, &quot;Why didn&#39;t you tell them while you were away?&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;When I came out, I was so grateful and happy that I was free that I didn&#39;t even want to raise him,&quot; she said. &quot;I seem to prefer, you know, never talk about it, just not think about it. And since I left this building, that&#39;s when I decided that I would never tell anyone this story.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You thought you would never say that?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;No. And I don&#39;t think they&#39;ll believe me. Since I&#39;ve heard it spoken of, it sounds unbelievable.&quot;<br />\r\nAfter graduating from high school, Hilton said she tried to forget: she was a figure at every high-profile show and became famous for all the wrong reasons, like the 2003 sex tape scandal that made the headlines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/03/ef76d73a-f942-451d-9a55-88317c4a3860/thumbnail/620x350/618b91d0bba40532680fbdb1d60300c9/tracy-smith-and-paris-hilton-620.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Smith asked, &quot;The sex tape took place after school. Is there a connection?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That would never have happened if I didn&#39;t go to this school,&quot; he replied. &quot;Don&#39;t you think the sex tape will happen?&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Not.&quot;<br />\r\nWhy not? &quot;I felt very lost when I left this school,&quot; said Hilton. &quot;And then I finally met the person who did. And I would never have allowed someone like this in my life if I didn&#39;t have an experience like this, and that&#39;s why I would never put myself in this situation.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;But I wanted love so badly. I didn&#39;t really know. I was so naive. And I trusted the wrong people. And I&#39;ll regret it for the rest of my life.&quot;<br />\r\nBut despite everything she&#39;s been through - or maybe because of it - Paris seems the last laugh: she&#39;s founded her own fashion and merchandise empire and is reportedly worth around $ 300 million, a self-promoted fortune.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You really are like the patron saint of selfie culture,&quot; said Smith. - Yes! &quot;So do you feel proud or guilty?&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;A little of both,&quot; Hilton said.<br />\r\nHe spent so much of his life in front of the camera that people thought they knew him. But 39-year-old Paris Hilton says she finally got to know each other. Smith asked, &quot;You said you felt like a child for so long? In what sense? Explain that to me.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;I&#39;ve always been a kid at heart. And I never really wanted to grow up. That&#39;s exactly how I was for so long. Maybe because I didn&#39;t really have a child.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;But now,&quot; he laughed, &quot;I&#39;m all grown up.&quot;</p>', 'Paris, Hilton', 'Hilton_1599831514.jpg', '2020-09-11 17:38:34', '2021-12-19 17:38:37');
