(402, 7, 3, 79, 'how-netflix-is-reinventing-entertainment-and-corporate-culture-1599832792', 'How Netflix is reinventing entertainment and corporate culture', 0, '<p>The New York Times once described the Netflix lobby as &quot;the coolest place to watch and watch in Hollywood&quot;. That was last year. Now?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It should be full of people, applause, speeches and everything. It&#39;s empty now,&quot; said Reid Hastings, co-founder and co-CEO of Netflix. As Lesley Stahl was featured, the 80-foot video wall promoting the new Netflix show was now surrounded by lots of empty chairs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;ll be back,&quot; said Hastings. &quot;We&#39;ll get this vaccine and then the lobby will pump up again!&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I know why you are so optimistic because, like toilet paper and Lysol, you are one of the few companies that is really successful in this pandemic,&quot; said Stahl.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;People love entertainment,&quot; said Hastings, &quot;be it war, times of peace, or COVID.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Yes, but you avoided my question, which is you are perfectly healthy. Your subscription number is, right?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We got off to a faster start of growth than in any year in our history, from about 160 million to 190 million. And so much growth.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;And international?&quot;<br />\r\nNetflix&#39;s global growth in recent years has been exponential.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews2.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/05/c17a0d9e-89f5-4fbe-b3ae-af2220bbe0c0/thumbnail/620x350/c30105e2ce750a4e62c2b93171bff9b4/netflix-scroll-620.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This service is now available in 190 countries. And financial growth is also extraordinary. When the company went public in 2002, its share price was $ 15 per share. During the pandemic, Netflix was trading for around $ 500.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stahl told Ted Sarandos, Co-CEO of Netflix, &quot;They created this monster. Watching overeating is addicting. It changes our habits, it changes our sleeping habits, we don&#39;t read much. We don&#39;t watch CBS much! The People say it does. theirs. &quot;a ruined sex life. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Well, you did something wrong, Leslie!&quot; Sarandos laughs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stahl interviewed Hastings in 2006 when Netflix shipped mostly small red envelopes of DVDs around the country. Then he tells her that he thinks it doesn&#39;t matter to a CEO and that he should pass it on to someone else. &quot;I really had a fight,&quot; he confessed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So is he CEO material now? &quot;It&#39;s starting. It&#39;s trying. I&#39;m trying.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the man who said he wasn&#39;t a good CEO is now the co-author of a book on running a business. The title is &quot;No Rules Rules: Netflix and the Culture of Reinvention&quot; (Penguin Press) and expresses a very unorthodox style of government that gives Netflix employees tremendous freedom and freedom.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Liability - unlimited rest time and pays the highest market wage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In return, employees will undergo a &quot;guardian test&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We ran like a professional sports team,&quot; said Hastings. &quot;We try to find the best players in the field all the time. If someone moves to another company, will we work really hard to keep them on Netflix? And if so, they will pass the watch test. If.&quot; No, we gave them a very generous release package and let them go. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Sometimes they don&#39;t want to go,&quot; Stall said, &quot;but the test guards don&#39;t deserve to be kept? And that&#39;s why you have a reputation for being mean. Some people call it the Hunger Games Company.&quot; &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s not like the Hunger Games at all,&quot; said Hastings. &quot;It&#39;s a complete collaboration. But if you want to win the World Cup for fun, you always have to have the best players on the pitch.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No doubt this is a difficult place, he said. &quot;Without a doubt, this isn&#39;t for everyone.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On tough Netflix, honesty is the best policy no matter what. The idea of &quot;radical openness&quot; arose because Hastings said he had undergone marriage counseling.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Well, it&#39;s been a long time. We&#39;re married 29 years now, but when we started our marriage we had this great marriage counselor. And he let me see that I was just lying. I say conventional things like, &quot;Family is the most important.&quot; and then I wanted to work for a long time, you know. So it helped him a lot that it really showed me that I wasn&#39;t that honest. And it helps me live a more balanced life. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/05/d52506fc-f363-471b-ac34-7ea4dacd6699/thumbnail/620x465/03f5706e81827528d8758a5eb33c999f/reed-hastings-interview-1280.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nNetflix also hosts what Hastings calls &quot;Live 360&quot;. &quot;It&#39;s Live 360, we usually have lunch or lunch, then everyone goes out and gives us feedback on how they can be more effective at work.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So did you get any response or criticism?&quot; Asked Stahl.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;All the time! To be too brave and not really listen, or I would be criticized for being too positive and polite and not seeing problems. Lots of things. And, you know, there&#39;s always a grain of truth.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In his book, Hastings tells what he said about him in one of those sessions - that he was too aggressive, arrogant, and scoffed when other people had ideas. Stahl asked: &quot;Do you know yourself [in this]?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Yes,&quot; he replied. &quot;And again I tried to soften it up. And then, you know, you can&#39;t really change your character.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ted Sarandos joined Netflix more than 20 years ago. He says what is Hastings vision<br />\r\nsell it to the company: &quot;Reed described Netflix in 1999 almost exactly as it is now. And why does this seem crazy, at a time when the internet is so slow and expensive, it seems incomprehensible that - I mean, If anything, when you receive a video in your email. , it took days to open and see.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Dan Reed was very clear about where it was going. And I&#39;m just tired. Anyway, I&#39;m not sure I think he&#39;s right. But his sense of clarity about it is amazing.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hastings is leading Netflix through four major changes - from renting DVDs, streaming other people&#39;s shows, producing your own shows, to moving globally.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year, Netflix received more Oscar and Emmy nominations than any other studio, and this is thanks in large part to Sarandos. &quot;My job is to select everything on Netflix,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last year it selected nearly 400 shows and each - be it &quot;The Crown&quot; or its royal cousin &quot;Tiger King&quot; - started on the pitch. &quot;We probably listen to about 100 every day. So these are films and series, television, global and documentaries.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first sound Sarandos heard and the first show Netflix produced in 2013 was House of Cards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stahl asked, &quot;Tell us why you wanted the Cardboard House in the first place.&quot; What do you see there &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That&#39;s Shakespeare,&quot; said Sarandos. &quot;It&#39;s about greed, power and sex - all good television quality.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kevin Spacey and Robin Wright star in House of Cards. Stahl asked Hastings, &quot;What must you do to get them to sign?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Ted&#39;s charm and great checkbook! That combination can do it all.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How big is a checkbook? Well, Sarandos paid $ 100 million for the first two seasons of House of Cards. Netflix has been known to buy its way - as booed by &quot;Saturday Night Live&quot;, where Netflix executives literally dump money on future show producers:<br />\r\nSarando&#39;s budget for content spent on programming last year was $ 15 billion. &quot;Yes. But not that many in the world,&quot; said Hastings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;But you paid some stars 30 million, 40 million bucks? The pressure on other studios to agree on what you did was enormous. How much will Smith get today? Forty million? Fifty million?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I can&#39;t tell you what Will Smith did,&quot; Sarandos laughed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Variety has announced that Netflix will likely pay Will Smith $ 35 million to star in the sequel to the Netflix film &quot;Bright&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This summer, Netflix transferred $ 100 million of its assets to a black-owned bank, and Hastings and his wife donated $ 120 million of their own money to historic black colleges and universities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hastings, valued at $ 5 billion, has pledged to donate most of his fortune to charity.<br />\r\nStahl asked Hastings, &quot;So Ted is your content manager, then you make him co-CEO. People are wondering if this is your first step?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Very well,&quot; he said. &quot;But you know, at some point we&#39;re all going to die.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So are they going to grab your leg?&quot; He laughed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;ll see!&quot;</p>', 'NetFlix, Corporate Culture', 'NetFlix_1599832792.jpg', '2020-09-11 17:59:52', '2021-08-13 18:06:02'),
(403, 7, 15, 154, 'vin-scullys-baseball-treasure-1599898835', 'Vin Scully\'s baseball treasure', 0, '<p>The last time the Vin Scully Hall of Fame reached the Vin Scully Hall of Fame Sunday morning was a sweltering summer evening at Dodger Stadium in Los Angeles. That was eight years ago, but the privilege of going to the ballroom in person feels like it was a century ago.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Baseball in 2020 is the season for cardboard cutouts in the stands and the sound of the fans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scully thinks he saw it all - balls outside the park, yes, but fans outside the park too? Thank you, COVID!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve spent my life in sports and almost closed it,&quot; Scully told reporter Lee Cowan.<br />\r\nHe&#39;s not just the voice of the Dodgers. Scully is the heart of the baseball storyteller. After 67 seasons, the redhead who started with the Brooklyn Dodgers at the age of 23 retired in 2016 before her 89th birthday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That&#39;s enough in my heart, in my head. And I never doubted that I would have to wait another year,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Without regrets?&quot; Cowen asked.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Nothing. Uh-huh.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Is it strange to look like a fan?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t look at it critically,&quot; Scully replied. &quot;I didn&#39;t really listen to what the speaker was saying, &#39;Are you trying to steal my stuff?&#39; &quot;You know, I don&#39;t have any of that!&quot; &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nobody can &quot;steal&quot; Scully&#39;s stuff, but you can collect it now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews2.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/05/a5972ebc-58ac-4aef-b3f6-84363cc7f7ce/thumbnail/620x697/ba04d94a9a3d9b52c2e272d1ddad5813/vin-scully-dodgers-kimono.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nOver the years, he&#39;s collected several of the game&#39;s crown jewels - World Series trophies, World Series rings, President&#39;s autographs, and more prizes than anywhere to place them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Awards are received gratefully, but only for a moment,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So he decided to sell some of those monumental moments at a hunting auction in Philadelphia. She wants results, which could be very significant, for her five children, 16 grandchildren, and charity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cowan asked, &quot;Is there anything hard to let go of?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You know, I have to be so cool because I don&#39;t really feel anything, I hate giving up. Nothing.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even the piece of paper Scully received as a child on the top-right deck of Polo Square in New York: &quot;And this is Babe Ruth. And he reached into his pocket and pulled out 50, 100 business cards, and each one had his own Signature, Baby Ruth.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews3.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/05/3f4a017a-b536-4922-932b-1ebe4615979b/thumbnail/620x374/8efb2f196e9fb7e01e0ac9315ce04196/babe-ruth-autograph-620.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;So you were given this card by Babe Ruth himself?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Yes, isn&#39;t that wonderful?&quot; Scully said. &quot;Somehow, it showed when we started digging.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Have you forgotten you have it?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;No, I haven&#39;t forgotten, but I&#39;m not sure where he is!&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some items he has owned for most of his career, such as the shabby leather tie he carries to every game. &quot;Oh, I&#39;ve never lived without it.&quot; There are still taped notes about him, such as the poem by Shel Silverstein which he reads every time he sees a child in the stands:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><em>&quot;Oh, the thumbsucker&#39;s thumb may look wrinkled and wet<br />\r\nand withered and white as snow,<br />\r\nbut the taste of the thumb is the sweetest taste yet<br />\r\nas only we thumbsuckers know.&quot;</em></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews2.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/05/cbff1b66-4c96-4576-b3cb-0f1e13678786/thumbnail/620x465/2f7794620a4eac6014fa6accb48511db/vin-scully-world-series-ring-1280.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nCowan also noted Scully&#39;s 1988 World Series ring. It&#39;s hard to miss!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He&#39;ll be sure to keep it, Cowen thought. But not. &quot;I&#39;ve been wearing it every day, almost every hour of every day, but it will pass,&quot; said Scully.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Vin Scully is part of baseball&#39;s history as a player and gambler.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And he&#39;s not out of the game. In fact, he recently joined Twitter:<br />\r\n... to keep talking about the great moments in baseball. He&#39;d seen them enough to know baseball was going on.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, time didn&#39;t stop for anyone. &quot;I mean, I&#39;m 92 years old,&quot; he said. &quot;Even when I live to be a hundred years, it will only be a few years. Where I am, I am - calm, peaceful and at home, away from the maddening crowd.&quot;</p>', 'Vin Scully, Baseball', 'Dodger_1599833094.jpg', '2020-09-11 18:04:54', '2021-12-19 17:38:24'),
(404, 7, 5, 44, 'twitter-to-download-or-tag-misleading-posts-about-election-results-1599834410', 'Twitter to download or tag misleading posts about election results', 0, '<p><strong>Starting next week, Twitter will flag or remove misleading allegations about the election, the company said on Thursday.</strong><br />\r\nThe policy applies to tweets &quot;that are intended to undermine public confidence in an election or other civil process,&quot; Twitter said. This includes, according to the company, false accusations of electoral fraud or electoral fraud or ballot results, including claiming victory before results are confirmed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The policy will take effect on September 17, a few weeks before the November 3 presidential election. Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, many Americans are expected to vote for the first time by letter in this election, and many are relying on search engines and social media to find out how to do this. The majority of ballots sent by post will likely delay election results for some time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Technology companies are working to strengthen their policies to prevent misinformation. However, it is unclear whether their efforts will be enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Thursday, Google announced it would tighten its search guidelines in connection with elections, in particular by removing the auto-settlement function of claims against or against political candidates or in connection with the voting process. This means that searches such as &quot;prize to candidate&quot; or claims such as &quot;You can vote by phone&quot; won&#39;t be completed automatically, the company said. Last year the company banned political advertising.<br />\r\nLast week, Facebook said it would limit new political advertising in the week leading up to the election and remove posts spreading misinformation about COVID-19 and the vote. He will also attach links to official results on candidate publications and campaigns declaring previous victories.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This policy could reduce the spread of propaganda, according to ProPublica, but also affect the ability of election officials to receive timely information about elections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Twitter has a more aggressive policy than Facebook. He banned political advertising altogether and began fact-checking President Donald Trump&#39;s tweets in May, which angered him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Twitter, users prefer labeling guidelines rather than deleting annoying tweets from world market leaders. This approach continues to be used with the latest rules. Even if a candidate posts misleading allegations about the election, the results will most likely remain valid because Twitter sees it as &quot;in the public interest&quot;. However, the visibility of the post will decrease and users will not be able to tweet it again.<br />\r\n&quot;We will not allow our services to be abused in civil proceedings, especially in elections,&quot; Twitter said on Thursday in a blog post. &quot;Any attempt to do this - both at home and within the country - will be made under the strict application of our rules, which apply equally and make sense to all.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even though the policy was in effect weeks before the US election, more than 80% of Twitter users are outside the US and enforced worldwide.</p>', 'Twitter, Misleading posts', 'Twitter False claim_1599834410.jpg', '2020-09-11 18:26:50', '2021-08-17 01:35:09'),
(405, 7, 5, 46, 'americas-top-cybersecurity-expert-when-you-have-paper-you-have-a-receipt-1599836963', 'America\'s Top Cybersecurity Expert: \"When You Have Paper, You Have a Receipt\"', 0, '<p><strong>The world&#39;s best cybersecurity experts are concerned about how the voting system can be protected from hackers. But one thing they don&#39;t care about are newsletters.</strong><br />\r\nThe postal and postal voting system is tough and secure because it creates a verifiable paper trail, said Christopher Krebs, director of the National Security Agency&#39;s Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency (CISA).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both postal and private voting use a similar method of tallying votes, but not all e-voting booths create a paper backup for every vote. Each country is responsible for its own election process, Krebs said, which makes it difficult for hackers to interfere with the national vote. Although tallying votes manually on paper can take some time, even though the tabulation process went wrong in some areas, paper grading helps reviewers verify accurate results.<br />\r\n&quot;If you find abnormalities or something unusual, you want to be able to retrieve the tape,&quot; Krebs told CNET. &quot;And if you have paper, you have receipts. So you can upgrade to the exact number.&quot;<br />\r\nHer office coordinates with private and government cybersecurity researchers to identify and report digital vulnerabilities. CISA recently released a guide designed to help states identify electoral gaps by working with federal government and private sector security experts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Krebs unveiled a security plan for the August election at the annual Black Hat Cybersecurity Conference.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Disclosure is an important part of enhancing the cybersecurity of services and systems [voting],&quot; Krebs said. &quot;Our goal is [election officials] if they find any kind of vulnerability or omission in a security position, [they] have a process you can work on to address that vulnerability.&quot;<br />\r\nOther well-known security researchers have also confirmed the value of the mail system in Black Hat. In his virtual keynote address, Georgetown law professor Matt Blaze said that while the mail and post voting system was unreliable, it was reliable, widely available, and didn&#39;t pose much of a risk of disrupting the digital voting system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;[Post voting] is ubiquitous, and it&#39;s generally an established, predictable concept,&quot; Blaze said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Blaise stressed that any election can be exploited by poor participants and elections by safe post but also poses logistical challenges and that countries need to expand their voting infrastructure just before elections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t think I&#39;ve had a problem more difficult than the security integrity of civilian elections,&quot; Blaze said. &quot;In fact, the current voting system that has been studied is in some dire way and most likely usable.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jake Brown, moderator for Black Hat and executive director of the University of Chicago&#39;s Cyber Policy Initiative, also spoke at the conference in support of postal voting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In addition to the obvious benefits of long-distance postal voting in COVID, postal voting adds to the amount of time people have to vote in weeks from a few hours on election day,&quot; Brown told CBS News. &quot;He made sure voters avoided long queues caused by technical problems with touch-screen voting machines and electronic voting booths like the ones we have seen in Georgia and Wisconsin,&quot; during the by-election.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brown also expressed concern that government voting sites could target a variety of attacks, including ransomware designed to interfere with voting machines and government computers, as well as hacks that display false information such as false election data on government websites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;A ransomware attack on the electoral roll a week or two before an election will result in haunting chaos and ballots counted,&quot; Brown said. &quot;Attacks on official government election websites that alter information about voting procedures or even election results will also be disastrous.&quot;</p>', 'Americans, Cyber Security Experts', 'Cyber Securtiy_1599836963.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:09:23', '2021-08-16 08:33:01'),
(406, 7, 5, 48, 'solid-fuel-boost-for-nasas-new-moon-launch-test-in-utah-1599836972', 'Solid fuel boost for NASA\'s New Moon Launch Test in Utah', 0, '<p>Northrop Grumman fired a five-segment solid-state amplifier in a spectacular earth-shake test Wednesday to pave the way for downstream missions that move astronauts and cargo to and from the moon aboard NASA&#39;s new space rocket.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe test engine burned 6 tons of fuel per second and started at 15:05 (CET). It erupted instantly in a burst of flames and plumes of exhaust gas soared in the clear blue sky above the Northrop Grumman manufacturing facility in Promontory, Utah.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/02/2f79b799-acde-48cb-9b36-44a08b72f758/thumbnail/620x337/90d97abb903e9b244ba97e249435361d/090220-srbtest-3.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The SLS &quot;Flight Support Booster 1&quot; locked beside it on a large test bench and consumed over 1.5 million pounds of fuel in just two minutes, generating 3.6 million pounds of thrust.<br />\r\nAs the fuel burns, the exhaust stream turns into a swirling cloud of orange flames before swings around to the nozzle and dousing the interior of the rocket with carbon dioxide to extinguish the remaining flame.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Boeing SLS rocket, which is being built for NASA&#39;s Artemis lunar program, will be equipped with two solid-state rocket accelerators (SRB) that will provide nearly 7 million pounds of thrust - 75% of the rocket&#39;s launch force - and the hydraulic system will have to actuate the control nozzle. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The shuttle&#39;s four upgraded main engines add &pound; 2m of thrust, giving the SLS an initial takeoff boost of over &pound; 8m. In comparison, the liquid-powered Saturn 5 rocket built for NASA&#39;s Apollo lunar program - the most powerful rocket successfully launched to date - is worth &pound; 7.5 million.<br />\r\nThe SLS rocket, which carries a capsule for the Orion space team, is scheduled to complete its first unmanned flight test by the end of next year. A manned mission with four astronauts around the moon is planned for 2023, followed by a lunar landing mission in late 2024.<br />\r\nWith the launch of Flight Support Booster 1, the sixth test of the SLS five-segment amplifier since 2009, the aim was to gather technical data on the performance of new materials and equipment that may be included on SLS downstream flights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Solid fuel SLS boosters are similar to those used to launch NASA&#39;s space shuttle. However, the new version includes an additional fuel segment, better avionics and better materials. Boosters were not restored after use, and shuttle era shuttle and other recovery options were removed.</p>', 'Soild Fuel, Moon Launch Test', 'Solid Booster_1599836972.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:09:32', '2021-08-15 15:51:02'),
(407, 7, 5, 38, 'according-to-the-report-amazon-is-tracking-threats-to-the-workforce-within-the-company-1599836977', 'According to the report, Amazon is tracking \"threats to the workforce\" within the company', 0, '<p><strong>According to a job listing recently posted on its website, Amazon could increase oversight of employees engaged in the e-commerce company&#39;s work.</strong><br />\r\nA screenshot of the ad (see below), which was later removed, shows that Amazon wants to hire an analyst to gather information about &quot;threats to the organization of the workforce&quot;. Other responsibilities include tracking &quot;funding and activities associated with internal and external corporate campaigns against Amazon.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The job advert was posted in January, according to a deputy report, but did not attract public attention until this week after being posted on Twitter. Amazon said the list was &quot;not an accurate description of the role&quot; and removed it from its website. The company also has a team of analysts that monitors and prepares for a number of incidents, including large gatherings near the company building that could harm team members.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/03/ac44191a-0f20-42b7-86fe-3bf31867677d/thumbnail/620x286/e51e8a4939b65efc33cbb8bf49694ee5/screen-shot-2020-09-03-at-11-23-19-am.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAmazon was accused earlier this year of firing workers complaining of its policies, including procedures to protect workers at COVID-19 warehouses. About two dozen Amazon employees at distribution company Staten Island, New York, quit in March because they feared their jobs could expose them to the coronavirus.<br />\r\nOver the past few months, employees at the Whole Foods supermarket chain have been owned by Amazon. A group of employees sued the company, claiming they had been fined for supporting the Black Lives Matter movement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In May, two former Amazon employees, Maren Costa and Emily Cunningham, said they were fired for campaigning for company warehouse workers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mary Kay Henry, president of the International Service Union, said it was typical of &quot;corporate America opposing organization, which frankly, of course, took place in the Amazon warehouse.&quot;</p>', 'Amazon Tracking, Threats to Labor', 'Amazon threats_1599836977.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:09:37', '2021-08-12 21:13:44'),
(408, 7, 5, 32, 'apple-will-release-ios-14-without-tracking-function-1599836980', 'Apple will release iOS 14 without tracking function', 0, '<p>Apple is slowing down new privacy features in the next version of its iPhone operating system that will make it difficult for app makers to track people online to help sell digital ads.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The decision outlined on Thursday concerns iOS 14, which is expected to be released later this month as a free software upgrade for about a billion iPhone users. Apple intends for iOS 14 to automatically block tracking as soon as it launches. However, the company has announced that it will maintain the tool until early next year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The same protection should be in the next operating system for iPad and Apple TV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For this feature, the app must explicitly ask users for permission to collect and share data about their online behavior via a unique code that identifies each iPhone. This requirement raises concerns that most users will block tracking, making it harder for free apps to sell the ads that make up the majority of their sales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At this point, the app will automatically receive the tracking code, unless iPhone and other Apple device users can also change the privacy controls themselves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook, which runs the largest digital advertising network behind Google, warned last week that new privacy features in iOS 14 could deal a crushing blow to many apps if they already grapple with a recession caused by the coronavirus.<br />\r\nDespite Apple delaying a new tracking tool, the Cupertino-based California firm stressed that this should not be taken as a sign that it is withdrawing from its outspoken commitment to protecting the privacy of its customers as a &quot;fundamental right.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We want to give developers the time needed to make the necessary changes to the application and advertising model,&quot; the company said in a statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apple&#39;s delay has disappointed those trying to combat digital surveillance when it comes to online tracking, said Craig Danulov, CEO of The Privacy Co., which recently launched its own privacy app to prevent iPhone users from snooping. Protect your eyes. Eye.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This delay can only be seen as detrimental to millions of users who don&#39;t even understand how much tracking is going on,&quot; said Danulov.<br />\r\nThe iPhone maker topped several trillion shares in August when its shares first hit $ 468. Despite the coronavirus outbreak, Apple&#39;s stock is up 60% this year.</p>', 'Apple Ios, Without Tracking', 'Apple Ios_1599836980.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:09:40', '2021-08-12 20:58:28'),
(409, 7, 5, 23, 'tiktok-is-struggling-to-stop-the-spread-of-viral-suicide-videos-1599836996', 'TikTok is struggling to stop the spread of viral suicide videos', 0, '<p><strong>TikTok is trying to download a copy of a disturbing video depicting a man&#39;s suicide that has gone viral on the video sharing platform in recent days. Social media platform users warned others to avoid graphic videos whenever possible.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The man first broadcast the disturbing scene live on Facebook in late August. Since then, the video has been copied and distributed on various social media platforms, including the most recent TikTok.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;On Sunday night, the suicide video which was originally broadcast live on Facebook was distributed to other platforms, including TikTok. Our moderation system and team detected and removed these videos that violated our guidelines for content that featured, praised, glorified, or encouraged suicide, &quot;a TikTok spokesman told CBS News on Tuesday.<br />\r\n&quot;We prohibit accounts that repeatedly attempt to upload videos, and we value members of our community who have reported content and warned others not to view, activate, or share such videos on the platform out of respect for individuals and families.&quot; said a spokesman.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Facebook spokesperson told CBS News Tuesday that they deleted the original video on the day it was released and &quot;have since used automation technology to delete copies and posts.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TikTok&#39;s unique algorithm and content recommendation system make it easier to distribute content than other apps. Unlike other platforms like Facebook and Instagram, which primarily focus on the people you follow, TikTok&#39;s main &quot;Pages For You&quot; feed offers users viral content regardless of whether they follow the account they are on. position, which is very influential. It is difficult to avoid unwanted footage.<br />\r\nGiven TikTok&#39;s youth user base, graphic content can easily reach large numbers of children and teens. While TikTok serves to erase all copies of the video, users warn others to slide when they see a gruff image of a man with a long beard sitting at a table.<br />\r\nSome users also warned users that the video would appear buried in another video that seemed harmless. Many say the safest option is to stay completely out of the app until TikTok fixes the problem.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TikTok already has measures in place to limit content related to self-harm. Searching for &quot;suicide,&quot; &quot;suicide video&quot; and other related terms gave no results. Instead, users will see the National Suicide Prevention Line number and the Advice and Assistance section.</p>', 'TikTok, Struggling', 'TikTok_1599836996.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:09:56', '2021-08-12 21:08:22'),
(410, 7, 5, 41, 'walmart-test-service-for-drone-delivery-of-food-and-other-products-1599837006', 'Walmart test service for drone delivery of food and other products', 0, '<p><strong>Walmart said it was testing groceries and household appliances with automated drones and joining forces with other retailers to scale up their coronavirus delivery business.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dealers started trials on Wednesday in partnership with Flytrex, a company that supplies unmanned aerial vehicles. The project, undertaken in Fayetteville, North Carolina, will leave &quot;certain groceries and staples&quot; from Walmart stores to buyers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Walmart is one of the few retailers whose sales increased during the pandemic amid a boom in e-commerce. The company&#39;s online sales nearly doubled in the last quarter, while in-store sales increased 9%. Competitors Amazon and Target also posted jumps in profit this summer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Walmart emphasized the experimental nature of the drone project, saying it would help companies study how retail customers and workers use the technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We know it will take time for millions of packages to be sent by drone,&quot; the company said in a press release. &quot;It still feels like science fiction, but we are at a time when we learn more about the technology available and how we can use it to make our customers&#39; lives easier.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Walmart customers can download the Flytex app to see if they qualify for unmanned aerial vehicle deliveries, said a Walmart spokesperson. The company did not provide any information about the size or duration of the trial.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last month, Amazon received approval from the Federal Aviation Administration for its own air vehicle delivery system designed to deliver packages to customers in 30 minutes or less. UPS and Alphabet Wing subsidiaries also have FAA approval to deliver unmanned aerial vehicles.</p>', 'test sservice, Walmart, Drone', 'Walmet Drone_1599837005.png', '2020-09-11 19:10:06', '2021-08-12 21:09:36'),
(411, 7, 5, 42, 'amazon-will-fill-33000-business-and-technology-jobs-many-of-which-offer-six-figure-salaries-1599837010', 'Amazon will fill 33,000 business and technology jobs, many of which offer six-figure salaries', 0, '<p>With many retailers struggling to stay afloat in a crowned economy, Amazon hires like crazy. The e-commerce giant said Wednesday that there are thousands of vacancies, with pay for many positions increasing to six figures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nAmazon currently has 33,000 jobs at the company and the technology is open nationwide, the company announced at a Virtual Career Day event on September 16, where employees can learn more about the position.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On average, the job offers a total annual compensation of $ 150,000, including a salary and stock bonus, an Amazon spokesman told CBS MoneyWatch by email. The company also plans to announce soon that it is hiring thousands of additional positions per hour.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;COVID-19 continues to affect millions of people across the country and people are excited about the opportunity to return to work,&quot; said Beth Galeti, senior vice president of human resources, in a statement on the online job fair. &quot;We continue to hire people with different backgrounds and skills.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Amazon, anyone can attend an upcoming job event by registering and booking online meetings with Amazon recruiters, 1,000 of which are available for 20,000 career training a day.<br />\r\nIn addition to individual training sessions, panel discussions and interviews with career experts and company executives will take place, according to Amazon. Starting Wednesday, users will be able to register for seminars and introductory sessions to review software code and learn more about work on the Amazon logistics network.<br />\r\nLast year&#39;s private exhibitions attracted 17,000 people in six cities, and according to Amazon, more than 200,000 applied for jobs in the week leading up to the event.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPS employs 100,000 contract workers<br />\r\nAmazon&#39;s expansion occurs when other businesses pile up during the holidays. UPS anticipates hiring more than 100,000 seasonal workers by Wednesday before package volumes increase annually in October and continue through January.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The full-time and part-time positions are primarily package manager, driver, assistant and driver of private vehicles in thousands of regions across the country, according to the company. About 123,000 UPS employees - nearly a third of the US workforce - have started seasonal employment, according to UPS.<br />\r\nThe increased volume of online orders during the pandemic has sometimes slowed shipments from Amazon as the company hired 175,000 more people in warehouses this year to help package and ship orders. Walmart and Target also saw sales spike during the health crisis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other traders made it much worse. J.C. Penney, J. Crew and Brooks Brothers go bankrupt. And Lord &amp; Taylor, which has been in business for nearly 200 years, recently said it would close its shop forever. Companies in other industries have announced acquisitions or layoffs, including Coca-Cola and American Airlines.</p>', 'Amazon, Technology jobs', 'Coorporate jobs_1599837010.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:10:10', '2021-08-15 12:23:47'),
(412, 7, 5, 44, 'russia-china-and-iran-stepped-up-their-attacks-before-the-election-microsoft-warned-1599837013', 'Russia, China and Iran stepped up their attacks before the election, Microsoft warned', 0, '<p>Washington - Groups backed by Russia, China and Iran have launched cyber attacks in recent weeks targeting Trump and Biden&#39;s campaigns, as well as people and organizations competing in the 2020 race to interfere in the upcoming elections. Microsoft warned on Thursday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tom Burt, vice president of security and customer trust firm, said in a blog post that malicious activity &quot;clearly shows that foreign activity groups have stepped up their efforts in the 2020 elections as expected&quot;. Tech companies find and stop most attacks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The revelations came after the Treasury Department announced sanctions against four people with ties to Russia, including a Ukrainian lawmaker who met Rudy Giuliani in December to try to influence the US presidential election. MP Andrei Derkach has been an &quot;active Russian agent&quot; for more than a decade and has &quot;carried out an undercover influence campaign&quot; to develop baseless stories about officials in the presidential election, the ministry said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In August, the US intelligence community issued an assessment warning of continued activity by China, Russia and Iran. Russia is said to be actively trying to &quot;insult&quot; Biden, while China prefers Trump to lose his re-election. Meanwhile, Iran can seek to &quot;undermine&quot; America&#39;s democratic institutions and the president through online content.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Christopher Krebs, head of the cyber security and infrastructure security agency, said he was aware of the hacking attempt uncovered by Microsoft and noted that the attempt did not involve election infrastructure or interference with the electoral system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The announcement is in line with previous intelligence by intelligence services on various malicious cyber activities targeting the 2020 campaign and reiterates that this is a full-scale effort to protect democracy,&quot; Krebs said in a statement. &quot;Everyone involved in the political process must remain vigilant against these types of attacks. Today we are releasing guidelines on how to improve cybersecurity against compromised accounts. We encourage anyone who has experienced a cyber incident to report to CISA and the FBI.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Microsoft has identified three groups of hackers targeting hundreds of organizations, advisors, think tanks and political parties involved in the upcoming elections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Strontium, which operates in Russia and is also known as Fancy Bear, launched a series of attacks in early September 2019 that were monitored by Microsoft to steal login information or tamper with accounts, &quot;perhaps to help gather information. Or a shutdown,&quot; said Burt. The hackers&#39; targets include Republican and Democratic advisers, the German Marshall Fund in the US and other think tanks, national and state party organizations in the US, and political parties in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Russia-based group was behind attacks on the democratic presidential campaign in 2016 and reported on Russian interference in the last presidential election in a report by special lawyer Robert Mueller.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Strontium, which operates in Russia and is also known as Fancy Bear, launched a series of attacks in early September 2019, monitored by Microsoft to steal credentials or compromise accounts, &quot;perhaps to help gather information. Or disrupt operations,&quot; said Burt. The hackers&#39; targets include Republican and Democratic advisers, the German Marshall Fund in the US and other think tanks, national and state party organizations in the US, and political parties in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Russia-based group was behind attacks on the democratic presidential campaign in 2016 and was identified in Special Counsel Robert Mueller&#39;s report on Russian interference in the last presidential election.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Microsoft, Chinese-powered zirconium carried out thousands of attacks between March and September, resulting in nearly 150 disruptions. The hacking group, which was aimed at those involved in the presidential campaign, &quot;appears to have targeted Joe Biden&#39;s presidential campaign indirectly and unsuccessfully via email accounts outside of the campaigns of those associated with the campaign. The group also targeted at least one celebrity.&quot; previously linked to the Trump administration. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The China-based hackers also targeted members of the international relations community, as well as scholars from more than 15 universities and accounts with links to 18 international political and political organizations such as the Atlantic Council and the Stimson Center, Microsoft said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A third Iran-based hacking group, Phosphorus, &quot;carries out an espionage campaign targeting various organizations traditionally involved in geopolitics, economics or human rights in the Middle East region.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The group is trying to break into the personal or professional accounts of voters. Microsoft says that between May and June, Phosphorus tried unsuccessfully to get into the Trump administration and staff accounts for the Trump campaign.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thea MacDonald, Trump campaign spokeswoman, said she &quot;takes cybersecurity very seriously and does not publicly comment on our efforts.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We were a big target during President Trump&#39;s re-election campaign, so it&#39;s no surprise that this malicious activity is targeting our campaign or employees,&quot; he said. &quot;We are working with our partners Microsoft and others to reduce this threat.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Biden campaign confirmed the attacks, saying they failed to &quot;target the non-campaign email accounts of people linked to the campaign&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;From the start of our campaign we knew that we would be subjected to such attacks and we are ready to face them,&quot; the campaign read. &quot;Biden for President takes cybersecurity seriously. We will remain vigilant against this threat and ensure campaign assets are secured.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Microsoft said it would continue to disclose additional activity and called for more federal funding in the United States to ensure states can protect their electoral infrastructure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Although the political organizations targeted by these participants are not organizations that maintain or operate the voting system, increased electoral activity in the United States is linked to the broader ecosystem,&quot; said Burt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'Elections, Microsoft warned', 'Russia China and Iran Microsoft_1599837013.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:10:13', '2021-08-12 21:06:27'),
(413, 7, 5, 85, 'uber-will-order-masked-selfies-from-the-driver-to-make-sure-they-cover-the-face-1599837894', 'Uber will order masked selfies from the driver to make sure they cover the face', 0, '<p><strong>Customers trying to sign up for Uber without a mask must show evidence of mouth and nose congestion if they wish to travel at another time. He quoted medical experts as saying that wearing a mask could slow the spread of COVID-19, which has killed more than 180,000 Americans to date.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>If the driver reports that a passenger does not wear a mask while traveling, the person will have to send a selfie with the face on the Uber app before they can call Uber again, the company said in San Francisco.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mask tests will be launched in the United States and Canada later this month, and then in Latin America and other countries.<br />\r\nThe policy now in place allows drivers and drivers to cancel trips without penalty if the other does not wear a mask.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/09/01/c492d861-457d-4d88-86eb-0d90c043864f/thumbnail/620x1255/2681711ac78249e1241a88e29ba32e87/file.gif\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nUber&#39;s move comes as transportation companies, including airlines, enforce a mask policy. All US airlines require passengers to wear a faceplate on their aircraft.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But as many companies can attest, few customers hesitate to follow the rules.<br />\r\nDelta Air Lines has banned at least 240 people from flying over their refusal to comply with its rules, CNN reported. The Delta Detroit-to-Atlanta flight returned to its gates in late July after two customers refused to meet mask requirements.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Uber&#39;s new rules extend to what the company imposed in May. At the time, everyone in the Uber car was forced to wear masks, but asked the Uber Eats driver and supplier to prove they were wearing masks by taking selfies that showed closed mouths and noses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Now drivers are also required to provide photo proof that they are wearing masks if they have previously been reported not to do so. &quot;By adding this new feature, feedback from one driver can help keep Uber safe for the next driver,&quot; said Uber.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Uber claims the verification tool uses technology that recognizes masks as photo subjects and does not process biometric information.</p>', 'Uber, Masked', 'Uber_1599837894.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:24:54', '2021-08-17 08:03:02');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(414, 7, 5, 69, 'facebook-has-threatened-to-prevent-people-in-australia-from-exchanging-messages-if-new-rules-are-passed-1599838170', 'Facebook has threatened to prevent people in Australia from exchanging messages if new rules are passed', 0, '<p><strong>Facebook warned Monday that it would prevent people in Australia from sharing news on its platform if the Australian government came up with a plan to force them and Google to pay news organizations for content shared on their platforms.</strong><br />\r\nThe announcement comes after the Australian Commission for Competition and Consumer Protection published its plans for a mandatory code of conduct by the end of July. According to the plan, news organizations will be able to negotiate payment for their content with Google and Facebook - and if the group fails to reach an agreement after a three-month process, &quot;independent arbitrators will choose within 45 business days which of the two parties&#39; final bids is most suitable.&quot; Day. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australian cashier Josh Friedenberg said Facebook and Google could be forced to pay hundreds of millions of dollars in &quot;substantial sanctions&quot; if they failed to comply with the guidelines, according to the BBC.<br />\r\nFacebook said in a statement that its plans &quot;misunderstand the dynamics of the Internet and will hurt the news organizations themselves which the government is trying to protect&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If we accept that this draft code becomes law, we will be reluctant to stop giving publishers and people in Australia the opportunity to share local and international news on Facebook and Instagram,&quot; the company said. &quot;This is not our first choice - it will be our last. But it is the only way to prevent an outcome that goes against logic and is destructive and does not contribute to the long-term sustainability of the Australian news and media sector.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook also claims that news organizations in Australia benefit more from their relationship with Facebook than an article-sharing company.<br />\r\n&quot;In the first five months of 2020, we returned 2.3 billion clicks from our Facebook newsfeed to Australian news sites for free - about A $ 200 million in additional traffic for Australian publishers,&quot; the company said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook also stressed that other social networking services in the country will not change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an open letter, Google Australia claims that the regulations &quot;may result in your data being transferred to major news companies&quot;. In the letter, Google Australia also claimed that &quot;the law will force us to give one group of companies - the news media - an unfair advantage against anyone with a website, YouTube channel or small business.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the proposal, the media company produces content that &ldquo;examines and explains issues of concern to the Australian public; Issues that involve Australians in public debate and influence democratic decision-making; or issues related to local and local events &quot;are negotiable. Companies must also meet&quot; minimum standards for professional writing &quot;, maintain editorial independence, operate in Australia and earn over A $ 150,000 annually.<br />\r\nIn July, the government said the plan was designed to address &quot;a sharp imbalance in bargaining power between the Australian news business and Google and Facebook.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;News content provides significant benefits to digital platforms, far beyond limited direct revenue from advertising as opposed to news,&quot; said committee chairman Rod Sims in a summary of the proposal. &quot;The news business must receive a fair amount in return for this benefit.&quot;</p>', 'Facebook, Threatened', 'Facebook_1599838170.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:29:30', '2021-08-15 02:37:39'),
(415, 7, 5, 59, 'zooms-revenue-rose-nearly-3300-in-the-second-quarter-1599838209', 'Zoom\'s revenue rose nearly 3300% in the second quarter', 0, '<p><strong>Zoom Video Communications, a company that makes virtual dating software that has become a staple in the lives of many Americans during the pandemic, announced Monday that its net income was up nearly 3,300 percent to 185.7 million recently. The US dollar rose for the quarter ended July.</strong><br />\r\nRevenues more than quadrupled this quarter to $ 664 million. In just three months, the revenue overshadowed the company&#39;s sales last year. It was also nearly $ 200 million more than Wall Street analysts had expected.<br />\r\nZoom ended its second fiscal quarter with 370,200 customers with at least 10 employees, up from 265,400 at the end of April. A year ago, Zoom only had 66,300 subscribers in this category paying for subscriptions.<br />\r\nInvestors also use Zoom. The company&#39;s stock price has increased fivefold so far this year, giving the San Jose, California-based company a market value of $ 92 billion - more than General Motors and Ford combined. After Zoom shares on Monday, a new After hitting a record in regular trading, the stock rose nearly 9% in long-term trading after the income statement was published.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In early June, Zoom warned that there could be a wave of customer cancellations in the second half of this year as efforts to contain the spread of the new coronavirus allowed more workers to return to offices. But the ongoing epidemic has forced many big businessmen to close their offices for the rest of the year and possibly next summer, developments that could push Zoom even higher.<br />\r\nAs a sign of confidence, Zoom raised its revenue forecast for the fiscal year ending January to nearly $ 2.4 billion, compared with forecasts of around $ 1.8 billion in early June. That estimate now exceeds double Zoom&#39;s $ 910 million revenue expected at the start of the fiscal year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zoom is booming in large part because the worst pandemic in a century shut down a large part of the economy in March, and businessmen closed their offices and schools and closed their locations. This forces millions of workers and students to turn to Zoom and other video conferencing services to get work and school done.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zoom is quickly becoming the cheapest video conferencing service and establishing itself as the pandemic&#39;s favorite place to remotely connect everything from virtual cocktail parties to complex court hearings in addition to everyday work.<br />\r\nThe sudden search seems to find Zoom at first, leaving the service vulnerable to hackers and criminals exploiting security flaws to break into or eavesdrop on meetings. Zoom believes he closed most of the doors and ended up winning over several school districts that were temporarily closed for security reasons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recently, Zoom has had a serious breakdown as many schools resume online classes after summer break. Although the blackout only lasted a few hours, the disruption has raised awareness of an increasingly dependent public on teleconferencing software.</p>', 'Zoom, Revenue increase', 'Zoom_1599838209.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:30:09', '2021-08-12 20:56:42'),
(416, 7, 5, 108, 'amazons-delivery-drone-has-been-approved-by-the-faa-1599838352', 'Amazon\'s delivery drone has been approved by the FAA', 0, '<p><strong>The sky&#39;s the limit, at least for e-commerce giant Amazon. This weekend, Amazon Prime Air received approval from the Federal Aviation Administration to operate its unmanned aerial vehicle.</strong><br />\r\nThe FAA on Saturday gave Amazon a token of approval for its drone delivery system, ultimately aiming to deliver light packages to customers in sparsely populated areas within 30 minutes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The Amazon Prime Air concept uses an autonomous unmanned aerial vehicle system to deliver packages to customers safely and efficiently,&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The agency stressed its role as a safety regulator, saying it supports &quot;innovations that benefit the public, especially during a health or weather crisis&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Amazon, the agreement marks a milestone for Prime Air and the speed of delivery. The concept is still in the testing phase, but could be implemented on a large scale, according to David Carbon, Vice President of Prime Air.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This certification is an important step forward for Prime Air and demonstrates the FAA&#39;s confidence in Amazon&#39;s operating and safety procedures for the autonomous unmanned aerial vehicle service that will one day deliver packages to our customers worldwide.&quot; Carbon statement.<br />\r\nCertificates are awarded under Part 135 of the FAA regulations, which requires a demonstration of the concept of autonomous package delivery to Amazon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amazon said it would use FAA approval to launch drone test flights for specific customer deliveries in the hope that one day the technology would serve its customers around the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPS and Alphabet Wing have previously received FAA approval to operate their own unmanned aerial vehicle delivery service.</p>', 'Amazon, Drone, FAA', 'Amazon Approval_1599838352.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:32:32', '2021-08-17 14:58:56'),
(417, 7, 5, 112, 'the-chinese-government-has-limited-sales-of-tiktok-ordered-by-trump-1599838541', 'The Chinese government has limited sales of TikTok ordered by Trump', 0, '<p><strong>The Chinese government makes it difficult to sell US assets to TikTok on behalf of the US government.</strong><br />\r\nChina on Friday restricted exports of artificial intelligence technology, apparently among the kind TikTok uses to choose which videos to distribute to its users. This means TikTok owner ByteDance in China must have a license to export limited technology to foreign companies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is clearly aimed at delaying negotiations on the ByteDance deal in this high-stakes poker game,&quot; said Dan Ives, an analyst at Wedbush, in a research note. &quot;By playing with the TikTok key algorithm, ByteDance / TikTok will likely have to go through a licensing process to move software code from China to the US,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nThe Trump administration threatened to ban TikTok in mid-September and ordered ByteDance to sell its US businesses, asserting a national security risk due to Chinese ownership. The government is concerned that consumer data will be disclosed to Chinese authorities. TikTok denies this poses a national security risk and demands that the government does not threaten the ban.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Potential buyers of US TikTok assets include Microsoft and Walmart, as well as possibly Oracle. Oracle declined to comment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Saturday, China&#39;s state-run Xinhua News Agency quoted state trade adviser and Professor Cui Fan as saying ByteDance should consider suspending talks about selling TikTok in the US.<br />\r\n&quot;As with cross-border transactions, we will follow applicable laws, which in this case also includes the United States and China,&quot; said ByteDance consultant Erich Andersen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Chinese government&#39;s new restrictions could be TikTok&#39;s &quot;ranking tactic,&quot; Alex Zukin, an analyst at RBC Capital Markets, told the Associated Press. Even so, according to AP, Zukin hopes the agreement can be announced &quot;in the near future&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week, the Wall Street Journal reported that ByteDance wanted $ 30 billion for US operations but met with opposition from bidders. The paper said in a news item Sunday that negotiations on the deal were &quot;on hold&quot;.</p>', 'Chines Government, Tiktok, Trump', 'Tiktok China_1599838541.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:35:41', '2021-08-13 21:05:03'),
(418, 7, 5, 89, 'twitter-warned-of-a-video-by-a-top-republican-parliament-manipulating-the-words-of-a-disabled-activist-1599839117', 'Twitter warned of a video by a top Republican parliament manipulating the words of a disabled activist', 0, '<p><strong>The GOP&#39;s top congressman tweeted a video that changed the words of a disabled activist who interviewed Joe Biden, creating the false impression that Biden said he supported the decisive police. Twitter signaled the video as &quot;infiltrated content,&quot; and the activist said the congressman owed an apology to &quot;the entire community of people with disabilities&quot;.</strong><br />\r\nLouisiana Congressman Steve Scalis, a second-rate Republican in parliament, covered the documentary from a conversation in July between Biden and Adi Barkan, who has ALS (also known as Lou Gehrig&#39;s disease), who spoke into a computer voice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In his full interview, Barkan once said to Biden: &quot;We can reduce the responsibility given to the police and divert some of the funds for social services, psychological counseling and affordable housing.&quot; He asked if Biden was &quot;open to this type of reform&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;I propose this type of reform,&quot; Biden said before answering at length about the need to increase funding for mental health services. He noted, &quot;This is not the same as getting rid of or neutralizing all cops.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Barkan then asked, &quot;But do we agree that we can divert some of the funds?&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Yes. Sure,&quot; said Biden.<br />\r\nThe fraudulent video Scalise shared manipulated Barkan&#39;s computerized voice to answer his question in &quot;But do we agree we can give some of the funds to the police?&quot; To replace.<br />\r\nScalis tweeted the video that was continued, writing, &quot;No police. Crowd rule. Total chaos. This is the result of the Democratic program.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Biden has repeatedly stated that he does not support the removal or removal of the police department. The Trump campaign and many of Trump&#39;s GOP supporters continue to claim that Biden supports them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Barkan, who was present at this year&#39;s Democratic Assembly, urged Scalise to share the fake footage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These are not my words. I lost the ability to speak, but not my agency or my mind,&quot; he tweeted at Scalise.<br />\r\n&quot;You and your team treat my word for your own political gain. Please delete this video immediately. You owe an apology to the entire disabled community.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Biden also stepped in, tweeting Barkan again, writing, &quot;This video is about a graduate student - and a gruff attempt to spread misinformation at the expense of someone using assistive technology. This video should be removed. Now.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scalise has deleted the tweet. But his office still protects him from sharing rigged videos. Scalise spokeswoman Lauren Fine told the Washington Post that the video &quot;condensed&quot; into &quot;the essence of what [Barkan] wants&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We paired the police station with Barkan&#39;s last question for clarity because we couldn&#39;t fit a full 3 minute clip into a one-minute edit,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Twitter Warende, Videos', 'Twitter_1599838716.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:38:36', '2021-08-15 23:32:00'),
(419, 7, 5, 81, 'spacex-canceled-one-launch-it-succeeded-by-one-second-1599839440', 'SpaceX canceled one launch, it succeeded by one second', 0, '<p><strong>Planned first of the SpaceX Falcon 9&#39;s two launches was canceled on Sunday due to bad weather. However, later on, the company managed to take advantage of better conditions to launch an Argentine satellite to remotely monitor the spectacular orbit around Earth&#39;s poles.&nbsp;</strong><br />\r\nIt was the 100th flight of SpaceX rockets since 2006, the 92 for the Falcon 9 family, and the first since 1969 to send a rocket from Cape Canaveral to its southeastern trajectory over Cuba en route to its satellite payload polar orbit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews2.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/08/30/32075c1c-314a-4121-ada3-f16b81f271db/thumbnail/620x348/b3e16b55a863c7c4f938a02820e9380c/083020-launch1.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nIn addition to the drama, Falcon 9&#39;s first flight, which had flown earlier, returned to the Air Force&#39;s proper landing at Cape Canaveral and rocked the space shores with multiple sonic booms that could be heard as far as Orlando. It was only Florida&#39;s second landing of 12 recoveries that year, 59th place on SpaceX overall.<br />\r\nMoonwalker Buzz Aldrin watched takeoff from his home a few miles south of the Air Force Station and tweeted &quot;good job @SpaceX&quot; to land &quot;in my backyard&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/media/EgtLAHpXcAE4kJS?format=jpg&amp;name=240x240\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nSpaceX plans to launch two Falcon 9s just nine hours apart on Sunday. This is the shortest time between the two American classes starting out of orbit since 1966. The double-headed ball comes after the last-minute dramatic &quot;fireside&quot; Saturday morning at United. Launch the Alliance Delta 4 heavy missile from the National Intelligence Service&#39;s secret spy satellite.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The flagship of Sunday&#39;s flight plan is the Falcon 9, which is designed to carry 60 Starlink space relays from historic site 39A at the Kennedy Space Center. The SAOCOM 1B mission follows the example of a nearby air force station.<br />\r\nBut the Starlink repeaters were removed from the hangars the previous Sunday, and SpaceX later tweeted that the team had stopped launching &quot;due to bad weather during flight operations&quot;. The next chance to launch Starlinks is on Tuesdays at 9:29 p.m.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For most of the day, SAOCOM 1B flight times did not appear, but the storm died down as the day progressed and the second take-off window, circling around Falcon 9, was cleared for takeoff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The mission started at 19:18. when the nine main propulsion motors are started, they go out to full thrust and the missile propels the Pad 40 under the still cloudy sky. In addition to the Argentine satellite in the rocket&#39;s nose cone, two small tourism satellites were added to aviation as part of a &quot;share-share&quot; agreement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All previous Falcon 9s fired from Florida rose to the east or northeast. To enter polar orbit from Cape Canaveral, the SAOCOM 1B Falcon 9 takes off to the southeast and then performs a &quot;dogleg&quot; maneuver after exiting the Florida coast to turn a further southward trajectory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews2.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/08/31/b80742e4-f723-4266-a99a-63269a6e89cf/thumbnail/620x230/854ad8e72695fe060d279a72e3e85134/083020-landing.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 1960, falling debris from a damaged missile killed a cow in Cuba and sparked protests in the island nation. All orbital flight missions in 1969 began at Vandenberg, where the missile remained until it orbited over the Pacific.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SpaceX originally planned to launch SAOCOM 1B from Vandenberg, but applied for permission to move flights to Cape Canaveral to resolve ground handling issues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The company is believed to have received government approval for the move, partly due to maneuverability that minimizes excess flight, the high altitude of missiles reaching more densely populated areas, and the fact that the Falcon 9 has automation. has an aviation security system. AFTS is designed to end flights quickly when an impending catastrophic problem is detected.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 6,720 pound SAOCOM 1B requires a polar orbit so its cloud penetration radar can monitor the entire planet as it rotates from below. The spacecraft is operated according to the identical L-band mapper radar launched in 2018 along with the Italian satellite COSMO-SkyMed X-Band.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bound to a 360-mile orbit, the $ 600 million SOACOM system is used to monitor soil moisture and a host of other factors affecting the agricultural sector by gathering high-resolution data over time, regardless of cloud cover.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One of the main goals of the SAOCOM satellite is to provide information about the agricultural sector,&quot; Raul Kulichevski, executive and technical director of CONAE, the Argentine space agency, told Spaceflight Now.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One of the things we are developing is a soil moisture map, not only on the surface, but by using the L-band capability, we can measure soil moisture 1 meter below the surface. So this is very important. Information.&quot;</p>', 'SpaceX Canceled, Onle Launched', 'SpaceX_1599839440.jpg', '2020-09-11 19:50:40', '2021-08-12 00:09:35'),
(420, 4, 1, 54, 'coronavirus-oxford-university-vaccine-trial-paused-after-participant-falls-ill-1599851885', 'Coronavirus: Oxford University vaccine trial paused after participant falls ill', 0, '<p>Last clinical preliminaries for a Covid antibody, created by AstraZeneca and Oxford University, have been required to be postponed after a member had a speculated antagonistic response in the UK.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AstraZeneca portrayed it as an &quot;everyday practice&quot; stop on account of &quot;an unexplained ailment&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The result of antibody preliminaries is by and large firmly viewed the world over.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AstraZeneca-Oxford University antibody is viewed as a solid competitor among handfuls being grown worldwide.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oxford Covid antibody triggers safe reaction&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How near building up an antibody right?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What medications can help treat Covid?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Expectations have been high that the immunization may be one of the first to come available, after effective stage 1 and 2 testing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Its transition to Phase 3 testing as of late has included exactly 30,000 members in the US just as in the UK, Brazil and South Africa. Stage 3 preliminaries in antibodies frequently include a large number of members and can most recent quite a while.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The New York Times is detailing a volunteer in the UK preliminary has been determined to have cross over myelitis, a provocative condition that influences the spinal line and can be brought about by viral diseases.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, the reason for the sickness has not been affirmed and a free examination will presently work out if there was any connect to the antibody.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Choice on restarting preliminary could be days away&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From the outset this may appear to be disturbing. An immunization preliminary - and any antibody, yet one getting monstrous worldwide consideration - is required to be postponed because of a speculated genuine unfriendly response. However, such occasions are not incredible. To be sure the Oxford group portray it as &quot;normal&quot;. Whenever a volunteer is admitted to emergency clinic and the reason for their sickness isn&#39;t promptly obvious it triggers an examination to be required to be postponed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is really the second time it has occurred with the Oxford University/AstraZeneca Covid immunization preliminary since the primary volunteers were vaccinated in April. An Oxford University representative stated: &quot;In huge preliminaries, ailments will occur by chance yet should be freely looked into to check this cautiously.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A ultimate choice on restarting the preliminary will be taken by the clinical controller the MHRA, which could take just days. Be that as it may, up to that point all worldwide immunization locales, in the UK, Brazil, South Africa and the USA are waiting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Oxford University group accept this cycle outlines that they are focused on the wellbeing of their volunteers and the best expectations of lead in their examinations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wellcome Trust chief Sir Jeremy Farrar, a specialist in irresistible illness control, said there were regularly stops in immunization preliminaries and it was significant any antagonistic responses were paid attention to.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is urgent that all that information is shared straightforwardly and straightforwardly on the grounds that the open must have total trust that these immunizations are sheltered and viable and, at long last, will ideally conclude the pandemic,&quot; Sir Jeremy included.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UK specialists have said an impermanent interruption could be viewed as something to be thankful for on the grounds that it demonstrated the analysts are organizing the wellbeing of immunization above everything else.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Individuals can create symptoms from taking any medication however they can likewise become sick normally.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where are we in the quest for an antibody?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>US President Donald Trump has said he needs an antibody accessible in the US before 3 November&#39;s political decision, however his remarks have raised feelings of dread that governmental issues might be organized over security in the scramble for an immunization.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Tuesday, a gathering of nine Covid-19 antibody engineers tried to console the general population by reporting a &quot;memorable promise&quot; to maintain logical and moral principles in the quest for an immunization.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AstraZeneca is among the nine firms who joined to the vow to just apply for administrative endorsement after immunizations have experienced three periods of clinical examination.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Media captionCoronavirus antibody: How close would we say we are and who will get it?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Industry goliaths Johnson and Johnson, BioNTech, GlaxoSmithKline, Pfizer, Merck, Moderna, Sanofi and Novavax are different signatories.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They promised to &quot;consistently make the wellbeing and prosperity of immunized people our first concern&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alternate routes and &#39;filthy stunts&#39; in the scramble for an antibody&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In what capacity will the world inoculate seven billion individuals?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The World Health Organization (WHO) says about 180 antibody applicants are being tried far and wide yet none has yet finished clinical preliminaries.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The association has said it doesn&#39;t anticipate that an antibody should meet its viability and wellbeing rules so as to be endorsed for the current year due to the time it takes to test them securely.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Comparable slants have been shared by Thomas Cueni, chief general of the International Federation of Pharmaceutical Manufacturers. The business body speaks to the organizations that marked the promise.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In spite of this, China and Russia have started immunizing some key laborers with locally created antibodies. Every one of them are as yet recorded by the WHO as being in clinical preliminaries.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the interim, the US public controller, the Food and Drug Administration (FDA), has proposed that Covid immunizations might be endorsed before finishing a third period of clinical preliminaries.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A week ago it additionally developed that the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention had encouraged states to consider postponing certain necessities so as to be prepared to convey a possible immunization by 1 November - two days before the 3 November presidential political race.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In spite of the fact that President Trump has indicated that an antibody may be accessible before the political decision, his Democratic adversary Joe Biden has communicated wariness that Mr Trump will tune in to researchers and actualize a straightforward cycle.</p>', 'Coronavirus, Oxford University', '_114291816_mediaitem114291815_1599851885.jpg', '2020-09-11 23:18:05', '2021-08-12 22:54:29'),
(421, 4, 1, 68, 'coronavirus-social-gatherings-above-six-banned-in-england-from-14-september-1599852085', 'Coronavirus: Social gatherings above six banned in England from 14 September', 0, '<p>Get-togethers of in excess of six individuals will be illicit in England from Monday - with certain exceptions - in the midst of a precarious ascent in Covid cases.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The law change will boycott bigger gatherings meeting anyplace socially inside or outside, the legislature said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, it won&#39;t matter to schools, working environments or Covid-secure weddings, memorial services and sorted out group activities.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It will be authorized through a &pound;100 fine if individuals neglect to consent, multiplying on every offense up to a limit of &pound;3,200.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new principles - which come into power on 14 September - mark a change to England&#39;s present direction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At present, the direction says two families of any size are permitted to meet inside or outside, or up to six individuals from various families outside. As of recently the police have had no forces to stop get-togethers except if they surpassed 30.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Head administrator Boris Johnson will give further subtleties of the progressions at a Downing Street news meeting at 16:00 BST on Wednesday, close by senior consultants Prof Chris Whitty and Sir Patrick Vallance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What are the new principles for meeting my companions?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Five reasons ascend in Covid cases isn&#39;t all it appears&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One of the bits of criticism we had including from the police was that we required the guidelines to be very straightforward so everyone comprehends what they are,&quot; said Health Secretary Matt Hancock.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Furthermore, presently this will currently be thoroughly implemented by the police.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Media captionOne and two meter social separating - what does it resemble?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Hancock revealed to BBC Breakfast: &quot;This is truly straightforward. Get-togethers are alright, they ought to be socially separated obviously, however bunches just of up to six.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said it implies that a few families won&#39;t have the option to see the two grandparents simultaneously. &quot;You know, I have three youngsters,&quot; he said. &quot;We have a group of five. Thus we&#39;ll have the option to see each other individual in turn, in general family.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tested on whether the new principles could stop grandparents assisting with childcare, Mr Hancock stated: &quot;I&#39;m not effectively attempting&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, he said the legislature is &quot;very stressed over&quot; the &quot;intense issue&quot; of youngsters possibly giving the infection to more established grandparents.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Want to turn it around by Christmas&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Matt Hancock said the standards would be set up for &quot;years to come&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I truly trust we can turn this round before Christmas. I believe that, in a pandemic, Christmas is far off,&quot; he revealed to BBC Radio 4.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;A quarter of a year is quite a while in a pandemic and I especially trust this solid guideline, along with the neighborhood move we&#39;ve made in places like Bolton... I especially trust accordingly this can attempt to do that by Christmas.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>THE NAKED SCIENTISTS: Where did COVID-19 originate from?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>THE SECRET LIFE OF TEACHERS: What&#39;s it like getting back to homerooms in the midst of a worldwide pandemic?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Hancock was likewise gotten some information about testing, after individuals with manifestations battled to get to testing as of late.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Sadly we have seen this very sharp ascent over the most recent few weeks of individuals without manifestations who don&#39;t have a valid justification approaching and getting a test,&quot; he stated, saying 25% of individuals who were getting a Covid test were not qualified.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve even heard accounts of individuals saying &#39;I&#39;m going on vacation one week from now in this way I will go get a test&#39;. No. That is not what the testing framework is there for.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Initially: What are the new standards?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Get-togethers of in excess of six individuals in England won&#39;t be permitted in law from Monday 14 September&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new principle applies to individuals in private homes, inside and outside, and places, for example, bars, caf&eacute;s, bistros and open air spaces&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It applies to all ages&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The standard doesn&#39;t matter to schools and working environments, or weddings, memorial services and sorted out group activities&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A full rundown of exclusions is expected to be distributed under the steady gaze of the law changes&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Individuals who overlook police could be fined &pound;100 - multiplying with every offense to a limit of &pound;3,200&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Educator Sir Jeremy Farrar, who sits on the administration&#39;s logical warning board of trustees, said the following four to about a month and a half &quot;will be totally critical to such a fall and winter we have&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So I am extremely steady of the limitations coming in and genuinely trust they will be sufficient.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laura Kuenssberg: The administration&#39;s admonition framework is blazing red&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UK Covid cases up by 2,460 - check the numbers in your general vicinity&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a few exemptions to the new principles. Families and backing bubbles greater than six can mingle together - however not with any other individual simultaneously - and social occasions can be more than six in the event that it is for work or training purposes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Archbishop of Canterbury, Justin Welby, said the new standards didn&#39;t influence spots of love as that may be &quot;not a party&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, Parkrun - which not long ago declared it was to continue in England - is &quot;unaffected&quot; as it is a sorted out game, its coordinators said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No 10 said any gathering of at least seven individuals assembling anyplace &quot;chances being scattered by police or fined for rebelliousness&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BBC political reporter Nick Eardley brought up that bars and caf&eacute;s would be permitted to have in excess of six clients inside, yet that the gatherings of six would need to be socially removed from one another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The reason behind permitting this, however not permitting bigger gatherings of individuals inside others&#39; homes, is that organizations must be open in the event that they follow security and cleanliness apportions set by the administration, he included.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bringing down Street said Mr Johnson held a virtual roundtable with police powers a week ago, and heard officials needed more clear standards and implementation on social contact.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The declined organizations in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland can set their own Covid limitations and, while to a great extent actualizing comparable guidelines, have moved at their own pace during the pandemic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The quantity of individuals permitted to meet inside or outside fluctuates in the UK&#39;s four countries. In the event that you are meeting inside: up to eight individuals from three distinct family units can meet in Scotland; up to six individuals from two families in Northern Ireland; up to four families can frame a &quot;broadened family unit&quot; in Wales.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Media captionWhat is the R number and I&#39;m not catching it&#39;s meaning?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pastors and government counselors prior communicated worry over a &quot;sharp ascent&quot; in cases and a &quot;sincere&quot; expression of remorse was given after deficiencies in England&#39;s trying framework.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Generally speaking, there have been 8,396 new cases detailed since Sunday - with 2,460 covered Tuesday alone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There were additionally 32 passings announced, however these won&#39;t have been identified with the latest ascent in cases.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enormous get-togethers &#39;most serious danger&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The forbidding of get-togethers of more than six individuals is incompletely about taking care of a particular issue - giving police forces to crackdown on enormous social events.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It likewise gives clergymen and authorities the chance to caution people in general against lack of concern with signs diseases might be on the ascent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, what is more significant is the place the UK goes from here.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lockdown got us time, yet has basically just conceded the issue - how to secure individuals, especially the most powerless, from the infection while keeping society working.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Better medicines, additionally testing and an organization of contact tracers has placed the UK in a superior situation than it was in the spring - despite the fact that there are issues with the last two.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Further limitations of pretty much any kind include some significant pitfalls - regardless of whether to wellbeing, instruction, the economy or each of the three.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It implies the UK, similar to all countries, is confronted with the incomprehensibly troublesome errand of adjusting hurts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With winter around the bend - when respiratory infections flourish - the choices are simply going to turn out to be much mor