(482, 4, 13, 161, 'brexit-gina-miller-says-2017-ruling-no-legal-defence-for-government-1599901297', 'Brexit: Gina Miller says 2017 ruling no legal defence for government', 0, '<p>Gina Miller has said the administration isn&#39;t right to utilize Parliamentary power as its legitimate guard for endeavoring to supersede the EU withdrawal understanding.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pastors state Mrs Miller&#39;s 2017 court triumph over Brexit maintained the &quot;key guideline&quot; that Parliament is sovereign in homegrown law and can enact to break arrangement commitments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, Mrs Miller says the two issues were &quot;mentally and legitimately particular&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 2017 decision, she stated, strengthened the &quot;significance of the standard of law&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mrs Miller was at the focal point of a milestone fight in court in which she tested the then PM Theresa May&#39;s entitlement to summon Article 50 - which started the way toward leaving the EU - without the express endorsement of Parliament.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Supreme Court collectively managed in support of herself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The court&#39;s decision is currently being refered to by Boris Johnson&#39;s legislature as the legitimate reason for proposed enactment which would change key parts of the EU Withdrawal Agreement - the lawfully restricting settlement which set out the terms on which the UK left the EU on 31 January - in case of the different sides not concurring a future exchange association.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>EU exchange talks hang in balance in the midst of Brexit bargain column&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How could the Northern Ireland Brexit bargain change?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The disputable Internal Markets Bill, to be discussed in the not so distant future, would enable the administration to change or scrap arrangements identifying with the Northern Ireland Protocol overseeing exchange between Northern Ireland and Great Britain and UK government uphold for Northern Irish organizations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The move has started outrage across Europe, with Ireland&#39;s Europe serve saying on Friday that for the UK to &quot;renege&quot; on a lawfully official arrangement was an exceptionally &quot;provocative&quot; act.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Amazed and baffled&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s more, Mrs Miller said she was &quot;astonished and disillusioned&quot; that pastors were utilizing the 2017 Supreme Court administering as legitimate defense for what she said were their &quot;subjective&quot; activities.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The issue of Parliamentary sway is mentally and lawfully unmistakable from global arrangement commitments went into by Her Majesty&#39;s administration,&quot; she said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 2017 decision, she included, &quot;represents the significance of the standard of law, something that this legislature appears to be resolved to sabotage&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mrs Miller was likewise instrumental in another fruitful lawful test a year ago, in which she upset the administration&#39;s endeavor to suspend Parliament for five weeks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While the agent portrays herself as a straightforwardness campaigner, pundits state she was constantly restricted to the UK&#39;s takeoff from the EU following the 2016 Brexit vote.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Restricting commitments&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an announcement delivered on Thursday, the legislature said it kept on remaining by the &quot;set up guideline&quot; of global law that a state is obliged to release its settlement commitments in compliance with common decency.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, it said the UK presently wound up in &quot;uncommon conditions&quot; and when Parliament endorsed the Withdrawal Agreement recently, the enactment used to do it &quot;explicitly affirmed&quot; its capacity to ignore arrangements coming first the Agreement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Parliament is sovereign as an issue of homegrown law and can pass enactment which is in break of the UK&#39;s deal commitments,&quot; it said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightHOUSE OF COMMOSNS&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture inscription&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lawyer General Suella Braverman has said the administration is qualified for do what it is doing&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Settlement commitments just become authoritative to the degree that they are cherished in homegrown enactment. Regardless of whether to sanction or cancelation enactment, and the substance of that enactment, is for Parliament and Parliament alone.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This guideline, it expressed, had been &quot;affirmed&quot; by the Supreme Court in its 2017 decision.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This understanding has been contested by some driving legal advisors, raising the chance of another legitimate test before the finish of post-Brexit progress period on 31 December.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There have been unsubstantiated reports of a split among the administration&#39;s three boss law officials over the subject of whether clergymen would end up in penetrate of the pastoral code by proposing enactment that was unequivocally in resistance of worldwide law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Guardian guaranteed that both Attorney General Suella Braverman and her agent Michael Ellis had contended that it would not yet that Lord Keen, the Advocate General for Scotland, had taken the contrary view.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Master Keen, who spoke to the legislature in the 2017 case, has safeguarded its activities as of late. He told the Lords no penetrate of UK law was being proposed and the administration was compelled by a sense of honor to &quot;release its commitments&quot; to Northern Ireland in the event that they couldn&#39;t be settled through the EU-UK contest goal measure.</p>', 'Gina Miller', '_92867193_gina_miller_2_getty_1599901297.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:01:37', '2021-12-19 17:41:09'),
(483, 7, 5, 248, 'mark-zuckerberg-said-facebook-made-an-operational-mistake-by-not-moving-police-stations-1599902096', 'Mark Zuckerberg said Facebook made an \"operational mistake\" by not moving police stations', 0, '<p><strong>Facebook made a mistake earlier this week by failing to remove the website of a police group urging armed civilians to enter Kenosha, Wisconsin after violent protests after police shot Jacob Blake, CEO Mark Zuckerberg said.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe Kenosha Guardian page violated Facebook guidelines and was tagged by &quot;a group of people,&quot; Zuckerberg said in a video posted on Facebook Friday. In recent weeks, the social media giant has issued new guidelines to remove or restrict posts from groups that threaten public safety.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook closed the page on Wednesday after a 17-year-old gunman allegedly killed two people and injured the third Tuesday night during a protest in Kenosha after Blake, who was black, was shot.<br />\r\n&quot;It was largely an operational error,&quot; said Zuckerberg. &quot;The players, reviewers, to whom the first complaint was addressed, didn&#39;t really accept this.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zuckerberg did not apologize for the error, saying Facebook had not found any evidence that Kyle Rittenhouse was aware of the Kenosha Guard page or the invitation he posted for armed militias to Kenosha.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook is now removing posts praising the shooting or the shooter, Zuckerberg said. However, a report by The Guardian on Thursday found instances of support and even donation messages still being shared on Facebook and photo-sharing service Instagram.<br />\r\nZuckerberg also rejected the treatment of Blake, who was shot in the back by Kenosha police, and the 17-year-old white man accused of Tuesday&#39;s murder, Kyle Rittenhouse, who had an AR-15 rifle in proximity to police carried out without being challenged.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zuckerberg also confirmed civil rights demonstrations in Washington on Friday</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It felt like things weren&#39;t really getting better at the pace they should be and I thought it was very painful and very scary,&quot; said Zuckerberg.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zuckerberg also said the company was working on improving its performance, although it did not provide details. He acknowledged that the upcoming presidential election will present a bigger challenge in terms of content polarization.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;During this very sensitive, polarized and highly polluted time, there are real risks and risks that continue to increase during the election,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Mark Zuckerberg, Facebook owner, Operational Mistake', 'Mark Zukerberg_1599902096.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:14:56', '2021-08-17 13:20:37'),
(484, 7, 5, 54, 'social-media-censorship-thats-not-what-you-think-1599902432', 'Social Media Censorship? That\'s not what you think', 0, '<p><strong>Musician Joy Villa&#39;s red carpet at the Grammy Awards over the past three years has been embellished with pro-Trump messages that cement him as a vocal favorite of the conservative movement. With more than 500,000 followers on Instagram, Facebook, YouTube and Twitter, Villa called his social media community &quot;Joy of the Tribe&quot; and recruited him several years ago to wage a public battle against his alleged experiences. YouTube is censoring it.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I posted the Make America Great Again music video on YouTube and it was downloaded from YouTube in a matter of hours,&quot; Villa told CBSN Originals. &quot;I took it to my other social media. I said to my fans,&quot; Hey, listen, YouTube is censoring me. This is unfair censorship. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Villa sees him as part of a model of social media companies trying to shut out conservative voices - an accusation made by many like-minded users, including President Trump himself, against Facebook, YouTube and Twitter in recent years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cbsnews1.cbsistatic.com/hub/i/r/2020/08/28/9ef4ab51-ea97-4bd6-be3b-bc4134668ab9/thumbnail/620x349/592857f0ecddfeb0f59b2910b635d407/acq-yt-makeamericagreatagainmv-joyvilla-072817-mp4-00-02-39-06-still003.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nBut those who study tech industry practices say that deciding what content to leave behind and what not has nothing to do with &quot;censorship.&quot;<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\n&quot;The problem in the United States is that when we talk about free speech, we often misunderstand,&quot; said Henry Fernandez, co-chair of Change the Terms, a coalition of organizations working to reduce online hate. spread.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The first amendment is very specific: it protects all of us as Americans from a government that limits our speech,&quot; he said. When people talk about it, &quot;Well, if they shoot me off Facebook, it&#39;s an attack on my free speech or my first change on the right side&quot; - that&#39;s just not true. Companies have the option to choose which speeches they allow. You are not the government. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A YouTube spokesperson said Villa&#39;s video was warned not because of the statement but because of a privacy complaint. Villa denied this, but after smearing the face of someone who didn&#39;t want to be seen on video, YouTube got him back online and the video remains visible on the platform today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We always have rules on YouTube that define what is and cannot be published. Our rules have no concept of political affiliation or party and we apply them consistently, regardless of who uploads them,&quot; said YouTube spokesman Alex Joseph. .<br />\r\nWhile Villa and others on the right are voicing their grievances, activists on the other side of the political spectrum say their online speeches often cut out for reasons that have received little attention.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Carolyn Wassinger, an activist who provides Facebook feedback and guidance on minority platform user experiences, told CBSN Originals that implicit bias is an issue that influences content moderation decisions on most social media platforms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;By community standards, white men are a protected class, just like black trans women. Community standards don&#39;t take into account homophobia and violence and how these overlap. He sees them all as separate things that need to be protected,&quot; Wiesinger said. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So used to and depend on it. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Artificial intelligence tools that automate the moderation process and enforce community standards on websites don&#39;t recognize the intent or origin of the people who post them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, Wassinger said, &quot;I was told about the use of lynch images. ... I was told about violent content when I presented images of racism and transphobia.&quot;<br />\r\nAccording to a recent report on platform transparency, from April to June 2020, nearly 95% of comments flagged as hate speech on Facebook were discovered by AI. and on YouTube, 99.2% of comments removed for violating community standards were tagged by AI.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That means you apply these community standards and these bots only look for certain things. They are automatic. They can&#39;t make decisions about them,&quot; Wysinger said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prejudice can be built into algorithms by the programmer who designed them, even if not intentional.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Unfortunately, the technology is made up of a homogeneous group, mostly white and Asian men. So what happens is the opinion, the experience that goes into making this decision, reflects on the majority group. And so are people with different backgrounds - black people. . &quot; &quot;Different religions, conservatives, liberals - they don&#39;t have a definite picture if the company is more diverse,&quot; said Mark Lucky, a digital strategist who has previously worked at Twitter, Reddit and Facebook.<br />\r\nMark Zuckerberg, CEO of Facebook, said he believed the platform &quot;should be as expressive as possible&quot; and that social media companies &quot;shouldn&#39;t be brokering the truth about everything people say online&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, a recent study by the Pew Research Center found that nearly three-quarters of adults in the United States believe that social media sites deliberately censor political views. In the past two years, two hearings in Congress have discussed technology censorship.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We hear that there is anti-conservative prejudice from Facebook or other platforms because conservatives keep repeating this,&quot; said Susan Benesh, executive director of the Dangerous Speech Project, a Washington-based organization that has advised Facebook, Twitter, Google and others. . Internet companies are ways to reduce harmful content online while protecting freedom of expression.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But he added, &quot;I would be surprised if this was partly due to the fact that the most popular and most visited groups on Facebook and Facebook Pages are very conservative on an almost daily basis.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also finds it interesting that &quot;many conservatives or ultra-conservatives complain that platforms are biased, while Black Lives Matter activists believe that the platforms download their content disproportionately&quot;.<br />\r\nA 2019 review of more than 400 political Facebook pages by left-wing media analyst Media Matters found conservative pages fared the same as liberal pages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, reliable data on this issue is scarce, and social media platforms are largely unsure of how to make decisions about how to moderate content.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amid persistent criticism, Facebook has commissioned an independent review, led by former Republican Senator John Kiel, to investigate allegations of anti-conservative bias. The 2019 Kyl report contains detailed recommendations for improving transparency. Facebook agreed to form a board of directors to make decisions about content removal. Facebook said it would &quot;further research our future policies and practices and adapt them if necessary&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fernandez said the focus should be on obliging technology companies to publicly disclose their moderation rules and tactics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Benes points out, &quot;We have almost no control over downloads, so moderating content is actually more complicated than simply downloading or releasing content.&quot; from technology companies to enable process assessment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Protecting freedom of expression while keeping people safe is a challenge that needs to be continuously improved and refined. We are working with outside experts and affected communities around the world to develop our policies and we have a global team dedicated to implementing them,&quot; said in a statement on Facebook. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Twitter&#39;s statement reads: &quot;Twitter does not use political ideology to make decisions about whether to judge content on our services or how we enforce our policies. From a simple business perspective and to serve public calls, tell Twitter to keep all votes on the service.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, users like Wysinger grapple with mixed feelings about social media websites promising connections but sometimes leaving them in the dark.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Like it or not, we were on Facebook, Instagram and Twitter all day and when they blacklisted us, I didn&#39;t know of anyone who didn&#39;t post on Facebook as soon as the ban was lifted: &#39;I&#39;m back!&#39; said Wiesinger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s like a forced relationship, you can&#39;t even leave a forced relationship because of you</p>', 'Social Media, Censorship', 'Cencorship on social media_1599902432.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:20:32', '2021-08-12 00:09:25'),
(485, 4, 12, 62, 'scottish-labour-leader-to-face-no-confidence-vote-1599902524', 'Scottish Labour leader to face no-confidence vote', 0, '<p>The pioneer of Scottish Labor is to confront a demonstration of majority disapproval at a gathering of the gathering&#39;s overseeing body.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A movement hosts been submitted to the gathering&#39;s Scottish Executive Committee (SEC) asking it express that it has no trust in Richard Leonard&#39;s authority.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The council is required to decide on the movement on Saturday morning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Leonard is now confronting calls to stop from his very own portion MSPs - yet says he has no goal of doing as such.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is perceived that the movement to the SEC has been marked by 33% of its individuals - which means it will go to a vote of the full board of trustees.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The council is made up chose delegates just as worker&#39;s organization authorities and agents of the gathering&#39;s grassroots participation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Work MSPs endeavor to trigger initiative challenge&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leonard blames Labor rivals for &#39;damage&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fourth MSP calls for Scottish Labor pioneer to stop&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Leonard said that huge numbers of the SEC individuals who had marked the movement were &quot;not ordered by their associations to cast a ballot in that manner&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s more, he said the exact opposite thing Labor supporters and potential electors needed to see was simply the gathering &quot;turning in&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said the transition to expel him was &quot;altogether factional&quot;, including: &quot;They don&#39;t have anything to state or offer, no thoughts, no arrangement to secure positions and expectations for everyday comforts against the setting of the Covid emergency.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It comes after four Scottish Labor MSPs - James Kelly, Daniel Johnson, Jenny Marra and Mark Griffin - freely called for Mr Leonard to leave prior this month.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They host guaranteed that the gathering faces &quot;fiasco&quot; at the following year&#39;s Scottish Parliament political decision in the event that he stays in his post.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Leonard, who was a nearby partner of previous UK Labor pioneer Jeremy Corbyn, still appreciates the help of numerous on the left of the gathering.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, his faultfinders highlight the gathering&#39;s bleak assessment of public sentiment appraisals as confirmation that change is required.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scottish Labor is at present the third biggest in the Scottish Parliament, behind the SNP and Conservatives, and lost everything except one of its MPs in a year ago&#39;s broad political race.</p>', 'Scottish Labour', '_114325198_gettyimages-1219281788_1599902524.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:22:04', '2021-08-15 17:22:09'),
(486, 4, 12, 57, 'coronavirus-england-and-wales-contact-tracing-app-gets-launch-date-1599902613', 'Coronavirus: England and Wales\' contact-tracing app gets launch date', 0, '<p>Another Covid-19 contact-following application will be dispatched across England and Wales on 24 September, the administration has declared.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The application will let individuals examine scanner tag like QR codes to enroll visits to accommodation scenes and will execute Apple and Google&#39;s technique for recognizing different cell phones.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Organizations are being approached to show QR code banners to help the application.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wellbeing Secretary Matt Hancock depicted the dispatch as &quot;a pivotal turning point&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The principal adaptation of the NHS contact-following application, expected for the entire of the UK, was tested on the Isle of Wight in May however later deserted.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have to utilize each instrument available to us to control the spread of the infection including bleeding edge innovation,&quot; said Mr Hancock.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The dispatch of the application in the not so distant future across England and Wales is an extremely important occasion and will help our capacity to contain the infection at a crucial time.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As indicated by the most recent figures distributed by the Office for National Statistics, there were an expected 3,200 new cases a day in England during the primary seven day stretch of September, contrasted and 2,000 the prior week.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some cordiality scenes have just been utilizing their own QR code-based frameworks for test and follow yet are currently being approached to change to the NHS form.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Colleges, medical clinics, relaxation premises, urban focuses and libraries are being approached to show banners in collective zones, for example, bistros, where individuals assemble for longer than 15 minutes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An elective framework, for example, a transcribed register, should likewise be kept up for guests who don&#39;t have cell phones, the Department of Health and Social Care said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do I need to give my contact subtleties in the event that I eat out?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coronavirus following application is delivered in NI&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scotland&#39;s Covid application downloaded just about multiple times&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Welsh Health and Social Services Minister Vaughan Gething said dispatching a joint application with England was &quot;the most viable alternative&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He included that the move reflects &quot;development over our common outskirt&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It bodes well to utilize the equivalent application, working in the very same way, paying little mind to which nation you&#39;re in.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Presentational dark line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Investigation box by Rory Cellan-Jones, innovation journalist&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has had a long and pained incubation yet the group behind the NHS Covid-19 application are trusting that they&#39;ve at last got it directly when it can make a critical commitment to restricting the spread of the infection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Back in April, an application appeared to be a key weapon in the administration&#39;s arsenal however since Baroness Dido Harding assumed control over the Test and Trace program, it&#39;s been consigned to the &quot;cherry on the cake&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Around the globe there are despite everything questions among those dealing with contact following applications about exactly how great Bluetooth is as a method of estimating the separation between individuals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, the way that bars, eateries and other neighborliness organizations are currently being advised they need to make a superior showing of logging contact subtleties of guests presents a chance.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They may now observe having QR codes for guests as a basic method of conforming to the standards, and that could empower take-up of the application.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There has been some disarray about whether organizations will conform to the standards on gathering client information in the event that they depend on the application. However, I&#39;ve been informed that they will be consistent despite the fact that the idea of the application implies none of the information will be obvious either to them or to the specialists.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Presentational dim line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Flag picture perusing &#39;more about Covid&#39;s&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SOCIAL DISTANCING: What are the standards now?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Backing BUBBLES: What are they and who can be in yours?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FACE MASKS: When do I have to wear one?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TESTING: What tests are accessible?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Flag&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scotland dispatched its own application on Thursday that has just been downloaded about multiple times.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Protect Scotland application illuminates individuals in the event that they have been in close contact with somebody who later tests positive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Northern Ireland was the initial segment of the UK to dispatch a contact-following application - StopCOVID NI was authoritatively dispatched toward the finish of July.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In England, from Monday, get-togethers will be restricted to up to six individuals - in a measure named &quot;the standard of six&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has been reprimanded by some Conservative MPs who have said it ought to be exposed to more parliamentary examination.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scotland and Wales - which alongside Northern Ireland have lapsed forces to set their own Covid limitations - likewise decreased the size of get-togethers to six individuals from Monday.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Scotland, youngsters younger than 12 won&#39;t tally towards the aggregate, and in Wales the standard won&#39;t make a difference to kids under 11 and up to 30 individuals can in any case meet outside.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new measures followed a continued ascent in Covid cases, with more than 2,000 positive cases recorded over the UK on five sequential days in the current week.</p>', 'Coronavirus', '_113922622_nhs1_1599902613.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:23:33', '2021-08-14 21:40:54'),
(487, 4, 6, 109, 'furlough-must-be-extended-and-targeted-say-mps-1599902741', 'Furlough \'must be extended and targeted\', say MPs', 0, '<p>The UK government ought to consider a focused on expansion of its vacation conspire, MPs have said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Covid emergency chances mass long haul joblessness and reasonable firms could go under without help, the Treasury Select Committee has cautioned.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, a sweeping maintenance of the plan would not be acceptable incentive for cash, it included.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Treasury said it would &quot;keep on advancing in supporting earnings and business.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Coronavirus Job Retention Scheme is because of end on 31 October. Under it, laborers put on leave have gotten 80% of their compensation up to a limit of &pound;2,500 per month.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From the outset, this was totally paid for by the legislature. However, firms needed to begin making a commitment to compensation in September as the plan slowed down.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Executive Boris Johnson has recently said that broadening vacation past October would just keep individuals &quot;in suspended liveliness&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chancellor Rishi Sunak additionally precluded an augmentation, rather saying that organizations will be given &pound;1,000 for each furloughed specialist still in work toward the finish of January.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Covid: What happens when the leave of absence conspire closes?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Expand vacation plan &#39;or danger second flood of employment cuts&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the panel&#39;s administrator, Mel Stride, said the chancellor &quot;ought to deliberately consider focused on expansions&quot; to the plan.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The key will help those organizations who, with extra help, can get through the emergency as reasonable endeavors, as opposed to zeroing in on those that will lamentably just not be practical in the changed post-emergency economy.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pay and abilities&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the second report of its investigation into the financial effect of Covid-19, the council likewise cautioned that the pandemic gambled enlarging the sex pay hole because of the distinctions in long periods of paid work in lockdown - particularly if work designs are changed forever.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The MPs additionally said individuals ought to have the option to reskill, and that independent ventures ought to have the option to completely partake in the administration&#39;s Kickstart Scheme, which intends to make work positions for youngsters on widespread credit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Federation of Small Businesses (FSB) exchange body said with the vacation plot slowing down, &quot;policymakers should take a gander at measures to stem mass joblessness, including a replacement conspire.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>FSB public executive Mike Cherry stated: &quot;The need should be securing feasible independent companies - and all the positions they give - that have been lopsidedly [hit] by the Covid emergency, including those got by neighborhood lockdowns, subject to proceeded with public limitations, or with staff that have legitimately endured due to Covid.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Media captionJulie changed positions before lockdown - at that point got jobless and ineligible for the leave plot&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Resolution Foundation, which crusades on expectations for everyday comforts, said that &quot;broadening support for the hardest-hit segments of the economy will be fundamental to restrict the ascent in joblessness Britain faces in the months ahead.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Torsten Bell, the research organization&#39;s CEO, stated: &quot;This definitive record of the financial effect of Covid ought to be required perusing for Treasury authorities arranging the Autumn Budget against the profoundly unsure background of rising Covid case numbers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The chancellor should rethink his arrangements to quickly eliminate uphold given the difficult reality that the financial emergency is staying put.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This week driving business bunches cautioned that the UK hazards a second rush of employment cuts and a more slow monetary recuperation on the off chance that it doesn&#39;t expand its vacation plot.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Germany, Belgium, Australia and France have all chosen to broaden or dispatch new pay uphold plans into one year from now.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previous Labor PM Gordon Brown told the BBC that the UK ought to copy other nations&#39; momentary working plans.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Brown said the finish of the vacation plot on 31 October was a &quot;precipice edge&quot; that could trigger &quot;a tidal wave of joblessness&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The administration must change course here,&quot; he told the Today program.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Momentary working plans would permit firms to lessen representatives&#39; working hours while keeping them in occupations, with the state beating up their compensations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You must impart a sign that joblessness matters,&quot; he said. &quot;We would prefer not to obliterate any greater limit and aptitudes in the economy.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightGETTY IMAGES&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A Treasury representative said that when the UK plot closes it will have assisted with paying for 9.6 million positions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We will keep on enhancing in supporting livelihoods and business,&quot; the representative said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;re helping representatives return to work, where they need to be, through a &pound;1,000 maintenance reward.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Also, we are making new parts for youngsters with our Kickstart Scheme, making impetuses for preparing and apprenticeships, and supporting and ensuring occupations in the travel industry and friendliness divisions through our VAT cut and a month ago&#39;s Eat Out to Help Out plan.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The UK&#39;s joblessness rate has been at 3.9% since the lockdown was presented.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, the Bank of England anticipates that that rate should twofold to 7.5% before the year&#39;s over when the legislature financed uphold plans reach a conclusion.</p>', 'Furlough\\', '_114269853_gettyimages-631894670_1599902741.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:25:41', '2021-08-17 22:46:05'),
(488, 7, 5, 94, 'fda-approved-coronavirus-test-without-special-computer-1599903044', 'FDA approved Coronavirus Test without Special computer', 0, '<p><strong>On Wednesday, the Food and Drug Administration approved the first rapid tests for the coronavirus, which do not require special computer equipment.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abbott Laboratories&#39; 15-minute test costs $ 5, giving it a competitive advantage over similar tests that would need to be loaded into small machines. The stand-alone test is about the size of a credit card and is based on the same technology used to test for flu, sore throat and other infections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the newest, cheaper and simpler test available in the US market. This opens up new opportunities for expanding testing as schools and businesses struggle to reopen and flu season approaches. The FDA also recently highlighted a Yale University saliva test that passed multiple supplies causing congestion tests.<br />\r\nBoth tests have limitations and cannot be done at home. Several companies are developing rapid in-house tests, but not yet. Abbott&#39;s new test, like most older coronavirus tests, still requires a nasal swab from a health care professional. The saliva test at Yale eliminates the need for tampons, but can only be done in a high-quality laboratory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In general, rapid tests like Abbott&#39;s are less accurate than tests developed in the laboratory. The FDA said in a statement announcing the decision that in some cases Abbott&#39;s negative test results may need to be confirmed by laboratory tests. The agency issued emergency clearance for patients suspected of having COVID-19 in Abbott&#39;s tests late Wednesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both of these supplements are designed to help increase the number of tests available. About 690,000 people are currently tested every day in the US, up from 850,000 daily tests late last month. Many public health experts believe that the country should test significantly more people soon to identify those infected, isolate them and contain the virus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The FDA notes that the Abbott test can be used in a doctor&#39;s office, emergency room, or in some schools. &quot;Given the simplicity of this test, it is likely that this test will be widely available,&quot; said the FDA.<br />\r\nNasal swabs sent to the laboratory have been the standard for screening for COVID-19 since the pandemic began. Although the tests are considered to be very accurate, they are based on expensive specialty machines and chemicals. This shortage of supply has resulted in repeated delays in reporting, especially during last month&#39;s spike in cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Governments and health professionals view rapid testing that can be carried out outside the laboratory system as key to increasing capacity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This screening test is what we need in schools, in the workplace and in nursing homes to catch asymptomatic transmitters,&quot; said Dr. Jonathan Quick of the Rockefeller Foundation in an interview earlier this month. The non-profit group is urging the United States to run about 4 million tests a day through October, mostly rapid tests.<br />\r\nThe fourth rapid test for COVID-19<br />\r\nAbbott&#39;s BinaxNOW is the fourth rapid test to detect the COVID-19 antigen, a protein found on the surface of the coronavirus, not the virus itself. This is considered a faster, if sometimes less accurate, screening method. Other tests have to be performed on a small machine.<br />\r\nInside the Abbott test is a special layered strip that interacts with the COVID-19 antigen. The patient&#39;s nose swab is inserted into the card and a few drops of chemical solution are added. The marker on the card indicates whether the test is positive or negative - similar to a pregnancy test.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two other antigen test manufacturers, Quidel and Becton Dickinson, said they were not meeting the demand for such tests. The third, LumiraDx, plans to begin testing for its recently approved antigen later this month. Abbott expects labor tests to begin in September and reach 50 million tests per month by October.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The inclusion of antigen testing will go a long way in meeting the Trump administration&#39;s estimate that 90 million tests for COVID-19 will be available per month by September if needed. But US Test King Admiral Brett Giroar stressed that the US can control the outbreak with far fewer tests.<br />\r\n&quot;We don&#39;t need a lot of tests&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s capacity ... we don&#39;t need a lot of tests to open it safely and sensibly,&quot; Giroar told reporters recently in a conversation. He identified several key indicators of decline, including new infections and hospitalizations, although testing has slowed down.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Earlier this month, the FDA approved a test based on Yale&#39;s saliva that is believed to reduce time and cost compared to similar tests. This is the fifth COVID-19 saliva test approved by regulators. All of them require laboratory processing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SalivaDirect was developed by the Yale School of Public Health and can collect samples with any sterile container instead of the special tube required for previous testing. This requires less chemicals. External experts welcomed the new approach but noted its limitations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is not a rapid test, this is a laboratory test that still has a long delay like other tests,&quot; said Dr. Michael Mina from Harvard University.</p>', 'FDA Approved, Corona Test', 'FDA Approval_1599903044.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:30:44', '2021-08-12 00:01:01'),
(489, 7, 5, 218, 'mayer-the-ceo-of-tiktok-resigned-under-us-pressure-to-sell-a-video-sharing-app-1599903223', 'Mayer, the CEO of TikTok, resigned under US pressure to sell a video sharing app', 0, '<p>Kevin Meyer, TikTok CEO, resigned Thursday under pressure from the US on his Beijing-based parent company to sell the hugely popular video app that the White House claims poses a national security risk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a letter to officials, Meyer said his decision to leave after &quot;the political environment has changed dramatically&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His resignation follows President Donald Trump&#39;s order to ban TikTok unless parent company ByteDance sells its US filing business to a US company within 90 days. ByteDance is in talks with Microsoft about a possible takeover.<br />\r\nWalmart said Thursday it could join Microsoft in its TikTok offering. Microsoft and TikTok declined to comment on the development.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The sales situation was unusual as Trump demanded payment from the US government for his involvement in the deal, which experts said was unprecedented.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I have thought seriously about what the structural change of the company entails and what it means for the global role I have enlisted,&quot; Mayer said in the letter. &quot;With this in mind, and since we assume we will find a solution soon, I want to tell you with a heavy heart that I have decided to leave the company.&quot;<br />\r\nTikTok is grateful to Mayer for his tenure. He joined the company in May and was previously the CEO of Walt Disney.<br />\r\n&quot;We estimate that the political momentum has significantly altered the scope of Kevin&#39;s role in recent months and we will fully respect his decision,&quot; the company said in a statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ByteDance launched TikTok in 2017, then bought Musical.ly, a video service popular with teenagers, and combined the two. Douyin Dual Service is available for Chinese users. TikTok has gained immense popularity because of its funny, silly videos, and ease of use, and has hundreds of millions of users worldwide.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TikTok properties in China raise concerns about possible video censorship, including those criticizing the Chinese government, and the risk of Beijing gaining access to user data.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Earlier this month, President Trump ordered a broad, but unspecified, ban on doing business with owners of Chinese consumer apps, TikTok and WeChat, amid tightening US control over Chinese tech firms, fearing they pose a threat to national technology firms. Representing security. Since then, TikTok has launched a website to refute claims by the Trump administration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TikTok also filed a lawsuit on Monday against the US Department of Commerce, President Trump and Commerce Secretary Wilbur Ross, seeking to prevent the government from &quot;illegally banning&quot; TikTok by reversing Trump&#39;s order.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TikTok expressed surprise at the order, claiming that it was &quot;issued without due process&quot;.</p>', 'Mayer Tiktok, US Pressure', 'Tiktok CEO_1599903223.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:33:43', '2021-08-14 10:06:52'),
(490, 7, 5, 146, 'jeff-bezos-now-costs-200-billion-1599903370', 'Jeff Bezos now costs $ 200 billion', 0, '<p><strong>Jeff Bezos is the true embodiment of the old adage that &quot;the rich are getting richer,&quot; with Amazon founder net worth exceeding $ 200 billion for the first time on Wednesday.</strong><br />\r\nBezos&#39; personal fortune has soared to shocking levels today as the share price of his e-commerce company hit a record high of $ 3,438 per share.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the same time, the Tesla stock rally has raised CEO Elon Musk&#39;s net worth to more than $ 100 billion, according to the Bloomberg Billionaire Index, a ranking of the world&#39;s 500 richest people.<br />\r\nThe increase in affluence was mainly seen at the top of the index and was mainly due to increased inventory levels as the coronavirus forced consumers to get more from their online purchases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Facebook&#39;s Mark Zuckerberg, for example, also had a net worth of more than $ 100 billion that month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Widening income inequality is fueling efforts to bridge the gap between progressive lawmakers, including Senator Bernie Sanders, who this month proposed a bill to tax &quot;extreme&quot; welfare gains amid the ongoing pandemic.<br />\r\nBezos, who started Amazon in 1994, has been the richest person in the world since 2017.<br />\r\nMicrosoft founder Bill Gates is the second richest person in the world with a net worth of $ 124 billion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tim Cook, Apple&#39;s CEO, recently became a billionaire when the market price of his company - the most valuable in the world - shot up to $ 2 trillion. Cook&#39;s fortune is less than a quarter of the person at the bottom of Bloomberg&#39;s list, Indian industrialist Vikram Lal, whose personal fortune is estimated at $ 4.5 billion.</p>', 'Jeff Bezos', 'Jeff bezos_1599903370.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:36:10', '2021-08-10 20:22:08'),
(491, 7, 5, 178, 'the-apple-app-store-will-be-without-fortnite-for-now-1599903541', 'The Apple App Store will be without Fortnite for now', 0, '<p><strong>A district judge ruled that Apple could continue to support the popular Fortnite game from the iPhone maker app store. Fortnite maker Epic Games sued Apple last week for bringing the game back to the iPhone download center.</strong><br />\r\nThis multiplayer game where players take part in a last-person shootout in the animated world hasn&#39;t been available on the Apple App Store since mid-August. The game was removed after Epic Games enabled a feature that allowed users to make in-game purchases for virtual weapons or other items directly from Epic rather than through Apple&#39;s payment system. Apple, which charges up to 30% commission on transactions, requires developers to use the App Store to route all payments through Apple&#39;s systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Google also removed the hit game Epic from its app store due to a dispute over direct payments. At present, neither Apple nor Google allows users to download and install Fortnite on mobile via their digital marketplace. Epic has also filed a lawsuit against Google.<br />\r\nThe growing battle between Epic and Apple, as well as Google, has attracted the interest of antitrust experts, who are increasingly concerned about the increasing control Apple, Google and other tech giants have over the US economy. Congress held a high-level hearing last month with Apple and the CEOs of Google, as well as Amazon and Facebook, on whether the country&#39;s biggest technology company should face stricter antitrust regulations.<br />\r\nEpic&#39;s lawsuit against Apple seems to reinforce that story. In its lawsuit, Epic accused Apple of engaging in anti-competitive behavior in its App Store, Apple&#39;s main distributor of games and apps. Game creators also turned to social media to win over fans, tweeting that Epic was &quot;against the App Store monopoly&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The questions Epic raised in his lawsuit aligned with the legislature&#39;s concerns during a recent trial, said antitrust expert Eleanor Fox, a professor at New York University School of Law. The problem is that antitrust laws like yours are now formulated to benefit dominant firms and do little to fix prices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If Epic was just about whether Apple was overpricing, it was permitted under the antitrust laws,&quot; Fox said. &quot;The antitrust law doesn&#39;t block pricing.&quot;<br />\r\nDuring Monday night&#39;s preliminary hearing, a U.S. District Court judge. Yvonne Gonzalez Rodgers said Apple could keep Fortnite from its app store while Epic&#39;s lawsuit against the iPhone maker continues. However, the judge said the decision was limited to Fortnite, and Apple&#39;s decision to remove another offering from Epic - the Unreal Engine, a tool popular with other app developers - was not permitted along with other forms of revenge.<br />\r\n&quot;Apple has decided to take serious action and thus influence the overseas and third-party developer ecosystem,&quot; Rodgers said in his decision.</p>', 'Apple App, Without Fornite', 'Apple App store_1599903541.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:39:01', '2021-09-23 08:15:42');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(492, 7, 5, 163, 'ubers-former-head-of-security-has-been-accused-of-trying-to-cover-up-a-massive-hack-1599903686', 'Uber\'s former head of security has been accused of trying to cover up a massive hack', 0, '<p><strong>The former Uber security chief was charged with a notable attempt to cover up a hack in 2016 that revealed the personal information of 57 million app users and drivers, the Justice Department said Thursday. Joseph Sullivan was accused of obstructing justice and offending crimes in which law enforcement officials withheld knowledge of the crime.</strong><br />\r\nThe complaint alleges that on November 14, 2016 - 10 days after Sullivan testified to the Federal Trade Commission about a previous data breach - a hacker told Sullivan that he had successfully compromised the company&#39;s systems. Instead of reporting to the Commission as required by law, Sullivan claimed that he &quot;took deliberate steps to prevent knowledge of violations from reaching the FTC&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Witnesses reported that Sullivan appeared shaken by the incident,&quot; said the complaint. One witness also said that in a private conversation Sullivan said he did not believe they had committed a new offense and that the team needed to make sure news of the violation did not get to the surface.<br />\r\nIn the complaint, Sullivan is accused of paying the two hackers $ 100,000 in Bitcoin through the Bug Bounty program - a legal program designed to reward those who point to corporate security flaws - even though the hackers stole data. have what goes against the program requirements. . He also claimed that Sullivan tried to get the hackers to sign a nondisclosure agreement that said they did not steal or store any data, even though he and the hackers knew this was untrue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After Uber came under new management in 2017, executives discovered the breach and reported it to the FTC, according to the complaint.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Responding to the allegations, Uber told CBS News, &quot;We continue to cooperate fully with the Department of Justice investigation. Our decision in 2017 to disclose the incident was not only correct, but also embodies the principles we use in conducting our day-to-day operations. these: transparency, integrity, and accountability. &quot;<br />\r\nThe complaint also alleges that Sullivan misled the company after discovering the breach by not divulging important details about the hack. In producing a brief on the new CEO, Sullivan claimed to have edited a draft of his team to remove details about what the hackers were stealing and falsely stated that hackers were only paid after they were identified.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sullivan was ultimately fired, the complaint said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The two hackers responsible for the breach pleaded guilty on October 30, 2019. The complaint alleges that &quot;after Sullivan, the two [hackers] had targeted and succeeded in hacking into another technology company and its user data&quot; did not alert authorities to the breach at Uber.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Silicon Valley is not the Wild West,&quot; said US attorney David Anderson in a Department of Justice statement. &quot;We expect good corporate citizenship. We expect criminal behavior to be reported quickly. We look forward to working with our investigation. We will not tolerate company closings. We will not tolerate illegal payments of money at unspoken levels.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A spokesman for Sullivan told CBS News that &quot;there is no reason for the accusation,&quot; adding, &quot;Without the efforts of Mr. Sullivan and his team, those responsible for the incident would likely never have been identified.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The spokesman also said that Sullivan &quot;is working closely with relevant legal, communications and other teams&quot; and that the company&#39;s legal department &quot;is responsible for deciding whether and to whom matters should be disclosed&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If convicted, Sullivan receives a maximum sentence of five years in prison for disability and three years for a mission.</p>', 'Uber Security, Massive Hack', 'Uber charges_1599903686.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:41:26', '2021-08-15 02:21:47'),
(493, 7, 5, 161, 'legal-solutions-prevent-uber-and-lyft-from-closing-down-in-california-1599903857', 'Legal solutions prevent Uber and Lyft from closing down in California', 0, '<p><strong>A California court ruled Thursday that Uber and Lyft are under no obligation to immediately classify their drivers as employees rather than independent contractors. The decision will allow Welcome Services to continue working in the state after threats of retirement.</strong><br />\r\nJust hours before the decision, Lyft announced it would cease operations in California at 23:59. on Thursday. &quot;This change also requires an overhaul of the overall business model - it is not a change that can be changed overnight,&quot; the company said of the law, which took effect January 1.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week, a US judge ordered companies to treat drivers as full-fledged employees, as required by a law passed in California last year. The transportation company appealed the decision, claiming that the new law did not apply to them.<br />\r\nUber also threatened to stop its operations in California if he was forced to comply with the law. &quot;We can&#39;t hire 50,000 people overnight,&quot; CEO Data Khosrowshahi said on a podcast earlier this week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ruling allows the company to continue treating their drivers as contractors until the first hearing of the case, which is scheduled for October 13.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Transfer fees to the driver<br />\r\nBoth companies cut their labor costs by classifying drivers as contractors who do not receive the same benefits and protections at work as company employees. As independent contractors, Uber and Lyft drivers are responsible for their own expenses, including taxes, and will not receive sick leave, weekends or benefits if injured on the job.<br />\r\nClassifying a driver as an employee will pass many of these costs to Uber and Lyft. This is a much more expensive arrangement for companies, which previously had nothing to gain from.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>California authorities have also said that treating drivers as contractors is more expensive because the company is not contributing to the decline in state unemployment insurance on behalf of drivers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hard ball game<br />\r\nCalifornia is a key part of the businesses of the two companies, accounting for about a fifth of all pre-pandemic Lyft trips and about a tenth of Uber trips.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The threat of closure in the state is an assertive strategy by the company previously operating in Austin, Texas. In 2016, the city issued a voting action rejected by Uber and Lyft asking them to take their driver&#39;s fingerprints to check the past.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two days later, Lyft and Uber left town, confusing drivers and, according to Wired, leaving many drivers without food. The following year lawmakers repeal Austin&#39;s laws, and Uber and Lyft returned shortly thereafter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Corporations in California are taking a similar approach, incorporating millions of people into a November voting initiative that places drivers in a separate worker category with some protections but does not qualify for full employment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dan Ives, an analyst at Wedbush, said major service disruptions would anger drivers and create more public support for a voting initiative called Proposal 22.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We believe this is a smart move for Lyft with Uber and today the court&#39;s decision is a major win for both players,&quot; he said in a statement to investors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an update on upcoming cancellations, Lyft thanked &quot;the tens of thousands of drivers, drivers and government officials who urged California to keep driving easy.&quot; An Uber spokesman said the company will &quot;continue to maintain the ability of drivers to work with the freedom they desire&quot;.</p>', 'Legal Solution, Uber', 'uber lyft owes me_1599903857.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:44:17', '2021-08-17 15:34:55'),
(494, 7, 5, 216, 'the-england-wales-contact-corona-tracing-app-gets-a-start-date-1599904681', 'The England-Wales contact Corona tracing app gets a start date', 0, '<p>The new Covid-19 tracking application will be launched in England and Wales on September 24, the government said.<br />\r\nThis app allows users to scan QR codes such as barcode to register hospitality visits and apply Apple and Google methods to recognize other smartphones.<br />\r\nCompanies are encouraged to display posters with QR codes in support of the application.<br />\r\nHealth Secretary Matt Hancock described the start as a &quot;pivotal moment&quot;.<br />\r\nThe first British version of the NHS contact tracing app was tested on Isle of Wight in May but was abandoned.<br />\r\n&quot;We need to use every tool to control the spread of the virus, including modern technology,&quot; said Hancock.<br />\r\n&quot;The launch of applications later this month in England and Wales is a turning point and will help us keep the virus at a tipping point.&quot;<br />\r\nAccording to the latest figures released by the Office for National Statistics, there were around 3,200 new cases daily in the UK during the first week of September, up from 2,000 the previous week.<br />\r\nSome restaurants are already using their own QR code-based testing and tracking systems but now want to upgrade to the NHS version.<br />\r\nUniversities, hospitals, recreational facilities, community centers, and libraries are asked to put up posters in public areas such as cafes where people gather for more than 15 minutes.<br />\r\nAlternative systems such as handwritten registers should also be kept for visitors without smartphones, according to the Ministry of Health and Social Services.<br />\r\nHealth and Social Services Secretary Getty Welsh said putting forward a joint proposal with Britain was the &quot;most practical option&quot;.<br />\r\nHe added that the move reflected &quot;moving across our common borders&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;It makes sense to use the same app and the same way it works no matter which country you are in.&quot;</p>', 'CoronaVirus, APP Launched', 'Corona app launch_1599904681.jpg', '2020-09-12 13:58:01', '2021-09-23 08:13:46'),
(495, 4, 14, 118, 'leeds-dwp-office-failed-to-enforce-social-distancing-1599905851', 'Leeds DWP office failed to enforce social distancing', 0, '<p>An administration office neglected to do what&#39;s necessary to forestall the spread of Covid, a wellbeing and security investigation found.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Laborers were imagined accumulated around a work area at the Department for Work and Pensions (DWP) in Leeds where there have been two affirmed Covid-19 cases.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Health and Safety Executive (HSE) discovered administration had neglected to guarantee social removing was kept up.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The DWP said it had taken &quot;earnest activity to redress all issues distinguished&quot; at the Quarry House office.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During the pandemic, most of DWP representatives in Leeds have been telecommuting yet there have still been several individuals in the workplace, situated inside a milestone expanding on the eastern edge of the downtown area.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There has been an enlistment drive at the DWP in the midst of an ascent in Universal Credit inquirers due to Covid, an informant told the BBC.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Quarry House in Leeds&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionQuarry House in Leeds is referred to locally as &quot;The Kremlin&quot; in view of its monumental engineering&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The informant has been working at home for the DWP however said he was worried for his wellbeing when getting back to the structure, which is likewise home to parts of the NHS.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He stated: &quot;I hear anecdotes about individuals congregating, not following outlaid direction. In an office so large it is hard to screen day in and day out.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Individuals I have addressed are anxious about a return, they and I feel it isn&#39;t yet sheltered enough to return.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The workplace was occupied pre-Covid, I don&#39;t have the foggiest idea where everybody would work from in typical occasions let alone in an infection episode.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So what number of companions would i be able to meet at this point?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;We should act&#39; to forestall second lockdown - PM&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Five different ways to abstain from getting Covid inside&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s the most recent with the leave of absence plot?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The HSE examined the workplace on 27 August in the wake of accepting a report of a &quot;work environment concern&quot;. During the visit photos were taken, including one of laborers standing near one another.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report accumulated after the examination stated: &quot;You are neglecting to guarantee, so far as is sensibly practicable, the wellbeing and security of your representatives/office staff at work since you have not executed fundamental measures to forestall the spread of Covid-19.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The DWP had hazard surveyed for the workplace being about half full, which the HSE said &quot;might be driven and ridiculous&quot;, prompting a danger of &quot;blockage&quot; and making it more hard to keep up social removing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Presentational dim line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What the report found&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A line administrator offered guidance to a gathering of staff around a work area, with staff not following social separating&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Walkways had been assigned as two-path travel notwithstanding just being about a meter wide&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Walkways passed near work areas assigned as usable&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Flights of stairs were assigned as two-way travel yet didn&#39;t seem, by all accounts, to be adequately wide for 2m removing - even at assigned passing focuses&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Little tables, &quot;breakout units&quot; and seats needed &quot;don&#39;t utilize&quot; signage.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Presentational dim line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The BBC has seen spilled messages indicating the workplace has had at any rate two positive Covid cases among staff.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two messages have as of late been sent to laborers saying individuals had been sent home from the influenced floors and profound wipes completed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Charles Law, mechanical official with the PCS association, stated: &quot;It&#39;s amazingly stressing for our individuals who work for the office, particularly on the off chance that they&#39;re required to quit being at home and come into the work environment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s stunning that the HSE would do such a condemning report on a leader DWP office and we&#39;re amazingly worried for the security of our individuals.&quot;</p>', 'social distancing', '_114305492_dwp-1_1599905851.jpg', '2020-09-12 14:17:31', '2021-12-19 17:40:29'),
(496, 7, 5, 137, 'the-government-needs-to-protect-arm-headquarters-in-britain-the-labor-party-said-1599906129', 'The government needs to protect ARM headquarters in Britain, the Labor Party said', 0, '<p><strong>The British government needs to step in to ensure Cambridge-based chipmaker ARM remains headquartered in the UK, Labor said.</strong><br />\r\nSoftBank, which bought ARM in 2016, is in advanced talks to sell the company to Nvidia in the US.<br />\r\nThe government should accept a &quot;legally binding statement&quot; about the location of ARM, said Ed Miliband of the Labor Party.<br />\r\nA government spokesman said any takeover that posed a threat to Britain would be investigated.<br />\r\nARM is one of the world&#39;s leading manufacturers of microprocessors for smartphones and other devices.<br />\r\nIt was sold to Japan&#39;s SoftBank for &pound; 24.3 billion in 2016, but the conglomerate is now known to be in talks to sell ARM to US chipmaker Nvidia.<br />\r\n&quot;The government needs to show leadership and get legally binding guarantees from Nvidia if it takes over the company to retain UK-based ARM instead of seeing jobs and decisions transferred abroad,&quot; said a business statement. Shadow Secretary Ed Miliband.<br />\r\n&quot;Even though the proposed acquisition is essentially a trade matter for the stakeholders, the government continues to monitor them,&quot; said a government spokesman.<br />\r\n&quot;If we believe the takeover could pose a threat to Britain, the government will not hesitate to carry out further investigations into the terms of the contract.&quot;<br />\r\nARM co-founder Tudor Brown, who worked for the company for 29 years, has previously spoken out against selling ARM to semiconductor companies.<br />\r\nInstead, he should remain a neutral supplier for tech companies, he advises.</p>', 'British Govermnet, Arm Headquarter', 'Arms HQ_1599906129.jpg', '2020-09-12 14:22:09', '2021-08-17 04:07:38'),
(497, 4, 12, 56, 'brexit-further-clashes-over-work-on-ni-port-controls-1599906144', 'Brexit: Further clashes over work on NI port controls', 0, '<p>Stormont pastors have conflicted over the condition clergyman&#39;s suggestion that work ought to be ended on offices at ports that could be utilized for checks identified with Brexit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The controls are right now utilized for keeps an eye on agri-food items and creatures.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In July, the UK affirmed it expected to put outskirt control posts at Northern Ireland&#39;s ports.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Work to extend the posts was then mentioned by the administration.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notwithstanding, it is perceived Environment Minister Edwin Poots has taken the view that to press ahead with the development of current purpose of passage controls would be a misuse of open assets after the most recent UK Internal Market Bill.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new bill sets out standards for the activity of the UK inside market - exchange between England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland - after the finish of the Brexit change period in January.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There has been contention over the bill expressly expressing that these forces ought to apply regardless of whether they are contradictory with worldwide law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, priests state it is expected to forestall &quot;harming&quot; duties on merchandise going from the remainder of the UK to Northern Ireland if economic accord dealings with the EU fall flat.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightPA MEDIA&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture subtitle&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Edwin Poots says he would not like to make any hindrances around Northern Ireland&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a letter to Mr Poots, the Westminster Environment Secretary George Eustice set out what work is needed to extend controls at Northern Ireland&#39;s ports.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Subtleties have not been distributed and in an announcement, Stormont&#39;s Department of Agriculture, Environment and Rural Affairs expressed &quot;this issue is as of now being considered by the leader and it is improper to remark further&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Stormont authorities are concerned any clerical request to stop take a shot at the purposes of section could be in break of the Northern Ireland Act.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The demonstration - which supports the Stormont chief - enables the Northern Ireland secretary to arrange a priest or division to make a move on the off chance that he trusts it is needed to satisfy the UK&#39;s worldwide commitments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Government promises &pound;355m to ease GB-NI exchange&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UK government to upgrade fringe checks at NI ports&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Government affirms new minds products entering NI&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why Brexit is as yet a major issue&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sinn F&eacute;in, the SDLP and the Alliance Party contend that procedure with chip away at the controls is needed to satisfy the chief&#39;s worldwide commitments.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The issue was put to a cross-network vote during a late meeting of the leader on Thursday night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No authorisation was provided for the earth priest to opportunity to stop and think the work.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The chief deferred its conversations on Thursday night so as to acquire legitimate exhortation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pastors continued their procedures on Friday evening and further conversations are normal in the coming week.</p>', 'Brexit', '_114279330_westminsterflagsepa_1599906144.jpg', '2020-09-12 14:22:24', '2021-08-15 17:16:14'),
(498, 4, 12, 99, 'what-is-the-row-over-uk-internal-markets-all-about-1599906252', 'What is the row over UK \'internal markets\' all about?', 0, '<p>The Scottish and UK governments are going into another protected stalemate over post-Brexit powers and the &quot;inner market&quot; after new enactment was postponed at Westminster. What is the most recent column about?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Force snatch&#39; or &#39;force flood&#39;?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new UK Internal Market Bill has quickly run into debate over its effect on converses with the EU and on worldwide deals, given it could re-compose portions of the Brexit withdrawal arrangement.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Anyway the center capacity of the bill is likewise argumentative for what it may mean for the eventual fate of devolution.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Portions of this column may appear to be to some degree natural, since it&#39;s really been going on pretty much since the time the Brexit vote in June 2016.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The subject of how controls right now practiced from Brussels are split after the progress time frame closes on 31 December has been now observed the two governments conflict at the Supreme Court.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At its most essential level, this is a line about who gets what.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Scottish government says a Westminster &quot;power get&quot; is in progress, since anything which isn&#39;t explicitly saved should consequently come to Holyrood.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the UK government says what&#39;s going on speaks to &quot;the greatest exchange of forces throughout the entire existence of devolution&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can contend the throw about who is correct, however that is maybe something of a sideshow to the more central clash - how these forces are utilized, and what it could mean for the fate of guidelines and norms in the UK.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture copyrightPA&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Who sets the norm?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the present time, the UK is important for the European single market, with mutually concurred guidelines and principles directly over the landmass.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Post-Brexit, the UK government needs to keep on having a joint market across England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland - the &quot;inside market&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, rather than the principles and guidelines around things like food and air quality and creature government assistance being set in Brussels, presently they must be set nearer to home - and there is a column over who ought to have the last say.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Numerous forces are set to be straightforwardly constrained by the Scottish, Welsh and Northern Irish organizations, in fields including food naming, vitality productivity and backing for ranchers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, the UK government has said the lapsed organizations will in any case need to acknowledge merchandise and ventures from all different pieces of the UK - regardless of whether they have set various guidelines locally.</p>', '\'internal markets\'', '_108108721_mediaitem108108720_1599906252.jpg', '2020-09-12 14:24:12', '2021-08-13 03:00:44'),
(499, 4, 16, 113, 'new-yorks-last-great-jazz-parlour-1599906490', 'New Yorks last great jazz parlour', 0, '<p>In the mid twentieth Century, Harlem, New York,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>was the beating focus of America&#39;s dark social and scholarly soul.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, throughout the previous 25 years, Marjorie Eliot has proceeded with this inheritance by facilitating free jazz shows in her little Harlem level.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s 15:00 (3:00pm) on a cool Sunday in February when the music begins saturating the lobby of 555 Edgecombe Avenue in Harlem.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lofty Beaux Arts fabricating, a National Historic Landmark worked during the 1910s, was initially proposed for white inhabitants just &ndash; a strategy that finished as African Americans rushed to New York City from the US South in the mid twentieth Century as a major aspect of the Great Migration that made Harlem the beating focal point of America&#39;s dark social and scholarly soul. All through the Harlem Renaissance and for quite a long time after, a rundown of unbelievable dark artists lived here, including Duke Ellington, Count Basie and Andy Kirk, who kept jazz, swing and enormous band songs floating through the 14-story structure.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Today, be that as it may, the melodic runs of the piano were originating from loft 3F. Outside, an enthusiastic horde of around 40 individuals had just clustered up around a manually written sign outwardly of the entryway that read &quot;Music: 3:30&quot;. There was a more seasoned couple from the Upper West Side remaining close to three college understudies from France. A lady from Denmark had brought her two young adult kids and her mom. Another couple drew closer from the lift and said hesitantly, &quot;We&#39;re here for Marjorie.&quot; A man close by answered, &quot;Everybody&#39;s here for Marjorie.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Marjorie Eliot is a modest lady in her 80s, and loft 3F is something other than her home &ndash; it&#39;s her stage. Each Sunday throughout the previous 25 years, the piano player, entertainer and dramatist has crushed 50 lawn seats into her 700-sq-ft condo, welcomed a portion of the city&#39;s best artists to her home and made the way for any individual who needs to tune in to the personal jazz and theater exhibitions, for nothing out of pocket. She never knows precisely who will appear or where they&#39;ll be from. There are no tickets or reservations &ndash; you simply must be outside when the music begins.</p>', 'jazz parlour', 'download (1)_1599906490.jpg', '2020-09-12 14:28:10', '2021-12-19 17:37:22'),
(500, 4, 16, 101, 'florences-wine-portals-from-the-17th-century-1599906615', 'Florences wine portals from the 17th Century', 0, '<p>While a Florence caf&eacute; had to close due to Covid, it had the option to keep one aspect of the business open as seventeenth Century buchette del vino, or &quot;wine openings&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The buchette del vino, or &quot;wine openings&quot;, turned out to be very import to Florence during the plague of 1630 as they took into account the protected offer of wine and food. Today, there are more than 180 of these socially far off, drink serving windows from the seventeenth Century that are peppered all through the Italian city; notwithstanding, hardly any local people knew their unique capacity before the pandemic. Since lockdown, they have drawn individuals from around the globe.</p>', 'Florences wine portals', 'download (2)_1599906615.jpg', '2020-09-12 14:30:15', '2021-12-19 17:37:11'),
(501, 7, 5, 162, 'a-scammer-cloned-my-business-on-instagram-1599906690', 'A scammer cloned my business on Instagram. \'', 0, '<p><strong>On the other hand, on the last weekend of August, when Emma Hiccott-James is taking a leisurely holiday on a bank holiday, she struggles to save her company&#39;s reputation.</strong><br />\r\nShe recently opened an Instagram page for her cosmetics business, which she has built for 12 years and has been cloned.<br />\r\n&quot;For some reason, the scammers tagged me in one of the photos, which seemed like a mistake,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nAnd it warns them of cloned sites, where the only real difference from the legitimate Little Soap Co site is the extra &quot;o&quot; at the end of the name.<br />\r\n<strong>PayPal details</strong><br />\r\nAs well as making page copies, scammers want to make money too.<br />\r\n&quot;The account became private and we found that they spent the whole night on Monday&#39;s bank holiday and hundreds of our supporters who had been in our last race were contacted, saying they had won and asked for details about PayPal,&quot; he said. Emma.<br />\r\nAt least one of his customers answered, but he doesn&#39;t know how many more were affected or lost money.<br />\r\nTrying to convince Instagram to remove the fake page proved disappointing.<br />\r\n<strong>Square Place</strong><br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s impossible to talk to someone on Instagram,&quot; Emma told.<br />\r\n&quot;Then we just realized it.<br />\r\n&quot;We couldn&#39;t register it as a business presentation account because the forms you need to fill out take you through a cycle that doesn&#39;t end. Instead, you come back first.<br />\r\n&quot;Looks like they don&#39;t want to be contacted.<br />\r\n&quot;Send me with dementia.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/996F/production/_114297293_screenshot2020-09-09at13.03.46.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nFacebook owns Instagram.<br />\r\nLastly, Emma tells humans or software bots - she&#39;s not sure who - on Facebook Messenger what she considers trademark infringement.<br />\r\n&quot;I received an email saying it wasn&#39;t a violation, it was a violation of the terms and conditions of the community guidelines,&quot; he said.<br />\r\n&quot;And the bill was accepted.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Very happy&quot;<br />\r\nBut it&#39;s an &quot;out of control&quot; email with no personal touch.<br />\r\n&quot;It felt like Facebook was saying, &#39;Done - next&#39;,&quot; said Emma.<br />\r\nThe matter was also registered with the police at the time, who told Emma that such cloning was &quot;widespread&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;We are very fortunate with how quickly it breaks,&quot; he said.<br />\r\n&quot;But the three of us are working on it.<br />\r\n&quot;Not all companies have these resources.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Iron fort&quot;<br />\r\nAnd he remains angry about how to solve it.<br />\r\n&quot;For every other digital platform we pay for, we use good customer service, while Facebook, which is a great example for many companies, is very different,&quot; said Emma.<br />\r\n&quot;It feels like an iron fort.<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s very difficult to talk to someone.<br />\r\n&quot;And chatbots still aren&#39;t smart enough to help.&quot;<br />\r\n<strong>Fake account</strong><br />\r\nFacebook told &quot;We have removed the account that caught our attention for illegal behavior.<br />\r\n&quot;We continue to invest in our team and technology to identify and eliminate fraud, and we have donated &pound; 3 million to Citizens Advice to set up an anti-fraud program in the UK to spread the spread of fraud and provide support to those affected.&quot;<br />\r\nEvery day, Facebook&#39;s detection technology blocks millions of attempts to create fake accounts.<br />\r\nHowever, account cloning remains a problem for Facebook and Instagram.<br />\r\nTwitter and LinkedIn both have to deal with such scams.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Bitcoin Scam&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cloning is remarkable easy to do&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/10161/production/_114298856_screenshot2020-09-09at13.25.57.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nOn his blog, security specialist at antivirus company ESET Jake Moore describes how he copied his Instagram account this afternoon - and convinced one of his followers to send him money with a sad story about his bank account being blocked and on social media.<br />\r\nThe suggestions are:<br />\r\nTo avoid cloning, search your hashtags or do a reverse image search on Google to see if photos you post appear elsewhere.<br />\r\nOnce cloned, take a photo with an official certificate and email it on Facebook<br />\r\nIf you receive a message from someone you don&#39;t know asking for money, don&#39;t send the money<br />\r\nWhen you receive a message from someone you know who wants money, ask them to make sure the message is real<br />\r\nEmma is definitely planning to keep an eye on suspicious activity related to her brand and has since discovered another cloned account and two cloned versions of her personal Instagram page - all of which have been deleted.<br />\r\n&quot;Everything is kind of creepy,&quot; he said</p>', 'Scammer Cloned, Insta', 'SCammer Clone_1599906690.jpg', '2020-09-12 14:31:30', '2021-08-17 22:01:11'),
(502, 4, 16, 180, 'japans-ancient-vegetarian-meal-1599906832', 'Japan\'s Ancient Vegetarian Meal', 0, '<p>Accepted to adjust the brain, body and soul, shojin ryori is an entrancing understanding into the cautious parity of new and old idealized by Japan.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nEdged in dynamic pink, a shadow-slender cut of radish sits on a delicate square of sesame tofu. Next to it, a pot of udon stews delicately while a close by bushel holds a home of fresh tempura &ndash; shaping only three of the dozen dishes set before me. We are situated in a calm tatami room at Ekoin, one of in excess of 100 sanctuaries that structure the old complex of Koya in provincial Wakayama prefecture. Roosted on the mountainside, the town is the focal point of Shingon Buddhism, and our feast is known as shjin ryri, a profound cooking idealized by priests over hundreds of years.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Known for its greenery secured burial grounds and forested journey courses, Koya is home to a long custom of love. The town&#39;s numerous sanctuary lodgings, known as shukubo, offer guests the opportunity to encounter the methods of Buddhism, from contemplation to calligraphy &shy;&ndash;yet not many realize that the modest sanctuary suppers are likewise an open door for otherworldly investigation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shojin ryori is a veggie lover, otherworldly cooking consummated by Buddhist priests over hundreds of years (Credit: Credit: directphoto.bz/Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shojin ryori is a veggie lover, otherworldly cooking consummated by Buddhist priests over hundreds of years (Credit: directphoto.bz/Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frequently called &quot;commitment cooking&quot;, shjin ryri was created by priests, yet has as of late discovered its way from sanctuary eateries to Tokyo&#39;s Michelin-star tables. Both negligible and ample, it is frequently connected with severity; be that as it may, devoted gourmet experts declare a bunch of visual, specialized and occasional blends are conceivable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Showing up in Japan with Buddhism in the sixth Century, shjin cooking was generally a straightforward undertaking, protected by persevering clerics and priests, clarifies Shiten, Ekoin&#39;s occupant minister. It was the lessons of thirteenth Century essayist and Soto Zen school originator, Dogen, nonetheless, that spearheaded the profound focal point of the workmanship. Dogen accepted that, like the act of blossom masterminding or tea function, shjin ryri had the ability to adjust psyche, body and soul.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may likewise be keen on:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Japan&#39;s obscure indigenous cooking&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; A dumpling following back to Genghis Khan&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&bull; Japan&#39;s most polarizing superfood&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dogen&#39;s celebrated article, &quot;Tenzo Kyokun&quot;, signifying &quot;Directions to the Cook&quot;, traces not just the significance of fixing determination and equalization, yet the care of the gourmet expert. The basic dish of goma dofu (sesame tofu) &ndash; which requires long periods of granulating and blending &ndash; is a notable model, with the dreary cycle requesting a determined concentration from the gourmet specialist. Given the protracted, work escalated measure and the nearly short second it takes to eat, Shiten thought of it as the embodiment of shjin food, and an exercise in adjusting the desires for the inner self.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shjin gourmet specialists are needed to have the three personalities of Japanese Zen Buddhism, known as sanshin, and they become as much an aspect of the supper as their fixings. Aishin (the large brain) must be kept up for tranquility and inspiration; roshin (the parental psyche) is expected to regard and care for the fixings and cafe; while kishin (the valuable psyche) requires the cook to work with joy and appreciation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The antiquated complex of Koya in country Wakayama prefecture is the focal point of Shingon Buddhism (Credit: Credit: VW Pics/Getty Images)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The antiquated complex of Koya in country Wakayama prefecture is the focal point of Shingon Buddhism (Credit: VW Pics/Getty Images)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Shjin ryri truly signifies &#39;nourishment for otherworldly practice&#39;,&quot; clarified Eric Rath, a teacher of Japanese examinations and driving master in Japanese food culture. &quot;In particular, it alludes to a veggie lover dinner that likewise avoids fixings like garlic and green onion, which Buddhists accepted energized the interests,&quot; he kept, laying out the fundamental principles, of which there are numerous complexities and augmentations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s a profound interest, yet in addition it&#39;s an open door for you to associate with others&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The managing ideas of shjin food are fixated on a progression of Buddhist statutes, adjusting the requirement for food to strict qualities, for example, keeping away from hurt. &quot;It&#39;s about parity,&quot; clarified Mari Fujii, who has shown the cooking for over 30 years in the verifiable shoreline city of Kamakura, known for sanctuaries, situated Buddhas and old political impact. Gaining from her better half&#39;s time as a tenzo (the Buddhist culinary expert in a sanctuary or religious community) at a neighborhood Kamakura sanctuary, she before long embraced the ways of thinking into her home cooking: &quot;To have the option to satisfy your sanctuary obligations, you were unable to eat excessively or excessively little. It&#39;s tied in with finding the ideal parity, and this originates from the standard of five,&quot; she said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Drawing essentialness from the five periods of Chinese Philosophy known as wuxing, the number mirrors the repeating balance required in nature and society. In shjin ryri, this applies to shading, flavor and strategy: the goshoku (shade) of white, dark, red, green and yellow; the gomi (kind) of sweet, sharp, severe, pungent and umami; and the goho (method) of stewed, seared, crude, steamed and flame broiled are totally required components.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Requiring long stretches of planning, goma dofu (sesame tofu) is viewed as the embodiment of shjin cooking (Credit: Credit: Promo_Link/Getty Images)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Requiring long stretches of planning, goma dofu (sesame tofu) is viewed as the embodiment of shjin cooking (Credit: Promo_Link/Getty Images)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just as controlling wholesome parity, the standards are intended to engage the five detects, motivating the burger joint to notice and worth every fixing just as the consideration taken to set it up. Before eating even starts, this is done through the reciting of the five Zen reflections, urging priests to be appreciative, mindful of their flaws, endeavor to enhance them, eat for good wellbeing and to satisfy their commitments. Gone from cook to cafe, the dinner shapes a scaffold, as Fujii clarified: &quot;it&#39;s an otherworldly interest, yet additionally it&#39;s an open door for you to associate with others.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As essential as the necessary components, the limitations mirror the estimation of nonappearance that is perceived in Buddhist preparing and Japanese style known as &quot;mama&quot;. The unfilled space utilized in ikebana (Japanese blossom course of action) is equivalent to the picked stems, while Dogen at first recorded six flavors &ndash; &shy;&shy; checking plain close by the other five. This inclination for nuance and insignificant penance is vital, yet among Japanese coffee shops who favor meat and the conventional fish-based dashi stock, the cooking is regularly seen as dull and unexciting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fujii keeps up an unlimited energy for the food&#39;s prospects, notwithstanding: &quot;There are endless varieties and it is so illustrative of the seasons, not once in 36 years have I gotten exhausted with shjin ryri,&quot; she said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The occasional part of shjin ryri is one of its establishing standards and offers a great part of the assortment that Fujii loves. Known as evade, this component takes its name from an old Japanese counter framework and signifies &quot;10 days&quot;, mirroring a hyper-irregularity still basic in Japanese cooking. Numerous Japanese caf&eacute;s, for instance, change menus at regular intervals, with new brightening leaves enhancing plates to feature the season and every day specials selected at the market every morning.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sansai (wild mountain plants) are regularly utilized as fixings in shojin ryori (Credit: Credit: Kyoko Uchida/Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sansai (wild mountain plants) are regularly utilized as fixings in shojin ryori (Credit: Kyoko Uchida/Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One such caf&eacute;, Sougo in Tokyo, is the making of acclaimed culinary expert Daisuke Nomura. He was head gourmet specialist when the profoundly acclaimed, family-run shjin ryri eatery Daigo was granted two Michelin stars in 2009, and he later struck out all alone to additionally investigate the food&#39;s prospects.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The most significant piece of shjin is thought and appreciation&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I needed to progress in the direction of another age of shjin ryri,&quot; he said. &quot;I figure dishes ought to advance with time, and I needed the opportunity to challenge myself and work with new components.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Utilizing the antiquated most loved of sesame tofu for instance, he clarified how a solitary change can make a scope of new mixes: &quot;Chilly, it&#39;s very restricted, yet when singed it opens up endless choices &ndash; I&#39;ve served it with umami sauce, even crushed potato. At the point when I understood the distinction one change can make, it enlivened me, it truly speaks to what I need to do here at Sougo.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nomura grasps the ways of thinking of shjin ryri and has discovered they are lined up with the developing maintainability focal point of eateries around the world. Close by the hyper-occasional component of evade is an intend to utilize privately sourced fixings. Known as shindofuji, the second center idea features the requirement for being in concordance with nature, urging the cook to explicitly look for what develops around them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shading, flavor and procedure are totally required components in shjin food (Credit: Credit: Paolo Negri/Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shading, flavor and procedure are totally required components in shjin cooking for food to interest the five detects (Credit: Paolo Negri/Alamy)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The last column, and maybe the most intelligent of the maintainability zeitgeist, is ichimotsu zentai, which implies truly &quot;to utilize the entire thing&quot;. Requesting regard, it is a forerunner to the zero-squander development. &quot;The most significant piece of shjin is thought and thankfulness,&quot; noted Nomura, &quot;For us to endure, we get the lives of different things, so we should not squander them.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This mindfulness and thankfulness has risen above shjin food to be perceived toward the beginning of all dinners in Japanese every day life. Guests will no uncertainty have heard the expression &quot;itadakim</p>', 'Meal', 'p08q7n7l_1599906831.jpg', '2020-09-12 14:33:52', '2021-12-19 17:36:59');
