(512, 4, 7, 46, 'she-got-ill-when-the-pandemic-hit-and-still-is-six-months-later-1599909135', 'She got ill when the pandemic hit - and still is, six months later', 0, '<p>Monique Jackson accepts she got Covid-19 right off the bat in the pandemic and almost a half year later she&#39;s as yet unwell. One of thousands in this position, she has been keeping an outlined journal about her indications and her vain endeavors to get treatment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>About a year prior, Monique Jackson viewed a Ted talk about mushrooms and was enchanted. Growths, the speaker stated, are the first internet, they have an organization that runs under whole woods; it empowers trees to help one another on the off chance that they fall into difficulty.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nowadays, as she fights the Covid for the 24th week straight, it&#39;s something she ponders regularly.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She has suspected &quot;long-tail Covid&quot; an unmistakable response to the infection that specialists are simply starting to consider. She became ill in March and from the outset it was by all accounts a mellow form of the illness however her manifestations have never disappeared. Months after the fact, she is attempting to comprehend what is befalling her body.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Monique is a social butterfly, practically hyperactive she says. In ordinary occasions, she rehearses Thai boxing and jiu-jitsu and cycles 12 miles every day to and from her activity in a craftsmanship exhibition in focal London.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, the previous barely any months have significantly transformed her. Presently, she has a rundown on her room divider reminding her to spare enough vitality every day to brush her teeth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m not an apathetic individual,&quot; she says. Occasionally, however, it&#39;s everything she can never really down the steps.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While her body declines to co-work she&#39;s discovered an outlet for her eagerness in Instagram, where she&#39;s begun a delineated journal of her indications.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She&#39;s utilizing the journal to inform individuals regarding this new condition and to associate with others similarly situated, the &quot;long-haulers&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Much about Covid is perplexing specialists yet &quot;long-tail&quot; Covid is one of the most bewildering highlights of the pandemic. For what reason are a few people getting a form of the sickness that simply isn&#39;t disappearing - regularly the individuals who were just somewhat influenced in any case?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Monique became ill simultaneously as a companion, after they took a train venture together. Toward the starting they would stay in contact, their indications reflected each other impeccably yet then they severed contact for some time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I needed to stop, it was excessively freaky,&quot; Monique says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the initial fourteen days she felt fluey - she was so worn out she could scarcely get up. It was as yet cold in London yet she was scarcely dressed and held a pack of ice to her head to keep cool. Thermometers were sold out however she figures she probably had a temperature.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s abnormal saying &#39;I think&#39;. Such an extensive amount this is simply, you think - however you simply don&#39;t have the foggiest idea.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By week two she was attempting to relax. An emergency vehicle came yet said her oxygen levels were OK. &quot;They disclosed to me I was having a fit of anxiety, conceivably off the rear of side effects.&quot; She wasn&#39;t tried for Covid-19 then in light of the fact that in March the UK was holding the modest number of test packs it had for the most outrageous cases.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She attempted to treat herself with regular cures. When eating crude garlic and entire bean stew peppers, she thought it was unusual that she was unable to taste anything. What&#39;s more, she was worn out. &quot;I didn&#39;t have vitality to message multiple individuals daily,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following fourteen days, a portion of the manifestations lifted however they just appeared to be supplanted with new ones. &quot;I had this squeeze in the focal point of my chest. Furthermore, that squeeze transformed into what felt like such a fire,&quot; she says. &quot;It resembled teeth-gritting torment on the left side. I thought I was having a coronary failure.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She called 111 and they exhorted taking paracetamol. They said it appeared to cause the torment to vanish for certain individuals however they didn&#39;t completely get why.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The paracetamol worked however nearly when that agony went her stomach and throat started to consume &quot;like fire&quot; when she ate. Specialists thought she had a ulcer. It wasn&#39;t until later that gastric issues were perceived as a side effect of the infection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Around a month and a half in, Monique began having consuming sensations when she peed and torment in her lower back. The specialist put her on three unique rounds of anti-infection agents before concluding it was anything but a bacterial contamination.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It was simply distress,&quot; she says. &quot;And afterward it just went.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Monique cut herself off from web-based media. In any event, tuning in to web recordings was troublesome in light of the fact that any notice of Covid would make her restless and influence her relaxing. A self-admitted news addict, presently she was unable to confront it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She was worried about the possibility that that in the event that she went via web-based media she would see post after post of dead bodies. She discovered comfort in web based shopping however in any event, entering a dress size in the inquiry tab raised shocking tales about new manifestations of the infection. &quot;I was really terrified of going on Google,&quot; she says&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Inevitably she requested that a companion fill her in on what had been going on the planet. One of the main things she learned was that a higher extent of individuals from dark and minority ethnic foundations were passing on. Monique is blended race and she was frightened.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It seemed like a thriller where all the individuals of color ceased to exist,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One day she was lying in the shower tuning in to a digital recording when the two white has coolly referenced that a great deal of African Americans were biting the dust from Covid-19.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She sat straight as an arrow and promptly snatched her telephone to email dark family members in the US.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, she thought about the way that most of individuals she had depended on of late had been individuals from minorities - the Uber drivers who took her to arrangements, the emergency clinic laborers, the individuals in the corner shop where her food originated from. &quot;Each and every individual who I was seeing on my Covid venture,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In her normal everyday life, it wasn&#39;t that way.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As weeks passed by, a few side effects traded out for other people, getting increasingly unusual. A genuine annoyance was joined by an unusual sensation in her ear, similar to a parcel of crisps being squashed in somebody&#39;s grasp. Her hands went blue and she needed to hurry to a warm tap to attempt to bring the blood once again into them. The specialist later inquired as to whether she had snapped a photo, yet it had been the keep going thing at the forefront of her thoughts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I continued calling about new manifestations and I would be asked, &#39;How&#39;s your psychological well-being doing?&#39;&quot; she says. &quot;The suggestion being that these indications weren&#39;t treatable or weren&#39;t genuine torment.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She got weird rashes everywhere on over her body or her toes would go splendid red, at times she would wake up with agonizing feelings in various pieces of her middle.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One night, as she was conversing with her companion on the telephone she felt the correct side of her face drop. She went directly to the mirror however her face looked ordinary. She was concerned she was having a stroke however the specialists found no proof of one.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She&#39;s had odd sensations everywhere on over her body as well. At times it seems like somebody is getting her leg with their hands or hairs are being hauled over her face - even inside her mouth.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She invested a great deal of energy attempting to disclose what was occurring to specialists. Frequently she just had a five or 10-minute bring in which to attempt to hand-off all that was going on in her body and it wasn&#39;t sufficient.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;On the off chance that they&#39;d said to me, &#39;Look, you have Covid, and we have no clue about how to treat this,&#39; at that point that&#39;d be fine,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She wriggles as she attempts to sum up how she was dealt with. She&#39;s hesitant to censure staff of the NHS, huge numbers of whom have given her phenomenal consideration yet she says the framework isn&#39;t working for individuals in her position.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was nine weeks before Monique could get a test for Covid. During that time, she was frightened of passing the infection to another person.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Government counsel said to segregate for seven days or until manifestations disappeared - yet imagine a scenario where they never disappeared, she thought.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her flatmates contrived a framework to stay away from contact in the house - they each had a spot on the cooler they&#39;d use to pull it open.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At that point they would go to their rooms to eat alone.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One day she went to get some outside air at a recreation center close to her home with a companion when a little youngster ran up near her. Monique bounced up to move away from the little child. The mother was irate. &quot;The kid was not even close to you!&quot; she said. Monique attempted to clarify, she wasn&#39;t apprehensive about getting contaminated, she feared passing the infection on. Wiped out individuals should remain at home, the mother advised her.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She trusts that her journal will help individuals to comprehend that it&#39;s not generally that straightforward.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While companions made a special effort to support her, Monique could tell that others were getting tired. None of what was befalling her appeared well and good to anybody. &quot;One individual said I was getting fixated on having Covid,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At long last the UK government opened up testing to anybody demonstrating indications. She was excited however there was a trick - the main community she could discover was a drive-in and she didn&#39;t have a vehicle. &quot;A large portion of my companions can&#39;t drive,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One companion stepped up and give her a lift, and the way that he put himself in danger in the process isn&#39;t lost on her.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the testing place she expected to be consoled by medical attendants and specialists yet rather it was staffed by fighters, their khakis doused on a sweat-soaked day in June. As she stuck a q-tip up her nose it struck her how youthful they were.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The outcomes returned negative - demonstrating that she no longer had the infection, however not that she had never had it. It was a gigantic help since she&#39;d been told this implied she was unable to contaminate her loved ones. Be that as it may, she felt odd. &quot;The sentiment of being infectious is mentally difficult to proceed onward from,&quot; she wrote in her journal later. It was likewise befuddling on the grounds that she wasn&#39;t feeling any better.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Four months after she previously became ill, she chose to move out of her home offer in East London. Staying aware of straightforward things like cleaning was troublesome and she needed to associate with family who could support her.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her breathing had improved, though toward the starting she was unable to make it up the steps ceaselessly to slow down by July she could do it one go.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, subsequent to getting the hoover for around four minutes to attempt to tidy up her room she fallen from windedness. She was</p>', 'pandemic hit', '_114181623_crying_1599909135.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:12:15', '2021-08-16 09:49:55'),
(513, 7, 5, 174, 'the-man-who-owns-3000-cameras-1599909293', 'The man who owns 3,000 cameras', 0, '<p>One of the world&#39;s largest collections of cameras is hidden away in a town hall in the coastal town of Fife - but hardly anyone knows it&#39;s there.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At least 3,000 cameras, including some dating over a century, belonged to the late Neville &quot;Jim&quot; Matthew.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After a career that took him around the world, he retired in the ancient village of St. Monans in the Eastern Neuk.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He took over the former Salvation Army hall to preserve his treasured collection. In the hall, cameras, accessories and souvenirs fill the shelves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This includes stereoscopic and 3D cameras, as well as Eastern European models, including many that are rare in the West.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/9E10/production/_114246404_p1940390a.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAt the heart of this collection is the Kodak Brownie line of cameras - with nearly every model ever made.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Brownie was the first camera available and could only be bought for a dollar when it first went on sale in 1900.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jim wanted his collection to be traction, but he was getting older and worse, and the task was a huge challenge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead, it is limited to opening once a year for village festivals and from time to time for private tours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/18113/production/_114197589_p1940379a.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;She loves to talk about it with people when they come into the room,&quot; said his widow Dorothy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Sometimes I have to come down and save him because he doesn&#39;t know when to stop.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He&#39;s a very good talker. He doesn&#39;t say much, but if it&#39;s something that interests him, he can talk for a long time.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jim, who died in late 2017 at the age of 81, had started the collection 24 years earlier on a trip to Vancouver, Canada to meet his daughter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They went to an antiques shop and his wife Dorothy bought him an old camera as a gift.<br />\r\nShortly thereafter, while Jim was recovering from heart surgery, they traveled along the west coast of the United States to Oregon, where there are many antique shops.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He started pottery and found lots of cameras he liked,&quot; said Dorothy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It expands from there. When it enters your mind, it comes out.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He&#39;s not going to quit. He never said why. He just started and moved.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dorothy says Jim gathers &quot;at the best of times&quot; because people ditched their old cameras and opted for new digital models.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Whenever he went anywhere, he always came back with several cameras,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He travels a lot for work and fun and is always looking for flea markets or places to sell used goods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Poland has turned out to be an invaluable tourist destination as it eliminates many Russian cameras from the Soviet era.<br />\r\n&quot;He&#39;s going to try to find cameras on all sides when he goes on vacation,&quot; said Dorothy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also asked his friends if they had time to find him a camera, and they often did.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jim was born in Bolton, Greater Manchester, and went to sea as a cadet engineer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While at sea, his parents moved to Glasgow, where he met Dorothy - and changed his name from Neville, who didn&#39;t do well in Scotland.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/EC30/production/_114246406_p1940377.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe couple soon married and had three children.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jim&#39;s job as a marine engineer has taken him around the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her family lived in Hong Kong for seven years, two years in Greece, five years in the Netherlands and 12 years in Canada.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dorothy says Jim &quot;lives to travel&quot; and there are very few places he hasn&#39;t visited.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/FFB3/production/_114195456_p1940373a.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nHe often travels alone because he is only interested in being behind the camera, his wife said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I lost a lot of money.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He&#39;s taking great pictures so I think he&#39;s happy with the results. He wants to take pictures, not just photos. He&#39;s totally immersed in them.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As Jim&#39;s collection grew, the couple lived in the Netherlands and kept their cameras in their office.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In preparation for retirement, they bought a house in St. Petersburg. Monans to be close to Dorothy&#39;s mother.<br />\r\nIt wasn&#39;t big enough to hold a camera collection, so Jim bought the local Salvation Army Hall.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nearly three years after his death, Dorothy worked with a charity to transfer ownership of the building and collections and turn them into a museum.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/976/cpsprodpb/15EBE/production/_114209798_p1940395a.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dorothy, who now lives in Canada, said she was &quot;very pleased&quot; by the sight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I didn&#39;t know this was going to happen and I was worried about what we were going to do,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t want them to be dumped.&quot;</p>', '300 Cameras, Man', '3000Cameras_1599909293.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:14:53', '2021-08-12 15:21:22'),
(514, 4, 7, 44, 'why-i-stopped-hiding-my-scars-1599909373', '\'Why I stopped hiding my scars\'', 0, '<p>Jayne, Emily and Laura make them thing in like manner - they all have scars. Aimee, as far as concerns her, has flare-ups of psoriasis that can leave her face shrouded in red patches. Yet, every one of the four have come to feel good in their own skin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;My legs appeared as though I&#39;d come directly from The Walking Dead&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following medical procedure, I got a substance eating bug (necrotising fasciitis) which consumed my legs from my mid-thigh down to my feet. At first, there was no substance on my bones from my leg down. They took skin from my back, my base, and my stomach and they&#39;ve supplanted all the skin from my thigh down, which looks somewhat like reptilian skin. To get the measure of skin they required, they needed to extend it like a web to make the skin greater - like through a pasta machine.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I had a condition called lipoedema. It&#39;s transcendently ladies that get it and it&#39;s irregular fat cells starting from the waist. I was on top about a size eight to 10 and afterward on the last a 18 at once. I lost a great deal of weight, yet it doesn&#39;t eat less or practice away and it&#39;s excruciating. I began going to and fro to the GP around eight years back, and afterward was informed that this condition wasn&#39;t treatable on the NHS. In 2017 I got the fearlessness to proceed to have some medical procedure on it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;d gone into it so amped up for having this extraordinary life, having the option to simply wear ordinary garments, which I wasn&#39;t ready to previously, and afterward around five days after I had the subsequent medical procedure, I turned out to be incredibly, sick. The following thing I recollect that, I woke up to find that I&#39;d been in a state of unconsciousness and I was absolutely insane and I had psychosis and I thought everyone was robots. I thought I was in the emergency clinic for clinical examinations and it was simply completely alarming. My family had been there, they didn&#39;t think I would endure the night, and they&#39;d needed to sign an assent, since they thought they would need to cut away both of my legs. It was an unnerving time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was around six-seven weeks in before I really observed what my legs resembled and it was an immense stun. They just looked like two line cleaners. For someone that needed to have thin legs, my legs seemed as though I&#39;d come directly from The Walking Dead. Somehow or another, intellectually, it&#39;s been truly extreme since I have PTSD (post-horrible pressure issue), particularly to do with anything clinical.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However what it has done is it&#39;s truly caused me to value my life more. I&#39;ve experienced a spell of making a decent attempt to do heaps of things on the off chance that one day something occurs and I&#39;m not here any more. I need to tick the same number of things off that can list as I can. I haven&#39;t been to the Moulin Rouge in Paris, or the Orient Express. I need to visit Petra, need to go to Amsterdam. I don&#39;t know about the mile-high club, if [my partner] Carl&#39;s up for that one, however it&#39;s on there notwithstanding.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It isn&#39;t in every case simple. I&#39;m not generally upbeat and it&#39;s changed my character. At that point I simply dust myself off and I go into the following day with a &quot;Right that is it, we will do this.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jayne, 49, from Shropshire&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;It speaks to a great deal of torment, yet additionally a ton of surviving&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>My scar&#39;s on my correct hand, very near my wrist. It&#39;s somewhat raised off my skin. To the touch, it feels somewhat hard, somewhat uneven in certain territories, delicate in regions, and as far as its shading, it&#39;s somewhat more obscure than my shade. In my life I have self-hurt multiple times on my arm and it&#39;s completely been on a similar zone. This is on the grounds that I would not like to get additional scars on an alternate aspect of my body.</p>', 'scars\\', '_113795579_976xgarden20200201_181536_1599909373.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:16:13', '2021-08-15 02:05:28'),
(515, 7, 3, 82, 'marvel-avengers-games-can-be-more-personal-than-movies-1599909585', 'Marvel Avengers: Games can be more \"personal\" than movies', 0, '<p><strong>Thor spins M&ouml;lnir&#39;s hammer and smashes the robotic hair from space.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>He&#39;s defended planet Earth, the work he&#39;s done in comics, television and - most recently - films for nearly 50 years. But this time Thor&#39;s look and voice are a little different on screen. And it will behave differently depending on who is playing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because this isn&#39;t a movie. This is a new game with the Avengers. According to the actor who resurrected Thor for these reasons, this isn&#39;t just a bad clone of Marvel&#39;s hugely hit blockbuster.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travis Willingham told Newsbeat Radio 1, &quot;For me ... he&#39;s making his own film.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Instead of just being in a passive observer perspective.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/170C7/production/_114270449_screenshot2020-09-07at11.45.51.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe Black Widow, best known for her role as Scarlett Johansson in the film, was played by Laura Bailey in this drama.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And for them, the main difference between the two versions is choice. &quot;You have to embody this character,&quot; he said. &quot;You have to feel like them - but they have to be the version you want.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travis and Laura share a sofa in their home in California - they spoke with us online. Because - a story twist - in the real world, Black Widow and Thor are married.<br />\r\n&quot;How does it feel to sit next to a god?&quot; Travis joked in his voice, Thor. He says he doesn&#39;t get tired of the inevitable comparisons to the hugely successful film franchise.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I love what Chris Hemsworth does as Thor,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/3C2F/production/_114270451_avengers6.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s a lie to say that I didn&#39;t use this as a starting point for the hero.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He can be very violent or very aggressive - on the contrary, he makes him a very real character and is connected with lots of obvious weaknesses and strengths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;My movies are always showing!&quot;<br />\r\nWhen the game was first announced, the character was criticized by some for looking like a rather boring version of the legendary superhero.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But behind the animation is the king.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From Nolan North (who played Nathan Drake in the Uncharted series) and Troy Baker (best known for his role as Joel in The Last of Us) to Travis and Laura.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travis was most recently cast as the kingpin in Spider-Man and Laura as Abby in The Last of Us 2.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fall Guys: Small dots, obstacles, and hate mail<br />\r\nThey also have a long history of playing that role in previous games, from mobile titles to Lego versions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The developers hope the new version of the character will appeal to Marvel fans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The game is played from a third person perspective. Like titles like Destiny 2 or The Division, players must work their way through missions to further enhance the skills, equipment, and strengths of their chosen characters.<br />\r\nSo far the reviews have been mixed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some reviewers were frustrated by the lack of variety in gameplay and technical issues, while being impressed by the game&#39;s appearance and some cinematic moments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travis and Laura hope to find viewers who are interested in more Avengers action.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There&#39;s no way we can be like a movie,&quot; said Laura.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We made up a very different story and were happy to part like that.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Travis added, &quot;Being with this character, being able to decide what action to take, having this agency, is unique.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I find it refreshing for audiences who know Marvel to know that there are new rules, new dynamics, and new things to learn and explore.&quot;</p>', 'Marvel Avengers, Games', 'Marvel avengers_1599909585.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:19:45', '2021-08-16 14:59:20'),
(516, 4, 16, 210, 'the-king-his-lover-and-the-elephant-in-the-palace-1599909607', 'The king, his lover - and the elephant in the palace', 0, '<p>Toward the beginning of August, Spain&#39;s previous King Juan Carlos left the nation following claims of monetary bad behavior. Yet, the nation&#39;s fondness for its ruler started to unwind as far back as 2012, after a doomed elephant chase. With the ruler on that safari was his previous sweetheart Corinna zu Sayn-Wittgenstein. She talks solely to the BBC about a multi-million euro blessing from Juan Carlos, her cases of provocation by Spain&#39;s mystery administration - and that elephant.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Aside from Corinna zu Sayn-Wittgenstein would truly not like to discuss the elephant - the one King Juan Carlos shot dead on 11 April 2012. The media announced the creature was 50 years of age and gauged five tons, with tusks in excess of a meter long.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Not that she can check the animal&#39;s essential measurements when gotten some information about the occurrence. &quot;I have no clue,&quot; says the Danish-conceived business expert, who was raised in Germany. Truly, she was on the safari with the ruler, however she says she was a good ways off when the shooting occurred.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I saw it thereafter on the grounds that everyone goes to see it,&quot; she says. &quot;Yet, I left following two minutes. I&#39;m a tracker, however I&#39;ve never executed an elephant in my life and never would. For me, the entire chasing experience was horrible in that sense.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The safari in Botswana was a present from the ruler to her child on his tenth birthday celebration. Juan Carlos had gotten near zu Sayn-Wittgenstein&#39;s kids during his sentimental relationship with her from 2004 to 2009 - a relationship which the Spanish open thought nothing about at that point. Since 1962 he has been hitched to Queen Sofia.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I wasn&#39;t enthused about going on this outing,&quot; zu Sayn-Wittgenstein says. &quot;I felt that King Juan Carlos was attempting to get me to return to him, and I would not like to give a bogus impression. I nearly had feelings about this excursion.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All things considered, incidentally. Before sunrise on 13 April 2012, the ruler fell in his extravagance safari tent, cracking his hip.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On his re-visitation of Madrid, the media fell on the safari story like a ravenous lion on a delicate gazelle. The disclosure of the elephant chase came extremely not long after a defilement examination started into the ruler&#39;s child in-law, I&ntilde;aki Urdangarin - he is still in jail.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This was a period of genuine difficulty in Spain, with joblessness running at 23%. Subsequent to going through an activity, King Juan Carlos unveiled his first conditional appearance in clinic utilizing a mobile stick. He was asked how he was.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lord Juan Carlos apologizes for the chasing trip after his release from medical clinic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m heartbroken,&quot; he said. &quot;I committed an error, and it won&#39;t occur once more.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lord Juan Carlos had been generally distant in light of his place in Spain&#39;s tormented, grisly history. As head of state after Francisco Franco&#39;s demise in 1975, the ruler had regulated Spain&#39;s change from tyranny to majority rule government and looked down an upset endeavor in 1981. Presently the harm to the well known ruler was massive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tune in to Spain: The elephant in the royal residence on Crossing Continents, on BBC Radio 4 at 11:00 on Thursday 20 August&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Or then again look up some other time on the web&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The emergency exploded in light of the fact that the Botswana trip put a few things on the table,&quot; says Jose Antonio Zarzalejos, a previous manager of Spain&#39;s conservative, government supporting paper ABC.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Right off the bat, that the ruler was transparently untrustworthy to Queen Sofia. Besides, that amidst a monetary emergency, Juan Carlos visited a nation where Spain had no strategic portrayal. So the ruler - as head of state - was off the radar of the Spanish government. Furthermore, thirdly, this was an over the top expensive outing - we didn&#39;t have the foggiest idea who paid for it. It made an inferior picture of the lord.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Short presentational dim line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lord Juan Carlos and zu Sayn Wittgenstein met at a shooting party in February 2004.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She says the lord was experiencing difficulty with his shotgun. &quot;What&#39;s more, I&#39;m very learned pretty much all that, so I could clarify what wasn&#39;t right,&quot; she says. &quot;I think he was very astounded.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The relationship moved gradually.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We wound up talking on the telephone for a couple of months,&quot; she says. &quot;The principal date was in late-spring. We generally chuckled a great deal. We promptly tapped on numerous things, and we had numerous normal interests - governmental issues, history, fabulous food, wines&hellip;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was living in London at that point, having recently begun my own consultancy business. What&#39;s more, I was a single parent of two. So we would meet in Madrid in a little bungalow on the bigger bequest, and we voyaged together.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In the main year it was more troublesome on the grounds that I was occupied and he had a full plan, however he would telephone me up to 10 times each day. That is to say, it was a quickly solid, profound and important relationship.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At a certain point, zu Sayn-Wittgenstein says she asked the lord how this would sit with his better half, Queen Sofia.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He said they had a plan to speak to the crown, however they drove entirely unexpected, separate lives. What&#39;s more, the ruler had quite recently emerged from an almost 20-year relationship with another woman who likewise had a significant spot in his heart and in his life.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lord and zu Sayn-Wittgenstein turned out to be close. She invested energy with the ruler&#39;s companions and she met his youngsters.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2009, her dad got a visit from Juan Carlos.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He rang me and said the lord had come see him and revealed to him he was particularly infatuated with me, and planned to wed me,&quot; she says. &quot;He likewise told my dad he was unable to do it straight away, it may take some time. He needed my dad to realize he was intense about me.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was before during the very year that zu Sayn-Wittgenstein says King Juan Carlos had proposed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Clearly, it&#39;s an extremely enthusiastic second when something to that effect occurs,&quot; she says. &quot;What&#39;s more, I was particularly infatuated with him, however I predicted - I&#39;m a political tactician - this would be extremely troublesome. Furthermore, I figured it may destabilize the government.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That is the reason I never truly empowered it - I just accepting it as a badge of the earnestness of the relationship, as opposed to something that would really appear.&quot;</p>', 'palace', '_114010059_blurchristmas_crop976_1599909607.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:20:07', '2021-12-19 17:35:33'),
(517, 7, 1, 62, 'four-meat-workers-at-the-smithfield-factory-died-from-a-covid-19-fine-of-13494-1599910219', 'Four meat workers at the Smithfield factory died from a COVID-19 fine of $ 13,494', 0, '<p><strong>U.S. Department of Labor on Thursday offered Smithfield Foods a $ 13,494 fine for failing to protect employees at a meat processing facility in Sioux Falls, South Dakota. Nearly 1,300 workers approved of COVID-19 and four died.</strong><br />\r\nThe sanctions permitted by the law come after the agency&#39;s safety and health agency inspected a pork processing facility, which was closed to employees for several weeks in April and May due to the coronavirus outbreak. OSHA cited Smithfield as insufficient prior to the first known infection at the factory on March 23, such as distributing workers or providing face coverings and physical barriers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The agency&#39;s instructions set out steps employers can take to protect workers during a pandemic that has killed more than 191,000 Americans. This includes social distancing, physical barriers, face shields and disguises, and security warnings that are communicated in a language that company employees understand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Employers must immediately take appropriate action to protect the safety and health of their workers,&quot; Sheila Stanley, director of OSHA Sioux Falls, said in a press release. &quot;Employers must fulfill their obligations and take the necessary measures to prevent the spread of the coronavirus in the workplace.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Smithfield is great<br />\r\nSmithfield dismissed OSHA&#39;s findings as baseless and said he would appeal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We are taking immediate action on our own initiative to keep our employees as healthy and safe as possible so that we can fulfill our obligation to the American people to safeguard food supplies,&quot; said Keira Lombardo, executive vice president of corporate affairs and compliance, Smithfield. Legislation specified in the email. &quot;We incurred an additional COVID-19 cost of $ 350 million just in the second quarter. Ironically, OSHA then used what we did as a model for their April 26 guideline.&quot;<br />\r\nThe Sioux Falls community is seeing an early leap in COVID-19 cases affecting the facility, according to Smithfield. The company&#39;s responses include asking OSHA to visit its operations in March and April - complaints that have been ignored, Lombardo said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;OSHA conducted an investigation and published its citations in accordance with established procedures and legal standards. The risks and necessary precautions were known at the time and Smithfield did not respond in a timely manner,&quot; the agency said in an email to CBS MoneyWatch. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Union: There are no &quot;real consequences&quot; for death<br />\r\nBoth OSHA and Smithfield have been punished by United Food and Commercial Workers, which represent 1.3 million meat producers and other key workers, including those at the Smithfield facility in Sioux Falls.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Smithfield is a multi-billion dollar company that has failed to protect its employees from many deaths and over a thousand infections. This OSHA response confirms that the company will have no real consequences,&quot; said Marc Perone, international president of the Union. said in the email.<br />\r\nFactory employees work from elbows in the production of nearly 5% of the country&#39;s pork. The UFCW said it was trying to negotiate more protection against the coronavirus that caused the spring outbreak.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A massive outbreak of meat processing plants across the country followed. United Food and Trade Workers, the largest trade union representing meat processing workers, counted 122 meat-packaged worker deaths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prior to OSHA&#39;s disclosure that four Smithfield workers had died from COVID-19, local media reported that only two Smithfield workers had died from the virus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OSHA opened an investigation to Smithfield&#39;s Sioux Falls facility on April 20 after a team from the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention visited the facility to discuss how meat packaging facilities should operate during a pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>OSHA asked South Dakota health authorities in June for all test results, Smithfield correspondence, or photos of the facility. The following month, Smithfield asked the South Dakota District Court to drop the subpoena. The company&#39;s legal action was later denied by the court after Smithfield and OSHA reached an agreement on the matter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A study published by the CDC last month found 929 employees - a quarter of factory workers - and 210 close contacts were infected. The initial state report was 853 employees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meat packers are aggressively defending themselves, emphasizing their role in the country&#39;s diet and warning of a meat shortage if processing plants are to be closed. President Donald Trump signed an executive order in April declaring the essential infrastructure of a meat factory. Since then, most have remained open.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The US slaughterhouse has more than recovered from the economic slowdown, according to the US Department of Agriculture. Red meat and pork production will exceed 2019 this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BJ Motley, chairman of the Smithfield Workers&#39; Union in Sioux Falls, told the Associated Press that Smithfield had followed most of the actions recommended by the CDC, but workers still gathered near the factory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But with increased demand for meat and staff shortages since the outbreak, Motley said, &quot;They&#39;re pushing their workers a lot harder now.&quot;</p>', 'Covid 19, 4 Died', 'SmithField workers died_1599910219.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:30:19', '2021-08-17 19:59:55'),
(518, 4, 16, 129, 'prosopagnosia-the-artist-in-search-of-her-face-1599910422', 'Prosopagnosia: The artist in search of her face', 0, '<p>Carlotta has always been unable to perceive faces, neither the essences of others, nor her own. Her condition, face visual impairment, has majorly affected her life yet has likewise given her a feeling of direction as a craftsman - to make self-representations of the face she can&#39;t picture in her brain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Carlotta plunks down to draw a self-picture. The room is extremely dim, lit just by a couple of candles. She needn&#39;t bother with light, since she&#39;s not utilizing a mirror or a photo - rather, with one hand she follows the forms of her face, while her other hand portrays the shapes on paper.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s consistently an unexpected when I see my drawings in light,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her condo is loaded up with self-representations - around 1,000 of them, she thinks. Every one is totally extraordinary, and they have a supernatural quality. Shapes cover. A few heads might be extended on head of one another, occasionally topsy turvy. In one, she has three eyes, in another six.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the off chance that she sees herself in a mirror, Carlotta will think, &quot;the lady seeing me is in my nightie and in my level, so it must be me&quot;. She will likewise perceive her hair - it&#39;s what occurs underneath those dark twists that is a riddle.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Short presentational dim line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Carlotta&#39;s condition started to cause issues when she was a little youngster, in Munich during the 1960s, however from the outset nobody truly took note.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;At the point when I went out on the town to shop with my mom, or went to the specialist&#39;s medical procedure, we would meet individuals who my mom obviously perceived, yet I didn&#39;t know what their identity was,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was flabbergasted that my mom could do this. I thought this was a stunning blessing she had, of perceiving others.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frequently Carlotta would hang tight for her mom outside the shops with her canine, and follow an inappropriate individual home, possibly acknowledging it wasn&#39;t her mom when they turned down an inappropriate road. She never revealed to her mom why. &quot;I thought it was most likely an issue with me, that I wasn&#39;t thinking enough.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So she depended on different pieces of information. &quot;I started to see what garments individuals were wearing, the manner in which they strolled, their voice or on the off chance that they were wearing glasses. Everybody has their own specific manner of breathing and their own particular manner of moving, the manner in which their garments stir, and that is the way I attempt to distinguish individuals.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was just when Carlotta went to class that she at long last got a handle on there was something other than what&#39;s expected about her. &quot;It was truly hard, on the grounds that the mystery of perceiving others&#39; faces that my mum had, I understood other youngsters had also,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All things considered, she didn&#39;t disclose to her folks. She expected that perceiving faces was an expertise, such as tying your shoelaces, that she would ace one day.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>School was a ruthless and frightful experience. Everybody appeared to be identical to Carlotta. On one event she was sent to the staff space to gather something from an instructor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I thumped on the entryway of the staff room. A man was remaining there, and I stated, &#39;I need Mr Schultz.&#39; I needed to rehash this multiple times, and he turned out to be exceptionally furious with me. He stated, &#39;I am Mr Schultz!&#39; He&#39;d been my top of the line educator, however I simply didn&#39;t remember him.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tune in to The face dazzle picture craftsman on Outlook, on the BBC World Service (maker Fiona Woods)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Download the Outlook web recording&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She had a go at recording every last bit of her instructors&#39; characterizing qualities - on the off chance that they had glasses or a whiskers, what shoes they wore - yet she additionally recorded which educators were well disposed and which ones weren&#39;t, and one day an educator furiously reallocated the rundown.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During mid-day breaks, Carlotta normally stood separated from different youngsters. The issue came when the ringer rang and the instructors would come to gather their classes. Kids would arrange in the play area, yet never in a similar spot. &quot;I regularly returned inside with an inappropriate class, and I didn&#39;t understand until I broke through to an inappropriate study hall. Also, clearly, in the event that a youngster can&#39;t perceive her cohorts, at that point she should be inept.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Educators responded with outrage and criticism.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;They made me remain before the class and stated, &#39;You have only sawdust between your ears.&#39; Or they&#39;d affront me: &#39;You&#39;re thick as a block.&#39;&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The kids harassed her as well. As an outcome, she pulled back from everybody. &quot;I wouldn&#39;t utter a word for all to hear. I would simply accomplish my composed work and didn&#39;t generally participate.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The school thought Carlotta had a learning handicap and kept in touch with her folks proposing that she be sent to an exceptional school. However, they realized this was pointless and overlooked the letters.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Toward the finish of the school day, Carlotta would run home dangerously fast and submerge herself in books. She read all that she could, particularly about nature, and fantasized about moving far away from everybody.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I had this thought I could dive deep into the backwoods and make myself such a cavern,&quot; she says.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;There would be a cavern for the kitchen, and a cavern of books - that would be the greatest. I just truly needed to dive deep under the earth into the haziness.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Being with others was hard for me. I very much wanted being in nature and being all alone.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the point when she left school at 17 she searched for a vocation which required as meager human contact as could be expected under the circumstances. She adores ponies, so she turned into a man of the hour, until managing the ponies&#39; proprietors and their kids turned out to be excessively.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Subsequent to filling in as a truck driver and concrete blender, she accepting a vocation as a projectionist, which was both lone and charming. Sci-fi films were her top choice, in light of the fact that the characters were more unmistakable and the plot was in this way simpler to follow.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This issue I have with faces is actually very explicit to people. The essences of creatures or outsiders I find extremely simple to remember!&quot; she says. This doesn&#39;t make a difference, however, to chimpanzees; they are excessively like people.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In her mid-20s she satisfied her youth fantasy about cutting herself off from individuals completely. She purchased a pontoon and cruised along the Australian coast for a year, understanding books and getting her day by day dinners from the ocean.</p>', 'Prosopagnosia', '_113324271_976xlostinface_still_1_1599910422.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:33:42', '2021-12-19 17:26:01');
