(519, 4, 7, 42, 'they-wanted-to-drown-me-at-birth-now-im-a-poet-1599910718', '\'They wanted to drown me at birth - now I\'m a poet\'', 0, '<p>Conceived in an Indian town with cerebral paralysis, Kuli Kohli was fortunate to endure. Neighbors disclosed to her folks they should toss her in the waterway, rather they carried her to the UK. As she grew up here, composing turned into her ways to get out - and changed her life in manners she never anticipated.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Holding back to be approached stage in her old neighborhood of Wolverhampton, Kuli Kohli felt wiped out with uneasiness. She was frozen her words wouldn&#39;t come out and stressed she would crash and burn. Her heart took off and her nerves banged. Self-question dashed through her psyche. &quot;For what reason am I getting myself through the entirety of this?&quot; she asked herself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The host invited Kuli to the vacant seat that was hanging tight for her. It was dull, a spotlight enlightened the stage, and a little influx of praise undulated around the room.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rising up out of the side of the stage, Kuli anxiously drew nearer the mic. She slowly inhaled and a couple of moments of quiet went before she imparted one of her sonnets to a crowd of people for the absolute first time.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mine&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have a fantasy; kindly don&#39;t impact it,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has a place with me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have a fragile heart; kindly don&#39;t break it,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has a place with me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have significant serenity; kindly don&#39;t upset it,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has a place with me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I need to follow a way; kindly don&#39;t deter it,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has a place with me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have an astounding life; it would be ideal if you let me live it,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has a place with me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have a decision; kindly don&#39;t decide for me,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has a place with me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have opportunity; kindly don&#39;t catch me,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It has a place with me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have unimaginable emotions; kindly don&#39;t hurt me,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They have a place with me.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I have a great deal of affection; kindly don&#39;t loathe me,&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Love is mine to share.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m on my material excursion; don&#39;t tail me&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It won&#39;t be reasonable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So... I have a fantasy; it&#39;s my fantasy to be free.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kuli had more explanation than most to encounter stage trepidation. She was brought into the world with cerebral paralysis, a neurological condition that influences her discourse, her development, stance, coordination and parity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Getting up in front of an audience and spilling out her verse was her triumph against the individuals who revealed to her that her life did not merit living due to her incapacity - that she could never add up to anything or accomplish her objectives. She was grasping and claiming an aspect of her personality, something she had been caused to feel embarrassed about for her entire life.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Short presentational dark line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 1970, when Kuli was conceived in a far off town in Uttar Pradesh, northern India, it before long became clear that she was not normal for different youngsters.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kuli&#39;s mom was around 15 years of age when she brought forth her. She was the primary conceived and numerous inside the network were baffled that she was not a kid - first-conceived girls were frequently viewed adversely. However, her sex wasn&#39;t the main thing the locals took note.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Individuals thought I was a weird young lady, since I was unique. Practically when I was conceived, individuals would advise my mom to dispose of me since no one would wed a young lady like this,&quot; she says.</p>', 'indian poet', '_113946341_kuli_at_penn_hall_school976x976_1599910718.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:38:38', '2021-08-16 10:22:28'),
(520, 4, 7, 55, 'world-suicide-prevention-day-could-i-have-stopped-my-dad-killing-himself-1599911074', 'World suicide prevention day: \'Could I have stopped my dad killing himself?\'', 0, '<p>We think we realize what self-destructive conduct resembles when somebody is youthful, yet when they are older the signs are frequently very unique. Kris Griffiths never envisioned his dad would murder himself, yet now acknowledges he missed various warnings.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the event that you stop somebody in the road and ask what the words &quot;male self destruction&quot; infers they&#39;ll presumably make reference to an artist, possibly Kurt Cobain or Keith Flint, or maybe a footballer, for example, Gary Speed. In all probability it will be somebody who became well known when they were youthful, maybe carried on with an existence of overabundance, and didn&#39;t make it to the relative steadiness and poise of middle age.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This discernment is upheld to a degree by measurements: self destruction is Britain&#39;s greatest enemy of guys under 50, with 45 to 49 the pinnacle age section, as per the latest authority figures for England and Wales. The figures additionally grimly affirm that the general self destruction rate has increased forcefully to its most significant level since 2000, with 75% being men - one passes on generally at regular intervals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Inside these dreary numbers, in any case, lies a shrouded segment of men who are smothering their carries on with far away from TV screens and Twitter channels - a later age bunch where self destruction rates rise once more, however out of the open eye. In 2018 my dad got one of them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Short presentational dim line&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Father was 76 when he ended his life, year and a half after Mum had passed on following a long ailment. He was always unable to deal with an amazing loss accomplice, feeling progressively desolate, futile and secluded, notwithstanding customary visits from his youngsters and grandkids.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One motivation behind why multiple times a bigger number of men than ladies kill themselves, is broadly thought to be the deep rooted molded adherence to manly personal conduct standards: stifling feelings as opposed to communicating them, which is considered shortcoming; and declining to look for help, either from loved ones or wellbeing experts.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The inclination to self-sedate with medications or liquor is likewise undeniably more normal among men, which constantly aggravates the issue, prompting incautious conduct.</p>', 'suicide', '_114297835_oldmangettyb_1599911074.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:44:34', '2021-08-15 03:37:34'),
(521, 4, 11, 123, 'rated-awards-stormzy-dizzee-rascal-and-j-hus-win-grm-daily-awards-1599911403', 'Rated Awards: Stormzy, Dizzee Rascal and J Hus win GRM Daily awards', 0, '<p>J Hus has been respected at the GRM Daily Rated Awards - winning collection of the year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Aitch and AJ Tracey&#39;s Rain got best video, while JAE5 brought home the honor for maker of the year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In his acknowledgment discourse, J Hus honored fans and everybody that participated in his subsequent collection, Big Conspiracy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So much exertion, difficult work, hard labor. I love you so much,&quot; he said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>D-Block Europe got male craftsman of the year, while Stefflon Don was the main female champ at the honors - for female craftsman of the year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All the candidates in the collection, mixtape and video of the year classifications were male.</p>', 'Rated Awards', '_114306975_jhuspic-theowilliams-1_1599911403.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:50:03', '2021-08-13 09:22:33'),
(522, 4, 11, 116, 'edinburghs-richard-cockerill-and-duhan-van-der-merwe-win-pro14-awards-1599911516', 'Edinburgh\'s Richard Cockerill and Duhan van der Merwe win Pro14 awards', 0, '<p>Edinburgh&#39;s Richard Cockerill says he is &quot;somewhat astounded&quot; subsequent to being named Pro14 mentor of the year, as winger Duhan van der Merwe was additionally casted a ballot players&#39; player of the period.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The pair were the decision of their friends following selections from club mentors, skippers and bad habit commanders.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Edinburgh beat Conference B yet lost to Ulster in the play-off semi-finals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m glad that it gives everyone acknowledgment at Edinburgh Rugby,&quot; Cockerill said of his honor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;ve buckled down over the most recent three years to fabricate what we&#39;re doing and, while it&#39;s consistently ideal to be perceived for an individual honor, it&#39;s a lot of a collaboration.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cockerill said Edinburgh were &quot;colossally baffled&quot; not to arrive at the Pro 14 last, yet included: &quot;We&#39;re as decided as ever to ricochet back and drive the club forward.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ulster must &#39;oversee vitality&quot; against Leinster&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scottish sides must be more heartless - Lawson&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Van der Merwe, who joined Edinburgh subsequent to leaving Montpellier in summer 2017, is one of six players from the club named in the Pro14 Dream Team.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The South Africa-conceived 25-year-old, who scored 11 attempts in 19 appearances and completed the season as the association&#39;s chief in meters made, protectors beaten and total separations, said he feels &quot;special&quot; to win the honor.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Never in my most extravagant fantasies did I accept that I could accomplish something this enormous and it&#39;s a splendid inclination realizing that it was casted a ballot by the folks I face in the Guinness Pro14 week in, week out,&quot; he included.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Getting an honor like this is monstrous for me and ideally features that the difficult work I&#39;ve placed in all through my vocation is beginning to pay off.&quot;</p>', 'Pro14 awards', '_114287116_18287472-1_1599911516.jpg', '2020-09-12 15:51:56', '2021-09-23 08:15:16'),
(523, 4, 13, 92, 'searches-for-dog-swept-over-waterfall-near-fort-william-1599912274', 'Searches for dog swept over waterfall near Fort William', 0, '<p>In excess of 20 individuals have been assisting with searching for a canine that has been absent since Saturday in the wake of being cleared over a cascade.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Angus Curran&#39;s springer spaniel, Angus, was being strolled by a companion when the mishap occurred at Lower Falls in Glen Nevis, close to Fort William.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A prepared sniffer canine got what Mr Curran accepts was Angus&#39; aroma almost a croft near the falls&#39; vehicle leave.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jumpers and automaton pilots have been among the volunteers searching for the canine.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Curran, a previous trooper with 1 Scots, The Royal Scots Borderers, said he and the others have been looking through consistently since Saturday.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He got Angus while filling in as a gamekeeper.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Curran stated: &quot;I was flabbergasted that on Wednesday we had 20 or more individuals appear and help with the pursuit.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have had jumpers in the water to check he isn&#39;t stuck or caught in the stream.&quot;</p>', 'Fort William', '_114329638_angusone_1599912274.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:04:34', '2021-12-19 17:40:57'),
(524, 4, 1, 73, 'coronavirus-fourteen-cases-after-drefach-sport-club-awards-1599912459', 'Coronavirus: Fourteen cases after Drefach sport club awards', 0, '<p>Around 100 individuals are disconnecting after 14 Covid cases were connected to a games club grants evening in Carmarthenshire.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Police and boards have cautioned Carmarthenshire, Pembrokeshire and Ceredigion could be placed into lockdown if individuals didn&#39;t social separation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It comes after around 60 to 80 individuals went to an occasion at Drefach Cricket and Football Club.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Carmarthenshire pioneer Emlyn Dole said individuals were &quot;putting lives in danger&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Dole revealed to BBC Wales that a couple of individuals&#39; activities were gambling others&#39; wellbeing, making him &quot;furious&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The gathering said the occasion at the games club was hung on 29 August and around 100 individuals were having to self-separate for 14 days.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture subtitle&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A shut sign has been set on the entryway of the games club&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an announcement, given on Monday, the Drefach FC said it had suspended preparing until further notification after some senior players tried positive for Covid-19.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We quickly exhorted Public Health Wales and are liaising with them on a proceeding with premise,&quot; it said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We are anticipating further counsel from them and guarantee you that we will refresh you further when it is gotten.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture inscription&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Dole said officials would be out in grocery stores and town focuses ensuring individuals social removed&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a joint explanation with Dyfed-Powys Police, Mr Dole, close by the pioneers of Pembrokeshire and Ceredigion chambers, stated: &quot;The exact opposite thing we need to do is go into a neighborhood lockdown, as has just happened somewhere else in Wales.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In any case, if the rising danger and absence of social separating proceeds with we may need to make important move.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This pandemic is a long way from being done - the infection is as yet circling and the danger is still high. Individuals need to regard the measures that are set up and assume individual liability for social separating and great cleanliness.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What are the standards for meeting companions?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dr Giri Shankar: &quot;We deal with any bunches of Coronavirus properly, including by giving exhortation around disease avoidance and control, and by supporting contact following where required.&quot;</p>', 'Coronavirus', '_114304427_football4_1599912459.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:07:39', '2021-08-11 23:58:51'),
(525, 7, 1, 83, 'more-than-half-of-the-population-of-americas-major-cities-is-struggling-financially-against-the-backdrop-of-the-coronavirus-pandemic-1599912501', 'More than half of the population of America\'s major cities is struggling financially against the backdrop of the coronavirus pandemic', 0, '<p><strong>More than half of American families in the country&#39;s largest cities struggle to pay their credit cards and access medical care. This is evident from a recent study that highlighted the ongoing economic costs of the coronavirus.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to an August study by Harvard University, NPR and the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation, most residents of Chicago (50%, Houston) (63%), Los Angeles (56%) and New York (53%) states lost their jobs. Places during a pandemic that weighed on their budgets and drained their household savings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of the financial troubles are in homes where major addicts are evicted, laid off or their working hours are reduced, the results show. The largely colorful district was hit hardest.<br />\r\nFor example, in Chicago, 69% and 63% of blacks and Spaniards respectively report serious financial problems, compared to 33% of whites. In Houston, 81% of blacks and 77% of Hispanics fought.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Robert Blendon, a retired Harvard public health professor who co-authored the study, said the survey and other data highlighted the economic disparities highlighted by the coronavirus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We want to believe that we are all in this together, [but] the results show a problem that focuses on people earning less than $ 100,000, people who have lost their pay or jobs, and black people and Latin women,&quot; she said. in a statement.<br />\r\nOf the nearly 3,000 city dwellers surveyed in the study, a large number of households in New York, Los Angeles, Chicago, and Houston said that getting medical care was difficult in recent weeks because treatment costs were too high or not. find a doctor. Barriers to accessing health care range from an inability to schedule appointments at the right time to a lack of doctors accepting their insurance.<br />\r\nThis underscores how inaccessible health care is for many Americans, said Richard Besser, CEO of the Johnson Foundation. &quot;At a time when a large number of people desperately need medical care, many cannot get it,&quot; he said in a statement. &quot;It is unacceptable that in a rich country like ours, factors such as income or race play a large role in access to health care.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Harvard poll reflects a study by Rand Corp. the opposite. Until June, people earning less than $ 25,000 a year had difficulty paying their bills. Nearly one-third of middle-class families who earn between $ 25,000 and $ 125,000 a year say they also have problems, according to the survey.</p>', 'America, Financially struglling, families', 'US strugling financially_1599912501.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:08:21', '2021-08-17 19:01:01'),
(526, 4, 13, 131, 'piranha-found-dead-in-river-ness-at-inverness-1599912597', '\'Piranha\' found dead in River Ness at Inverness', 0, '<p>What is believed to be a piranha or a nearby relative of the fish has been discovered dead in the River Ness at Inverness.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The disclosure by Ness District Fishery Board followed a fisherman going over two Central American types of fish in the stream.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The board said the fish found on Tuesday could be a piranha or a silver dollar, a relative of piranha and pacu.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The other outlandish fish discovered were believed to be Jaguar cichlids.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is suspected the fish were kept as pets before being dumped. The warm water species would not have endure long in the Ness.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yet, the fishery board said the fish could have had ailments or parasites that represented a danger to local fish.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionTwo cichlids were found by a fisherman before&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two cichlids were found by an individual from Inverness Angling Club, and a third by the fishery board after chief Chris Conroy and an associate examined whether other colorful fish had been dumped.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>picture captionThe fish found on Tuesday was dead&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Conroy stated: &quot;Any arrival of non-local species into the wild is very flippant and could have critical negative effects on our local fish stocks.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The species found to date are altogether local to a warm atmosphere thus had practically zero possibility of getting by in the virus waters of the River Ness. They could anyway represent a huge malady hazard.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The River Ness streams from Loch Ness to the ocean at Inverness.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Ness waterway framework&#39;s local species incorporate salmon, trout and European eels, an animal proposed to be behind the legend of the Loch Ness Monster.</p>', 'Piranha', '_114291139_chris_1599912597.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:09:57', '2021-12-19 17:26:47'),
(527, 7, 1, 80, 'a-13-year-old-boy-died-of-brain-eating-amoebae-after-vacationing-in-florida-the-family-said-1599912782', 'A 13-year-old boy died of brain-eating amoebae after vacationing in Florida, the family said', 0, '<p><strong>One teenager&#39;s family said he died of brain-eating amoeba after resting at a campsite in North Florida last month, local TV WJXT reported. Tanner Lake Wall, 13, of Tent, Florida, was at the resort, which includes a water park and lake, before suddenly falling ill a few days later, according to his parents.</strong><br />\r\n&quot;He&#39;s just the guy you&#39;ve always wanted,&quot; said Travis Wall, the boy&#39;s father. His mother said the teenager was very active and was loved openly. Wall&#39;s early symptoms include nausea, vomiting, neck stiffness, and severe headache.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wall&#39;s parents took him to a hospital in Gainesville, Florida, where doctors put the teenager on a ventilator and gave his family a poor diagnosis. &quot;They said, &#39;He has parasitic amoebas and there is no treatment,&#39;&quot; his father told the station. On August 2, Stena was removed from the life support system after showing no brain activity.<br />\r\nWall&#39;s parents hope their tragic story will tell other families about the dangers of this potentially fatal infection. &quot;So parents realize they may not think about it because I can tell you for sure we are not,&quot; said Travis Wall. &quot;We grew up on lakes and rivers and things like that.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Naegleria fowleri - also known as &quot;brain-eating amoebae&quot; - can cause a brain infection known as primary amoebic meningoencephalitis, according to the CDC. Amoebas are usually found in fresh water such as lakes, rivers and springs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CDC warns that infection can occur if contaminated water gets into a person&#39;s nose and brain. Symptoms start with a severe headache, fever, nausea, and vomiting. Later symptoms can cause neck stiffness, seizures, altered mental status, hallucinations, and coma.<br />\r\nSigns of infection usually begin several days after swimming or nasal exposure to other contaminated water. People die within one to 18 days of symptoms appearing. However, according to the CDC, humans cannot become infected by ingesting contaminated water.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Wall family told WJXT that warning signs should be installed to educate others about the dangers of swimming in warm water in summer. The station failed to identify the campsite the Walls visited because officials had not yet traced Wall&#39;s disease back to the site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;People need to be aware of hot water from July to the second half of September that these amoebae can get up to your nose. Can dive. &quot;Can swim, water sports, skiing, things like that,&quot; explained Travis Wall. .<br />\r\nInfection with Naegleria fowleri is rare, according to the CDC. Between 2009 and 2018, 34 infections were registered in the United States. In most cases, according to the CDC, people became infected with recreational water, while three people became infected with contaminated tap water after rinsing their noses. One person was infected with tainted tap water used in sliding doors in the yard.</p>', 'Amoebae, Florida, boy Died', '13y boy_1599912782.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:13:02', '2021-08-17 13:55:50'),
(528, 7, 1, 75, 'home-depot-announced-a-deal-for-black-friday-which-will-run-for-two-months-1599912959', 'Home Depot announced a deal for Black Friday, which will run for two months', 0, '<p><strong>Over the past few years, retailers have been trying to shift their sales to Black Friday and the entire Christmas shopping season. COVID-19 has only accelerated this trend.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Home Depot is working to increase the crazy shopping bonaza that occurs the day after Thanksgiving each year by announcing this week that pricing starts in November and runs through December.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead of limiting the Black Friday offering to one day a season, according to Home Depot, the sale price for the holiday will be extended for the entire two-month route both in-store and online. The company&#39;s mobile app will also allow customers to view offers over the next month before playing lower prices online, he added.<br />\r\nClosed for Thanksgiving<br />\r\nThe home improvement chain also adheres to its practice of closing its stores on Thanksgiving so that &quot;employees and customers can have important time with family and loved ones knowing they have access to our offerings all year round,&quot; Home Depot said in one of the press releases on Wednesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Home Depot isn&#39;t the first retailer to enjoy a vacation. Last week, Walmart unveiled its list of annual toys and trends for the 2020 holiday season.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In another departure from the past, Walmart will not be holding an in-store event to mark the release of the 36 Hot Toys event, which this year includes Frozen 2 Magic in Motion Elsa Doll for $ 59 and LEGO Death Star Finale including Duel, exclusive to Walmart, for $ 89.</p>', 'Black Friday, Announced', 'Black Friday_1599912959.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:15:59', '2021-08-14 15:30:01'),
(529, 7, 1, 76, 'the-death-of-young-teachers-due-to-the-corona-virus-triggers-warnings-at-the-start-of-the-new-school-year-1599913898', 'The death of young teachers due to the corona virus triggers warnings at the start of the new school year', 0, '<p>Teachers in three states are died due to Coronavirus in the begining of this&nbsp; New Year Session. Leader of teacher Union is worried that if the accurate precautions are not taken it will deadly impact on across the country&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Missouri, AshLee DeMarinis was just 34&nbsp; when she was died on Sunday after three week admitted in hospital. &quot;The kids loved him so much. He was a brilliant special teacher,&quot; former colleague Mandy Blanks told CBS KMOV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In South Carolina, 28-year-old Demi Bannister was diagnosed with the virus on Friday and died on Monday, according to Richland 2 School District officials. Bannister is a third-grade teacher starting her fifth year at Windsor Elementary School in Columbia.<br />\r\nAccording to official information, Bannister was in school for a teaching week on August 28, a few days before the start of the school year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two other educators recently died in Mississippi. It&#39;s not clear how many teachers in the US have signed on to COVID-19 since the new school year began, but Mississippi itself has reported 604 cases among teachers and staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The news comes amid grim new data on COVID-19 cases in children: More than 500,000 children in the US have been tested for the coronavirus since the pandemic began. According to the American Academy of Pediatrics, children account for 9.8 percent of all COVID-19 cases in the United States, with more than 6.3 million cases reported, according to JoTwo and other educators who recently died in Mississippi. It&#39;s unclear how many teachers in the US have signed on to COVID-19 since the start of the new school year, but Mississippi itself has reported 604 cases among teachers and staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The news comes amid grim new data on COVID-19 cases in children: More than 500,000 children in the US have been tested for the coronavirus since the pandemic began. According to the American Academy of Pediatrics, children account for 9.8 percent of all COVID-19 cases in the United States, with more than 6.3 million cases reported, according to Johns Hopkins University.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Randy Weingarten, president of the American Teachers&#39; Federation, said schools needed guidelines such as mandatory covering of faces and strict social distancing rules in order to open safely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If community penetration is too high, like in Missouri and Mississippi, if you don&#39;t have the testing infrastructure, and if you don&#39;t take security precautions to prevent the spread of the virus in schools, we don&#39;t think you can reopen straight away,&quot; Weingarten said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Johnny Dunlap, a 39-year-old drama and forensic teacher at Dodge City High School in Kansas, said he was considering giving up before the district made masks mandatory for teachers and students. Even so, a history of bladder cancer and high blood pressure made him worry about being around many people. Existing health conditions can put people at a higher risk of serious illness and death from the virus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was in high school with nearly 2,000 students, which goes against the advice they&#39;ve been giving us for half a year,&quot; Dunlap said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The early stages of the pandemic claimed the lives of dozens of teachers. The New York Department of Education alone lost 31 teachers among 75 employees blamed for the coronavirus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the United States, the American Teachers&#39; Federation lists 210 union members who have died. The list includes support and retired staff and teachers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The start of a new school year brings new deaths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Oxford, Mississippi, 42-year-old Nakoma James teaches high school and helps coach football in high school. He died during the first week of class on August 6, but was in quarantine when teachers and students returned to class, said Adam Pu, head of the Lafayette school district.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pew remembers that James was a seventh grader when he started teaching 30 years ago.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;My stomach hit a lot when I heard it,&quot; said Pew.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>James worked with the soccer player during summer training, but investigations have found no new cases linked to him, Pew said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another Mississippi teacher died on Sunday. History teacher Tom Slade recently posted on Facebook about his fight against coronavirus pneumonia. On Tuesday, the American flag was flown in front of Vancleave Middle School by half of the staff, said CBS subsidiary WLOX.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Slade was teaching privately when the school year started on Aug. 6, principal Raina Holmes said, but she was quarantined after coming into contact with someone who was positive at a church meeting. His last day of class was August 21.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Slade was known to joke around using a judge&#39;s hammer to calm down noisy students.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He always brought humor to his class, and his students loved that part of him,&quot; said Holmes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Potosi, private lessons began on August 24. De Marinis was already in hospital at the moment, but prepared for the year weeks earlier, said his sister Jennifer Heisenb&uuml;ttel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Superintendent Alex McCall said contact tracing determined he was not in close contact with teachers, students or staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Demarinist grew up near New York, but has developed an interest for his rural schools and Potosi, a city of 2,600, said Heisenb&uuml;ttel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Demarinis wanted to teach special education from childhood when a special education teacher helped him with mild dyslexia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He had the patience of a saint. He was totally destined for it,&quot; said Heisenb&uuml;ttel. &quot;The kids love him. He touched so many lives.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>DeMarinis has asthma which can increase the risk of serious illnesses compared to COVID-19. He felt uncomfortable in mid-August, said Heisenb&uuml;ttel. After experiencing a fever and shortness of breath, he was tested for the coronavirus and was immediately hospitalized.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s not clear where DeMarinis got the virus from.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Heissenbuttel is a nurse who works in the intensive care unit of a New York-area hospital. Somehow she managed to avoid a disease her brother couldn&#39;t suffer from.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I thought it was me, not him,&quot; said Heisenb&uuml;ttel.</p>', 'Teachers death, Corona virus', 'Corona Related death of young_1599913898.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:31:38', '2021-08-12 00:11:09'),
(530, 7, 1, 110, 'indoor-restaurants-in-new-york-may-resume-later-this-month-at-25-capacity-1599914199', 'Indoor restaurants in New York may resume later this month at 25% capacity', 0, '<p><strong>Indoor dining in New York could resume Sept. 30 with a 25% capacity limit, Governor Andrew Cuomo announced at a press conference on Wednesday. Due to the Corona virus pandemic, restaurants in the city can only be exported and shipped from March.</strong><br />\r\nThe decision to allow indoor dining has restrictions for both customers and restaurants, Cuomo&#39;s office said in a press release.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All users should check the temperature of their doors, one person on each side must provide their contact information to the company if follow-up is required, and masks should be worn when they are away from the table.<br />\r\nAll tables must be at least one meter apart. The bar can only be used as a service bar, meaning no one is allowed to sit on it. According to the report, they can only be used as a &quot;source for making drinks&quot; served at the table. Restaurants must also &quot;allow outside ventilation&quot; and &quot;operate to improved standards of filtration, ventilation and air purification&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>All restaurants must close at midnight.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I want to thank the New Yorkers for their hard work to improve compliance, and now we can take the next step in opening our restaurant,&quot; Cuomo said.<br />\r\n&quot;This is good news and the right step forward, especially for restaurant owners and staff who have experienced difficulties. However, it is up to all of us to ensure compliance and the health and safety of those around us,&quot; added the governor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://pbs.twimg.com/media/EhfVBGeXcAA0F6l?format=png&amp;name=small\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe guidelines will be reviewed no later than November 1. Restaurants may be allowed to increase capacity by up to 50% if pollution levels do not rise, the statement said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cuomo said the city will appoint a team of 400 people to work with the state police task force to ensure all guidelines are followed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New York moved into the third stage of the opening in July, but the resumption of indoor dining was delayed at the time as cases increased across the country, particularly in places where indoor dining had resumed. At that time, Cuomo also said that residents&#39; compliance with disease protection measures, such as wearing masks, had begun to slip. Local governments are also &quot;not pushy enough,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The city is entering its fourth phase and its final resumption is on July 20.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New York state has 440,578 confirmed coronavirus cases, of which 33,016 have died since the pandemic began, according to data from a tally by Johns Hopkins University. The country has made impressive changes since the pandemic began when it was the country&#39;s biggest hotspot. At its peak in early April, the state reported nearly 800 deaths from COVID-19 every day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>576 new positive cases of COVID-19 were reported in New York as of Tuesday, and a total of 463 people have been hospitalized with the virus, Cuomo said on Wednesday. Three people died from the coronavirus in the state on Tuesday.</p>', 'NewYork, Indoor resturant', 'indoor dining newyork_1599914199.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:36:39', '2021-08-15 16:42:57'),
(531, 7, 1, 211, 'the-governor-of-south-dakota-is-using-5-million-in-tourism-promotion-funds-to-reduce-the-coronavirus-despite-the-surge-in-covid-1599914435', 'The governor of South Dakota is using $ 5 million in tourism promotion funds to reduce the coronavirus despite the surge in COVID', 0, '<p><strong>South Dakota Governor Christie Noem&#39;s government said on Tuesday it was using federal funds to help alleviate the coronavirus and fund a $ 5 million travel ad campaign aimed at getting people into the state. The move will also be taken if the country turns out to be one of the country&#39;s biggest hotspots for COVID-19 infection.</strong><br />\r\nIn the 30-second venue, which premiered on Fox News last month in conjunction with Noah&#39;s speech at the Republican National Congress, the governor said, &quot;With our stunning views and wide open spaces, we are a safe place to explore.&quot; However, currently the country ranks second in the country with 439 new cases per 100,000 population in the last two weeks.<br />\r\nThe ad was told by Noem. It features dramatic shots of South Dakota landscapes such as Mount Rushmore and Badlands National Park, and ends with a presentation by the governor and a visit to South Dakota.<br />\r\nThe state counted 124 infections among people who participated in the Sturgis motorcycle race in August, but does not publish a ranking of infections related to the secondary rally. Health officials in 12 states found more than 300 people with the infection attended the rally, including a Minnesota man who died.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Spokesman Noem Ian Fury defended the use of federal funding for the coronavirus for promotional purposes, saying the state &quot;must definitely encourage tourism&quot; because it is so important to South Dakota&#39;s economy. After agriculture, it is the country&#39;s biggest industry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That&#39;s how people put food on the table,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nThe money for advertising will come from the $ 1.25 billion that the federal government has received to deal with the coronavirus crisis. The US Treasury Department allows states to advertise the money as tourism continues and keeps visitors safe. The Department of Tourism is considering advertising on networks such as History, TBS, USA, Hallmark, A&amp;E and Discovery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fury said the job in an ad promoting the country as a &quot;safe research post&quot; was in line with a Treasury Department request that the money be used to fight the pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Senator Reynold Nesiba, a Democrat from Suu Falls who is a member of the Budget Committee, criticized the decision, saying it was Noah who was raising his political profile rather than helping the country. He argues that the governor&#39;s office has emphasized a cautious approach to using federal funds and has delayed its use for non-profit organizations, universities and companies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The way to push our economy back is by facing a pandemic,&quot; said Nesiba.<br />\r\nNoem&#39;s approach is to use a pandemic control approach to attract businesses and tourists to the country. He said he was focused on the number of patients hospitalized with COVID-19, not the number of infections. That&#39;s 68 people on Tuesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Celebrate what makes America great,&quot; he said in the ad. &quot;And experience an amazing place and face in South Dakota.&quot;</p>', 'South Dakota, Governor funds', 'South Dakota_1599914435.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:40:35', '2021-08-14 06:30:15'),
(532, 4, 14, 116, 'former-prisoner-fighting-for-us-criminal-justice-reform-1599915051', 'Former prisoner fighting for US criminal justice reform', 0, '<p>The US has the one of the world&#39;s biggest jail populaces with more than 2,000,000 individuals in prison. A considerable lot of those are individuals who can&#39;t bear the cost of bail so stay in jail while they anticipate preliminary.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Harvey Murphy&#39;s involvement with and out of jail has been the main thrust for his work in criminal equity change. Harvey works for Just Leadership USA, a New York-based association that needs to cut the jail populace significantly inside the following 10 years.</p>', 'US criminal justice', 'download (3)_1599915051.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:50:51', '2021-12-19 17:40:17'),
(533, 7, 1, 104, 'more-than-500000-children-in-the-united-states-have-tested-for-the-coronavirus-since-the-pandemic-began-the-report-said-1599915171', 'More than 500,000 children in the United States have tested for the coronavirus since the pandemic began, the report said.', 0, '<p><strong>New data released this week shows that more than 500,000 children in the United States have tested for the coronavirus since the pandemic began, according to the American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP). The group said children made up 9.8 percent of all COVID-19 cases in the United States, with more than 6.3 million cases reported, as summarized by Johns Hopkins University.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nThe AAP reports that there were 70,630 new cases of children between August 20 and September 3, an increase of 16% in two weeks, bringing the total to 513,415 in the country. Puerto Rico is among the six states and territories where child cases are increasing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AAP and the Children&#39;s Hospital Association have compiled data on children of various ages, according to 49 state health departments in New York, Puerto Rico, and Guam. Texas was excluded from the analysis, the AAP noted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Deaths from the corona virus in children<br />\r\nThe report said the cumulative death toll in the United States for children from the coronavirus was 103. In a subset of data analyzed from 42 states and New York, children accounted for 0 to 0.3% of all deaths from COVID. 19 and 18 countries did not report child deaths.<br />\r\n&quot;Currently, serious illness due to COVID-19 in children appears to be rare,&quot; said the AAP. But health experts say children can spread COVID-19.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, the Center for Disease Control has released new data on a deadly and mysterious childhood illness with a clear link to the coronavirus. The CDC has been monitoring the outbreak of multisystem inflammatory disease in children (MIS-C), also known as PMIS or sometimes also known as PMIS, since mid-May.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The CDC describes it as a &quot;rare but serious illness related to COVID-19&quot; that sometimes occurs after contracting the disease COVID-19 or after coming into contact with someone who has COVID-19. Instead of attacking the lungs as a new coronavirus disease in adults, this syndrome, although very rare, can cause serious, even fatal, heart complications in children.<br />\r\nAs of September 3, the CDC has compiled reports of 792 confirmed cases of MIS-C and 16 deaths in 42 states, New York and Washington, DC. Another case is being investigated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>CDC data show that &quot;most cases occur in children between the ages of 1 and 14 years, with a mean age of 8 years&quot;. They also found that &quot;more than 70% of the cases reported were in black Spanish / Spanish (276 cases) or non-Spanish (230 cases) children&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some students are back in private lessons<br />\r\nThe AAP report was released when thousands of children returned to private schools this week. On Long Island, parents look nervous and excited as they leave their children.<br />\r\nStudents line up in Richardson, Texas to check temperatures before entering the building. Forrester Elementary School in San Antonio is usually home to 850 children. but this morning only 53 private classes voted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I feel like they are just a little unbalanced, maybe a little bit because the room is different and everyone is wearing a mask,&quot; director Kelly Mantle told CBS News. &quot;I think it will be the new norm for a while and the kids get used to it and we get used to it every day.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new AAP number worries some teachers, for example in suburban Phoenix, where the first day of private lessons was canceled after teachers called patients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In New York, new cases are up more than 25% compared to two weeks ago. And while New York schools are preparing for private lessons in the coming weeks, Governor Andrew Cuomo is trying to assuage parental fears.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We will have a COVID certificate for every school in the state,&quot; he said.</p>', 'US, Corona test, pandemic', 'children corona_1599915171.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:52:51', '2021-08-17 06:09:21'),
(534, 4, 14, 132, 'coronavirus-what-powers-do-the-police-have-1599915261', 'Coronavirus: What powers do the police have?', 0, '<p>From Monday, it will be illegal in England to hold most parties of in excess of six individuals.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Police will have the option to separate bigger gatherings and to fine the individuals who don&#39;t observe the standards.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What can police do on the off chance that I meet at least six companions?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From Monday 14 September, indoor and outside parties of in excess of six individuals will be restricted in England.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are exemptions for working environments, schools and events like weddings and memorial services. The administration is because of layout any further exclusions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What are the new standards for meeting my companions?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new standards restricted the hole between non-enforceable Covid rules presently set up and the law.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For instance, current rules state outside social occasions bigger than six should possibly happen if everybody is from two families. In any case, police are just ready to scatter and fine individuals if the gathering is bigger than 30.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new guidelines will be upheld by law, so police can make a move on the off chance that you are in a gathering of more than six. The administration says: &quot;Putting the new, lower limit in law will make it simpler for the police to distinguish and scatter unlawful social affairs.</p>', 'police', '_114297740_1024-police-gettyimages-1228360765_1599915261.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:54:21', '2021-12-19 17:40:06'),
(535, 4, 14, 132, 'crime-agency-under-fire-over-bank-signature-forgery-1599915583', 'Crime agency under fire over bank signature forgery', 0, '<p>The National Crime Agency is confronting analysis for neglecting to explore reports claiming that banks manufactured marks and created proof in court activities to repossess homes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MPs encouraged the NCA a year back to examine the issue following a BBC News examination.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The NCA has gotten in any event 19 boxes of proof identifying with 362 occurrences.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Be that as it may, against defilement campaigners and MPs state casualties haven&#39;t been reached and no examination has been begun.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The NCA says it is making a &quot;careful evaluation&quot; of the material submitted to decide if a criminal examination was fundamental.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We are proceeding to survey the material, incorporating extra data provided in May 2020,&quot; said a NCA representative.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Along with accomplices in the FCA and SFO, we are making an exhaustive evaluation to decide if there are reason for a crook or administrative examination.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Government-possessed bank &#39;fashioning marks&#39; in repossession cases&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MPs call for investigation into supposed imitation of marks&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In July 2019, an examination by the BBC set out proof of mark phony on court reports utilized by banks and their delegates to repossess.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Penmanship specialists affirmed that by and large sent to the NCA, marks utilized over a similar name couldn&#39;t have been marked by a similar individual; and that a similar mark had been given up various names.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Picture Copyright @VictoriaLIVE@VICTORIALIVE&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Report&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following the BBC examination, the Treasury Committee encouraged the NCA to research the issue.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>MPs state the broad documentation submitted to the NCA upholds charges, denied by the banks, that proof has been created or hidden in court activities to recuperate individual and business obligations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, hostile to debasement campaigners state not a solitary complainant has been reached by the NCA among several casualties.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;We have been through the ringer&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In one model, Anna Britton, 49, from Portishead, had to sell her home and move back with her two girls to her folks&#39; two-bed level after a contest with a bank over business obligations.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The three needed to share a room and were destitute for over three years. Anna says the injury prompted her then-12-year-old girl getting seriously anorexic</p>', 'Crime', '_114265630_nca1_1599915583.jpg', '2020-09-12 16:59:43', '2021-12-19 17:39:54');
