(540, 4, 11, 156, 'parasite-is-best-picture-oscars-2020-winner-watch-speech-1599916316', 'PARASITE IS BEST PICTURE OSCARS 2020 WINNER: WATCH SPEECH', 0, '<p>PARASITE is the Oscars 2020 champ for Best Picture! Congrats to Kwak Sin Ae and Bong Joon Ho on their Oscar wins. This is the fourth movie chief Bong Joon Ho and entertainer Kang-ho Song teamed up on and this is their first Best Picture selection. Essayist, Director and Producer of PARASITE, Bong Joon Ho won three Oscars for PARASITE altogether, including wins for Writing (Original Screenplay) and Directing, just as speaking to winning nation South Korea for the movie&#39;s International Feature Film Oscar win. Different candidates for Best Picture included FORD V FERRARI, THE IRISHMAN, JOJO RABBIT, JOKER, LITTLE WOMEN, MARRIAGE STORY, 1917, and ONCE UPON A TIME...IN HOLLYWOOD. Watch Kwak Sin Ae and Bong Joon Ho&#39;s Oscar acknowledgment discourse beneath!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE: This clasp has terminated.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The cast and team of PARASITE acknowledge the Oscar for Best Picture at Oscars 2020.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>See the full record underneath:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kwak Sin Ae: [via translator] I&#39;m confused. We never envisioned this to actually occur. We are so upbeat. I feel like an ideal crossroads in history is occurring at the present time. I offer my most profound thanks and regard for all the individuals from the Academy for settling on this choice. Much obliged to you.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Miky Lee: Hi everyone. I truly prefer to thank chief Bong. Much obliged to you for being you. Furthermore, I like every little thing about him: his grin, his insane hair, the manner in which he talks, the manner in which he strolls, and particularly the manner in which he coordinates. Also, what I truly like about him is his comical inclination and the truth of the matter is he can be truly ridiculing himself and he never pays attention to himself. Much thanks to you, thank you kindly. Also, I&#39;d prefer to thank every individual who&#39;s been supporting &quot;Parasite,&quot; and who&#39;s been working with &quot;Parasite&quot; and who&#39;s been adoring &quot;Parasite&quot;. Also, I&#39;d prefer to thank my sibling who&#39;s been continually supporting our structure our fantasies, in any event, when it looked unimaginable dream. Much obliged to you, Jae. I need to thank my sibling Jae, and particularly, I ridiculously, truly need to thank our Korean film crowd, our moviegoers who&#39;s been truly supporting every one of our motion pictures, and never delayed to invigorate us for sentiment on what they feel like their motion pictures. Furthermore, that made us actually always be unable to be smug and continue pushing the chiefs, the makers, continue pushing the envelopes. What&#39;s more, without you, our Korean film crowd, we are not here. Thanks much.</p>', 'OSCARS', '9a5a970c2636f2a129af720f818670e40c28cbf12f5780df4972c2a0744d1a33-770x443@2x_1599916316.jpg', '2020-09-12 17:11:56', '2021-08-16 13:03:30'),
(541, 4, 11, 159, 'watch-brad-pitts-oscars-2020-speech-for-best-supporting-actor-1599916449', 'WATCH BRAD PITT\'S OSCARS 2020 SPEECH FOR BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR', 0, '<p>Brad Pitt is the Oscars 2020 victor for Actor in a Supporting Role for his presentation as Cliff Booth in Once upon a Time...in Hollywood! Congrats to Brad Pitt on his subsequent Oscar win. Brad Pitt was first selected in this class for his supporting part in 12 MONKEYS. During his discourse, Pitt recognizes his costar Leonardo DiCaprio expressing &quot;Leo, I&#39;ll enjoy the fruit of your labor quickly, man. The view&#39;s incredible.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Different candidates for Actor in a Supporting Role remembered Tom Hanks for A BEAUTIFUL DAY IN THE NEIGHBORHOOD, Anthony Hopkins in THE TWO POPES, Al Pacino in THE IRISHMAN, Joe Pesci in THE IRISHMAN and Brad Pitt in ONCE UPON A TIME... IN HOLLYWOOD.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Watch Brad Pitt&#39;s Oscar acknowledgment discourse underneath!&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>UPDATE: This clasp has terminated.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brad Pitt acknowledges the Oscar for Actor in a Supporting Role for the film, ONCE UPON A TIME... IN HOLLYWOOD, at Oscars 2020.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>See full record underneath:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Amazing, much obliged. This is mind boggling, truly amazing. Much obliged to you to the Academy for this honor of respects. They revealed to me just have 45 seconds up here, which is 45 seconds more than the Senate gave John Bolton this week.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m thinking possibly Quentin does a film about it. At long last, the grown-ups make the best choice. This truly is about Quentin Tarantino. You are unique. You are unique. The entertainment world would be an a lot drier spot without you and I love the ethos you gave Cliff Booth. Search for the best in individuals. Anticipate the most noticeably terrible, yet search generally advantageous. Leo, I&#39;ll enjoy the fruit of your labor quickly, man. The view&#39;s incredible. Also, to the remainder of the cast and team, Big Bad Bob Richardson, Robert Garcia, Richie, my man, Mike Mo. Hello, I additionally need to state, you realize why we&#39;re doing this. I believe it&#39;s time we give a little love to our trick organizers and our trick groups.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tune in, I&#39;m somewhat gobsmacked. I&#39;m not one to think back, yet this has caused me to do as such. Also, I think about my people taking me to the drive in to see Butch and Sundance. What&#39;s more, stacking up my vehicle and moving around here. What&#39;s more, Gina and Ridley offering me my first chance, to all the magnificent individuals I&#39;ve met en route to remain here now sometime in the distant past in Hollywood, ain&#39;t that reality. This is for my children who shading all that I do. I worship you.</p>', 'BRAD PITT\'S OSCARS', '436316118e958f1861fa495432dac2c257be7c6de76d48d1de02d8b892bfe7a8-770x443@2x_1599916449.jpg', '2020-09-12 17:14:09', '2021-08-17 00:09:43'),
(542, 4, 11, 123, 'best-oscar-2020-tweet-highlights-from-winners-attendees-and-celebs-1599916590', 'BEST OSCAR 2020 TWEET HIGHLIGHTS FROM WINNERS, ATTENDEES AND CELEBS', 0, '<p>It was an important night at the 2020 Oscars with some enthusiastic and entertaining acknowledgment discourses. There were awakening melodic exhibitions, remembering a contacting For Memoriam accolade highlighting Billie Eilish. Prior to the show, stars developed on the Oscars 2020 honorary pathway wearing the best Oscar design, dresses and show-halting looks. #BongHive was drifting all through online media demonstrating gratefulness for PARASITE&#39;s chief Bong Joon Ho. PARASITE won 4 Oscars and made Oscar history for the first non-English language film to win the honor for Best Picture.</p>', 'OSCAR\\', '7d4a96f692a53c04ed9b639a51cf2ee0dfe310a9a5b76c6f4f4dc6aae63db263-770x443@2x_1599916589.jpeg', '2020-09-12 17:16:30', '2021-08-18 03:06:20'),
(543, 7, 1, 135, 'stopping-the-astrazeneca-covid-19-vaccine-study-is-one-of-the-safety-valves-said-dr-fauci-1599917859', 'Stopping the AstraZeneca COVID-19 vaccine study is \"one of the safety valves,\" said Dr. Fauci', 0, '<p><strong>The suspension of AstraZeneca&#39;s coronavirus vaccine studies &quot;is not uncommon,&quot; said Dr. Anthony Fauci, the country&#39;s leading infectious disease expert, on Wednesday. Being vigilant about possible side effects is part of the process, he explained.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is really one of the safety valves you have in clinical trials like this,&quot; he told CBS this morning. &quot;So it&#39;s a shame this is happening. We hope they can sort it out and continue with the rest of the process.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>AstraZeneca canceled a phase 3 break on Tuesday after a participant fell ill. It was not clear what symptoms the participants experienced. AstraZeneca is one of three companies currently in the final stages of a vaccination trial.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is a routine measure that must be taken whenever there is a potentially unexplained disease in any of the studies being examined to ensure that the integrity of the studies is maintained,&quot; said a statement from AstraZeneca.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fauci said &quot;broadly&quot; that the side effects were related to something other than vaccines, but those who did the research could not guess.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;They always assume that this is directly due to the actual vaccine or therapeutic agent or what is in clinical trials,&quot; he said. &quot;That&#39;s why we say we do careful safety research. This is an example of what you do to make sure this is a safe product.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fauci, who is a member of the White House coronavirus working group, is also investigating previous predictions that the safety and effectiveness of the vaccine will be known by the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Maybe November, December. Is it possible? Could it be that we could find out sooner, say October? I can be sure. I don&#39;t think it&#39;s possible, but you can&#39;t rule it out, &quot;he said. &quot;I think the more likely scenario is that we&#39;ll find out at the end of this calendar year, and we hope that we can start vaccinating in earnest starting in 2021.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Donald Trump has expressed optimism that a vaccine will be ready before the 2020 presidential election on November 3, although health experts believe that is unlikely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When asked about the politicization of this type of vaccine, Fauci said he hopes and believes the solution will not be politicized.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;When decisions are made about whether to issue the EEA, which is emergency approval, or even approve a vaccine, there is also advice on how to manage it,&quot; he said. &quot;There is a lot of transparency in it, so I hope and believe there will be no politicization about it. It may be a political atmosphere, but I don&#39;t think we will politicize any real decisions about vaccines.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fauci also said there were other &quot;safety valves&quot; during the testing process, including &quot;independent data and security monitoring agencies that regularly review data to determine levels of experience.&quot;</p>', 'AstraZeneca, Covid-19', 'AstaraZeneca_1599917859.jpg', '2020-09-12 17:37:39', '2021-08-16 14:38:33'),
(544, 7, 6, 102, 'loreal-has-introduced-makeup-recycling-in-stores-across-the-uk-1599918487', 'L\'Oreal has introduced makeup recycling in stores across the UK', 0, '<p><strong>Cosmetics giant L&#39;Oreal introduced make-up recycling bins in 1,000 shops in the UK under environmental stress.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Maybelline brand and recycling company TerraCycle will install recycling stations at Tesco, Boots, Sainsbury&#39;s and Superdrug stores. The head of L&#39;Oreal, based in the UK, said the company aims to be a &quot;leader&quot; in creating beauty recycling habits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, Greenpeace said that companies &quot;cannot claim to have done enough&quot; without reducing single-use plastic production. Starting Thursday, consumers can leave blank makeup products of any brand in recycling bins at participating Tesco and Superdrug stores, which are available online.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boots and Sainsbury&#39;s will follow in late September.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Selfridges can rent clothes under ecological pressure Morrison plans to leave behind all &quot;bags for life&quot; for paper Solid products, shadow palettes, foundation or concealer tubes, mascara, eyeliner and lip products are allowed, although no makeup brushes, nail polish or aerosols are available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Used goods are collected in stores, sorted, cleaned and recycled into plastic pellets which can be used to make other products such as garden furniture. Networks such as The Body Shop and skin care specialist Kiehl&#39;s, also owned by L&#39;Oreal, are now offering prizes to customers for returning empty products to recycling stores.<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/9B82/production/_114301893_32dedfe7-5f88-4dcf-a86e-468fa9900d31.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wismay Sharma, state manager for L&#39;Oreal UK and Ireland, told&nbsp; that the company &quot;has the ability to make a real impact&quot;.<br />\r\nNearly half of makeup artists don&#39;t know that beauty products can be recycled, according to a recent study of more than 1,000 Maybelline users.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When asked what makes Maybelline and TerraCycle&#39;s new Make-up Not Make Waste program different, Stephen Clark, director of communications at TerraCycle, said the number of shops involved made recycling easier for consumers. their beauty products.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also said the company can recycle mixed materials such as mirror compactor as well as beauty products with pumps and triggers, which local authorities don&#39;t need to do.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Destruction of our planet&quot;<br />\r\nHowever, environmental campaign group Greenpeace said, &quot;Recycling will only help us so far&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Will McCallum, Head of Oceans, Greenpeace, UK, said: &quot;With an almost daily stream of research showing the extent to which plastic pollution is damaging our planet, it is disappointing to see large plastics manufacturers such as the makeup industry fail to do so. Reducing the footprint of ordinary plastics.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Without an action plan to switch to reusable packaging and reduce single-use plastic production, companies cannot claim to have done enough.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the Zero Waste Week campaign, the cosmetics industry itself produces more than 120 billion packaging units each year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>L&#39;Oreal told&nbsp;that global plastic consumption was 137,000 tonnes in 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The cosmetics company has pledged that 100% of its plastic packaging will be refilled, reused, recycled or composted by 2025.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Sharma also said the company provided &euro; 50 million (&pound; 45.4 million) to invest in plastic recycling or waste projects.</p>', 'Loreal, Makeup recycling', 'Loreal_1599918487.jpg', '2020-09-12 17:48:07', '2021-08-16 12:21:48'),
(545, 7, 8, 136, 'the-us-wildfires-were-triggered-by-climate-change-said-the-governor-of-california-1599919150', 'The US wildfires were triggered by climate change, said the governor of California', 0, '<p>According to the new baseline report, the global response to Covid-19 hardly thwarts the causes of climate change.<br />\r\nWhile CO2 emissions fell sharply during the blockade, long-term gas concentrations in the atmosphere continued to increase.<br />\r\nThe period from 2016 to 2020 will likely be the five warmest years in history, according to the study.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The authors say that the &quot;irreversible&quot; effects of climate change are increasing. The United in Science report brings together experts from various international organizations, including the United Nations and the World Meteorological Organization (WMO), for an up-to-date picture of the state of the global climate.<br />\r\nThe study shows that the global blockade has a significant and direct impact on greenhouse gas emissions. The daily value decreased 17% in April 2020 compared to 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/BCFA/production/_114287384_fire2.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nHowever, this sharp decline did not continue. When the world returns to work, emissions increase and are within 5% of the previous year in June.<br />\r\nBy 2020, emissions are expected to fall by 4-7%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although emissions can tell us what is happening on Earth, the concentration of these gases in the atmosphere is important for global temperatures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because CO2 takes centuries, adding less amounts to the air increases the warming potential of all the gases that have accumulated over the decades.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This new study shows that this is exactly what is happening at some of the major monitoring stations around the world. At the Mauna Loa Observatory in Hawaii, the amount of CO2 measured in air samples increased from 411 ppm in July 2019 to 414 ppm in July this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Likewise, concentrations at the Cape Grimm monitoring station in Tasmania increased from 407 to 410 ppm in the year to July.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/10B1A/production/_114287386_fire3.png\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A full global picture of atmospheric concentrations of warming gases will be available later this year - but experts say the direction of travel is clear.<br />\r\n&quot;The concentration of greenhouse gases, which has been at the highest level in three million years, continues to increase,&quot; said WCO Secretary General Prof. Petteri Taalas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In much of Siberia, there is a continuous and extraordinary heat wave in the first half of 2020, which would be very unlikely without anthropogenic climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;And currently 2016-2020 will be a record for the hottest period in five years. This report shows that many aspects of our lives will be disrupted in 2020, but climate change will continue to slow down, &quot;he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report also highlights the growing gap between actions taken to meet temperature thresholds and the reality of reducing emissions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In order to prevent a warming release of more than 1.5 &deg; C (from pre-industrial times) in this century, the production of greenhouse gases must be reduced immediately.<br />\r\nThe study says that by 2030, the world must reduce the combined emissions of the six carbon-producing countries in order to have a reasonable chance of remaining under the 1.5 &deg; C &quot;fence&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While it is not impossible, the report states that a slowdown in the pandemic of carbon emissions will be needed every year from now to the end of the decade.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, the authors argue, the evidence for the effects of climate change is growing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Global sea levels are rising much faster than previously recorded. Between 2016 and 2020 the growth rate was 4.8 mm per year, increasing by more than 4.1 mm between 2011 and 2015.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The amount of sea ice in the Arctic is continuing to decline at a rate of 13% per decade. Increasing temperatures also cause drought and heat waves, which increase the risk of fires.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Siberia, a recent attribution study found that the heat that lasted between January and June this year was at least 600 times more likely than man-made climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It has never been so clear that we need a long-term, integrative and clean transition to tackle the climate crisis and achieve sustainable development,&quot; said UN Secretary General Antonio Guterres in the report&#39;s foreword.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We need to make recovery from the pandemic a real opportunity to build a better future,&quot; he wrote. &quot;We need science, solidarity and solutions.&quot;</p>', 'Wildfire, Climate Change', 'Fire_1599919150.jpg', '2020-09-12 17:59:10', '2021-08-13 12:38:35');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(546, 7, 8, 173, 'sir-david-attenborough-strongly-warned-that-the-species-were-going-extinct-1599922407', 'Sir David Attenborough strongly warned that the species were going extinct', 0, '<p><strong>Sir David Attenborough returns to our screens this weekend with a brand new production that is incredible.<br />\r\nProgram tone is very different from normal. Long ago, beloved British naturalists were not here to celebrate the incredible biodiversity on earth, but to send us away with strong warning.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The one-hour film &quot;Disappearance: The Facts&quot; will open on Sunday, September 13 at 8pm CET on BBC One in the UK. &quot;We are facing a crisis,&quot; he warned at the outset, &quot;and a crisis that has consequences for all of us.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here is a staggering account of the damage our species has done to nature. The scene of destruction<br />\r\nThere are stunning images of animals and plants you would expect from an Attenborough production, but also gruesome scenes of destruction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In one sequence, the monkeys jump from a tree into a river to escape a huge fire. Other koalas hobbled in vain for cover as the fire engulfed the surrounding forest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/95B3/production/_114332383_extinction-thefacts_10_16_14_16.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is a small army of experts ready to measure the extent of ecosystem damage in the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One expert warns that of the eight million species on earth, one million are threatened with extinction. Humans &quot;threaten 1 million species with extinction&quot; Wild animals are in &quot;catastrophic decline,&quot; warned the report, Which million species are threatened with extinction, what are we saving?<br />\r\nSince 1970, vertebrates - birds, mammals, reptiles, fish and amphibians - have shrunk by up to 60%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We met the last two northern white rhinos. These large animals have been found by thousands of people in Central Africa, but are critically endangered due to habitat loss and hunting.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;A lot of people think extinctions are fantasy stories told by conservationists,&quot; said James Mwenda, the caretaker who looked after them, &quot;but I&#39;ve seen them, I know what they are.&quot;<br />\r\nJames patted and patted the giant beasts, but it became clear that they were the last of their kind when he tells us that Najin and Fatou are mother and child.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/4793/production/_114332381_extinction-thefacts_10_07_50_00.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Species always come and go, that&#39;s how evolution works. But, said Sir David, the rate of extinction has increased dramatically.<br />\r\nIt is now believed to occur at 100 times the natural rate of evolution - and it is accelerating. &quot;In my entire life I have encountered some of the most amazing animal species in the world,&quot; says Sir David in one of the film&#39;s most intriguing parts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Only now do I realize how lucky I am - many of these miracles seem to have been lost forever.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crisis in nature<br />\r\nSir David tries to explain that this is not just about the disappearance of the great creatures he has featured in the hundreds of programs he has undertaken over six decades as director of natural history.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The loss of pollinating insects can harm the food crops on which we depend. Trees and other plants regulate the flow of water and produce the oxygen we breathe. Meanwhile, the sea is being emptied of fish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are now about 5% of trawlers compared to pre-early 20th century, says one expert.<br />\r\nBut pandemics are perhaps the most direct example of our ever-increasing risk of disturbance with nature, as we have all experienced in the most brutal manner over the past six months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/D177/production/_114332635_extinction-thefacts_10_08_10_11.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The program traces the suspected origin of the coronavirus back to a population of bats living in a cave system in China&#39;s Yunnan province.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We looked at China&#39;s &quot;wet market&quot; in Wuhan, which specializes in the sale of wildlife for human consumption and is believed to be linked to many early infections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A reason for hope<br />\r\nSerena Davis, who leads the program, admits that the program is uncompromising crisis in nature.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Our job is to report the facts presented by the evidence,&quot; he explained.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the program did not leave viewers feeling that all was lost. Sir David explained that there was still hope.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Your goal is not to drag the audience into the depths of despair,&quot; Davis said, &quot;but to take people on a journey to see what&#39;s driving this problem. We can work it out, too.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The program ends in an iconic style.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We see one of the most famous moments in one of the films Sir David made in his long career when he encountered a group of gorillas in the mountains on the border between the Democratic Republic of Congo and Rwanda.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/E3D3/production/_114332385_extinction-thefacts_10_56_46_18_jpg.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nA young gorilla named Poppy tries to remove her shoes while talking to the camera.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The experience stuck with me,&quot; said Sir David, &quot;but I was sad because I thought I might see the last of its kind.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Programmers returned to Rwanda and after a long journey found Poppy&#39;s daughter and granddaughter in a deep bush.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We know that the Rwandan government is working with local people to protect animal and gorilla breeding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There used to be 250 of Sir David&#39;s visits in the 1970&#39;s, now there are more than 1,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It shows, said Sir David, what we can achieve if we focus on it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I may not be here to look at it,&quot; he concluded, &quot;but if we make the right decisions at this critical moment, we can protect our planet&#39;s ecosystem, its incredible biodiversity, and all of its people.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The final line was a heavy punch: &quot;What happens next,&quot; said Sir David, &quot;depends on each of us.&quot;</p>', 'Extinct, Sir David', 'Sir David_1599922407.jpg', '2020-09-12 18:53:27', '2021-09-23 08:14:46'),
(547, 7, 8, 141, 'climate-change-taxes-fly-frequently-and-get-rid-of-jeeps-the-government-says-1599932650', 'Climate change: Taxes fly frequently and get rid of jeeps, the government says', 0, '<p><strong>Frequent travel taxes, phasing out of polluting SUVs, and restrictions on cars in city centers are some of the solutions proposed by the public to climate change.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>A civilian assembly of 108 people from all walks of life published their report after weeks of debate. They suggest limiting road construction and using the pandemic to reduce emissions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lawmakers said the report provided &quot;unique information,&quot; but Extinction Rebellion activist said it didn&#39;t go far enough.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The report says governments must take the lead on climate change and stresses that climate policy must be fair to everyone - especially the poorest in society. His radical conclusion could offer political closure to ministers, who are usually nervous when the public reacts to policies affecting lifestyles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What is the citizen meeting?</strong><br />\r\nThe Citizens Group or Assembly is made up of six government committees - groups of parliamentarians that handle government activity and research policy. Meeting members were selected to present multiple perspectives from across the UK and spend 60 hours of their time studying and discussing climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They met over six weekends and were asked how they could come up with ideas to help Britain achieve net zero emissions by 2050. Your results are published in more than 550 pages of the report.<br />\r\nMembers said it was &quot;important to have strong and clear governance&quot; to tackle climate change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>One member, Sue of Bath, said: &quot;Although the country is still battling the coronavirus, it is clear that most of us believe that setting priorities for net-zero politics is not only important but achievable.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hamish, a software engineer from rural Aberdeenshire, told BBC News that the government &quot;must develop a long-term strategy to help us.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The main theme of this report is education. Ibrahim, a general practitioner from Surrey, said, &ldquo;Media plays a role - including schools. Maybe we should look at the curriculum.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You can&#39;t go up to someone and say, &#39;You have to switch to a hydrogen boiler because it&#39;s low on CO2,&#39; but they don&#39;t know.&quot; You are more likely to get support from people if they find out about the problem. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Members say the government should start to stop selling new, polluting vehicles, such as SUVs, and curb advertising for highly polluting goods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another key message is the need for fair politics. Amanda from Kent said, &quot;Electric cars should be more accessible to everyone - not just people who make enough money.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They also support higher taxes for frequent flights and investments in clean aviation technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is climate change? Very simple guide<br />\r\nClimate change: what do all the terms mean?<br />\r\nThe Covid crisis is not so important to slow climate change<br />\r\nTracy, a mother from Northern Ireland, said, &quot;I&#39;m also going to be flying a lot - so I think there must be something stopping us from doing so many flights - to reduce our emissions.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Regarding what we eat and how we use the land, the meeting called for a voluntary reduction of red meat consumption by 20-40%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The government cannot pass laws prohibiting the consumption of red meat,&quot; said Amanda, &quot;but with education, advertising and labeling, we can change their attitudes towards red meat consumption - as we do with smoking.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>They also said:</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Companies need to make products with less energy and materials People need to fix things and share a lot more than owning all their devices Britain needs to get more energy from wind and solar offshore and on land<br />\r\nNew residential buildings should be easily accessible via hiking and biking trails Most members are not particularly interested in nuclear power or burning wood in power plants - and most are unsure whether carbon should be captured and stored.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They believe the government should use the Covid crisis to limit support for the high carbon industry.<br />\r\nWhat&#39;s the reaction like?<br />\r\nThe lawmakers behind the meeting said the report provided &quot;a unique glimpse into an informed public thinking about the compromises and changes that will be needed to achieve the goals agreed by Parliament&quot;. They say, &quot;Your job deserves action.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Crispin Truman, of the provincial charity CPRE, said he had demonstrated that &quot;the public&#39;s desire to end Britain&#39;s contribution to the climate emergency far exceeds government action&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dan Tom Burke of the e3g Climate Change Brain added: &quot;This is a strong tribute to the common sense of the British public. There are clear lessons for politicians and editors across the political spectrum about the role our citizens can play in shaping public order.&quot; &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, Green Group&#39;s (XR) radical uprising condemned the proposal for being too embarrassed to respond to an internationally agreed proposal to limit global warming to 1.5 &deg; C. They warned that the report could be buried in the country&#39;s bureaucracy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What is happening right now?</strong><br />\r\nThe committee behind the report has asked Prime Minister Boris Johnson to respond before the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This could be a challenge as Covid and Brexit have forced climate change to reduce the government&#39;s priority list, a claim the government denies, according to a recent report by the Institute for Governance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A government spokesman said he would investigate the report.</p>', 'Climate Change, Taxes', 'Climate change_1599922830.jpg', '2020-09-12 19:00:30', '2021-08-17 06:20:31'),
(548, 7, 8, 179, 'civil-science-takes-advantage-of-peoples-love-for-trees-1599932460', 'Civil science takes advantage of people\'s love for trees', 0, '<p><strong>Citizen research projects are most effective in raising awareness of some of the threats facing the nation&#39;s tree.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, these systems are less productive in providing meaningful data for scientific control. These results come from a study assessing the ability of British people to participate in a tree health study coordinated by Opal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The results were published in Insects magazine. The publication of this research coincides with the conclusions of a government public consultation on a tree-like strategy for the UK. The strategy will support the government&#39;s commitment to plant 30,000 hectares of trees annually by 2025.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\n<strong>Fruits of Opals</strong><br />\r\nThe Open Air Laboratory (Opal) was launched in 2007 and involved more than 650,000 people in a series of environmental studies that harnessed the collective power of &quot;civilian scientists&quot;, ordinary people who take a closer look at the nature around them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/1834F/production/_114315199_opal.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;The OPAL Tree Health Study is actually an experiment to see if the public can contribute to &#39;official&#39; surveillance,&quot; said Opal Director David Slawson.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As pioneers, we have a responsibility to inform the government and civil society about the results.&quot; It was created as a result of a number of factors coming together. In his article, Dr. Slawson together with co-author Prof. Andy Moffat of Forest Research: The couple noted:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In early 2010, the resources of government employees to monitor, identify and eradicate pathogens were limited, so we are testing the effectiveness of &#39;civilian scientists&#39; to support this need.&quot; When the Conservative government tried to cut public spending at the time, it had a strong impact on funding government agencies, such as those responsible for state biosecurity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the time, however, Prime Minister David Cameron was promoting his concept of a &quot;great society&quot; that encouraged people to be more involved in the community around them. Against this backdrop, the Ministry of Environment and Forestry Committee have developed an action plan that includes public engagement and involvement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Because resources are limited, it is considered useful to consider the role of citizen science in supporting and maintaining surveillance and observation frameworks. Opal, coordinated by Imperial College, partnered with Forest Research (the Forestry Commission&#39;s research unit) and the Food and Environment Research Agency (Fera) to launch a tree health study in May 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Commitment to the environment</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>About 39,000 people took part over six years. More than 80% of the participants stated that they had no experience working with trees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/C063/production/_114315294_ash_bbc.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nNearly 60% of the trees studied were in roads, schools, parks, or gardens, indicating that most people choose to do research near their homes or schools.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The OPAL Tree Heath research project aims to determine the effectiveness of a civic scientific approach to contribute to state tree health, public engagement and needs monitoring,&quot; write the researchers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;While this approach is considered successful in terms of public engagement, it is believed to be not very successful in producing useful data on specific pests and tree diseases.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dr. Slawson said the tree health study was successful in reaching a new generation of conservationists and giving them their first experiences on the subject.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It not only increases their knowledge and understanding of tree health science, but it also has a positive impact on their attitudes and behavior towards the environment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was also rated a success in terms of the geographic scope of the results presented.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Data challenge<br />\r\nWhile the study provided a volume and breadth of results likely beyond the reach of professionals and scientists, it identified a number of &quot;challenges&quot; including data entry errors and lack of verification.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This means that the data are not considered reliable enough to be exposed to scientific methodologies used in the laboratory. Dr. However, Slawson told BBC News that the other OPAL study, as well as other research projects for citizens, did not experience such &quot;challenges.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that the experience gained from the project provided plans for future endeavors. You write: &ldquo;First, the mix of OPAL&#39;s success in achieving its goals of public engagement and scrutiny suggests that any scientist or politician considering a civic scientific approach must be perfectly clear about the overall objectives of the proposed activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Is public information an objective, public engagement or observation and science? Knowing these goals will influence decisions about which approach to take and the depth of civic participation in those activities.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This study concludes with the assumption that if a future civic research project is to collect relevant data, it is preferable to focus on the time and skills of individuals who have experience or expertise in the area under consideration.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This will help reduce errors and the need for citizens to research future research projects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We recommend that a non-professional play a key role, especially during a crisis when he or she can be trained on a specific pest or disease, only be present for a limited time, and submit photos for review,&quot; said Dr. Slawson.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added, &quot;We are proposing developing a network of civilian observers to help the British government achieve its ambitious goal of training at least two percent of the UK population (1.3 million) as biosafety volunteers.&quot;</p>', 'Civil Science, Advantages', 'Citizen_1599922855.jpg', '2020-09-12 19:00:55', '2021-08-18 00:09:13'),
(549, 7, 8, 162, 'the-pringles-whistle-tries-to-rise-from-the-recycling-nightmare-1599932713', 'The Pringles Whistle tries to rise from the \"recycling nightmare\".', 0, '<p><strong>Pringles&#39; signature tube is being recycled after it was criticized that it was almost impossible to recycle.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Potato-based breakfast containers have now been condemned as a recyclers&#39; nightmare. It is an intricate construction with a metal base, plastic cap, removable metal cap, and a cardboard sleeve lined with foil.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The recycling association calls him the number one bad guy for recycling - along with the Lucozade sports bottle. Now Pringles Kellogg&#39;s makers are trying out a simpler can - although experts say it&#39;s not a complete solution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The current version is especially problematic because it combines so many different ingredients<br />\r\nAbout 90% of the new boxes are made of paper. About 10% is a polyal (plastic) barrier that locks the inside to protect food from oxygen and moisture that can affect taste.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But what about the lid? Two options have been tried at several Tesco stores - recyclable plastic covers and recyclable paper covers. Kellogg&#39;s says this cap is still creating the &quot;pop&quot; mark associated with the product.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Simon Elin of the Recycling Association told that&nbsp;&quot;The Pringles pipe is a badly designed bulwark from a recyclers point of view.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This new version is an improvement and we generally welcome it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;But honestly, if they want to stick to plastic covers that only add to the problem of plastic pollution - people leave them for picnics and fall into rivers and seas. Those plastic covers have to be removed.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/13983/production/_96095208_brands.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kellogg&#39;s says that the packaging must be airtight or the food inside will be wasted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new design has been under construction for 12 months. Pringles has a shelf life of 15 months - and three million cans are produced in Europe each day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Ellin says polished coating cards are recyclable, but the product needs to be tested at a recycling plant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And what about the criticized Lucozade Sports bottle? Mr Ellin said the basic, unchanged design was still a big problem as machines had difficulty distinguishing between the plastic in the bottle and the plastic that formed the outer shell.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He asked the Suntory manufacturer to reduce the size of the outer shell as in the new Ribena bottle. The company plans to do this in the new year. Suntory says it is working on a new material that is made entirely of algae extract and is 100% edible, biodegradable, and compostable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Environmentalists say a trivial change like this will not solve the world&#39;s environmental crisis - but, on a large scale, it will help.</p>', 'Pringle, Recycling', 'Pringles_1599922879.jpg', '2020-09-12 19:01:19', '2021-08-17 17:13:58'),
(550, 7, 1, 135, 'what-is-the-r-number-and-how-is-it-calculated-1599941113', 'what is the R number and how is it calculated?', 0, '<p><strong>The reproductive number or R-value for Covid-19 now officially returns above one in the UK, although it varies by region.</strong><br />\r\nScotland has the highest estimated value - between 1.1 and 1.5. But what does that mean?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is r?<br />\r\nThe reproductive rate is a way of assessing the corona virus or the ability of a disease to spread. This is the average number of people who will pass the virus on to an infected person. Measles has one of the highest rates of R 15 in the nonimmune population. This means that on average one person transmits measles to 15 other people.<br />\r\nThe coronavirus - officially known as Sars-CoV-2 - has a reproductive number of about three if we don&#39;t take steps to prevent its spread.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/FE72/production/_114283156_1024-spread-gettyimages-1213710695.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>How is R calculated?<br />\r\nYou cannot understand the moment when people were infected. Instead, scientists are working backwards. Data - such as the number of deaths hospitalized or tests that have tested positive for the virus over time - is used to assess how easily the virus is spreading.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why is a number above one dangerous?<br />\r\nWhen the number of reproductions is greater than one, the number of cases increases exponentially - snowballing as unpaid credit card debt. But if the numbers were lower, at some point the disease would stop spreading because not enough new people were infected to keep it going. Governments everywhere want to reduce the number of reproductions from about three (the number R if we don&#39;t take action) to less than one.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is the UK R number?<br />\r\nThe dial number is not specified. Rather, it changes with changes in our behavior or with the development of immunity. Mathematical modellers from Imperial College London are trying to track the changes in numbers when isolation, social distancing and total lockdown occur in the spring. Before any action was taken, they were more than one in number, and conditions were ripe for a major outbreak. Successive restrictions remove it, but only after the full block is pressed below one.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Friday 11 September, the government announced that the UK R-number is expected to be 1.0 to 1.2.<br />\r\nAre there regional differences?<br />\r\nScotland has the highest R number - between 1.1 and 1.5. In Wales it ranges from 0.5 to 1.0 and in Northern Ireland from 0.3 to 1.4. In the UK, the highest forecast coefficient R is in London and the Northwest - with a range between 1.1 and 1.3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than 1.6 million people have to be barred from mingling outside their homes in the Birmingham area - due to a spike in cases. But the Midlands as a whole actually has the lowest percentage in the UK, from 0.9 to 1.1.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What does R mean by tightening or loosening the lock?<br />\r\nIn the past, the British government has stated that the number R is one of the most important factors in making political decisions. He later said that this estimate was less reliable and less useful because of the relatively small number of cases. However, when cases increase again, more attention will be paid to local and national R-rates. The goal is to keep the reproductive number below one.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Is that the most important number?<br />\r\nThe reproducible number is one of the top three. The other is severity - some people have very mild ailments that don&#39;t cause much trouble. But the coronavirus and the disease it causes, Covid-19, can be serious and deadly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The latter is the number of cases that matter in deciding when to act. If you have a large number but loosen the limit so that the number of replicas is about one, you still have a large number of cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How about the vaccine?<br />\r\nVaccines are another way to reduce reproductive numbers. Coronavirus patients naturally infected an average of three other people. However, if the vaccine can protect two of them from infection, the number of reproductions will drop from three to one.</p>', 'R Number, Carona virus', 'R number_1599940799.jpg', '2020-09-12 23:59:59', '2021-08-12 00:14:33'),
(551, 7, 1, 161, 'coronavirus-oxford-university-resumes-vaccine-testing-after-a-break-1599940867', 'Coronavirus: Oxford University resumes vaccine testing after a break', 0, '<p><strong>The trials of the Covid-19 vaccine developed by AstraZeneca and the University of Oxford were resumed after discontinuation due to side effects reported in patients in the UK.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Tuesday, AstraZeneca said it had suspended research to see if these side effects were vaccine-related.But on Saturday the university said it was safe to continue. Health Secretary Matt Hancock welcomed news that the trial would resume.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This gap shows that safety always comes first. We will support our scientists in delivering an effective vaccine as quickly as possible,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The university said in a statement that &quot;some participants are expected&quot; to fall ill in a larger study like this one &quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that studies could now proceed on recommendations from independent safety review commissions and UK regulators, regulators for drugs and health products.<br />\r\nIt will not reveal any information about the patient&#39;s illness for confidentiality reasons, but the New York Times reports that a volunteer in the UK study was diagnosed with transverse myelitis, an inflammatory syndrome that affects the spinal cord and can be caused by a viral infection. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the World Health Organization (WHO), nearly 180 vaccine candidates are being tested worldwide, but none have completed clinical trials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is great hope that the vaccine could be one of the first to hit the market after successful Phase 1 and 2 testing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>About 30,000 participants in the US, UK, Brazil and South Africa have been involved in transitioning to Phase 3 testing in recent weeks. Phase 3 studies on vaccines often involve thousands of participants and can last several years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Government scientific adviser Sir Patrick Valance told a press conference on Downing Street Wednesday that what happened during the Oxford Process was not unusual.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Risk of &quot;losing control&quot;<br />\r\nThe news came after Prof Sir Mark Walport, a member of the government&#39;s scientific advisory group, Sage, warned that Britain was &quot;on the verge of losing control of the virus&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He told BBC Radio 4 Today, &quot;You just have to look all over the channel to see what&#39;s happening in France and what&#39;s happening in Spain.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Official figures released on Saturday showed an additional 3,497 people in the UK had tested positive for the virus. For the second day in a row, the number of cases registered each day exceeded 3,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The total number of confirmed cases so far stands at 365,174. Meanwhile, government figures show that nine more people died within 28 days of testing positive for Covid-19, resulting in 41,623 fatalities in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Official figures show the UK coronavirus epidemic is rising again after the number of Rs - the virus reproduction rate - rose to 1 to 1.2 for the first time since March.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, daily coronavirus cases in Scotland have hit a four-month high, according to the latest information from the Scottish Government.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A total of 221 people have tested positive for the virus in the past 24 hours - the highest daily number since May 8, when 225 tested positive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new &quot;rule of six&quot; restrictions, which will halt the climb, will take effect Monday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the UK, indoor and outdoor meetings with more than six people are prohibited, except in certain circumstances such as at work or school. Anyone who breaks the rules can be fined.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Scotland, communication is limited to a maximum of six people inside and outside. However, unlike the UK, they must come from two households and children under 12 are exempted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In Wales, it is also illegal for more than six people from extended families to meet inside on Monday - but up to 30 can still meet outside.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Local restrictions in parts of Northern Ireland, including Belfast and Ballymena, will take effect Monday to reduce face-to-face contact in affected areas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cabinet Secretary Michael Gove agreed that fines may be needed to ensure people isolate themselves when necessary. He told Radio 4&#39;s Today, &quot;I don&#39;t want fines, but I don&#39;t want people to behave in a way that harms those who are most vulnerable.&quot;</p>', 'Oxford university, Test', 'Vaccine Pause_1599940867.jpg', '2020-09-13 00:01:07', '2021-09-23 08:14:57'),
(552, 7, 17, 149, 'six-months-after-the-pandemic-was-declared-where-are-the-global-hotspots-1599942049', 'Six months after the pandemic was declared, where are the global hotspots?', 0, '<p><strong>Where were the hotspots six months after the pandemic was declared?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The coronavirus continues to spread globally, with nearly 30 million confirmed cases in 188 countries, and the death toll quickly approaching one million. Six months after the World Health Organization (classified as a pandemic by WHO), the virus is on the rise in many countries, and some that appear to have succeeded in suppressing the initial outbreak also saw an increase in infections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the number of confirmed cases during the Spring Summit is likely to be underestimated for the true infection rate, as extensive tests were not conducted in many countries at the start of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where are cases and deaths increasing?<br />\r\nAsia is the continent with the highest number of confirmed cases today. India has the second highest number of confirmed cases in the world after the US and recorded the highest daily number on Friday below 100,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This increase is due to the government continuing to lift restrictions to stimulate the economy, but it also reflects tighter testing - as daily testing rose to more than one million per day in August.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Due to its population size, India has a low death rate due to Covid-19. However, more than 1,000 deaths were reported as of Friday, with more than 1,000 people killed each day since early September. In Latin America, Brazil has the most deaths with around 130,000 to date. More than four million cases have also been recorded, the third highest in the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>New confirmed cases in the region are also on the rise in Argentina, which now has a population of more than half a million people.<br />\r\nIn the Middle East, Iran has been particularly hard hit by the virus, and documents sent to the News channel which show that the death toll there is more than double the official figure of around 23,000. There are also increasing cases in neighboring Iraq.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cases continue to increase in Indonesia. The country has nearly 9,000 deaths, the largest in Southeast Asia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Africa has recorded more than one million confirmed cases, although the true extent of the continent&#39;s pandemic is unknown. Testing rates are reportedly low, which could deviate from official estimates, but South Africa and Egypt have recorded the largest outbreaks recorded to date. Corona virus cases are on the rise again in Europe Several European countries are seeing an increase in the number of cases every day for fear of a return of the virus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hans Kluge, Director General of the WHO European Office, compared Covid-19 to a &quot;long-tailed tornado&quot; and warned that cases that develop among young people could spread the disease to older people who are more vulnerable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A number of European countries have reinstated local blockades in the hardest-hit regions, again urging people to wear face coverings and abide by social distancing rules.<br />\r\nThe patterns of infection that developed after the lockdown ended were not limited to Europe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other countries where the virus has re-emerged include Peru, Israel, South Korea and Australia - although most are now seeing more cases after the reintroduction of tighter restrictions.<br />\r\nIn the table below, the countries can be sorted by mortality, mortality, and general cases. In the colored bar on the right, the countries where the cases have increased to more than 5,000 per day are the countries that have a black bar as of that date.<br />\r\nCases in the United States slowed down after the second wave<br />\r\nThe United States has reported more than six million coronavirus cases, nearly a quarter of the world. The number of daily cases increased in July but has decreased since then.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With nearly 200,000 deaths, the United States has the highest death toll in the world.<br />\r\nUniversity of Washington estimates suggest there could be more than 400,000 deaths by the end of the year, although that could be reduced to 290,000 if 95% of Americans wear masks in public.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The explosion was bad for the US economy. In the three months from April to June, GDP fell by a record 33%.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How is the spread of the corona virus?<br />\r\nThe virus that causes the Covid-19 respiratory tract infection was first discovered in Wuhan, China, at the end of 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The outbreak spread rapidly across the world in the first few months of 2020 and was declared a global pandemic by the WHO on March 11.<br />\r\nA pandemic occurs when a contagious disease spreads easily from person to person at the same time in many parts of the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Europe and North America experienced their first major eruptions in April, but as they began to settle, Latin America and Asia saw leaps and bounds.<br />\r\nGovernments around the world are being forced to restrict social movements and close businesses and premises to slow the spread of the virus. This has had a devastating effect on the global economy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The International Monetary Fund said the world was in the midst of the worst recession since the Great Depression and warned that it would take two years for economic performance to return to pre-pandemic levels.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the United Nations, up to 265 million people could starve to death from the effects of Covid-19 by the end of the year.</p>', 'Coronavirus, 6month, pandemic', 'hotspot_1599942049.jpg', '2020-09-13 00:20:49', '2021-12-19 17:35:21'),
(553, 7, 7, 41, 'the-collapse-of-the-democratic-republic-of-the-congo-in-a-gold-mine-caused-fear-to-50-people-1599942979', 'The collapse of the Democratic Republic of the Congo in a gold mine caused fear to 50 people', 0, '<p><strong>Rescuers excavated debris after a gold mine in the Democratic Republic of Congo collapsed and about 50 people died.</strong><br />\r\nThe mine near the city of Kamituga in the east of the country was withdrawn on Friday in heavy rain. Local officials said most of the terrified dead were young and called for two days of mourning. Accidents are frequent in the DRC mining industry, which has poor safety standards.<br />\r\nVideo footage showed hundreds of people trying to clear debris blocking the mine&#39;s entrance. Some rescuers used shovels or hands to move the debris. The governor of South Kivu Province Theo Cassie said he was saddened by the &quot;tragic deaths of 50 people, most of them young people&quot;.<br />\r\nHowever, Kamituga Mayor Alexander Bundya said &quot;we are still not sure exactly how many&quot; were killed, &quot;AFP reported. An eye witness told AFP that heavy rain meant &quot;water entered three tunnels. When people try to get out, there is no way the water can flow fast.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/32A4/production/_114346921_36743d1c-df7b-4d9c-bfd2-312d908eb03d.jpg\" /><br />\r\nMr. office. Cassie added that she would &quot;take steps to prevent such incidents from happening again&quot;.<br />\r\nThe Democratic Republic of Congo has rich mineral deposits such as cobalt, diamonds, copper and gold, but after years of conflict and mismanagement, its population is still among the poorest in the world.</p>', 'Democratic Republic, Congo', 'Congo_1599942979.jpg', '2020-09-13 00:36:19', '2021-08-15 02:53:14'),
(554, 7, 4, 82, 'grand-prix-of-tuscany-luis-hamilton-defeats-valteri-botas-against-mugello-pole-1599943540', 'Grand Prix of Tuscany: Luis Hamilton defeats Valteri Botas against Mugello Pole', 0, '<p><strong>Louis Hamilton took seventh pole position in nine races this season at the first Tuscan Grand Prix.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The world champion beat Mercedes teammate Valteri Botas in the first Formula 1 race on the spectacular Mugelo track by just 0.059 seconds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Red Bull closed the second line, Max Verstappen beat Alex Albon. And Charles Leclerc gave Ferrari something to celebrate in fifth place at the 1000 Grand Prix. Hamilton did so when needed Botas was in charge of all three training sessions and Hamilton looked to his hind legs to qualify.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But Hamilton was fastest in the second session with 0.013 seconds and extended his first-half lead of the top 10 penalties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hamilton did not improve in his final lap and Botas&#39; hopes were dashed when Esteban Ocon of Renault turned around and raised a yellow flag.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hamilton said, &quot;This weekend is very close. It&#39;s a very challenging program and Walter was faster than me yesterday and this morning and even in the first quarter of the day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/onesport/cps/800/cpsprodpb/2B9C/production/_114346111_hamreuters3.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;I worked really hard behind the scenes to improve my dialogue and arrangements and ended up getting the tour I needed. &quot;In the end I thought the wind was blowing hard and I couldn&#39;t go any faster. But I did my job.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is crazy. You alternate six, seven, eight and nine at 180 mph and G-Force is crazy.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Botas said he believes Okon&#39;s incident cost him his first place since the 70th anniversary of the Silverstone Grand Prix last month. The Finn said: &quot;I have more and am waiting for time to get better, but I didn&#39;t have a chance. It is certainly disappointing.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Verstappen&#39;s lead at Red Bull was the smallest in leading positions all year round. &quot;I didn&#39;t expect to fight in qualifying but this weekend looks very promising,&quot; he said. &quot;To finish third, we can be very satisfied with that.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/onesport/cps/800/cpsprodpb/79BC/production/_114346113_lecepa.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leclerc said that over the weekend he expected Ferrari to be even stronger on the track they have after two disappointing appearances at Spa and Monza, but he didn&#39;t expect to be the best of the others.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Leclerc is the only Ferrari driver in the top 10. Team-mate Sebastian Vettel finished 14th and retired in second qualifying when he was 0.534 seconds behind Leclerc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I feel a lot better,&quot; said Leclerc. &quot;Very happy with my last lap. P5 is definitely the best we can do. Overall, very happy with the car. We did a pretty good job with balance this weekend compared to Monza, where we fought a lot. Today is one of the strongest side of the car.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The race will be difficult but at least we have a position and now it is up to us to maintain it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leclerc led the race and Sergio Perez overtook Lance Stroll, although the Canadian took advantage of a new body package that the Mexican, who was notified before the weekend that he would be eliminated for Vettel for 2021, would not progress to the next competition in Russia.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Daniel Ricciardo of Renault, Carlos Sainz and McLarens Ocon lead the top 10, and Lando Norris of McLaren second in eleventh.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;When in doubt, walk away,&quot; said Russell<br />\r\nGeorge Russell, who missed the whole of the last training session with braking problems, put in an excellent performance to beat Williams teammate Nicholas Latifi for 18th despite running a long distance and jumping over gravel and grass at the exit of the extremely fast left-hander Savelli.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Russell held his feet for a moment and entered the terrifying double flat with Arrabbiata&#39;s right hand, sliding 0.088 seconds ahead of Latifi. So he went on to note that he was never ranked in F1 by a teammate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Russell said he picked up Casanova over the left and right apartment for the first time over the weekend and thought he&#39;d try to take the seventh turn, Saveli, also flat, adding, &quot;Honestly that&#39;s kind of silly to be.&quot; &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t know [how I kept him on the road],&quot; continued Russell, revealing that the team had put pressure on the car before qualifying. &quot;When in doubt, give up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I knew Nicholas was ahead of me on the previous two stretches and I knew that if I didn&#39;t finish the last lap he would finish ahead of me. I held him tight and the diffuser was badly damaged. Q2 is definitely planned.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/onesport/cps/800/cpsprodpb/6705/production/_114337362_fansreuters.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>', 'Grand Prix, Luis Hamilton, defeat', 'TUscan_1599943540.jpg', '2020-09-13 00:45:40', '2021-08-12 00:01:26'),
(555, 7, 4, 121, 'alex-morgan-the-tottenham-hotspur-woman-entered-the-us-1599943723', 'Alex Morgan: The Tottenham Hotspur woman entered the US', 0, '<p><strong>Tottenham Hotspur has completed signing US striker and football icon Alex Morgan on a visa.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 31-year-old helped the US win the World Cup by scoring six goals at the 2019 tournament in France. Morgan, who gave birth to their daughter on May 7, scored 107 goals in 169 appearances for the United States.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He is the fifth member of the world championship team to register for the WSL club this summer. Sam Mavis, Rose Lovell, Tobin Heath and Kristen Press have confirmed the move in England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Midfielder Mavis and Lavelle joined Manchester City, while Manchester United signed a contract with striker Heath and Press.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Morgan has played for the Orlando Pride since 2016, and the Florida-based club said that while it will not be available for the upcoming NWSL American fall series, it will retain its rights to the NWSL upon its return.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Morgan, who received jersey # 13, has joined &quot;for the 2020-21 season&quot; following the initial announcement that he will not sign a short-term contract until the end of December, according to Spurs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another star name in the WSL<br />\r\nMorgan&#39;s arrival comes after a boom in London and the Southeast Regional High Division in recent years when co-head coach Karen Hills took office in 2007.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They will not compete in the WSL until the second season of the season, having finished seventh in their debut premier league campaign since their last release since their promotion in 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Morgan has captured one of the sport&#39;s biggest names.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He was nominated three times - in 2016, 2017 and 2019 - for the FIFPro World XI and won an Olympic gold medal with the US in London in 2012.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The move comes after a summer of major transfers in the women&#39;s game in England, including Chelsea&#39;s addition to Danish star Pernil Harder for a fee set to exceed &pound; 250,000, as well as Dutch defenders Lucy Bronze and Alex Greenwood at Manchester City from European champions Lyon.</p>', 'Alex Morgan, Hotspur woman, US', 'Alex Morgan_1599943723.jpg', '2020-09-13 00:48:43', '2021-09-23 08:15:47');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(556, 7, 4, 134, 'tour-de-france-soren-kragg-andersen-wins-the-14th-stage-1599943958', 'Tour de France: Soren Kragg Andersen wins the 14th stage', 0, '<p><strong>Soren Kragg Andersen celebrates a surprise win at the 14th stage of the Tour de France and wins a great tactical journey by the Sunweb team.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Dane struck three kilometers before a busy final and went away for his first win on stage. Primoz Roglic maintained his lead for 44 seconds in the yellow shirt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Peter Sagan finished fourth at Lyon to reduce Sam Bennett&#39;s lead to 43 points after Sagan Bora-Hansgrohe&#39;s men fired the Irishman early. Luka Mezgetz was second and Simone Consoni third when the peloton came 15 seconds after Krag Andersen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was feeling very emotional. I had a dream about it, but it&#39;s hard to say you&#39;re good enough until you did. I&#39;m amazed,&quot; said Crag Andersen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I have really good legs all day, but you never know how good other people are. It took me a long time on the tour to be sure, but I know when I suffer, they suffer.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Very flat before the climb begins&quot; - guide to Stage 15 by Adam Yates<br />\r\nWith two short but sharp inclines in the 194km Clermont-Ferrand final, Sunweb played his cards perfectly to beat and win the favorite.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tiesj Benoot strikes at the top of the first ascent, forcing teammate Sagan Lennard Kamna to give chase before Kamna gains his own lead but is sent back as well.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Julian Alafilip tried to pull out of his way to seek his second victory in the race but was blocked by Mark Hirsch of Sunweb who then attacked.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The winning shot of the 12th stage forces Hirsch to chase Sagan. Once the group reunited, Krag Andersen left and could not be caught as his teammates were working to prevent a counterattack.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sunweb initially sent two racers to join Stefan Kung and Edward Theons who split early, but realized that a party of four would not keep their distance and adapted their plans brilliantly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bora-Hansgrohe is also in a great race. Sagan used the first climb of the day to exit and returned four points to Ireland&#39;s Bennett in the intermediate sprint before his team could unleash Bennett on the second climb.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bennett tried hard to close the distance but stopped 115 km to the end and rolled for nearly 20 minutes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The record-winning seven-time Sagan green shirt ended up picking up just 23 points for Bennett and must continue to take advantage of opportunities on hilly terrain, with Bennett consistently being faster in sprints.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was a relatively quiet day for the whole standings, except for a late strike by defending champion Ineos Grenadier Egan Bernal, who lost 38 seconds to Roglic in the 38th stage, which was quickly halted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sunday&#39;s 174.5 km stage is very important to the entire competitor as it covers three major climbs, including the final at Grand Colombier.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>French racer Romain Barde failed to start Stage 14 after leaving the race on Friday night with a concussion, and said on Saturday that the MRI showed slight bleeding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The AG2R rider La Mondiale had a terrible accident on stage 13 and appeared to have crashed while trying to get up before continuing the last two climbs and struggling when he slipped from fourth to eleventh.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Stage 14 result</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>1. Soren Kragh Andersen (Den/Team Sunweb) 4hrs 28mins 10secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Luka Mezgec (Slo/Mitchelton-Scott) +15secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Simone Consonni (Ita/Cofidis) Same time</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Peter Sagan (Svk/Bora-Hansgrohe)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Casper Pedersen (Den/Team Sunweb)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. Jasper Stuyven (Bel/Trek-Segafredo)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7. Matteo Trentin (Ita/CCC Team)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8. Oliver Naesen (Bel/AG2R La Mondiale)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9. Sonny Colbrelli (Ita/Bahrain McLaren)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10. Marc Hirschi (Swi/Team Sunweb)</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>General classification after stage 14</h3>\r\n\r\n<p>1. Primoz Roglic (Slo/Jumbo-Visma) 61hrs 03mins 00secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Tadej Pogacar (Slo/UAE Team Emirates) +44secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Egan Bernal (Col/Ineos Grenadiers) +59secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Rigoberto Uran (Col/EF Pro Cycling) +1min 10secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Nairo Quintana (Col/Arkea-Samsic) +1min 12secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. Miguel Angel Lopez (Col/Astana) +1min 31secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>7. Adam Yates (GB/Mitchelton-Scott) +1min 42secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>8. Mikel Landa (Spa/Bahrain McLaren) +1min 55secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>9. Richie Porte (Aus/Trek-Segafredo) +2mins 06secs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>10. Enric Mas (Spa/Movistar) +2mins 54secs</p>', 'Tour de France, 14 stage', 'Tour Da France_1599943958.jpg', '2020-09-13 00:52:38', '2021-08-15 04:27:24'),
(557, 7, 17, 145, 'navid-afkari-iran-is-executing-young-fighters-despite-global-protests-1599944160', 'Navid Afkari: Iran is executing young fighters despite global protests', 0, '<p><strong>Iran has executed a fighter accused of murder and defied international calls for his rescue.</strong><br />\r\nNavid Afkari, 27, was sentenced to death for killing a security guard during a wave of anti-government protests in 2018.<br />\r\nHe said he was tortured to confess.<br />\r\nHuman rights organization Amnesty International called the executions of Afrikaans a &quot;parody of justice&quot;.<br />\r\nIn the out-of-date footage released by the group, Afkari said, &quot;If I am executed, I want you to know that an innocent man was executed even though he tried and struggled with all his might to be heard.&quot;<br />\r\nAfkari was executed while hanging in the southern city of Shiraz, state media reported.<br />\r\nHis lawyer said his client was prohibited from seeing his family before he died, as required by Iranian law.<br />\r\n&quot;Are you in such a rush to execute the sentence that you paid Navid for the last visit?&quot; Hassan Younesi said on Twitter.<br />\r\nThere have been calls for an end to the executions, including from a union representing 85,000 athletes worldwide.<br />\r\nThe World Players Association said it was &quot;wrong&quot; to participate in the protests and called for Iran to be banned from world sports if it continued.<br />\r\nUS President Donald Trump also appealed for mercy, saying &quot;the fighters&#39; only act is anti-government demonstrations in the streets&quot;.<br />\r\nThe International Olympic Committee (IOC) described his execution as &quot;very sad news&quot; and said their thoughts were on his family and friends.<br />\r\n&quot;It is very worrying that inquiries from athletes around the world and the IOC&#39;s behind-the-scenes work ... are not achieving our goals,&quot; the statement said.<br />\r\nAccording to human rights activists in Iran, the Afkari brothers, Wahid and Habib, were sentenced to 54 and 27 years in prison in the same case.<br />\r\nIn an audio recording from the prison where he is being held, Afkari says he was tortured. Her mother said her sons were forced to testify against one another.<br />\r\nHis lawyer said on Twitter that, contrary to Iranian news, there was no video of the killing of the security guard at the time. He added that the footage used as evidence was taken one hour before the crime occurred.<br />\r\nIranian authorities deny the torture allegations.<br />\r\nAfkari is a national master of wrestling, a sport that has a long history and is very popular in Iran.<br />\r\nIn 2018, protesters took to the streets in Iranian cities amid economic hardship and political repression.</p>', 'Iran, Navid Afkari', 'Navid_1599944160.jpg', '2020-09-13 00:56:00', '2021-12-19 17:35:09'),
(558, 7, 4, 147, 'harry-maguire-man-utd-boss-ole-gunnar-solskjaer-insists-the-defender-will-remain-captain-1599944345', 'Harry Maguire: Man Utd boss Ole Gunnar Solskjaer insists the defender will remain captain', 0, '<p><strong>Harry Maguire remains Manchester United captain, confirmed manager Ole Gunnar Solskjaer.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maguire, 27, was sentenced to probation on the Greek island of Syros after being convicted of grievous bodily injuries, resisting arrest and repeated attempts at bribery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He maintained his innocence and appealed the decision to overturn the sentence. &quot;He will be our captain,&quot; Solskjaer told MUTV.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He&#39;s doing really well and of course I&#39;ll be here to support him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;re going to let Harry and his people and the process go on. For me he is the tallest person, the highest person, and he&#39;s always been a positive person with the right values. So I really look forward to seeing Harry do what he does. best.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maguire will now be given a full trial in a higher court, telling that&nbsp;his &quot;conscience is clear&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He was withdrawn from the England squad last month but manager Gareth Southgate said he would &quot;try&quot; to call the defender back in October.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>United will take on Aston Villa on Saturday before they take on Crystal Palace in the Premier League on September 19.</p>', 'Harry Maguire, captain', 'Harry maguire_1599944345.jpg', '2020-09-13 00:59:05', '2021-08-15 21:17:34'),
(559, 7, 4, 127, 'england-versus-australia-sam-billings-looks-world-class-james-anderson-1599944515', 'England versus Australia: Sam Billings looks world class - James Anderson', 0, '<p><strong>Sam Billings looked like &quot;part of the scene&quot; as he finished his first century in England against Australia, says British presenter James Anderson.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Billings&#39; 118 balls with 110 balls helped England recover 57-4 in the first game of a one-day draw, but the hosts lost 19 of those games at the Emirates Old Trafford.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;When he picks up speed, he looks world class,&quot; Anderson told BBC Sport. &quot;In a stressful situation, he really took his chances.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kent Billings, a 29-year-old hitter, has only played 19 ODIs since his debut in 2015, often being used as a substitute when other players are absent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Against high-quality attacks from Australia and over difficult terrain, he did the innings well and came close to winning England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With universal Ben Stokes missing the draw, Billings took his seat at five o&#39;clock.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve been threatening to have substantial results for a long time and good ones to get big and demanding results,&quot; said Billings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That&#39;s all I can do. I don&#39;t think I&#39;ll defend this place no matter how many runs I do.&quot; Match two of three draws will take place on Sunday at 13.00 CET.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Australian batsman Steve Smith is ready to play after missing the opening game. He passed a second concussion test after hitting his head in the net on Friday.<br />\r\nBillings missed the winning campaign for the 2019 World Cup with a shoulder injury which he described as &quot;the hardest time of his career&quot;. This summer, however, he was even more involved as an England break player.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He had made it three and a half centuries before Friday&#39;s game and scored his highest score to date of 67 against Ireland that summer. In the past, Billings said he was putting too much pressure on himself to get good results.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;For me that&#39;s the difference yesterday. 10 out of 30 balls - I&#39;ll probably do something stupid and explode,&quot; he said. &quot;Maybe a little more experience, a little more confidence in my abilities at this level, I can handle the pressure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m definitely not at my best, but instead of trying to push the problem and try it, I can start.</p>', 'sam billings, world class, player', 'sam billing_1599944515.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:01:55', '2021-09-23 08:14:07'),
(560, 7, 4, 182, '2020-us-open-alexander-zverev-beat-pablo-kareno-busta-to-reach-the-final-1599945534', '2020 US Open: Alexander Zverev beat Pablo Kareno Busta to reach the final', 0, '<p><strong>German Alexander Zverev reached his first Grand Slam final in the hardest of ways after beating Spaniard Pablo Careno Busta by five feet in a thrilling US Open.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fifth-seeded 23-year-old Zverev looked defeated when Kareno Busta played smart and precise to take the lead in two sets. However Zverev showed incredible determination to turn things around and won 3-6 2-6 6-3 6-4 6-3 against the 20th seed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zverev will face Austrian second winner Dominic Thiem in the final on Sunday. The 27-year-old team beat Russian third seed Daniil Medvedev in the second semi-final on Friday at Flushing Meadows 6: 2, 7: 6 (9: 7), 7: 6 (7: 5).<br />\r\nIn the finals there will be a new Grand Slam champion, who was crowned for the first time at the 2014 US Open when Croatian Marin Cilic won.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The absence of the 2019 champions, Rafael Nadal and Roger Federer, in the Grand Slam behind closed doors, as well as the expulsion of Novak Djokovic, who hit the referee with a ball, gave a new name the opportunity to receive an important trophy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Swiss tennis player Stan Wawrinka is the last outside the Top Three to win the Australian Open, French Open, Wimbledon or US Open after winning Flushing Meadows in 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zverev&#39;s chances of becoming the latest Grand Slam champion look slim after Kareno Busta&#39;s strong start. But the former world number 3 now has a guest win after a return to the semi-finals that was neither qualitative nor captivating.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zverev grinned in disbelief as he waved his fist at the box as Kareno Busta darted back into the net in the second game point. &quot;I know that I have to create better and more stable tennis,&quot; said Zverev.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I know I have to play better. I never came back from two sets to love, but I&#39;m happy to do it at the moment. &quot;I&#39;ve reached my first Grand Slam final and that&#39;s the most important.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zverev showed both sides of his abilities in a bizarre match Zverev has long been touted as one of the next generation to replace Nadal, Federer and Djokovic, but too often points out a number of flaws that cause much doubt about his true credibility.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Here the world number seven shows both sides of that makeup as she returns to win a two-set deficit for the first time in her career.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zverev lacked the goals and intensity in the first two sets as a focused Kareno Busta fulfilled a perfect game plan to capitalize on the lead. Zverev&#39;s second serve was a definite weakness in his game and came back when it got worse in the second set.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Double faults in each of his first two service games put Kareno Busta 3-0 up. She finished the one-sided set and won only three points out of 19 on her second serve.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another telling statistic is Zverev&#39;s 22 own mistakes compared to just three Kareno Busta missiles. This led to former US Open semifinalist Tim Henman, who described Zverev&#39;s second appearance in his role as a television analyst as a &quot;horror show&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Suddenly, Zverev slacked off in the third set and looked more like the player who won the ATP final two years ago. His serve play improved dramatically as he won four love ties and also reduced random errors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zverev maintains this level at fourth as it is a question of whether Kareno Busta can overcome his nervousness.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zverev continued to score more winners for regular mistakes in important games and helped him stop serving in the first and final games of the set.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In fact, it was Zverev who won the match and Kareno Busta who lost.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zverev should be given more credit for displaying extraordinary determination and refusing to panic when losing.</p>', 'Alexander Zverev, beat, pablo', 'Alexander Zverev_1599945534.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:18:54', '2021-08-15 02:31:47'),
(561, 7, 4, 87, '2020-us-open-victoria-azarenka-and-naomi-osaka-womens-final-1599945606', '2020 US Open: Victoria Azarenka and Naomi Osaka, women\'s final', 0, '<p><strong>Two-time Grand Slam winner Victoria Azarenka said she was &quot;mentally elsewhere&quot; until her final grand final as she prepares to face Naomi Osaka at the US Open on Saturday.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 31-year-old Belarusian will play her first Grand Slam final after losing to Serena Williams at the 2013 US Open. The 22-year-old Japanese Osaka tennis player is eyeing her third major after winning the US Open in 2018 and the Australian Open in 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Azarenka have won their last 11 matches while Osaka is unbeaten in 10. The two must meet in the final of the Western and Southern Open, played before the US Open at Flushing Meadows, so that Osaka can withdraw from the game with a lower leg injury.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Azarenka enjoys her surprise back on top<br />\r\nAzarenka, world 27, won her first title in four years since Osaka&#39;s retirement and now has an even bigger prize. The former number one in the world continued his Grand Slam form behind closed doors, surprising those who erased him.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Azarenka took her time to give birth in December 2016 and was stopped by a long battle over custody of her son, Leo.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He only won one game last year when he competed in the Western and Southern Open last month, and admitted last week that he was thinking of quitting when the WTA tour was halted due to the coronavirus pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead, she is preparing for her third final at the US Open after beating Serena Williams in the adorable semi-final on Thursday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I am very different mentally. I think seven years ago, after winning the Australian Open and playing consistently well, I should be in the final,&quot; said Azarenka, who lost to Williams in the US final. Opened in 2012 and 2013</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t think that&#39;s what happened this year. &quot;But this year was funnier, more fulfilling and more fun to me. I feel more comfortable.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The benefits of ripening Osaka from increased mental strength Former world number 1 Osaka has struggled to overcome tightened controls following their victories at the 2018 US Open and 2019 Australian Open Grand Slams.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Osaka dropped to 10th place after failing to maintain that top level, but the 22-year-old said she has&nbsp; eveloped greater mental resilience in recent months.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This can be seen in the confident stretch up to the two Flushing Meadows finals. &quot;I would say that I think this time is very different,&quot; said Osaka. I feel like I&#39;ve learned a lot through the ups and downs, not even counting the finals, but only in the regular tournaments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I feel stronger mentally and now I feel healthier. I feel like I must have more confidence in myself. I have the feeling that all these games are related to each other and after reaching the third set as long as you can stay calm about the result. Be supportive. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Every time Osaka reached the Grand Slam quarter-finals, she continued to win tournaments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I would say the closer we are to the final, the more nobody remembers except the winner,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That&#39;s probably one of my biggest motivators.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Osaka face each other after Azarenka&#39;s early lessons<br />\r\nAzarenka ranked the Osaka youths when they first met when Belarus won 6-1 and 6-1 in the third round of the 2016 Australian Open.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;To be honest, I&#39;m a little happy he beat me like that because I still have a lot to learn and can see it as a good experience,&quot; said Osaka afterwards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Osaka beat Azarenka in the other two meetings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both wins were practical: Osaka won the Italian Open in 2018 6-0 and 6-3 and at last year&#39;s French Open 4-6: 7-5: 6-3.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The path to the goal<br />\r\nUndisclosed Azarenka faced a difficult path to the final after facing players interviewed in four of their six matches.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The opponents&#39; wins against Belgian Elise Mertens (16th) and Williams (3rd) were impressive.<br />\r\nThe thigh problem that led to Osaka&#39;s withdrawal from the Western and Southern Open did not stop the Japanese fourth seed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Despite missing sets in all three of her games, including a high-quality semi-final against 28-year-old Jennifer Brady, Osaka&#39;s serve play was the foundation of her success.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>She won 93% of her serve games and 81% of points on her first serve - her total is only better with women than Madison Keys, who withdrew from her match in the third round.</p>', 'Victoria Azarenka, final womens', 'Victoria Azarenka_1599945606.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:20:06', '2021-09-23 08:14:15'),
(562, 7, 4, 120, 'giro-rosa-anemiek-van-vleiten-won-the-second-stage-and-led-the-race-1599945644', 'Giro Rosa: Anemiek van Vleiten won the second stage and led the race', 0, '<p><strong>Defending champion Anemic van Vleiten won the Giro Rosa&#39;s second stage and took the leader&#39;s jersey.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Dutch road racing world champion, 37, won over a minute ahead of Anna van der Bregen of Boels-Dolmans and Katarzyna Niewiadoma of Canyon-SRAM.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mitchell-Scott Van Vleiten&#39;s driver took the lead when he was mechanically afflicted. But he returned to the front to catch up and pass Van der Bregen with a distance of less than 3 km to the left of the 124.8 km stage from Paganico to Archidoso.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Van Vleiten pulled off Elisa Longo Borghini&#39;s pink maglia jersey, which led to Trek-Segafredo to victory in the team trials on Friday. This will be Van Vleiten&#39;s last Giro Rose with Mitchellton-Scott after announcing in August that he would join Movistar next season.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The third stage of the nine-day race took the 142.2 km riders from Santa Fiora to Assisi on Sunday.</p>', 'Giro Rosa, wom second stage', 'Giro Rosa_1599945644.png', '2020-09-13 01:20:44', '2021-08-15 03:55:59'),
(563, 7, 4, 86, 'nba-playoffs-boston-celtics-beat-the-toronto-raptors-to-reach-the-conference-finals-1599945687', 'NBA Playoffs: Boston Celtics beat the Toronto Raptors to reach the conference finals', 0, '<p><strong>The Boston Celtics reached the Eastern Conference final with a 92-87 win over defending champions the Toronto Raptors in a decisive draw.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fred VanVleet of the Raptors lost a three-point lead that would tie the game 12 seconds ahead 90-90. After that, Kemba Walker took a free throw on the opposite end to seal victory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jason Tatum of the Celtics took part in the seventh game with 29 points and 12 rebounds. The Celtics will face the Miami Heat in the final of the conference.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Houston striker was kicked out of the NBA bubble The first game in the series - the Celtics&#39; third final appearance in four seasons - takes place on Tuesday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Heath reached the Eastern Conference final for the first time since 2014 with a 4-1 win over the Milwaukee Bucks. The Raptors recovered from 2-0 to draw 3-3 against the Celtics, but VanVleet&#39;s 20 points weren&#39;t enough to win.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Jaylon Brown added 21 points and eight rebounds for the Celtics while Marcus Smart had 16 points, six assists and a vital block in the last minute.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I hand over my hat to Toronto. They are the reigning champions and they have a lot of heart,&quot; said Tatum.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;They made us win this. I think we reacted after we were almost 3-0, then we won 2-2. That&#39;s great and I think it will help us move forward.&quot;</p>', 'NBA, Boston Celtics beat', 'NBA_1599945687.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:21:27', '2021-09-23 08:16:59'),
(564, 7, 4, 164, 'mo-farah-won-the-antrim-half-beach-marathon-but-missed-the-british-record-1599945744', 'Mo Farah won the Antrim half beach marathon, but missed the British record', 0, '<p><strong>Four-time Olympic champion Mo Farah won a half marathon on the Antrim beach on the beautiful coast of Northern Ireland.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Farah followed last week&#39;s world record one hour in Brussels when he returned to track with another impressive performance on Saturday. In the final stages of the race he stretched significantly and won in one hour 27 seconds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 37-year-old finished third, 12 seconds ahead of Mark Scott and Ben Connor, with 16 seconds to go. Stephen Sculion of Belfast delighted the home fans with a superb fourth place and set Northern Ireland&#39;s record 61:08.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tommy Hughes broke the world record in the 1960s with four seconds after 71:26. Scullion determines initial velocity. The race started in Larne in perfect condition, as the participants had good running conditions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We hope Farah will beat her own British half marathon record by 59:32, but she will have to make do with beating top-class pitches. Initially, Scullion was responsible for co-production with Farah, and they crossed the two mile mark in about 9 minutes and 35 seconds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When they arrived, the Glennerm Road Sculion stood in front of the packed crowd, including Farah, Scott, and Connor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Via the four mile marker, runners cover an average distance of 4:45 / minute and follow the most difficult parts of the route with the climb.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A group of four approached the Black Arch and clearly stretched. Farah leads Connor, Scott and Sculion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A little over 30 minutes in the middle<br />\r\nThe leaders were in the middle at 30:18, and the second half of the race promised a shorter time due to descent.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The lead pack continued to change positions, and Scott was about four seconds behind in a hand-to-hand fight with Farah and Connor and beloved home Sculion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Speed started picking up for the remaining three miles, and Scott tried to keep up with Farah in direct pursuits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After 1 km to the end, Farah moved, broke away from Scott and continued on his way to victory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scott (60:39) finished second in the first half of the marathon and Connor third with 60:35.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Partridge broke the NI record<br />\r\nDuring the women&#39;s race, the top three broke Northern Ireland&#39;s records.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lily Partridge took the winner in an impressive 71:36 time, followed by Sam Harrison (71:59) and Clara Evans (72:22).</p>', 'Mo Farah, won Antrim half', 'mo farah_1599945744.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:22:24', '2021-08-14 07:39:04'),
(565, 7, 7, 47, 'charlottesville-removes-a-confederate-statue-near-a-violent-white-nationalist-demonstration-1599947302', 'Charlottesville removes a Confederate statue near a violent white nationalist demonstration', 0, '<p><strong>The crowd greeted Saturday when workers in Charlottesville removed a Confederate statue near a violent white nationalist demonstration three years ago. The removal of the bronze Confederate soldier figure known as &quot;idle&quot; was seen in Charlottesville as a cornerstone in removing the symbol of the separation of the civil war.</strong><br />\r\nThe Washington Post reports that the process of removing the statue began Saturday morning when workers attached rope to the 900 pound statue in preparation for removing it from its pedestal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A crowd of about 100 people greeted them from behind the metal barricade as the figure was lifted from its base and lowered to the floor. The statue has stood in front of the Albermarle County Courthouse for 111 years.<br />\r\nAll members of the crowd wear masks amid the coronavirus pandemic. Some wore blue hats and danced to music broadcasts on local radio stations during the United Civil War.<br />\r\nThe happy scene stands in stark contrast to the violence during the Unite The Right demonstration on August 12, 2017. A woman was killed and dozens injured when self-proven white supreme authorities rammed their car into a crowd protesting white nationalist demonstrations. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is an extraordinary moment,&quot; said local organizer Don Gathers. &quot;A lot of the racist tensions, riots and protests that we see across the country originate here in Charlottesville. But now I&#39;m moving in a positive light.&quot;<br />\r\nThe Charlottesville City Council decided to remove Lee and a nearby memorial to his partner Thomas J. Stonewall Jackson, but a small group of Confederate supporters filed a lawsuit to save him. The case will be referred to the Virginia Supreme Court and may take months to resolve.</p>', 'Charlottesville, statue', 'Chharlottesvilles_1599947302.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:48:22', '2021-08-16 07:08:12'),
(566, 7, 1, 211, 'canada-has-not-reported-a-new-coronavirus-death-for-the-first-time-since-march-1599947342', 'Canada has not reported a new coronavirus death for the first time since March', 0, '<p><strong>Canada did not report any new deaths from COVID-19 on Friday for the first time in six months. The last time the country reported a new death from the virus was on March 15, at the start of the North America lockdown due to the pandemic, Reuters reported.</strong><br />\r\nAs of Friday night, more than 6 million people in Canada had tested for COVID-19, 2.1% of whom were positive. Some 702 new cases were reported as of Friday, but Canada&#39;s Department of Health reported no new deaths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Canada&#39;s Public Health Agency, Quebec reported a new death on September 11, but Ontario canceled a previously reported death. This means that the number of reported deaths of 9,163 remained unchanged from the previous day.<br />\r\nAs the numbers increased, &quot;I remember the way Canadians came together to reduce the spread of COVID-19,&quot; said Dr. Teresa Tam, Canada&#39;s director of public health, in a statement. &quot;We were physically separated to draw a curve, but we found new ways to be together and connect while we were some distance away.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of the cases (80.0%) and deaths (93.7%) were reported in Ontario and Quebec.<br />\r\nDeaths from the coronavirus increased in April and continued to rise through July, before starting to increase in the summer, according to the country&#39;s health ministry. 71.3% of deaths in Canada are over 80 years of age.<br />\r\nSeveral Canadian provinces have started to loosen lockdown restrictions as schools reopen for private lessons, which recently led to a spike in cases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Compared to the United States, its southern neighbor, Canada has fewer infections and deaths from the coronavirus. The country has 137,676 cases of COVID-19 and 9,214 deaths as of Saturday, according to Johns Hopkins University.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In relative terms, the United States exceeded 6.4 million cases and 193,000 deaths as of Saturday.</p>', 'Canada, Corona free', 'No corona case_1599947342.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:49:02', '2021-08-17 14:04:58'),
(567, 7, 7, 64, 'eleven-becomes-an-official-holiday-in-new-jersey-1599947394', 'Eleven becomes an official holiday in New Jersey', 0, '<p><strong>Eleventh, the annual anniversary of the end of slavery in the United States, is now an official holiday in New Jersey. Governor Phil Murphy signs a bill on Thursday that specifies a day to be celebrated on the third Friday in June each year.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Juninist is a holiday commemorating June 19, 1865, when black slaves in Galveston, Texas were told they were free. That day comes nearly six months after Congress passed the 13th Amendment ending slavery.<br />\r\n&quot;Celebrating this date is only one component of our collective approach to ending a long-running generational cycle of suffering and injustice,&quot; Murphy said in a statement. &quot;Our eleventh will celebrate the end of the physical chains that once captured black Americans. While more work needs to be done to end the remaining oppression, Uninasti is a marker [key] reminiscent of our mission, one To create a society that makes black communities possible. we achieve the full equality they deserve. &quot;<br />\r\nMurphy posted a video on Twitter in which he signed the bill on Thursday accompanied by singer SZA who grew up in New Jersey. New Jersey legislators passed the law in July.<br />\r\n&quot;I am a direct descendant of slavery,&quot; said SZA at the signing. &quot;My immediate descendants, my great-grandmother, my great-grandmother, this is my family. I feel like this isn&#39;t even a blemish of the past, but the present reality that we are experiencing - post-traumatic slave syndrome and PTSD and its effects now.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Murphy told SZA that many states recognize eleven but few recognize them as holidays, &quot;when government officials actually don&#39;t go to work that day&quot;. The bill states that New Jersey vacation vacations are paid for government employees.</p>', 'Eleven, Official Holiday', 'Juneteenth_1599947394.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:49:54', '2021-08-16 02:33:18'),
(568, 7, 7, 80, 'trump-will-visit-california-on-monday-to-learn-more-about-wildfires-1599947439', 'Trump will visit California on Monday to learn more about wildfires', 0, '<p><strong>President Trump will travel to California on Monday to hear from local and federal fire and emergency officials about the recent fires that have engulfed the state.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>White House deputy spokesman Judd Deere said in a statement that Trump and California Governor Gavin Newsum spoke by telephone, adding that &quot;The White House and FEMA are in constant touch with governments and regions during the response. Officials stay. This natural disaster.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The president continues to support local, state and federal sponsored emergency forest fire fighting,&quot; Deer said.<br />\r\nTrump approved the Presidential Declaration on a Great Catastrophe for California in August. Deere said the government had also approved 10 grants for fire management and 24 grants for other western states affected by the fires, providing a federal share of 75% of the costs. More than 26,000 federal employees and 230 helicopters are stationed in the area to extinguish the flames.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump visited California after the country was hit by fires in 2018. The president clashed with Newsham Democrats about how best to fight wildfires.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At least 19 people have died in California, Washington and Oregon when historic fires swept through the west, burning millions of acres and evacuating thousands of people. An Oregon official said the state was preparing for &quot;mass deaths&quot; as the fires continued.</p>', 'Trump, California, Brifing', 'Trump for briefing_1599947439.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:50:39', '2021-08-15 12:18:57'),
(569, 7, 3, 83, 'toots-hibbert-a-popular-reggae-star-died-at-the-age-of-77-1599947494', 'Toots Hibbert, a popular reggae star, died at the age of 77', 0, '<p><strong>Toots Hibbert, reggae co-founder and most popular star who gave the music its name and later made it into an international movement through classics such as &quot;Pressure Drop&quot;, &quot;Monkey Man&quot; and &quot;Funky Kingston&quot;. He is 77 years old.</strong><br />\r\nToots &amp; the Maytals forward Hibbert has been in a medical coma at Kingston Hospital since the start of this month. According to her homework, she was admitted to the intensive care unit after complaining of difficulty breathing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Local media revealed that the singer was expecting a COVID-19 test result after showing symptoms.<br />\r\nNews of the deteriorating health of the five-time Grammy nominees comes just weeks after his last known live appearance during Jamaica&#39;s celebrations of emancipation and independence in August.<br />\r\nAccording to a family statement, Hibbert died Friday at the West India University Hospital in Kingston, Jamaica, surrounded by a family.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ziggy Marley, Bob Marley&#39;s son, tweeted about the death, saying he spoke with Hibbert a few weeks ago and &quot;told him how much I love him, laugh and respect each other,&quot; adding, &quot;He is a father figure. We are.&quot;<br />\r\nA former boxer of muscles, Hibbert is a band leader, songwriter, multi-instrumentalist and performer whose concerts sometimes end with dozens of people dancing with him on stage. According to many, he is also the greatest reggae singer, so spiritual that he was able to turn &quot;Do re mi fa so la ti do&quot; into the national anthem. His husky tenor, unusually warm and harsh, has been compared to Otis Redding&#39;s voice, making him more accessible to American audiences than many reggae players.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Original songs like &quot;Funky Kingston&quot; and &quot;54-46 This is My Number&quot; have emotions and arrangements for calls and answers that soul and gospel fans know. Hibbert even recorded the American hit album &quot;Toots In Memphis,&quot; which was released in 1988.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Never immersed in politics as his friend and contemporary of the great Bob Marley, Hibbert invoked heavenly justice in &quot;relieving pressure&quot;, preaching peace in &quot;revolution&quot;, justice in &quot;Bam Baam,&quot; and resenting drug arrests and closings. 1960. in &ldquo;54-46 This is my number. Almost unlike everyone else, he recorded everyday life in Jamaica in the years following his independence from Great Britain in 1962, regardless of whether he was worried about marriage (&quot;Sweet and Cool&quot;) or about paying the rent (&quot;Harsh Weather&quot; &quot;) speak. One of his most popular and surprising songs is the adaptation of John Denver&#39;s nostalgic Country Roads (Take Me Home), which transformed the West Virginia setting into the world that Hibbert is so familiar with.<br />\r\nLike other reggae stars, Hibbert&#39;s following increased following the release of the hit 1972 film Harder to Come, in which Jimmy Cliff emerged as a poor Jamaican who moved to Kingston and dreamed of a career in music. Jamaican productions are word of mouth in the US, and the soundtracks, often among the greatest in film history, include &quot;Pressure Drop&quot; and &quot;Sweet and Dandy&quot; by the Maytals. Hibbert also appears in the film as himself, recording &quot;Sweet and Dandy&quot; in the studio while Cliff&#39;s character watches in awe. Around the same time, the Maytals signed with Island Records and released the critically acclaimed album &quot;Funky Kingston,&quot; which critic Lester Bangs described as &quot;the most compelling and diverse set of reggae songs by a single artist ever released.&quot; (This album will later be released in two different versions).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By the mid-1970s Keith Richards, John Lennon, Eric Clapton, and many other rock stars had become fans of reggae, and Hibbert ended up recording with some of them. The 2004 tribute album, Grammy-winning True Love, included cameos by Richards, Bonnie Wright, Ryan Adams, and Jeff Beck. Hibbert has also been the subject of the 2011 BBC documentary Reggae Got Soul, with Clapton, Richards and Willie Nelson as commentators.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A visit to Saturday Night Live in 2004 brought Hibbert an unexpected admirer, guest host Donald Trump, who recalls hearing an example of a joke in his book, Think Like a Billionaire: &quot;My daughter, Ivanka, has told me how great you are and she is. right. The music relaxes me and surprisingly I wasn&#39;t nervous. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Maytals were originally a vocal trio with Hibbert, Henry &quot;Raleigh&quot; Gordon and Nathaniel &quot;Jerry&quot; Mathias, and the band later added instrumentalists such as bassist Jackie Jackson and drummer Paul Douglas. They split in the early 1980s, but over the next decade, Hibbert began working with the new cast from the Maytals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hibbert&#39;s career came to a halt in 2013 after suffering head injuries from a bottle of vodka tossed at a concert in Richmond, Virginia, suffering from headaches and depression. But at the end of the decade, he made a comeback and released another album in 2020, &quot;Got To Be Tough,&quot; featuring contributions from Ziggy Marley and Ringo Starr, whose son Zak Starkey was co-producer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hibbert Grammy nominations include Best Reggae Album 2012 for Reggae Got Soul and Best Reggae Album 2007 for Light Your Light. Hibbert was ranked 71st on Rolling Stone&#39;s list of the 100 Greatest Contemporary Singers in 2008. In 2012, the Jamaican government awarded him an Order of Merit award for his outstanding contribution to country music.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hibbert has been married to his wife Doreen for nearly 40 years and has eight children, including reggae actors Junior Hibbert and Leba Hibbert.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Frederick Nathaniel Hibbert (&quot;Toots&quot; is a childhood nickname) was born in May Pen, Clarendon Parish. He was the son of a Seventh Day Adventist pastor, and he remembers the very long journey down the dirt road to school, the hours singing in church, and the private moments of listening to American radio stars such as Ray Charles and Elvis Presley.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When he was young, his parents died and he moved to Trench Town in Kingston, where local music thrived. Moving from street parties to recording studios, he painted future stars like Bob Marley and Desmond Decker. He founded the Maytals, named after his hometown, with fellow singers Matthias and Gordon, began working with Jamaican producer Coxsone Dodd and quickly became the star of the national festival competitions starting in 1966.The Maytals (eventually renamed Toots &amp; the Maytals) won the year opening with &quot;Bam Bam&quot;, 1969 with &quot;Sweet and Dandy&quot; and 1972 with &quot;Pomp and Pride&quot;. Hibbert would joke that he thought it best to skip the festival as winning is so easy, despite returning in 2020 with bright and inspiring Rise Up Jamaica.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maytals began when ska was the most popular piece of music, soaring during the transition to deferred rock rock and at the forefront of a faster, more danceable sound in the late 60s. His scandalous chant &quot;Do the Reggay&quot; is widely recognized as the song that gave reggae its name, even if the honor was not intentional.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If a girl doesn&#39;t look so pretty or doesn&#39;t dress appropriately, we&#39;ll say she&#39;s lost. One day I was playing and I didn&#39;t know why, but I started singing, &#39;Do reggae, do reggay&#39; - keep it&quot;, he told the Stern newspaper. in 2012. &quot;Maybe I&#39;ll call it streggay if I think about it a little longer. It&#39;ll be something - everyone&#39;s dancing to Streggay&#39;s music.&quot; &quot;</p>', 'Toots Hibert, Died at 77', 'Tooth hibert_1599947494.jpg', '2020-09-13 01:51:34', '2021-08-14 05:28:12'),
(570, 7, 7, 80, 'oregon-firefighters-fled-the-state-amid-fire-damage-1599987468', 'Oregon firefighters fled the state amid fire damage', 0, '<p><strong>Oregon&#39;s top employee resigned Saturday as wildfires raged in other western states.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Marshall Jim Walker resigned as the Oregon state police chief after receiving paid administrative leave, News source&nbsp;reported. The reasons for Walker&#39;s departure have not been officially disclosed, but sources say State Police President Travis Hampton has lost faith in Walker&#39;s ability to deal with the state&#39;s bushfire crisis, OregonLive.com reported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Temple Deputy Chief Mariana Ruiz has been named the country&#39;s new fire department. Before Walker was released, he was effectively delegating work managing the state&#39;s wildfire response to Ruiz Temple, news sources said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Mariana leads with grace, transparency and courage,&quot; Governor Kate Brown said in a statement. &quot;It embodies the experience Oregon needs to deal with this crisis.&quot;<br />\r\nHampton also issued a statement in support of Ruiz Temple.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Mariana is in this position because Oregon is in an unprecedented crisis that needs an immediate response,&quot; he said, according to OregonLive.com.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These reactions and circumstances demand a change in leadership. I have absolute confidence in Mariana to lead the Office of the State Fire Marshal (OSFM) at this critical time. She has been tested, trusted, and respected - she has a rare combination of Technical Operations and Administration skills. &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nWildfires burned 1 million acres in Oregon last week, with the two largest occurring on the Portland, Marion County and Clackamas County subways.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oregon is one of seven western states that have received federal government assistance in managing forest fire damage. The others are California, Colorado, Montana, Utah, Washington, and Wyoming.</p>', 'Oregon, Firefighter', 'Oregon_1599987467.jpg', '2020-09-13 12:57:48', '2021-08-18 04:54:58');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(571, 7, 17, 159, 'trump-gathered-in-nevada-to-fight-for-votes-on-the-battlefield-in-key-states-1600406411', 'Trump gathered in Nevada to fight for votes on the battlefield in key states', 0, '<p><strong>President Trump rocked a rally in Nevada on Saturday night.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The bottom line is that if we win, America wins,&quot; the president told a crowd in Minden, about 50 miles south of Renault, as part of the pressure to turn Nevada red in November.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump immediately called Nevada Governor Steve Sisolak a &quot;political hack&quot; after arguing with a Democrat over a rally originally planned for a hangar at Renault Airport earlier this week. The Trump 2020 campaign had to be scrapped as the governor limited outdoor gatherings of 50 people under the coronavirus.<br />\r\nThe demonstration was moved to a hangar at Minden Airport near Lake Tahoe.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Republicans in the state accused the governor of influencing Trump&#39;s chances of re-election, but the Renault rally was canceled by airport officials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;These are people we trust with millions of ballots, unsolicited ballots, and we have to win over these countries. Who will believe it?&quot; will. However, the US Postal Service and government officials say it is safe to vote by mail.<br />\r\nAs part of an ongoing campaign against postal voting, supporters of the presidential campaign are asking federal judges in Las Vegas to block state law and prevent fewer than eight postal ballots from being sent to all active Nevada voters. A few weeks before the election.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It never happened&quot;<br />\r\nTrump told the audience he was deeply offended by Joe Biden over an ad the Democratic candidate made for a magazine story. Trump called the soldiers killed &quot;gunfire&quot; and &quot;losers.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Nobody loves our military and respects it more than I do. There are 25 witnesses on file who say that never happened,&quot; Trump told previous and current officials defending his character.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump called Biden a &quot;poor man&quot; for running the ad. &quot;You&#39;re embarrassing, but you know the good part, now I can be really bad.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that because of the ad, he felt he no longer needed to be &quot;good&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Joe Biden can&#39;t rule our country because he doesn&#39;t really trust our country,&quot; he said. &quot;He is the worst candidate in the history of presidential politics.&quot;<br />\r\nTrump said the Democratic candidate, California Senator Kamala Harris, would become president &quot;in about a month&quot; if Biden won, claiming that the former vice president would be a figure and that Harris would retain power.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He claimed the media would treat Biden &quot;like Winston Churchill&quot; if he could be in the debate phase on September 29. slower itinerary.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Do you know where he is now?&quot; He&#39;s back in his basement! &quot;<br />\r\nThe president reiterated that if Biden is elected president, he will move the suburbs from his home by allowing Antifa to move. &quot;Don&#39;t let them ruin the suburbs!&quot; he told the crowd.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said Democrats wanted to allow churches to burn while agitators left rioting on the streets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Biden&#39;s plan is to appease domestic terrorists and mine is to catch domestic terrorists,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://a57.foxnews.com/static.foxnews.com/foxnews.com/content/uploads/2020/09/1862/1048/AP20257101173361.jpg?ve=1&amp;tl=1\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;This is a leftist madman Biden who wants to serve his government,&quot; he told the rebels.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said that unlike Biden, he would always support &quot;law enforcement heroes&quot;. Trump did not mention a single case of alleged police brutality that sparked protests across the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also suggested that the &quot;sham&quot; poll showing he failed in Biden was an attempt to pressure voters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;My people are not oppressed!&quot; He said to the crowd who was comforted.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He told the crowd that they had to be interviewed in November. &quot;It would be very difficult to fool you people watching the vote,&quot; he laughed, adding that Democrats would still find ways to cheat.<br />\r\nWhen Trump listed a list of candidates for Supreme Court judges, including Sensan Ted Cruz and Tom Cotton, he assured Biden he would appoint a &quot;radical leftist maniac&quot; to court.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said he would go to California on Monday and say all the heart for those affected by the wildfires, but added that the key to keeping the fires alive was &quot;forest management.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The President also expressed his concern about wind energy and windmills when talking about renewable energy. He said they were killing birds, rotting too fast, and jokes about electricity being powered by windmills wouldn&#39;t work unless it was windy. He added that he likes solar energy but said it is too expensive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump said the country was &quot;catching&quot; the coronavirus that has killed more than 190,000 Americans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If Sleepy Joe and Obama, you won&#39;t get the vaccine for three years,&quot; he said. He suggested that a vaccine could be ready before the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, Fauci disagreed last week that the pandemic was almost over, saying Americans should &quot;sit back&quot; in the fall and winter when flu season could make fighting the pandemic even more difficult.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump cited polls showing he was working better with the Spaniards, which would be key to victory in Nevada.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cf-images.us-east-1.prod.boltdns.net/v1/static/694940094001/fa7befa4-4312-43f9-a258-2a5dffacda5a/2248e8e7-2896-4c4f-aa65-670110241611/1280x720/match/image.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Several thousand people covered the tarmac in Minden, including 64-year-old Tom Lenz from Sparks, Nevada, who said he didn&#39;t vote for Trump last time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;But I&#39;ll do it this time.&quot; I think he knows what he&#39;s doing, &quot;said Lenz.&quot; He is for faith, for life, he has made more peace in the world. Biden couldn&#39;t even speak. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump said &quot;Joe Biden has been on the wrong side of history for 47 years,&quot; citing Biden&#39;s voice on the Iraq war in 2003 and the success of his own administration against ISIS.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said Biden would undermine social security and protection for existing conditions. (The existing requirements are covered by ObamaCare.) He added that Biden plans to provide medical care to &quot;illegal aliens&quot; and overturn the school decision.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Don&#39;t ever forget that they were after me because I fought for you!&quot; He told the crowd, adding that in his second term he would make America the world leader in manufacturing, restore jobs, hire police, ban protected cities and appoint Conservative judges. &quot;We want law and order. We must have it!&quot; he says.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We will uphold freedom of religion, freedom of expression and the right to store and carry weapons,&quot; he said, adding that he would lead troops home and end &quot;endless wars&quot; and put women first on the moon.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said his government would teach children to always respect the American flag.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;For years you have a president who apologizes for America, now you have a president who defends or America,&quot; he said, alerting the crowd to vote on November 3. &quot;Together we will return to our country.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The president lost six Nevada election votes to Hillary Clinton in 2016 by 2 percentage points, but the campaign is investing heavily in the state to change the outcome of that round.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nevada has not elected a Republican president since 2004.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Democrats are scared. They know President Trump has momentum,&quot; said GOP President Michael MacDonald.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some Democrats are concerned about Trump&#39;s possible achievement in Nevada. The president is showing growing support from well-educated Latins and white voters, the two main constituencies in the state.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The president plans to host a Latin round table for Trump in Las Vegas on Sunday morning, followed by an evening rally at a manufacturing facility near Henderson.<br />\r\nTrump is also planning a fundraiser in Las Vegas that weekend asking couples to put in $ 150,000.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The President will visit Arizona on Sunday and California on Monday.</p>', 'Donald Trump, Nevade to fight', 'Trump_1600005035.jpg', '2020-09-13 17:50:35', '2021-12-19 17:34:57'),
(572, 7, 12, 113, 'a-summons-from-the-chairman-of-the-dhs-democrats-will-emerge-from-the-chamber-at-the-trial-1600005311', 'A summons from the chairman of the DHS Democrats will emerge from the Chamber at the trial', 0, '<p><strong>Democrats on the Parliament&#39;s Homeland Security Committee asked Chad Wolfe to testify about threats to the nation, a request that Wolf made &quot;very disappointed,&quot; he said.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Benny Thompson summoned the Acting Secretary of State for Homeland Security on September 17 for an audience. The commission said Wolf had renounced his commitment to appear on September 8.<br />\r\n&quot;Nineteen years after the 9/11 attacks, we continue to face serious threats to our homeland.&quot; From the coronavirus pandemic to the rise of right-wing extremism to ongoing election disruptions, there are pressing threats that require our attention, &quot;Thompson said in a statement:&quot; Mr. Wolf&#39;s refusal to testify - and thus evade Congressional scrutiny at this critical moment - is overwhelming. worrying given the serious problems facing the ministry and the nation. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wolf stepped back and told a special report late Friday that he was &quot;deeply disappointed&quot; by the move. He agreed to testify twice about threats and global unrest in Portland in August. Since then, President Trump has officially nominated him for the role he currently holds as an actor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;ve been nominated since then and it&#39;s been a long time practice not to testify on any other subject while you run,&quot; he told host Brett Bayer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said DHS had advised Assistant Secretary Ken Cuchinili to testify on his behalf, and that &quot;I am pleased to testify before the committee after my verification process has gone one way or another.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;So we are very friendly with the commission and unfortunately it happened,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, Intelligence Commission Chairman Adam Schiff announced that the commission was considering complaints about DHS and intelligence reports that interfered in the Russian elections.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have received an irregularity complaint alleging that DHS suppressed reports of Intel interference in the Russian elections, altered information to reflect Trump&#39;s false accusations, and made false statements to Congress.&quot; Wednesday afternoon in Schiff, California. &quot;This endangers our national security.&quot;<br />\r\nHe added, &quot;We will investigate.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wolfe called the complaint &quot;utterly bogus&quot; and &quot;fabricated&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;We are very clear about Russian interference in our elections ...&quot; Wolf said in a special report. &quot;We have produced more than 27 different reports in the last 12 months, I think only three in August. We have given more than 40 different briefs, private briefs to members of Congress ... about Russian interference in our elections. I have had appearing in the media about it. I talked about it in the Congressional Testimony, and I&#39;m even talking about it in my country this week about national security.</p>', 'Summons, DHS Democrats, Chamber Trial', 'DHS_1600005311.jpg', '2020-09-13 17:55:11', '2021-08-12 20:57:41'),
(573, 7, 12, 101, 'boeing-contractors-maintained-safety-solutions-in-the-development-of-the-737-max-1600005579', 'Boeing contractors maintained safety solutions in the development of the 737 MAX', 0, '<p><strong>Two high-ranking Boeing Co executives who led the development of the 737 MAX defended the company&#39;s decision regarding a critical cockpit system that was later linked to two fatal accidents. These are the results of a statement by Congress that was reviewed by Reuters.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Michael Teal, then chief product engineer of the 737 MAX, and Keith Leverkun, vice president and general manager of the 737 MAX program, were interviewed separately by investigators on the US Transportation and Infrastructure Committee in May.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t think the aircraft development was a failure,&quot; Leverkusen told investigators about the Panel House, which will publish the final report on its investigation into the development of the aircraft, which was set up in March 2019 after the deaths of 346 people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leverkusen defended the decision to hook a new MAX safety system called MCAS to a single sensor involved in both fatal accidents. Since then, Boeing has agreed to use data from two separate sensors when the aircraft returns to service, which could come later this year.<br />\r\n&quot;In my opinion, based on our understanding and assumptions about the flight crew&#39;s actions, it is not a mistake,&quot; said Leverkusen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Leverkusen later testified: &quot;It is clear that our assumptions about human-machine interactions were wrong. Because the process is based on industry standards for the pilot reaction to certain errors. And what became clear after the incident was that the assumption was wrong.&quot;<br />\r\nCongressional investigators also question evidence that Boeing never conducted an internal financial analysis to determine whether the Federal Aviation Administration would require more expensive simulator training.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Teal said if the 737 MAX design warranted simulator training, Boeing would build it, realizing that customers might be disappointed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Would airlines be happy with that, of course not,&quot; he said, noting that Boeing had signaled over the years that simulator training was unnecessary.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last year, Boeing confirmed that it had agreed to pay Southwest Airlines Co. $ 1 million for a MAX discount if training is required. In January, Boeing reversed course, saying it would recommend simulated training to all pilots before the MAX returns to service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Teal, now chief engineer on the 777X project, said the plane manufacturer had revised some of the pilot&#39;s assumptions after the 737 MAX crashed. &quot;This is the exercise we are now offering for the new aircraft,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boeing did not immediately respond to a request for comment. The Wall Street Journal, which previously covered the transcript, said Leverkusen retired earlier this year, as long planned, and cited a Boeing spokesman.</p>', 'Boeing Contractors, 737 Max', 'Boeing_1600005579.jpg', '2020-09-13 17:59:39', '2021-08-17 23:38:48'),
(574, 7, 12, 89, 'the-new-investor-finds-out-that-stocks-are-falling-too-1600009565', 'The new investor finds out that stocks are falling too', 0, '<p><strong>New wave investors have suffered heavy losses in recent days and received tough lessons about how the stock market works.</strong><br />\r\nTech stocks fell during the three-day trading period ended Tuesday by the largest margin of nearly six months, wiping out thousands of dollars from individual investors&#39; portfolios.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some new investors have taken the option of making big bets that tech stocks will continue to rise unchecked and be destroyed. Others who have joined this stock in the last few months were able to squeeze out the recent gains. Meanwhile, investors who jumped into the market in March and gambled in safety saw the simple haircut on their wallets.<br />\r\nThis painful trading period is a warning to some of the newest traders that stocks aren&#39;t just going up. They also fall, and sometimes for no apparent reason.<br />\r\n&quot;The market is an emotional amusement park,&quot; said Temitayo Ola, 31, who lives in Los Angeles. Mr. Ola has been handling stock trading intensively in March.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As someone new to the stock market, I didn&#39;t know there might be a period when you make such a withdrawal,&quot; he said. Wall Street financial managers and analysts said the withdrawal did not appear to be due to the fact that stocks ran out at short notice. Even though the losses pushed the Tech Nasdaq Composite into a correction on Tuesday - a drop of 10% or more from its recent high - such an event is considered a fair market, especially if many technical stocks remain multiplying for the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Investors who bought some of the biggest tech stocks in March are still seeing consistent returns that boost their investment portfolios. Including recent losses, shares of Apple Inc. rose more than 60% in the last six months. Facebook Inc. shares 50% higher, while Microsoft Corp. more than 30% advanced. And shares of Tesla Inc. nearly tripled in that time.</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:600px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>Ticker</th>\r\n			<th>Security</th>\r\n			<th>Last</th>\r\n			<th>Change</th>\r\n			<th>Change %</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=AAPL\" rel=\"nofollow\">AAPL</a></td>\r\n			<td>APPLE INC.</td>\r\n			<td>112.00</td>\r\n			<td>-1.49</td>\r\n			<td>-1.31%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=FB\" rel=\"nofollow\">FB</a></td>\r\n			<td>FACEBOOK INC.</td>\r\n			<td>266.61</td>\r\n			<td>-1.48</td>\r\n			<td>-0.55%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=MSFT\" rel=\"nofollow\">MSFT</a></td>\r\n			<td>MICROSOFT CORP.</td>\r\n			<td>204.03</td>\r\n			<td>-1.34</td>\r\n			<td>-0.65%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=TSLA\" rel=\"nofollow\">TSLA</a></td>\r\n			<td>TESLA INC.</td>\r\n			<td>372.72</td>\r\n			<td>+1.38</td>\r\n			<td>+0.37%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Ola is not alone. Millions of investors have surged the public this year, using apps on their smartphones to trade stocks like never before. Investors opened new accounts at record levels this year using newer trading applications such as Robinhood Markets Inc. and work with more traditional brokerage firms such as Charles Schwab Corp. sink. and TD Ameritrade Holding Corp.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trading volume grows as customers buy and sell stocks at a crazy rate. Several brokers reported increased activity, coinciding with the biggest decline in the stock market in months.<br />\r\nTrading activity in the Vanguard Group brokerage activity last week was higher than usual, said Charles Kurz, a company spokesman. Merrill Edge, the self-managed brokerage of Bank of America Corp, noted that trading activity had tripled since nearly March last year, to a total of nearly three million accounts, said Matthew Card, a spokesman for Bank of America.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Card added that customers have access to bank investment and educational content 25 times faster than in 2019, indicating that many are still learning the ropes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The influx of individual investors has contributed to the strong recovery in the stock market since the start of this year. The S&amp;P 500 index is up nearly 50% from the lowest level in March. However, the rally led some recent entrants to believe that most stocks are moving in one direction - a mistake that has proven to be detrimental.</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:600px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>Ticker</th>\r\n			<th>Security</th>\r\n			<th>Last</th>\r\n			<th>Change</th>\r\n			<th>Change %</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=SPX\" rel=\"nofollow\">SPX</a></td>\r\n			<td>n.a.</td>\r\n			<td>n.a.</td>\r\n			<td>n.a.</td>\r\n			<td>n.a.</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>PRODUCT PLAN AFTER SNOW TESLA FROM S&amp;P 500</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was up before last week,&quot; said Ola, a video producer, who said he had been doubling his money since launching in March.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Ola said he only lost $ 10,000 in call options for DocuSign Inc. - basically a bet that wins when the stock price goes up. and Rocket Cos. He has another contract for Apple that he will likely lose too.</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:600px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>Ticker</th>\r\n			<th>Security</th>\r\n			<th>Last</th>\r\n			<th>Change</th>\r\n			<th>Change %</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=DOCU\" rel=\"nofollow\">DOCU</a></td>\r\n			<td>DOCUSIGN</td>\r\n			<td>197.94</td>\r\n			<td>-8.01</td>\r\n			<td>-3.89%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=RKT\" rel=\"nofollow\">RKT</a></td>\r\n			<td>ROCKET COMPANIES INC.</td>\r\n			<td>22.75</td>\r\n			<td>-0.40</td>\r\n			<td>-1.73%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>Options trading is very stable as investors seek to increase their profits by betting on whether the stock price will go up or down. Average daily activity in options trading hit a record 28 million contracts last month, a significant increase over the previous year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;People trade options to make more money, but I prefer L more,&quot; Ola said, referring to the disadvantages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the same time, most of its stock portfolio, which consists of technology stocks such as Apple, Tesla and Microsoft, fell sharply. Each of these shares gave up a portion of their recent gains on Tuesday - no more than Tesla, which hit its biggest record.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;If you&#39;ve been seeing this emerging market boom since March lows, you thought that investing was very easy and it wasn&#39;t,&quot; said Steve Sosnik, chief strategy officer at Interactive Brokers.<br />\r\nMOTOR NIKOLA LAWYER AGAINST THE &quot;FAKE AND DEEPER&quot; CLAIM</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The technology name Megacap has proven popular with investors trading stocks and options, said Sosnik.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think there should be a lot of people who are a little bit surprised by how bad your ROI is,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Sosnick said demand for equity options for Apple and Tesla recently outpaced bearish sell options, suggesting investors are more concerned about a lack of profits than about hedging against losses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some investors weren&#39;t surprised by the setback and saw it as an opportunity to buy stocks that they missed earlier in the year. Tyler Snyder, a 21-year-old HVAC engineer in Kitchener, Ontario, took part of the loss and bought a stake in International Business Machines Corp. Last Friday after the company&#39;s shares fell nearly 5% in two trading days.</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:600px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>Ticker</th>\r\n			<th>Security</th>\r\n			<th>Last</th>\r\n			<th>Change</th>\r\n			<th>Change %</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=IBM\" rel=\"nofollow\">IBM</a></td>\r\n			<td>INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS MACHINES CORP.</td>\r\n			<td>121.46</td>\r\n			<td>+0.90</td>\r\n			<td>+0.75%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>SPECIFIC SALES MODULATION SUPPORTS MARKET RISK DURING CORONAVIRUS TURBULENCE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I felt like a kid in a candy shop,&quot; said Snyder. &quot;The market is what you get by with it. A lot of fear that money will be shaken up now.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the weather couldn&#39;t have been worse for some investors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Farhoud Moaddel, 50, who lives in London, watched Tesla share a higher rocket over the summer before joining the action. He said his fianc&eacute; made a lot of money selling shares. The company&#39;s shares appear unstoppable and have more than quadrupled since December.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I just came in and the music stopped,&quot; said Mr. Moadel. Your Tesla stock has lost up to $ 20,000 in value since you bought it, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Moaddel, who is self-employed, sees parallels with the poor investment decision he made: he sold 400 shares to Amazon.com Inc. at a loss during the 2008 financial crisis. Mr Moaddel now doubts whether he owns the Tesla stock or deducts the loss.</p>\r\n\r\n<table border=\"1\" style=\"width:500px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>Ticker</th>\r\n			<th>Security</th>\r\n			<th>Last</th>\r\n			<th>Change</th>\r\n			<th>Change %</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=AMZN\" rel=\"nofollow\">AMZN</a></td>\r\n			<td>AMAZON.COM INC.</td>\r\n			<td>3,116.22</td>\r\n			<td>-58.89</td>\r\n			<td>-1.85%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t know if it will slide any further,&quot; he said. &quot;I have to see what happens, but it will be very painful.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition to his investment in Tesla, Mr. Moaddel also bought stakes in several other technology companies. The stocks fell too - and the weather was far from perfect for the pair.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We want to get married and we can handle every pound,&quot; he said.</p>', 'New Investor, Stock Falling', 'New Investor_1600009565.jpg', '2020-09-13 19:06:05', '2021-08-12 00:11:58'),
(575, 7, 6, 91, 'the-budget-deficit-reached-200-billion-in-august-as-projections-for-2020-have-not-been-available-since-world-war-ii-1600009742', 'The budget deficit reached $ 200 billion in August, as projections for 2020 have not been available since World War II.', 0, '<p>The US budget deficit hit $ 200 billion in August as the country continues to battle the coronavirus pandemic, and experts warn it could reach levels not seen since World War II later in the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the Ministry of Finance&#39;s monthly report, an additional $ 200 billion in August resulted in a cumulative fiscal year deficit of about $ 3 trillion.<br />\r\nThe Congressional Budget Agency estimates the federal deficit could reach $ 3.3 trillion this year, the highest level since 1945.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The estimate corresponds to 16% of gross domestic product and the largest deficit since World War Two.<br />\r\nMost of the reported spending was due to increased government spending related to economic aid legislation during the pandemic, which includes small business loans and direct payments to US households.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, the White House faces Democrat leadership at the expense of the possibility of an additional stimulus package. Last week, White House Chief of Staff Mark Meadows said the president was ready to sign a $ 1.3 trillion bill, but White House President Nancy Pelosi said she wanted something closer to 2.2 trillion. Dollar.</p>', 'Budget Deficit, US', 'Budget Deficit_1600009742.jpg', '2020-09-13 19:09:02', '2021-08-17 16:20:10'),
(576, 7, 6, 121, 'nyse-president-says-return-to-wall-street-office-is-important-to-us-economy-1600010049', 'NYSE President Says Return to Wall Street Office is \"Important\" to US Economy', 0, '<p><strong>Stacy Cunningham, President of the New York Stock Exchange, stressed the importance of Wall Street employees returning to office after months of virtual work, calling it &quot;critical&quot; for the US economy&#39;s recovery from the coronavirus pandemic.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s very important that people come back to the office to support the economy,&quot; Cunningham give interview to news channel.<br />\r\nJPMORGAN LOOKS AT EMPLOYEES ABOUT POSSIBLE INCENTIVE FRAUDS AGAINST CORONAVIRUS</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In mid-March, the NYSE joined a number of other New York companies that temporarily closed their retail space for e-commerce after two people tested positive for COVID-19. Back then, the decision, Cunningham said, was to choose between &quot;security and livelihood.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The exchange reopened on May 26.<br />\r\nTrump praised JPMORGAN for telling retail workers to return to the office</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We don&#39;t have to do this now,&quot; said Cunningham. &quot;We know how to protect people. By wearing masks and social distancing, we can separate people and be safe.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Their comments came as Goldman Sachs, JPMorgan and Chase announced plans to bring employees back into the office in the coming weeks.</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:600px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>Ticker</th>\r\n			<th>Security</th>\r\n			<th>Last</th>\r\n			<th>Change</th>\r\n			<th>Change %</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=GS\">GS</a></td>\r\n			<td>GOLDMAN SACHS GROUP INC.</td>\r\n			<td>200.92</td>\r\n			<td>+0.91</td>\r\n			<td>+0.46%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=JPM\">JPM</a></td>\r\n			<td>JP MORGAN CHASE &amp; CO.</td>\r\n			<td>101.07</td>\r\n			<td>+1.24</td>\r\n			<td>+1.24%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>In a note sent Wednesday by Goldman CEO David Solomon, the bank told its employees it was prepared to see more employees returning to their offices around the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GOLDMAN SACHS JOINS WITH JPMORGAN IN ANNOUNCEMENT OF RETURN TO THE OFFICE AFTER THE CLOSURE OF THE CORONAVIRUS OFFICE</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In the coming days and weeks, colleagues in this office will hear from senior management, business and / or local authorities what to expect in the coming months, including rotating teams in the office where possible to help everyone.&quot; Who could make this happen. chance to enter their office? &quot;said the note.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Goldman said it would accurately manage the number of workers in each building every day and would continue to adhere to health and safety protocols and community guidelines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>JPMorgan announced to employees this week that they will be calling its best sales force back to the office after months of remote work, a source with knowledge of the matter told FOXBusiness. The bank is advising senior sales and trade officials in London and New York that they and their teams must return to office by September 21.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We need to focus on city safety and restore confidence in the city so people can return to office,&quot; said Cunningham. &quot;Because in that way we will help the economy recover. We don&#39;t have to choose between lockdown [and security].&quot;</p>', 'NYSE President, US Economy', 'NYSE_1600010049.jpg', '2020-09-13 19:14:09', '2021-09-23 08:13:28'),
(577, 7, 6, 161, 'american-express-is-extending-its-homework-policy-through-june-2021-1600011025', 'American Express is extending its homework policy through June 2021.', 0, '<p><strong>American Express expands its domestic policy work through June 2021 to provide additional flexibility to its entire global workforce during the coronavirus pandemic.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We are taking this step to offer colleagues more flexibility in balancing work and family, especially since many of you have to plan for an uncertain academic year which may include distance learning or an older relative who cares for them. You are depending on you on public transport to get to work and you may not be comfortable using public transportation at this time, &quot;Stephen Square, chairman and CEO, said in a statement.<br />\r\nNoting that workers across America have concerns about returning to the office, Squery added, &quot;I hope this news provides you with security as you take care of yourself and your loved ones.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even though it has been announced, the expansion policy will not affect the plan to leave the financial services company.<br />\r\nAmerican Express restarted gradually this week at its offices in New York and London. About 10% of employees decide to return to the first phase. In addition, to date, the company has started to phase out its nearly 30 branches worldwide. The majority occur in Europe and Asia, where the rate of coronavirus infection remains consistently low.</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:600px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>Ticker</th>\r\n			<th>Security</th>\r\n			<th>Last</th>\r\n			<th>Change</th>\r\n			<th>Change %</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=AXP\">AXP</a></td>\r\n			<td>AMERICAN EXPRESS COMPANY</td>\r\n			<td>103.36</td>\r\n			<td>+0.59</td>\r\n			<td>+0.57%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As we continue to open more offices for more colleagues, you can choose to return to work or continue working from home by June 30, 2021, unless local authorities require you to work in an office or you do your work from home with the same efficiency. , &quot;added Squery.&quot; I want to thank you again for your focus and resilience over the past few months. I believe we will continue to be productive and will support us and our customers in the future. &quot;<br />\r\nAmerican Express joins a growing list of companies that have expanded their consumer policies in the face of the ongoing pandemic.<br />\r\nBoth Google and Uber have announced that they will be extending their voluntary home work guidelines until at least next summer, while companies such as Slack, Twitter and Facebook have adopted permanent homework policies. In July, Ford also announced that it would offer paid employees in the US the option to work from home at least until the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>JPMorgan Chase, meanwhile, takes the opposite approach: According to a report in the Wall Street Journal, the bank&#39;s top managers are asking retail employees to stay in the office until September 21.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>American Express posted an 85% drop in profit in the second quarter as the coronavirus pandemic cut customer spending. The New York-based financial services company earned $ 257 million, or 29 cents per share, as revenue fell 29 percent to $ 7.68 billion.</p>', 'American Express, Policy', 'Work from home policy_1600011025.jpg', '2020-09-13 19:30:25', '2021-09-23 08:17:27'),
(578, 7, 6, 146, 'deployment-of-the-coronavirus-vaccine-will-require-8000-cargo-planes-iata-1600011195', 'Deployment of the coronavirus vaccine will require 8,000 cargo planes: IATA', 0, '<p><strong>The International Air Transport Association warned governments around the world that the air transport industry may face severe capacity constraints that could prevent the timely spread of a COVID-19 vaccine.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Safe delivery of the COVID-19 vaccine will be the mission of this century for the global air cargo industry. However, it will not be done without careful prior planning. And now is the time to do so,&quot; said IATA CEO and CEO Alexander de Juniac in a statement. . . &quot;We call on the government to take the lead in facilitating cooperation in the supply chain so that facilities, security mechanisms and border processes are ready for the daunting and complex task ahead.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The trading group determined that it would take 8,000 Boeing 747 cargo planes to deliver a single dose to 7.8 billion people.<br />\r\nJETBLUE added 24 new non-stop routes</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To ensure that vaccines are serviced and transported on time, IATA emphasizes the importance of having reliable temperature control facilities, trained personnel and monitoring functions.<br />\r\nThe organization also noted that the vaccine would be a &quot;very valuable item&quot; requiring early action to ensure that shipments were protected from possible counterfeiting or theft.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition, IATA is calling on the government to immediately implement procedures for the transport of cross-border air cargo carrying the COVID-19 vaccine, including releasing crew members for quarantine, lifting curfews and prioritizing deliveries upon arrival. Avoid possible temperature deviations due to delays and free tariffs.<br />\r\nThe warning comes as air cargo capacity has been badly affected by the pandemic as airlines reduce their network and long-term aircraft storage due to lower demand.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Even assuming half of the vaccine needs can be shipped by land, the air transport industry will still face the biggest challenge,&quot; added de Juniac. &quot;In planning their vaccination programs, especially in developing countries around the world, governments should consider carefully the limited air cargo capacity that is currently limited. If borders remain closed, travel is shortened, fleets are grounded and personnel evacuated, capacity life-saving vaccine deliveries will be severely affected. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are more than 27.9 million confirmed coronavirus cases and more than 905,000 deaths worldwide, according to Johns Hopkins University. The United States is responsible for more than 6.3 million of these cases and more than 191,000 of these deaths.</p>', 'Coronavirus, Vaccine, Cargo', 'Cargo vaccine_1600011195.jpg', '2020-09-13 19:33:15', '2021-08-18 05:26:41'),
(579, 7, 6, 122, 'new-york-ceos-call-on-de-blasio-for-crackdown-on-crime-quality-of-life-issues-1600011728', 'New York CEOs call on de Blasio for crackdown on crime, quality of life issues', 0, '<p>New York business leaders in various industries have issued letters urging Mayor Bill de Blasio to take action against &quot;other public safety and quality of life issues that threaten economic recovery.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Regardless of New York&#39;s success in fighting the coronavirus, the number of New Yorkers who are unemployed, homeless or at other risk is unprecedented,&quot; the letter said. &quot;There are widespread concerns about public safety, hygiene and other quality of life issues contributing to worsening conditions in shopping areas and neighborhoods in five regions.&quot; Returning to a safe and healthy work environment, our employees, customers, customers and visitors will urge de Blasio to take immediate action to &quot;restore basic services as a necessary precursor to addressing the city&#39;s long-term, complex and economic challenges.&quot; &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Business leaders also warned the twice mayor that &quot;people will return slowly if their concerns about the safety and vitality of our community are not dealt with swiftly and with respect and justice to the city&#39;s diverse population.&quot;<br />\r\nThe effort is being organized by the New York Partnership, a group of companies whose members employ more than 1.5 million New Yorkers. The letter was signed by more than 160 company executives including Bank of America, Macy&#39;s, Citigroup, Lyft and Jet Blue.<br />\r\n&quot;We look forward to your response and partnerships with you and others working together for lively recreation and a bright future for our city&quot;, concluded company managers.<br />\r\nBill Neidhard, a spokesman for the mayor, told News channel that the city &quot;is grateful for the contributions of business and that we will continue to work with them to rebuild a fairer and better city.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Democratic mayor&#39;s government, said Neidhard, wants &quot;to restore these services and keep jobs, and the most direct way to do this is through long-term loans and federal incentives.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the stagnant legislator in Congress, Neidhardt added: &quot;We ask these leaders to join in this fight because the stakes cannot be higher.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the New York Police Department, there were 242 shooting incidents throughout the city in August, 166% more than last year and 87% more on August 31st. Meanwhile, homicides were up 34 percent and thefts were up 22 percent in August. On Labor Day weekend alone, the NYPD announced that 160 people had been arrested after 23 shootings.</p>\r\n\r\n<table style=\"width:600px\">\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>Ticker</th>\r\n			<th>Security</th>\r\n			<th>Last</th>\r\n			<th>Change</th>\r\n			<th>Change %</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=BAC\">BAC</a></td>\r\n			<td>BANK OF AMERICA CORP.</td>\r\n			<td>25.50</td>\r\n			<td>+0.36</td>\r\n			<td>+1.43%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=M\">M</a></td>\r\n			<td>MACY&#39;S INC.</td>\r\n			<td>7.05</td>\r\n			<td>-0.35</td>\r\n			<td>-4.73%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=C\">C</a></td>\r\n			<td>CITIGROUP INC.</td>\r\n			<td>51.00</td>\r\n			<td>+0.05</td>\r\n			<td>+0.10%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=LYFT\">LYFT</a></td>\r\n			<td>LYFT INC.</td>\r\n			<td>30.76</td>\r\n			<td>+1.25</td>\r\n			<td>+4.24%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<td><a href=\"https://www.foxbusiness.com/quote?stockTicker=JBLU\">JBLU</a></td>\r\n			<td>JETBLUE AIRWAYS</td>\r\n			<td>12.34</td>\r\n			<td>+0.09</td>\r\n			<td>+0.73%</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n\r\n<p>The New York City Council voted in July to cut $ 1 billion from the New York budget to target programs to support youth and community development. The New York Post reports that budget cuts in the city have also reduced the amount of weekly garbage collection, causing spills on city streets, and a growing number of homeless places in the city.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, a partnership study in New York found that less than 10% of city workers have returned to their workplaces and offices since the last month, and only a quarter of large employers expect to be able to return their workers by the end of the year. .</p>', 'New York, Crackdown', 'newyork ceo_1600011728.jpg', '2020-09-13 19:42:08', '2021-08-15 19:23:23'),
(580, 7, 2, 124, 'louis-vuitton-announces-the-return-of-physical-shows-in-china-1600016579', 'Louis Vuitton announces the return of physical shows - in China', 0, '<p><strong>When Dior, Herm&egrave;s, and other French luxury giants presented their Spring-Summer 2021 collection online last week at Paris Men&#39;s Fashion Week, Louis Vuitton was known for his absence.</strong><br />\r\nInstead of dealing with virtual storefronts, the label released a mysterious short video, &quot;Zoooom With Friends,&quot; in which a team of cartoon mascots load a crate of a ship sailing on the Seine.<br />\r\nThis shipment has literally and metaphorically arrived in Shanghai.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200807135753-07-louis-vuitton-ss21.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nOn Thursday, Louis Vuitton presents a spectacular menswear collection for spring-summer 2021 entitled &quot;Message in a Bottle&quot; by the Huangpu River. Although travel restrictions prevented menswear art director Virgil Ablo from being there in person, his eclectic DNA is imprinted throughout the collection, which comes in the stream of formal wear, followed by animal-themed streetwear and vibrant colors.<br />\r\nLauryn Hill is broadcast in a branded virtual platform that is broadcast live on Instagram and the Louis Vuitton website. Otherwise, it&#39;s a very physical show - on a scale rarely seen around the world when the coronavirus pandemic begins to disrupt the global fashion calendar in February.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200807091846-01-louis-vuitton-ss21.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe face mask is barely visible. The crowd sat side by side and spread Louis Vuitton in the heat of the night. And while security measures were put in place, including temperature checks and paperless tickets, the show returned to normal, said the creative consultant present and former Elle China editor Ye Zi (aka Leaf Greener).<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s like we are returning to our new normal way of life,&quot; he said in a telephone interview.<br />\r\nHe finished again<br />\r\nThe decision to avoid Paris for Shanghai was of course practical. Physical fashion shows are not strictly a question in Europe (Jacquemus, for example, is showing off his new collection in a wheat field outside Paris), but social distancing requirements have made traditional storefronts nearly impossible.<br />\r\nHowever, many restrictions have been relaxed in China and several live events are taking place. On the day of the Louis Vuitton show, Shanghai reported only seven new cases of Covid-19, none of which were broadcast locally, according to Chinese state media.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200807134938-06-louis-vuitton-ss21.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nBy placing storefronts in China, the label also conveys a clear message about the importance of restoring the country&#39;s luxury market to its business model.<br />\r\nThe parent company LVMH, which also includes brands such as Christian Dior, Celine, Fendi, and Givenchy, saw a 46% drop in fashion and leather goods profits in the first half of 2020. The accompanying press release, while optimistic, noted &quot;an improvement. gradually&quot;. from May in Europe and the US &quot;its assessment of the Chinese market was much higher. The conglomerate stated that they had experienced&quot; strong gains &quot;in China in the second quarter of this year.<br />\r\nWhether Louis Vuitton&#39;s rivals will emerge in Asia in the coming season - or whether Abloh will return to more familiar territory once the pandemic has subsided - remains to be seen. But as major European fashion houses have shifted their focus eastward over the past decade, the pandemic could prompt others to follow suit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200807133729-05-louis-vuitton-ss21.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;There will be more physical events here,&quot; predicts Griner, who advises several Western brands. &quot;And I think it&#39;s a wise direction because we have the ability to do it.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Not just a fashion show&quot;<br />\r\nLouis Vuitton&#39;s new song is aimed partly at Chinese consumers, Greiner added, citing the use of cartoon characters as something Asian culture &quot;likes&quot;. (Characters from the brand&#39;s teaser videos appear on the track as large rubber bands, printed on bags, and hung on various items of clothing).<br />\r\nHowever, Ablo also spoke on a broader subject, describing the collection in his exhibition notes as a &quot;platform for nuance&quot; on which he strives for &quot;inclusion, unity and humanity&quot;. At the end of Hill&#39;s performance, the singer announced that Ablo and Louis Vuitton would make a donation to the MLH Foundation to support the Black&#39;s company affected by Covid-19.<br />\r\n&quot;What you saw today was not just a musical or some other fashion show,&quot; Ablo said in a video Hill shared and posted on his personal Instagram Thursday. &quot;What you see is a black imagination manifesting in real life.&quot;<br />\r\nHowever, as the event explained, &quot;Abloh embraces the global Louis Vuitton community and meets customers in their part of the world&quot; - and with the brand&#39;s next event taking place in Tokyo in September, it now seems to be. means Asia.<br />\r\nThis article has been updated to take into account that Greener is consulting several Western brands.</p>', 'Louis Vuitton, China', 'Louis Vuitton_1600016579.jpg', '2020-09-13 21:02:59', '2021-08-12 00:04:18');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(581, 7, 2, 115, 'black-is-king-beyonces-visual-album-is-a-celebration-of-fashion-and-symbolism-1600017855', 'Black Is King \': Beyonc\'s visual album is a celebration of fashion and symbolism', 0, '<p>Many of the lines and lyrics can be quoted in &quot;Black Is King&quot;, Beyonc&eacute;&#39;s new visual album, which is released today on Disney +. Above all, however, the two seem very well suited to portray the stylistic celebration created by the artist. The first appeared after three minutes: &quot;Let black be a synonym for joy.&quot; The second appeared half an hour later with the song &ldquo;Mood 4 Eva&rdquo; with Jay-Z, Childish Gambino and Mali singer Oumou Sangar&eacute;. Beyonce wore a long leopard dress with a slit higher than the top and laughed at the camera as she sang, &quot;I&#39;m in a good mood.&quot;<br />\r\nThis nearly 90-minute film is proof of both of these claims.<br />\r\n&quot;Black Is King&quot; is considered a celebration of &quot;the breadth and beauty of black origins,&quot; as Beyonc&eacute; wrote in an Instagram post announcing its launch. &quot;Black Is King&quot; is in addition to the album he made in 2019 with &quot;The Lion King: The Gift&quot;. Accompanying Disney&#39;s CGI remake of the animated film from 1994 (Beyonc&eacute; greets the older Nala in film). It follows a young man&#39;s journey towards self-discovery, with an emphasis on the stories of black and African traditions told through the artist&#39;s own narrative.<br />\r\nAesthetically, however, this project is a world in itself. All over the world, from South Africa to West Africa, from England to Belgium, from New York to Los Angeles. It shows Queen Bay - the project&#39;s writer-director and executive producer - in a phenomenal, concise and lively set universe as strong and beautiful as the cultural message conveyed through music.<br />\r\nThe fashion moments prepared by the old Bay Zerina Akers stylist and costume designer are too many to count. Just like in Lemonade, which was released in 2016, Beyonc&eacute; seamlessly transitioned from clothing to clothing, from color blocks to patterns, from major European labels to independent African brands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200731131227-05-beyonce-black-is-king.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThere&#39;s a lovely Erdem floral dress on wheels from the British company&#39;s fall-winter 2019 collection, but also a built-in long-sleeved body from French label Marine Serre with the brand&#39;s crescent moon print. A sparkling bodysuit dress is followed by a wild blue suit and sleek feminine cut, much like the yellow ensemble the artist wore at the end of the film in a heavenly rendering of &quot;Spirit&quot;, surrounded by a black chorus with pink silk pants and a blazer. . With a changing style, Beyonce is able to fully embody a variety of characters.<br />\r\nAccessories also play a big part in Black Is King, from sunglasses (small cat eyes with diamonds, as they say) to towering hats honoring African fashion traditions and Egyptian Queen Nefertiti. The earrings were large and lightning fast; The bracelet adorned the length of the arm; Pearls appear and reappear all the time. Nothing to underestimate and that&#39;s the point.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200731132324-14-beyonce-black-is-king.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThis artistic talent shares other cast. Jay-Z and the young hero look great in camel-colored costumes, matching turtlenecks, and big necklaces. Tina Knowles-Lawson, Bay&#39;s mother, appeared in the accompanying head-sharp pink suit. Even blue ivy looks decorated with ball gowns and pearls.<br />\r\nFor the song &quot;Brown Girl&quot; Naomi Campbell, Adut Akech, Lupita Nyong&#39;o, Kelly Rowland and Aveng Ade-Chuol put on a stunning ensemble on a stunning all-black debut ball. (Other well-dressed celebrities who appeared in film at different times include Farrell Williams, Nigerian singer Mr. Izzy, and Ghanaian artist Shata Weil.)<br />\r\nIn the chorus moment, perhaps the mastery of the film aesthetic really shines through.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The synchronized swimming numbers reminiscent of the technical colors of Esther William&#39;s water from the 1940s and 1950s are a hypnotic kaleidoscopic dream in orange and fuchsia hues with Bay in the center. The final choreographed sequence in the middle of the desert, where the dancers wear primary colors, looks like a moving image.<br />\r\nThis scene embodies Beyonce&#39;s creative mission in recent years: to honor black history and identity and to celebrate black talent.<br />\r\n&quot;The events of 2020 make the film&#39;s vision and message more relevant as people around the world embark on historic journeys,&quot; he wrote on Instagram. &quot;I believe that when black people tell their own story, we can shift the axis of the world and tell a TRUE story of generational wealth and soul wealth that is not told in our history books.&quot;</p>', 'Black King, Fashion and symbolism', 'Fashion_1600017821.jpg', '2020-09-13 21:23:41', '2021-08-18 06:21:11'),
(582, 7, 2, 132, 'understand-the-orthodox-jewish-womens-dress-code-and-its-various-interpretations-1600022436', 'Understand the Orthodox Jewish women\'s dress code and its various interpretations', 0, '<p>Based on the true story of Deborah Feldman, a Jewish woman who left the Satmar community in Williamsburg, Brooklyn in search of a new life, the Netflix hit series &quot;Unorthodox&quot; introduced Hasidic culture - and its dress code for women - to the US. Mass flow a. One of the most talked about aspects of the show are the clothes that shape the story of the protagonist Esti (played by Shira Haas) from start to finish.<br />\r\nThe show&#39;s costume designer, Justin Seymour, did hours of research, including a week-long stint at the Satmar community in New York. &quot;I consider one of the greatest gifts in my work to be very creative, but also very educational,&quot; he said in a telephone interview.<br />\r\n&quot;You have to be sensitive, respectful and informed when observing such a closed community,&quot; said Seymour, a non-Jew. She said she found that the women she met during her research had adopted designer brands for shoes, headscarves, and bags. &quot;Kate Spade, Chanel, Ferragamo and Hermes are all leading designers,&quot; he said, &quot;adding a little glamor to the conservative dress code.&quot;<br />\r\nWhether she washes thrift shops for silk scarves (she says she bought over 100 for the show) or makes faux leather straps (hats worn by married husbands, usually made of mink), Seymour says she works hard at ensuring that each costume fits. with Orthodox Jewish law, but also celebrates the nuances of individual style.<br />\r\nOrthodox clothing is often viewed by outsiders as too restrictive and leaves little room for individual freedom and self-expression. The fictional characters Feldman and Esti struggle against the pressure their community exerts, which affects their appearance. However, all three of the Jews interviewed for this article felt they had more freedom to explore their personal styles than other people. They may adopt - especially in less conservative households or chapters - and many devout women play with fashion to reflect their personal tastes while sticking to the religious dress code they follow.<br />\r\nOrthodox Judaism encompasses many traditions and customs, with the Williams Hasids only one group that is particularly wary. And while women living in these particular communities tend to follow stricter dress codes, followers of modern Orthodox, for example, choose to interpret some of the core principles differently.<br />\r\nSpecific codes of style differ from community to community, and dress is often dictated by practicality or religious events - Shabbat, Yom Tov (meaning holiday), weddings, and bar mitzvahs - as well as personal taste. But wherever you are or for whatever reason, in the world of Orthodox Jewry what you wear is determined by the concept of humility, which is called tzniut in Hebrew and tznius in Yiddish. From Tel Aviv to Massachusetts, clothes are chosen with clothing in mind.<br />\r\nTamara Fulton, a fashion stylist and lifestyle editor who is married to an Orthodox rabbi and lives in London, stated, &quot;There are many different Jewish communities around the world with great diversity, but their basic principles are the same. Tznius is an inner word. Judaism is easily misunderstood and means &quot;modesty&quot; but it is not just about modest clothing. Tznius applies to both men and women and is based on the concept of humility. It is really about how you are in the world and how you behave in a controlled but dignified manner, &quot; said Fulton.<br />\r\nFor Orthodox women, this usually means the following: there are no pants to wear, and skirts and dresses must fall below the knees, even when sitting. The arms are covered by the elbows and the cleavage is heavily cut. Clothes were changed frequently - with sewn slits in the skirt and additional cuts. Layering is also widely used to create the final look.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200508080732-06-unorthodox-netflix-production-still.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nOnce you are married, covering your hair is another major principle in tznius. Not all women will shave their real hair like Esti did in one of The Unorthodox&#39;s most memorable scenes (her hair was totally shaved for her). But many observant women wear scarves or scarves, the Yiddish says for wigs.<br />\r\nA Jewish teacher who teaches at an all-girls school in Israel and who also lives in Haredi or the ultra-Orthodox community in Manchester, northern England, agreed to be interviewed for this article but asked not to be named. out of courtesy.<br />\r\nShe wears a scarf herself and explains that it can often be used as an accessory or as a means of changing your appearance. On the phone she said, &quot;One (woman) I know has different colored leaves with different styles. Because she said, &#39;I covered my head and thought of hats for hats.&#39; So if I want to be blonde one day and brown the next, why not? &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nThe hijab style also depends on the community. For example, some Hasidic women wore short wigs with a cap over them so that there was no doubt that they wore a head covering. Sheitels are made from human and synthetic hair. Whenever he lived in Manchester, his teachers always preferred to wear his human hair wigs on special occasions. &quot;I&#39;ll have real hair for Shabbat and then synthetic hair for every day,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nIt is also common to wear gifted jewelery on the Sabbath or on special occasions. &quot;It is believed that married women should have beautiful jewelry,&quot; said the teacher. &quot;Maybe simple, but high quality.&quot;<br />\r\nSeymour notes that jewelery is an important part of an &quot;unorthodox&quot; mix of costumes. She recalls having to dress up about 60 women for Esti and her husband&#39;s Yankees wedding scene, all in diamonds and pearls. Later in this scene, the groom presents his new bride with a pair of latticed diamond earrings. &quot;They were very close to the earrings Deborah Feldman received,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nAs in other cultures and religions, different colors meant different things, but black was not the only color that Hasidic women wore. &quot;When I lived in Israel, we almost never wore black,&quot; said the teacher. &quot;They are very light colors. But not red - never red! Because this color is not considered simple. (In the Hasidic community) women tend to wear dark blue, a bottle of green, brown and gray.&quot;<br />\r\n&ldquo;For all women, clothes are an expression of oneself. The idea is to look chic but don&#39;t attract too much attention, &rdquo;he explained.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200602161118-01-unorthodox-fashion.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nOrthodox women buy clothes in a variety of places, from clothing stores owned by Jews in their community to other non-Jewish shops or malls. Fulton has several shops that often sell items that are suitable for them. &quot;I prefer wearing clothes that are designed to be worn as is, rather than overlaying or modifying modesty,&quot; he says. &quot;H&amp;M and Zara are good for that.&quot;<br />\r\nShe also noticed that many haute couture designers were producing collections that offered options for women who wanted to dress modestly. &quot;It&#39;s interesting to see how designers like Valentino, Erdem and McQueen, for example, come up with the right style for women who want to dress more modestly. I&#39;m also a big fan of the overall revival of the 70s inspired by Laura Ashley Design and brands like The Vampire Woman. &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nAnother brand that has become popular with attentive and secular women is Batsheva. The CFDA / Vogue Fashion Fund winning brand for 2018 is known for its ruffled, prairie-style dresses. Created by native New Yorker Batsheva Hey, the Fundamentals true to their name are centered around his personal history and culture.<br />\r\nHer husband, photographer Alexei Hay, started following Orthodox practices shortly before dating began. At their wedding, Batsheva, who grew up in a secular Jewish family and did not strictly adhere to the Jewish dress code, said men and women were separated, which is a tradition, and Haye wore her mother&#39;s wedding dress made of Mexican lace. and suitable for tznius.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200525160153-orthodox-wedding-batsheva.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nWith no formal training in fashion design, Hay - a former lawyer - initially started making clothes while raising children at home. It launched its brand in 2016.<br />\r\n&quot;When I started Batsheva, I found that so many of the references that caught my eye were retro or outdated,&quot; he said by telephone. &quot;Also in my (neighborhood) and in Brooklyn, not far by the subway, I have seen Orthodox women dressed like this.&quot; Hey, he said he was forced to work within certain preset rules, but reinterpreted them. In this way, he has developed a style that is humble but at the same time different and fun.<br />\r\n&quot;The aim of the Orthodox Jews is not to give up beauty,&quot; he said. &quot;You have to work on it to make it look beautiful.&quot;<br />\r\nSeymour echoed that feeling: &quot;In costumes at The Unorthodox, I want to honor women around the world who want to look beautiful without breaking the rules of modesty.&quot; He said he was impressed by the pride that many women in the Satmar Church have agreed to dress well in. &quot;If the show can bring a little more glamor and beauty and pride to our (all women&#39;s) clothes, I will be happy.&quot;</p>', 'Orthodox, interpretations', 'Orthodox_1600022436.jpg', '2020-09-13 22:40:36', '2021-08-18 02:58:06'),
(583, 7, 2, 213, 'dior-teamed-up-with-ghanaian-artist-amoako-boafo-to-create-a-stunning-new-collection-1600023003', 'Dior teamed up with Ghanaian artist Amoako Boafo to create a stunning new collection', 0, '<p>As the creative director of Dior Men, Kim Jones has demonstrated global art collaborations and collaborated with the likes of Raymond Petibon, KAWS, Hajime Sorayama, and Daniel Arsham to enrich the Streetwear Meet Savile Row collections and performances. And now he has added a new artist to the roster and, together with Ghanaian artist Amoaco Boafo, created one of the most talked about collections of the 2021 spring-summer men&#39;s fashion season.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200714075116-dior-mens-ss21-2.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nJones&#39;s latest design, modeled by a group of all-black models in a short film uploaded to YouTube (a new standard since the coronavirus pandemic so far has not included a physical examination), skillfully combines Boafo&#39;s motives and sensibilities.<br />\r\nThe bunches of colored blocks and neon pop-ups are reminiscent of a bold backdrop where the artist paints his face with his fingers. The long ivy embroidered shirt has its roots in a portrait of Jones which can be seen in the artist&#39;s studio in Accra. One of Baofo&#39;s motifs is visible from the leather turtleneck.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200714075811-dior-mens-ss21-6.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe collaboration seeds were planted last December. Jones, who was showcasing his collection in Miami before the fall, was particularly impressed by the Boafo exhibit at the recently opened City Rubel Museum.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200714075307-dior-mens-ss21-3.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;(Boafo&#39;s work) just spoke to me; he immediately grabbed me. The intensity of his portraits, the power of movement and the choice of colors in them - it all touched me in his work and the way he saw things,&quot; said a Jones statement. &quot;In creating this collection, I wanted to share this passion and celebrate the power of his work to make him better known.&quot;<br />\r\nHowever, like art that has long played a role in Jones&#39;s creative practice, Boafo has long loved fashion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200714075455-dior-mens-ss21-4.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" />&quot;Fashion inspires my work and that&#39;s why I tend to watch characters with that sense of style,&quot; he explains from his studio in the film.<br />\r\nWorking with black artists at a time when the fashion industry is increasingly demanding systemic racism can be seen as opportunistic. However, for Jones, who moved between Ethiopia, Kenya, Botswana and Ghana as a child with his hydrogeological father, the relationship was more personal.<br />\r\n&quot;I&#39;ve wanted to work with African artists for a long time because I grew up in Africa, and African art has always been important to me,&quot; he explains in the video.<br />\r\nThe show went against what Dior proposed during a fashion show in early July. Women&#39;s clothing designer Maria Grazia Chiuri presents her latest collection in the form of a short film with a very white model.</p>', 'Dior, Ghanaian artist', 'Dior_1600023003.jpg', '2020-09-13 22:50:03', '2021-08-18 09:47:30'),
(584, 7, 12, 115, 'the-former-fifth-prime-minister-spoke-out-against-the-bill-after-brexit-1600086534', 'The former fifth prime minister spoke out against the bill after Brexit', 0, '<p><strong>David Cameron is the fifth former Prime Minister to criticize the new bill which is meant to revoke the Brexit withdrawal agreement.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The internal market bill is then submitted to the legislature, which the government refers to as an &quot;insurance policy&quot;. Cameron said there were &quot;concerns&quot; about this issue and violating international agreements should be a &quot;last resort&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Former Prime Ministers Tory Theresa May and Sir John Major and Labor Tony Blair and Gordon Brown condemned the plan. Earlier, Police Secretary Keith Malthaus called it a &quot;practical&quot; move.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He repeated comments by Justice Secretary Robert Buckland on Sunday that a law would exist if Britain and the EU did not agree to a post-Brexit trade deal.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Boris Johnson was expected to speak to reporters at an event later, but 10 people confirmed it was canceled due to pressing parliamentary issues.<br />\r\nThe government is expected to win the vote in the General Assembly at the next stage of the bill, which takes place around 22:00 CET (21:00 CET). However, it is also expected to face more problems at a later date, especially as the legislature focuses on debates in Lords.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Former Attorney General Jeffrey Cox said he would vote against him, accusing Johnson of damaging Britain&#39;s international reputation for &quot;immoral&quot; rights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A senior government source told that &quot;all options are on the table&quot; regarding possible action against Tory lawmakers who do not support the bill.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Prime Minister&#39;s Special Representative for Freedom of Religion or Belief, Tory MP Rehman Chishti, has resigned the proposed law, saying, &quot;I have always acted in a manner that respects the rule of law ... [and] because I have now chosen the law. -this invite. It will go against the values that are most important to me. &quot;&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shadow Labor business secretary Ed Miliband also called the proposed bill &quot;legislative hooliganism&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Britain left the European Union on January 31, after negotiating and signing a withdrawal agreement with the bloc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The two sides are in the final weeks of negotiations for a post-Brexit trade agreement before the transition period ends on December 31. Informal talks will take place in Brussels this week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An integral part of the withdrawal agreement - now an international treaty - is the Northern Ireland Protocol, which is designed to prevent a tough border from returning to the Irish island.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Government&#39;s proposed Internal Market Act will replace the portion of this Agreement with regard to goods and allow the UK to change or interpret state aid rules for subsidies to businesses in Northern Ireland in the event of goods that neither party relies on. have agreed to trade agreements in the future.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Last week, Northern Ireland Secretary Brandon Lewis said the bill would &quot;violate international law in certain and limited ways,&quot; which would generate some criticism from all sides of the political spectrum.</p>', 'Fifth PM, Brexit', 'x-PM uk_1600086534.jpg', '2020-09-14 16:28:54', '2021-08-16 23:55:57'),
(585, 7, 12, 64, 'yoshihide-suga-was-chosen-by-the-ruling-party-in-japan-to-replace-shinzo-abe-1600760295', 'Yoshihide Suga, was chosen by the ruling party in Japan to replace Shinzo Abe', 0, '<p><strong>Japan\'s ruling party has chosen Yoshihide Suga as its new leader to replace Shinzo Abe, meaning it is almost certain that he will become the country\'s next prime minister.</strong></p><p>Last month, Abe announced his retirement for health reasons. Suga, 71, is the chief cabinet secretary in the current government and should have won. He is considered a close ally of Abe and is likely to continue the policies of his predecessors.<br>Suga won the vote for the presidency of the Conservative Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) by a large margin, receiving 377 votes out of 534 votes from legislators and local officials.</p><p>He sent two other candidates, Fumio Kishida, the former foreign minister, and Shigeru Ishiba, the former LDP secretary general and former defense minister.<br>After the party chooses a new chairman, a new vote will take place in parliament on Wednesday, with Suga almost certain he will become prime minister because of the majority in the LDP.</p><p>Assuming a tentative deadline, Suga is expected to stay in office until the September 2021 general election.</p><p><strong>Who is Yoshihide Suga?</strong><br>Mr. Suga is the native son of an experienced strawberry farmer and politician.</p><p>Given his central role as Chief Cabinet Secretary in government, he is expected to ensure continuity at the top of the interim government through the 2021 elections.</p><p>\"Shinzo Abe and other party bosses voted for and joined Suga precisely because he was the best candidate for \'continuity\', someone they think can continue Abe\'s rule without Abe,\" said Koichi Nakano, Dean and Professor. in political science from Sofia University in Tokyo, he told the BBC.</p><p>Although not considered the most energetic or passionate politician, Suga has a reputation for being extremely effective and practical.</p><p>One of his most recent appearances is the transition from Emperor Akihito, who abdicated, to his son Naruhito in 2019. Suga is the name of Reiva\'s new era in front of the Japanese public and the world.<br>Although he became a favorite for the LDP leadership following Abe\'s resignation, it is unclear if he will lead the party in next year\'s general elections.</p><p>Observers claim that at that point, party dynamics could change to bring more passionate people to the top and reach a wider range of general voters.</p><p><strong>What can we expect?</strong><br>Mr Suga pledged to continue Abenomics, an economic policy signed by Mr Abe designed to stimulate the world\'s third largest economy through easing cash, budget spending and structural reforms.</p><p>But like its predecessors, it must first deal with the urgent requirements of the coronavirus pandemic.</p><p>Prior to his election, Suga promised to expand Covid-19 to Japan in the first half of 2021.</p><p>He added that doing so would raise the minimum wage, encourage agricultural reforms, and increase tourism.</p><p>On foreign policy, he is expected to follow Abe\'s lead and prioritize Japan\'s long-term alliance with the United States while maintaining stable relations with China.</p><p><strong>What is the Japanese Political Perspective?</strong><br>The change in leadership comes at a difficult time for the country. Japan is still battling the coronavirus pandemic that caused the biggest economic slump in history.</p><p>Mr. Abe\'s long-term project to start an economy called Abenomics is still ahead of the pandemic and the country has been experiencing stagnation, recession or very slow growth for several years.</p><p>The government\'s plans to reform the post-war pacifist constitution are also underway. Abe wants to change part of the constitution to officially recognize Japanese soldiers, now known as Self-Defense Forces, who are essentially unable to participate in an international military mandate.</p><p>The new government under Mr. Suga can ensure stability for all these projects.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/8F80/production/_113963763_gettyimages-1228073683.jpg\" alt=\"\"></figure><p>When he was the cabinet secretary, \"he really lacked vision,\" said Prof. Nakano warned.</p><p>\"The only slogans he made were \'Self-Help, Mutual Help, and Public Aid\'. He emphasized neoliberal self-help and self-responsibility during a pandemic that left many people economically vulnerable.\"</p><p>New elections for the state parliament, the lower house, are scheduled for September 2021, and at that point there will likely be another leadership contest in the LDP.</p><p>The race is more about who can win over the general voters - rather than just promising continuity, say observers.</p><p><strong>Why did Shinzo Abe step back?</strong><br>Mr Abe said he did not want his illness to affect decision-making and apologized to Japan for failing to serve his term.</p><figure class=\"image\"><img src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/138F6/production/_114281108_mediaitem114152175.jpg\" alt=\"\"></figure><p><br>However, the 65-year-old man had been suffering from ulcerative colitis, an inflammatory bowel disease, for years, but his condition has recently gotten worse.</p><p>Last year he was Japan\'s longest serving Prime Minister. His current term begins in 2012.</p><p>He suddenly stepped down from his previous term as prime minister in 2007, also because of his chronic illness.</p>', 'Japan Election, Yoshihide Suga', 'Yoshihide Suga japan_1600086685.jpg', '2020-09-14 16:31:25', '2021-08-15 22:14:21'),
(586, 7, 6, 149, 'tiktok-turned-down-microsofts-offer-at-eleven-hour-1600088074', 'TikTok turned down Microsoft\'s offer at eleven hour', 0, '<p><strong>Microsoft says its offer to buy US operations for the hugely popular TikTok video-sharing app has been turned down, paving the way for Oracle to a last-minute deal.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>US President Donald Trump has set a September 15 deadline for the sale or closure of Chinese applications. The Trump administration says TikTok and other Chinese apps pose a threat to national security.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Microsoft and Oracle are on the run to buy TikTok from Chinese company ByteDance. TikTok is a very popular video sharing app, downloaded 2 billion times worldwide, which allows people to create and upload videos that are 15 seconds long.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Wall Street Journal and Reuters reported that Oracle, which sells database technology and cloud systems to companies, won the tender citing people with knowledge of the matter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previous reports said Oracle is seriously considering buying TikTok&#39;s US, Canada, Australia and New Zealand businesses with securities firms such as General Atlantic and Sequoia Capital.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A TikTok spokesman told&nbsp;that the company &quot;does not comment on Microsoft&#39;s developments nor on Oracle&#39;s speculations.&quot;<br />\r\n<strong>What did Microsoft say?</strong><br />\r\nMicrosoft announced on Sunday that &quot;ByteDance announced today that it will not sell its US TikTok operations to Microsoft. We are confident that our proposal will be both good for TikTok users and protect national security interests.&quot; &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We look forward to seeing how services perform in these important areas,&quot; he said in a statement. This paved the way for Oracle, which Trump said would be a &quot;great company&quot; last month to take over TikTok&#39;s US operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oracle President Larry Ellison is a supporter of Mr. Trump and organized a fundraiser for him in February.<br />\r\nEarlier this month, Trump said the government would have to receive a &quot;large portion&quot; of the selling price of US TikTok units if US companies bought them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, there is some confusion about the deadline. Mr Trump&#39;s order is scheduled for September 20. However, the US President has repeatedly stated that the deadline is September 15.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Why this happened?</strong><br />\r\nTrump has ordered TikTok owner ByteDance to sell or close its US business within 90 days. The forced sale of TikTok businesses in America is part of a broader crackdown on Chinese tech companies in America.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump said apps like TikTok, WeChat and device maker Huawei pose a threat to national security because data collected about consumers can be shared with the Chinese government. The Chinese company denies this claim.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/17A30/production/_114361869_gettyimages-1268426141.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nHuawei also faces a Sept. 15 ban affecting non-US suppliers. You must stop shipping to Huawei if their products contain American technology. In order to supply Huawei, they need a license from the US Department of Commerce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What has the Chinese said about that?</strong><br />\r\nTwo weeks ago, China announced new government restrictions on technology exports. The rule is believed to aim to delay the sale of TikTok. Limitations mean that some technologies, such as B. KI, must obtain government approval before being exported.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>TikTok has become very popular because it has a sophisticated algorithm that predicts what users want to see.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/DDF0/production/_114361865_gettyimages-1227809947-1.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThis type of technology will now be in the spotlight of the Chinese government.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This highly valued algorithm is not for sale or broadcast, according to a report in the South China Morning Post.</p>', 'Tik Tok', 'TikTok reject_1600088074.jpg', '2020-09-14 16:54:34', '2021-08-13 11:14:37'),
(587, 7, 10, 141, '2020-us-election-bloomberg-donates-100-million-to-biden-in-florida-1600089259', '2020 US election: Bloomberg donates $ 100 million to Biden in Florida', 0, '<p><strong>Billionaire Mike Bloomberg has pledged at least $ 100 million (&pound; 78 million) to support Joe Biden&#39;s Democratic presidential campaign in Florida.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Of the states on the battlefield, Florida has the largest proportion of the votes needed to win. Mr Bloomberg has spent $ 1 billion this year beating Mr Biden and becoming a Democratic contender. Donald Trump has hinted that he will spend his own money in the state before the initial September 24 voting begins.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Both campaigns aim to reach voters who can vote early by email and set the tone for the final weeks of their campaigns. Postal voting is expected to double from 2016 as the coronavirus pandemic encourages voters to avoid polling stations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Florida offers 29 of the 270 colleges needed to win an election. Only California (55) and Texas (38) offer more, but are considered safe Democratic and Republican territories, respectively. President Trump won Florida in 2016, while Democrat Barack Obama took over the state in 2012.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Who is Mike Bloomberg?</strong><br />\r\nA very simple guide to US elections &quot;Mike Bloomberg is committed to helping Trump win, and that will happen in the US,&quot; Kevin Sheakey, Bloomberg&#39;s adviser, told Reuters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a tweet, Donald Trump responded by criticizing Bloomberg&#39;s own candidacy for the Democratic presidential nomination, which reportedly spent $ 409 million (&pound; 313 million) on it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I thought Minnie Mike was done with democratic politics,&quot; he wrote of the former mayor of New York. &quot;Save New York instead.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Earlier this week, when asked by reporters if he would consider spending his own money in Florida, Trump told reporters, &quot;If I have to, I will. Whatever it takes, we have to win.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Initially, the president enjoyed significant financial gains over his rivals, but Biden&#39;s successful fundraising filled the void.</p>', 'US Election, 100$ Donated', 'Joe Biden_1600089259.jpg', '2020-09-14 17:14:19', '2021-08-16 14:27:44'),
(588, 7, 7, 71, 'belarusian-protests-lukashenko-will-meet-with-putin-while-unrest-continues-1600089957', 'Belarusian protests: Lukashenko will meet with Putin while unrest continues', 0, '<p><strong>Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko flew to Russia for talks with Vladimir Putin.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This will be their first face-to-face meeting since protests erupted in Belarus last month since a controversial presidential election. Putin recognized Lukashenko as Belarus&#39; legitimate leader and said there were troops ready to intervene if protests got out of hand.<br />\r\nThere is speculation that he may want a closer relationship in exchange for further support. The talks will take place at Russia&#39;s Black Sea resort in Sochi when joint military exercises begin near the western Belarusian city of Brest.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Police arrested dozens of people as opposition supporters gathered for the march. Tens of thousands of people marched through the Belarusian capital Minsk and other cities on Sunday to demand Lukashenko&#39;s resignation. Police said they had arrested about 400 people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Belarusian opposition accuses Lukashenko, who has been in power for 26 years, of manipulating the presidential election.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He insisted he won 80% of the fair vote and described the protests as Western and anti-Russian support.<br />\r\nAlexander Lukashenko wants the meeting to show home protesters that Russia supports: a new reminder that Vladimir Putin can keep up with what is happening in Belarus and can send security forces.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In turn, he was busy signaling to Moscow that he was the one keeping Belarus in its orbit by labeling the protesters as anti-Russian and supporting them from the West.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some speculate that Putin will promote closer economic and political ties with Minsk at the expense of his support. This alone risks increasing tensions rather than stabilizing the things Moscow wants - and there is no guarantee that a weakened Lukashenko will keep his promises at all.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So, there is a growing feeling that Moscow will publicly support him for now if he starts talking behind the scenes about transition plans.</p>', 'Belarusian Protest, Coronaviru s', 'Belarus_1600089957.jpg', '2020-09-14 17:25:57', '2021-08-15 16:27:14'),
(589, 7, 7, 56, 'climate-change-fijis-sea-level-rise-creates-ghost-cities-1600090464', 'Climate change: Fiji\'s sea level rise creates \"ghost cities\"', 0, '<p>We cannot avoid the fact that the earth&#39;s temperature is increasing, but the effects of climate change are being felt more strongly in some parts of the world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Pacific island nation of Fiji causes less than 1% of global carbon emissions, but sea level rise, coastal erosion and severe storms have dramatic impacts on the country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Villages near the sea were abandoned as high tides inundated homes and resources, forcing residents to move inland to higher, safer land.</p>', 'Fijis Ghost Town, High sea level', 'Ghost house_1600090464.jpg', '2020-09-14 17:34:24', '2021-08-14 09:24:09'),
(590, 7, 7, 75, 'mercy-baguma-a-woman-who-died-in-glasgow-with-a-crying-baby-and-was-buried-in-uganda-1600091021', 'Mercy Baguma: A woman who died in Glasgow with a crying baby and was buried in Uganda', 0, '<p><strong>Mercy Baguma, who died and sought asylum in England, is buried near his family home in Uganda.</strong><br />\r\nIn August, her body was found in an apartment in Glasgow near her crying child. It is not clear how Ms. Baghuma died, but the case has sparked calls for changes to the British asylum system.<br />\r\nThe Positive Housing Charity (PAIH) which helped him said he was &quot;practically poor&quot; because he could not find a job because his right to work in Britain had run out.<br />\r\nEric Nnana, father of Mrs. One-year-old Baghuma Adriel called the police four days after being last contacted.<br />\r\nShe worries to hear her son cry in their locked apartment. Baby &quot;in just three days&quot; Police forcibly opened the door and found the 34-year-old man&#39;s body in the hallway while Adriel was found alive in his bed.<br />\r\nHis death was described by police as &quot;inexplicable but not suspicious&quot;.<br />\r\nAdriel is said to have not eaten for at least three days, PAIH said. The charity helped raise funds for the repatriation of her body and funeral expenses for Ms. Baghuma. Raising money for babies He is buried in Bugiri, Uganda, 150 km east of the capital Kampala.<br />\r\nPAIH said the remaining &pound; 75,000 (US $ 97,000) would be donated to Adriel. He called for a public investigation into the death of him and other asylum seekers in Glasgow, as well as the placement of asylum seekers in the Scottish city.<br />\r\nScotland&#39;s First Minister, Nicholas Sturgeon, said a &quot;comprehensive reform&quot; of the asylum system was&nbsp; necessary, starting with &quot;principles of dignity, compassion and support for our neighbors&quot;. The UK Home Office has announced that they will investigate Ms. Baghuma.<br />\r\nHe is believed to have come to England about 15 years ago as a student, reports the Guardian.</p>', 'Mercy Baguma, Uganda', 'Mercy Baguma_1600091021.', '2020-09-14 17:43:41', '2021-08-17 07:34:16'),
(591, 7, 7, 87, 'dong-tam-case-two-people-were-sentenced-to-death-in-vietnam-for-police-murder-1600092088', 'Dong Tam Case: Two people were sentenced to death in Vietnam for police murder', 0, '<p><strong>One of 29 defendants in a fatal land dispute in Vietnam was sentenced to death.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The remaining inmates were sentenced to life imprisonment of up to 15 months on probation. Police entered Dong Tam Village in January to secure the construction of a fence around the land officers wanted to confiscate near the airport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Strong resistance from villagers sparked clashes in which three police officers and a retired employee were killed at the scene. The robbery and death of a popular local leader, 84-year-old Le Din Keane, has sparked huge public controversy. Land disputes are widespread in Vietnam, but rarely escalate into such conflicts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>What happened at Dong Tam?</strong><br />\r\nPolice arrived in the village in January to secure land seized by the Ministry of Defense around Mieu Mon Airport near Dong Tam when soldiers were building a border fence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The land has been the subject of a dispute with villagers who say they did not receive adequate compensation for its confiscation. Authorities said a group of residents led by Le Dinh Kinh fiercely opposed the police and three police officers - Colonel Nguyen Huy Thinh, Captain Pham Cong Huy and Lieutenant Colonel Duong Duc Hoang Quan - were set on fire and set on fire.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/1081D/production/_110531676_e6b5dc7c-4d40-4341-9877-65b17934caa6.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Keane was later shot dead by police who said they hit him with a grenade. His son Le Dinh Chuc was injured in the attack. Deputy Minister Luong Tam Quang said police had confiscated petrol bombs, iron bars and other weapons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Keane&#39;s family and supporters have opposed the official bill. Over the next several days, three of Mr. family members. Keane appears on television with a wounded face, apparently admitting that they have an improvised weapon and a petrol bomb. Human rights groups say the confession was obtained, and Kin&#39;s wife, Du Ti Thanh, said she was beaten by police.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>How did the argument start?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The dispute started about three years ago when the Vietnamese military operated at Mieu Mon Airport.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Residents complained that about 50 hectares of their land had been inappropriately confiscated and handed over to the Viettel Group, Vietnam&#39;s military communications company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/6933/production/_110513962_gettyimages-670608826.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAll land in communist Vietnam belongs to the state, so the government can technically use whatever it wants for military or civilian purposes. However, local residents protested that they did not receive adequate compensation for the land confiscated and refused to take it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The dispute first caught public attention in 2017 when four people were arrested for &quot;disorderly behavior&quot; in protests against land acquisition.</p>', 'Vietnam, Sentence death', 'Vietnam_1600092088.jpg', '2020-09-14 18:01:28', '2021-08-16 14:49:25'),
(592, 7, 7, 104, 'humpback-whales-enter-crocodile-river-in-australian-first-1600092274', 'Humpback whales enter crocodile river \'in Australian first\'', 0, '<p><strong>Australian officials said they would try to rescue a humpback whale from a crocodile-infected river in the Northern Territory after it disappeared and reached 30 km inland.</strong><br />\r\nWhales and others undertake annual ocean migrations when some of them &quot;misunderstand,&quot; experts say.<br />\r\nTwo whales then emerged from the river, but at least one was left. This is the first case of a whale found in crocodile territory in outback Australia.<br />\r\nGiven their length of 16 meters, it is believed that the humpback whale will not be bothered by crocodiles.<br />\r\nBut that risk could increase if the whales washed ashore in shallow water, officials said Monday.<br />\r\n<strong>Wait what happened?</strong><br />\r\nThe whales were spotted last week on the East Alligator River by sailors in Kakadu National Park, Australia&#39;s largest national park and a World Heritage Site.<br />\r\nThe sight of the animals swimming in the bends of the muddy river - away from the open water - shocked the locals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/F5C4/production/_114361926_copyandsve.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s something that has never been recorded before - not only in the Northern Territory - but also in Australia. Really, very unusual,&quot; said Carol Palmer, a marine ecosystem scientist with the Territory government.<br />\r\nThe river&#39;s &quot;brown muddy water&quot; made it difficult to determine whether more than one whale needed help, he added.<br />\r\n<strong>How did the whales get there?</strong><br />\r\nMiss Palmer told the Australian Broadcasting Corporation that experts are not sure &quot;why this whale went wrong off the north coast of the country.&quot; They are believed to have headed south to Antarctica but mistakenly entered an estuary which brought them upstream into a river system.<br />\r\nIn the spring, whales migrate to warmer waters off Australia&#39;s coast to give birth before returning to Antarctica in search of food. But when the whales get into a shallow turn and get washed ashore, &quot;it&#39;s easy for them to eat,&quot; Palmer told the ABC. &quot;There is no way to lift the 12-16 meter humpback whale off the sandbar and then the ladder can enter.&quot;<br />\r\n<strong>What are employees doing to help?</strong><br />\r\nIn order to clear the way to the sea, boats are prohibited from the river.<br />\r\nWe hope that the whale will go away on its own, but it is still around the deepest part of the river - about 20 km from the sea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/14B50/production/_114361848_12657200-3x2-xlarge.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nPalmer said officials were considering several options for removing them, such as using &quot;loud noises&quot; from nearby boats or recording conversations with humpback whales.<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s difficult at every level but everyone is really trying to move forward as positively as possible,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Humpback whales, Australian first', 'Vietnam_1600092274.jpg', '2020-09-14 18:04:34', '2021-08-16 12:42:43'),
(593, 7, 12, 142, 'bernadette-walkers-parents-have-been-charged-with-murder-1600092755', 'Bernadette Walker\'s parents have been charged with murder', 0, '<p><strong>The missing teen&#39;s parents are accused of murdering him.</strong><br />\r\nCambridgeshire Police said 17-year-old Bernadette Walker disappeared on July 21 from her mother and father in Peterborough, who said she had not been seen for three days. A murder investigation has been launched, although his body has not been found.<br />\r\nSarah Walker, 37, and Scott Walker, 50, of Century Square in Millfield, Peterborough, will appear in court for murder. Det Supt Jon Hutchinson said, &quot;Although my team has made significant progress on this investigation over the last few days, we have not found Bernadette. Therefore, my request is directed to anyone with information about what happened to him or where you are. may lie. &quot;connected immediately. &quot;<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/15D70/production/_114365498_c86d8dcf-3ff3-4dc0-9693-23dedcf8f6ef.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>', 'Bernadette walkers, murder', 'Bernadette walkers_1600092755.jpg', '2020-09-14 18:12:35', '2021-08-11 23:56:27');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(594, 7, 12, 91, 'kidbrooke-truck-crash-the-driver-is-killed-and-the-child-is-critical-1600092966', 'Kidbrooke Truck Crash: The driver is killed and the child is critical', 0, '<p><strong>A man has died and an 11-year-old child is in a life-threatening condition after a truck crashed into a house in southeast London.</strong><br />\r\nEmergency services were called to Broad Walk, Kidbrooke, at 8:05 CET, where six people were injured in the crash. The London Fire Brigade (LFB) said the truck driver was pronounced dead at the scene.<br />\r\nThe other two men were hospitalized, the London Ambulance Service (LAS) added.<br />\r\nThe Royal Greenwich District Council said it was aware of the accident but said &quot;no vehicles or council staff were involved&quot;.&nbsp;The LFB said the accident structurally damaged a house on Woolacombe Road.<br />\r\nStation Commander Nathan Hobson said, &quot;It was a provocative accident and it looks like a truck collided with two cars and hit a house.<br />\r\n&quot;A special search and rescue team was present at the scene and efforts were made to free the truck driver. Unfortunately, he was pronounced dead at the scene.&quot;<br />\r\n<strong>&quot;Very tragic&quot;</strong><br />\r\nA local resident who chose not to be named said the scene was &quot;very tragic&quot; after the truck crashed just 30 meters from his house.<br />\r\nHe added, &ldquo;I was getting ready to run for school, suddenly the police, ambulance sirens, the sound of helicopters continued to sound.<br />\r\n&quot;The local traffic is controlled by the police, then I heard people talking about a truck hitting a house ... then someone was sent in an ambulance.<br />\r\n&quot;Truly tragic - my thoughts are on the people I love.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/800/cpsprodpb/14114/production/_114369128_eh3cuf7wsae4khe.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAccording to LAS, six patients were treated at the site for injuries and several were discharged.<br />\r\nA spokesman added: &quot;Unfortunately, one patient was found dead at the scene.<br />\r\n&quot;Of the other five patients, we took three to the hospital and two were discharged immediately.&quot;<br />\r\nNaturally, one of the patients was taken by ambulance to a large trauma center in London.<br />\r\nPolice said officers were trying to find the driver&#39;s relatives and advised people to stay away from the scene.</p>', 'Kidbrooke Truck, Driver Killed', 'kidbrooke_1600092966.jpg', '2020-09-14 18:16:06', '2021-08-12 00:03:19'),
(595, 7, 12, 103, 'coronavirus-report-a-violation-of-the-six-rules-urged-the-minister-1600093150', 'Coronavirus: Report a violation of the \"six rules\", urged the minister', 0, '<p><strong>People should report any suspicion to neighbors of violating the new &quot;rule six&quot; restrictions on social gatherings, said the Minister of Criminal Investigation.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kit Malthouse appealed to residents to provide details of alleged violations of the law through a non-emergency number. Starting today, new rules will limit indoor and outdoor gatherings in England and Scotland, and domestic groups in Wales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They appeared after UK or R screenings, with the number increasing between 1 and 1.2 for the first time since March. Another 3,330 positive cases were reported in the UK on Sunday - the third day in a row with more than 3,000 - with five more deaths.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the UK government&#39;s coronavirus dashboard, the total number of deaths reported from coronavirus in the UK is 41,628. When asked by BBC Radio 4 today whether someone should report a meeting of seven or more people in a neighboring park, Malthouse said, &quot;Neighbors can do this through a non-emergency number.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;And when you worry and see things like that, you have to think about it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Minister of Crime and Police added that &quot;there has been discussion as to what reporting mechanisms may exist, but there is clearly an emergency number (101) that people can call and report any problem they want&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>National Police Chiefs Council (NPCC) chairman Martin Hewitt denied that enforcement of rule six was dependent on people &quot;poisoning&quot; their neighbors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;He holds us all responsible,&quot; he told a ABC Channel breakfast.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We will continue to use it as we have done for almost six months,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We are part of a group that is trying to explain the rules to the public and encourage people to obey them.&quot;<br />\r\nPreviously, Home Minister Priti Patel had appealed to the public not to violate the rules. The recent spike in cases suggests that more needs to be done to stop the spread.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Union leader Sir Keir Starmer told LBC he supports the new government rule, adding, &quot;You can argue why not five or why not six or seven - you have to use science-backed numbers and they say six, and I think we should. follow that rule. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was later announced that Sir Keir would isolate himself after a family member showed possible symptoms of the coronavirus.<br />\r\nProfessor Bobby Duffy, director of the Political Institute at King&#39;s College London, told BBC Radio 4 World of One that people &quot;relatively rarely&quot; reported about other people and that the crisis had generated positive feelings about local communities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a survey of attitudes during the pandemic, one in 20 said they reported another rule violation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof Duffy said, &quot;It&#39;s still in the minority, but in terms of the number of incidents, that&#39;s a huge report for fellow citizens.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new rules come amid reports that Britain&#39;s testing system is overburdened and Scottish First Minister Nicholas Sturgeon has expressed &quot;serious concern&quot; about what he says is lagging behind in laboratory networks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Alice Wiseman, director of public health at Gateshead, said local authorities requested a mobile testing unit on Saturday which appeared a day late and dozens of people were sent elsewhere to be tested.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We can&#39;t do contact tracing if we don&#39;t get a positive result,&quot; he told the BBC. &quot;In theory, there are potential people who ask Kovid for a walk and don&#39;t know.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Doris-Ann Williams, executive director of the British Association for In Vitro Diagnostics, said testing delays were due to staff shortages and they were &quot;trying hard to recruit more&quot; to increase winter capacity.</p>', 'Uk, Coronavirus violation', 'Uk Corona_1600093150.jpg', '2020-09-14 18:19:10', '2021-08-16 12:11:10'),
(596, 7, 6, 142, 'arm-can-the-crown-jewels-of-british-technology-be-protected-1600095279', 'ARM: Can the \"crown jewels\" of British technology be protected?', 0, '<p><strong>The British government is &quot;considering&quot; protecting and securing future investment in Cambridge-based ARM Holdings, which US technology giant Nvidia will buy from Japan&#39;s Softbank.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was a much calmer stance than the government when Softbank bought out the world&#39;s leading chip designer in July 2016. At that point, Softbank announced that it had made legally binding commitments to increase investment, fill the workforce and maintain its UK headquarters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is not too late for the government to impose conditions, but rather to talk about whether they should be implemented or what they should start with.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>ARM co-founder Hermann Hauser described the deal as &quot;an absolute disaster for Cambridge, Great Britain and Europe&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said Nvidia would &quot;destroy&quot; the ARM business model, which involved licensing chip projects to hundreds of companies around the world, some of which rivals Nvidia. ARM, which was acquired by one of its customers, would take away that competitive advantage, he said.<br />\r\nJenson Huang, CEO of Nvidia, told reporters today that the fact that a $ 40 billion (&pound; 31.2 billion) deal is underway should show you they believe ARM&#39;s trading prospects are there. will survive any worries from other customers in the company.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that the company intends to maintain ARM headquarters in the UK and invest millions in building a state-of-the-art supercomputing center in Cambridge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The one who escaped?<br />\r\nThe chief of Nvidia described ARM as &quot;one of the greatest technology companies of all time&quot;. It is these types of companies that the government wants to exclude from EU state aid rules to support them with long-term investments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When you have your own tech giant, the big American and Chinese companies won&#39;t push you around easily. This is the philosophy that underlies the government&#39;s public investment plans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I asked the former cabinet minister if the new regime would allow the new sale of ARM to Softbank. First of all, he said, you need a new law. Current takeovers can only be blocked because of media pluralism, financial stability or national security.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the era of cyber warfare, high-performance computers are definitely the new cavalry, and could there be a reason to block this deal?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the former minister said the status of the United States and Japan as allies made it difficult for him to rise. The government should ask the Competition and Market Inspectorate to investigate, and the results can be challenged in court. &quot;It doesn&#39;t make sense to start with a limited chance of success.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new law should be general enough that the government can block deals based on its objectives as they feel &quot;blocked&quot; - which would discourage foreign investment in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Isolating Britain from a possible takeover from Silicon Valley would mean that most entrepreneurs prefer to start their own business in the US. Why are you limiting your options,&quot; the former minister said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The British tech crown has been handed over to international investors, but the new boss says even if ownership has changed it won&#39;t work. Without government interference - which is complicated - we only need to believe its words for now.</p>', 'Arm, British Technology', 'arm_1600095279.jpg', '2020-09-14 18:54:39', '2021-08-18 06:12:38'),
(597, 7, 6, 145, 'arm-the-uk-based-chip-designer-was-sold-to-us-company-nvidia-1600095477', 'ARM: The UK-based chip designer was sold to US company Nvidia', 0, '<p>UK-based computer chip designer ARM Holdings was sold to US graphics chip specialist Nvidia.<br />\r\nThe deal is worth $ 40 billion (&pound; 31.2 billion) four years after it was bought by Japanese conglomerate Softbank for $ 32 billion. ARM technology, along with many other devices, is at the heart of most smartphones. Nvidia has promised to keep its business in the UK, hire more people and keep the ARM brand. He added that the deal would create &quot;the leading computing company for the era of artificial intelligence (AI)&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;ARM will continue to be based in Cambridge,&quot; said Jenson Huang, CEO of Nvidia. &quot;We will expand this great site and create world-class artificial intelligence research facilities to support developments in health care, life sciences, robotics, driverless cars and more.&quot;<br />\r\nA number of executives have signed open letters asking the Prime Minister to stop the merger. A senior government source told the BBC they would not block the sale but said conditions could apply to the takeover. Promises that &quot;don&#39;t matter&quot;<br />\r\nSoftbank has promised to create jobs through September next year and maintain ARM headquarters in the UK.<br />\r\n&quot;When you read the message from Nvidia, you have said so far that you will respect what Softbank was doing at the time,&quot; said Sonia Laud, head of investment, Legal &amp; General Investment Management.<br />\r\n&quot;But when the deadline ends and Brexit negotiations are clearly underway, it will be very interesting to see how this will develop in the future.&quot;<br />\r\nThis appears to raise concerns that British jobs will be lost and the decision will be shifted to the US. Last week, the Labor Party asked the government to intervene.<br />\r\nHowever, the two founders of ARM have raised other concerns regarding the acquisition.<br />\r\nHerman Hauser and Tudor Brown suggest that ARM remains &quot;neutral&quot; rather than owned by a company like Nvidia, which makes its own processors.<br />\r\nThere are concerns that a conflict of interest will arise as ARM customers become dependent on businesses also competing for sales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition, the two founders claim that Washington can try to prevent Chinese companies from using their expertise in larger trade disputes between countries because ARM is owned by US companies.<br />\r\n&quot;If ARM becomes an American subsidiary of an American company, it falls within the scope of the provisions of Cfius [Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States],&quot; Hauser told BBC Radio 4&#39;s Today.<br />\r\n&quot;[This] means that if hundreds of British companies that incorporate [ARM technology] into their products want to sell and export it anywhere in the world, including China - an important market - the decision to export is a hit will be made in the White House, not in Downing Street. &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nHe added that he believed that the pledge to maintain and increase the number of jobs in Britain would be &quot;meaningless&quot; unless British ministers stepped in to make it legally enforceable.<br />\r\nHowever, the managing director of ARM has reduced the risk of an export ban.<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s not about company ownership, it&#39;s about analyzing the product itself,&quot; Simon Segars told the BBC.<br />\r\n&quot;Most of our products are developed in the UK or outside the US and most of our products are not under many US export control rules.&quot;<br />\r\nMr Huang added that ARM has &quot;some of the best computer scientists in the world&quot; at Cambridge and intends to retain them and attract others to Nvidia&#39;s largest location in Europe.<br />\r\nChip manufacturer<br />\r\nARM creates computer chip designs that others can then customize for their own purposes. Instruction sets are also being developed to define how the software controls the processor.<br />\r\nThe company is based in Cambridge but also has offices around the world, including a joint venture in Shenzhen, China.<br />\r\nHundreds of companies have licensed their innovations, including Apple, Samsung, Huawei and Qualcomm. To date, 180 billion chips have been produced based on his decision, according to ARM.<br />\r\nWhen Softbank took over ARM, it promised to maintain the company&#39;s UK headquarters and increase the number of local jobs, which it managed to do.<br />\r\nSoftbank founder Masayoshi Son described the company as a &quot;crystal ball&quot; that would help him predict where the technology was going. However, the downsides from other investments, including office rental company WeWork, have led to a rethink.<br />\r\nCalifornia-based Nvidia takes over Intel and becomes the world&#39;s most valuable chip maker in July.<br />\r\nSo far, it has specialized in high-end graphics processors (GPUs). They are widely used by gamers to provide more detailed graphics, as well as by professionals for tasks such as research, machine learning, and extracting cryptocurrency.<br />\r\nNvidia is also an ARM customer and uses its project to develop Tegra CPUs.<br />\r\nUnder the agreement, Nvidia Softbank will pay $ 21.5 billion in treasury stock and $ 12 billion in cash. This will generate an additional $ 5 billion in cash or stock if certain goals are achieved.<br />\r\nNvidia will also spend $ 1.5 billion in capital for ARM employees.<br />\r\nServer chip<br />\r\nMr Huang previously said that one of the changes he wanted to make was to accelerate the development of ARM designs for processors used in computer servers, which is a fast growing sector.<br />\r\nHowever, experts say that Nvidia&#39;s risk is that the acquisition could push ARM&#39;s broader list to focus on competitive chip technologies that are lagging in terms of adoption but have an advantage they don&#39;t have. controlled by the company.<br />\r\n&quot;ARM is facing increasing competition from RISC-V, an open source architecture,&quot; wrote Geoff Blaber of CCS Insight in a recent study.<br />\r\n&quot;If partners believe that the integrity and independence of ARM is compromised, it will accelerate the growth of RISC-V and lower the value of ARM in the process.&quot;<br />\r\nMr Blaber also suggested that regulators block the deal.<br />\r\n&quot;This process will take months, if not years, with a high probability of failure,&quot; he told the BBC.<br />\r\nHuang said he expected it would take more than a year to &quot;train&quot; regulators and answer all their questions, but said he had &quot;full confidence&quot; that they would eventually approve the investment.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'UK Based, Chip Design', 'Arm design_1600095477.jpg', '2020-09-14 18:57:57', '2021-08-17 13:22:55'),
(598, 7, 6, 258, 'singapore-sells-covid-contact-tracing-tokens-1600095669', 'Singapore sells Covid contact tracing tokens', 0, '<p>Singapore has started distributing Bluetooth token contacts to its five million residents in an effort to curb the spread of Covid-19.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The token, which can be worn or carried on a strap, is a hardware version of an existing contact tracing app that launched in March.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like apps, they use Bluetooth to search for other users&#39; devices and then register any contacts with those devices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They may be popular with the elderly who don&#39;t use smartphones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The government also hopes the icon will help open up the economy further by restarting conferences and allowing better tracking of risky conditions such as busy hotels, cinemas and gyms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The initial spread occurred in areas with a higher concentration of elderly people who have a higher health risk than Covid-19 and are less likely to own smartphones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the symbol is available to all citizens, including foreigners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Singaporeans currently register at shops and office buildings using a separate SafeEntry system that uses a QR code to register user attendance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>SafeEntry now requires an application or token to be registered for some risky activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Better for privacy?</strong><br />\r\nAn adviser who was tapped by the government technology agency for feedback earlier that day said it was a better option for anyone concerned with confidentiality.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I prefer to use the tag on top of the application,&quot; said Bunny Huang, who queued up to get the tokens on the first day they became available.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Like the app, the information on the tokens is stored, regularly cleaned and uploaded - or in the case of a physically transferred token - to the Ministry of Health if the user has a positive test.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The token can be carried with a strap or in a pocket and does not require a mobile phone to function.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/803A/production/_114362823_gettyimages-1207755797.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coronavirus: The England-Wales contact tracing app gets a start date<br />\r\nTraceTogether: Singapore turned to Covid technology to trace contacts<br />\r\nThe advantage of the hardware version, according to Huang, is that the software update cannot contain secret location data or other sensors without the user being aware of it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;With the token, I know how to destroy it if I want,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The token will also help protect people who don&#39;t have smartphones and people who struggle with the app&#39;s functionality, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Worldwide applications<br />\r\nSingapore was the first government to introduce a tracking application at the national level in March.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since then, around 2.4 million people have downloaded the app, with around 1.4 million using it in August.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Singapore government data has long known that this number must be increased in order for applications and tags to be implemented.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the Ministry of Health said the program helped reduce the time it takes to identify and quarantine close contacts in Covid-19 cases from four to two days.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The city-state is more enthusiastic about contact tracing apps than many other countries which have been slower to implement or try to make good use of them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>England and Wales, for example, will not display their apps later this month, while Australia is struggling to get information from apps that don&#39;t go through regular contact tracing.</p>', 'Singapore, Covid', 'singapore_1600095669.jpg', '2020-09-14 19:01:09', '2021-11-02 00:35:55'),
(599, 7, 6, 141, 'unemployment-layoffs-planned-to-be-double-from-the-last-recession-1600095931', 'Unemployment: Layoffs planned to be double from the last recession', 0, '<p><strong>Businessmen in Britain are planning more than twice as many cuts as they did amid the recent recession, new data show.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>About 180,000 jobs were cut off between January and March 2009, and 380,000 between May and July this year. The cuts could reach 735,000 in the fall, say the researchers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This figure comes from a request for information from the Institute for Employment Research (IES). Social distancing measures to prevent the spread of Covid-19 have halted much of the UK economy, forced workers to stay at home, closed shops and stopped transportation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a result, many companies have been forced to consider reducing their workforce by forcing employees to be laid off. Employers in England, Scotland and Wales must notify the Bankruptcy Office if they intend to fire 20 or more workers at each &quot;company&quot; using a form called HR1.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This information is usually not published, but on September 8, the BBC&#39;s request for freedom of information revealed that employers registered more than 380,000 vulnerable jobs between May and July 2020.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This suggests that the current wave of redundancy is more than double the previous quarterly high of 180,000 from January to March 2009.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Then the crisis in the financial sector affected a large part of the economy - and forced many employers to lay off their staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Comparing events to the events of the last recession shows that we are experiencing a crisis at work that we have never seen before,&quot; said Tony Wilson, director of IES.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>IES is calling for additional support for eligible businesses to retain employees, as well as training and advice to help those who have lost their jobs find new jobs quickly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A government spokesman said: &quot;Supporting jobs is an absolute priority. That&#39;s why we are implementing a comprehensive work plan to protect, create and support jobs in the UK by providing significant and targeted support where it is most needed.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Government actions include a &pound; 2 billion &quot;startup program&quot; to encourage employers to create new apprenticeships and apprenticeships, additional trainers to work in employment offices, and a &pound; 1,000 incentive for employers to encourage people to return from work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Will these planned layoffs be completed?<br />\r\nSince form HR1 was submitted early in the redundancy process, it provides an early indication of what&#39;s going on in the labor market.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The number of layoffs for HR1 does not include employers who have laid off less than 20 jobs. Therefore, the total number of layoffs is usually higher.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The National Bureau of Statistics also publishes the number of layoffs based on labor force surveys, which are used to calculate the monthly unemployment rate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are always published months after the data is collected, so there hasn&#39;t been a big increase in layoffs or unemployment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the redundancy rate is about 20% higher than the HR1 figure in recent years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On that basis, the IES estimates that 445,000 jobs could be cut between July and September, which is significantly worse than the quarterly peak of the previous recession.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During this recession, however, the actual reduction is 80% higher than the reported reduction - which could result in some 735,000 layoffs amid the coronavirus crisis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, companies sometimes announce layoffs from plans that they won&#39;t change when things change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For example, at the beginning of 2019 there was a big leap in the layoff plan that had not been implemented. Wilson believes that without their deal could be linked to Brexit fears, which never happened.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The peak in 2018 could be attributed to the collapse of construction company Carillion, which had less impact on jobs than initially feared.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Northern Irish businesses submitted form HR1 to the Northern Ireland Statistics and Research Agency and are not included in these figures.</p>', 'unemployment, recession', 'Unemployment_1600095931.jpg', '2020-09-14 19:05:31', '2021-09-23 08:14:58'),
(600, 7, 6, 149, 'wetherspoon-66-positive-employees-in-50-pubs-1600096026', 'Wetherspoon: 66 positive employees in 50 pubs', 0, '<p><strong>JD Wetherspoon said 66 of his workers had tested positive for the coronavirus but the pub was safe to visit.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The company, which employs more than 41,000 people, said most of its pubs have not yet tested positive for the virus. There have been one or more cases among employees in its 50 pubs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Weatherspon boss Tim Martin dismissed claims made by pediatrician Professor Hugh Pennington that the pub was &quot;dangerous&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said: &quot;The situation about pubs is largely misunderstood.&quot; Last month, Professor Pennington of the University of Aberdeen said pubs were &quot;a much more dangerous place&quot; for getting children back to school during the pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since opening on July 4, some 32 million people have visited the 861 open pubs, according to the company.<br />\r\nIts 40 pubs reported that one worker tested positive for the coronavirus and six found two.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additionally, two pubs reported that three employees tested positive and two others said they had four employees.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Cleaning practice</strong><br />\r\nA Wetherspoon spokesperson said the pub was not closed for a thorough cleaning. The company said it had invested &pound; 15 million in hygiene and social distancing measures at the site.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The spokesman said, &quot;The advice Weatherspoon received from health officials is that employees should isolate themselves if they come into close contact with someone who has a positive test result. Close contact means within 2 meters in 15 minutes or more or 1 meter. for 1 minute or so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In our experience, health officials generally do not recommend closings unless social distancing guidelines are followed.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added that since the company pub opened, &quot;staff have cleaned surfaces regularly and many hand sanitizers have been installed in each pub&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said that every room was cleaned during trade and at the end of the day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to Weatherspun, 28 of the affected employees have returned to work. A company spokesman said the workers, as well as those working around them, had been isolated for 14 days and received full wages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The chain said signing off on the NHS tracking and tracking system was mandatory on their premises.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A company spokesman said there was no list of affected pubs. &quot;Whenever there is a situation, we look at the local press, public health and the council,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rule six<br />\r\nMr Martin said pubs and shops are safer than homes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s much easier to accidentally pass the virus on to homes where people are calmer and less alert,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As of Monday, social gatherings of more than six people had been banned both indoors and outdoors in England and Scotland and only indoors in Wales.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This follows an increase in new cases of the corona virus. Another 3,330 positive cases were reported in the UK on Sunday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Martin said no influx of people came into his restaurant before the so-called &quot;rule of six&quot; was introduced and it was trading 22.5% below the equivalent on Saturday last year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added, &quot;If pubs are closed or restricted in such a way as to become unprofitable, most of the hard work of the 3.2 million hotel workers currently working to maintain hygiene and social standards to maintain distance will be lost.&quot;</p>', 'Wetherspoon, 66 positive', '66 staff corona_1600096026.jpg', '2020-09-14 19:07:06', '2021-08-16 15:05:57'),
(602, 7, 2, 110, 'valentinos-couture-collection-was-an-extreme-response-to-the-pandemic-1600322453', 'Valentino\'s couture collection was an \'extreme response\' to the pandemic', 0, '<p>Valentino&#39;s fall 2020 haute couture collection sets the bar high for what can be achieved with trackshows while the lockdown measures are still in place.<br />\r\nWhile the coronavirus pandemic is forcing fashion houses to rethink seasonal presentations, Pierpaolo Piccioli, Valentino&#39;s Creative Director, puts on a live performance that only a handful of local audiences attend. The show takes place at the famous Roman studio Cinecitt&agrave; - Europe&#39;s largest film production studio. It was broadcast live on the brand&#39;s website to showcase a new collection that had become popular with labels unable to host major events.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200722085446-restricted-01-valentino-haute-couture-fall.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nBut what sparked the industry was the level of artistic attention paid to Valentino&#39;s performances, which turned them from standard track coverage to a kind of &quot;live film.&quot;<br />\r\nThe live video, titled &quot;Of Grace and Light,&quot; was shot in collaboration with British photographer Nick Knight and features unreleased music from the FKA branch. It shows the graceful movements of the models on a dark stage, as if they are swaying in the wind.<br />\r\nUnlike the aerial circus troupe, the models sit on air rings or on twisted cords, as they show off dramatic long white dresses that stand out in completely black surroundings. Each model plays with spotlights and color graphics projected onto the outfit and is bathed in light so that the viewer can take advantage of the exaggerated silhouettes of silk, sequins and tulle.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200722085832-restricted-02-valentino-haute-couture-fall.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nDuring a virtual press conference, Piccioli said the collection of 16 types of fashion styles was an &quot;extreme response&quot; to the harsh realities of closure, as well as the difficulty of making intricate prints and embroidery in remote social distancing settings.<br />\r\n&quot;The silhouette is very long and radicalized to show manual dexterity,&quot; the Italian home said in a statement.<br />\r\nWhile other fashion brands are struggling to get the most out of the digital platform, Piccioli&#39;s dream presentation stole the show and offers plans for other brands to want to take full advantage of the online possibilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200722090151-restricted-04-valentino-haute-couture-fall.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\n&quot;I don&#39;t want to feel boundaries. Fashion is made for emotions, dreams,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Valentionos counture, extreme response', 'Valentionos_1600322453.jpg', '2020-09-17 10:00:53', '2021-08-18 03:52:56'),
(603, 7, 2, 98, 'supermodel-joan-smalls-promises-half-her-salary-for-black-lives-matter-and-urges-the-industry-to-do-the-same-1600323140', 'Supermodel Joan Smalls promises half her salary for Black Lives Matter - and urges the industry to do the same', 0, '<p>Anti-racist protests occur every day around the world and the online fashion industry is at the forefront of controversies regarding offensive business and creative practices.<br />\r\nStamps and publications requested by former employees for discrimination, and statements of solidarity, including the use of black boxes on social media to support Black Lives Matter, are seen as empty signals for systemic racism in the industry.<br />\r\nIn response to the current climate, supermodel Joan Smalls has decided to take action - and she&#39;s urging others to follow suit.<br />\r\nSmalls pledged half of their salary to the Black Lives Matter organization for the remainder of 2020 and launched DonateMyWage.org to encourage the fashion and entertainment industry to donate a percentage of their salary - from hourly to yearly - to the organization of their choice.<br />\r\nIn a film published on Donatemywages.org, 31-year-old Puerto Rican-born Smalls speaks directly about the issue of racial discrimination in the fashion industry.<br />\r\n&quot;I see all the agencies, magazines, and brands posting black screens on their Instagram accounts. But what does that really mean? What is the fashion industry really going to do about it? It&#39;s just another trend?&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;This industry that uses our black and brown bodies, our constant culture of inspiration, our music and visualization images are available to us,&quot; he continued. &quot;They are part of a cycle that supports this conscious behavior.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;You continue to disappoint us with your insensitivity and deaf tone and your excuses for damage control &#39;We&#39;ll do better&#39;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200622090109-restricted-01-joan-smalls-runway-0221.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nDescribing herself as a &quot;black and Latin American woman&quot;, Smalls has built a very successful modeling career over the last decade and says she has had a &quot;constant battle&quot; against racism during her &quot;day-to-day&quot; career in the industry. guided. That includes photographers who don&#39;t want to photograph them &quot;because you don&#39;t have to shoot black girls,&quot; versus magazines, brands, and agencies who continue to work with people &quot;of that mindset,&quot; stylists, and casting directors who don&#39;t work with. color models because they &quot;don&#39;t treat us fairly and want to give us a chance&quot;.<br />\r\nSmalls said the list of people in the industry participating in racism was &quot;on the go&quot;.<br />\r\nSmalls was the first person on Latinx for beauty brand Est&eacute;e Lauder in 2011 and the first woman of color to appear on the cover of Porter magazine in 2015. She has been a fixed model on the Forbes list of highest paid models since 2013. Here.<br />\r\nAnd while he explains in the film that the sustained attitude of people who have shown racist ideas is a form of engagement that feeds &quot;the beast of racism and inequality&quot;, he is also grateful for the people in the industry who do. has supported.<br />\r\n&quot;With the same breath I want to acknowledge those who saw me for me, who fought for me. I salute you ... Thank you for being true to your morals and not letting others prevent you. What you know, was the right decision.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F190910105749-tom-ford-nyfw.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nFinally, Smalls says she doesn&#39;t need &quot;the approval of an industry that defines me as a symbolic black girl while ignoring my entire cultural identity.&quot; Instead, he&#39;s looking for &quot;identifying system problems, problems that come from the top down in the industry.&quot;<br />\r\nLook to the future. Smalls said of his &quot;favorite fashion industry&quot; that &quot;this is your chance. When you talk and show that if you care, if you really care, show ... We see you. See you. You we are now?&quot;<br />\r\nIn addition to donating half his salary at the end of the year, Smalls is committed to holding the brands he works for accountable for its own actions, encouraging financial donations and implementing policies that actively encourage inclusion. advance. &quot;If I can do that as individuals, imagine what we can do as a team to be the positive change the world needs.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;I urge you to use your voice and your infrastructure to help us,&quot; he said. &quot;I urge all of you to stand with us. Together we are stronger.&quot;</p>', 'SuperModel Joan, Black Lives', 'super model_1600323140.jpg', '2020-09-17 10:12:20', '2021-08-12 00:09:57'),
(604, 7, 7, 94, 'two-giant-snakes-fell-from-the-ceiling-of-the-australian-kitchen-1600323831', 'Two giant snakes fell from the ceiling of the Australian kitchen', 0, '<p><strong>A man in Brisbane, Australia returned home to find two giant snakes that fell through his kitchen ceiling on Monday.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Carpet pythons are about 2.9 meters (9.5 feet) and 2.5 meters (8.2 feet) tall, according to North Brisbane Snake Catcher and relocation snake hunter Stephen Brown who removed them from the property.<br />\r\n&quot;These two snakes are two of the fattest snakes I have ever seen and the amount of muscle they have,&quot; Brown told News channel, adding that they were &quot;very well fed.&quot;<br />\r\nThe snake hunter posted a surprising find on Facebook, including some stunning photos.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200901043808-04-brisbane-carpet-pythons-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Snake hunter Stephen Brown told News channel that the pair were &quot;two of the fattest snakes I have ever seen&quot;.<br />\r\nIn the Post, Brown revealed that his client had found two very large pythons on a beach carpet when he returned home.<br />\r\n&quot;When I got there, I found that they had crumbled through the ceiling of the customer in the kitchen,&quot; he wrote.<br />\r\nWhen Brown arrived, he found one row at the front door and another in the bedroom, he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200901043855-05-brisbane-carpet-pythons-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe snake hit the ceiling.<br />\r\nThe snake hunter told News channel&nbsp;that it is snake mating season, and the two men will likely be fighting for a nearby woman who may be on the roof or somewhere in the house.<br />\r\n&quot;I couldn&#39;t check for roof vacancies because there was no room to crawl between the roof and the ceiling,&quot; said Brown, who said snakes are common in warm, dry roof cavities during the colder winter months.<br />\r\nChiton snakes are non-venomous and not aggressive when left alone, Brown said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200901043603-02-brisbane-carpet-pythons-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nChocolate in photo with two snakes.<br />\r\n&quot;No snake wants to hurt anyone,&quot; he added, but they would defend themselves when threatened.<br />\r\nThe creatures were taken to a state forest, 1 kilometer from the man&#39;s house, Brown said.<br />\r\nSnakes are not uncommon in Australian homes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200828021036-australia-snake-toilet-medium-plus-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nLast month, a woman in north Queensland who was struggling to flush her toilet was surprised to find four snakes in a tub of water.<br />\r\n25-year-old Sophie Pearson, who lives on a sugar cane plantation, told News channel that when she got into her bathroom, she had to press a button hard for the toilet to work.<br />\r\n&quot;I&#39;m a little confused,&quot; he told 7News. &quot;So I decided to take off the top and see what the problem was.&quot;<br />\r\nWhat he found were four common tree snakes, the largest one being 1 meter long, reports 7News.</p>', 'Gaint Snakes, Australia', 'Huge Snake_1600323817.jpg', '2020-09-17 10:23:37', '2021-08-17 14:31:57'),
(605, 7, 2, 129, 'the-young-designer-is-tearing-down-the-steering-wheel-to-empower-women-1600324428', 'The young designer is tearing down the steering wheel to empower women', 0, '<p>Starting a fashion brand is difficult. Launching a fashion brand during a global pandemic is nearly impossible.<br />\r\nTeniola &quot;Tia&quot; Adeola made her debut at New York Fashion Week about a month before the new coronavirus hit major fashion capitals and effectively brought the global fashion industry to its knees. The Adeola fashion show in February provided the opportunity to introduce the newly founded brand with the same name to the world. Its design - youthful, sexy, transparent and disheveled - caught the attention of the fashion press and gave it a &quot;One to Watch&quot; status.<br />\r\nIn the days after the show, the young designer was at the top of the saying, staying three nights before it finally crashed.<br />\r\nAnd then everything changed. Adeola returned to his family home in Lagos, Nigeria to get rid of the worst locks.<br />\r\n&quot;It tastes very sweet,&quot; said Adeola, who was returning to his studio in Manhattan. &quot;I&#39;m so grateful and grateful to be in quarantine with my family, but from moving studios to sharing a room with my sister ... it&#39;s just a lot.&quot;<br />\r\nHe spent the first month like he was completely at a standstill, taking time to grieve. But finally Adeola returned to work. When he thought about what he had done again, he said emphatically, &quot;I represent the generation that will change the world.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200813111447-tia-adeola-fashion-designer-6.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nWith the mission, he returned, looked at the paintings for hours on end, and reconnected with his original references to art history, which inspired a series of face masks with an autographed steering wheel.<br />\r\nAdeola&#39;s Rudder is a subversive answer to the art history book he first studied in school. As she tells, her dissertation analyzes Spanish dresses from the 16th century in exquisite paintings. On researching work from this period, he found that the drawings did not depict black people unless they were depicted as slaves or fools. While this sticks to her, she says it doesn&#39;t detract from the fact that the clothes in the photos are beautiful.<br />\r\n&quot;The way artists manage to get textures, fabrics and materials down with strokes is amazing to me,&quot; he said. &quot;And frills - they were called frills back then and were made with starch ... the bigger your steering wheel, the higher you are in society.&quot;<br />\r\nThe Adeola steering wheel is doing something to get back that piece of history. She is working on her own designs and has put the power of expression in the hands of a young and diverse community of women. And the community has some well-known members: Gigi Hadid, Dua Lipa, and Face all wearing their clothes.<br />\r\nBesides celebrities, Adeola came up with the idea to surround himself with women. &quot;There would be no Tia without women in my community who support me and make everything possible,&quot; he said. &quot;People turn to the brand&#39;s Instagram page and see amazing photos they like, but they don&#39;t realize there&#39;s a makeup artist, she&#39;s got a hairdresser, she&#39;s got a photographer, she&#39;s got an assistant too. All these women in my neighborhood come to my mind. when I made this dress. &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nAdeola will not appear during New York Fashion Week this September, but is working on a short film due for release later this fall. As the challenges of the pandemic continue, the designer is not clear on the road, but one thing is certain: he is determined to keep going and let the steering wheel in the way.</p>', 'Young Designer, Empower Women', 'Young Fashion_1600324428.jpg', '2020-09-17 10:33:48', '2021-08-15 20:06:15'),
(606, 7, 2, 137, 'new-york-fashion-week-is-back-with-a-social-and-digital-distant-event-1600325813', 'New York Fashion Week is back with a social and digital distant event', 0, '<p>It will be a fashion month like no other. The coronavirus pandemic has replaced traditional track formats and been replaced by a combination of virtual broadcasts and, in some cases, physical broadcasts with limited audiences.<br />\r\nNew York Fashion Week (NYFW) runs from September 13-17 in front of London, Milan and Paris.<br />\r\nOrganizers adapted to the situation by organizing a series of outdoor events. Jason Wu opened the schedule with a show at the Spring Studios runway in Manhattan. She presented her spring-summer 2021 collection to a socially distant crowd of just 30, sending models like India Moore in a complete set inspired by the Mexican city of Tulum.<br />\r\nHarlem&#39;s Fashion Row, a platform established to promote fashion diversity through the support of color designers, kicked off NYFW Sunday with a virtual presentation of a collection by black designers Kristian Lor&eacute;n, Kimberly Goldson and Rich Fresh.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200914030632-04-new-york-fashion-week.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nReturning designers include Anna Sui and Chromat with digital presentations, while a number of well-known NYFW professionals such as Michael Kors will not be attending this time.<br />\r\nTo broadcast virtual events, the Fashion Designers Council of America (CFDA) created Runway360, a digital platform for displaying new collections or other creative projects. And although regular fashion week will be very different this year, switching to virtual could lead to a more sustainable presentation - a recent Ordre report, which specializes in online showrooms, found that international fashion weeks emit similar amounts of greenhouse gases. . per year as a small country.<br />\r\nThe digital format also allows aspiring designers to shine without all the usual hierarchies. Stephen Kolb, CEO of CFDA, said 10 new US brands will be showcased this week, including mother and child avant-garde luxury brands Dur Doux and Oak &amp; Acorn, a Harlem-based sustainable denim brand that creates bold and asexual styles.<br />\r\nThis new approach also left room for non-standard labels to develop their creative muscles, including the band Imitation of Christ, which was just formed from the early 2000s. The conceptual fashion group that worked on clothing before the practice&#39;s name returned to the charts nearly 20 years after hosting a Gothic show at a New York funeral home (Chloe Sevigny was a noted participant in the original iteration).<br />\r\nAccording to the NYFW, London Fashion Week on September 17 will also see a combination of live and digital events as organizers combat restrictions on the new coronavirus imposed in Britain following a recent spike in new cases. And despite growing fears that a new wave of Covid-19 cases will emerge in parts of Europe, Milan and Paris are still planning some physical shows later this month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200914002203-03-new-york-fashion-week-0913.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe popular social media app TikTok aims to attract a Gen Z audience through its own online fashion month and is teaming up with labels such as Louis Vuitton, Alice + Olivia, and Saint Laurent to broadcast songs live. and presentation of the capsule collection.qw 7&nbsp;</p>', 'Newyork fashion, digital distant', 'Newyork_1600325813.jpg', '2020-09-17 10:56:53', '2021-08-12 00:05:51');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(607, 7, 2, 134, 'cfda-fashion-awards-2020-winner-of-variety-in-the-events-39-year-history-1600327645', 'CFDA Fashion Awards 2020: Winner of \"Variety\" in the event\'s 39 year history', 0, '<p>Organizers of one of the most famous fashion award programs described this year&#39;s recipient as the &quot;most diverse group winner&quot; in the event&#39;s 39-year history.<br />\r\nThe CFDA Fashion Awards, often referred to as the Fashion Oscar, featured an online ceremony on Monday evening honoring a number of prominent black designers, including Haitian American Kerby Jean-Raymond, who brought home the coveted American menswear designer this year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200914143337-01-cfda-fashion-awards-2020-pyer-moss.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nOther celebrities recognized by the Council of American Fashion Designers (CFDA) include Christopher John Rodgers of New York, dressed as Michelle Obama and named American Designer of the Year. Liberian-American designer Telfar Clemens, meanwhile, was named Accessory Designer of the Year after winning a cult following for his signature bag, one of which was recognized by Congressman Alexandria Ocasio-Cortes on Capitol Hill. Of the six winners that night, only six BIPOC figures (black, local and colored) were included in the list of 30 strong candidates.<br />\r\nThe American designer for women&#39;s clothing - the most coveted award of the evening - goes to Uruguay-born Gabriela Hearst, a supporter of sustainable practices. Creative director Valentino Pierpaolo Piccioli has been named International Designer of the Year for Women, and Kim Jones, recently appointed as Karl Lagerfeld&#39;s successor to Italian label Fendi, has been named International Designer of the Year for Men.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200914143748-07-cfda-fashion-awards-2020-christopher-john-rogers.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nThe prestigious awards ceremony which was originally scheduled for June was initially postponed due to the coronavirus pandemic. Instead, organizers chose a virtual show to coincide with New York Fashion Week, which starts on Sunday evening. The number of prize categories has also been reduced from 11 to six, with this year&#39;s CFDA only focusing on designers and not models or other personalities in the industry.<br />\r\n&quot;The lack of a party allows us to focus on helping designers through the global pandemic and to focus our efforts on scholarships and bringing racial justice to fashion,&quot; said CFDA President and CFO Tom Ford in a statement on Runway360, a digital platform. A number of Fashion Week events take place here.<br />\r\nThis year&#39;s recipient joins a list of notable previous winners including Calvin Klein, Carolina Herrera and Rick Owens. Last year, Brandon Maxwell and The Row founders Mary-Kate and Ashley Olsen took home the best honor, while Jennifer Lopez received the Fashion Icon Award.</p>', 'CFDA Fashion AwarD, 2020', 'cfda Fashion_1600327645.jpg', '2020-09-17 11:27:25', '2021-08-18 00:54:48'),
(608, 7, 2, 137, 'how-the-famous-stylist-beyonce-daniel-obassi-used-fashion-to-create-endless-prospects-for-the-future-1600329202', 'How the famous stylist Beyonc Daniel Obassi used fashion to create endless prospects for the future', 0, '<p>Daniel Obassi believes in the power of Instagram. A versatile creative person who has taken portraits for the New York Times and Billboard and designed fashion editions for Vogue Portugal and Dazed has long used this platform to connect with like-minded people from the world of art and fashion.<br />\r\nThis last year linked him with his most famous counterpart to date. &quot;I received a DM from (Kwasi Fordjour), Beyonc&eacute;&#39;s creative director, and said she would be interested in this upcoming project,&quot; said Obassi by telephone from Lagos. Then he said, &quot;Oh, this is for Bay&quot; and I said, &quot;Excuse me?&quot; &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200819115250-03-beyonce-black-is-king-style-restricted.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nBeyonc&eacute;&#39;s undisclosed project is the visual album &quot;Black Is King&quot;, the companion of which was criticized in last year&#39;s remake of &quot;The Lion King&quot;. The production, which the singer calls a celebration of &quot;the breadth and beauty of the black family,&quot; offers a versatile combination of African artists and artists as well as artists from the diaspora, both on camera and behind the scenes.<br />\r\nInitially Obassi suggested that Forjur help him in the research process. Instead, he was hired to work with a team of Nigerian artists to help talented talent in the Lagos scene. &quot;We actually talked on the phone the next day ... Next, I knew we were filming and the style, and then the video came out,&quot; he said. &quot;I didn&#39;t like it until the credit came in. &#39;OK, it really happened.&#39;<br />\r\nLooking back at personal projects 25 years earlier, Black is King - an Afro-futuristic vision of a world in which black and African artists are celebrated and whose traditions come to the fore - is a fitting committee. Over the past three years, Obassi has used fashion, photography and film for similar purposes.<br />\r\nIn short films such as Alien in the City and Strike, as well as in photo series such as Lagos Futurism, he combines traditional, modern and imaginary to create Nigeria free from the constraints of political and social realities. Dark skin, Afro hair, and beautiful clothes (often by local designers) abound, and a diversity of gender and sexuality is evident.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://dynaimage.cdn.cnn.com/cnn/q_auto,w_727,c_fit/http%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200818141307-daniel-obasi-nigerian-stylist-2.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAs part of a growing cultural scene in Lagos, Obassi has the opportunity to work with other Nigerian talents to make Beyonc&eacute;&#39;s vision a reality, including superstar Afrobeat Mr. Easy and Thebes Savage (both shot for Billboard June 2020) and designers Emmy Kasbit, Lanre Da Silva and Tola Adegbite from Turfah, with whom he has worked in the past.<br />\r\n&ldquo;This project is just a collection of people I love, people I respect, people who are my friends, people whose work I grew up as an artist. Great, like, &#39;You too? Oh wow! Oh my God , yes! &rdquo;he said.<br />\r\nSpeaking to CNN, Obassi shared his thoughts on community, fashion and the limitless possibilities of the imagination.<br />\r\nDaniel Obassi: Yes, you could say that, because this is a very contemporary work that talks about changes in African history. My work has always been tied to the fact that (African) stories are best told by Africans. We all have different experiences, but in all this diversity and under this difference, we still have things that tie us all together, you know?<br />\r\n(For me) It gives all of us this new opportunity to really work together and create beautiful works across all our different interfaces. It&#39;s always been about figuring out how to do this.<br />\r\nSome film critics disagree with this framework of cross-cultural exchange, pointing out that the lack of specificity that results from borrowing and combining different African cultures is problematic.<br />\r\nI wouldn&#39;t say it is cross-cultural in that sense because the creative direction comes from its end. Rather, it&#39;s about the fact that even a country like Nigeria is so diverse and has so many tribes. On a typical day, many of these tribes tend to live side by side not only for political reasons, but because of everything that has happened before all of us. So Black Is King united us all.<br />\r\nWhen we try to play the role of &quot;Key to the Kingdom&quot; (when the prince marries his master from childhood), it is very important to find a structure that speaks of Nigeria as a country. The place, the National Theater for the Arts (in Lagos), makes it really beautiful because it&#39;s a structure we can all look at and say, &quot;Oh my God, this is Nigeria.&quot;<br />\r\nWhen you look at artists making work from Ghana, when you see artists making work from South Africa, when you look at videos they are working on, you can see the power in the specificity of the culture. see where they are.<br />\r\nFor me this is an imaginary space where everything is infinite. In this room you can explore your past, future, and current ideas.<br />\r\nMany of them have to do with the fact that when we were growing up, we (Nigerians) didn&#39;t really have many references to futurism in our culture or in the stories they told us. In addition, much of our history is lost or damaged, even making the past feel very hazy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Afrofuturism gives you this space to determine for yourself what your future holds and what you believe in. Often it feels very personal. I love to see cases in culture, in society, in politics, in things that I and the people I know went through as I grew up creating my own alternative reality. Many of the works and stories we see today are either very negative or very contradictory, so Afrofuturism can be a space of healing, a space where you can run away and believe that things can get better.<br />\r\nWhen did you first recognize the power of imaging and fashion as a tool for building the world?<br />\r\nWhen I was young I was in a lot of amazing stories that we grew up with like (Nigerian Kids TV Show) (Moonlight Stories), about the animal kingdom where animals can talk and other things that would happen on a normal day wouldn&#39;t real; and stories and books like writers painting a world that doesn&#39;t look like anything you saw when you left the house. Its brightness and specificity allow you to see that thoughts are really very powerful.<br />\r\nOne of the things I love about fashion is the fact that it works that way. You can walk into this space and get inspired by the idea of shape or form, using materials or clothing to create a style, look or feel that doesn&#39;t exist, and people will relate to it or not. It depends on how far you can think or how well you can strengthen your imagination.<br />\r\nIn your films and photos, you often try to lift and find beauty in historically marginalized groups. What political potential does the production of an image like this have?<br />\r\nI think the most important thing about pictures is that they talk a lot. You don&#39;t even have to say much about a good picture. I like to think about what we are doing in and about ourselves with subtle and calm activism.<br />\r\nWhen we talk about beauty in this country - or even the world - we have issues that are visually linked to skin politics and gender. We work in a very materialistic industry and see image as (a reflection of one&#39;s point of view). Therefore, it is very important for me to differentiate (my work) as a platform and use it to say what I want to say.<br />\r\nI&#39;m talking about natural hair; I really (realized) that I wasn&#39;t spending any more touching on the skin to reveal the beauty of what black skin looks like. In terms of gender, I have always positioned women in positions of strength, power and beauty. and when you look at masculinity, weirdness, and all that, society teaches you that you can&#39;t be so masculine.<br />\r\nThese are things we experience every day. So it&#39;s important that I always find a way to put this forward in one way or another. We&#39;re in a place where everyone&#39;s nice to talk about these things, but three years ago it wasn&#39;t very good.<br />\r\nThis year alone you did &quot;Black Is King,&quot; a stylish editorial for Dazed and The Face, and featured in i-D magazine. What do you want to achieve next?<br />\r\nI love making experimental films so I think this is the next film I hope to work on soon. In terms of goals, I try to strengthen myself not only as a creative person, but also as an entrepreneur. Besides, I don&#39;t know. Everything can fly from anywhere.</p>', 'Beyonce Daniel Obassi, future', 'Daniyal famous designer_1600329202.jpg', '2020-09-17 11:53:22', '2021-12-19 17:29:16'),
(609, 7, 12, 151, 'trump-denies-the-history-of-the-cdcs-vaccines-and-head-masks-1600330484', 'Trump denies the history of the CDC\'s vaccines and head masks', 0, '<p>President Donald Trump has again denied claims by health officials regarding the coronavirus - this time about the importance of wearing masks and the timing of getting vaccinated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And he belittled Dr. Robert Redfield, director of the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, said doctors were &quot;confused&quot; by the statement from Congress.<br />\r\nRedfield said on Wednesday that masks could provide more effective protection against the coronavirus than a vaccine President Hippie may not be able to stop. And he set a timetable for when the general public in the US can expect the outcome of the widespread coronavirus vaccination in the second or third quarter of 2021. Both statements appear to contradict what Trump said.<br />\r\n&quot;I can even say further that this mask protects me more from Covid than if I got the Covid vaccine because the immunogenicity can be 70%. And if I don&#39;t get an immune response, the vaccine won&#39;t protect me. This face mask Redfield told lawmakers during public testimony, adding that the American public has not accepted the use of masks to a level that can control the outbreak effectively.<br />\r\nIn response to testimony from the Redfield Congress, Trump stepped forward against the doctor he appointed to lead the CDC and challenged the agency&#39;s head on two counts: the coronavirus vaccination schedule and the effectiveness of masks versus vaccinations. .<br />\r\nRedfield told the Budget Committee on Wednesday, &quot;If you ask me when it will be publicly available to the American public so we can use the vaccine to return to our normal lives, we might think of a third.&quot; end of second quarter, third quarter of 2021. &quot;<br />\r\nThe president told reporters that Redfield was &quot;confused&quot; when he said this.<br />\r\n&quot;I think he made a mistake in saying that. It&#39;s just misinformation,&quot; Trump said.<br />\r\nThe president also said Redfield&#39;s comments to Congress about masks being likely to be more effective than vaccines were incorrect and that Redfield may have misunderstood the problem.<br />\r\n&quot;Maybe he was wrong,&quot; Trump said, adding later. &quot;As for masks, I hope the vaccine is much more useful than masks.&quot;<br />\r\nRedfield said in a statement about his masked testimony that he believed in &quot;the importance of vaccines and in particular the importance of the Covid-19 vaccine&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;The Covid-19 vaccine is what will bring Americans back to normal. The best protection we have right now against this virus is through major efforts to reduce mask wear, hand washing, distance and attention, he said, without referring to claims. Trump, that he&#39;s confused.<br />\r\nA CDC spokesman made a statement in response to Trump&#39;s comments about the vaccine and appeared to support the president&#39;s statement.<br />\r\n&quot;At today&#39;s trial, Dr. Redfield answered the question of how long it took all Americans to complete their vaccination against Covid, and his estimate was in the second or third quarter of 2021. He was not referring to the duration of the Covid-19 dose. A vaccine will be available for all Americans, &quot;said the spokesman.<br />\r\nThis is not the first time Trump has forced Redfield to reconsider its response to the pandemic.<br />\r\nEarlier this year, Trump said Redfield misquoted in the Washington Post before doctors confirmed his quote was correct.<br />\r\nThe commute comes a day after the Trump White House held a peace treaty ceremony with senior officials from three countries who largely ignore distancing and social disguise guidelines - and the president called it awkward and unjustifiable being part of the &quot;servant&quot;. A group of people who are not wearing masks to prevent the spread of the virus.<br />\r\nDespite repeated calls from the CDC for Americans to wear masks to prevent the spread of the coronavirus, Trump said Tuesday night at ABC City Hall: &quot;There are a lot of people who believe masks are not good.&quot;<br />\r\nWhen asked for specific examples, Trump answered Kellner.<br />\r\n&quot;They come, they serve you and they have masks. And I saw them a few days ago when they served me and played with masks. I don&#39;t blame them. ... They play with masks. ... They touch them and then they hit the plate. Not that could be good, &quot;Trump said.<br />\r\nThe president sometimes wears a mask and says it&#39;s important. But his actions sent a different message to his supporters: the White House and Trump re-election campaigns also ignored CDC guidelines, government guidelines and local health officials, leaving large crowds of athletes standing side by side and wearing no masks.<br />\r\nOther senior health officials in the Trump administration, including Adm. Brett Giroard, Assistant Secretary of Health and Human Services, and Dr. Bob Cadletz, assistant secretary for preparedness and response for the Department of Health and Human Services, also testified on Wednesday of the importance of wearing masks to prevent the spread of the coronavirus.<br />\r\nAfter Trump questioned the effectiveness of ABC masks, spokeswoman Kaylee McEnnany told reporters Wednesday that the president &quot;has always supported wearing masks&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;Yesterday he quoted an incident recorded by Dr. (Anthony) Fauci, which means that masks can have unintended consequences. While we support wearing and being patriotic, the unintended consequence can be improper use,&quot; Makinani said.</p>', 'Trump, CDC', 'Donald Trump_1600330484.jpg', '2020-09-17 12:14:44', '2021-08-12 00:12:58'),
(610, 7, 12, 145, 'the-call-to-block-the-coronavirus-is-the-greatest-violation-of-civil-liberties-as-opposed-to-slavery-in-us-history-according-to-the-bar-1600331021', 'The call to block the coronavirus is \"the greatest violation of civil liberties,\" as opposed to slavery in US history, according to the bar', 0, '<p><strong>Attorney General William Barr said on Wednesday that calling for a nationwide blockade to prevent the spread of the coronavirus was &quot;the biggest violation of civil liberties&quot; in history, &quot;apart from slavery&quot;.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The comments came minutes after he attacked hundreds of Justice Department lawyers working under him, likening them to preschool to defend his politically minded decisions in the Trump administration.<br />\r\nOn the occasion of the Constitution Day celebrations hosted by Hillsdale College, the host asked Barr to explain &quot;constitutional barriers to banning Church gatherings during Covid-19.&quot;<br />\r\nThat question led Bar to a four-minute answer in which he said state governors had used their executive powers to prevent citizens and businesses from returning to work.<br />\r\n&quot;You know, a nationwide lockdown on an order to stay at home is like house arrest. Apart from slavery, which is another type of restriction, it is the biggest violation of civil liberties in American history,&quot; said Bar. when the applause came. From the crowd.<br />\r\nCovid-19 has measured minority victims, including black people, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.<br />\r\nIn recent weeks, Barr has taken a much more aggressive stance, defending the Trump administration&#39;s policies, including arguing that postal voting is unsafe, attacking Mueller&#39;s investigation of Russian interference in the 2016 election, and criticizing the governor for responding to the coronavirus. &quot;Most managers do what bureaucrats always do, which is ... they go against common sense,&quot; Bar said Wednesday. &quot;They treat the free citizens of the country like babies who can&#39;t take responsibility for themselves and others.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;We have to give business people a chance to tell them what rules you know, what masks, what mask rules you have this month ... and then let them try to adapt their business to it and you will at least have the ingenuity and people. will be the only one having the freedom to earn a living, &quot;he added.<br />\r\nProsecutor<br />\r\nSince the end of the investigation, Mueller Barr has been badly beaten by Justice Department officials and even ordinary lawyers as he rocked the case in a way that undermined longstanding legal policy.<br />\r\nOn Wednesday he upped the stakes and compared it to preschool.<br />\r\n&quot;Name a successful organization or institution whose decisions of employees at the lowest level are considered sacred. There is no. There is no. Nobody allows the youngest members to set the agenda, &quot;said Bar during his speech.<br />\r\n&quot;This may be a good philosophy for a Montessori preschool, but there is no way to run a federal agency,&quot; added the attorney general.<br />\r\nHe noted that doing so is likely to spark strained relations between the politically appointed leadership of the Justice Department in Washington and professional lawyers across the country serving in various presidencies.<br />\r\nIt&#39;s noteworthy that some prosecutors failed to sign positions in court, which President Donald Trump and Bar wanted for their legislation, as in the criminal case against Roger Stone.<br />\r\nIn his speech, Bar questioned any criticism he received for &quot;meddling&quot; in the case. The Attorney General has the highest power, he said.<br />\r\n&quot;These people are agents of the Attorney General. As I said, FBI agents, whose agent do you think you are?&quot; Bar asked on Tuesday, adding that lawyers can also be influenced by politics in their careers. &quot;And I said, &#39;What exactly am I bothering with?&#39; &quot;If you cook it right away, it will be the desire of the youngest member of the organization who has the idea that she wants to do something. What makes it sacred? &quot;&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;They don&#39;t have the political legitimacy to be public figures to make difficult decisions, and they don&#39;t have the political backing needed to publicly defend those decisions,&quot; Barr said.<br />\r\nThe speech came after Bar raised alarming and politicizing rhetoric in a series of interviews and spoke out against Democrats in the election.<br />\r\nIn short, the US Attorney General, Senior DOJ Officer, and US Attorney General are political. But they are political in a good and necessary sense, &rdquo;he said.<br />\r\nBar also met with a team of prosecutors investigating Robert M&uuml;ller&#39;s election in Russia - and even appeared to be getting comments from one of the law industry&#39;s most respected lawyers.<br />\r\n&quot;Once again, the Obama administration asked several people in M&uuml;ller&#39;s office to write their reports to the Supreme Court. Maybe that explains something,&quot; he said Wednesday.<br />\r\nMueller, a life-long Republican who led the FBI for 12 years, was targeted by Trump and the Conservatives before and after the investigation ended, and because some of his team&#39;s top prosecutors have worked for Democrats in the past.<br />\r\nBarr&#39;s comments on Wednesday appeared to refer to Michael Driben, a Justice Department attorney who is the best criminal policy translator on M&uuml;ller&#39;s team. Dreeben is considered one of the greatest criminal law experts in the legal industry and in the corridors of the Department of Justice, and is among the elite of lawyers who have argued more than 100 times before the Supreme Court. He is now in private practice.<br />\r\n&quot;Did you know that Bar really lost him when he bent over to attack the likes of Michael Driben,&quot; Andrew Weissman, another longtime federal attorney who led Paul Manafort&#39;s investigation to M&uuml;ller&#39;s team, wrote on Twitter.<br />\r\nThis story has been updated with Barr&#39;s comments on M&uuml;ller&#39;s investigation.</p>', 'US History, Violation of civil liberties', 'Attorney General_1600331021.jpg', '2020-09-17 12:23:41', '2021-08-17 05:15:09'),
(611, 7, 12, 154, 'mayor-of-seattle-says-barrs-proposal-to-blame-terrible-1600331484', 'Mayor of Seattle Says Barr\'s Proposal to Blame \"Terrible\"', 0, '<p>Seattle Mayor Jenny Durkan said Wednesday that a report in which Attorney General William Barr asked prosecutors to file charges against them was &quot;appalling and the Trump administration&#39;s recent abuse of power&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The New York Times reported that prosecutors have asked prosecutors from the Justice Department&#39;s Civil Rights Department to investigate whether they can blame Durkan for the protests this summer when some protesters set up police-free zones in downtown Seattle.<br />\r\n&quot;The Department of Justice cannot be a political weapon used by order of the President against those who oppose government action,&quot; said Durkan, a former US lawyer, in a statement. &quot;This is an act of tyranny, not democracy.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;After all, this is not a story for me. It&#39;s about how this president and attorney general tend to weaken the law and use the Justice Department for political purposes,&quot; he added. &quot;It&#39;s amazing to try to use civil rights laws to investigate, intimidate, or obstruct those fighting for civil rights in our country.&quot;<br />\r\nDurkan and the Trump administration have argued repeatedly about how to deal with protesters who camp and occupy an area outside the Seattle Police Department on the east side of Capitol Hill, which protesters call the Capitol Hill Autonomous Area.<br />\r\nDespite Trump&#39;s threats, Durkan said the city would not accept federal troops to take protesters out. &quot;The threat of invasion of Seattle - to divide and encourage violence in our city - is not only unwanted, but illegal,&quot; he said at the time, saying most of the protests were peaceful.<br />\r\nSeattle police finally dispersed protesters from the area in July after Durkan issued an emergency order.<br />\r\nBar&#39;s suggestion that prosecutors consider filing a lawsuit against the mayor aligned with his public stance following George Floyd&#39;s death by Minneapolis police in late May.<br />\r\nThe Attorney General pretended to be a man of law and order and spoke in a speech to provide strong support to the police and quell unrest rather than a peaceful message advocating law enforcement reform.<br />\r\nNews Channel&nbsp;on Wednesday morning reported that Bar was disappointed with the work of several local and state prosecutors with riot-related crimes, and told Justice Department prosecutors he wanted them to sue aggressively. in the context of violence against protests, including a survey using the law of the rarely used coin, according to people with knowledge of the matter.<br />\r\nThis is a topic that is growing in popularity in the conservative media, which Bar is closely following, and which is sometimes known to focus on the issue.<br />\r\nHowever, some federal lawyers were taken aback last week when the Attorney General indicated the possibility of bringing charges against rioting protesters in a conspiracy to overthrow the US government.</p>', 'Mayor, Barrs proposal blame', 'Mayor_1600331484.jpg', '2020-09-17 12:31:24', '2021-08-18 05:03:00'),
(612, 7, 12, 132, 'the-court-of-appeal-discusses-the-fate-of-harvards-positive-action-policy-1600332000', 'The Court of Appeal discusses the fate of Harvard\'s positive action policy', 0, '<p><strong>US appeals court judge Sandra Lynch beat lawyers and questioned Harvard&#39;s positive action guidelines on Wednesday. He implicitly challenged his allegations of bias against Asian American students and allegations of the Supreme Court precedent.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;You are first saying that the Harvard system is deliberately discriminatory because it uses subjective criteria,&quot; Lynch, the loudest of the three judges hearing the case, told Harvard candidate William Konsovoy. &quot;But in Bakke&#39;s case, which naturally binds us, they also used subjective criteria and spoke brilliantly of the Harvard plans at the time.&quot;<br />\r\nLynch cites University of California regents v Bakke, a 1978 case in which the Supreme Court first allowed universities to use race as a &quot;plus&quot; factor in acceptance of diversity on campus.<br />\r\n&quot;We said he was more likely to bias and attack the system,&quot; Konsovoy explained, &quot;because he used subjective criteria. ... I thought it was just common sense.&quot; Lynch had the sharpest questions about Konsovoy and a Department of Justice lawyer, and was also against practices that traditionally benefit black and Spanish people.<br />\r\nJudge Juan Toruela asked several questions during the 80-minute trial, but was equally skeptical of Harvard&#39;s argument against Asian Americans and questioned the evidence. But neither Torruella nor Chief Justice Jeffrey Howard bowed, as Lynch did in the long-running case now in the Bund.<br />\r\nAppointment phase.<br />\r\nAt one point, Howard turned to the claim of &quot;racial balance&quot; that was at the heart of the &quot;Fair Student Admissions.&quot; &quot;On the one hand, institutions are looking for diverse student communities and diverse communities. On the other hand, there are real imbalance concerns,&quot; Howard said, asking about the so-called &quot;return.&quot;<br />\r\nHarvard attorney Seth Waxman said admission rates for blacks, Spanish, Asian-Americans and others varied widely over the years so they could produce individual assessments and meet Supreme Court precedents.<br />\r\nBakke and other Supreme Court decisions have banned quotas and &quot;racial equality&quot; associated with them. The Harvard case, filed six years ago, seems to be routinely directed to the Supreme Court and has been an important test of this important phase since 1978 at Bakke.<br />\r\nThe Boston-based commission on Wednesday ruled on US District Judge Alison Burroughs&#39; 2019 ruling that refutes the argument that Harvard is illegally discriminated against and can be diversified by non-racial factors such as the economic status of families.<br />\r\n&quot;Harvard demonstrated that, individually or in combination, there is no viable, non-competitive alternative that would enable it to achieve a sufficiently diverse student body while maintaining standards for academic benchmarks and other excellence,&quot; Burroughs wrote.<br />\r\nThe lawsuit was filed on behalf of an Asian-American by Edward Bloom, a conservative lawyer who has long opposed racial politics and previously sought white college students to challenge him. After President Donald Trump took office, the US Department of Justice joined the case and joined a group of students to get Blum&#39;s fair approval.<br />\r\nThe case, which has been followed since its inception due to rampant positive action practices across the country, has gained renewed popularity as it focuses on systemic racism that culminated in the recent police murder of George Floyd on August 3. May was driven in Minneapolis.<br />\r\n&quot;Personal&quot; results<br />\r\nOne controversy is Harvard&#39;s use of &quot;personal&quot; scores in addition to academic and extracurricular assessments, which SFFA candidates say will improve the prospects of black and Spanish candidates and put Asian-Americans at a disadvantage.<br />\r\nOn Wednesday, Konsovoy argued that flexible &quot;personal&quot; judgments had led to racial stereotypes among Asian Americans. During the pilot, the SFFA claimed that Asian-Americans broadcast as one-dimensional broadcast or simply &quot;smart with books.&quot;<br />\r\nJustice Department attorney Eric Dryband confirmed the claim, telling the court that Asian-American candidates routinely, but suspiciously, receive lower personal ratings. Three Cushion also claims that Harvard continues to monitor the racial makeup of the upcoming class to reach a certain level.<br />\r\nDuring a survey by Lynch on how the Harvard program differs from the positive action program recently launched by the Supreme Court at the University of Texas in 2016, Dreyband said Harvard was not taking the narrow or limited approach it needed. He argued that Harvard looked at the race of students at every step of the admissions process and &quot;saturated&quot; the whole process with it.<br />\r\nHarvard Waxman attorneys challenged this emphasis and asked the Appeal Council to rely on the findings of Burroughs, who heard statements from 25 witnesses during a three-week trial in 2018 and examined hundreds of pages of the exhibition.<br />\r\nAccording to Waxman, Harvard admissions officers are committed to extensive &quot;individualized&quot; assessments when considering who should be accepted. He said a committee of 40 admissions officers weighed many of the academic and extracurricular characteristics and the personal results of applicants were exaggerated.<br />\r\n&quot;In this appeal,&quot; he said, &quot;personal evaluation becomes even more important, similar to Frankenstein.&quot;</p>', 'Court Appeal, Harvard', 'Court_1600332000.jpg', '2020-09-17 12:40:00', '2021-08-17 23:23:42'),
(613, 7, 12, 138, 'the-postal-service-on-time-has-not-yet-recovered-from-the-changes-in-the-director-general-said-the-senate-democratic-report-1600332505', 'The postal service on time has not yet recovered from the changes in the director general, said the Senate Democratic report', 0, '<p><strong>The Punctual Postal Service has yet to recover from Postmaster General Louis DeJoy&#39;s controversial change to the US Postal Service in the November election, according to a new Senate Democratic report.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shortly after joining the agency in June, DeJoy, a donor and Trump ally, came under fire for radical changes to the U.S. Postal Service, including a tighter mail van schedule, meaning leaving the Post Office. behind the machining center to stay on time. DeJoy&#39;s action led to widespread delays in postal services across the country shortly before the general election, most of which are thought to have taken place by post.<br />\r\nThe report describes the results of an investigation initiated by Senator Gary Peters, a Michigan Democrat who is a senior member of the Senate Government Affairs and Homeland Security Committee. According to the report, DeJoy has not considered or investigated the impact of the changes on the postal service.<br />\r\nAccording to Peters&#39; office, each of the country&#39;s 67 districts has seen a drop in on-time deliveries of high-quality mail, which are expected to be the fastest. In early August, the report found that on-time premium mailing was 9.1 percentage points lower than the week before DeJoy started implementing the changes.<br />\r\nIn the second week of August alone, according to the report, there were about 85 million delays in premium mail deliveries than there was for DeJoy&#39;s orders. In some parts of the country, on-time premium mail delivery fell 15 to 20 percentage points in the weeks following DeJoy&#39;s truck orders.<br />\r\nThe report also noted that in early September, when several countries were preparing to send correspondence bulletins, on-time deliveries in many parts of the country started to decline.<br />\r\nThe report was released shortly after a New York court hearing about some of the changes DeJoy ordered and the potential impact on the election.<br />\r\nDuring the hearing, USPS &#39;vice president of logistics, Robert Sintron, testified that service standards &quot;returned&quot; from their levels in July. When asked whether the new rule to cut delivery hours could result in a backlog in campaign letters, Sintron said he could.<br />\r\nAnother senior USPS official who testified, Angela Curtis, acknowledged that the rule change caused delays, but also blamed the increase in coronavirus cases among postal workers.<br />\r\nDeJoy testified twice before Congress about these changes and whether or not they will affect the 2020 elections.<br />\r\nOn Wednesday, DeJoy had to comply with a call from the Chamber&#39;s supervisory committee after failing to provide documentation of changes to the letter that caused the delay. Sources with knowledge of the matter said the USPS was working with the commission to set deadlines. A Commission official confirmed this but noted that not all documents had been submitted. &quot;The Post has started publishing several documents and we look forward to a more complete process today.&quot;<br />\r\nIn recent weeks, DeJoy has acknowledged operational disruptions, but USPS said the situation is improving and many changes are routine and have been planned over the months.<br />\r\nDeJoy has vehemently denied he ordered changes to deliberately sabotage campaign letters this year when there will be record levels of vote absenteeism due to the coronavirus pandemic.</p>', 'Senate Democrate, postal service', 'Democrate_1600332505.jpg', '2020-09-17 12:48:25', '2021-08-15 09:43:29'),
(614, 7, 12, 225, 'republicans-have-brushed-aside-past-concerns-about-georgias-controversial-candidate-and-pressed-her-to-join-the-team-1600335686', 'Republicans have brushed aside past concerns about Georgia\'s controversial candidate and pressed her to join the \"team\".', 0, '<p>Republican lawmaker Steve Scalis said in mid-June that Congressional candidate Marjorie Taylor Green had made &quot;disgusting&quot; comments against blacks, George Soros and Muslims, and supported his main antagonist, the neurosurgeon. John Cowen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But in August, Green - who also supports the QAnon conspiracy theory - beat Kovan in the second round of GO elections for the US parliamentary seat in conservative northwest Georgia. Last week the Democrats dropped out of the race.<br />\r\nAnd since winning the GOP award, Scalis, like other Republican Green critics, has changed his mind.<br />\r\nThis week Scalis told CNN that he wanted to sit down with Green, the first-time candidate and owner of a commercial construction company, to discuss his goals, noting repeatedly that he had been told he was &quot;very strong&quot; against abortion. .<br />\r\n&quot;People who know them say that their true aspiration and passion is to fight for life and socialism,&quot; said Scalis. &quot;These are things that people are passionate about.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;You have to respect every area and I think I owe him a very good open conversation,&quot; he added.<br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>', 'Republicans, Georgia controversial', 'majore green_1600335686.jpg', '2020-09-17 13:41:26', '2021-09-23 08:14:36'),
(615, 7, 12, 109, 'the-university-of-georgia-will-allow-soccer-but-not-private-voting-this-fall-1600335837', 'The University of Georgia will allow soccer - but not private voting - this fall', 0, '<p>The Georgian Marching band Redcoat performs on the pitch during a match between the Georgia Bulldogs and the Missouri Tigers at the Sanford Stadium on November 9, 2019 in Athens, Georgia.<br />\r\n(CNN) Student groups and government officials have criticized the University of Georgia for not allowing face-to-face voting on campus this fall.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Meanwhile, thousands of fans are expected to attend UGA&#39;s first home football game on October 3.<br />\r\nThe university has yet to find a suitable place for early voting on campus, said UGAVotes, a non-partisan voter registration group for students, in a statement on Wednesday. The group hopes a private vote can be held at the university&#39;s large basketball arena to avoid long lines and crowded conditions, but universities don&#39;t believe they have the resources to clean up the Colosseum at night, according to Marshall Burton Jr. . and CEO of UGAVotes.<br />\r\nIn August, the university announced plans that would allow up to 23,000 fans to participate in home football matches. Critics learned of this detail after the university voted.<br />\r\n&quot;From a student point of view, it is very disappointing to see UGA prioritizing football matches and how long and hard they work to get to a point where everyone feels comfortable,&quot; said Juliet Eden. Senior Director and Communications at Fair Fight UGA, a division of a voting group founded by former Georgia Democratic Governor Stacey Abrams. &quot;It&#39;s hard to see that they are not striving so hard to create a safe environment for early voting on campus.&quot;<br />\r\nHowever, a UGA spokesperson dismissed the idea that private polls should be compared to watching games.<br />\r\n&quot;Those comparing this issue to a football match should be able to see that football matches are played outdoors. However, social distancing is still needed as stadium capacity is significantly reduced,&quot; UGA spokesman Greg Trevor said by email. Wednesday. &quot;We are also eliminating queues because we want to keep the campus as safe as possible and limit the number of visitors during the pandemic.&quot;<br />\r\nThe school&#39;s website states that Sanford Stadium, which can accommodate more than 90,000 people, will be around 20% to 25% busy for a football match. And the Athena Banner-Herald announced in August that the school&#39;s athletics department had assured its amplifiers that it would devote significant resources to measures such as more coronavirus testing and better clean-up procedures for the fall.<br />\r\nPrivate voting is taking place on the UGA campus for the 2016 presidential election and 2018 midterm elections. This year, students can continue to use the postal ballot, which is being used increasingly during the Covid pandemic. -19 or at a location outside the university in central Athens.<br />\r\nThe university said it would offer a shuttle to the center&#39;s polling center.<br />\r\n&quot;This is certainly a disappointing decision in our opinion. However, we are confident that there is an alternative voting on campus that can complement this voting hall,&quot; UGAVotes Burton told CNN. &quot;We are not experts at all on social distancing or rebuilding. So if universities don&#39;t think they&#39;ve succeeded in implementing these safeguards to make voting safe for everyone, then this is the solution.&quot; To do. &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nThe announcement caught the attention of a number of politicians in Georgia, including Senate Democratic candidate John Osoff, who tweeted, &quot;I urge the UGA to immediately cancel courses and ensure that students on campus can vote safely and early!&quot;<br />\r\nFair Fight UGA created a petition asking the school to change its decision and Abrams shared it, writing on Twitter: &quot;# COVID19 should not be used as an excuse to prevent voting, even in College colleges, limit it.&quot; Within hours, over 600 people had sign.<br />\r\n&quot;If we can have football, we have to vote,&quot; wrote the UGA Fair Fight on Wednesday.</p>', 'University of Georgia, voting private', 'soccier_1600335837.jpg', '2020-09-17 13:42:02', '2021-08-16 22:36:28'),
(616, 7, 12, 130, 'trump-turned-rosh-hashanahs-call-into-an-electoral-campaign-pitch-telling-jewish-leaders-we-love-your-country-1600336025', 'Trump turned Rosh Hashanah\'s call into an electoral campaign pitch, telling Jewish leaders, \"We love your country.\"', 0, '<p><strong>President Donald Trump on Wednesday called for a high-profile vacation with Jewish leaders but turned to an election campaign, pleading for more support from Jewish voters and repeating statements that sparked criticism of anti-Semitic groups for Americans. to Israel.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We really appreciate you, we love your country and we are very grateful,&quot; Trump said, closing his appointment.<br />\r\nThe use of &quot;your country&quot; in conversations with Americans is reminiscent of earlier statements he made when criticizing the assumption that American Jews feel loyal to Israel.<br />\r\nIn August 2019, Trump was sharply criticized for being &quot;disloyal&quot; to the Jews who voted for Democrats.<br />\r\nOn Wednesday he immediately asked for support in the upcoming election.<br />\r\n&quot;And I have to say that everything you do on November 3 will be very important because if we don&#39;t win, Israel will have a big problem,&quot; Trump told attendees.<br />\r\nHe complained about the lack of support he received from the Jewish people in 2016, saying that their vote &quot;seemed almost automatically to be a democratic one&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;Which really amazes me, and I have to tell you because I saw a poll that I got 25% of the Jewish vote in the last election. And I&#39;m saying here that I have a son-in-law and a daughter who is Jewish. &quot;I have a beautiful grandson who is Jewish,&quot; Trump said. &quot;But I was amazed that it looked like an almost automatic democratic vote.&quot;<br />\r\nThe president told the audience that he hoped they could &quot;handle it better&quot; in the 2020 elections.<br />\r\n&quot;I hope you can explain what happened to the people. We need more support from the Jewish people for Israel,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nTrump also called Jared Kushner, his son-in-law and senior adviser, &quot;extraordinary for Israel. He is truly a leader for Israel.&quot;</p>', 'Donald Trump, Jewish leaders', 'Trump rush_1600336025.jpg', '2020-09-17 13:47:05', '2021-08-17 18:46:30');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(617, 7, 12, 120, 'a-major-in-the-armys-national-guard-said-the-federal-convention-called-for-heat-rays-and-stored-ammunition-before-finalizing-the-dc-protests-1600336161', 'A major in the Army\'s National Guard said the federal convention called for heat rays and stored ammunition before finalizing the DC protests.', 0, '<p><strong>Federal officials attempt to get the hot beam scorching the target&#39;s skin and collect thousands of rounds of ammunition to evacuate peaceful protests in Lafayette Square in June. This emerged from the written testimony of a major in the Army National Guard. Who is on site.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Major Adam DeMarco described such preparations - including the inability of officials to procure a stern warning device to warn protesters to disperse - in a letter in August answering follow-up questions after speaking before the Nature Committee. Resources have testified. in June about federal officials&#39; efforts earlier this month. DeMarco, who identifies on stage as one of the top officers in the National Guard, ran as a Democrat for Maryland&#39;s third congressional district in 2018.<br />\r\nNews of the contents of DeMarco&#39;s letter was first reported by NPR.<br />\r\nIn the letter, DeMarco was told that on the day of the protests, the Capitol Defense Department military police chief emailed him and others asking if the DC National Guard had an explosive &quot;remote acoustic device&quot;. The baffles in the demonstrator or &quot;active repulsion system&quot;, have a &quot;directed energy beam that provides intense heat to the surface of the skin.&quot;<br />\r\nDeMarco wrote that he replied that the DC National Guard had no equipment and, as far as he could tell, no acoustic devices were used in Lafayette Square. When he was looking for an acoustic device the next day, the DC National Guard told him, &quot;They are no longer looking for it.&quot;<br />\r\nTherefore, the US Park Service&#39;s &quot;diversion warning&quot; originated not from this system, but from the &quot;red and white megaphone&quot; Demarco used on it, he wrote. He testified that even 30 feet from the megaphone, &quot;warnings about deployment were barely audible and I could see only a few words&quot; - while front-line protesters were far from warning.<br />\r\nHe also referred to the handover of weapons to the DC National Guard on the afternoon of the protests, which he later learned contained &quot;about 7,000 rounds of ammunition&quot;.<br />\r\nFederal agents have been criticized for using smoke cannons and rubber bullets to evacuate peaceful protesters in Lafayette Square to protest institutionalized racism and police brutality following the death of cop George Floyd. The move sparked outrage from lawmakers and members of the public, including former Defense Secretary James Mathis and Washington Mayor Muriel Bowser, who described the incident as an attack on protesters.<br />\r\nLaw enforcement dispersed the crowd shortly before a controversial photo of President Donald Trump at a nearby church retrieving a Bible after declaring himself president for law and order. The incident embodied Trump&#39;s position against widespread national unrest, which he promised to adopt as a central principle in his re-election campaign.<br />\r\nA Department of Defense official with knowledge of the matter minimized DeMarco&#39;s account, reports the Post, claiming that emails containing information about certain weapons were routine in assessing available inventory. The official told the newspaper that federal police did not receive heat radiation devices in the first days of demonstrations in the city.<br />\r\nDeMarco attorney David Laufman denied this trait on Wednesday, saying, &quot;Investigations of the presence of heat rays against US citizens exercising their initial installation rights are not routine.&quot;<br />\r\nIn a statement to the commission in June, DeMarco testified that tear gas was actually used, contrary to official information from federal officials.<br />\r\nI could feel irritation in my eyes and nose, and from my previous exposure to tear gas during my training at West Point and later in my military, I recognized the irritation as an effect compatible with CS or &quot;tear gas&quot;. DeMarco said on the panel. &quot;And that night I found tear gas on the street nearby.&quot;<br />\r\nIn contrast, acting US park police chief Gregory Monahan testified at the time that tear gas had not been used, but his testimony indicated that he identified tear gas as a specific type of gas called CS gas. .</p>', 'Major Army, National Guard', 'army national_1600336161.jpg', '2020-09-17 13:49:21', '2021-08-10 20:14:47'),
(618, 7, 12, 86, 'chad-wolf-appears-ready-to-defy-house-subpoena-to-testify-dhs-official-says-1600336322', 'Chad Wolf appears ready to defy House subpoena to testify, DHS official says', 0, '<p><strong>Acting Interior Secretary Chad Wolfe appeared poised to oppose a subpoena issued last week to testify about threats to the US homeland on Thursday because he has no plans to attend a hearing, according to a department official.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The move marks the final round-trip between the House Security Committee, chaired by Mississippi Democratic Representative Benny Thompson, and the Department of Homeland Security for the date the commission asks for testimony.<br />\r\nWolfe&#39;s anticipated move comes as his tenure as acting secretary is increasingly emphasized. Last week, a federal judge in Maryland ruled that Wolfe was likely the unauthorized acting secretary of the department and then did not have the authority to enforce specific asylum rules for contested work. CNN previously reported that the government&#39;s accountability service found that Wolf and Ken Cucchinili, the senior deputy secretary of national security, had been appointed under an unauthorized successor.<br />\r\nCNN asked the committee for comment. The committee sent a press release to journalists just before 3:00 p.m. Wednesday who calls Wolf as a witness.<br />\r\nCuccinelli criticized the parliamentary committee for not withdrawing his request for testimony from Wolf, whose candidacy was postponed, on Thursday.<br />\r\n&quot;President Thompson can complain about whatever he wants, but the facts are clear and they are not on his side,&quot; Cucinelli said in a statement Wednesday. &quot;The old precedent is that future candidates will not testify before other commissions because their nominations are imminent.&quot;<br />\r\nCuccinelli cited DHS&#39;s offer to testify on his behalf, which was included in a letter to Thompson last week, before a subpoena stating that Wolf could not take the testimony.<br />\r\n&quot;I have prepared my testimony and I have a clear schedule to come to trial this morning,&quot; Cucchinili said. &quot;Instead, the majority of the commission decided to do a media show instead.&quot;<br />\r\nOrganizers summoned Wolfe last week alleging he asked the department to change the information.<br />\r\n&quot;From the coronavirus pandemic to the emergence of right-wing extremism to the disruption of the ongoing elections, there are urgent threats that require our attention,&quot; Thompson said in a statement on Friday. &quot;Mr Wolfe&#39;s refusal to testify - and thus escape Congress&#39; control at this critical time - is very worrying given the serious problems facing the Department and the nation.&quot;<br />\r\nThompson&#39;s committee had previously asked Wolfe&#39;s predecessor, Kevin McAllanan, to learn about terrorism. Finally, McAllanin appeared before the panel.</p>', 'Chad Wolf, DHS offical', 'chad wolf_1600336322.jpg', '2020-09-17 13:52:02', '2021-08-10 20:17:34'),
(619, 7, 12, 155, 'trumps-request-for-a-higher-number-in-the-fight-against-incentives-undermines-republican-strategy-1600336593', 'Trump\'s request for a \"higher number\" in the fight against incentives undermines Republican strategy', 0, '<p><strong>President Donald Trump&#39;s call for &quot;higher numbers&quot; is in a stalemate amid new coronavirus stimulus hindering CSOs&#39; efforts to unite against Democrats pushing for a bigger aid package.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump said on Wednesday, &quot;Go for a much higher number, Republican Party&quot; in a tweet mentioning payment for coronavirus stimuli - a message that undermines Hill&#39;s strategy that Republicans are pursuing to oppose attempts at democratic negotiations. to a number higher than the top line So far, GOP legislators have submitted their proposals.<br />\r\nThe president&#39;s message was thwarted by Republicans who want to focus on the Democratic Party&#39;s internal struggles over their party&#39;s response to the pandemic and the Democratic leadership&#39;s refusal to support closer and limited relief efforts. Instead, the tweet immediately caught Republican attention and raised questions about whether they would join Trump&#39;s call for a higher price. So far, Republicans have not received the presidential summons. Some Republican lawmakers opposed Trump&#39;s proposal to aim for a &quot;higher number&quot; on Wednesday, while others shied away from asking if they would support the move.<br />\r\nSenate majority John Tun of South Dakota warned of Trump&#39;s tweet urging CSOs to save more money for incentives, warning that a more expensive proposal could worsen Republican support.<br />\r\nAsked if Republicans would support more, Thune said, &quot;I&#39;m not sure what that means more ... but I do know what the threshold is for getting Republicans in the Senate, and whether the numbers are right.&quot; passes in the Senate mostly passed by the votes of a Democrat and a handful of Republicans. There has to be a realistic distance if we are to increase, to optimize the number of Republican senators who will vote in favor. &quot;<br />\r\nIn late July, Republicans submitted an estimated $ 1 trillion stimulus proposal in the Senate, which Democrats criticized as insufficient because they approved a more expensive $ 3 trillion proposal.<br />\r\nSince then, Democrats have proposed cutting their top request to $ 2.2 trillion, but Republicans in the White House and Senate have rejected it. Instead, Senate Republicans tried unsuccessfully last week to pass a bid reduced by about $ 500 billion, a move that Democrats blocked.<br />\r\nWhen asked what most Republicans would support, Tune said on Wednesday, &quot;I mean $ 1 trillion in the beginning and we have a lot of opposition to it. I think our members might be in that area.&quot; and added, &quot;But if you move up from there, you&#39;re going to lose Republican support pretty quickly.&quot;<br />\r\nGOP Party leader Kevin McCarthy, from California, fled when he was pressured by reporters over Trump&#39;s tweet. When asked if Republicans would be more supportive than ever, he brushed off the issue, instead blaming Democrats for the postponement. &quot;I don&#39;t think the Democrats really want it. I think the speakers are slowing it down,&quot; he said, then walked to the DPR.<br />\r\nHouse GOP Party Conference Chairman Liz Cheney, from Wyoming, said on Wednesday, &quot;I don&#39;t want to commit to myself at that high level,&quot; adding, &quot;I am very concerned about funds being taken over and not being spent. I think a solution. the real thing for that is we have to push the economy back. &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nA House adviser familiar with the talks said little progress had been made in a phone call Wednesday between Speaker of Parliament Nancy Pelosi and Finance Minister Steve Mnuchin, and Pelosi continued to urge the government to reach the best Democratic number of around two. One trillion dollars.<br />\r\nA Pelosi spokesman said the talks included discussions about an ongoing resolution that would provide solutions to address gaps as the government funding deadline approached, but that there was no resolution yet. .<br />\r\nSenate Budget Committee Chair Richard Shelby, a Republican from Alabama, told reporters Wednesday that no agreement had been reached on the timing of the ongoing resolution. Republicans want it to leave in mid-December, but some Democrats are pushing for a new year with a new Congress and possibly a new government.<br />\r\nIn a statement, Chuck Schumer, the minority chairman of the New York Senate, and Pelosi used Trump&#39;s tweet on Wednesday.<br />\r\nWe are encouraged that after months of the Senate Republican press to curb the overwhelming needs of the American people, President Trump is now urging Republicans to &quot;tackle much higher numbers&quot; in the next coronavirus bailout. The leading Democrats in Congress said.<br />\r\n&quot;We are looking forward to hearing from the presidential negotiators that they will finally greet us with a bill that reflects the great health and economic crisis that has gripped our nation,&quot; they said.<br />\r\nWhite House spokeswoman Kaylee McEnnany said at a press conference on Wednesday, &quot;What the president is referring to is a $ 500 billion bill that goes to the Senate. There are no direct payments. So he wants more than $ 500 billion US Dollars and he really wants. looking at these immediate incentive payments and we hope Nancy Pelosi will work with us in good faith. &quot;<br />\r\nWhile some Republican senators have speculated they could potentially fulfill a proposal that cost more than last week&#39;s weak $ 500 billion plan, switching to pro-Democracy numbers would split the conference and risk losing McConnell more than that. Half the members.<br />\r\nSenator Mike Brown, a Conservative Republican from Indiana, told CNN he didn&#39;t see much desire to climb any higher than last week and said more than $ 1.5 trillion was &quot;an acrobatic feat.&quot; &quot;.<br />\r\nWhen asked about Trump&#39;s tweet asking Republicans to support more incentive funding, Missouri Senator Roy Blunt, a member of the Senate Republican leadership, said he believed &quot;their number will exceed our trillion dollars.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;I think a deal has to be made here,&quot; said Blunt. &quot;I&#39;m afraid the window may close at the end of this month and we have to work on it to see what we can agree on together. And I think their number will be bigger than our trillion dollars.&quot;<br />\r\nSouth Carolina GOP Senator Lindsey Graham said Wednesday, following the president&#39;s tweet, &quot;to count me at camp that I&#39;m trying to do something,&quot; but added that he believes &quot;we can do this for less than the $ 2 trillion generated and responsible need.&quot; . &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nMeanwhile, some Democrats continue to express disappointment over the lack of progress in the negotiations.<br />\r\n&quot;I want everyone to return to the negotiating table first and foremost,&quot; said Abigail Spanberger, a Virginia Democrat who faced re-election in Donald Trump County and won in 2016.<br />\r\nRepresentative Stephanie Murphy, a Florida Democrat who chairs the Blue Dogs group, said: &quot;&quot;</p>', 'Trumps Call, Republic Strategy', 'fight under cuts_1600336593.jpg', '2020-09-17 13:56:33', '2021-08-16 18:27:36'),
(620, 7, 1, 235, 'what-is-the-eea-and-how-does-it-relate-to-how-quickly-we-get-the-coronavirus-vaccine-1600342016', 'What is the EEA and how does it relate to how quickly we get the coronavirus vaccine?', 0, '<p><strong>When talking about the possible availability of vaccine candidates, you have probably heard the term Emergency Authorization (EUA) all over the news recently. But what exactly is it and how does it apply to vaccines?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>An emergency license, as the name suggests: a medical device that has received specific approval from the US Food and Drug Administration for use in an emergency. Sometimes it&#39;s a product that has been FDA approved but under different conditions, and sometimes it&#39;s a new product that hasn&#39;t received the go-ahead from the agency.<br />\r\nThere is concern and ongoing debate about whether a vaccine candidate should be given EEA - or direct approval - without first completing a Phase 3 clinical trial. According to the FDA website, in the case of a public health emergency, the agency could use an emergency. Use approval &quot;to assist in the delivery of medical devices as quickly as possible by delivering unapproved medical devices to patients in need when there are no adequate, FDA approved and available alternatives.&quot; However, this is only the case if the &quot;known and potential benefits of the product in diagnosing, preventing or treating the disease or condition identified are greater than the known risks and potential of the product&quot;.<br />\r\nSo, the EEA essentially sped up the process of procuring potentially useful medical devices approved for specific public use during emergency medical care, without the rigorous testing and follow-up normally required to get FDA approval - the traditional one. It took years.<br />\r\nWhen emergency medical care ends, &quot;the EEA issued under this statement will cease to apply,&quot; according to the FDA. However, manufacturers can still send documents to agencies for routine approval.<br />\r\nThe EEA hasn&#39;t been around that long. The process was incorporated into the project Biological Shield Act, passed by Congress in 2004, which allows the federal government to prepare and enforce new &quot;medical precautions&quot; during declared public health emergencies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And despite the publication of multiple EUAs over the years, only one vaccine has ever received one - but this is an unusual and controversial fact. In 1997, the Department of Defense initiated a mandatory anthrax vaccination program. Shortly thereafter, the soldiers claimed that the vaccine had made them sick, so they and a judge withheld the 2003 program. The Department of Defense urged the EEA, which then overturned a 2005 court ruling so that it could continue to vaccinate military personnel. - this time on a voluntary basis.<br />\r\nEUA during this pandemic<br />\r\nDuring the Covid-19 pandemic, the FDA repeatedly gave EUA various medical devices, such as ventilators. personal protective equipment including masks; Molecular and antigen tests to diagnose Covid-19 and serological tests for antibodies; and even medications such as remdezivir and plasma recovery. Like hydroxychloroquine and chloroquine, EUA can be withdrawn. These drugs have been approved for the treatment and prevention of malaria and hold promise against new laboratory tests for the coronavirus. Early small studies in patients with Covid-19 are optimistic and the drug is being promoted by PresidentTrump. However, larger studies have shown that the drug is ineffective in treating patients with Covid-19. In addition, one of the side effects can also be potentially dangerous in people with a history of heart disease. After about two and a half months in the EEA, the emergency clearance was revoked.<br />\r\nMany experts believe that giving EUA a vaccine against Covid-19 is problematic. First, vaccines are given to selected healthy people, compared to drugs given to seriously ill patients who might die without them. So, so to speak, drug manufacturers have raised the bar to ensure there are no unexpected side effects that make healthy people sick - and the only way to find out is with large-scale research like the one that&#39;s being done. .<br />\r\nThe FDA has announced that they will keep the vaccine at a higher standard. Dr. Peter Marx, director of the FDA&#39;s Center for Organic Product Evaluation and Research, said Thursday that the requirements are stricter than emergency approvals for experimental drugs.<br />\r\n&quot;For us, for a vaccine that has sufficient production information, emergency clearance, if we give emergency clearance, will really be a plus emergency,&quot; Marx said at a seminar organized by Duke University&#39;s Margolis Center for Health Policy. has been arranged.<br />\r\nOn Friday, Marx and Hahn said in a joint blog post that they would &quot;soon&quot; issue more guidelines on how high the standard was.<br />\r\nThey found that producers had to submit an application to the FDA or EEA for full approval, which is known as a license application for organic products. With so many stakes at stake, we understand the importance of being as transparent as possible about our work, including how we make decisions about the COVID-19 vaccine, &rdquo;wrote Marx and Hahn.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The FDA has announced that it wants at least 50% effectiveness - meaning that any vaccine under consideration should reduce the risk of infection or serious illness by at least 50% compared to a placebo.<br />\r\nIn a series of tweets from Dr. Peter Hottes, Professor and Dean of Tropical Medicine at Baylor College of Medicine, stated earlier this month that &quot;EUA contains poor quality or poor feedback. Something is being injected into tens of millions, maybe hundreds of millions of Americans?&quot; &quot;<br />\r\nIn addition, Hotez pointed out that the mRNA technology used in the two most advanced Phase 3 vaccines - Moderna and Pfizer / BioNTechvaccine - &quot;is a new technology that has not been licensed before&quot;. We have no history or experience with such vaccines. Even more reason for a full / comprehensive review. &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nHotes also pointed out that in this highly politicized climate, there is a lack of trust in government and federal agencies. &quot;We see the White House abusing the EEA mechanism in 2020 - don&#39;t forget the EEA for hydroxychloroquine, which has been abolished? Neither the White House nor the HHS division,&quot; he wrote on Twitter.<br />\r\nPolitical subtext<br />\r\nThere are also concerns that the president is seeking a vaccine for political reasons in preparation for the November elections.<br />\r\nPresident Trump has said several times that he believes a vaccine could be available on election day. Undoubtedly, the pace of medical innovation is moving faster than ever, and human trials of vaccines began just 67 days after the virus was first identified. U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention recently urged public health officials to prepare for potential vaccine distribution by the end of October. And FDA Commissioner Dr. Stephen Hahn said he would consider the EEA before completing the Phase 3 trials.<br />\r\nHowever, several health officials told CNN that the idea of making a vaccine publicly available on November 3 was unlikely. &quot;There is great concern about the nature of the political expediency, and when that [October] date is chosen ... and just choosing that date before the election triggers fears that the government is not too busy, make sure that Every Vaccine Is Really Not only effective, but also has a little side effects, &rdquo;said Dr. Ali Khan, dean of the School of Public Health at the University of Nebraska Medical Center and former director of the CDC&#39;s Public Health Services.<br />\r\n&quot;We&#39;re all optimistic that there are currently three vaccines in Phase 3. Maybe one of those vaccines is so great that you don&#39;t have to vaccinate 30,000 people to see it work.&quot; However, there is a concern that if you don&#39;t do all these so-called phase 3 studies, you will miss out on rare side effects, &quot;he told CNN earlier this month.<br />\r\nWhen vaccines - other medical devices - are given sufficiently, rare side effects can occur. In 1976, the government released a vaccine, which was produced hastily, about seven months after the Ford government became convinced that a new strain causing a pandemic was imminent.<br />\r\nThe pandemic never happened, but 40 million people were vaccinated as part of the mandatory program. This vaccine is then associated with a neurological disorder called Guillain-Barr&eacute; syndrome, which can develop after infection or, rarely, after vaccination with live vaccines. The connection was never made, but the program was terminated.<br />\r\nTo demonstrate vaccine effectiveness, dozens of people in the placebo arm had to be infected, while very few, if any, infections were observed in the vaccinated cohort of study participants. It can take weeks, even months, to determine the difference between these two populations.<br />\r\nLess confident<br />\r\nThis lack of doubt in public is real. A CNN poll in August found that 40 percent of Americans don&#39;t want to get a vaccine once it&#39;s available - even if it&#39;s cheap and easy to get. Such low vaccine uptake could affect a country&#39;s ability to control the virus and return to normal.<br />\r\nIf history is any guide, skepticism - if not outright suspicion - of an unapproved vaccine is nothing new. In a study published in 2009, months after the US declared a public health emergency due to the H1N1 flu and the World Health Organization declared a pandemic, researchers looked at people&#39;s willingness to use drugs or vaccines with EUA (not fully approved by the FDA). by interviewing a representative sample of more than 1,500 adults in the United States.<br />\r\nThey found that more than 77% of respondents would become very, very or very worried if they were offered an unapproved vaccine. 63% said they would not accept it.<br />\r\nHowever, there were several other key factors that convinced respondents that EEA-approved vaccines were safe to use. When the vaccine was given by health workers, 55% of respondents said they would drink it. If accompanied by an information sheet, more than 57% of respondents said they would get it. And when they are managed by their healthcare providers, that figure is 68%. Transparency is the key to trust.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The head of the state health authority - Alex Hazard of the US Department of Health, Dr. Francis Collins of the National Institutes of Health, Dr. Anthony Fauzi of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases, Dr. FDA Stephen Hahn and Dr. The CDC&#39;s Robert Redfield is all trying to convince Americans that politics won&#39;t be a problem if a vaccine is available.<br />\r\nFauci said he believes a vaccine is likely to get closer towards the end of the year and that he will not be comfortable making a vaccine widely available unless it is supported by science. &quot;I am not a regulator. I mean, I just do science. I will report science accurately and I will definitely be very concerned and screaming if I see interference,&quot; Fauzi told CNN&#39;s Jim Acosta in the Situation Room. .<br />\r\nRegarding emergency clearance, &quot;I would not be comfortable with a vaccine unless it is proven in clinical studies to be safe and effective,&quot; Faucisaid said in an interview with NBCs Today.<br />\r\nDr. Luciana Borio, former FDA chief scientist, agrees that most importantly, vaccines need to be proven safe and effective.<br />\r\nButifa has been shown to be safe and effective in appropriate and well-controlled clinical studies and should not be maintained until all the strict FDA approval requirements have been met because some requirements cannot be established quickly. .<br />\r\nSafe and effective vaccines can save lives and help fight the pandemic, Boris wrote on Twitter. &quot;The EEA is the most appropriate regulatory mechanism for vaccine distribution that has been shown to be safe and effective in Phase 3 RCTs (randomized controlled trials) but does not yet meet all FDA approval standards.&quot;<br />\r\nMoncef Slavey, chief adviser to Operation Warp Speed, the federal government&#39;s Covid-19 vaccination program, said it was &quot;unethical&quot; not to take swift action to release the Covid-19 vaccine if proven successful.<br />\r\n&quot;If we know that the vaccine is 70%, 80% or 90% effective, it would be unethical to store it,&quot; Slavey said in an interview with CNN on Friday.<br />\r\nOn Tuesday, nine biopharmaceutical companies, including those at the forefront of their vaccine testing programs, signed an unusual commitment to &quot;high ethical standards&quot; on the condition that they would not seek preliminary regulatory approval for the Covid-19 vaccine.<br />\r\nThey promise to &quot;submit emergency clearance or approval only after demonstrating the safety and efficacy of a phase 3 clinical trial designed and conducted in accordance with the requirements of regulatory agencies such as the FDA.&quot;<br />\r\nIn fact, on the same day, AstraZeneca, one of the signatories, said it had stopped testing around the world for an unexplained disease in a volunteer in the UK. Drug manufacturers call suspensions a &quot;routine measure.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Disease occurred accidentally in a large study but needs to be independently verified for careful verification. We are working to accelerate the review of a single event to minimize the potential impact on the study plan,&quot; the statement said. Statement sent to CNN.<br />\r\nAccording to FDA guidelines, any vaccine - whether emergency or approved - must prevent disease or reduce its severity by at least 50%.<br />\r\nFor all intrigue, it may be worthwhile to revert to the original EEA criteria - particularly the provision that they should only be assigned if &quot;no reasonable, approved and available alternatives&quot;. It&#39;s understandable that most people don&#39;t do this, but I don&#39;t want to hear them. There are reasonable alternatives that have worked well in many parts of the world and follow basic public health measures: wearing a mask, maintaining physical distancing, maintaining good hand hygiene, and avoiding large crowds, especially indoors.<br />\r\nFollowing these rules will greatly reduce the chances of people getting sick and slow the transmission of the virus. It will also give us more time to make sure we get vaccine evidence, which is really blown away.</p>', 'EEA, Coronavirus, Vaccine', 'Vaccine_1600342015.jpg', '2020-09-17 15:26:56', '2021-08-12 00:14:30'),
(621, 7, 1, 195, 'nih-cares-very-much-about-serious-side-effects-in-astrazeneca-coronavirus-vaccine-study-1600342474', 'NIH \"Cares Very Much\" About Serious Side Effects In AstraZeneca Coronavirus Vaccine Study', 0, '<p><strong>The Food and Drug Administration is considering following UK regulators in continuing studies of the coronavirus vaccine, which was halted after a participant suffered a spinal cord injury despite the National Institutes of Health investigating the case.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The highest NIH levels are very worrying,&quot; said Dr. Avindra Nat, intramural clinical director and head of viral research at the National Institute for Neurological Disorders and Stroke, NIH. &quot;Everyone expects a vaccine, and if you have serious complications, they can be missed.&quot; There is still much uncertainty about what happened to the anonymous patient, to the point of disappointment for those eager to keep up with the progress of vaccine testing. AstraZeneca, which is conducting a global study of the vaccine it makes with the University of Oxford, said volunteers from the sample had recovered from severe spinal cord infections and were no longer hospitalized.<br />\r\nAstraZeneca did not confirm that the patient had transverse myelitis, but Nat and other neurologists said they understood it. Transverse myelitis causes a number of symptoms, including inflammation of the spinal cord, which can lead to pain, muscle weakness, and paralysis. British regulators, regulators for medicines and health products, are investigating the case and allowing a retrial.<br />\r\nAstraZeneca &quot;needs to be more open about the potential complications of the vaccine that will eventually be given to millions of people,&quot; said Nat. &quot;We wanted to see how we could help, but the lack of information made it difficult.&quot;<br />\r\nThe decision to proceed with the study is complicated because it is difficult to determine the cause of the rare injuries that occurred during vaccination studies - and because scientists and authorities need to assess the risk of unusual side effects to a potential vaccine to limit a pandemic.<br />\r\n&quot;There are many factors involved in this decision,&quot; said Nat. &quot;I&#39;m sure it&#39;s all on the table. The last thing you want to do is hurt a healthy person.&quot;<br />\r\nThe NIH has not yet collected tissue or blood samples from the British patient and the investigation is &quot;in the planning stages,&quot; Nat said. US researchers can examine samples from other vaccinated patients to see if any antibodies produced in response to the coronavirus also attack brain tissue or the spinal cord.<br />\r\nSuch a study could take a month or two, he said. The FDA declined to comment on how long it will take before deciding on another decision.<br />\r\nDr. Jesse Goodman, a professor and doctor at Georgetown University, chief scientist and chief vaccine regulator at the FDA during the Obama administration, said the agency would review the data and possibly consult with previous UK regulators to allow the US investigation to proceed, which had only just begun when the injury was reported. Two other coronavirus vaccines are also under follow-up studies in the United States<br />\r\nIf damage in the UK study is found to be caused by a vaccine, the FDA can suspend the interrupt. If it can be continued, regulators and scientists will definitely look for similar symptoms in other test takers.<br />\r\nOne volunteer in the early stages of the AstraZeneca study had a similar side effect, but the researchers found she had multiple sclerosis that was not related to vaccination, according to Dr. Elliott Froman, director of the Center for Multiple Sclerosis and Neuroimmunology at the University of Texas. .<br />\r\nNeuroscientists who study diseases such as transverse myelitis say they are rare - at a rate of perhaps 1 in 250,000 people - and most often because of the body&#39;s immune response to the virus. Less often, such episodes have also been linked to vaccines.<br />\r\nThe exact cause of the disease is key to the authorities&#39; decision on whether to continue with the process. Sometimes the underlying medical condition is &quot;exposed&quot; by a person&#39;s immune response to the vaccine, resulting in illness, as occurs in MS patients. In this case, the test can be continued without fear because the disease is not vaccine-specific.<br />\r\nEven more worrying is the phenomenon of &quot;molecular mimicry&quot;. In such cases, small portions of the vaccine may look like tissue in the brain or spinal cord, resulting in an immune attack on those tissues in response to the vaccine components. If so, it is likely that transverse myelitis will recur when the test is restarted, Dr said. William Schaffner, an infectious disease specialist at Vanderbilt University School of Medicine. The second case will end the process, he said.<br />\r\nIn 1976, a massive swine flu vaccination program was stopped when doctors began diagnosing a similar disease, Guillain-Barr&eacute; syndrome, in people receiving the vaccine. At the time, no one knew how common GBS was, so it was difficult to know if the episodes were vaccine-related.<br />\r\nFinally, the researchers found that the vaccine increased the risk of the disorder by one more case in the 100,000 vaccinated patients. The regular seasonal flu shot increases the risk of GBS in about one more case per 1 million people.<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s very, very difficult to know if a rare event was caused by a vaccine,&quot; said Schaffner. &quot;How do you relate increased risk to something that happens to one in a million people?&quot;<br />\r\nBefore the FDA allows testing to resume in the US, it wants to find out why the company and the UK&#39;s Independent Data Security and Monitoring Panel (DSMB) believe it is safe to continue, Goodman said. AstraZeneca processes in the US have a separate security notice.<br />\r\nFDA officials should review the full details of the case and request more information about the study volunteers concerned before deciding whether to pursue the US study, Goodman said. AstraZeneca may also need to update the safety information provided to study participants.<br />\r\nIt is possible that the volunteers&#39; health problems were accidental that had nothing to do with the vaccine, said Dr. Amesh Adalya, a senior scientist at the Johns Hopkins Center for Health Security. Usually, research doesn&#39;t stop at health problems, even if they are serious.<br />\r\nHowever, many leading health authorities have expressed disappointment that AstraZeneca has not released any further information on the health issues that have caused AstraZeneca to close its UK litigation.&quot;There is so little information that it is impossible to understand what the diagnosis is or why the DSMB and sponsors are convinced,&quot; Goodman said.<br />\r\nAstraZeneca said it could not provide further information on the health issue as it would violate patient privacy, although it did not specify how.<br />\r\nHowever, there is an urgent need for transparency in a political climate shaped by the volatility of vaccines and distrust of the Trump administration&#39;s handling of COVID-19, leading scholars say.<br />\r\n&quot;While I respect the critical need for patient confidentiality, I thought it would be helpful to know how they perceive this issue,&quot; Goodman said. &quot;What is the diagnosis? If there is no clear diagnosis, what makes you feel like this research can be restarted? The interest and potential concern about the COVID-19 vaccine is so great that the more information that is provided the more convincing.&quot;<br />\r\nThe FDA must consider all possible risks of experimental vaccines against the threat of COVID-19, which has killed nearly 200,000 Americans.<br />\r\n&quot;There are also potential consequences if you stop the research,&quot; Goodman said.<br />\r\nIf the AstraZeneca vaccine fails, the US government will support six more COVID-19 vaccines in the hope that at least one will work. The potential problem with the AstraZeneca vaccine shows that it is a wise investment, said Adalya.<br />\r\n&quot;That&#39;s part of the idea of not just having one vaccine candidate in front of you,&quot; he said. &quot;This gives you a little more insurance.&quot;<br />\r\nSchaffner says researchers must remember that vaccine research is unpredictable.<br />\r\n&quot;Investigators are inadvertently hiding their own vaccine,&quot; said Schaffner. &quot;The Oxford investigators were there this summer and said, &#39;We&#39;ll get there first.&#39; But that&#39;s why ... Dr. [Anthony] Fauzi and the rest of us said, &quot;You never know what would happen if you had gone through extensive human testing.&quot;</p>', 'NIH, AustaZeneca', 'Nih_1600342474.jpg', '2020-09-17 15:34:34', '2021-09-23 08:16:33'),
(622, 7, 1, 98, 'the-cdc-study-shows-the-coronavirus-rarely-kills-children-but-minorities-are-at-a-higher-risk-1600343088', 'The CDC study shows the coronavirus rarely kills children, but minorities are at a higher risk', 0, '<p><strong>According to a new report from the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, children and adolescents from minority groups, such as adults, are disproportionately affected by the coronavirus.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ethnic and racial minority children, those with basic health conditions, and children between the ages of 18 and 20 are more likely to die, according to the CDC-led research team in a study published Tuesday in the agency&#39;s weekly report on morbidity and mortality. .<br />\r\nThe report also revealed how unusual it is for children and adolescents to die from the coronavirus. Of the country&#39;s 190,000 registered deaths, only 0.08% - or 121 - were reported in those under 21. The latest CDC report shows that 377 children, adolescents and adolescents under the age of 24 have died from the coronavirus. Researchers asked 50 states, New York, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, Guam and the US Virgin Islands to provide information about coronavirus deaths in people under the age of 21 between February 12 and July 31. Forty-seven jurisdictions responded.<br />\r\nAmong the approximately 6.5 million Covid-19 cases in the country, researchers found a total of 391,814 cases of Covid-19 and MIS-C in people under the age of 21. While people under 21 make up 26% of the US population, they make up only 8% of all reported cases.<br />\r\nSpaniards, blacks, and Indians / Alaskans were disproportionately affected. 44% of the 121 people who died were Spanish, 29% were black children, 4% were Native Americans and 4% were residents of an Asian or Pacific island. While this group makes up 41% of the US population under the age of 21, they are responsible for approximately 75% of deaths in this age group. Fourteen percent of deaths occur in white children.<br />\r\n&quot;Infants, children, adolescents and young adults, especially those from racial and ethnic minorities at higher risk, those with underlying diseases and their caregivers, need clear, consistent and developmentally appropriate language communication and prevention of COVID-19, &quot;write the researchers. .<br />\r\nWhile 25% of deaths occurred in previously healthy children, 75% had at least one basic health condition and 45% had two or more. The diseases most frequently reported were chronic lung disease, including asthma; Obesity; neurological and developmental disorders and cardiovascular disease.<br />\r\nThe distribution between different age groups is very different, with young age groups outperforming adolescents and young adults. About 10% of deaths occurred in infants under 1 year of age, another 9% in children between 1 and 4 years of age, another 11% in the 5 to 9 range and 10% in the 10 to 13 years range. But nearly 20% of deaths were seen in adolescents between the ages of 14 and 17, and more than 40% were between 18 and 20 years.<br />\r\nThis is somewhat in line with previous CDC statistics, which found that children 0-4 years of age were four times less likely to be hospitalized and nine times less likely to die between the ages of 18 and 29, and five times less than 17 years and nine. times less likely to be hospitalized. and die 16 times less frequently than people 18 to 29 years old.<br />\r\nBoys fared worse than girls, with boys accounting for 63% of deaths and women 37%.Although children are conclusively less likely to become seriously ill and die, according to many studies they can become infected and transmit SARS-CoV-2 to others.<br />\r\nFor example, in a study published last week in MMWR, researchers analyzed contact tracing data from 184 people who had connections to three child care centers in Salt Lake County from April to July.<br />\r\nThey found at least two asymptomatic children who had not only contracted the virus but also passed it on to other people, including a mother who was hospitalized. An eight month old baby infected both parents.<br />\r\n&quot;Infected children exposed to these three facilities have mild to no symptoms. Two out of three asymptomatic children may have passed on SARS-CoV-2 to their parents and possibly their teacher,&quot; wrote the Salt Lake Health Department researcher. County. . A study from South Korea analyzed data on 91 asymptomatic, asymptomatic and symptomatic children diagnosed with Covid-19 between February 18 and March 31 at 22 centers across the country. It found that 22% of children were asymptomatic. The study was published in JAMA Pediatrics in late August.<br />\r\n&quot;This underscores the concept that children who are infected, with or without symptoms, are more likely to go unnoticed and resume normal activities, which can contribute to viral circulation in their community,&quot; wrote two doctors at Children&#39;s National Hospital in Washington, D.C. Colombia. in the attached edition.<br />\r\nCDC researchers in the current study said it was important to keep an eye on children infected with Covid-19. &quot;Although infants, children and adolescents are more likely to have milder COVID-19 disease than adults, this population develops complications, including MIS-C and respiratory failure. People infected with or exposed to SARS-CoV-2 must be closely monitored. so that clinical damage can be detected early, &quot;they wrote.</p>', 'CDC Study, Coronavirus', 'CDC_1600343088.jpg', '2020-09-17 15:44:48', '2021-08-17 18:39:17');
