(623, 7, 1, 170, 'when-adult-asthma-sends-you-to-the-emergency-room-1600343402', 'When adult asthma sends you to the emergency room', 0, '<p>Imagine this scenario: You have had asthma symptoms for the past three days and you can treat it with a rescue inhaler. You don&#39;t have time to call your doctor, but inhalers help every time you use them. Today you have difficulty speaking without feeling out of breath. You use your rescue inhaler, but after 15 minutes you still feel the wind. This is just one scenario that should be a red flag for adults with asthma. This means you will have emergency adult asthma care and will have to go to the emergency room for proper treatment.<br />\r\nThe signs and symptoms of worsening asthma are dangerous in adults<br />\r\nThe presence of more common asthma symptoms means that the disease is not well controlled. If you experience symptoms more than twice a week you should contact your doctor. You may need to change your treatment for better control. However, there are some symptoms that could mean you are in danger and need immediate help. Severe asthma attacks in adults can be rapid and fatal. Signs and symptoms of a potentially fatal asthma attack include:<br />\r\nExcitement or fear that gets worse over time, or feelings of fear or impending doom</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bluish skin, lips, or nails</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Confusion or altered consciousness</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Heart rate and rapid breathing</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Progressive shortness of breath or what people call air hunger</p>\r\n\r\n<p>sweat</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Language problems due to tightness or being unable to lie down due to difficulty breathing</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Use chest and neck muscles to help you breathe</p>\r\n\r\n<p>See a doctor immediately (call 911) if you or anyone else with any of these signs or symptoms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What to Expect in the Emergency Room<br />\r\nWhen you enter the emergency room, the staff will assess your symptoms and risk factors. This provides them with information about possible life-threatening situations. Risk factors can help you with this, even if you look stable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A major risk factor for a potentially fatal asthma attack is hospitalization for past asthma attacks. In this case, you need very careful monitoring. Other risk factors include a history of uncontrolled asthma or a new need for oral corticosteroids to treat the disease.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Emergency asthma in adults requires aggressive treatment. This includes supplemental oxygen and inhaled medications to relax and open airways. The staff can provide you with medication with a nebulizer or inhaler. The inhaled dose is very common, sometimes every 30 seconds. They will continue until you get better or can no longer tolerate the side effects. You will also be given corticosteroids either orally or via an intravenous line (intravenous). This drug helps stop asthma attacks. A nurse will accompany you and monitor your condition until you show signs of improvement. Monitoring includes continuous measurement of oxygen levels and regular monitoring of peak flow rates.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes asthma attacks don&#39;t respond to standard treatment. If the seizure is this severe, your doctor may give magnesium by IV. This drug relaxes the airway muscles. You may also need to use a mechanical ventilator to make breathing easier. If necessary, you need to be treated in an intensive care unit (intensive care unit). Your doctor may also take you to the hospital if your symptoms persist after 2 to 3 hours of aggressive treatment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What to expect when you get home<br />\r\nYour doctor can send you home if treatment in the emergency room improves your symptoms and peak flow rates. Or you can go home after being hospitalized. Before you leave, the staff will spend time with you to make sure you have the equipment you need to stay healthy. This includes a description of the criteria used to control asthma and how it looks when the disease is controlled:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yes, you can do all normal activities</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You have a maximum flow rate of at least 80% of your best flow rate</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is no more than one asthma attack per year requiring oral corticosteroids</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Symptoms no more than twice a week</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Do not use life-saving equipment more than twice a week</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wake up from sleep due to symptoms no more than twice a month</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will likely go on a prescription for inhaled corticosteroids and oral corticosteroid treatment. The staff will review the purpose of each of your asthma medications and how to use your inhaler properly. If you have trouble using your inhaler, ask the staff about the nebulizer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you don&#39;t have an asthma treatment plan when you arrive, the staff will provide you with one before you leave. You can renew your plan if you have one. The plan includes avoiding asthma and checking peak flow rates. Most importantly, determine what medications and actions to take in each area of asthma. Some general guidelines for areas of asthma are as follows:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Green room: You will have no symptoms and can do all your normal activities. Its maximum flow rate is 80% or better. This area is your daily goal. You use long-term medication for control or maintenance in this area.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Yellow zone: You have symptoms, you may wake up at night and not do some of your normal activities. Their peak flow is 50 to 79% at best. This area is a warning. You will need to add your rescue medication to your maintenance medication. If your symptoms do not improve within an hour, you should call your doctor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Red area: You have severe symptoms and you are unable to carry out any normal activities. The maximum flow rate is less than 50%. This is a danger zone. You must use your rescue medicine immediately. See an emergency doctor if symptoms do not improve within 15 minutes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When consulting your regular doctor, you may need to change your asthma action plan to suit your individual needs.</p>', 'Asthma, Emergency', 'Asthema_1600343402.jpg', '2020-09-17 15:50:02', '2021-08-17 11:59:23'),
(624, 7, 3, 75, 'acm-awards-who-won-who-loose-1600343727', 'ACM Awards Who won Who loose?', 0, '<p><strong>The Academy of Country Music Awards is broadcast live on Wednesday evening, bringing together the biggest names in country music.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Keith Urban delivers the Grand Ole Opry House event to an empty audience amid the Covid-19 pandemic, but the show is live.<br />\r\nThe actors are Taylor Swift, Carrie Underwood, Luke Brian, Eric Church, Luke Combs and Tim McGraw.<br />\r\nSwift took the stage for the first time in seven years to play &quot;Betty&quot; from her new album &quot;Folklore&quot;.<br />\r\nIn the broad category, Old Dominion won Band of the Year and Luke Combs won Album of the Year for &quot;What You See Is What You Get&quot;.<br />\r\nArtist of the year, ACM&#39;s biggest award, was awarded last and was surprised. Urban looked surprised when he opened the envelope and announced that this year&#39;s winner had finished the series between Carrie Underwood and Thomas Rhett. Despite having to share the awards, the two stars seemed equally excited during their acceptance speeches.<br />\r\nPreviously, Underwood won the award in 2009 and 2010.<br />\r\nCheck out the list of winners below.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>DUO OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Brooks &amp; Dunn</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brothers Osborne</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dan + Shay&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Florida Georgia Line</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maddie &amp; Tae</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>GROUP OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Lady A</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Little Big Town</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Midland</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Old Dominion&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Highwomen</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>NEW FEMALE ARTIST OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Ingrid Andress</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gabby Barrett</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lindsay Ell</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Caylee Hammack</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tenille Townes<strong>&nbsp;*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>NEW MALE ARTIST OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Jordan Davis</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Russell Dickerson</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Riley Green&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cody Johnson</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Morgan Wallen</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>ALBUM OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Center Point Road &mdash; Thomas Rhett</p>\r\n\r\n<p>GIRL &mdash; Maren Morris</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Heartache Medication &mdash; Jon Pardi</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What You See Is What You Get &mdash; Luke Combs&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wildcard &mdash; Miranda Lambert</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>SINGLE OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;God&#39;s Country&quot; &mdash; Blake Shelton&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One Man Band&quot; &mdash; Old Dominion</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Rainbow&quot; &mdash; Kacey Musgraves</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Rumor&quot; &mdash; Lee Brice</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;What If I Never Get Over You&quot; &mdash; Lady A</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>SONG OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;10,000 Hours&quot; &mdash; Dan + Shay with Justin Bieber</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Girl Goin&#39; Nowhere&quot; &mdash; Ashley McBryde</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;God&#39;s Country&quot; &mdash; Blake Shelton</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One Man Band&quot; &mdash; Old Dominion<strong>&nbsp;*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Some of It&quot; &mdash; Eric Church</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>VIDEO OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;10,000 Hours&quot; &mdash; Dan + Shay with Justin Bieber</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;God&#39;s Country&quot; &mdash; Blake Shelton</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One Man Band&quot; &mdash; Old Dominion</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Remember You Young&quot; &mdash; Thomas Rhett&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Sugar Coat&quot; &mdash; Little Big Town</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>SONGWRITER OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Ashley Gorley</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Michael Hardy</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hillary Lindsey<strong>&nbsp;*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Shane McAnally</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Josh Osborne</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>ENTERTAINER OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Luke Bryan</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Eric Church</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Luke Combs</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thomas Rhett&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Carrie Underwood&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>FEMALE ARTIST OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Kelsea Ballerini</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Miranda Lambert</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Maren Morris&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Kacey Musgraves</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Carrie Underwood</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>MALE ARTIST OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>Dierks Bentley</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Luke Combs&nbsp;<strong>*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thomas Rhett</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chris Stapleton</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Keith Urban</p>\r\n\r\n<h3><strong>MUSIC EVENT OF THE YEAR</strong></h3>\r\n\r\n<p>10,000 Hours -- Dan + Shay with Justin Bieber</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dive Bar -- Garth Brooks Featuring Blake Shelton</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Fooled Around and Fell in Love -- Miranda Lambert Featuring Maren Morris, Ashley McBryde, Tenille Townes, Caylee Hammack &amp; Elle King<strong>&nbsp;*WINNER</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Old Town Road -- Lil Nas X Featuring Billy Ray Cyrus</p>', 'ACM, Awards, Won', 'ACM Awards_1600343727.jpg', '2020-09-17 15:55:27', '2021-08-12 20:57:56'),
(625, 7, 3, 78, 'the-emmy-awards-will-live-live-live-expecting-something-to-go-wrong-1600348727', 'The Emmy Awards will \"live, live, live\" expecting something to go wrong', 0, '<p>The virtual Emmy Awards will be &quot;live, live, live,&quot; with the producer fully anticipating the offense and planning to play with them as much as possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The first major entertainment industry award after the pandemic will be broadcast on ABC and hosted by Jimmy Kimmel, who told the Hollywood Reporter he likes to &quot;expose me to difficult situations. So when the worst happens and it all happens.&quot; Booty, there will definitely be a part of me that enjoys it. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>watching other awards shows which are focusing on taped elements - like&nbsp; THE BET AWARDs and Daytime Emmys&nbsp; in June.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Having the nominee present from home - surrounded by family in some cases - will add a level of familiarity to the production. As Hudlin notes, people are inviting these programs into their homes for consumption, and &quot;Now we can go into their homes.&quot;<br />\r\nSpeaking to reporters with Zoom, producers also acknowledged that they paid attention to the tone of celebrating the best work on television while recognizing the unorthodox nature of this year&#39;s awards and what&#39;s happening in the world. This includes a fire that covers the Los Angeles air from which the award will originate.<br />\r\n&quot;The fire crisis we face is bigger than our little prize,&quot; said Hudlin, to which Stewart added, &quot;We are not deaf. We are trying to put on a show against a lot of things in this country.&quot;<br />\r\nTalents recently announced at the show include Jason Bateman, Sterling K. Brown, Lavern Cox, Earl von Graf on Sesame Street, Morgan Freeman, Ilana Glaser, Abby Jacobson, Lynn-Manuel Miranda, D-Nice and Randall Park. RuPole, Patrick Stewart and Jason Sudeikis. N.E.R. will also have a live performance in the &quot;In memoriam&quot; segment.</p>', 'Emmy Awards, live, go wrong', 'Emmy Awards_1600348592.jpeg', '2020-09-17 17:16:32', '2021-08-18 03:45:16'),
(626, 7, 3, 67, 'jim-carrey-as-joe-biden-in-snl-1600349037', 'Jim Carrey as Joe Biden in \"SNL\"', 0, '<p><strong>Jim Carrey will play the Democratic candidate and former vice president on SNL this season, NBC reported on Wednesday.</strong><br />\r\nThe show will return just in time to mock the 2020 presidential election when it debuts on October 3. The series will premiere in five consecutive episodes leading up to the November 3 election.<br />\r\nKerry was a surprising choice to play Biden because he was not part of the cast and former cast member Jason Sudeikis is known for his role as Biden.<br />\r\nHowever, over the past four years, SNL has attracted outside talent to play more characters. These include Robert De Niro as Robert Mueller, Brad Pitt as Dr. Anthony Fauci and of course Alec Baldwin as President Donald Trump.<br />\r\n&quot;SNL&quot; usually attracts more attention during election years, and Kerry&#39;s entry in combination with Trump at Baldwin should provide turbulent moments as the show takes over the debate and other election news.<br />\r\nThe other big news for &quot;SNL&quot; on Wednesday is that the show must return to the live audience.<br />\r\nSNL plans to have a &quot;limited studio audience&quot; at Rockefeller Center this season, its 46th on television, NBC reported. This is the first time since March that SNL has aired on Studio 8H due to the coronavirus pandemic.<br />\r\nAfter production stopped, &quot;SNL&quot; resumed a virtual show called &quot;Saturday Night Live At Home&quot; in April.</p>', 'Jim Carrey, Joe Biden, SNL', 'jim jerry joe_1600349037.jpg', '2020-09-17 17:23:57', '2021-08-17 18:18:00'),
(627, 7, 3, 72, 'chris-evans-appreciated-the-fans-support-after-the-embarrassing-photo-from-nsfw-1600349452', 'Chris Evans appreciated the fans\' support after the \"embarrassing\" photo from NSFW', 0, '<p><strong>The way you look at Chis Evans, he looks at you too, supporter.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Avengers star appeared on the Tamron Hall Show on Tuesday, turning to an inappropriate photo that briefly popped up on his verified Instagram account over the weekend.<br />\r\n&quot;Did something happen this weekend?&quot; Evans joked with Hall after asking him about it.<br />\r\n&quot;Captain America&quot; has previously used the attention of a viral moment to fulfill his patriotic duty by posting on Twitter: &quot;Now I have your attention ... VOTE November 3 !!!&quot;<br />\r\nHe said to Hall, &quot;That&#39;s called a frown, Tamron.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Look, it&#39;s been an exciting weekend full of lessons and learning moments,&quot; said Evans. &quot;You know, a lot of things happen, it&#39;s a shame, you have to take the punches. I would say I have a lot of fantastic fans who really support me and that&#39;s really good.&quot;<br />\r\nAs for the front - or what people up front suspect - Chris Evans&#39; fans are backing it.</p>', 'Avengers, Chris Evans', 'Chris_1600349452.jpg', '2020-09-17 17:30:52', '2021-08-17 22:38:34'),
(628, 7, 3, 65, 'jennifer-aniston-and-brad-pitt-are-back-together-this-time-for-a-good-cause-1600350507', 'Jennifer Aniston and Brad Pitt are back together, this time for a good cause', 0, '<p><strong>History has shown us that people get pretty excited whenever Jennifer Aniston and Brad Pitt are within the vicinity of each other.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>That happened again recently, albeit virtually, according to a photo posted by Dane Cook.<br />\r\nCook recently shared a group photo on Instagram, which included the exes in the cast of a &quot;Fast Times at Ridgemont High&quot; table read scheduled to stream Thursday for charity.<br />\r\nBesides Aniston, Pitt and Cook, the photo included Matthew McConaughey, Sean Penn, Jimmy Kimmel, John Legend, Ray Liotta, Julia Roberts, Shia LaBeouf, Morgan Freeman and Henry Golding.<br />\r\nAniston and Pitt made headlines in January when they were photographed sharing a moment backstage after they both won at the SAG Awards.<br />\r\nThe pair were married from 2000-2005 and had a pretty famous split.Proceeds raised will go to CORE and to the REFORM Alliance.</p>', 'Jennifer Aniston, Brad Pitt', 'Brad_1600350481.jpg', '2020-09-17 17:48:01', '2021-08-12 21:03:25'),
(629, 7, 3, 84, 'comedy-central-broadcasts-one-hour-special-south-park-pandemic-1600350755', 'Comedy Central Broadcasts One Hour Special \"South Park\" Pandemic', 0, '<p><strong>&quot;South Park&quot; returns on September 30th for a special one hour event - and what shouldn&#39;t come as a surprise in 2020 is Covid-19.</strong><br />\r\nNext titled &quot;Special Pandemic&quot;, Stan&#39;s father, Randy Marsh, will tap into the growing welding market for Tegridy Farms&#39; pot business and &quot;enjoy his role in the COVID-19 stove.&quot; , Comedy Central said in its press release.<br />\r\nMeanwhile, episode footage shows kids at school with dividers around their desks and a police sign replacing their teacher.<br />\r\nThe animated comedy series created by creators Matt Stone and Trey Parker does not shy away from current events. For example, in 2015 the event started a debate on gun control.<br />\r\nThe long-running series, which ended its 23rd season last year, first premiered on Comedy Central in 1997. The premiere date for season 24 has yet to be announced.<br />\r\nComedy Central will debut its pandemic episode at 8pm. ET. The episode will air after airing on the West Coast at South Park Studios, on CC.com and on the Comedy Central app. It will also be available on HBO Max 24 hours after its premiere.</p>', 'Comedy Central, South Park', 'Comedy_1600350755.jpg', '2020-09-17 17:52:35', '2021-08-11 23:58:07'),
(630, 7, 3, 93, 'challenger-celebrates-the-crew-by-outlining-what-went-wrong-with-the-failed-flight-1600351857', 'Challenger celebrates the crew by outlining what went wrong with the failed flight', 0, '<p>Subsequent coverage of the Challenger disaster is always vaguely disgusting because we all know how the story ends. But Challenger: The Final Flight moves in a complicated way - celebrating the lives of the lost in 1986 and the neglect, politics, and pressure to achieve it have become the anatomy of failure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The four-part documentary series that airs on Netflix goes beyond history, including efforts to diversify the space program, the half-dozen women who have joined the astronaut class since 1978, and how NASA has exploited the idea. Taking Master into Space Public relations action as people are blessed for the shuttle missions. (There&#39;s even a clip from a Jerry Seinfeld practice routine to illustrate the idea.)<br />\r\nThis teacher, Christa McAuliff, is the name that most resonates with an unprecedented crew of seven diverse people who died despite warnings and alarms regarding the safety of the shuttle and, in particular, the o-rings used to bolster solid missiles. -state made by Challenger. Share 73 seconds after launch.<br />\r\nDeath does not overshadow the anger or emotions shared not only by friends and family, but also by NASA veterans, some of whom still vividly remember how their fears were overlooked or ignored, and the arrogance that Success caused by the program was expressed.<br />\r\n&quot;How can you live with yourself to make a decision like that?&quot; asked June Scobie Rodgers, widow of Aviation Commander Francis &quot;Dick&quot; Scobie. (In particular, some of the former employees surveyed disagreed with their roles.)<br />\r\nDirectors Stephen Lecart and Daniel Junge (who worked with a team that includes executive producer JJ Abrams) paint best with the widest brush, and capture the romance surrounding the most numerous space programs about &quot;The Right Stuff.&quot; &quot;has been the best<br />\r\nA symbol of American knowledge exemplified by the introduction of the reusable spacecraft.<br />\r\nThis ingenuity stands in stark contrast to the mistakes made, and evident in the aftermath of the accident, when the Reagan administration attempted to soften the findings of the investigation commission so as not to cripple and embarrass NASA.<br />\r\nIf it gets a good grade, it&#39;s an explicit belief that NASA has learned from this painful chapter by tackling technical issues and adapting its bureaucratic culture.<br />\r\nEven those who are old enough to remember tragedy on television - an image that will remain indelible in the coming days - will be captured by some of the old footage and home video, including the faces of students, NASA staff, and the gathered crowd noticing that bursts. smoke means something is terribly wrong.<br />\r\n&quot;The country needs something you feel comfortable with,&quot; said astronaut Robert Crippen of national sentiment about the space shuttle program in the 1980s.<br />\r\nSince today&#39;s needs are greater than ever, these observations explain why the timing of The Last Flight feels so touching and precise.</p>', 'Challenger celebrates, crew failed', 'Celebrates crew_1600351857.jpg', '2020-09-17 18:10:57', '2021-08-16 22:43:50'),
(631, 7, 3, 87, 'the-devil-all-the-time-brings-its-superstar-cast-into-a-dark-thriller-on-netflix-1600352018', '\"The Devil All the Time\" brings its superstar cast into a dark thriller on Netflix', 0, '<p>Only casting should spark interest in &quot;The Devil All the Time&quot; - Batman (Robert Pattinson) and Spiderman (Tom Holland), finally together, but this film can&#39;t feel like a slogan that it lacks. Based on Dale Ray Pollock&#39;s grim novel, the horror character continues on parallel paths and heads for a lot of violence and anger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pollock actually plays the film&#39;s narrator (often used), and he&#39;s an unconventional naturalist who gives director Antonio Campos&#39;s film literary authenticity. As well as attracting a cast of extraordinarily good actors - many in relatively minor roles - the compliant nature of adaptations weighs in on much of film life.<br />\r\nPut simply, &quot;The Devil All the Time&quot; has the texture of a Cohen brothers film with a hint of &quot;LA Confidential&quot; in terms of music and timing. But despite vivid renderings of a secret era and small town like Knockemstiff, Ohio, he lacks the wits in these films and is so moving around that it becomes easy to nervously wait for the line to cross.<br />\r\nIn fact, those depicted by the superstar above had to be warned or appeared until more than a third of the film, which started in 1957, was from a soldier returning from WWII. and before it ended, he jumped into the days of escalation in Vietnam, which lasted for about 20 years.<br />\r\nCovering this type of soil is a tough task that can be done better and extends over a limited range. Having said that, the film essentially moves from character to character, in a way that definitely feels episodic, leaving several talented actors - including Hailey Bennett and Mia Vasikovska - with little work to do.<br />\r\nThe initial part is based on the soldier mentioned above (Bill Skarsg&aring;rd), whose adult son Arvin (Netherlands) grows up with a young girl (Eliza Scanlen) who survives a separate tragedy.<br />\r\nElsewhere, there are two serial killers (Jason Clark and Riley Kew) who pick up and kill the passengers. a corrupt sheriff (Sebastian Stan, another refugee from the Marvel universe) tries to get re-elected; and a lecherous preacher (Pattinson) who appears in the film for nearly an hour, giving sermons that only describe his hypocrisy.<br />\r\nArvin&#39;s father didn&#39;t teach him much, but he supported justice in the form of revenge. The character certainly offers a different side to the Dutch, one of the few people who have been given significant screen time to show much in the way of compassion or humanity.<br />\r\nBringing the cast together is, of course, a promotional coup for Netflix, likely to place the film on the most popular lists, amid an increase that includes planning for weekly executive positions in times of the deadline for the theater business.<br />\r\nHowever, feeling compelled (or at least motivated) to watch is not the same as liking it. And with &quot;The Devil All the Time&quot; mistakes are not just the details.</p>', 'Devil all the time, Superstar, Netflix', 'Devil_1600352018.jpg', '2020-09-17 18:13:38', '2021-08-12 00:11:15'),
(632, 7, 17, 294, 'madonna-was-supposed-to-make-a-biographical-film-about-her-life-1600352677', 'Madonna was supposed to make a biographical film about her life', 0, '<p>If anyone had to tell Madonna Louise Chicone&#39;s story, it had to be Material Girl herself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Madonna will be making an upcoming biographical film about her life, co-written by Diablo Cody.<br />\r\nThe film, which is distributed by Universal, is untitled.<br />\r\n&quot;I want to convey the extraordinary journey in which life as an artist, musician, dancer has brought me - someone who is trying to find his way into this world,&quot; Madonna said of the statement in the film. &quot;The focus of this film will always be on the music. Music keeps me going and art keeps me alive. There are so many untold and inspiring stories, and who can tell them better than me. It&#39;s important train travel in amusement park life to share with them my voice and vision. &quot;<br />\r\nThis film followed Madonna&#39;s rise to fame, from her Catholic education in Michigan, to her move to New York, and her subsequent international fame.<br />\r\nOn a recent Live Instagram, Madonna said the film would ruin her songwriting, singer and actress skills.<br />\r\nMadonna teased the news over the weekend by writing, &quot;Are you ready for the story of my life ... am I?&quot;<br />\r\nMadame X, we are sure of it.</p>', 'Madonna, biographical film', 'madonna_1600352677.jpg', '2020-09-17 18:24:37', '2021-12-19 17:34:44'),
(633, 7, 3, 97, 'raised-by-wolves-is-a-kind-of-science-fiction-show-that-can-be-shown-by-hbo-max-on-the-map-1600584757', 'Raised by Wolves is a kind of science fiction show that can be shown by HBO Max on the map', 0, '<p><strong>Raised by Wolves is perhaps the most original of the series this year, a daring brain science fiction concept that covers so many premiere basics that it&#39;s hard to imagine where the show could end. Ridley Scott, who also directed the first two episodes and produced by Blade Runner and Alien, was uneven in places, but joins the alpha level of the streaming package in terms of risk-taking.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Aaron Guzikowski&#39;s (The Red Road) premise contradicts simple description. But it is difficult to escape the serious echoes of the real world when people are forced to build colonies beyond Earth after destroying the planet not because of climate change, but also because of unrestricted ethnicity and wars between believers and atheists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In this regard, we are embarking on an atheist effort that sends a pair of androids - known as mother (Amanda Colin) and father (Abubakar Salim) - with multiple fertilized embryos to the habitable planet Kepler-22b. It is planned to bear and raise children to lay the foundation for human survival.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Conditions are difficult to say as the group throws the ball unexpectedly from a corner. In addition, a ship entering orbit is actually a coffin inhabited by believers, and raises the specter that a military action starting on earth will follow humanity into space.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There have been many appearances of actors like androids, but it&#39;s hard to imagine anyone more believable than Colin - I think of the work of Scandinavian colleague Alicia Vikander in &quot;Ex Machina&quot; - Salim, whose father tried Change shouldn&#39;t distract children by telling jokes that bad to dad. The cast also includes Travis Fimel (&quot;Viking&quot;) as a soldier on another ship, though that&#39;s all anyone has to do with regards to the show&#39;s rainbow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Put simply, the show has been staggering time and time again, with a visually appealing design and appearance that transcends some blockbuster special effects. It&#39;s also writing proof that the story takes you into twists and turns - including flashbacks to convey character details - despite the multitude of actions that need to be blocked for any of this to make any sense.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>HBO Max (as CNN, a division of WarnerMedia) got off to a rather tedious start to the original program, but &quot;Raised by Wolves&quot; is sort of an ambitious proposition set to make waves in the passionate streaming arena. This is especially true for those interested in service fantasy, science fiction, and comics such as Game of Thrones and DC Entertainment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even in this smaller universe, this series isn&#39;t for everyone. But that should make HBO Max a regular target for discriminating against some people.</p>', 'Wolves, HBO, Fiction movie', 'wolves scitifics_1600584756.jpg', '2020-09-20 10:52:37', '2021-08-16 07:20:37'),
(634, 7, 3, 107, 'ratch-flies-closer-to-american-horror-story-than-one-fly-over-a-cuckoos-nest-1600584857', 'Ratch flies closer to American Horror Story than One Fly Over a Cuckoo\'s Nest', 0, '<p>In a recent hybridization of intellectual property, Ryan Murphy&#39;s &quot;Ratched&quot; is essentially &quot;American Horror Story: A Cuckoo&#39;s Nest,&quot; a kind of prequel in which Sarah Paulson plays the stoic, stoic nurse in &quot;One Flew Over the Cuckoo&#39;s Nest. &quot; . in the Florida Sea with the excess of the noir force. The big, spectacular roles of the cast are amazingly abundant, but mostly to serve up shiny trash.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Netflix&#39;s eight-part drama (and no, it&#39;s not meant to be a check-in, limited series release) is created by newcomer Evan Romanski and takes on all of Murphy&#39;s lead, starting with some of the grisly murders of another pastor by producer Finn Whitrock. The character is under psychiatric protection in the ancient coastal town of Northern California in 1947, where stylish fashion and Hitchcock-Ian music accompanies every long coastal journey.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Enter Paulson&#39;s Mildred Ratched, whose confirmation smoothly belies more serious intentions. While looking for a place as a nurse in a restaurant for reasons that soon become apparent, she immediately arouses the suspicions of the head nurse (Judy Davis) and the curious landlady (Amanda Plummer) at the motel where Mildred is moving.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are already three fancy roles, but wait, there are others, including Cynthia Nixon as Assistant Governor (Vincent D&#39;Onofrio) who found political motivation to be interested in mental health programs; Sophie Oconedo as patient; and Sharon Stone as a rich woman who keeps her secrets and desires to take revenge on the asylum administrator (Jon Jon Briones).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s very feminine firepower and the cast immerses themselves in all this chewing with cruel neglect.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sadly, that&#39;s a little too frivolous, and her relationship with The Cuckoo&#39;s Nest - the 1975 Oscar-winning film starring Jack Nicholson based on the Ken Cassie novel - feels pretty lame. While the series took on the social morals of the time, including homophobia and sexism, it played primarily as an excuse for the darker horror story-style violence emanating from the noisy areas of Murphy&#39;s prolific filmography rather than being high pitched. (See &quot;Hostility: Beth and Joan&quot; or &quot;American Detective Tales&quot;) or the source.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s a shame that Paulson is the perfect choice to play the tense and very calm character who won an Oscar for Louise Fletcher, and like Murphy&#39;s other new Netflix era song, &quot;Hollywood,&quot; all of her casting and overall gorgeous look.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This lavish attribute is sacrificed on a bottomless altar of dirt, and the title finally feels more than just to appeal to those curious about how the series and films will overlap.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The result, simply put, is that &quot;Ratched&quot; will suffer for all the wrong reasons, and even in the &quot;Joys of Guilt&quot; cabinet it doesn&#39;t deserve to stay long.</p>', 'Ratch Flies, Horror story', 'Rached flies_1600584857.jpg', '2020-09-20 10:54:17', '2021-08-17 23:12:10'),
(635, 7, 3, 105, 'emmy-preview-watchmen-and-mandalorian-show-you-the-way-to-a-strange-virtual-weekend-1600585303', 'Emmy Preview: \"Watchmen\" and \"Mandalorian\" show you the way to a strange virtual weekend', 0, '<p><strong>Emmys will be handed out this weekend, but in preparation for the main event in what may be the oddest week in the awards 72 years history, 70 categories have been unveiled, highlighting the television industry&#39;s awkwardness.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 75 awards (multiple jury categories have multiple winners) have so far been awarded to 26 different streaming networks and services, some of which, such as Disney +, Apple TV + and Quibi, didn&#39;t exist in the last year. Another 54 categories will be distributed over the weekend - 30 on Saturday at the Creative Arts Show and two dozen during the main show on Sunday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The two programs have won five awards each, and both come from the fantasy / science fiction / comic genre Game of Thrones skillfully presented during their parade through the Emmy story: &quot;Guardians,&quot; a limited edition HBO comic and film; and The Mandalorian, the addition to the Star Wars universe that made Baby Yoda the world&#39;s most popular meme, from Disney +. (HBO and CNN share the parent company WarnerMedia.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the first time, the Emmy will be held virtually, with nominations staying at home due to the coronavirus pandemic. But producers determined to &quot;live, live, live,&quot; as they described in conversations with reporters, sent 130 cameras into the field, and hoped that technically nothing (or at least very little) was wrong.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Netflix has broken a record 160 nominations with such a wide variety of programs, but that&#39;s no guarantee of winning the most trophies, in part because it often competes with itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So far, HBO - Emmy Leader for the two decades before Netflix caught up - and Netflix garnered a dozen Emmys each in a four-day presentation, followed by Disney + with six Emmys. This is largely thanks to &quot;The Mandalorian&quot;, which was also nominated for best drama and received awards in areas such as visual effects, cinematography and sound.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although the most famous categories are still waiting, there are already some notable milestones, including Emmys for some neo-vegetarians: legendary producer Norman Lear (98) beat his own record as the oldest person to win a Live Audience Award. &quot;ABC Special&quot; and naturalist David Attenborough (93) received their third Emmy of their career notable for the BBC story &quot;Seven Worlds, One Planet&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The creative arts ceremony will be shown on FXX and the main television show will be shown on ABC. Tyler Perry receives the Governor&#39;s Award.</p>', 'Guards and Mandalorian, Emmy Preview', 'Emmy Prreview_1600585303.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:01:43', '2021-08-13 06:02:15'),
(636, 7, 3, 86, 'why-celebrating-emmys-now-is-more-than-good-1600585580', 'Why celebrating Emmys now is more than good', 0, '<p><strong>The gravity of 2020 can leave celebrities and their jobs feeling shallow until you stop thinking about what that job means to us today.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Global pandemics, race wars, upcoming presidential elections that divide nations, and a fiery climate crisis in the western United States are not making a happy year - and those are only part of what will happen in 2020.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So it&#39;s not surprising that many of us feel that the rewards are not above what we need to focus on right now. But this list of problems is precisely why pop culture - and television in particular - is so important today. Television not only informs and reflects who we are, it connects us and offers protection from stories that we can avoid when things get too overwhelming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I don&#39;t know about you, but this year it seemed to me the definition of &quot;too much.&quot; Here are some examples of how television can help you get through your day. &quot;Friend&quot;: Miss showed up at Starbucks for your favorite latte? Feeling like this recently, I decided to air some episodes of this hit series. I wasn&#39;t a fan when it originally aired for lack of representation (how do you live in New York, for example, and don&#39;t have a very diverse cast?).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But this time, when I walked into the fictional Central Perk Caf&eacute; on Friends, I felt convinced. It reminds me of encountering my appearance and the fun (and drama) that can arise when that happens.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was easy to see and I hope to meet my own friends in person one day. I never imagined in a million years that a 90s sitcom would inspire me to look to the future, but here we are. Also, I finally felt armed and ready for curious questions about the song &quot;Smelly Cat&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When and when the friends meeting finally works out, I&#39;ll be there for Rachel, Ross, Monica, and the whole gang. 72 Primetime Emmy Awards: Speaking of Friends, Jennifer Aniston and The Morning Show were among the Emmy nominees for Sunday, and it felt right to stop and get to know some of last year&#39;s great TV shows.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The most-nominated series, HBO&#39;s The Guardians with 26 nominations, feels terrifying with its focus on racism during country-wide civil unrest over racial injustice. I know of at least three people who have discovered the charm of Crete Sheath, the best comedy, since the quarantine began.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>And many more where it came from. Fortunately for us consumers, the streaming wars are raging with newcomers to Apple TV +, Disney +, HBO Max, and Peacock. So, there are many things to enjoy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While we remain in this period of constant uncertainty, Hollywood is also trying to get back to work creating new shows.</p>', 'Celebrating, Emmys night', 'Emmy is good_1600585580.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:06:20', '2021-08-16 23:20:13'),
(637, 7, 3, 73, 'justin-bieber-and-rapper-chance-get-holy-in-an-exciting-new-video-1600585668', 'Justin Bieber and Rapper Chance get \"Holy\" in an exciting new video', 0, '<p>Justin Bieber and Chance Rapper release the new song &quot;Holy&quot; with a five minute video starring Ryan Destini from Fox&#39;s &quot;Star&quot; series and &quot;NCIS &quot;&#39;s Wilmer Valderrama.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The song, which Bieber shared on Instagram, Twitter and YouTube Thursday evening US time, is about love, hope and faith. The video was shot by Colin Tilly, who recently shot Cardi B and Megan T Stallion&#39;s &quot;WAP&quot; video of Bieber as an unemployed oil worker and Destini as his girlfriend, a nurse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The couple was evicted from their home and on the street before Valderrama, who plays a US Army soldier, took them to a hot meal with his family. The final footage of the video shows characters at the dining table holding hands and praying.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bieber shared the video and said on social media that it marked a &quot;new era&quot;. Chance the rapper referred to Bieber as a &quot;best friend&quot; in an Instagram post earlier this week before the song was released.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>When he shared the video on Thursday, he said, &quot;I made one of my most important songs with one of my most supportive friends and I really want you to listen to it tonight when it falls. I know you felt something about this record and I know that feeling is love. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bieber and Chance the Rapper have collaborated on a number of songs including &quot;No Brainer&quot; in 2018 with DJ Khaled and Quavo, &quot;I&#39;m The One&quot; in 2017, and &quot;Confident&quot; in 2013.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Holy&quot; is Bieber&#39;s first new song since the release of his album &quot;Changes&quot; in February - his first album in nearly five years.</p>', 'Rapper, Justin Bieber', 'justine barbar_1600585668.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:07:48', '2021-08-18 03:24:06');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(638, 7, 3, 126, 'tiff-2020-got-off-to-a-strange-start-for-the-oscars-1600586281', 'TIFF 2020 got off to a strange start for the Oscars', 0, '<p>That year the wings were cut at the Toronto International Film Festival with seemingly endless growth. Instead of the thousands of titles stuck in parts of the program, there are 50 that are simply gorgeous. Blame it on the pandemic. The release plan has been revised, some films will wait until 2021. Netflix is increasing as registrants revise the qualification rules. However, the selection of decorative items in Toronto is procedural and we have to respect the films that make the jump knowing they will land on unstable ground.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was a letter of intent that happened in Toronto from the very beginning. Other festivals such as Cannes remain; Telluride followed suit. Venice and Toronto are fighting well and New York and London are at the front, but as a launch pad they don&#39;t have the same spring this year. The propulsion relies on red carpet gastronomy and pressed meat from industry insiders and the opinion of sleepless and overly caffeinated journalists. It helps to have everything in one place.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In contrast, press screenings in Toronto are held on virtual portals, while public screenings are limited online and in theaters. The stars enter via zoom. These can never be compared, but the systems stick together and bring new cultural insights to living rooms around the world. Because the arts plan their opposition to the economic realities of Covid-19, this is important.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What did it mean in those strange years for films to come out against the backdrop of a pandemic? The traditional trajectory for many - Autumn Festival thunderbolts, passing the end of the year, and continuing to compete for prizes - has turned into a bigger marathon with Oscars postponed to April (this may be optimistic). It took some of these films a long time to see a normal release. Some may be lost in the delay between when the pandemic ends and when it ends. On the other hand, a less crowded program leaves more room for the film to be screened more deeply than a sip of thin air the fall festival fairs hold. Success can still turn into a little golden man in the spring.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, maybe this fall will take a little peek at the horizon and explore more of what&#39;s on our feet. And what we have are some really good films.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>One Night In Miami</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200917174838-tiff-2020-one-night-in-miami-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One Night in Miami&quot; marks Regina King&#39;s feature film directorial debut.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sometimes the movies feel like they are made in the moment, and One Night Regina King in Miami is one of them. Their performance in the hit game Kemp Power pits Malcolm X, Sam Cook, Jim Brown and Cassie Clay (soon to become Muhammad Ali) in a fictional room game that ignites the night when Clay defeats Sonny Liston to become world heavyweight champion. Category. Heavyweight performances by Kingsley Ben-Adir, Aldis Hodge, Eli Gori, and Leslie Odom Jr. takes us from the humble atmosphere of a motel and into a place where language and ideas emerge - where Black America and its future. They can be discussed lively if no decisions are made.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These four voices from the past reached this moment and spoke with terrifying knowledge. &quot;Our people literally die on the streets every day,&quot; said X; It was the language we heard on the news all summer. One Night in Miami is a call to clarity, a vehicle for excellence, and a definite directorial debut for an Oscar winner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;MLK/FBI&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200917180749-tiff-2020-mlk-fbi-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sam Pollard&#39;s documentary is based on the latest disclosure of the FBI&#39;s surveillance of Martin Luther King Jr. to paint a doomed picture of fear and prejudice underpinned by institutional power. For anyone who has followed the release of the document, there may be a little you didn&#39;t know beforehand, but Pollard skillfully assembled a compelling evidence base, starting with informants in King Jr. orbit. to the knock on the phone to the scandalous letter from the FBI. By adding additional context, we also show the role of popular culture in glorifying the FBI, Pollard, who drew the line between television and film, and the public support of J Edgar Hoover and his office when it all happened.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I think this whole episode is the darkest part of office history,&quot; said the interviewee James Comey. As for the evidence, it&#39;s hard to disagree.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&#39;Nomadland&#39;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200917174449-tiff-2020-nomadland-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The film&#39;s golden lion in Venice won a full win last week. Chloe Zhao&#39;s exquisite creative work immersed Francis McDormand in the little-known American baby boomer culture of adopting a nomadic lifestyle. Their reasons are diverse: financial ruin, disappointment, personal loss. McDormand Fern&#39;s character was all over the top, losing her husband as well as her city - Empire, Nevada - when the American cast closed in 2011.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The sight that drives your converted van through the Badlands to the west coast is breathtaking, lively and hard and the friendship warm. While Fern is fiction, most players are real people, and interactions are strongest in this confined space. McDormand, who appears as kind-hearted Sasha Baron Cohen, replaces the truths of a unique American reality in exchange for friendship and compassion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m not homeless, I&#39;m homeless,&quot; Fern said, &quot;it&#39;s not the same.&quot; Zhao and McDormand&#39;s creation is a unique work, beautifully completed, similar to something we&#39;ve never seen before.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&#39;Pieces of a Woman&#39;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Criticism was also shared by Cornell&#39;s bad-mouth melodrama, but what was undeniable was the change in power that host Vanessa Kirby (&quot;The Crown&quot;) gave her. The Hungarian director starts off with a 30-minute sequence where husband Martha and Kirby Sean (Shia LaBoeuf) have a home delivery, which is tragically wrong. What begins playfully and lovingly becomes satisfying and exciting to the heart; honestly the unspoken image of loss as one can imagine.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s an experience that the couple and the film will never recover from - that&#39;s how strong an early volley, whatever follows it, will always be a step down in dramatic stakes. But Martha&#39;s calm determination and anguish was skillfully played by Kirby, bringing &quot;Pieces of a Woman&quot; to a satisfying conclusion. This is already an award-winning achievement that earned her the Volpi Cup for best actress in Venice. More gongs could follow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&quot;Limbo&quot;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200917180519-tiff-2020-limbo-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The British indie greats won hearts in Toronto after being announced in the official Cannes elections earlier this year. Set on a remote Scottish island, Ben Sharrock&#39;s play shares many of the same themes as nomadic land - displacement, loss, isolation, raw nature - but operates at a higher stakes because neither side chooses to be there. Where.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>We follow Omar (Amir El-Masri), a Syrian asylum seeker living in a windy purgatory, waiting for his case to be tried. He wandered around the island, carrying his limbs and the weight of the world on his shoulders, and phoned his parents in Turkey and asked him to come back. But he is determined to find friendly ties with Afghanistan and loyal fans of Freddie Mercury Farhad (Gulf of Vikash) and West African brothers Abedi (Kwabena Ansah) and Wassef (Ola Orebie), all on their mission to stay in Britain. united. Some applications succeed, others tragically fail. Meanwhile, a course on &quot;cultural awareness&quot; should be followed to humiliate everyone involved.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The still waters flow deep into El-Masri&#39;s restrained appearance, while the situation propels Omar through 4: 3 cameraman Nick Cook&#39;s composition. It is a serene and beautiful story that is easy to find in unexpected places.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>&#39;I Care a Lot&#39;</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200917175639-tiff-2020-i-care-a-lot-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>You know thriller is dark when it starts with the uncontrollable exploits of a parent, but what&#39;s fun is &quot;I&#39;m so worried.&quot; Jay Blackeson&#39;s film wasted no time paving its way to a moral abyss, and Rosamund Pike was behind the wheel, restoring the recklessness of Frozen who was last seen in David Fincher&#39;s The Gone Girl. Pike plays Marla Grayson, a professional guardian whose goal is to lock himself in a nursing home and pocket his fortune in his corporate pocket. He was the supreme leech and proud that he was truly good at it. But when a new client (Diane West) proves difficult because of her extraordinary and violent relationship, Grayson decides that attack is the best form of defense.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From there, the film takes a completely different perspective and is constantly changing gears. Salty, sour and seasoned with real poison, little if anyone could take root, but it&#39;s nice to see everyone squeeze it. &quot;Trust me, no one is good,&quot; said Grayson in his opening voice. Yes, not kidding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Apples&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Christo Nikus&#39; drama about the amnesia pandemic lives in the same absurd and disturbing world as George Lantimos (&quot;The Favorite&quot;) - which makes sense if you find out that Niko was once an assistant director. However, this extraordinary debut, which focuses on interrupting human work and restoring one&#39;s sense of self - good, bad, painful - is characterized by its tenderness. This is thanks in large part to his host Aris Servetalis and the compassionate eyes of Niku, who proclaimed himself to be the most important new voice in the Greek New Wave. It is hoped that greater things will come.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Beans&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tracy Deere&#39;s adult film is unlike any other adult film where this Mohawk Tekehenthahva girl has an experience most young people have never had. The story takes place in the midst of the 1990 Oka Crisis, a land dispute between Mohawk and authorities over plans to build a holy cemetery in Quebec, Canada. It was inspired by events from the director&#39;s childhood. Deer find a canal in the newcomer Kiawentiio, the tekehentahkhwa (peanuts of his friends) moving in the middle of a blockade and armed conflict in danger that was famous in his youth. As tensions mount, even a child is not free from abuse by an increasingly angry audience - and citing past documentaries, Deer added archival footage to aid criticism in the script.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>History tells us this story has a happy ending, but Deer never satisfied the audience and the film won its streak of wins. And like a light in the dark, Kiawentiio&#39;s meaningless feat was a breakthrough that was sure to attract additional attention.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;New Order&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Michael Franco&#39;s latest film isn&#39;t for everyone. The highly cynical drama bordering on the nihilistic and cutting-edge revolutionary drama of the Mexican provocateurs has something to say, and he puts it in a very grim manner. But it&#39;s definitely not boring.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the opening of the busy hospital with our patients being discharged, we moved on to civil marriage. Sirens sound in the distance as guests sip champagne and feel safe in their paved surroundings. The revolution was not recognized, and certainly not the proletariat, who started painting Mexico City a beautiful green. But to paraphrase Mike Tyson, everyone has a plan until they get a gun in the face.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The bride Marian (Nai&aacute;n Gonz&aacute;lez Norvind) is kidnapped and the family and house employees do everything they can to get her back while the police and military create a military zone in the city. One act of violence follows another, as power plays turn characters into pawns in a game of chess that they never wanted to play (even if their lifestyle had lowered the board).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Franco appears to be working on the thesis that, rather than inspiring a better world, unrest is something that can be used to consolidate power. The film&#39;s prestige is as threatening as it is with a worrying conclusion.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Another Round&#39;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you can live continuously, will that be an improvement? This is the question behind Thomas Winterberg&#39;s drunken comedy about four middle-aged teachers who experiment on themselves to take away their excitement. At the suggestion of storyteller Martin (Mads Mickelsen, who reproduces his relationship with Winterberg), they target a blood alcohol level of 0.05% and take it from there. Of course, things get confusing in both professional and personal life, but like any good scientist they at least take notes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mickelsen shows a vulnerable side a million miles from his big (and perhaps career-defining) change when Hannibal Lecter, and supporters Thomas Bo Larsen, Lars Rant and Magnus Milang add quite a punch to the story. It would be too easy to call &quot;Another Round&quot; another comedy about a midlife crisis. There is a lot of soul - and soul searching - with laughter.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Toronto International Film Festival is coming to an end, but the competition for awards has only just begun. Let the marathon begin.</p>', 'Tiff, OScars', 'Tiff oscar_1600586281.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:18:01', '2021-08-18 00:15:41'),
(639, 7, 3, 123, 'chrissy-teigen-accidentally-revealed-the-gender-of-baby-3-1600586466', 'Chrissy Teigen accidentally revealed the gender of baby 3', 0, '<p><strong>Chrissy Teigen removed the cat from her bag for her third pregnancy.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Teigen, who is married to singer John Legend, updated fans on Thursday via her Instagram story as she removed the gender of her future baby. Talking about complications with the placenta, she said, &quot;It&#39;s weird because the baby is so healthy. He&#39;s big.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He immediately realized his mistake, but laughed, &quot;Looks like, whoops! That&#39;s stupid.&quot; Teigen posted the video on his Instagram Stories and entitled &quot;Hahahahahaha can tell you too&quot;. Teigen and Legend already have a 4 year old daughter and a 2 year old son. They revealed that they were expecting another child in the &quot;Wild&quot; Legends music video in August when she finally picked up the baby.</p>', 'Chrissy Teigen, Acidentally', 'chriss_1600586466.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:21:06', '2021-08-17 21:19:55'),
(640, 7, 3, 145, 'jaden-smith-starts-a-series-on-racial-and-social-justice-on-snapchat-1600586542', 'Jaden Smith starts a series on Racial and Social Justice on Snapchat', 0, '<p><strong>Jaden Smith follows in the footsteps of his famous mother with her own show on social media.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Smith, son of Jada Pinkett Smith and Will Smith, will host the Solutions Committee on Snapchat. The Snap Original series claims to be a 22-year-old man who &quot;seeks help from young activists and celebrity friends to find out and understand what we can do to bring change to the main issues of racial and social justice to make our time happen&quot; . The series discusses, among other things, criminal justice reform, access to voice and education reform.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Historically, people between the ages of 18 and 23 are less likely to vote. This is because a lot of young people feel they have no information or don&#39;t know what to get it. This show is about it. To educate young people. People and believe they are. feeling empowered and ready to choose, &quot;Smith said in a statement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Joining her are some of her well-known friends and family, including Hailey Bieber, Common, Janelle Mon&aacute;e, Phoebe Robinson, Yara Shahidi, Lena Waithe, and Sister Willow Smith.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pinkett Smith hosted his popular Facebook series &quot;Red Red Talk&quot;.</p>', 'Jaden Smith, Series', 'jaden_1600586542.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:22:22', '2021-08-17 16:11:03'),
(641, 7, 3, 145, 'paul-rudd-a-certified-young-man-wants-you-to-wear-a-mask-1600586702', 'Paul Rudd, a \"certified young man,\" wants you to wear a mask', 0, '<p><strong>Paul Rudd wants you to be &quot;bae&quot; and wear a mask.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 51-year-old actor recorded the public announcement on behalf of New York Governor Andrew Cuomo as part of his &quot;Mask Up, America&quot; campaign. In it, Rudd wears a hood, New York hat, and some headphones while wearing a skateboard and speaking the language of the younger generation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rudd said, &quot;I was talking to my friend, Governor Cuomo, on the iPhone and he was just talking about how we millennials should wear masks because obviously a lot of Covid has been passed down by us over thousands of years.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;So Cuomes asked me, he said, &#39;Paul, you have to help.&#39; How old are you 26? &quot;Rudd says in the video.&quot; And I didn&#39;t fix it. So, mate, let&#39;s really talk. Masks, they really are animals. So pull these in your DM and pull them out. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Web series &quot;Hot Ones&quot; host Sean Evans makes a cameo and nods at Rudd&#39;s appearance in the episode.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This nation is still fighting the Covid-19 pandemic and young people are not immune to it,&quot; Cuomo said in a statement. &quot;We all have to do our job and wear masks. Many thanks to Paul Rudd for helping us spread this important message and reach out to young people like him.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the latest in a series of commercials for the masked campaign to include celebrities such as Billy Crystal and Robert De Niro.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The video was produced in collaboration with Rudd and Evans in coordination with Jane Rosenthal, producer and CEO of Tribeca Enterprises.</p>', 'Paul Ruff, Wear mask', 'paul_1600586702.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:25:02', '2021-08-16 21:56:22'),
(642, 7, 3, 132, 'drew-barrymore-has-nothing-to-hide-as-he-embarks-on-his-new-talk-show-1600586961', 'Drew Barrymore has nothing to hide as he embarks on his new talk show', 0, '<p><strong>If there&#39;s been a decade of great experience Drew Barrymore is enjoying as he prepares to start his own talk show, there&#39;s nothing to hide.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;One thing we want to say at this event is that I am who you think I am,&quot; he told reporters last week during a virtual press conference for the Drew Barrymore Show. &quot;I struggled, I failed and I think one of the most important things I want to teach my own children and myself as I grow up with them is that change is so important - change in the world, change in me.&quot; a tester and I never pretend to be someone I&#39;m not. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The eponymous talk show Barrymore, a former child actor turned multi-fanatic, kicks off Monday with Charlie&#39;s Angels meeting with Cameron Diaz and Lucy Liu. Barrymore&#39;s loyal partner, Adam Sandler, will also appear.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In keeping with everyday tradition, the Barrymore Show will also touch the corner of the human interest with segments such as &quot;Designed by Drew&quot; and &quot;Drew News&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m not a person, I&#39;m not in the mood, I&#39;m nothing, I&#39;m like a mixed bag myself,&quot; he said. &quot;I want a show that features all the different things that appeal to us.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Barrymore joins the increasingly busy field of daily television. Superstar singer Kelly Clarkson had great success with her own voice actor, who came out last year. Legacy Rachael Ray and Ellen DeGeneres are also back for the New Season this month.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Even though his name appears front and center of the title, Barrymore is reluctant to honor him completely. She said she never called the show &quot;her&quot; because she saw it as a collective effort.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I grew up on the set - this is my family grew up and these people become your family. You sometimes spend more time with them than your own family,&quot; he said. &quot;I&#39;ve never gotten into trouble, I&#39;ve never been inexperienced, I&#39;m on the team and that&#39;s why I&#39;ll never call this my show. Because I don&#39;t think I deserve to call it my show tense, energy.&quot; And its timing for this show . &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Knowing the state of the world, he was grateful to have the time to work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is crazy, in all my life I have never felt more humble and grateful than now to live, have two healthy children, be with this crew and this team and get this opportunity,&quot; he said. &quot;I don&#39;t know how I got here, but I&#39;ll never lose my eyesight and I never lose how lucky I am.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He added, &quot;I lost my job. [Like] being blacklisted at age 12, I value every job I have. I know what it feels like to lose and work for a lot of things and be very lucky and to have the opportunities I have and everything. in between. &quot;</p>', 'Drew Barry, talk show', 'Drew_1600586961.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:29:21', '2021-08-18 12:20:01'),
(643, 7, 3, 139, 'keeping-up-with-the-kardashians-ends-with-e-1600587517', '\"Keeping Up With the Kardashians\" ends with E!', 0, '<p><strong>You won&#39;t be able to keep up with the Kardashian family&#39;s pace on TV for long.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a joint statement to their &quot;amazing fans&quot;, the family at the center of the long-running show said &quot;Keeping Up With the Kardashians&quot; is over.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;After 14 years, 20 seasons, hundreds of episodes and several separate shows, we as a family have decided to end this very special journey,&quot; the statement said. &ldquo;We are very grateful to everyone who has watched us over the years - good times, bad times, happiness, tears and lots of relationships and children. We will have fond memories and many of the people we met along the way. should be stored forever. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>E! The statement on CNN was signed by Matriark Chris Jenner, Courtney Kardashian, Kim Kardashian West, Chloe Kardashian, Rob Kardashian, Kendall Jenner, Kylie Jenner and Scott Disick.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The show, which premiered in 2007, held on to E! and spawned several separate series. It has provided the family with a platform for many successful business ventures, including fashion and cosmetics lines, as well as mobile video games.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a statement posted on his Instagram account, Kardashian West wrote: &quot;Without following the Kardashians, I wouldn&#39;t be where I am today. I am very grateful to everyone who has watched and supported me and my family. The past 14 years. . Amazing years. This show made us who we are and I will forever be indebted to everyone who shaped our careers and changed our lives forever. &quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>E E! A spokesman said in a statement&nbsp;in part: &quot;Although it is an absolute privilege and we will miss it very much, we respect the choice of families to live their lives without our cameras.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new season will premiere on September 17 and the final season will premiere in 2021.</p>', 'Kardashians, End with E', 'Kardshan_1600587517.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:38:37', '2021-09-23 08:15:33'),
(644, 7, 3, 129, 'justin-bieber-assists-drake-in-dj-khaleds-pop-pop-video-1600587699', 'Justin Bieber assists Drake in DJ Khaled\'s pop-pop video', 0, '<p><strong>Drake has one of the greatest pop stars in the world replace him in the video for his single with DJ Khaled.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new video for the single &quot;Popstar&quot; features Drake Justin Bieber&#39;s rap lyrics. Here&#39;s the bottom line: DJ Khaled went after Drake to make a music video for his song despite the pandemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The superstar producer attempted phone calls, text messages, facetimings, and video messages to Drake, which annoyed the rapper. &quot;The guy left the rocker,&quot; Drake says in the video.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>So Drake decided to use the services of his Canadian counterpart, Bieber. The following scene is where Bieber experienced it: a party and his tattoo during a photo shoot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Singer Hailey&#39;s wife and Beeb manager, Scooter Brown, made sporadic appearances. Bieber has worked with Khaled on the singles &quot;Aku Ini&quot; and &quot;Without a Brain&quot;.</p>', 'Justin Bieber, Assista Drake', 'justine assist_1600587699.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:41:39', '2021-08-16 09:51:32'),
(645, 7, 3, 122, 'mariah-carey-announces-new-album-entitled-the-rarities-1600587832', 'Mariah Carey announces new album entitled \"The Rarities\"', 0, '<p><strong>Mariah Carey is waiting for a new album.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The singer announced Tuesday night via Twitter that the album &quot;The Rarities&quot; will be released on October 2nd.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This is for you my fans,&quot; tweeted Carrie. &quot;This is to celebrate us and to thank you for the pure love and support over the years. I am very grateful. The album RARITIES will be released on October 2.&quot; The album will contain 32 songs, some of which have never been previously released - as a single with Lauryn Hill entitled &quot;Save the Day&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There will also be some of Kerry&#39;s biggest hits including &quot;Always Be My Baby&quot; and &quot;Hero&quot;.</p>', 'Mariah Carey, Rarities', 'mariah_1600587832.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:43:52', '2021-08-10 20:22:49'),
(646, 7, 3, 124, 'crown-season-4-returns-on-november-15th-1600588467', '\"Crown\" season 4 returns on November 15th', 0, '<p><strong>November will be a real political November - and not just because of the US presidential election.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>We are talking about the return of the famous Netflix series &quot;The Crown&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The streaming service announced on Thursday that the fourth season will begin on November 15.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Towards the 1970&#39;s, Queen Elizabeth (Olivia Coleman) and her family were busy keeping in line by providing a suitable bride for Prince Charles (Josh O&#39;Connor), who has not been married. Many years,&quot; said the press release for the new season.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;As the nation began to feel the effects of the divisive policies introduced by Britain&#39;s first Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher (Gillian Anderson), tensions arose between her and the Queen as Thacher led the country in the Falklands War and caused conflict in society.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Something as important as monarchy cannot fail,&quot; says Coleman&#39;s voice, as Queen Elizabeth said at the start of the trailer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There will also be a bit of romance as the show investigates the relationship between Prince Charles and young Lady Diana Spencer (Emma Corinne), who &quot;tells a much-needed tale of the unification of England, with the royal family growing more closed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The crown was a huge hit for Netflix and won many nominations.</p>', 'Crown, Season 4', 'Crown season 4 resturns_1600588467.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:54:27', '2021-08-17 02:44:59'),
(647, 7, 3, 132, 'mulan-got-a-star-wars-change-and-lost-track-of-adding-to-the-show-1600588686', '\"Mulan\" Got a Star Wars change and lost track of adding to the show', 0, '<p><strong>As the song says, let&#39;s start a business: &quot;Mulan&quot; is big, it&#39;s a lot of fun. That&#39;s fine, but not great for turning a 1998 animated musical into a non-action, live-action film more suited than transcendent - a sensible investment to watch for the family, which is well worth it. will look, but not necessarily buy.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &quot;buy&quot; part and the business part of the show are inseparable from the film itself. After several delays related to the coronavirus, starting with a scheduled release in March, Disney disbanded and decided to offer the film via the Disney + streaming service for a premium price of $ 30. Although the film will be available to subscribers at no additional cost at a later date, Mulan became experiments in home entertainment, consumer preferences, and models that develop a balance between theater exhibition and streaming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This carries a lot of illegal, perhaps unfair, burdens to the film, in many ways the protagonist Mulan (Yifei Liu) has to bear the brunt of her family. For him, it was once again a decision to let his beloved exhumed father (Qi Ma) die, defend the country or steal his armor, disguise himself as a young man, and register to respond to the call to fend off the invasion. .</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These are the bones of the previous film and which &quot;the narrative poem Balada Mulan&quot; suggests. But this new &quot;Mulan&quot; - directed by Nicki Caro, based on a script associated with the writers&#39; quartet - has an underwater stream that&#39;s very Star Wars-like. As it turns out, Mulan has greatness within herself and must take this mysterious power (her &quot;Chi&quot;) to let go of her &quot;warrior&quot; heart and fulfill her destiny.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apart from this relationship, there is a powerful magician, Xianyang (Gong Li), who is also trapped in a patriarchal society that does not accept his talent. He responds by using his gift to help invaders from the north, whose ruthless leader Bori Khan (Jason Scott Lee) longs for revenge on the emperor (the unrecognizable Jet Li).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This structure not only raises the issue of &quot;women&#39;s power&quot;, but also the idea that detention for legal proceedings itself has the potential to lead to a dark side. First Mulan said, &quot;Learn your place.&quot; He is then warned by his useless commander (Donny Jenas The Deceiver) that the deception is a one-way street to drive out and humiliate the family.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is a fine cast and features a much-exposed acrobatic martial arts stunt for the first time in the US in &quot;The Thieving Tiger, the Hidden Dragon&quot;. The film is well shot and full of bright colors and lots of action - some of which might be a little intense for younger kids, which is reflected in the PG-13 ratings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The emotional crux of the film lies in the father-son relationship, but Liu&#39;s appearance works on many levels, expressing discomfort, guilt and humor in the continuation of his barracks - little question, no shower - to see how men behave and speak when women there is no.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Given the harsher tone, losing the music was probably the right choice, although the song &quot;Reflection&quot; was played over the final track sung by Christina Aguilera and Liu in English and Mandarin.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There was a clever callback, but when Mulan went her own way she found it bolder than some of the other straightforward Disney adaptations - think Beauty and the Beast or Aladdin - which followed and followed the line of animation closely the amount of cash coming out of a prince.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, even if they accept creative risks, they award unequal rewards - a solid, shaky film that doesn&#39;t resemble the elusive fairytale dust known as Disney magic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In general, Mulan has great respect for the story while building her independence from previous versions, complex operations that were successful in measured doses. The big unknown remains how much of this will eventually bring to the studio, which thanks to gambit streaming has become a more interesting topic and perhaps the most enduring part of its legacy.</p>', 'Mulan, Star wars', 'Lossing song_1600588686.jpg', '2020-09-20 11:58:06', '2021-08-10 20:23:04'),
(648, 7, 3, 224, 'dave-grohl-wrote-a-song-about-the-10-year-old-drumming-phenomenon-after-challenging-him-to-a-musical-duel-1600589223', 'Dave Grohl wrote a song about the 10 year old drumming phenomenon after challenging him to a musical duel', 0, '<p><strong>Nandi Bushell can&#39;t go on a world tour right now and kills off an impressive drum solo believing their age. </strong>Aside from the pandemic, it&#39;s still in elementary school and there&#39;s not much rock and roll messing around with your parents like a chaperone and a backpack full of homework.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, he did make friends online with Dave Grohl, the rock legend and frontman of Foo Fighters who inspired some of his most outrageous percussion shows.<br />\r\nThe two, separated by decades of experience and iconic performances from &quot;MTV Unplugged&quot;, have flattened themselves time and time again (online) in the continuing drum beat. This week&#39;s Grammy winner wrote an original song about Nandi and Haste talent. After delivering covers of Foo Fighters hits on his YouTube channel, a young percussionist from Ipswich, England, challenged Grohl to a drum duel in August.<br />\r\nGrohl, who regularly ranks among the best drummers in rock, finally accepted an invitation to play the drums. Grohl played his daughters &#39;drums so they could play sets of the same size and switch to the Fighters&#39; classic Everlong (Everlong, his first drum beat on the song, he says since it was recorded in 1997.).<br />\r\nIn response, he asked her to play &quot;Friends from a Dead End&quot; by Theom Crooked Vultures. Nandi, imitating Grohl&#39;s red flannel and pure facial expression, is more than done.<br />\r\nGrohl, who has three daughters, paid tribute to young Nandi&#39;s victory.<br />\r\n&quot;I have something special for you,&quot; he said in his latest video released this week. &quot;Something you&#39;ve never heard before. Something I&#39;ve never heard ... because I&#39;m going to write it down in my head - for you.&quot;<br />\r\nAccompanied by electric guitar, bass and drums, Grohl plays the original song &quot;Nandi&quot; with his daughters in the background.<br />\r\n&quot;Super girl number one / Nandi! / Best drummer in the world / Nandi! / Always on time / Nandi! A magic hero&quot;, growled Grohl.<br />\r\nOf course there are drum solos among Grohl&#39;s rave reviews for musical magic.<br />\r\nNandi was photographed the first time she heard her song of the same title, and a relaxed jaw-dropping smile stuck to her face every two minutes.<br />\r\n&quot;He wrote a song for me!&quot; he said amazed at the camera.<br />\r\nAt the end of the video, he jumps back from his chair and hopes to cover the song himself.</p>', 'Dave Grohl, 10year Song', 'Dave Grove_1600589223.jpg', '2020-09-20 12:07:03', '2021-08-17 13:47:18');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(649, 7, 7, 177, 'the-death-of-a-hong-kong-teenager-has-become-a-magnet-for-the-conspiracy-and-reveals-deep-problems-in-the-way-the-city-works-1600590725', 'The death of a Hong Kong teenager has become a magnet for the conspiracy and reveals deep problems in the way the city works', 0, '<p>The crowd retreated as tear gas streamed in and riot police lined the street with signs and batons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was August 10, 2019. Protesters gathered outside the Nathan Street Police Station, a busy Hong Kong shopping street that has become the latest battleground for anti-government protests that will rock the city for more than six months.<br />\r\nSmoke rose as experienced protesters wore masks over their faces and climbed into their goggles. Many bystanders reacted more slowly and extracted their lungs from the stinging and choking gas as they rushed off the road.<br />\r\nChan In-lam is the poor one. In a video the 15-year-old posted on social media, he complained that he was shopping and not participating in the protests.<br />\r\n&quot;I want to ask what did I do wrong?&quot; He said into the camera, his eyes red and puffy. &quot;I am completely normal, why do I have to suffer this?&quot;<br />\r\nLike many young Hong Kong residents, Chan supported the protest movement and took part in many large marches that eventually led the government to repeal extradition laws with China, leading to unrest. But she was never a frontline participant, her mother later testified, and avoided the protests that grew louder.<br />\r\nIf things turned out differently, he probably wouldn&#39;t have played a central role in the unrest - one of the many supporters who supported the movement but avoided direct clashes with police.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200914142143-hong-kong-tst-protest-0810-2019-02-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nPolice fire tear gas to disperse protesters who gathered outside a police station in the Tsim Sha Tsui neighborhood after attending a rally against Hong Kong&#39;s controversial extradition law on August 10, 2019.<br />\r\nSix weeks later, on the morning of September 22, Chan&#39;s naked body was found adrift in the sea. He died more than 48 hours.<br />\r\nThis discovery sparked media coverage and conspiracy theories. While police have been quick to classify the case as a suicide, some protest movements have accused the signs of impolite play - and even accused the authorities of engaging in cover-up.<br />\r\nIn the nearly 12 months since his death, controversy has not abated, fueled by surveillance footage that appears to show almost all of Chan&#39;s recent moves, with enough gaps to spark speculation and speculation.<br />\r\nAnd Chan is far from being part of the protest movement. He is considered one of his martyrs. Her face is shown on posters and flyers while other young people demand justice for her.<br />\r\nOn August 11 this year, a jury in Hong Kong decided after nearly two weeks of investigation that the cause of Chan&#39;s death could not be determined.<br />\r\nWhat should have been a personal tragedy for his family has become the subject of public debate about who to trust: police or protesters. Questions about Hong Kong mental health support and whether the facilities Chan contacted did not help have disappeared.<br />\r\nHowever, in a city separated by the government and its police, the case is unlikely to be the last one swallowed up by a conspiracy theory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200914142106-hong-kong-tst-protest-0810-2019-01-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Breakdown in trust</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many news events, especially those of unexplained or confusing death, attract conspiracy theories.<br />\r\nWhat has made Hong Kong particularly vulnerable to them since protests erupted last year is the way trust in the authorities has crumbled between certain groups and political divisions have grown, with the two competing nations reporting on a different story. The show has progressed.<br />\r\n&quot;The government and police have created a very mature environment for conspiracy theories to flourish,&quot; said Anthony Dapiran, a Hong Kong-based lawyer and author of City on Fire, a riot book. &quot;Both the police and the government are reporting events that are very much at odds with the objective experience of those who saw them in person or online.&quot;<br />\r\nViolent protests such as tear gas, petrol bombs and police accusations can confuse the following events even for those directly involved. The riots in Hong Kong were widely broadcast live, but not all of them were caught on camera - leaving gaps in knowledge where conspiracy theories could develop.<br />\r\nPolice denied allegations of using excessive force and using tear gas and other weapons too quickly, citing difficulties in controlling the protests that were large and often chaotic over long periods of time.<br />\r\nAlthough allegations of brutality continued to be forwarded to the authorities in the months following the June 2019 protests, a number of events have instilled public confidence in the dive. In late July, police were charged with readiness when bandits attacked protesters at a subway station in the northern city of Yuen Long. The following month, video shows officials violently storming the subway at Prince Edward Station and beating protesters and bystanders when they call for help. Separately, the police also faced allegations of sexual assault by a number of demonstrators, both during arrest and at the police station. The police have consistently denied this allegation.<br />\r\nPrior to Chan&#39;s death, there were unsubstantiated rumors that several people had died in the incident with Prince Edward. Although the bereaved person&#39;s family never appeared and there are no public records from the Hong Kong government to back up the claim, the theory soon became factual for many protesters and the station became a memorial covered in flowers.<br />\r\nA man who disappeared in connection with the events at that time finally appeared last month. In a video posted online, he said he fled to England two weeks before Prince Edward&#39;s protests for fear of being arrested.<br />\r\n&quot;He didn&#39;t come out early to disperse the tariff because he didn&#39;t want to help the police,&quot; said Paul Yip, director of the University of Hong Kong Suicide Research and Prevention Center. &quot;It&#39;s all very, very sad when you see the distrust between people and the police.&quot;<br />\r\nDapiran blamed Hong Kong authorities for breaches of trust, citing long delays in speaking to the public after major events - such as the Ewan Long attack - and the way senior officials spread conspiracy theories about alleged foreign leadership in the protests. .<br />\r\n&quot;All of this shows a lack of government leadership,&quot; he said. &quot;If the authorities abandon responsibility or disappear, as the government did for weeks last year, and / or if there is no trust in the authorities, a vacuum will be created.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200912140010-chan-yin-lam-cctv-2-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Conspiracy city</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chan will be featured in the surveillance video starting September 19, 2019. One evening, Chan took off his shoes and continued to walk around the campus of the HKDI president.<br />\r\nChan&#39;s body was found three weeks after the Prince Edward incident when allegations of sexual assault by police began to spread. When news emerged that she had participated in several protests earlier this summer, allegations circulated online - without evidence - that officers attacked or raped Chan, killed him and threw his body into the harbor.<br />\r\nSpeculation about Chan&#39;s death continued even after his mother publicly said she believed her daughter committed suicide and asked people to stop focusing on the case.<br />\r\nBut instead of putting a stop to the conspiracy theories, Chan&#39;s mother was consumed by them instead. He said he was overwhelmed by phone calls and online harassment, was accused of being an actor, or was in any way allied with the police to cover up his own daughter&#39;s murder.<br />\r\n&quot;My personal information is published online. I was plagued by phone calls in the middle of the night,&quot; Chan&#39;s mother said in an interview with a Hong Kong television operator last year. &quot;I lost my daughter, please stop persecuting me. It&#39;s too hard for us ... Please leave our family alone. I want my daughter to rest in peace.&quot;<br />\r\nThe Chan family could not be identified for this story. A lawyer representing Chan&#39;s mother did not respond to a request for comment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People fold paper cranes at the Hong Kong Design Institute as part of the Chan Monument on Oct.17, 2019.<br />\r\nYip, director of the Center for Suicide Research and Prevention at the University of Hong Kong, said that &quot;mistrust itself is very contagious when you feel very strongly about an issue.&quot;<br />\r\nIn a city where everything is divided from a political point of view and politicians, companies and celebrities are declared &quot;blue&quot; (pro police) or &quot;yellow&quot; (pro protest), the decision to speak to TVB is clearly a pro-government decision - poisoned by words. mother Chan to several observers.<br />\r\n&quot;The interview prompted (his mother) to immediately suspect the protesters and other Hong Kongers who identified themselves as &#39;yellow&#39;,&quot; said Sharon Yam, a professor at the University of Kentucky and a regular Hong Kong policy commentator. In an increasingly paranoid environment, he added, &quot;People in Hong Kong who are already skeptical may believe that Chan&#39;s parents were paid by the state to lie about their daughter&#39;s death.&quot;<br />\r\nWhen he appeared in court last month, Chan&#39;s mother was persecuted again. The audience screamed and accused her of being an actress. According to police, two people, a 17-year-old boy and a 65-year-old woman, were arrested and charged with rioting.<br />\r\nStill, the Chan family members weren&#39;t the only ones facing the fallout.<br />\r\nWhen the Hong Kong Design Institute (HKDI), where Chan studied, initially refused to release all the footage from the night of his death, students smashed the school, smashed windows and windows, smashed cameras and sprayed graffiti. Although HKDI ended up releasing more videos showing Chan&#39;s movements even when he left campus, some claimed that the school was actively covering up, and even said that the girl who appeared in the video was an actress. past.<br />\r\nPerhaps more than anything else, this HKDI surveillance footage has drawn media and public attention to Chan&#39;s case.<br />\r\nThe sight of Chan walking aimlessly around HKDI through the Hong Kong Island port, knowing that this will be one of the last times he is seen alive, is haunting. It was hard not to look for the signs of what he thought was coming.<br />\r\nIn 16 videos shot over nearly 90 minutes on the evening of September 19, Chan - wearing a black tank top and wide black and white striped trousers - looks confused or confused, but not overly angry. Her short brown hair was pulled back from her face and she shook hands in front of him as she walked as soon as she stopped and appeared to be counting on her fingers. He didn&#39;t see the phone or speak to anyone on the tape.<br />\r\nHe is seen walking around the campus for over an hour, waiting for elevators, walking off rooftops and through dining rooms where other students huddle on laptops or have dinner. At some point she threw away her bag and then her shoes and continued walking barefoot.<br />\r\nAt around 7:00 p.m., Chan appeared to be leaving campus. A witness investigating his death testified that he saw him enter a nearby subway station, but he did not pass through the ticket gates. What happened between that time and the discovery of his body three days later is unknown.<br />\r\nBut while these gaps in official records haunt many observers, the whole story of Chan&#39;s death begins much earlier.<br />\r\nThe evidence presented during the August 11 investigation paints a picture of an increasingly anxious young woman who, despite many options, appears to have slipped through the cracks in getting the help she needs.<br />\r\nPrior to his death, Chan lived with his grandfather but was closely related to his mother, who said the couple were &quot;like sisters&quot;. He had no contact with his father, who is a drug addict, and beat him, the court ruled.<br />\r\nChan was an outstanding student and began to struggle pedagogically since early 2019. He moved quickly and consistently to a number of schools. His grades drop and he gets into a fight with other students.<br />\r\nShe started missing for a long time, the court heard, and in March 2019 she had a confrontation with the police and she was taken to a state orphanage. There he tried to strangle himself with a plastic bag, hit his head against the wall, listened to the court, and forced officials to send him to the hospital.<br />\r\nThis was one of Chan&#39;s many interactions with medical professionals, according to evidence filed in court. She told doctors that she sometimes hears voices, but denied that she had attempted suicide. The doctor who examined her felt she was suffering from acute stress disorder but could not make her agree to a follow-up examination. However, the responsible social worker rejected the incident as an attempt to get out of the youth&#39;s house. Chan&#39;s thoughts were strengthened by the fact that they were discharged in front of the hospital and disappeared within a few weeks, the court heard.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In May, Chan reappeared and expressed his desire to change his life. She wants to enroll in a design course at HKDI and is looking for part time work. When the protests started that summer, Chan participated but remained on the fringes, his mother told the investigation.<br />\r\nAround this time, the court heard that he had also started contacting a boy named Wu, who was being held at the Tong Fuk Correctional Center on Lantau Island in western Hong Kong. He later described him as a friend and would visit him with Wu&#39;s father, the court heard.<br />\r\nTwo days after she shed tears at Tsim Sha Tsui on August 12, police were called to the Lantau Subway Station, where Chan screamed and screamed with great difficulty and said that she had lost her cellphone and must have a father of hers. Call a friend. The police said they refused to help the staff who then left.<br />\r\nFinally, Wu&#39;s father arrived at the train station and took Chan to a nearby restaurant. There he continued to act strangely, talking to people at other tables and ordering food that was not on the menu. After she left, she said she would return, but instead returned to the detention center, where Ms. Wu was detained, the court heard.<br />\r\nHe slept in front of the building at night and tried to get in in the morning to confront the staff. As a result, he was handcuffed and taken to a nearby police station.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>During a follow-up visit to the doctor, Chan said again that he heard voices and was very happy. She was taken back to the youth&#39;s home, where she began injuring herself again, destroying her room and banging her head against the wall, the court heard. He was then taken to Castle Peak Hospital, a mental health facility where staff said he had problems controlling him and had to be detained at some point.<br />\r\nChan refused to return to the young man&#39;s house, saying he heard voices while he was there and complained that he wasn&#39;t sleeping. A doctor reassured him, but dismissed his complaint as an indication he was &quot;a rebel,&quot; the court heard.<br />\r\nThis will be the last chance for an intervention that could save Chan&#39;s life.<br />\r\nAfter the investigation, the jury recommended that the hospital administration reconsider continuing care after a psychiatric consultation with a juvenile patient.<br />\r\nThe Hong Kong Ministry of Social Affairs did not respond to a request for comment. In a statement, Castle Peak Hospital said it had &quot;recorded the coroner&#39;s verdict&quot; and &quot;reviewed the jury&#39;s recommendations.&quot; In late August and through September, Chan&#39;s behavior was largely normal, according to the court. He returned home and immediately enrolled in HKDI where he became a friend and seemed to be enjoying the class.<br />\r\nHowever, on September 19, the situation got worse again. At 3 a.m., his grandfather testified in court while Chan was cleaning his room. She said she heard voices and couldn&#39;t sleep. Later that day, at HKDI, he took off his shoes and lay on the floor for an hour, using his backpack as a pillow, the court heard.<br />\r\nAfter class, Chan told his friends that he wanted to clean his locker. He spent nearly half an hour doing this before his friends persuaded him to go with them. When they got on the train at Tiu Keng Leng Station, Chan said he would come back to school later to continue cleaning. He refused to sit on the subway instead of sitting on the floor.<br />\r\nFinally Chan left his friends and said he was on his way home. Instead, he returned to HKDI, where he would spend the last hours of his life, before going to a nearby beach park, according to evidence presented in the investigation.<br />\r\nWhat actually happened next is not clear to point out the critical vacuum in scrutiny and testimony that ultimately left the jury unable to condemn.<br />\r\nDuring the investigation, forensic psychiatrist Robin Ho said Chan&#39;s behavior before his death showed signs of a possible psychotic breakthrough. Ho&#39;s assessment appears to be supported by Chan&#39;s complaints about hearing voices, his inability to sleep - which may also be contributing - and his obsession with order.<br />\r\nThe state of decomposition meant that it was impossible to determine the cause of Chan&#39;s death. But pathologist Garik Lee, who performed the autopsy, said that although he could not confirm, there was a &quot;clear possibility&quot; that he was drowning.<br />\r\nAn investigation found Chan was naked when he entered the water, an interpretation the jury agreed to in their ruling. According to court reports, a strong swimmer was unlikely to have chosen this method of committing suicide, but while in the middle of a psychotic episode on a hot summer&#39;s night, he was convinced that he had made the decision to go swimming. with fatal consequences.<br />\r\nExaminer David Co. instructed the jury and ruled out suicide and &quot;illegal murder&quot; as possible causes of Chan&#39;s death. He said there wasn&#39;t enough evidence of any punishment without a doubt - the legal standard. When her body was found, there were no obvious signs of bruising or injury, as well as signs of sexual abuse or rape, although pathologists admit that these marks may have disappeared while they were in the water.<br />\r\nKo asks the jury to assess whether Chan could have died in an accident or to make an open judgment, essentially admitting that the truth cannot be fully established. Therefore, the jury cited insufficient forensic evidence about how exactly Chan died and whether a mental disorder or disorder caused his death.<br />\r\nA diatom test comparing levels of certain types of microalgae in the victim&#39;s water, lungs, and blood may indicate that the victim is drowning. However, such a test was not carried out in Hong Kong. The jury recommended that a diatom test be performed if there is suspicion of future drowning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200912135938-chan-yin-lam-cctv-1-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>Tragic consequences</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>On its own, Chan&#39;s death was the tragedy of a young woman who showed signs of mental distress and who might have been saved if she had received the right help at the right time.<br />\r\nTo date, the conspiracy surrounding Chan&#39;s death has largely obscured the important question of whether the various agencies and institutions he worked for, from doctors to social workers, failed to help or even realized he needed help. . His death also highlights broader problems with mental health regulations in Hong Kong, especially for young people.<br />\r\nSince 2015, when a series of teenage suicides resulted in a public call for action, the government has increased funding to support mental health. However, experts warn that loopholes remain and the social stigma associated with identifying mental illness may prevent people from seeking help.<br />\r\nThe political unrest has exacerbated pressure on young people in Hong Kong who already face heavy pressure to do well in school, as well as the fact that a shrinking job market and housing squeeze can make it difficult for them to climb the ladder.<br />\r\nFor some young people, Yip, the HKU expert, said the protest movement may have saved their lives and provided the sense of community and solidarity they might need when someone is most vulnerable.<br />\r\nHowever, he is deeply concerned about how Chan and several other movement-related deaths have been turned into so-called &quot;martyrs&quot;. He said doing so was a risk of copying copies - even if the person might not have killed themselves. Purposely.<br />\r\n&quot;Every death by suicide is a very tragic case for us. We have to handle them very carefully, not feeling them, not trying to glorify them,&quot; he said.<br />\r\n&quot;When people feel so helpless, they may think that when I die, I can evoke so much emotion and energy and feed the movement itself (protest), which is very tempting.&quot;<br />\r\nHe blamed part of the long delay between Chan&#39;s death and the forensic doctor&#39;s examination for making room for the conspiracy to spread. And he fears that future cases where confusion or lack of evidence about how someone died could be equally affected.<br />\r\nYam, a professor at the University of Kentucky, said that &quot;mental illness, especially depression, anxiety and PTSD, is increasing and continues to be a stigma among Hong Kong residents.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;This stigma, coupled with the public&#39;s propensity for anti-government conspiracy theories, could result in a significant public health crisis in Hong Kong in which people cannot access mental health care,&quot; he added, which was mostly supported by the government or government. Provided by government-affiliated agencies.<br />\r\nIn the end, he attributed the problems to protests, particularly &quot;lack of police accountability and transparency&quot;.<br />\r\nAnd this lack of trust goes beyond the police and calling for all government action, no matter how many officials insist that their actions are in the public interest.<br />\r\nWhen authorities announced mass voluntary testing for the coronavirus this month, some saw it as a way to collect DNA samples from residents, or samples in Beijing sent by medics to help drive. The initial delay in closing Hong Kong&#39;s border on mainland China in the early months of the pandemic is also seen as politically tense, even as countries around the world struggle to respond in a timely manner.<br />\r\nIn short, Chan&#39;s coroner expressed his condolences for his family, especially his mother. Before he died, Chan was finally able to find out what he wanted and was kind to his friends and family.<br />\r\n&quot;Despite the controversy, I believe (Chan) treats you well,&quot; the judge told his mother, adding that he hoped the family would find a way to normalize over time.<br />\r\nAs Chan&#39;s case shows, Hong Kong itself may find it more difficult to achieve such normalcy.</p>', 'Hong Kong, Death', 'Hongkong teenager death_1600590725.jpg', '2020-09-20 12:32:05', '2021-08-12 00:10:57'),
(650, 7, 10, 190, 'senate-democrats-warned-the-gop-of-retaliation-if-mcconnell-pushed-trumps-trial-forward-1600590977', 'Senate Democrats warned the GOP of retaliation if McConnell pushed Trump\'s trial forward', 0, '<p>Senate Democrats, which are short on votes to suspend President Donald Trump&#39;s election to Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg&#39;s office, are considering various tactics for retaliation - from suspending the House to suspending this year&#39;s adjournment. pushing legislation to expand the courts if they win a majority in the fall.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Democrats began discussing their options on Saturday, with all senators vowing to keep the void in fierce fighting until the new Senate convenes next year and Joe Biden can occupy the White House. And while the exact course of action isn&#39;t detailed, Democrats say they agree on the issue: they plan to join the fight to stop running by urging the four Republicans to break ranks.<br />\r\n&quot;Mitch McConnell believes this fight is over. What Mitch McConnell doesn&#39;t understand is that this fight has just started,&quot; Senator Elizabeth Warren, a Massachusetts Democrat, said at an event in Ginsburg on Saturday.<br />\r\nFirst, Democrats want to stop running and are considering an unusual move to fill the entire Senate business to get the case backwards as long as possible, senators said. Under a rule that requires the Council to work unanimously, Democrats can reject day-to-day business, essentially stopping the Council.<br />\r\nMcConnell can eventually bypass such tactics at the booth if he has the support of 51 Senators, but they can expand production.<br />\r\nAnd if Democrats ultimately can&#39;t stop the candidates, they can pass a bill to expand the Supreme Court by adding extra seats to retaliate for what they perceive to be a tough Republican tactic.<br />\r\nIt&#39;s an option that has attracted increasing interest since Ginsburg&#39;s death - and one that Democratic leaders have not ruled out.<br />\r\n&quot;Basically we left the options open,&quot; Senate minority Dick Durbin told CNN host Anna Cabrera on Saturday evening when she was asked to add more seats in the court.<br />\r\n&quot;We prefer this through the regular process that Senator (Mitch) McConnell announced four years ago, and that all Republicans come forward and believe in this approach: we do not fill in any gaps about the Colonel in the final year of the Court&#39;s presidency,&quot; he said. Durbin related to the mood of the 2016 GOP Senator to fill the vacancies for the Supreme Court.<br />\r\nMcConnell promised on Friday that whoever nominates Trump as Ginsburg&#39;s representative will vote in the Senate, arguing that the situation is now different from 2016 because Republicans control the Senate and the White House.<br />\r\nThe subject of how the Democrats should react, according to Democratic sources, was the dominant topic at Saturday afternoon&#39;s Democratic Council conference at which many Democratic senators discussed the events and where minority leader Chuck Schumer warned, &quot;There&#39;s nothing about this. . The table &quot;if the Trump candidate is confirmed this election year.<br />\r\nSumer said Friday that the Supreme Court post &quot;must not be filled until we have a new president&quot;.<br />\r\nHowever, several things must happen for Democrats to successfully implement their approach to expanding the Supreme Court.<br />\r\nFirst, the Senate Democrats must win a majority by November - and the battle for control of the assembly is now on the brink of a razor. If they win a majority, that&#39;s almost certainly a very narrow advantage - maybe a seat or two, or even a 50:50 Senate. And if Biden wins the presidency, they will have to take a number of steps to make the expansion of the Supreme Court a reality.<br />\r\nThis then includes wiping out the filibuster, a stoppage tactic often used by minority Senate parties that require 60 votes in the House to overcome. You need a simple majority of Senators to lower that threshold to 51.<br />\r\nHowever, some Democratic senators have firmly spoken out against the filibuster killings because of concerns it could have long-term consequences for institutions and the state.<br />\r\nUltimately, an additional seat on the Supreme Court will receive legislation as soon as it is amended, which would be a highly controversial move even in the Senate House of Representatives.</p>', 'Senate Democrats, Gop', 'Senate Democrates_1600590977.jpg', '2020-09-20 12:36:17', '2021-08-17 18:09:40'),
(651, 7, 10, 305, 'the-last-us-elections-had-international-events-such-as-the-october-surprise-it-must-be-no-different-1600593665', 'The last US elections had international events such as the October surprise. It must be no different', 0, '<p>You may be finished in 2020, but be prepared. The next 50 to 120 days are perhaps the most volatile in the world in decades.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The October surprise American interviewers look forward to is usually an internal disturbance in the United States. Feel the seismic effect of Judge Ruth Bader Ginsburg&#39;s death, and it won&#39;t happen until mid-September. However, in the last two decades, major international events have loomed over the November elections.<br />\r\nIn 2016 there was Mosul&#39;s campaign against ISIS, the Syrian civil war that reached Aleppo, the Russo-Georgian war, and Osama bin Laden admitted on footage that he was behind the September 11, 2001 attacks.November 2020 Perhaps combining the unexpected with something now seen from outer space - the future direction of a very problematic superpower.<br />\r\nFor Washington&#39;s opponents and the lingering world order, perhaps reluctantly, moments of extraordinary opportunity are emerging. And from Moscow to Minsk, from Beijing to Tehran, there are three very important issues. Are you feeling better about Donald Trump in four years? Is there anything you think you can do when you try to get re-elected for the next 50 days?</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200704115055-xi-putin-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAnd if &quot;no&quot; is the answer to those two questions, then the 75 days of possible chaos and strife that followed pre-election elections offer another chance. In the White House, no one is likely to be behind the wheel, not underneath, fighting for their car keys. Is this also a window for competitors to do something about?<br />\r\nRussian President Vladimir Putin is a more skilled pragmatist and opportunist, despite the biggest gains in Trump&#39;s four-year term. His first term in office allowed Putin to make significant gains in the Middle East, something the Kremlin is doing with little US opposition and fanfare for Russia&#39;s own achievements.<br />\r\nHowever, it is important to remember that Russia&#39;s clashes with US patrols in Syria and a conspiracy to reward Russia for killing Americans in Afghanistan have been largely indisputable over the past six months. The Kremlin will likely not only be brave, but also carefully calculate what the next 120 days will likely be.<br />\r\nThe protest movement against Belarus&#39; brutal dictator, Alexander Lukashenko, is an uninvited but pressing topic on Putin&#39;s list. Russia has sent journalists, maybe technical support, maybe even some security forces to help Lukashenko. But he&#39;s still hesitant and is a bad bet in the long run because he betrayed his pathetic body language when he met Putin in Sochi. It&#39;s hard to overstate how important it is for Moscow to maintain control of Belarus, and how important it is to this protest movement - about the personal freedoms that utterly disappointed Putin, and not about the geopolitics on which it is nationalist. excited - failed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200909140646-belarus-rally-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nBelarus is also at the bottom of the US agenda. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo has been slowly supporting the protest movement - perhaps in his slim defense - after trying to seduce Lukashenko in hopes of turning him west.<br />\r\nThe Kremlin certainly does not accept the idea of years of supporting a leader they consider too weak to crush their own dissidents and too unpopular to challenge. Lukashenko is a costly predicament and they will likely plan to break free while forcing a closer alliance between Moscow and Minsk. The protests themselves will be a thorn to the side - unpredictable and indolent - if Putin believes a troubled Washington may not be able to respond to the next steps. Somewhat surprising that Putin has not installed a more flexible US government since 2017. Ambitious, capable and skillful, he has subtly pursued his goals over the past four years. That can change.<br />\r\nSubtlety is not seen in the &quot;maximum pressure&quot; the Trump administration is exerting on Iran. You may be forgiven for claiming success. Trump killed Iran&#39;s greatest formidable leader, Qassem Soleimani, in January in an act that many fear could set the region on fire. In fact, no. Tehran has withdrawn from low-level retaliation, and Trump recently tweeted in response to press reports that US diplomats could risk revenge 1,000 times harsher.<br />\r\nSanctions will be tightened almost to their elastic limit. And Covid-19 is hitting Iran hard. Mysterious fires have engulfed the Natanz nuclear power plant and other critical infrastructure. Even so, it would be wrong to believe that this erases the long and extraordinary memories of Tehran&#39;s solid ships. Internally, their hands had been strengthened in many ways by the collapse of the nuclear deal they hated. Trump also gave them gifts for breaking up. Five years ago, the world was united behind the JCPOA&#39;s ability to contain Iran&#39;s nuclear ambitions. The Europeans are now holding their heads as Trump shreds the deal, while Russia and China view Washington in confusion and demean their own allies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200815190816-03-trump-bedminster-press-conference-0815-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nAnd during this collapse, Iran is methodically and slowly fulfilling its promise of getting rich again. In public, they went beyond the terms of the contract, but still weren&#39;t competing for 20% enrichment, which would ring an alarm bell. The IAEA now believes it has enriched uranium ten times as much, but has also said positively that it could inspect a second suspicious site in the coming weeks.<br />\r\nThe wisdom of the western capital is that Iran understands the consequences of a bomb so heavy that outweigh its benefits. There is a paradox that the revenge new nuclear energy could be calmer. And in the Gulf world, Iran has not reacted, knows that Trump does not want a new war in the Middle East and is patient.<br />\r\nTrump&#39;s most important ally, one of the few to pursue goals that run counter to US interests, was impatient after a personal interview with Turkey-based White House President Recep Tayyip Erdogan. It seems that it has been a decade since its forces invaded Syria, attacked American ally Syrian Kurds and relocated American forces in full force. But that was over a year ago.<br />\r\nSince then, Turkey has consolidated its profits there and is busy elsewhere. He briefly swung his sword around the Greek islands. More importantly, Erdogan is investing political and military capital to support the Libyan government with the support of the United Nations. According to US authorities, Russia is saddling its opponents in the oil-rich East with Wagner&#39;s mercenaries, heavy armor, missiles and other means. Peace talks are ongoing but under a cloud of intense build-up on both sides.<br />\r\nPresidents Putin and Erdogan may see America&#39;s neutrality in Libya and Trump&#39;s busy days as reasons to act if talks stall.<br />\r\nPresidents Putin and Erdogan may see America&#39;s neutrality in Libya and Trump&#39;s busy days as reasons to act if talks stall.<br />\r\nPutin and Erdogan have celebrated their growing friendship despite Turkey being a member of NATO. Now the glow of his smile had disappeared. And Moscow has a long history of peace because it makes war more assertive. Both Putin and Erdogan can see American neutrality in Libya and Trump&#39;s busy days as reasons to act if talks fail.<br />\r\nThe next 120 days will be held hostage by reliance on the unrest of the past four years, myths about intense but ultimately imperfect personal relationships between Trump and other leaders, and the nature of the White House foreign policy impasse. US politics can face crises that have long been predicted and even trigger crises of its opponents. Even so, the world will not stop, and I hope this crisis is resolved, but it continues to spin in ways the obsessed White House does not expect.</p>', 'US Elections, October Surprise', 'trumps_1600593665.jpg', '2020-09-20 13:21:05', '2021-09-23 08:15:52'),
(652, 7, 6, 189, 'trump-said-he-agreed-to-a-deal-to-buy-tiktok-1600594199', 'Trump said he agreed to a deal to buy TikTok', 0, '<p><strong>President Donald Trump said on Saturday he had agreed to a deal between TikTok&#39;s parent company ByteDance and Oracle (ORCL) and temporarily lifted TikTok&#39;s ban on US app stores.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Commerce Department confirmed in a statement late on Saturday that it would postpone the restrictions, which were originally supposed to take effect Sunday, a week.<br />\r\nByteDance will continue to be the majority owner of TikTok under the agreement Trump approved, according to someone with knowledge of the matter.<br />\r\nSpeaking to reporters, Trump said he agreed to the deal &quot;in concept&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;I gave the deal, my blessing,&quot; Trump said. &quot;If you do that, that&#39;s fine. If you don&#39;t, that&#39;s okay.&quot;<br />\r\nThe deal will also cover Wal-Mart (WMT), Trump said, adding that &quot;the security will be 100 percent. They will use a separate cloud and very, very strong security.&quot;<br />\r\nTrump said the deal would include a $ 5 billion education fund in the United States, although he did not say which companies would make the payments. Trump had previously expressed his desire for the company to make payments to the US Treasury, but was surprised when he was told that such an arrangement was illegal.<br />\r\nTrump&#39;s blessings came hours before the Department of Commerce restrictions took effect and removed TikTok from US app stores, including those operated by Apple and Google. The White House declined to comment.<br />\r\nByteDance will continue to be the majority owner of TikTok under the deal Trump claims to have agreed to.<br />\r\nThis contradicts Trump&#39;s claim to reporters on Saturday that TikTok is &quot;completely controlled&quot; by Wal-Mart and Oracle, which will hold up to 20% of TikTok, the man said.<br />\r\nTikTok confirmed in a statement that Oracle and Walmart would jointly own up to 20% of the stake.<br />\r\n&quot;As part of this proposal, Oracle will be our trusted technology provider responsible for storing all US user data and maintaining the security of connected computer systems to ensure that US national security requirements are fully met.&quot; said TikTok. &ldquo;We are currently working on a trade partnership with Wal-Mart. The two companies will participate in the TikTok Global round before the IPO, where they can earn up to 20% of the accumulated share in the company. We will also expand the Support TikTok headquarters. Globally in the US and provides 25,000 jobs nationwide. &quot;<br />\r\nTrump also said that TikTok would be registered as a new company in Texas.<br />\r\nOracle CEO Safra Katz said in a statement:<br />\r\n&quot;Under this agreement, TikTok will operate in Oracle Cloud and Oracle will be a minority investor in TikTok Global,&quot; said Safra Katz, CEO of Oracle. &quot;Oracle will soon deploy, scale and deploy the TikTok system in Oracle Cloud. We are one hundred percent confident that we can provide a highly secure environment for TikTok and that we can guarantee data confidentiality for American TikTok users and users around the world. This increases security. significantly. and guaranteed privacy allows the TikTok user community to continue to thrive for the benefit of all parties.<br />\r\nWalmart plans a 7.5 percent stake in the start-up and Doug Macmillan, CEO of Wal-Mart, will serve on a five-person board of directors.<br />\r\n&quot;We are very pleased with our potential investment and trade agreement with TikTok Global,&quot; Wal-Mart said in a statement, adding, &quot;We will also conclude a trade agreement to provide TikTok with e-commerce, execution, payments and other multi-channel services. . &quot; Global. &quot;<br />\r\nSpeaking to reporters, Trump praised Walmart and Oracle executives, including Oracle chairman Larry Ellison, a close political ally.<br />\r\n&quot;You obviously own the combination of Wal-Mart, and high tech Oracle and the genius of the two company executives, don&#39;t you?&quot; Trump said.</p>', 'Trump, TikTok', 'tiktok_1600594199.jpg', '2020-09-20 13:29:59', '2021-12-19 17:34:30'),
(653, 7, 7, 164, 'manchester-united-have-been-drowned-by-former-wilfried-zaha-player-with-regret-at-the-start-of-the-epl-season-1600594713', 'Manchester United have been drowned by former Wilfried Zaha player with regret at the start of the EPL season', 0, '<p><strong>Manchester United regretted their English Premier League season with a 3-1 home defeat to Crystal Palace on Saturday when Wilfried Zaha scored twice against his former club.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Zaha scored the second penalty of the second half and sealed the win with one stroke to David De Gea, while Palace scored two of two wins and repeated his win from last season at Old Trafford.<br />\r\nDonnie van de Beek&#39;s debut goals on either side of Zaha&#39;s double after Andros Townsend opened the gates to Palace in the first half was the only bright spot for Ole Gunnar Solskjaer&#39;s men, who ended last season with a big bang. in the Champions League.<br />\r\nCrystal Palace striker Wilfried Zaha celebrated his side&#39;s third goal in a 3-1 win over Manchester United at Old Trafford. There was little of that quality to prove that when United lost their maiden EPL for the first time in six years, and their lack of pace in defense was evident when Townsend opened the Palace account in the seventh minute.<br />\r\nJeffrey Schlupp was able to avoid Victor Lindelof and concentrate on Townsend to score at the far post.<br />\r\nUnited improved towards the end of the first half but were still in debt to De Gea for stopping Jordan Ayu.<br />\r\nPalace captain Zaha was sent offside for an offside position before Palace won a penalty after Lindelof was heavily penalized for handball.<br />\r\nAyew&#39;s feeble effort was saved by De Gea, but the video assistant referee (VAR) ruled that the goalkeeper had turned too early and that Zaha was entrusted with a goal from the second shot on the spot.<br />\r\nFormer Ajax star van de Beek was called up from the bench to replace the ineffective Paul Pogba and showed his instinct to shoot at goal to pull you back. However, hopes for a home revitalization were dashed when Ivory Coast international Zaha Lindelhof crashed out and scored the third goal. .<br />\r\nCalvert-Levin hat trick of Everton&#39;s win<br />\r\nPreviously, Everton continued an excellent start to the season with a 5-2 shot at newly promoted West Bromwich Albion.<br />\r\nEverton new signing James Rodriguez scored his first Premier League goal when Dominic Calvert-Lewin scored a hat trick in the 1-0 win over Tottenham Hotspur on Matchday 1.<br />\r\nThe win wasn&#39;t quite as clear as the results showed, as Grady Diangana gave Albion an early lead at Goodison Park.<br />\r\nCalvert-Levin equalized before Colombia international Rodriguez gave them the lead before being involved in a controversial incident just before the break. Garden.<br />\r\nKieran Gibbs received a red card for pushing the former Real Madrid star against Albion boss Slaven Bilic, who was also sent to the stands to protest referee Mike Dean&#39;s decision.<br />\r\nAlbion dropped to 10 and leveled shortly after being restarted by Matthew Pereira before Michael Keane regained Everton&#39;s lead and Calvert-Lewin cemented the win with his second and third goals.<br />\r\nAt 23, Calvert-Lewin is the youngest Englishman to score a hat trick for Everton in the Premier League.<br />\r\nVictory for Leeds, Arsenal<br />\r\nSo impressive on the first day of a 4-3 defeat at Liverpool, Leeds sealed their maiden win of the season in another seven-goal thriller, beating Fulham 4-3 at Elland Road when Helder Costa scored twice.<br />\r\nHe opened an account at Leeds before Fulham striker Alexander Mitrovic equalized in the 35th minute after Joe Brian fouled from a penalty.<br />\r\nBrian then awarded a penalty to propel Patrick Bamford and Mateusz Klich back to Leeds&#39; lead with a 40th minute goal.<br />\r\nPatrick Bamford made it 3-1 for Leeds at the start of the second half and the match was considered for the fourth time after another superb goal from Costa.<br />\r\nBut Fulham reacted in the 62nd minute through Bobby Dekordova-Reed and Mitrovic&#39;s superb header four minutes later left Leeds nervous before the points were sealed.<br />\r\nA late start on Saturday took Arsenal 2-1 to West Ham. Substitute Eddie Nketia came off the bench in the 85th minute at the Emirates Stadium to mark the winner.<br />\r\nWest Ham appeared poised to earn a decent share of the points after Mikhail Antonio equalized Alexander Lacasette&#39;s opening in the first half when Nketia thinly rubbed the ball to score two wins in two for the Gunners.</p>', 'Manchester United, Wilfried, Zaha Player', 'Zeha_1600594713.jpg', '2020-09-20 13:38:33', '2021-12-19 17:34:18'),
(654, 7, 7, 163, 'bodyguards-for-british-foreign-secretary-dominic-raab-left-a-gun-on-the-plane-after-visiting-the-united-states-1600594905', 'Bodyguards for British Foreign Secretary Dominic Raab \"left a gun on the plane\" after visiting the United States', 0, '<p>A police officer traveling as part of British Foreign Minister Dominique Raab was stopped after reportedly leaving his gun on the plane.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The official accompanied Raab on a visit to the United States and left his gun on the plane upon their return to London Heathrow Airport on Friday, British agency PA Media reported.<br />\r\nWhen asked about the report, London police said they were &quot;aware of the incident during a flight to England on Friday 18 September&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;We take this matter very seriously,&quot; a police spokesman said in a statement on Saturday. &quot;Since then, the affected employees have been suspended from operations during an internal investigation.&quot; During his time in the United States, Raab met with officials, including Secretary of State Mike Pompeo.<br />\r\nEarlier this year, the police bodyguard was investigated by David Cameron after reports emerged that he had left a loaded gun and the passport of the former British Prime Minister in the toilet on a commercial flight.<br />\r\nPolice in the capital told CNN at the time that they had opened an investigation into the incident that delayed takeoff and that passengers on a British Airways flight from New York to London Heathrow Airport were panicked on Monday.<br />\r\nA passenger found a gun in the toilet and alerted the crew after the captain confirmed in the cabin that the gun had been officially carried on board. Newspapers, including the Daily Mail and The Sun, cite eyewitnesses.</p>', 'Body Guards, British Foreign Secretary', 'Britian Foreign sec_1600594905.jpg', '2020-09-20 13:41:45', '2021-12-19 17:34:07'),
(655, 7, 7, 156, 'lee-kerslake-drummer-for-ozzy-osbourne-and-uriah-heap-has-died-1600597736', 'Lee Kerslake, drummer for Ozzy Osbourne and Uriah Heap, has died', 0, '<p><strong>Lee Kerslake, drummer for Ozzy Osbourne and rock band Uriah Heep, has died according to a statement made by the band that was published on Facebook on Saturday.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The cause of death was not disclosed.<br />\r\nA post signed by lead guitarist Uriah Heep, Mick Box, called Kerslake &quot;one of the funniest men in the world&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;He has no passion for life and is not very loved by fans or anyone who comes to him,&quot; said Uriah Heep&#39;s official Facebook page. &quot;Shake in peace, my friend, and say hello to me with David, Gary, John and Trevor!&quot;<br />\r\nIn another post, the band said Kerslake would not be forgotten, mood rocker Ozzy Osbourne said on his own social media.<br />\r\n&quot;It&#39;s been 39 years since I saw Lee, but he lives forever on the notes he played for me, Blizzard of Ozz and Diary of a Madman,&quot; said Osborne.</p>', 'Lee Kerslake, Ozzy Osbourne', 'Lee Karsal_1600597736.jpg', '2020-09-20 14:28:56', '2021-12-19 17:33:57');
