(656, 7, 7, 167, 'a-poisoned-castor-oil-package-was-sent-to-trump-intercepted-by-law-enforcement-1600598067', 'A poisoned castor oil package was sent to Trump, intercepted by law enforcement', 0, '<p>A package of toxic castor oil sent to President Donald Trump was intercepted by law enforcement officials earlier this week, according to two police officers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Two tests were performed to confirm the presence of ricin. All White House mail is sorted and displayed on the site before reaching the White House.<br />\r\nA US law enforcement official told&nbsp; that investigators were investigating the possibility that the package sent to Trump came from Canada.<br />\r\nMary-Liz Power, spokesperson for Canada&#39;s Minister of Public Security, Bill Blair, said in a statement: &quot;As this is an active investigation, we are unable to comment.&quot;<br />\r\nThe FBI and Secret Service are investigating.<br />\r\nAuthorities are investigating other similar parcels sent to an address in Texas that may have linked to the same shipper in Canada, said a US law enforcement official.<br />\r\nCastor oil is a highly toxic compound found in castor beans used in terrorist attacks. Can be used in powder, granular, mist, or acid form. Ingestion causes nausea, vomiting and internal bleeding from the stomach and intestines, followed by liver, spleen and kidney failure and death from damage to the circulatory system.<br />\r\n&quot;The FBI and our US Postal Service and Intelligence partners are investigating suspicious mail received by the US government post office.</p>', 'Poisoned Castor', 'poison rici_1600598067.jpg', '2020-09-20 14:34:27', '2021-12-19 17:33:44'),
(657, 7, 7, 185, '2-killed-and-14-wounded-were-killed-in-a-shooting-at-a-backyard-party-in-rochester-1600598483', '2 killed and 14 wounded were killed in a shooting at a backyard party in Rochester', 0, '<p><strong>At least one person opened fire at a large garden party in New York City, Rochester, Saturday morning, killing two people and injuring 14 others in their late teens to early 20s, police said.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The shooting sent about 100 people into &quot;very chaotic scenes,&quot; said the acting president. Chief of Police Mark Simmons. Police believe at least three or four people held pistols and fired at least 40 shots, Captain Frank Umbrino said at a press conference on Saturday.<br />\r\nTwo 19-year-old children were pronounced dead at the scene, Umbrino said. None of the teenagers were residents of the house where the shooting took place, and it is likely that none of them were intended, Umbrino said.<br />\r\nNo suspects were arrested, Simmons said, and no motive was immediately known.<br />\r\nThe shootout prompted Mayor Lauli Warren to visit the neighborhood on Saturday calling for rest and healing in the city where protests have recently erupted against a notorious case - the death of Daniel Prude after meeting with police earlier this year.<br />\r\n&quot;Some of our young people - babies - who came to hang out for a while ... ran for their lives (Saturday). And that could not have happened,&quot; Warren told reporters.<br />\r\nWarren said he spoke with the party&#39;s emcee, who said he &quot;invited some friends inviting some friends inviting some friends&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;And he&#39;s out of control. He&#39;s just traumatized,&quot; said Warren.<br />\r\nThe 14 wounded were between 17 and 23 years old and taken to two hospitals with life-threatening injuries, police said.<br />\r\nPolice responded to gunfire at around 12:25 p.m. and were beaten by 100 to 200 people who tried to escape on foot and in vehicles, Umbrino said.<br />\r\nThe shooting took place at a house party that invited a number of people, but people from two close parties &quot;broke&quot; into the house and at one point there was a fight and an escalation, Umbrino added.<br />\r\nThe party took place despite some restrictions on gathering. Due to the coronavirus pandemic, the city government has advised residents to limit social gatherings to household members only and not gather in groups, according to the city&#39;s website.<br />\r\nIn addition, the city has banned more than five people from gathering since 11 p.m. in July. until 5 a.m. to curb what the city says is an increase in violence.<br />\r\nPolice were not aware of the party beforehand and did not accept interference, Simmons said.<br />\r\nAccording to a report from Democrat &amp; Chronicle, the neighborhood where the shooting took place was near the Rochester public market.<br />\r\nThe shooting occurred as the city and police were investigating the case of Prude, who died in March after being nailed to the ground by Rochester police. Camera footage released earlier that month sparked protests and allegations that local leaders were withholding the details of Prude&#39;s death from the public.<br />\r\nThis week, Simmons replaced the previous boss who was sacked because of the consequences. A New York law firm is conducting an independent investigation into the case in the city. New York lawyers also said he would set up a jury to investigate Prude&#39;s death.<br />\r\n&quot;For our community, which is going through so much at the moment, we have to deal with this tragedy (the shooting on Saturday) which is unnecessary - for people who choose to act violent - sad and shameful,&quot; Simmons said Saturday morning.<br />\r\n&quot;We as a department will do everything we can to bring those involved to justice,&quot; he said.<br />\r\nThe mayor wants peace and prayer<br />\r\nAdvisors - including from the city school - will be available at five recreation centers in Rochester on Saturday afternoon to help the community after the shooting, Warren said.<br />\r\nWarren said the townspeople involved in Saturday&#39;s shooting should &quot;stay calm and let these people (police) do what they have to do to go to trial&quot;.<br />\r\nHe demanded that &quot;everyone obey the 11pm curfew ... and not hold these mass gatherings.&quot;<br />\r\n&quot;Please protect our city in your prayers. Support your family in your prayers and of course all the neighbors who live here and have to go through this tragic situation, who are all hurt and suffering and crying now,&quot; he said.</p>', 'Rochester, shooting dead', 'shooting dead_1600598483.jpg', '2020-09-20 14:41:23', '2021-12-19 17:33:32'),
(658, 7, 7, 179, 'how-things-went-wrong-again-in-europe-when-the-second-wave-swept-across-the-continent-1600599268', 'How things went wrong (again) in Europe when the second wave swept across the continent', 0, '<p><strong>Having successfully suppressed the first spate of infections and deaths, Europe is now in the midst of a second wave of coronavirus that is spinning through the winter that raises questions about what went wrong.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Daily cases in the European Union and the UK hit a record high of more than 45,000 with a 14-day notice rate in the open, according to the European Center for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC). The leaders expressed concern about the pressure hospitals could face in the coming months and the prospect of a new national blockade coming.<br />\r\nAccording to the ECDC, the death rate in Europe has been stable for 72 days, although the death toll has increased in Bulgaria, Croatia, Malta, Romania and Spain. People gathered on the banks of the Seine as the sun set in Paris on Thursday amid the rise of the coronavirus.<br />\r\nThere are trends that can explain setbacks. The increase occurred immediately after the summer holidays as workers returned to the city center and children returned to school. The World Health Organization maintains that the increase may be partly due to easing measures and people getting out of safety, and there is evidence that young people are pushing for a second rise in Europe.<br />\r\nAlthough the number of cases and deaths has recently increased in Europe, the continent is still cheap compared to the US. Europe reported 4.4 million cases and 217,278 deaths out of a population of 750 million, while the United States reported 6.7 million cases and 198,000 deaths out of a population of 330 million.<br />\r\nSecond wave<br />\r\nBritish Prime Minister Boris Johnson told reporters on Friday that Britain was &quot;now experiencing a second wave&quot; and it was &quot;inevitable&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;Obviously we have been watching very closely the spread of the pandemic over the last few days,&quot; Johnson said. &quot;There is no doubt, as I have said for weeks, that we can now see a second wave. We see it in France, in Spain, all over Europe. It will be absolutely inevitable in this country.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200919065903-01-coronavirus-europe-social-life-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I don&#39;t want to enter a second national key. The only way to do this is if people follow the prompts.&quot;<br />\r\nUK Health Secretary Matt Hancock said Sunday the country was &quot;at a tipping point&quot; after a new spike in cases on Saturday when Britain registered 4,422 new cases, the highest since early May.<br />\r\n&quot;People have to follow the rules and if they don&#39;t follow them we are going to take much stricter action,&quot; Matt Hancock told the News channel. The minister was asked to reimpose a second national lockdown and said, &quot;I don&#39;t rule this out. I don&#39;t want to see it.&quot;<br />\r\nProtesters clashed with police over blocking doors in London&#39;s Trafalgar Square on Saturday. According to the Sofia Police, 32 people were arrested for disturbing violence, public order and assault on an emergency worker and two officers were lightly injured. &quot;Hostility towards officials who are just there to keep people safe is unacceptable,&quot; said superman Emma Richards.<br />\r\nBritain announced on Sunday that anyone who has tested positive for the coronavirus or has been identified as a close contact is required by law to self-isolate from September 28 or face fines ranging from &pound; 1,000 (US $ 1,300) to &pound; 10,000. British pound (US $ 13,000) for recidivists. Low-income individuals will be supported by a payment of GBP 500 (US $ 650) according to a government statement.<br />\r\nBritain has the highest death toll in Europe at over 40,000 and this week new restrictions on social gatherings across Britain were imposed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200919070051-05-coronavirus-europe-social-life-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /><br />\r\nTourists in the center of Amsterdam on August 21. The number of daily infections in the Netherlands has now doubled in just a week.<br />\r\nJohnson faced a backlash from the usual cheerleaders in the UK right-wing press, with the Daily Telegraph and Spectator questioning the government&#39;s game plan and Times of London columnist Matthew Paris writing that &quot;Johnson&#39;s brilliance has been lost&quot;.<br />\r\nHis conviction comes amid widespread criticism of Britain&#39;s collapsing test and prosecution system, which even the Prime Minister acknowledged as a &quot;big deal&quot;.<br />\r\nAccording to the Spanish Ministry of Health, new restrictions were announced in Madrid on Friday, accounting for about a third of all new cases in Spain. On September 11, the country reported a record 12,183 daily cases and had the highest number of cases in Europe - over 600,000 with more than 30,000 deaths.<br />\r\nFrance registered 13,215 new cases of Covid-19 in a 24-hour period on Friday. This is based on data published by the National Health Agency. This is the highest score since April. The figure also shows an increasing trend in hospital admissions, with 3,626 new patients in the last seven days. In one of France&#39;s major cities, CNN reported this week that hospitals were running out of ICU beds.<br />\r\nThe Czech Republic reported a record 3,130 daily infections on Friday as masks were again mandatory in schools, and the Netherlands reported 1,977 cases. Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte told a news conference that the number of daily infections in the country had doubled in just a week. &quot;With R 1.4, that figure will go up to more than 10,000 a day in three weeks,&quot; he said.<br />\r\n&quot;You don&#39;t have to be a mathematician or a virologist to understand that this type of number works in the hospital,&quot; he warns.<br />\r\nRestaurants, cafes and bars in six regions of the Netherlands will be subject to new restrictions starting Sunday.<br />\r\nItaly reports 1,907 daily cases, the highest number since May on Friday; Poland recorded a record 1002 daily cases on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cdn.cnn.com/cnnnext/dam/assets/200919070003-02-coronavirus-europe-social-life-exlarge-169.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Where did he go wrong?<br />\r\nWHO Director for Europe Hans Kluge warned this week about &quot;an alarming rate of transmission&quot; and a &quot;very serious situation&quot; in the region, adding that weekly cases surpassed those reported in March.<br />\r\nAlthough cases increased in the old age group between 50 and 79 in the first week of September, Kluge stated that the largest proportion of new cases was still in the 25 to 49 year age group.<br />\r\nIn late August, Kluge said the gradual increase in cases in Europe could be explained in part by &quot;easing public health and social measures, with the authorities relaxing some restrictions and making people unsafe.&quot;<br />\r\nOn September 16, friends gathered on the banks of the Vltava River in Prague as the Czech Republic has seen the most cases since the pandemic began.<br />\r\nHe said he was &quot;deeply concerned that a growing number of young people were being counted among the registered cases&quot; and recommended that large gatherings or parties be avoided.<br />\r\nCases are rising rapidly in some countries in densely populated cities, with people returning to offices, schools and public places after measures were lifted after the peak of spring.<br />\r\nLike Spain, Austria experienced the biggest leap in its capital city. Federal Chancellor Sebastian Kurz told Austrian news agency APA last week that the situation in Vienna was &quot;very dramatic&quot;, with more than half of all new infections reported.<br />\r\n&quot;We are at the start of the second wave. Difficult months await us in autumn and winter. The number of infections is increasing day by day,&quot; he tweeted, calling on Austrian citizens to reduce social contact, as an obligation to wear. from face masks to other public places.<br />\r\nTurkey recorded 63 deaths in a 24-hour period this week, the highest number of deaths in a single day. Turkish Health Minister Fahretin Koca reported weekly on Sept. 2 on the coronavirus that the country was &quot;at the second peak of the first wave&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A waitress in Vienna wears a face mask, as dictated by new, more stringent regulations from the Austrian government on September 14.<br />\r\n&quot;Today we are on the threshold because of the movements in the holiday and wedding seasons, which are an integral part of our tradition.&quot;<br />\r\nItalian authorities announced in late August that about 50% of new infections occurred at home and abroad during the summer holidays, especially among young people who are not aware of social distancing and wear masks.<br />\r\nIn countries such as Greece and Croatia, which were largely spared from the first wave, the number of cases increased rapidly in August as tourists rested in the summer following the resumption of internal European borders in June.<br />\r\nBut Europe can be comforted by the experience. Professor Mark Woolhouse, an epidemiologist at the University of Edinburgh, told&nbsp; earlier this month that the initial lockdown &ldquo;will never solve the problem for us in Europe or elsewhere; it&#39;s just delaying it. &quot;<br />\r\nAccording to News channel that&nbsp;from Johns Hopkins University, this may be due to an increase in testing levels, with daily deaths in Europe falling from 3,788 on April 18 to 504 on September 18, with a seven-day moving average.</p>', 'Second Wave, Continent', 'Second waves_1600599268.jpg', '2020-09-20 14:54:28', '2021-12-19 17:33:19'),
(659, 7, 7, 139, 'thai-protesters-declared-victory-at-rallies-aimed-at-reforming-the-monarchy-after-submitting-demands-to-the-authorities-1600599711', 'Thai protesters declared victory at rallies aimed at reforming the monarchy after submitting demands to the authorities', 0, '<p><strong>Anti-government protesters in Thailand declared &quot;victory&quot; on Sunday after presenting Bangkok authorities a list of demands for monarchy reform - an explosive and unprecedented move in a country that honors the king.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Thousands of people gathered in the nation&#39;s capital for the weekend protests, which start on Saturday and are part of a protest movement that has been gaining momentum since July.<br />\r\n21-year-old student leader and activist Panasaya &quot;Rung&quot; Sitijiravanatakul took to the public stage to speak directly to King Vajiralongkorn of Thailand - an act punishable by 15 years in prison under strict national law if he comments on defaming the monarchy.<br />\r\nThe Laws of Majesty&nbsp;has limits in considering the full context of the Thai monarchy and its intrigues within the palace.<br />\r\nDemocratic protesters are greeted with a three-finger symbol during a protest on September 19 in Bangkok, Thailand.<br />\r\nPanasaya enlisted in front of the crowd the ten demands of the Tamasat and Demonstration United Front, a student union that he spoke for. These include the repeal of laws prohibiting blasphemy of the monarchy, a new constitution, abolition of royal services, dissolving the military junta and dissolving the king&#39;s royal guard.<br />\r\nIn an interview with CNN, Panasaya said, &quot;I mean not harming the monarchy.&quot; But he also shared a message with the king: &quot;You must reform so that the monarchy in Thailand can continue. If you pay attention to what I have to say, I want you to consider our demands.&quot;<br />\r\nOn Sunday, a group of thousands more announced that they intended to forward ten questions to members of the secret council, the king&#39;s advisers.<br />\r\nHowever, Panasaya and other attendees were stopped by the police when they tried to contact the council. In a live television broadcast, Panasaya even agreed to pass demands on the police and declare victory to the demonstrators.<br />\r\nThe leader of the Chivarak &quot;Penguin&quot; Trench protests addressed the crowd before the disbandment and said, &quot;Our victory is that we forward our letter directly to the king so we can show that everyone is the same. Everyone is the same color. Blood - the color is red. Thank you all celebrated our victory. We told the people to raise their hands. &quot;<br />\r\nTrench said the movement would continue to pursue its goals peacefully.<br />\r\n&quot;We have achieved all of this with non-violent methods and will uphold the principle of nonviolence in our movement,&quot; said Parit on Sunday.<br />\r\nOn Sunday, demonstrators erected a &quot;people&#39;s plaque&quot; near the Thai royal palace, marking their movement as the &quot;vanguard of democracy&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;Here the people declare that this place belongs to the people, not the king,&quot; said the plaque. Protest leaders say it is a replacement for another plaque that marked the end of monarchy in 1932 but disappeared in 2017.<br />\r\nThai Prime Minister Prayut Chan-o-Cha thanked officials and everyone who worked together to end the situation peacefully on Sunday, his spokesman Anucha Burapachaysri said in a statement. .<br />\r\n&quot;Both the protesters and the officials avoided confrontation and incitement, which could create an unnecessary tense situation,&quot; the statement said.<br />\r\n&quot;The government intends to allow people to exercise their constitutional rights legally.&quot;<br />\r\nAsked to hand over the reform letter to the king, Burapachaisri said: &quot;I learned of your demands for monarchical reform when I heard your speech on stage, but I don&#39;t have the details yet. I need time to find out first. Gather information.&quot; We have more. many comments about this. &quot;<br />\r\nThe weekend protests escalated<br />\r\nEarlier this week, officials tried to prevent protesters from arriving - and dispel fears that the protests could turn violent.<br />\r\nOn Thursday, the prime minister warned protesters that if the coronavirus spreads during demonstrations, they could cause economic devastation, although he did not specify protest groups individually or specifically for scheduled weekend demonstrations.<br />\r\nAnd at a briefing Saturday morning, Thailand&#39;s royal police commander told people not to believe what he called rumors that police were &quot;suppressing the masses&quot; and urged officials not to react if they were &quot;provoked&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the afternoon, protest leaders opened the doors to Thammasat University, the heart of student activism in Thailand. They also gathered on campus in Sanam Luang, a public square near the official residence of the king at the Grand Palace.<br />\r\nThis comes after two months of nearly daily demonstrations, including one in Bangkok with around 10,000 people on 16 August. The movement started with students in cities across the country - but has since attracted a large proportion of the public.<br />\r\nProtesters and their supporters are calling for a series of institutional changes; For example, Pita Limjaroenrat of Napred&#39;s opposition party said that his faction would propose a council meeting to &quot;rewrite the constitution peacefully&quot;.<br />\r\nAnti-government protesters break through the gates of Tamasat University when they attend a democracy rally in Bangkok on Sept. 19.<br />\r\nThe best solution, said Limiaroenrat, is to select a &quot;group of people&quot; to rewrite. He told the media that if the country does not change, &quot;people will continue to take to the streets&quot;.<br />\r\nHowever, among these complaints, reform of the monarchy was the main demand. In an earlier protest on August 10, Panusaya read a series of calls for palace reform, including securing a real constitutional monarchy that places the king under a constitution.<br />\r\nThis is a radical idea in Thailand, where powerful royal institutions are viewed with godlike admiration by many - but discontent, especially among Thai youth, has simmered over the years.<br />\r\nOver the years resistance grew<br />\r\nThailand has been experiencing political turmoil for years. The military coup in 2014 was followed by failed promises to restore democracy and, according to activists, the suppression of civil rights and freedoms.<br />\r\nActivists say they are fed up with injustices such as the constitution that continues to hold on to power, the protracted coronavirus emergency - which they believe serves to suppress political opposition and free speech - and a shaky economy that leaves them with few job prospects. and the disappearance of democracy activists living in exile.<br />\r\nIn this atmosphere, their anger is now directed at King Maha Vajiralongkorn, who ascended the throne in 2016 and was crowned in May 2019.<br />\r\nSecurity forces are on high alert when anti-government protesters take part in protests in Bangkok on September 19.<br />\r\nVajiralongkorn is believed to have spent most of his time abroad and largely absent from public life in Thailand as the country grapples with the coronavirus pandemic.<br />\r\nSince he became king, billions of assets held by the Thai crown have been transferred to Vajiralongkorn, strengthening his control over the king&#39;s finances and significantly increasing his personal wealth.<br />\r\nThe Crown Property Act, passed in 1936, rearranged Thai royal family property into a separate category for royal property. The repeal of the act meant that the private ownership of the Crown and the King was placed in the category to be administered by King Vajiralongkorn.<br />\r\nEven though absolute monarchy was abolished in Thailand in 1932, the king still wielded considerable political influence. Thais are still expected to follow a long tradition of worshiping in royal institutions.<br />\r\nHowever, these changes seem to be taking root.<br />\r\nAt schools in Bangkok and southern Thailand, a video posted on social media shows students singing the national anthem while wearing white ribbons and giving a three-finger greeting from the Hunger Games film franchise that has become emblematic of the challenge. from the post-military government of Thailand. Coup.<br />\r\n&nbsp;cannot review the videos themselves.<br />\r\nTraditionally, Thai citizens have had to stop paying homage to the national anthem that is played in public spaces twice a day, and this rule is even stricter in schools.<br />\r\n&quot;The protests in Thailand are historic because this is the first time in Thai history that urban protesters have pushed for such reforms,&quot; Paul Chambers, professor and special adviser at the Center for ASEAN Community Studies at Naresuan University, told&nbsp;last month. .</p>', 'Thai Protestor, victory', 'Pro Democracy_1600599700.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:01:40', '2021-12-19 17:33:06'),
(660, 7, 3, 243, 'tiktok-and-wechat-downloads-exceed-the-ban-1600600171', 'TikTok and WeChat downloads exceed the ban', 0, '<p>People in the US rushed to download TikTok and WeChat after the Commerce Department announced plans to restrict access to both apps starting Sunday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Trump administration&#39;s executive order against China&#39;s two motions will go into effect on Sunday, but the restrictions affecting TikTok have been postponed for at least a week.<br />\r\nOn Saturday, President Donald Trump said he had agreed to a deal between TikTok parent company ByteDance and Oracle.<br />\r\nAccording to preliminary estimates by Sensor Tower, which tracks mobile apps, TikTok downloads in the US rose 12% on Friday to 247,000 on Thursday.<br />\r\nWeChat hit 10,000 installs on Friday, 150% more than the previous day. According to Sensor Tower, these are the most downloads an app has seen in a single day since October 2019.<br />\r\nAccording to Sensor Tower, WeChat rose to the top 100 among all free iPhone apps in the US at lunchtime Friday, compared to 1385 in the morning, according to Sensor Tower. The company says that WeChat is in the top 500 for the first time this year. Many people rely on WeChat as their primary method of staying in touch with family and friends in China.<br />\r\nAnyone who has downloaded TikTok or WeChat can still use the app - as long as it&#39;s already on their phone despite restrictions. But between Sunday and midnight Monday, WeChat will likely disappear from US app stores, including those operated by Apple and Google.<br />\r\nEven if you download the application to your phone before the deadline, you will not be able to receive security fixes or other updates that may cause interruptions or problems with the application in the future.<br />\r\nFor months, the Trump administration has argued that TikTok poses a national security risk because of its ownership in China. The administration claims parent company ByteDance may be required to transfer user data to TikTok to the Chinese government, jeopardizing the security and privacy of US consumers. TikTok has repeatedly stated that it stores data outside of China and has rejected requests from Beijing for US consumer data.<br />\r\nIn a statement on Friday, TikTok said it disagrees and is disappointed by the Trump administration&#39;s announcement. &quot;Our community of 100 million American users loves TikTok because it is a home for fun, self-expression and connectedness,&quot; the company said. &quot;We are committed to protecting their privacy and safety as we continue to work to bring joy to families and families.&quot; significant careers for those who create on our platform. &quot;&quot;<br />\r\nTencent, owner of WeChat, described the restrictions that were described by the commerce department as &quot;unprofitable&quot;.<br />\r\n&quot;Following the first executive order on August 6, we held extensive discussions with the US government and proposed comprehensive proposals to address its concerns,&quot; Tencent said in a statement Friday. &quot;... (G) Even our desire to offer a continuous service to our users in the US, which WeChat is an important communication tool, we will continue to discuss with the government and other stakeholders in the US how we can achieve a long-term solution can get.&quot; &quot;</p>', 'TikTok, Wechat, Ban', 'Tiktok_1600600171.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:09:31', '2021-12-19 17:29:04'),
(661, 7, 10, 229, 'ruth-bader-ginsburg-dies-trump-will-appoint-a-woman-to-replace-the-supreme-court-1600600781', 'Ruth Bader Ginsburg dies: Trump will appoint a woman to replace the Supreme Court', 0, '<p><strong>US President Donald Trump has announced next week to appoint a woman to replace late Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg, raising political strife over his successor.</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>87-year-old Ginsberg died on Friday, weeks before the presidential election. Trump&#39;s Democratic rival, Joe Biden, insisted that the decision to replace him would have to wait until the vote.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ideological balance of the nine-member court is critical to its decisions on major issues of American law.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But President Trump has vowed to swear &quot;soon&quot; on the successor to Ginsburg, a move that has angered Democrats who fear Republicans will vote in a Conservative majority in the country&#39;s highest court for a decade.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I&#39;m running next week. She will be a woman,&quot; Trump said Saturday at a rally in Fayetteville, North Carolina. &quot;I think he should be a woman because I like women more than men.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Several supporters sang, &quot;Fill in this post!&quot; As Trump speaks, urges him to take advantage of the rare opportunity to appoint a third judge in court during the president&#39;s life term.<br />\r\nTrump has previously praised two female judges who work on the federal appeals court as a possible option. The two judges, Amy Connie Barrett and Barbara Lagoa, are Conservatives who will provide Supreme Court records in support of Republicans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Democrats emphatically denied any nominations before the November election, arguing that Senate Republicans blocked Democratic President Barack Obama&#39;s election to the US Supreme Court in 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the time, Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell justified the move on the grounds that it was an election year. But on Friday, Senator McConnell said he intends to respond to any nominations from Trump and vote in the Senate before election day.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ginsberg, a liberal icon and feminist standard bearer, died of metastatic pancreatic cancer at his home in Washington, DC surrounded by his family. She is the second woman to sit on the Supreme Court.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supporters gathered in court on Friday evening to pay tribute to the woman known as &quot;The Notorious RBG&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s the order for?<br />\r\nAppointing judges in the United States is a political matter, meaning that the president can choose who is nominated. The Senate then votes to confirm or reject the election.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ginsburg, who served 27 years, is one of only four Liberals on the nine-seat bench. His death meant that if Republicans got the vote, the balance of power would crucially shift to the Conservatives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Obituary: Ruth Bader Ginsburg<br />\r\nThe death of Ruth Bader Ginsburg sets off a political storm<br />\r\nGinsburg Tribute: &quot;Warriors for Gender Equality&quot;<br />\r\nRuth Bader Ginsburg&#39;s most memorable statement<br />\r\nTrump, who elected two Supreme Court justices during his presidency, knows that his nomination will give the Conservatives control over important decisions for decades. Judges can serve for life if they don&#39;t retire.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We have been placed in this powerful and important position to make decisions for those who proudly voted for us. The most important of these has long been seen as the selection of judges by the US Supreme Court. We make that commitment right away! &quot;He wrote on Twitter on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>McConnell said earlier in a statement acknowledging Ginsburg that &quot;the president nominated by Trump will receive the vote in the US Senate.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2016, the Senator argued that &quot;the American people should have a say in the next Supreme Court Justice election,&quot; meaning that &quot;this office shouldn&#39;t be filled until we have a new president.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But now he says the Senate has the right to act because it is controlled by the Republican Party, and Trump is the President of the Republic.<br />\r\nHowever, Democrats have started repeating what McConnell said in 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Senate Democratic Chairman Chuck Schumer tweeted and repeated his exact line when Biden told reporters, &quot;There is no doubt - let me make it clear - that voters must choose the president and the president must choose the justice the Senate should consider.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ginsberg also had his feelings straightened out in the days before his death.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;My worst wish is not to be replaced until a new president is installed,&quot; he wrote in a statement to his grandson, according to National Public Radio (NPR).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The future of abortion rights is highly dependent on ballots<br />\r\nAnalysis by Laura Trevelyan, presenter of BBC World News America</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The death of Ruth Bader Ginsberg adds a new element of instability to the presidential election, with the question of what the fierce battle for women&#39;s elections means. Now, the future of Roe&#39;s extraordinary ruling on Wade&#39;s abortion rights is on the ballot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Trump, who, according to opinion polls, has continued to lose support from women with higher education since his election, is tinkering with so-called suburban housewives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For conservative women, especially evangelicals, who doubt their character, the importance of the right to life can be an important factor. If the Republican candidate for the Supreme Court is a woman, this could also be a way for her to appeal to voters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Democrats, who won seats in suburban rooms in a swinging neighborhood in 2018, mostly insist that a woman should have the right to control her own body.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The demise of the legendary RBG, which did so much to codify women&#39;s legal equality, will also be a tide for Democrats who can tell voters that gain is now under threat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a year that has seen so much turmoil over the coronavirus and racial justice in America, the culture war over abortion is now in focus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abortion: How Do Trump and Biden&#39;s Policies Compare?<br />\r\nWhat is the Supreme Court doing?<br />\r\nThe Supreme Court in the United States often has the final say on highly controversial laws, disputes between the state and the federal government, and final appeals to stop executions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In recent years, courts have extended gay marriages in all 50 states, approved travel bans for President Trump, and delayed US carbon emissions reduction plans as grievances continued.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why is the US Supreme Court so important?<br />\r\nIt also addresses issues such as reproductive rights, one of the main reasons some life-supporting conservatives want to upset the liberal balance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Who is considered the best challenger?<br />\r\nBarbara Lagoa: An American from Cuba from the 11th District Court of Appeal. She is the first Hispanic female judge on the Florida Supreme Court. He is a former federal prosecutor<br />\r\nAmy Connie Barrett: As a member of Chicago&#39;s 7th District Court of Appeals, she is a favorite of religious conservatives and is known for her views on abortion. He is an attorney at Notre Dame Law School in Indiana<br />\r\nKate Comerford Todd: Assistant White House Attorney, has a lot of backing in the White House. Has served as former senior vice president and attorney general for the US Chamber of Justice</p>', 'Ruth Bader, Ginsburg', 'President trump_1600600781.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:19:41', '2021-12-19 17:32:55'),
(662, 7, 17, 165, 'hancock-follow-the-covid-rules-or-they-will-be-become-tougher-1600601280', 'Hancock: Follow the Covid rules or they will be become tougher', 0, '<p>Covid restrictions in the UK will be tightened if rules are not followed, Matt Hancock warned, as the government provides &pound; 10,000 fines to people who fail to self-isolate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The health minister told the BBC&#39;s Andrew Marr that the country was &quot;at a turning point and we have a choice&quot;. &quot;If everyone follows the rules, we can avoid further blocking at the national level.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Prime Minister is believed to be considering banning household mixing and reducing pub work hours. When asked if Britain could face a new national ban, Mr Hancock said, &quot;I don&#39;t rule this out, I don&#39;t want to see it.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the interview he also said:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He said he would call the police on people who refused to self-isolate<br />\r\nThe government denies overreaction, and hospital admissions remain relatively low<br />\r\nHe said there was still hope that the vaccine would be &quot;surpassed&quot; this year.<br />\r\nThe move being considered by Prime Minister Boris Johnson could take the form of a two-week mine blockade in Britain, known as a &quot;breaker&quot;, to contain its recent decline.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Another 4,422 new Covid-19 cases and 27 deaths were reported in the UK as of Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new viral rule &quot;inevitable&quot;: sight at the No. 10<br />\r\nCan the &quot;broken chain&quot; stop the second wave of Covid?<br />\r\nMy neighbor broke the rules - what should I say?<br />\r\nPeople in the UK who refuse orders to self-isolate could be fined up to &pound; 10,000 starting September 28.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new legal obligations require people to self-isolate if they test positive for the coronavirus or if they are followed as close contacts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The new measures also include a one-time payment of &pound; 500 for those on low incomes and a penalty for employers to punish those who are forced to self-isolate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fines start at &pound; 1,000 and go up to &pound; 10,000 for recidivists and &quot;most serious offenses&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previous self-isolation tips are guidelines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prime Minister Boris Johnson said: &quot;We must do everything we can to control the spread of this virus, prevent infecting the most vulnerable, protect the NHS and save lives.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>England and Wales have fined more than 19,000 fines for alleged violations of coronavirus laws, the Attorney General said earlier this week, but more than half have not been paid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Earlier this week, Boris Johnson told Sun that &quot;I&#39;ve never done much for a culture of incognito,&quot; and people should talk about Covid violations before reporting them to the police.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Instead, Hancock said she would call neighboring police if they broke the rules and said it was &quot;absolutely necessary&quot; to break the chain of transmission.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Asked if the government&#39;s response had overreacted because coronavirus deaths were still low, Hancock said hospital admissions would increase and deaths would continue.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have seen in other countries that with the increasing number of cases, the next thing we see is the number of hospitalizations,&quot; he said.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Unfortunately, we&#39;ve seen that increase, doubling every eight days - people going to hospital - and then with a delay you see a sad increase in the number of people dying.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr Hancock said he continues to hope that a vaccine will be ready before the end of the year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We have a cavalry for the next few months - vaccines, mass testing and treatment improvements - but we all need to follow the rules from time to time to keep people safe,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Union leader Sir Keir Starmer told the BBC he supported the new fines and said it was important to take action against some people who did not comply.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also said he would support a future lockdown to support the government&#39;s message.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;In the end, it&#39;s not about party politics, it&#39;s about leading the nation through this virus,&quot; he added.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In short: what are the new rules?<br />\r\nIndividuals in Britain who have been told to isolate themselves from NHS Tests and Traces face fines of &pound; 1,000 - to &pound; 10,000 for the most serious offenders - for failing to do so.<br />\r\nThis includes those who have tested positive and those identified as close contacts in confirmed cases<br />\r\nThis also includes employers who force employees to ignore self-isolation orders<br />\r\nNHS Test and Trace regularly comes into contact with the isolator to verify compliance<br />\r\nThe action will be implemented from 28 September and implemented by the police and local authorities<br />\r\nThose on benefits or on low incomes who cannot work from home can get a flat rate of &pound; 500 if they isolate.<br />\r\nThe British government hopes the new fines will be repeated in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland - each with the authority to set their own coronavirus rules.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Those who received the highest sentences were identified as those who prevented others from isolating themselves, employers who insisted that workers come to work in violation of arrest warrants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Officials said NHS testing and tracing would be carried out regularly with people told to isolate themselves and would report any suspicion that these individuals were disobeying police and local authorities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The police will also monitor Covid-19 hotspot compliance for groups classified as &quot;high risk&quot;, as well as follow up on reports from the public that prove positive but do not self-isolate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Law enforcement may be followed by cases of &quot;high and serious&quot; violations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>McConnell said earlier in a statement acknowledging Ginsburg that &quot;the president nominated by Trump will receive the vote in the US Senate.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2016, the Senator argued that &quot;the American people should have a say in the next Supreme Court Justice election,&quot; meaning that &quot;this office shouldn&#39;t be filled until we have a new president.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But now he says the Senate has the right to act because it is controlled by the Republican Party, and Trump is the President of the Republic.<br />\r\nHowever, Democrats have started repeating what McConnell said in 2016.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Senate Democratic Chairman Chuck Schumer tweeted and repeated his exact line when Biden told reporters, &quot;There is no doubt - let me make it clear - that voters must choose the president and the president must choose the justice the Senate should consider.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Ginsberg also had his feelings straightened out in the days before his death.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;My worst wish is not to be replaced until a new president is installed,&quot; he wrote in a statement to his grandson, according to National Public Radio (NPR).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The future of abortion rights is highly dependent on ballots<br />\r\nAnalysis by Laura Trevelyan, presenter of BBC World News America</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The death of Ruth Bader Ginsberg adds a new element of instability to the presidential election, with the question of what the fierce battle for women&#39;s elections means. Now, the future of Roe&#39;s extraordinary ruling on Wade&#39;s abortion rights is on the ballot.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Trump, who, according to opinion polls, has continued to lose support from women with higher education since his election, is tinkering with so-called suburban housewives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For conservative women, especially evangelicals, who doubt their character, the importance of the right to life can be an important factor. If the Republican candidate for the Supreme Court is a woman, this could also be a way for her to appeal to voters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Democrats, who won seats in suburban rooms in a swinging neighborhood in 2018, mostly insist that a woman should have the right to control her own body.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The demise of the legendary RBG, which did so much to codify women&#39;s legal equality, will also be a tide for Democrats who can tell voters that gain is now under threat.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a year that has seen so much turmoil over the coronavirus and racial justice in America, the culture war over abortion is now in focus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Abortion: How Do Trump and Biden&#39;s Policies Compare?<br />\r\nWhat is the Supreme Court doing?<br />\r\nThe Supreme Court in the United States often has the final say on highly controversial laws, disputes between the state and the federal government, and final appeals to stop executions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In recent years, courts have extended gay marriages in all 50 states, approved travel bans for President Trump, and delayed US carbon emissions reduction plans as grievances continued.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Why is the US Supreme Court so important?<br />\r\nIt also addresses issues such as reproductive rights, one of the main reasons some life-supporting conservatives want to upset the liberal balance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Who is considered the best challenger?<br />\r\nBarbara Lagoa: An American from Cuba from the 11th District Court of Appeal. She is the first Hispanic female judge on the Florida Supreme Court. He is a former federal prosecutor<br />\r\nAmy Connie Barrett: As a member of Chicago&#39;s 7th District Court of Appeals, she is a favorite of religious conservatives and is known for her views on abortion. He is an attorney at Notre Dame Law School in Indiana<br />\r\nKate Comerford Todd: Assistant White House Attorney, has a lot of backing in the White House. Has served as former senior vice president and attorney general for the US Chamber of Justice</p>', 'Hancock, Covid restrictions', 'Covid become tougher_1600601280.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:28:00', '2021-12-19 17:32:42');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(663, 7, 8, 140, 'crocodile-gas-won-the-ig-nobel-prize-1600602198', 'Crocodile gas won the Ig Nobel Prize', 0, '<p><strong>Have you ever heard alligators perform party tricks by inhaling helium to speak in a funny voice?</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s not fun, but then you&#39;ll be careful never to smile at a crocodile. Stefan Reber and colleagues conducted an experiment to understand how alligators could communicate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It&#39;s a serious study, but a slightly funny aspect recently won the Ig Nobel Prize. Ten such awards were presented Thursday by the Annals of Improbable Research.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The annual Ig is meant to be a joke for the wiser Nobel Prize for Science. Another winner in 2020 will be a team that developed a method of identifying narcissists by examining their eyebrows. and a group that wanted to see what happens when earthworms vibrate with high frequency.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All of this sounds silly, but if you dig a little deeper, you&#39;ll find that much of the research Ig Nobels admits actually focuses on real problems and is published in peer-reviewed scientific journals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The testicular heat test won the Ig Nobel Ig Nobel wins for train therapy at amusement parks</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://ichef.bbci.co.uk/news/624/cpsprodpb/F669/production/_114418036_andre-geim.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dr. Reber told&nbsp; News channel that he was honored to receive Ig.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her team&#39;s research is trying to show that crocodiles and other reptiles can use their vocalizations to show their height - something mammals and birds can do when they cry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The resonance in your vocal apparatus generally sounds lower when you are higher because this is a larger space for the air to vibrate. We don&#39;t know if reptiles really have resonance. Frogs, amphibians for example don&#39;t. We need proof of concept that crocodiles are in fact. has an echo, &quot;he explained.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is done by placing the alligator in a closed tank which can be filled with normal air and supplied with oxygen and helium (heliox) individually. The vibrations of the vocal network do not change, but the sound produced by animals changes because the speed of sound is different for different gas mixtures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Analysis of the frequency spectrum confirms that the size of the alligators&#39; bodies does indeed correlate with the resonance they produce. &quot;Even though animals can use this signal, I didn&#39;t test it,&quot; said researchers at Lund University in Sweden.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is the 30th year of the Ig Nobel presentation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His usual homes are the Sanders Theater at Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts, USA; and the show is always wild, with lots of paper planes being thrown and a little girl screaming &quot;boring&quot; at anyone who&#39;s been talking too long.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But the Covid-19 crisis is forcing this year&#39;s ceremony online.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, some traditions have been preserved, such as the participation of real Nobel Prize winners. Dr. Team Reber was introduced to his Ig by Andre Geim, a researcher based in the UK who received the 2010 Nobel Prize in Physics for his work on graphene.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prof is a superstar who also won Ig for floating frogs earlier in his career.</p>', 'Crocodile, nobel prize winner', 'aligator_1600602198.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:43:18', '2021-12-19 17:32:30'),
(664, 7, 8, 149, 'climate-change-earthquake-cracks-reveal-the-extent-of-warming-oceans-1600602464', 'Climate change: earthquake cracks reveal the extent of warming oceans', 0, '<p>Scientists have discovered a clever new way to measure ocean warming using sound waves from underwater earthquakes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Researchers say the &quot;hack&quot; works because sound travels faster in warmer water. The team reviewed voice data from the Indian Ocean broadcast by earthquakes over a 10 year period.<br />\r\nAs the oceans warmed due to global warming, scientists saw an increase in the speed of sound waves. Their new method shows that the trend of decimal warming in the Indian Ocean is well above previous estimates. Accurate information about the warming of our oceans is essential for climate researchers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They understand that about 90% of the energy absorbed in our greenhouse atmosphere is absorbed by the oceans. However, accurate temperature measurement at different locations and at different depths is a major challenge.<br />\r\nProviding around 4,000 standalone devices called Argo Floats that collect temperature information has been very helpful, but there is a large knowledge gap.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is especially true for bodies of water deeper than 2,000 meters. Now, the research team has developed a completely different approach that takes advantage of the fact that the speed of sound in seawater depends on temperature.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This idea was first proposed and tested in the late 1970s using sound waves generated by scientists. However, concerns about the impact of these sounds on marine mammals and rising costs led to the idea being abandoned. The new approach involves using naturally generated sound waves that occur during an underwater earthquake.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scientists examined data from more than 4,000 earthquakes in the Indian Ocean between 2004 and 2016. The team then looked for pairs of &quot;repeaters&quot;, earthquakes with nearly identical origins and magnitudes. By measuring how long it took these slow-moving signals to cross water from Indonesia to a monitoring station on Diego Garcia Island, they were able to determine 10 years of temperature changes in the oceans.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It takes about half an hour of sound waves from Sumatra to Diego Garcia,&quot; said lead author Dr. Wenbo Wu of the California Institute of Technology told the news channel. &quot;Changes in temperature in the deep sea between Sumatra and Diego Garcia cause this half hour travel time to vary by tenths of a second.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Because we can measure these fluctuations very precisely, we can infer small changes in mean deep ocean temperature, in this case about a tenth of a degree.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The authors say the system has several significant advantages in that it can provide large average temperatures for 3,000 kilometers from Sumatra to Diego Garcia, reducing the impact of local fluctuations and increasing accuracy over the oceans like a hole.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This method is also quite inexpensive because it uses the collected data and is sensitive to temperatures lower than the 2000 m current limit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In their research, the scientists showed that the warming in the Indian Ocean was greater than previously calculated over the decades they studied.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, this paper has several important limitations. &quot;It is important to emphasize that these are results that can be applied in specific areas and this decade,&quot; said Dr. Wu.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&ldquo;We have to apply our methods across more regions and in different time frames to assess whether global deep ocean trends are systematically underestimated or overestimated.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It&#39;s too early to draw conclusions in that direction.&quot; For their ideas to be applied worldwide, scientists need access to more underwater receivers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The research team is currently working on data from the UN Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Organization&#39;s hydrophone network, which listens for underwater nuclear explosions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The hydrophone picks up the signals of the 10,000 shallow underwater earthquakes that occur around the world each year, said Dr. Wu.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;All of this data contains information about changes in temperature in the deep ocean - it&#39;s just waiting to be extracted.&quot;</p>', 'Climate Change, Earth Quake', 'Temprature_1600602464.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:47:44', '2021-12-19 17:32:17'),
(665, 7, 8, 175, 'the-siberian-landscape-was-shaped-by-climate-change-1600602886', 'The Siberian landscape was shaped by climate change', 0, '<p>Scientists warn that vast areas of Siberia - usually frozen all year round - are thawing - with potential climate-damaging effects. During melting, the earth is believed to emit large amounts of greenhouse gases, which highlights the problem of global warming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>BBC Moscow correspondent Steve Rosenberg is in a remote part of Yakutia investigating how the melting of permafrost is affecting not only the climate, but also landscapes and livelihoods in Siberia.</p>', 'Scientists, Siberian', 'siberian landscape_1600602886.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:54:46', '2021-12-19 17:32:05'),
(666, 7, 8, 135, 'what-math-is-involved-in-stirring-a-cup-of-tea-1600603017', 'What math is involved in stirring a cup of tea?', 0, '<p>A man who put a lot of thought into the math behind churning a cup of tea has won one of the world&#39;s most lucrative academic awards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Professor Sir Martin Haier of Imperial College London won the Mathematics Breakthrough Award 2021 for applying complex mathematics to simple situations, such as stirring a cup of tea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He plans to spend &pound; 2.3 million of his winnings on a house and hopes the award will inspire others to develop an interest in mathematics.</p>', 'Cup tea', 'Tea_1600603017.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:56:57', '2021-12-19 17:31:54'),
(667, 7, 8, 225, 'arachnid-venom-is-found-in-stinging-australian-trees-1600603058', 'Arachnid venom is found in stinging Australian trees', 0, '<p>The toxins produced by trees living in Australia are very similar to those of spiders and scorpions, scientists have found.<br />\r\nThe results, published in Science Advances, come from researchers at the University of Queensland.<br />\r\nThe sting from the tree leaves initially felt a stinging burning sensation.<br />\r\nIt turned into pain similar to the affected area several hours after being hit on a car door. This can take days or even weeks.<br />\r\nThe researchers said they found that the venom&#39;s molecular structure was knot-like, allowing the venom to tangled and repeatedly target the victim&#39;s pain receptors.<br />\r\nThe most painful pain in nature<br />\r\nThe tree - Dendrocnide excelsa - is also known as the hippie hippie.<br />\r\nIt has wide oval or heart-shaped leaves covered with needle-like hairs and is found mainly in the tropical forests of northeast Queensland.<br />\r\n&quot;The Australian stinging tree species is specifically known for producing very painful stings,&quot; said Irina Veter, professor in the University of Queensland&#39;s Department of Molecular Biology.<br />\r\nHe said the needle-like appendages &quot;look like fine hair, but actually act like subcutaneous needles that inject venom when they come into contact with the skin.&quot;<br />\r\nThe authors of the report call the newly discovered type of neurotoxin a &quot;hypopeptide&quot;.<br />\r\nUntil now, scientists couldn&#39;t find which molecule in the plant was causing such severe pain.<br />\r\n&quot;By understanding how this toxin works, we hope to better treat those who have been stung by plants to relieve or relieve pain,&quot; said Prof. Wind.</p>', 'Arachnid, Australia', 'Spider like toxin_1600603058.jpg', '2020-09-20 15:57:38', '2021-12-19 17:28:15'),
(668, 7, 5, 222, 'gore-tex-inventor-of-waterproof-fabrics-robert-gore-died-at-the-age-of-83-1600603417', 'Gore-Tex: Inventor of waterproof fabrics, Robert Gore, died at the age of 83', 0, '<p>Robert Wu Gore, who invented the Gore-Tex technology while working for his father&#39;s company in Maryland, USA, has died at the age of 83.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Introduced in 1976, this fabric has protected countless hikers, runners and outdoor activities from wet weather, but is also found in many products.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Chemical engineer Robert Gore becomes CEO of WL Gore &amp; Associates. He died Thursday after a long illness, the company confirmed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gore was born in Utah and received undergraduate and postgraduate degrees from the University of Delaware and the University of Minnesota.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He joined WL Gore &amp; Associates, which was founded in 1958 by his father, uncle Bill, and Vive Gore.<br />\r\nIn 1969, in the company&#39;s laboratory, he discovered a new form of polymer, a substance consisting of large molecules that repeat themselves and form long chains.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Her father asked her to find a new way to make duct tape. Robert Gore discovered that drawing a material called PTFE stretches the polymer 1000% to create micropore structures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This material produces fabrics with billions of pores that are smaller than water droplets and form a surface that is waterproof but breathable - or Gore-Tex.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It really was a turning point in the history of the company,&quot; Greg Hannon, chief technology officer of WL Gore &amp; Associates, told Delaware Online last year.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Among its various applications, Gore-Tex is used in medical devices including heart patches, guitar strings, space suits and vacuum bags.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>WL Gore &amp; Associates grew into a multi-billion dollar company during Gore&#39;s 1996 presidency. &quot;We plan to leave a legacy on society and future generations,&quot; including &quot;babies with surgically reconstructed hearts who live because of our medical products,&quot; said Gore.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In 2000 he stepped down as President of WL Gore &amp; Associates. During his career he received several awards for his contributions to science, including from the Society of Plastic Engineers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gore survives with his wife, as well as children, grandchildren and great-grandchildren.</p>', 'Gore Tex, Robert Gore, Died', 'Dierd in_1600603417.jpg', '2020-09-20 16:03:37', '2021-12-19 17:31:42'),
(669, 7, 7, 204, 'uganda-university-fireman-ivory-tower-destroyed-1600603651', 'Uganda University Fireman: Ivory tower destroyed', 2, '<p>The fire destroyed the iconic building at Makerere University in Uganda, a symbol of the capital.<br />\r\nKnown as the &quot;Ivory Tower&quot;, the shining night has left its striking white walls with blackened windows.<br />\r\nPolice in Kampala have started an investigation into the cause of the fire at one of Africa&#39;s oldest and most prestigious universities.<br />\r\nThe Vice Chancellor described the destruction as extraordinary.<br />\r\n&quot;It is a very dark morning for Makerere University. Our iconic Public Administration Building has caught fire and the damage is extraordinary. However, we are determined to restore the building to its historic state as quickly as possible,&quot; Deputy Chancellor Barnabas Navangwe wrote on Twitter.<br />\r\nQuick guide to Uganda<br />\r\nFirefighters put out the flames from around midnight to dawn on Sunday, Payson Atuhair told the BBC in Kampala. Initial reports suggested the fire may have originated from the roof and spread over the floor where the finance and archives departments were located.<br />\r\nEast African historian Derek Peterson said the fires were a disaster for Uganda and East Africa.<br />\r\n&quot;The building houses student files and the basement is full of archival files covering the entire history of the institution,&quot; he tweeted, adding that he wanted to help organize the project to catalog the collection.<br />\r\nMakerere was founded as an engineering school in 1922 and has grown to become a widely recognized university.<br />\r\nIts alumni include independence-era leaders such as Julius Nyerere of Tanzania, well-known writers such as Ngugi wa Tiongo from Kenya, academics and pastors such as John Sentamu and the recently retired Anglican Archbishop of York.</p>', 'Uganda University, Destroyed', 'Uganda_1600603651.jpg', '2020-09-20 16:07:31', '2021-08-17 18:53:42'),
(670, 7, 5, 203, 'google-and-facebook-are-under-pressure-to-ban-childrens-advertising-1600759049', 'Google and Facebook are under pressure to ban children\'s advertising', 1, '<p>An open letter signed by lawmakers, academics and child rights activists asked technology companies to stop advertising to anyone under 18.<br>Behavioral advertising not only undermines privacy but also places \"vulnerable\" youth under unfair marketing pressure, the letter said.<br>It is addressed to Google, Amazon, Apple, Facebook and Microsoft.<br>In a separate move, the Google YouTube property was charged with illegally extracting data from five million people under the age of 13 in Great Britain.<br>European data protection laws prohibit the extraction of data on babies.<br>\"The fact that advertisers have 72 million data points for children under the age of 13 shows the extent to which this law has been violated and the extraordinary supervision of children,\" the letter said.<br>\"There\'s no reason to target teens with personalized advertising up to 12 years of age.<br>\"You, the most powerful company on the internet, have a responsibility to protect your customers.\"<br>Litigation on YouTube<br>Among the 23 signatories were MP Caroline Lucas and clinical psychologist Dr. Eli Hanson. Friends of the earth are also mentioned in the letter.<br>It is coordinated by the Global Plan of Action, which claims that online advertising is accelerating consumption and putting unnecessary pressure on the planet.<br>All participating companies have been asked to comment, but none have responded.<br>Separately, data protection commissioner Duncan McCann sued Google on behalf of five million British children, claiming that he violated data protection laws by following children online, in violation of UK and European data protection laws.<br>The lawsuit, which was filed with the UK\'s Supreme Court in July, was strongly opposed by YouTube, which claims that its platform is not aimed at children under the age of 13.<br>McCann, who has three children under that age, believes children whose data were compromised could be paid between  100 and  500 in damages.</p>', 'Google, Facebook ban', 'Google facebook_1600603827.jpg', '2020-09-20 16:10:27', '2021-09-23 08:17:29'),
(674, 6, 10, 140, 'government-judge-wont-stop-mail-in-projecting-a-voting-form-in-montana-1601792738', 'Government judge won\'t stop mail-in projecting a voting form in Montana ?', 0, '<p>The Trump lobby and the Republican National Committee recorded the claim recently after Democratic Montana Gov. Steve Bullock gave a mandate permitting all regions in the state to change to a basically all-mail framework for the 2020 political race. Be that as it may, District Judge Dana Christensen administered against Trump&#39;s mission on Wednesday and dismissed its solicitation to obstruct the new democratic principles.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In his decision, the appointed authority impacted the Trump-upheld &quot;fiction&quot; that there is far reaching elector extortion in US races.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This case requires the Court to isolate truth from fiction,&quot; Christensen composed. &quot;... Integral to a portion of the (Trump campaign&#39;s) claims is the conflict that the up and coming political race, both broadly and in Montana, will fall prey to far reaching citizen misrepresentation. The proof recommends, in any case, that this charge, explicitly in Montana, is a fiction.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There is considerable proof from political race specialists and others that &quot;the utilization of mail voting forms present no huge danger of extortion,&quot; included Christensen, who was designated to the government seat by previous President Barack Obama in 2011.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Up until this point, the Trump lobby&#39;s claims in a few states the nation over have neglected to forestall the extension of mail-in casting a ballot. A comparable claim was excused in Nevada a week ago. In contrast to Montana, which is giving regions the alternative to direct all-mail decisions, the Nevada council concluded that all enlisted electors will consequently get a mail polling form.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wednesday&#39;s decision is a triumph for Bullock, since it maintains the progressions he requested. Bullock is running against Republican Sen. Steve Daines, and could flip the seat if Democrats have a superior than-anticipated appearing in November.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an announcement, Bullock stated, &quot;I&#39;m satisfied that the present choice will empower a huge number of Montanans to cast a ballot securely - face to face or via mail - this coming political race. Montanans can have confidence that our neighborhood political race managers will save the security and respectability of the political decision measure.&quot;</p>', 'Donald Trump, Joe Biden, Debate2020, Chriss, Wallace, American, Politics', '1_1601550704.jpg', '2020-10-01 15:11:44', '2021-12-19 17:31:30'),
(675, 6, 15, 153, 'where-do-american-celebrities-living-1601558622', 'Where do American celebrities living ?', 1, '<p>1. Bill Gates Worth: $81 billion Home: Medina, Washington&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Entryways, 60, invests a large portion of his energy at his 66,000-square-foot Medina, Washington, manor, nicknamed Xanadu 2.0 after the title character&#39;s home in Citizen Kane. The house disregards Lake Washington. It took Mr. Entryways seven years and $63.2 million to assemble this house, which is loaded up with bunches of innovative highlights. He bought the parcel for $2 million out of 1988, yet it&#39;s currently worth an expected $170 million, as per public records.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>2. Michael Bloomberg Worth: $45 billion Home: Manhattan, New York&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previous New York City Mayor Michael Bloomberg, 74, has in excess of twelve of properties around the world. He invests a large portion of his energy at his Upper Estate Side apartment, however he likewise claims homes in the Hamptons in New York, just as in London, Bermuda, Colorado and Florida.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Bloomberg&#39;s condo, situated at 17 East 79th St., ranges five stories with a limestone outside. During his three terms as city hall leader, Mr. Bloomberg lived in the apartment rather than Gracie Mansion. Notwithstanding, he evidently has an arrangement to transform it into a super house. Since 1989, he has been bit by bit purchasing up units at 19 East 79th St., the condo community that is directly nearby to his present living arrangement. Out of the six units in the white 1880 Greek-recovery style building, Bloomberg currently possesses five of them, as indicated by The New York Observer.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>3. Warren Buffett Worth: $65.5 billion Home: Omaha, Nebraska&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In spite of the fact that the shrewdest speculator on earth holds different land ventures, Mr. Buffett, 86, is known for living submissively.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His home sits on a corner in Omaha, Nebraska, which he purchased in 1958 for $31,500. Mr. Buffett has lived there from that point forward. The house, initially underlying 1921, went through a few extensions to make it a comfortable and agreeable 6,500-square-foot home for the man who has a total assets of over $65.5 billion.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>4. Larry Ellison Worth: $49.3 billion Home: Woodside, California&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prophet leader administrator Larry Ellison, 72, has a broad land portfolio. He has purchased up enormous pieces of entire neighborhoods in Malibu and around Lake Tahoe. He claims a $70-million Beechwood Mansion in Newport, Rhode Island; a nursery manor in Kyoto, Japan; and 98% of the place where there is Lanai, Hawaii&#39;s 6th biggest island, which he bought in 2012 for $500 million, as per distributed reports.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His domain in Woodside, California, with an expected estimation of $110 million, is designed according to sixteenth century Japanese engineering, total with a man-made 2.3-section of land lake.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>5. Imprint Zuckerberg Worth: $55.5 billion Home: Palo Alto, California&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The most youthful most extravagant business visionary docks the majority of his riches in schools, wellbeing and different philanthropies. His land portfolio remember his home for Palo Alto and a 9.9-million pied-a-terre close to Dolores Park in San Francisco.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Zuckerberg, 32, bought his first Craftsman-style 5,000-square-foot home in Palo Alto in 2011 for $7 million. He gobbled up four of the houses encompassing his home in the next years for about $43.8 million to more readily keep his protection. However, his arrangement to destroy and reconstruct those four homes has been slowed down.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>6. Jeff Bezos Worth: $67 billion Home: Medina, Washington&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Bezos, 52, during the time spent structure his web based business realm, gathered up a huge measure of genuine properties throughout the long term, procuring him the No. 26 spot on The Land Report&#39;s rundown of America&#39;s biggest landowners a year ago. As far as homes, he has a 165,000-section of land farm in West Texas, a waterfront house in Washington state, three connected lofts in Manhattan&#39;s Century Tower, and a 12,000-square-foot Beverly Hills home that flaunts Tom Cruise as a neighbor, as per Forbes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His home at Medina, Washington, near Amazon&#39;s central command, flaunts 5.35 sections of land and around 29,000 square-foot of living space. Beside the fundamental home, there&#39;s likewise a guardian&#39;s bungalow and a 4,500-square-foot boat storage on Lake Washington.</p>', 'Bill gates, Mark zuckerberg, joe biden, trump, news, breaking news, Us election, USA politics', '2_1601551931.jpg', '2020-10-01 15:32:11', '2021-12-19 17:37:58'),
(676, 6, 10, 184, 'presidential-discussion-who-won-the-trump-biden-conflict-1601554629', 'Presidential discussion: Who won the Trump-Biden conflict?', 2, '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a discussion that was what might be compared to a food battle, the victor was the man who developed least shrouded in slop.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Tuesday night, based on moment surveys and wagering markets, that man was Joe Biden - if simply because his principle objective was to demonstrate to Americans that he could hold up under tension, that he had not lost a stage because of his propelling age. He needed to show he could take a pie to the face, allegorically, and keep his cool.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He generally satisfied that guideline, in spite of the fact that it was in any event to some degree in light of the fact that Donald Trump, by his steady hectoring and interferences, only from time to time allowed the previous VP to state something really harming to his own motivation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Twitter Trump - the offbeat, blustering, annoying and gossip mongering part of this president - was on full presentation consistently and-a-half occasion. Tragically for the president, numerous Americans, even his own allies, locate his web-based media persona one of his more ugly ascribes.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump required this discussion to stir up a race that is inclining against him - and which has been surprisingly steady, through monetary, wellbeing and social affliction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Nothing about this chaotic situation appears liable to modify the elements of this challenge or change the psyches of the one of every 10 American citizens who state they are as yet uncertain (albeit maybe they&#39;ll resolve never to watch another of these).&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>LIVE updates, examination and response&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump and Biden conflict indignantly on Covid and race&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Reality checking the up-and-comers&#39; cases&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;Will you shut up, man?&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was away from on what sort of &quot;banter&quot; this would be. Donald Trump&#39;s goal was to shake Joe Biden - and he wanted to do it by continually intruding on the previous VP.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>By CBS News&#39; tally, Trump cut in on Biden a sum of multiple times.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That made for a progression of riotous trades, which included Trump scrutinizing Biden&#39;s insight and Biden considering Trump a jokester, shushing him and asking, irately: &quot;Will you shut up, man?&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On numerous occasions, Trump would kill at Biden, leaving the Democrat snickering and shaking his head.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As mediator Chris Wallace reported that the Covid was the following theme and that the two competitors would have over two continuous minutes to reply, Biden joked: &quot;Best of luck with that.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Directing this esteemed early evening occasion may have been the most exceedingly terrible activity in America on Tuesday night.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Biden&#39;s intentional camera move&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Covid was continually going to be troublesome territory for the president - and the point came up right off the bat in the discussion. Trump needed to shield a pandemic reaction that has brought about in excess of 200,000 American passings. He did as such by saying the means he&#39;s taken forestalled more passings and recommending Biden would have compounded the situation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Biden&#39;s answer was to talk legitimately at the camera, inquiring as to whether they could trust Trump (surveys demonstrate a lion&#39;s share of Americans object to Trump&#39;s treatment of the pandemic).</p>', 'debate2020, trump vs biden, joe biden, donald trump, us election, debate news, election date, usa politics', '3_1601554629.png', '2020-10-01 16:17:09', '2021-08-14 01:42:18'),
(677, 6, 4, 145, 'san-diego-loyal-relinquish-coordinate-after-a-supposed-homophobic-remark-1601574400', 'San Diego Loyal relinquish coordinate after a supposed homophobic remark', 0, '<p>San Diego Loyal relinquish&nbsp;coordinate&nbsp;after supposed homophobic remark&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Landon Donovan said his San Diego Loyal &quot;would not remain&quot; for fanaticism having left the contribute fight after a supposed homophobic remark was focused on straightforwardly gay midfielder Collin Martin.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A resistance player from Phoenix Rising was blamed for offering the remark not long before half-time in their second-level USL Championship game.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steadfast players returned after the sever however strolled when the arbitrator blew his whistle, relinquishing a match they were driving 3-1 and finishing their odds of arriving at the end of the season games.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They relinquished a match against LA Galaxy II a week ago after a supposed racial slur was focused on midfielder Elijah Martin. The player blamed for offering the remark has since been given up by Galaxy.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Steadfast players took a knee before strolling off during Wednesday&#39;s subsequent division game against Phoenix Rising.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Faithful supervisor and leader VP Donovan, who played in the Premier League for Everton, stated: &quot;We experienced a truly hard episode a week ago in the LA match and we made a pledge to ourselves, to our locale, to our players, to the club, to USL, that we would not represent bias, homophobic slurs, things that don&#39;t have a place in our game.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Martin had been sent off after the occurrence however the red card was repealed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Rather, one was allowed to 38-year-old previous forward Donovan - the United States&#39; second-most topped player - after he hit on the contribute the fallout.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Phoenix Rising said the player who was asserted to have offered the homophobic remark &quot;eagerly denied&quot; the charges.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I lost it since I recognize what this group has experienced,&quot; said Donovan. &quot;I realize how hard it was for them to try and take the field today around evening time given all that occurred, and afterward for it to happen again seven days after the fact was simply wrecking for me.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Donovan stated, notwithstanding players needing to proceed, the group concluded that if the rival who was affirmed to have offered the homophobic remark was not eliminated by either the official, or by his club, they would not play.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;On the off chance that they&#39;re not ready to act, at that point we need to act,&quot; he included.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Our folks, to their gigantic credit, said we were not going to represent this. They were exceptionally clear at that time that they were surrendering all expectations of making the end of the season games, despite the fact that they were beating perhaps the best group in the association.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;They said it doesn&#39;t make a difference. There are things more significant throughout everyday life and we need to stand up for what we trust in.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I have colossal pride in this gathering and this association.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In an announcement, the USL Championship said it knew about the charge and an examination was in progress.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Foul and damaging language of any kind has definitely no spot in our general public and won&#39;t go on without serious consequences in USL matches,&quot; it included.</p>', 'Football, Loyal forfeit, usa football, ronaldo, cristiano, messi, lional messi', '4_1601556027.jpeg', '2020-10-01 16:40:27', '2021-12-19 17:31:19'),
(678, 6, 15, 190, 'donald-trump-and-first-lady-melania-trump-tested-positive-for-covid-19-1601791942', 'Donald Trump and First lady Melania Trump Tested Positive for COVID-19 ?', 1, '<p>Mr. Trump&#39;s physician, Dr. Sean Conley, released a statement late on Thursday, saying the president and the first lady were &quot;both well at this time, and they plan to remain at home within the White House during their convalescence&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The President made the declaration on Twitter at almost 1 a.m. ET on Friday and the turn of events - following quite a while of incapacitating misfortunes, set against a gravely blundered government reaction directed by a president who more than once made light of the emergency - tossed new strife into the nation&#39;s authority at a snapshot of profound public strain.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In his declaration, Trump demanded: &quot;We will get past this TOGETHER!&quot; His significant other, who additionally tried good, expressed, &quot;We are feeling better.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Peruse: Trump&#39;s primary care physician discharges proclamation after the President and first woman test positive for Covid-19&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In any case, the idealistic standpoint could scarcely shroud the swarming feeling of destabilization setting in as the nation battles to rise out of an age characterizing emergency similarly as its legislative issues appear to weaken to new lows. Financial exchange fates tumbled. Inside the White House, associates portrayed a feeling of frenzy as they attempted to figure out who else may have gotten the illness and whether the President - who falls solidly inside the most noteworthy danger classification for genuine intricacies and who has been protected about uncovering subtleties of his wellbeing - was showing indications.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Questions stayed regarding why the President continued with his timetable on Thursday, remembering traveling to go to a pledge drive for New Jersey, despite being in close contact with a helper, Hope Hicks, who was known by a little gathering of assistants to have tried positive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Just a brief time before declaring his conclusion, Trump told a virtual crowd the pandemic was approaching an end.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I simply need to state that the finish of the pandemic is in sight, and one year from now will be perhaps the best year throughout the entire existence of our nation,&quot; Trump said during pre-recorded comments given to the Al Smith Dinner, assembled practically this year due to the episode.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After four hours, the President&#39;s timetable for Friday - which had remembered a pledge drive for Washington and a mission rally in Florida - was rejected. The main outstanding occasion will come at 12:15 p.m. ET when the President has a call on COVID backing to weak seniors.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was the primary sign of how the current year&#39;s presidential race will again be reshaped off guard, this time about a month before Election Day. Trump will probably be needed to drop a huge number of planned mission occasions one week from now, remembering for Arizona. Any endeavor to move consideration away from the pandemic and his reaction - which has caused his survey numbers to plunge - presently appears to be far-fetched.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump has over and overlooked to minimize the pandemic - he told writer Bob Woodward in February he &quot;needed to consistently make light of it&quot; - even as his organization&#39;s own wellbeing specialists begged Americans to pay attention to the infection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Indeed, even as a portion of his nearest worldwide partners, including Brazilian President Jair Bolsonaro and British Prime Minister Boris Johnson, caught the sickness, Trump kept on making light of it and disregard the thought that he could contract it himself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He has worn a cover rarely, and at Tuesday night&#39;s disorganized discussion taunted his opponent Joe Biden for wearing one so frequently. Rather than regarding suggestions about social separating, Trump has gathered huge mission rallies where his allies stand side by side, regularly without covers, to hear him talk.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since the spring, Trump has compelled lead representatives to permit organizations to resume and has as of late squeezed for schools to permit face-to-face learning. He has railed against limitations on indoor holy places and attacked Democratic lead representatives who keep on maintaining rules against huge get-togethers.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through everything, Trump has demanded that the broad testing routine at the White House would shield him from getting the infection himself.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Today around evening time, for instance, everybody&#39;s had a test and you&#39;ve had social separating and everything you need to,&quot; he said during Tuesday&#39;s discussion in clarifying why veils weren&#39;t important in that setting.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, the endeavors of his staff to shield him from the infection plainly missed the mark. In a notice sent after 12 PM on Friday, the White House doctor Navy Cmdr Dr. Sean Conley said Trump was &quot;well,&quot; however didn&#39;t determine whether he was showing side effects.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;They intend to stay at home inside the White House during their recovery,&quot; he composed of the President and first woman.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The White House clinical group and I will keep up a careful watch, and I welcome the help gave by a portion of our nation&#39;s most noteworthy clinical experts and establishments,&quot; Conley went on, without explaining what help was being given to the White House specialists.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The finding adds up to the most genuine known wellbeing danger to a sitting American president in many years, at any rate since President Ronald Reagan was non-lethally shot in 1981.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump has not been especially inevitable with subtleties of his physical wellbeing, including when he made a very late excursion to Walter Reed National Medical Center a year ago. The White House said he was getting a promising beginning on his physical test, however declined to state what tests were performed at the office.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a readout of his physical, Conley said this spring that Trump was in &quot;excellent wellbeing,&quot; yet recorded tallness and weight that put him in the corpulent classification. He is likewise known to have a typical type of coronary illness.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brief progress of intensity from the president to the VP is spread out in segment three of the 25th Amendment, a protected change welcomed on by the death of John F. Kennedy. It has been utilized occasionally since when presidents are needed to go under sedation for clinical methods.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There were no signs that Trump was getting ready to utilize the 25th Amendment.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Have confidence I anticipate that the President should keep completing his obligations without interruption while recouping, and I will keep you refreshed on any further turns of events,&quot; Conley wrote in his reminder.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>VP Mike Pence composed on Twitter, &quot;We join millions across America appealing to God for their full and quick recuperation.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the off chance that both Trump and Pence become unfit to do their capacities, the Presidential Succession Act assigns the House speaker as next. Asked in May whether the White House was making possibility arrangements to hand the capacity to the Democratic House Speaker Nancy Pelosi, White House press secretary Kayleigh McEnany sneered.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;That is not in any event, something that we&#39;re tending to,&quot; she said. &quot;We&#39;re keeping the President solid. We&#39;re keeping the VP sound, and, you know, they&#39;re solid as of now and they&#39;ll keep on being.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Mr. Trump&#39;s doctor, Dr. Sean Conley, delivered an announcement late on Thursday, saying the president and the main woman were &quot;both well right now, and they intend to stay at home inside the White House during their improvement&quot;.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>', 'Corona virus, news update, trump corona, first lady, Covid-19 trump, usa president, trump and wife, bcc, cnn, fox news, corona update, trump tested, melania trump, bbc news', '6_1601635561.jpeg', '2020-10-02 14:43:48', '2021-12-19 17:37:46');
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `user_id`, `category_id`, `views`, `slug`, `title`, `type`, `description`, `tags`, `image`, `created_at`, `updated_at`) VALUES
(679, 6, 10, 158, 'analysis-donald-trump-trying-to-avoid-us-election-2020-1601669896', 'Analysis: Donald Trump trying to Avoid Us Election 2020 ?', 1, '<p><strong>Analysis by Chriss Cillizza</strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Donald <strong>Trump</strong> has gone through months attempting to move the nation&#39;s concentration away from the <strong>COVID</strong>. He&#39;s deliberately minimized the danger it postures to Americans, pushed informal medicines, and guaranteed the nation that immunization would show up quickly. In pre-recorded comments at the yearly Al Smith Dinner on Thursday night, Trump guaranteed that &quot;the finish of the pandemic is in sight, and one year from now will be probably the best year throughout the entire existence of our nation.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Hours after the fact, soon after <strong>1 a.m. Friday</strong> morning on the East Coast, Trump declared that both he and first woman Melania Trump had tried positive for Covid-19. That analysis made Trump&#39;s procedure of changing the subject in these last 32 days before the political decision from Covid-19 to, well, whatever else, absolutely unimaginable.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump will presently be compelled to isolate for about fourteen days, taking him off the battlefield and likely constraining the rescheduling - if not through and through crossing out of, at any rate, the second presidential discussion, which was set for October 15 in Miami, Florida. (The solitary bad habit presidential discussion is on the timetable for next Wednesday in Salt Lake City; Vice President Mike Pence tried negative for Covid-19 on Friday morning, as per his office.)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That, all by itself, is a significant hit to a <strong>President</strong> who is a) following previous Vice President Joe Biden in public and swing-state surveying and b) sees his mission rallies - huge, rowdy issues - as the soul of his mission as well as his administration. Despite the continuous infection danger, Trump had expanded the recurrence of his mission travel throughout the most recent couple of months as he looked to promise the nation that the battle against the infection was being won and that the opportunity had arrived to proceed onward to different issues - most quite, as per Trump from the platform, the fierce fights occurring in urban areas around the nation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://news-zilla.com/uploads/ckeditor/12_1601669587.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; margin-bottom:20px; margin-top:20px; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump has likewise effectively spurned accepted procedures with regards to easing back the spread of the infection. Notwithstanding direction from the CDC - starting in April - that veil wearing is one of the main (and most ideal) approaches to battle Covid-19&#39;s irresistibleness, the President has not just communicated distrust about the need to wear covers yet has likewise ridiculed Biden for doing as such.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This trade, among Trump and presidential discussion mediator Chris Wallace, from Tuesday night, exemplifies how Trump has moved toward veil wearing:&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wallace: President Trump, you have started to progressively scrutinize the adequacy of covers as an infection preventer. Furthermore, truth be told, as of late you have referred to the issue of - of servers contacting their veils and contacting plates. Is it true that you are scrutinizing the viability of veils?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump: No, I believe that covers are OK. You need to comprehend if you look - I mean, I have a veil here. I put a veil on, you know when I think I need it.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This evening, for instance, everyone&#39;s had a test and you&#39;ve had social separating and everything that you need to, yet -&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Biden: Just like your assemblies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump: - I wear covers when required. At the point when required, I wear veils.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Wallace: OK, allowed me to ask -&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump: I don&#39;t have - I don&#39;t wear veils like him. Each time you see him, he has a cover. He could be talking 200 feet from them and he appears with the greatest veil I&#39;ve ever observed.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What&#39;s more, as per the pool correspondent going with Trump to and from the discussion, &quot;all relatives who entered without a veil, individuals from his organization and different visitors were not wearing covers.&quot; A specialist associated with the Cleveland Clinic moved toward the gathering offering covers if they didn&#39;t have them. Nobody in the gathering put on a cover. Likewise, previous New Jersey Gov. Chris Christie said on ABC News Friday morning that &quot;nobody was wearing covers in the room when we were preparing the President during that timeframe, the gathering was around 5 or 6 individuals altogether.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What the positive trial of the President and first woman demonstrate (and, all the more precisely, re-demonstrate) is that the COVID couldn&#39;t care less whether you trust in it or not. It taints Democrats, Republicans, and individuals who don&#39;t follow or think about governmental issues. Disregarding it or imagining it is showing signs of improvement - notwithstanding information that proposes we have never, truly, gotten over the primary wave - doesn&#39;t influence whether it can nauseate you.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It was consistently a truly begging to be proven wrong recommendation with regards to whether Trump&#39;s endeavors to make this political decision about &quot;peace&quot; or communism or, well, whatever he tweeted that day would be fruitful in the midst of the consistent walk of the infection in the nation. (As of Friday morning, 7.3 million Americans had been determined to have Covid-19 and 208,000 had been killed by the illness). Many surveys proposed that the infection and the economy, which has been vigorously influenced by the closures and log jams brought about by the infection, were (and are) the two most significant issues in the nation. Also, the early signs on Friday recommended that the financial recuperation from the underlying hit of Covid-19 had eased back; The economy included 661,000 positions in September, with the joblessness rate stuck at 7.9%. (That is the most noteworthy joblessness rate this late in a presidential political race since at any rate 1948.)&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The commonsense effects of Trump&#39;s finding are not kidding. Yet, the less-substantial effects might be considerably more exorbitant to a President who has banked his re-appointment on the possibility that things are getting a whole lot better and doing so incredibly, rapidly.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While Trump&#39;s conduct - consistent travel, absence of veil wearing, introduction to parts and heaps of individuals - consistently made him more probable than the normal individual to get the ailment, the way that he currently has it will constrain a recalibration for some individuals. Furthermore, that recalibration will revolve around this inquiry: If the President of the United States can get Covid-19, I&#39;m not catching that&#39;s meaning for my odds of getting it?&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>That vulnerability - and the tension it causes - is incredible. The infection, which has now been with us for most of a half year, feels all the more genuine and more compromising for some Americans today than it has in numerous months. It&#39;s figured out how to nauseate the most impressive and very much ensured individual in the nation. How individuals respond to the recently discovered newness of the danger - regardless of whether the danger remains generally equivalent to it did precede Trump&#39;s conclusion - is an X factor in the political race, especially given that we are under five weeks from the genuine vote.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What we can be sure of is that Trump&#39;s endeavor to make these last a long time of the political decision about some different option from the COVID bombed the subsequent he got his positive test back. Link news will cover his disease - and the individuals he came into contact with and whether they are likewise debilitated - one end to the other for quite a long time. While Covid-19 was the lead story for most media sources on most days throughout the previous barely any months, it is probably going to turn into the ONLY story for a long time to come.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In short: Everything Trump attempted to keep away from in the stretch run of the 2020 race is presently happening. Furthermore, it&#39;s all a result of him (and his positive test).</p>', ', Trump drama, joe biden, clash between, trump corona, first lady, covid reality, covid-19 updates, bbc news, cnn news', '11_1601669895.jpg', '2020-10-03 00:18:16', '2021-08-17 23:01:02'),
(680, 6, 5, 135, 'if-you-want-to-travel-around-shanghai-at-a-slow-pace-you-might-as-well-try-these-flowing-landscapes-1601784767', 'If you want to travel around Shanghai at a slow pace, you might as well try these flowing \"landscapes\"', 0, '<pre>\r\nShanghai&#39;s public transportation industry has gone through more than one hundred years of history. It is like a mobile &quot;museum&quot;, telling people about the development and changes of the city. During the 8-day holiday when the National Day and Mid-Autumn Festival meet, you might as well take some special bus lines to get a glimpse of the scenery of Shanghai and enjoy a relaxing moment.\r\n\r\n 49 Road: Shanghai&#39;s most beautiful bus line\r\n\r\nStarting from Hankou Road on the Bund in the east, ending at Shanghai Stadium, passing by Yueyang Road, Changshu Road, Yan&#39;an Road, Julu Road, Huaihai Road, Huangpi South Road, Renmin Avenue... The 49 road has the reputation of &quot;the most beautiful bus line&quot; in Shanghai.\r\n\r\nAccording to data from the Shanghai Local Records Office, in the early days of Shanghai&rsquo;s liberation, in order to adjust the route layout, develop direct north-south transportation routes, and strengthen the commuter routes between Shanghai&rsquo;s western district and the central city, after 1956, routes 41, 42, 45, 49, etc. . In 1964, the Shanghai public transportation system imported Skoda (SKODA) 706RTO diesel passenger cars from the Czech Republic, equipped with 49 roads, and used them until the end of the 1970s. In the 1980s, 49 road set up a &quot;service for you&quot; information desk, the team has won the &quot;National Workers Pioneer&quot; and other titles, for decades has been the pacesetter in the Shanghai public transport system.</pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Take this bus line, along the road, you can check in the Bund Scenery Reserve, Fuzhou Road Cultural Street, People&rsquo;s Square, Weihai Road, pass the old building of Minli Middle School, the original Dazhongli plot, as well as Jing&rsquo;an Villa, Sun Apartment, Shanghai Poster Industry Group Famous buildings such as the Shanghai Exhibition Center. New towns, concessions and old towns, old-fashioned bungalows and new-style buildings, fashionable street scenes and old lanes, petty bourgeoisie feelings and Shanghai-style accents, sitting in the window of the car, you can see the beauty of Shanghai.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Road 71: First Shanghai Red Theme Car</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This year&#39;s &quot;October&quot;, a group of light shows are quite eye-catching at the 71 road Bund terminal. At the top of the site, 56 lanterns and Xinghai lighting are arranged in a circle. The Shanghai landmark building stickers on the bus isolation door and the Shikumen shape of the dispatching outdoor wall fully demonstrate the cultural connotation of Shanghai-style architecture and Shikumen Lane.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Route 71 is Shanghai&#39;s first bus line with a mass transit capacity, but many people may not know it. Before it was adjusted to a mass transit route, it was a bus line with a long history.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On January 3, 1949, on the eve of the liberation of Shanghai, Road 3 opened, driving from the Bund of Beijing East Road to Panyu Road for a total distance of 8.3 kilometers. It was the predecessor of Shanghai Bus 71.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On November 1, 1956, the number of Shanghai bus routes was uniformly adjusted, and No. 3 was officially named Shanghai No. 71. Because the line is located on the main road of the city, it runs east-west and runs through the city center. There are many industrial and mining enterprises, hospitals, and Xincun communities along the way.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On June 25, 2016, Shanghai Bus No. 71 (then called Shanghai Yan&#39;an Road Mid-Transport Bus Project) broke ground. On February 1, 2017, China Transportation Volume 71 officially opened. Over the past three years, the cumulative passenger flow of Route 71 has exceeded 55 million, with an average daily passenger flow of 52,000 in 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In April of this year, No. 001, 71 Road, opened the Shanghai red theme car for the first time, and the special cultural explanation service also appeared on the car. The site of the First Congress of the Communist Party of China, the site of the Second Congress of the Communist Party of China, the former residence of Soong Ching-ling, the site of the editorial office of the early publication of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, the site of the editorial office of the Bolshevik, the Shanghai People&rsquo;s Heroes Memorial Tower and other red landmarks along the way, opening and closing times, and related historical events They are clearly connected in series to create a flowing landscape.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;Route 911: double-decker bus for sightseeing all the way</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bus 911 is certainly no stranger to old Shanghainese. Its predecessor was double-decker bus No. 1, which opened in the 1990s. It was the first batch of bus lines in Shanghai to introduce British double-decker buses from Hong Kong, and it was once a &quot;large passenger carrier&quot; on Huaihai Road. As soon as the car drew up to the station, passengers rushed up, and the two-story carriages were instantly full.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With the development of transportation in Shanghai, the functional positioning of Road 911 has gradually changed from commuter cars to sightseeing cars. In January 2008, the 911 open-top double-decker bus was unveiled. Until New Year&#39;s Day in 2018, these old convertibles withdrew from the stage of history.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>More than a month later, the brand new 911 double-decker bus was upgraded and returned. The most obvious change of the new car was to change the convertible top of the old car to non-convertible, which greatly improved the comfort of passengers and sightseeing conditions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 911 road passes through Huaihai Middle Road, a well-known bustling commercial street in Shanghai. In addition to &quot;buy, buy, buy&quot;, wandering among the plane trees, you can still breathe its unfinished elegance. The famous Wukang Building (Normandy Apartment) at the west end of the road has become a newly emerging &quot;net celebrity check-in point&quot; in the past decade. There are many outstanding historical buildings and preserved historical buildings along the street. It is also a celebrity street, such as Qin Yi, Ba Jin, Sun Daolin, Tang Shaoyi, and others who have lived here. The last stop is Laoximen Station, and you are not far from Yuyuan Garden and Chenghuang Temple, the representative of old Shanghai.</p>', 'china news, shingai, cpec, china daily, covid-19, trumpcovid, bbc news', 'dd_1601784767.jpeg', '2020-10-04 08:12:47', '2021-12-19 17:28:39'),
(681, 6, 7, 176, 'chinese-report-china-and-us-fight-the-epidemic-and-make-a-decision-1601838849', 'Chinese Report: China and US fight the epidemic and make a decision.', 0, '<p>The news of Trump&#39;s diagnosis shocked the United States and may affect the normal operation of the US government and the presidential election next month. Trump&#39;s infection is a symbol of the mess in the United States&#39; fight against the epidemic. As of yesterday, nearly 7.5 million cases have been diagnosed in the United States and nearly 210,000 deaths have been accumulated. The number of Americans who have lost their lives due to the new crown virus is more than twice the number of deaths in the five major US overseas wars after World War II. According to estimates made by the University of Washington, the death toll from the new crown in the United States will double to 400,000 by the end of this year. Many experts believe that the United States, as the number one economic and technological power, has world-class laboratories, scientists, and medical resources, but the cumulative number of confirmed cases and deaths far exceeds that of other countries, which is puzzling. Fauci, a member of the U.S. anti-epidemic work expert group, said that the number of deaths from the new crown in the United States is &quot;sobering.&quot;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>But even so, Trump gave his anti-epidemic performance an A+, saying that if it were not for his anti-epidemic performance, the number of deaths would be more than that. Since the outbreak of the epidemic in the United States, Trump has always shown advances and retreats on the issue of fighting the epidemic. He has neither implemented sufficient social distancing measures nor has he united domestic forces to fight the epidemic. He even often does not wear masks. Anti-scientific attitudes boasted and even blamed China. For example, claiming that &quot;no one knows the new crown better than me&quot; and said that drinking disinfectant can treat the new crown. Last month, a former staff of Vice President Pence broke out that Trump said &quot;new crown pneumonia or a good thing.&quot; The number of new coronavirus cases in the United States fell to about 20,000 in a single day a month ago. Trump ignored the opposition of local governments, experts, and scholars, and couldn&#39;t wait to ask the states to restart the economy, causing the epidemic to repeat itself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the other hand, although the Chinese mainland was the first area where the new crown epidemic broke out, under strong prevention and control measures, the epidemic has been effectively controlled in just over two months. People all over the world have seen China&#39;s outstanding performance in anti-epidemic measures, policy implementation, and people&#39;s unity. In particular, the speed of construction of Vulcan Mountain, Thunder Mountain, and Fangcai Hospital shocked the world and demonstrated China&#39;s strength to the world. Many countries have sought help from China, and China is also willing to extend a helping hand, helping Italy, Russia, Venezuela, and other countries to fight the epidemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Excellent epidemic control capabilities have made the Mainland one of the very few areas that have successfully controlled local cases near zero new cases. On this basis, the Mainland has the ability to promote economic recovery, with GDP growth of 3.2% in the second quarter, which is one of the best results of major economies in the world. The Mainland is on the National Day Golden Week holiday. The China Tourism Research Institute predicts that 550 million people will travel domestically during this holiday. The resumption rate of accommodation and tourist attractions businesses is expected to reach 100%, and consumption in tourist attractions can recover to 90% of the same period last year. From left to right, it shows that the mainland economy has gradually emerged from the impact of the epidemic.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The third wave of the epidemic has broken out in Hong Kong since July. With the full support of the Central Government and the united efforts of all Hong Kong citizens, the epidemic has only gradually eased in recent days. The central government dispatched a nucleic acid testing support team from the Mainland to assist the SAR government in implementing a community-wide testing program. It also helped to add quarantine and community treatment facilities at the AsiaWorld-Expo, making it the strongest support for Hong Kong to overcome the new crown epidemic. Trump&rsquo;s diagnosis of the new crown further reminds us to recognize the strengths and weaknesses of the anti-epidemic performance of the Mainland and the United States, and learn more about the effective anti-epidemic measures in the Mainland, such as strengthening community testing and screening, and strengthening the establishment of point quarantine to completely plug the import loopholes, Make good use of &quot;health code&quot; and other technical means for case tracking, etc. Only by learning from the Mainland and making persistent efforts to prevent the epidemic, can Hong Kong resume normal personnel exchanges with Guangdong and Macao as soon as possible and catch the express train of the motherland&#39;s economic recovery.</p>', 'usa china fight, usa and china, china war, clashes, usa vs china, china economy, china export, usa import', 'l_1601838849.jpg', '2020-10-04 08:25:25', '2021-12-19 17:31:06'),
(682, 6, 4, 134, 'the-three-kilometer-race-is-the-sick-spot-for-swimmers-1601785987', 'The three-kilometer race is the \"sick spot\" for swimmers ?', 0, '<p>In the national swimming competition, there is rarely a case where the world record, Asian record, and national record have been broken in a row. This shows that during the epidemic, Chinese swimming has not stopped improving, and coaches and athletes have been actively training in a closed state; the top players have performed steadily and in good condition, reaching the Olympic A standard; at the same time, some newcomers have emerged.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>However, good results were created in the evening preliminaries, and we still need to continue to look for the golden key to the explosion of the Tokyo Olympics &quot;morning finals&quot;; the overall results showed &quot;short distances broke out, middle and long distances were flat&quot;, and the final level of some events declined.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The physical fitness and physical testing of &quot;headline-grabbing&quot; are worthy of further study by experts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A relay world record, aim, break!</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The men&#39;s and women&#39;s 4&times;100m medley relay event is a newly created event for the Tokyo Olympics. The Chinese team was expected to make an impact on the Olympic qualifications at the Gwangju World Swimming Championships in South Korea last year, but the results were canceled due to a foul in the competition.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Fortunately, in the Jinan Station of the FINA Swimming World Cup in August last year, the Chinese team achieved relatively satisfactory results, enough to attack Olympic qualifications, but to be more secure, it is necessary to improve themselves as much as possible before the Olympic registration deadline. To ensure qualifications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Since the outbreak of the epidemic, the Chinese team has conducted three internal tests in March, May, and July, with normal ups and downs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', 'swimming event, china swimming, usa swimming, usa today, usa news, trump covid, america news, biden and trump, first lady', 'l_1601785987.jpeg', '2020-10-04 08:33:07', '2021-12-19 17:30:53'),
(683, 6, 7, 165, 'zhuhai-builds-hong-kong-and-macau-public-legal-service-coordination-platform-1601787462', 'Zhuhai builds Hong Kong and Macau public legal service coordination platform', 0, '<p>Dagong Wenhui all-media reporter Fang Junming reported: &quot;The Decision of the Standing Committee of the Zhuhai Municipal People&#39;s Congress on Optimizing the Business Environment of Zhuhai&quot; (hereinafter referred to as the &quot;Decision&quot;) was officially announced on the 4th, clearly establishing the communication and coordination of public legal services in Zhuhai, Hong Kong and Macao Mechanism and platform to promote the construction of a unified Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area public legal service system construction master plan in Zhuhai, and provide a one-door, accurate, high-quality public service for Hong Kong and Macao enterprises and residents in Zhuhai, as well as Zhuhai residents investing and living in Hong Kong and Macao legal service.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Encourage foreign companies to participate in government procurement and project bidding</p>\r\n\r\n<p>According to the &quot;Decision&quot;, it is clear that all kinds of market entities shall participate in market competition fairly. Among them, encourage and support small, medium and micro enterprises and foreign-invested enterprises to participate in government procurement and government investment project bidding. Guide the establishment of a financing credit evaluation system that adapts to the characteristics of small, medium and micro enterprises, improve policy support, risk compensation, and default handling mechanisms to improve corporate financing convenience.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Governments at all levels in Zhuhai and their relevant collection and administration departments shall strictly implement national and provincial tax and fee reduction policies, and implement a list of government funds, enterprise-related administrative fees, enterprise-related security deposits, and government-priced operating service charges Manage, accept social supervision, and prohibit unauthorized charges, unauthorized charges, over-standard charges and repeated charges. Where there is a minimum standard for government funds, corporate-related administrative fees, and enterprise-related security deposits collected in accordance with the law, they should generally be collected in accordance with the minimum standard to effectively reduce the burden on enterprises.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Established China (Zhuhai) Intellectual Property Protection Center</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &quot;Decision&quot; proposes to strengthen the legal protection of the business environment. Among them, speed up the construction of China (Zhuhai) Intellectual Property Protection Center, promote the establishment of a rapid collaborative protection mechanism for intellectual property rights, and provide comprehensive protection for the creation, application and transformation of intellectual property rights, rights protection assistance, dispute resolution, and extraterritorial protection.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The &quot;Decision&quot; also made it clear that Hengqin will give full play to the role of the experimental field and deepen the cooperation between Hengqin and the Macao Special Administrative Region. Support the moderately diversified economic development of the Macao SAR, and promote the convergence of regulations between Hengqin and the Macao SAR in terms of commercial system, project construction, investment and trade, and customs clearance. Break through the cross-border flow of people, logistics, capital, information and technology in Zhuhai and Macau.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Provide accurate public legal services for Hong Kong and Macao residents</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the same time, establish a communication and coordination mechanism and platform for public legal services in Zhuhai, Hong Kong and Macau to provide channels for communication, coordination, cooperation and exchanges in various public legal service fields. Promote the construction of a unified Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area public legal service system master plan in Zhuhai, and provide one-door, accurate and high-quality public legal services for Hong Kong and Macao enterprises and residents in Zhuhai, as well as Zhuhai residents investing and living in Hong Kong and Macao. Developed public legal services related to Australia in Hengqin, and strengthened communication and docking with associations and organizations such as the Macau Special Administrative Region Neighbourhood Association.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In addition, speed up the establishment of institutional rules compatible with international high-standard investment and trade rules. Continue to construct a new pattern of opening up, build and implement strategic fulcrums for maritime cooperation in the &ldquo;Belt and Road&rdquo; in accordance with national deployment, and deepen cooperation with countries and regions along the route in policy communication, facility connectivity, unimpeded trade, and financing.</p>', 'china hongkong, usa news, usa daily, us open, wwe, trump and biden, clash trump, usa china', 'hong_1601787461.jpeg', '2020-10-04 08:57:42', '2021-12-19 17:30:41'),
(684, 6, 7, 245, 'death-ratio-in-brazil-due-to-covid-19-every-24-hour-1601787958', 'Death ratio in Brazil due to COVID-19 every 24 Hour ?', 1, '<p>The Brazilian Ministry of Health declared on Saturday that the nation enlisted another 599 deaths from the (COVID-19) over the most recent 24 hours, bringing the loss of life to 145,987.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As indicated by the service, 26,310 new instances of the infection were enlisted in the course of the most recent day, carrying the complete to 4,906,833.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Brazil is the second nation on the planet in number of passings brought about by COVID-19, behind the United States, and third on the planet in number of cases, behind the United States and India.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The territory of Sao Paulo, the most crowded in the nation, has announced 1,003,429 instances of the infection, with 36,136 passings. Enditem</p>', 'brazil covid, brazil update, america news, america daily, corona usa, brazil deaths, trump covid, pandemic, president usa, usa daily, usa updates, brazil updates', 'brazil_1601787921.jpg', '2020-10-04 09:05:21', '2021-08-18 07:11:08'),
(685, 6, 4, 162, 'novak-djokovic-requests-line-judges-be-supplanted-by-innovation-1601789192', 'Novak Djokovic requests line judges be supplanted by innovation', 1, '<p>Novak Djokovic, who was broadly defaulted at the US Open after he unintentionally hit a ball which felled a line judge, on Saturday requested that the authorities be supplanted by machines.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In New York, the world number one was excluded in the wake of swiping at a ball in disappointment which at that point crushed into the throat of a lineswoman remaining behind him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The occurrence occurred on the show-stopper Arthur Ashe Stadium, one of only two courts at the competition which kept up the convention of utilizing linesmen and ladies.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On all the others, electronic line calling was utilized as a feature of plans to lessen the quantity of individuals on the Flushing Meadows site during the COVID pandemic.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There have been developing requires a comparative framework to be presented at Roland Garros which actually depends on authorities making decisions with the unaided eye.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Djokovic trusts it&#39;s the ideal opportunity for a reevaluate.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;With all regard for the custom and the way of life we have in this game, with regards to individuals present on the court during a match, including line umpires, I truly don&#39;t see a motivation behind why each and every competition in this world, in this innovative progressed time, would not have what we had during Cincinnati/New York competition,&quot; he said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The innovation is so exceptional at the present time, there is positively no motivation behind why you should keep line umpires on the court. Obviously I comprehend innovation is costly, so it&#39;s an efficient issue and a question mark.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Yet, I feel like we are on the whole moving towards that, and at some point or another there is no motivation to keep line umpires.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Perhaps you can let me know whether there is any critical motivation behind why we should keep other than convention that we had and have in this game. At that point I would likewise presumably then have less opportunities to do what I did in New York.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Top players, for example, US Open victor Dominic Thiem, Denis Shapovalov and Stefanos Tsitsipas have required a reconsider of administering at Roland Garros this week.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Saturday, Djokovic wrecked Colombian fortunate failure Daniel Galan to arrive at the last 16 in Paris for a record-equalling eleventh progressive year.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Djokovic cleared past 153rd-positioned Galan 6-0, 6-3, 6-2 with his most testing second coming when he helped groundstaff lay more earth on the outside of Court Philippe Chatrier after downpour had made it deceptive.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For the 2016 hero, who is pursuing an eighteenth Grand Slam title, it was the 71st success in Paris.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Djokovic additionally took his 2020 record to 34 successes against only one misfortune - his New York brainfade - as he proceeds with his offer to turn into the main man in 50 years to win every one of the four Grand Slam titles twice.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Next up for a spot in the quarter-finals is Russian fifteenth seed Karen Khachanov who beat Chile&#39;s Cristian Garin.</p>', 'us open, usa novak, Novak Djokovic, Novak demands, line judges, line novak, USA tennis, championship usa, trump covid, sports news, updated, footbal update, ronaldo, messi, nemar', 'nova_1601789192.jpg', '2020-10-04 09:26:32', '2021-12-19 17:28:50'),
(686, 6, 6, 153, 'global-market-shook-after-trump-tests-positive-for-covid-1601792388', 'Global market shook after Trump tests positive for Covid', 1, '<p>Worldwide business sectors and US stock prospects were irritated on Friday by news that President Donald Trump and First Lady Melania Trump have tried positive for COVID.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dow fates were down 445 focuses or 1.6 percent, generally coordinating their underlying move lower after Trump tweeted his condition, reports CNN. SP 500 prospects were down 1.7 percent and Nasdaq fates were down 2.3 percent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><strong>CNN </strong>said the finding is a destabilizing second that brings up issues about the political race and the US organization.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Today, @FLOTUS and I tried positive for Covid-19. We will start our isolate and recuperation measure promptly,&quot; Trump tweeted in no time before 1 am eastern time on Friday. &quot;We will get past this TOGETHER!&quot;Stocks in Asia Pacific additionally slid on the news. Japan&#39;s Nikkei 225 completed down 0.7 percent while Australia&#39;s SP/ASX 200 fell 1.4 percent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Different business sectors in the area incorporating those in India, Hong Kong, territory China and South Korea were shut for public occasions.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>European stocks were lower in early daytime exchanging with the FTSE 100 dropping 1 percent in London while France&#39;s CAC 40 shed 2 percent and Germany&#39;s DAX declined 1.1 percent.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Oil fates likewise tumbled. US rough prospects fell 4.3 percent to 37.06 dollars per barrel while Brent, the world oil benchmark, lost 4.2 percent to hit 39.20 dollars per barrel. Both had settled lower on Thursday.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Japanese yen has just flooded and was last exchanging at around 105 yen for each US dollar, up 0.4 percent. Gold costs were minimal changed at 1,913 dollars for every ounce.</p>', 'global market, stock exchange, london stock exchange, new york stock, usa stock exchange, india today, business ratio, washington update, global business, trump covid, world bank, who news, global warming, canada today, canada stock market', '7_1601792388.png', '2020-10-04 09:45:47', '2021-12-19 17:25:01'),
(687, 6, 10, 191, 'trumps-re-election-campaign-methodology-up-in-air-after-testing-positive-for-covid-19-1601792347', 'Trump\'s re-election Campaign methodology up in air after testing positive for Covid-19', 2, '<p>WASHINGTON, DC - President Donald Trump&#39;s positive Covid test has sabotaged his rehashed claims that the U.S. is &quot;adjusting the turn&quot; in its treatment of the pandemic, with only one month to go before the November 3 political decision.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump declared on Friday that he and his better half, Melania, had tried positive for Covid-19, and planned to isolate at the White House.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://news-zilla.com/uploads/ckeditor/4_1601791857.jpg\" style=\"height:50%; margin-bottom:20px; margin-top:20px; width:100%\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Today, @FLOTUS and I tried positive for COVID-19. We will start our isolate and recuperation measure right away. We will overcome this TOGETHER,&quot; he composed on Twitter.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump is 74 years of age, putting him at higher danger of genuine difficulties from the infection.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His doctor has said the president is &quot;well&quot; and will keep on playing out his obligations &quot;without interruption.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Notwithstanding, regardless of whether the president stays asymptomatic, he will probably need to stop face to face lobbying for a vague measure of time while he isolates at the White House.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It is hazy precisely what that implies for a leader of the United States, particularly for this one who has gone through months not having any desire to wear a face veil, not having any desire to pay attention to physical separating,&quot; David Smith, head of the Guardian paper&#39;s Washington agency, disclosed to FRANCE 24.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;The White House distributed a timetable for tomorrow, with different occasions that he will probably not be satisfying. It makes one wonder: will he seat a mission essentially, as his adversary Joe Biden has been doing a ton?&quot; Smith included. &quot;Apparently, if Trump is feeling all around ok, he would have the option to do that.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whatever structure Trump&#39;s mission takes in the coming days and weeks, his determination has genuinely subverted his endeavors to minimize the pandemic and pull together the race on different issues.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Previously, Trump has illegitimately anticipated that the Covid &quot;will vanish,&quot; and even addressed researchers who repudiated his affirmations in broad daylight.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&#39;This could be a truly critical blow&#39;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump has likewise generally overlooked his own administration&#39;s general wellbeing rules, frequently declining to wear a cover or watch social removing.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the main presidential discussion in Cleveland, Ohio, recently, Trump even derided his Democratic challenger, Joe Biden, for the size of his cover.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;Each time you see him, he has a cover,&quot; Trump said of his rival. &quot;He could be talking 200 feet away... What&#39;s more, he appears with the greatest cover I&#39;ve ever observed.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>With various surveys demonstrating that a lion&#39;s share of Americans oppose Trump&#39;s treatment of the pandemic - which has guaranteed at any rate 207,000 lives in the United States - his determination will probably just aggravate this feeling.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;This was a day numerous individuals dreaded, numerous individuals saw coming, numerous individuals thought may well occur, on the grounds that he was proceeding to hold crusade rallies, two or three them inside. He was resisting frequently his own general wellbeing rules on the Covid,&quot; Smith said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump&#39;s positive test outcome absolutely confuses his capacity to successfully crusade against Biden, who is presently driving in the surveys.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;We&#39;ve seen Trump truly flourishes off the energy of groups, of holding enormous occasions. It gives him a feeling of energy,&quot; Smith said. &quot;This could be a truly critical hit to a presidential mission that is as of now battling with Joe Biden well ahead in the surveys.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is likewise muddled how Trump&#39;s positive test will influence plans for the second presidential discussion, which is planned for October 15 in Miami, Florida.</p>', 'trump recovery, trump campaign, usa politics, election 2020, usa today, trump vs biden, trump for president, usa election date, first lady, biden for president, usa news, christmas', 'tttt_1601791915.jpg', '2020-10-04 10:11:56', '2023-01-30 03:40:21'),
(688, 6, 15, 279, 'trump-corona-update-when-trump-will-discharge-from-hospital-1601837209', 'Trump corona update: When Trump will discharge from hospital?', 2, '<p>President Trump says his condition is improving and if everything continues he could be released from the hospital tomorrow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Trump delivered a video from Walter Reed Medical Center on Saturday night, illuminating Americans that he felt &quot;much better,&quot; a day subsequent to entering the office in the wake of testing good with the Covid.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He also says he will start campaign and his struggle again.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I&#39;m feeling much better now, I will back soon</p>', 'Trump corona update, trump covid, usa today, us election, trump vs biden, trump campaign, biden campaign, barak obama, trump news, obama newsbreaking news, usa breaking, usa new updates', 'k_1601837208.jpg', '2020-10-04 22:46:49', '2021-12-19 17:37:35'),
(689, 6, 1, 124, 'donald-trump-views-after-tested-positive-for-covid-19-1601885408', 'Donald Trump views after tested positive for COVID-19', 2, '<p>President <strong>Donald Trump</strong> on Sunday made a short drive outside the Walter Reed National Military Medical Center, where he is being treated for <strong>COVID-19</strong>. Trump&#39;s motorcade drove past his allies who were seen waving at him.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In no time before he left the clinic, Trump posted a video on Twitter, saying &quot;I additionally figure we will pay a little astonishment to the nationalists that are holding up outside in the roads.&quot; In the video, Trump said that he had &quot;an exceptionally intriguing excursion&quot; where he took in a great deal about <strong>COVID-19</strong> by setting off to the &quot;genuine school&quot; and not the &quot;read the book school&quot;.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;It has been a fascinating excursion. I took in a ton about <strong>COVID-19</strong>. I learned by truly setting off to the school and this is the genuine school and this isn&#39;t the perused the book school. Furthermore, I get it and I get it,&quot; he said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The U.S. President further said that he is getting extraordinary reports from the specialists at Walter Reed. &quot;The work they do is completely stunning,&quot; he included.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prior today, Trump had valued his allies who are outside the Walter Reed medical clinic as he is being treated for novel COVID. &quot;I truly welcome the entirety of the fans and allies outside of the clinic. The truth of the matter is, they truly love our nation and are perceiving how we are making it more noteworthy than at any other time,&quot; Trump tweeted.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>His clinical group had said that Trump experienced two scenes of blood-oxygen drops during his disease yet he is probably going to be released on <strong>October 5 (Monday)</strong>.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On Thursday, President Donald Trump and First Lady Melania Trump were tried positive for COVID.</p>', 'trump says, trump corona update, trump sunday covid, about trump trump vs biden, usa today, us politics, biden ads, negative ads, election date, usa 2020', 'f_1601885407.jpeg', '2020-10-05 12:10:08', '2021-08-13 08:23:11'),
(690, 6, 12, 188, 'israeli-cabinet-minister-tests-positive-for-covid-19-1601886164', 'Israeli Cabinet minister tests positive for COVID-19', 0, '<p>Israel&#39;s Minister of Environmental Protection Gila Gamliel tried positive for the Covid-19, the Gila Gamliel said on her Twitter account late on Saturday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&quot;I was analyzed as certain for Covid. I feel better and want to recoup rapidly. I wish all Israeli patients complete mending,&quot; the priest said.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Gamliel is the fourth Israeli clergyman who has tried positive for COVID-19 since the flare-up of the pandemic in the nation in late February. The other three clergymen have recuperated.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The all out number of COVID-19 cases in Israel has arrived at 264,857 on Sunday, with 70,172 dynamic cases.</p>', 'israeli minister, Gila Gamliel, israel politition, usa election, trump corona update, us election, usa daily, trump today, israel today, bbc news, cnnn news', 'l_1601886164.png', '2020-10-05 12:22:44', '2021-12-19 17:30:29'),
(691, 6, 15, 299, 'canadian-pm-on-donald-trump-covid-19-news-1601893779', 'Canadian PM on Donald Trump COVID-19 News ?', 1, '<p>He Said:&nbsp;Sophie and I are sending our best wishes to <a dir=\"ltr\" href=\"https://twitter.com/POTUS?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1312005202590003200%7Ctwgr%5Eshare_3&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cbc.ca%2Fnews%2Fpolitics%2Ftrudeau-trump-covid19-1.5747731\" rel=\" noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">@POTUS</a> Trump and <a dir=\"ltr\" href=\"https://twitter.com/FLOTUS?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1312005202590003200%7Ctwgr%5Eshare_3&amp;ref_url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cbc.ca%2Fnews%2Fpolitics%2Ftrudeau-trump-covid19-1.5747731\" rel=\" noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">@FLOTUS</a>. We hope you both get well soon and have a full recovery from this virus.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Executive Justin Trudeau and spouse Sophie are sending their all the best to Donald Trump and his better half Melania after the pair tried positive for COVID-19.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trudeau says on Twitter that they are seeking after a full recuperation for the president and the principal woman.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump dropped the stunner early Friday only hours after Hope Hicks, probably the nearest counselor, tried positive herself.</p>', 'canada news, canada today, canada pm to trump, Justin Trudeau, trump covid, trump corona update, canada and usa, canada to trump, breaking news, well wishing, usa today', 'cb_1601893779.jpg', '2020-10-05 14:29:39', '2021-12-19 17:24:48'),
(692, 6, 1, 143, 'trump-after-returns-to-white-house-advises-americans-not-to-fear-covid-1601984599', 'Trump after returns to White House, advises Americans not to fear COVID', 2, '<p>Trump re-visitations of White House, advises Americans not to fear COVID that has slaughtered 210,000 in U.S.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>President Donald Trump arranged a sensational re-visitation of the White House on Monday night subsequent to leaving the military emergency clinic where he has been accepting a phenomenal degree of care for COVID-19.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He quickly lighted another contention by announcing that in spite of his ailment the country ought not fear the infection that has slaughtered in excess of 210,000 Americans &mdash; and afterward he went into the White House without a defensive cover.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Trump&#39;s message frightened irresistible ailment specialists and proposed the president&#39;s own ailment had not made him reevaluate his regularly carefree disposition toward the sickness, which has additionally contaminated his better half and a few White House helpers, including new cases uncovered on Monday.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Arriving at the White House on Marine One, Trump warily climbed the South Portico steps, taken out his cover and announced, &quot;I feel better.&quot; He offered a twofold go-ahead to the leaving helicopter from the porch patio, where associates had masterminded American banners for the dusk event.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>He went into the White House, where assistants were obvious processing about the Blue Room, without wearing a face covering.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Minutes after the fact, he tweeted a video of himself, advising Americans not to fear Covid or let it assume control over their carries on with, likely a troublesome directive for the groups of the individuals who have passed on from the infection. He said he found out such a great amount about the infection while in clinic, discussing the best hardware and drugs, any semblance of which the normal American would not approach.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Furthermore, he guaranteed antibodies are coming &quot;immediately.&quot;&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Prior, the president left Walter Reed National Military Medical Center for a holding up SUV that conveyed him to Marine One for the short helicopter trip back to the White House.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Indeed, even before he left the entryways, he tweeted that he&#39;d be back on the battle field soon.&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The 74-year-old Trump was relied upon to proceed with his recuperation at the White House, where he will be thought about nonstop by a group of specialists and medical caretakers. He reported his Covid finding early Friday.</p>', 'Trump corona update, usa today, covid today, trump today, biden vs trump, election 2020, usa politics, trump covid update, stock exchange, global market\', bbc news', 'j_1601984598.jpg', '2020-10-06 15:43:19', '2021-08-18 06:42:57');
